    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bancroft Prize’s Recipients are not a Small World While Connections are Significant</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Social Network, Bancroft Prize, American History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;network analysis and graphs theory and application&#10;History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">network analysis and graphs theory and application</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In 2022, the recipients of the Bancroft Prize were publicized, and two historians, Mia Bay, and Mae Ngai, were awarded the prestigious academic awards for history books. Curiously, the two historians both completed their dissertations under the supervision of two previous Bancroft Prize recipients, Eric Foner and David Brion Davis. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The difference between the awardees whose advisors were former awardees and non-awardees fostered our academic curiosity about the connection between the two variables: (1) becoming awardees and (2) being supervised by former awardees. We implemented this Social Network Analysis (SNA) methodology to explore the extent to which the advisor-advisee relationship could affect the distribution of this prize.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;According to the results of the SNA test of the current and past recipients of the Bancroft Prizes between 1992 and 2023, the median in-degree is 0, and the mean in-degree is 0.57, with a standard deviation of 0.72; the median out-degree was higher at 1, and its mean was 0.57 with a standard deviation of 0.52. There were 51 nodes with an out-degree of 0, meaning that they weren&#039;t advisors of other recipients. Moreover, 37 scholars advised one recipient, and only 7 scholars advised over one recipient. Connections between most recipients in the network weren&#039;t intense but loose.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;During the χ2 test, all 491 scholars could be divided into four groups: neither their advisors nor themselves were recipients (n =294), there were recipients while their advisors were not (n =50), they were not recipients, while their advisors were (n =197), they and their advisors were all recipients (n =10). The results of the χ2 test showed that scholars completing their dissertations under the supervision of previous recipients were more likely to receive the prize in their academic career than those whose advisors were not awarded, χ2 (491) = 12.541, p &lt;.001.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In 2022, the recipients of the Bancroft Prize were publicized, and two historians, Mia Bay, and Mae Ngai, were awarded the prestigious academic awards for history books. Curiously, the two historians both completed their dissertations under the supervision of two previous Bancroft Prize recipients, Eric Foner and David Brion Davis. &#10;The difference between the awardees whose advisors were former awardees and non-awardees fostered our academic curiosity about the connection between the two variables: (1) becoming awardees and (2) being supervised by former awardees. We implemented this Social Network Analysis (SNA) methodology to explore the extent to which the advisor-advisee relationship could affect the distribution of this prize.&#10;According to the results of the SNA test of the current and past recipients of the Bancroft Prizes between 1992 and 2023, the median in-degree is 0, and the mean in-degree is 0.57, with a standard deviation of 0.72; the median out-degree was higher at 1, and its mean was 0.57 with a standard deviation of 0.52. There were 51 nodes with an out-degree of 0, meaning that they weren&#039;t advisors of other recipients. Moreover, 37 scholars advised one recipient, and only 7 scholars advised over one recipient. Connections between most recipients in the network weren&#039;t intense but loose.&#10;During the χ2 test, all 491 scholars could be divided into four groups: neither their advisors nor themselves were recipients (n =294), there were recipients while their advisors were not (n =50), they were not recipients, while their advisors were (n =197), they and their advisors were all recipients (n =10). The results of the χ2 test showed that scholars completing their dissertations under the supervision of previous recipients were more likely to receive the prize in their academic career than those whose advisors were not awarded, χ2 (491) = 12.541, p &lt;.001.</ss:Data></Cell>
