    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">shuwan@buffalo.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">shuwan@buffalo.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wan, Shu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">shuwan@buffalo.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">103</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1001</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lach, Pamella R.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission describes a network analysis performed on Bancroft Prize awardees and their advisors, arguing that scholars being advised by previous Bancroft Prize winners are more likely to receive the award than those whose advisors have not won this prize.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission describes a network analysis performed on Bancroft Prize awardees and their advisors, arguing that scholars being advised by previous Bancroft Prize winners are more likely to receive the award than those whose advisors have not won this prize. I would be curious to know how the data were compiled, particularly how these relationships were defined and measured (what constitutes &quot;advising&quot; in this context beyond a dissertation advisor?). I&#039;d also be curious to know what sort of broader implications might be teased out of this type of analysis with respect to things such as institution type (private versus public, etc.), recipient identity (gender, race, etc.), and topic—are there some themes/time periods, topics that are more likely to win the prize? In short, this is an interesting submission that uses network analysis techniques to raise questions about gatekeeping in the historical profession, if not broader academia. I would encourage the author to tease out some of these larger conclusions. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1307</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rehberger, Dean</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This study provides evidence of a potential influence of academic lineage on the likelihood of receiving the Bancroft Prize. However, it&#039;s important to note that while there is a statistically significant association, the overall network connections appear to be relatively loose, indicating that other factors likely play substantial roles in determining prize recipients.  The research raises interesting questions about the dynamics of academic recognition and the potential impact of mentorship on scholarly success.  Yet is that a significant finding?   Further investigation into other contributing factors and a more comprehensive analysis of the academic ecosystem could provide additional insights into the distribution of prestigious awards like the Bancroft Prize.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very interesting application of network analysis.  Yet I think it shows the shortcomings of network analysis when the focus is primarily on factor of linkage -- is this a mentor?  Moreover, we do not have a sense of how strong the bond of mentor is (some mentors can play a significant role in the development of a work while other appear only for the sake of a named scholar).  Likewise, with this small of a sample and the &quot;loose&quot; findings of the data, it would be nice both to have the work contextualized in other scholarship and similar studies, and/or have a stronger sense of the conclusions to be drawn (even if the conclusion is that we really can&#039;t draw a conclusion from the data -- which appears to be the case here).&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">It is a good example of network analysis but sometimes when a study yields no significant conclusions. -- one either needs to push further and analyze more factors and/or include similar studies and work.  The author does neither here.  It really is a study at its very initial stage and I am not sure if it is ready for public presentation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">20</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1075</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Poole, Carson Leigh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I feel this submission is relevant to the conference by addressing the impact of networking and interpersonal connections for Bancroft Prize awardees. Its topic seems like it may also address potential inequalities in academic mentorships and the benefits of those mentorships, while using digital data methodologies to analyze whether this inequality is pervasive enough to reliably determine whether a book receives the Bancroft Prize. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a strong paper topic. I am leaning towards acceptance into the conference, however I would like the abstract to be clearer in how the digital aspect of &quot;digital humanities&quot; comes into play, on a deeper level than simply running and analyzing the data digitally. I am not familiar with SNA testing but I feel like the abstract could be clearer in how it addresses both the issues of equity/inequality in Bancroft Prize recipients who had previous awardees as mentors and those who did not AND how the digital application outlined here is specifically relevant to the Bancroft Prize. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I feel like this is a strong paper. However, I am on the fence about acceptance into the conference because I do not really see how it is specifically relevant to &quot;digital humanities&quot; other than the data being analyzed digitally. I am on the fence and leaning towards acceptance because it does somewhat address ethics in data science, but I think that connection is vague based on the abstract&#039;s wording. I think it may be more successful as a poster versus an individual paper presentation, because I feel the data being presented visually on a poster would better connect the data to the subject of mentorship from former Bancroft Prize awardees. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
