    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Evaluation framework for digital storytelling outcomes towards trustful AI in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library Digital storytelling, Human-machine collaborative workflow, Trustful AI, Evaluation framework design</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Asia&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;user experience design and analysis&#10;Computer science&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;user experience design and analysis&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Computer science&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Digital and Semantic Web related technologies facilitate the possibility of automatically generated digital storytelling products. This is closely related to the construction of data and technical infrastructure with a human-machine collaborative digital storytelling workflow. This presentation introduces our design for a workflow and evaluation framework (Figure 1) based on our digital storytelling practice since 2021. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The knowledge databases which record narrative elements, described in unified resource description frameworks, provide a crucial basis for creating human-machine collaborative digital stories by automatically identifying links and storylines. They also make it possible to create story-themes or plots that are machine-identifiable or -editable. To be a robust scholarly method for research, the reliability, validity, and evaluation of digital storytelling methodology and its outcomes need to be transparent, standardized, and reproducible to ensure that they meet academic rigour and scientific method (Figure 2). &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Trust is a significant issue, particularly if the providers do not make it clear that these digital stories are produced algorithmically. Trust is highlighted in the European Commission’s White Paper on AI. A lack of trust ‘is a main factor holding back a broader uptake of AI’ and prompts developing a clear regulatory framework (European Commission, 2020: 9). Hence the need for what has become known as &lt;em&gt;explainable AI&lt;/em&gt;; ‘in part motivated by the need to maintain trust between the human user and AI’ (Jacovi et al, 2021: 624). Whether this trust can be achieved seems uncertain, particularly as the risks of the use of AI in different scenarios are as yet unclear and not fully understood. When a human-machine collaborative digital storytelling product is presented or put into use, it is important to evaluate user experience; how the audience feels about the outcome, whether they are satisfied with it, as well as the accessibility, and ethical evaluation of the interactive effect.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital and Semantic Web related technologies facilitate the possibility of automatically generated digital storytelling products. This is closely related to the construction of data and technical infrastructure with a human-machine collaborative digital storytelling workflow. This presentation introduces our design for a workflow and evaluation framework (Figure 1) based on our digital storytelling practice since 2021. &#10;The knowledge databases which record narrative elements, described in unified resource description frameworks, provide a crucial basis for creating human-machine collaborative digital stories by automatically identifying links and storylines. They also make it possible to create story-themes or plots that are machine-identifiable or -editable. To be a robust scholarly method for research, the reliability, validity, and evaluation of digital storytelling methodology and its outcomes need to be transparent, standardized, and reproducible to ensure that they meet academic rigour and scientific method (Figure 2). &#10;Trust is a significant issue, particularly if the providers do not make it clear that these digital stories are produced algorithmically. Trust is highlighted in the European Commission’s White Paper on AI. A lack of trust ‘is a main factor holding back a broader uptake of AI’ and prompts developing a clear regulatory framework (European Commission, 2020: 9). Hence the need for what has become known as explainable AI; ‘in part motivated by the need to maintain trust between the human user and AI’ (Jacovi et al, 2021: 624). Whether this trust can be achieved seems uncertain, particularly as the risks of the use of AI in different scenarios are as yet unclear and not fully understood. When a human-machine collaborative digital storytelling product is presented or put into use, it is important to evaluate user experience; how the audience feels about the outcome, whether they are satisfied with it, as well as the accessibility, and ethical evaluation of the interactive effect.</ss:Data></Cell>
