    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Research on the Causes of Failure and Countermeasures of Digital Humanities Projects: Based on Analysis of the 22 &quot;Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; in DHA</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital Humanities Project, Digital Humanities Awards, Sustainability, Failure</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;project design, organization, and management</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">project design, organization, and management</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Projects are the fundamental unit of digital humanities and the vital manifestation of digital humanities practice. The Digital Humanities Awards (DHA) have been established since 2012 and have completed 12 rounds of selection. This award is supervised by a nomination committee composed of digital humanities scholars from countries and regions such as the United States, the United Kingdom, France, Australia and so on, covering six continents around the world. DHA is established with the mission of enhancing public awareness of digital humanities and highlighting the value of digital humanities resources. &quot;The Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; category was first set in 2014 and was intermittently suspended due to various reasons. The author summarized the &quot;Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; for six years, namely 2014, 2018, 2019, 2020, 2021, and 2023, and a total of 22 projects were awarded.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Preliminary research has found that the &quot;Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; from 2014 to 2023 exhibited the following significant characteristics: firstly, diverse and rich achievements. blogs, tweets, digital maps, speech videos, manifesto initiatives, digital websites, etc. have all become the presentation methods for this award type. Secondly, the responsible parties are diverse. The responsibility or award-winning subject of this award category presents a pattern of individual-oriented and multi-person-collaborative responsibility subjects. Thirdly, pay more attention to practical issues. Abnormal attention is paid to emerging social issues, including digital sustainability, data literacy, environmental humanities, digital public humanities, digital divide, algorithmic bias, etc. The following research will further summarize the internal and external causes of the failure of digital humanities projects in recent years, and propose specific and targeted implementation strategies to avoid risks. Thus providing rational, scientific and actionable experience and reference for the long-term sustainable development of digital humanities projects worldwide.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Projects are the fundamental unit of digital humanities and the vital manifestation of digital humanities practice. The Digital Humanities Awards (DHA) have been established since 2012 and have completed 12 rounds of selection. This award is supervised by a nomination committee composed of digital humanities scholars from countries and regions such as the United States, the United Kingdom, France, Australia and so on, covering six continents around the world. DHA is established with the mission of enhancing public awareness of digital humanities and highlighting the value of digital humanities resources. &quot;The Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; category was first set in 2014 and was intermittently suspended due to various reasons. The author summarized the &quot;Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; for six years, namely 2014, 2018, 2019, 2020, 2021, and 2023, and a total of 22 projects were awarded.&#10;Preliminary research has found that the &quot;Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; from 2014 to 2023 exhibited the following significant characteristics: firstly, diverse and rich achievements. blogs, tweets, digital maps, speech videos, manifesto initiatives, digital websites, etc. have all become the presentation methods for this award type. Secondly, the responsible parties are diverse. The responsibility or award-winning subject of this award category presents a pattern of individual-oriented and multi-person-collaborative responsibility subjects. Thirdly, pay more attention to practical issues. Abnormal attention is paid to emerging social issues, including digital sustainability, data literacy, environmental humanities, digital public humanities, digital divide, algorithmic bias, etc. The following research will further summarize the internal and external causes of the failure of digital humanities projects in recent years, and propose specific and targeted implementation strategies to avoid risks. Thus providing rational, scientific and actionable experience and reference for the long-term sustainable development of digital humanities projects worldwide.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ZHANG, XU</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Renmin University of China</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">China, People&#039;s Republic of</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">igeorgez@ruc.edu.cn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">igeorgez@163.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">igeorgez@ruc.edu.cn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ZHANG, XU</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">igeorgez@ruc.edu.cn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">UTC+8</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">52.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">34.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">105</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1305</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Elizabeth Parke, Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission summarizes the data from one category of the DHA focusing on failure and limitations of DH projects with the aim of showing the internal and external causes of DH project failures and limitations. The goal being to avoid future mistakes in projects by learning from past failings.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Greater attention to the method of data analysis would improve the contribution. Demonstrating what types of analysis were used on the data set and if/how the data was cleaned would improve transparency of suggested findings. Secondly, the focus on failures and limitations is innovative and is a rich area of future study. However, the recommendations suggested in the abstract on how to guide future DH projects should be further explained. Focusing on how to improve sustainability of future projects by looking at the past is admirable, however, addressing issues of grant funding and planning for endings (UVic endings project for example) would improve the context and engagement with relevant scholarship of this paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">36</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1121</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Risam, Roopika</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper explores projects in the &quot;Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; and aims to identify insights on commonalities between projects and recommendations for mitigating failure based on them. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Studying the DH Awards is a really interesting tactic that holds the possibility of identifying strategies for successful digital humanities projects. Limiting the study to the category dealing with failure is an interesting one that aims to find broader trends and insights from the ways project directors have dealt with failure. There seems to be a conflation between projects nominated and projects that received the award because there haven&#039;t been 22 recipients - it appears that it&#039;s actually 22 nominations. That said, between the number of awardees and number of recipients, it&#039;s not clear how or whether there are enough submissions to be able to make the kinds of generalizations that the author wants to make. There&#039;s a reason that there haven&#039;t always been years with failure nominations -- being able to publicly admit to failure is a privilege. People who are in minoritized positions, whether due to job role, race, gender, or other aspects of identity, have far more to lose by publicly admitting to failure. (As one of the recipients of the award and a nominee at least twice, I know firsthand that it&#039;s something I was fine being open about failure only once I had the job security of tenure.) Therefore, the author should consider how the idea -- and risks -- of admitting to failure itself might be a limiting factor in nominations and, therefore, limit generalizing to &quot;rational, scientific and actionable experience and reference for the long-term sustainable development of digital humanities projects worldwide.{</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a cool idea but limited in its conception and execution -- it seems like a poster, if there is room, would be an opportunity for the author to get some needed feedback on study design and implications.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">34</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1319</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bago, Petra</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission provides an analysis of the &quot;Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; category within the Digital Humanities Awards from 2014 to 2023, highlighting key patterns and themes among the awarded projects. It aims to offer insights into common challenges and failures in digital humanities projects, while also proposing strategies for mitigating risks and promoting the sustainable development of future initiatives.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract is well-organized and clearly articulates the research focus on a unique and underexplored topic—the analysis of failures and limitations in digital humanities projects. The attention to the &quot;Best Exploration of DH Failure/Limitations&quot; category is particularly valuable, as discussions around failures are often overlooked despite their potential to provide critical learning opportunities for the field. The proposal’s structure is coherent, offering a clear overview planned research. One suggestion for improvement would be to provide more specific details about the methodologies that will be used to analyze these case studies, which could strengthen the overall framework and theoretical foundation. Additionally, including a brief mention of how this work will contribute to broader conversations in digital humanities would further emphasize its significance. Overall, this is a strong and compelling submission that would add valuable insights to the conference.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">/</ss:Data></Cell>
