    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Depolitizing LGBTI+ identities: The consequences of the adoption of remote interpreting for LGBTI+ interpreters in international organizations</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">remote interpreting, LGBTI+ identities, minority tax, depolitization, impressionist narratives</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;user experience design and analysis&#10;Translation studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;user experience design and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Translation studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&#10;&lt;p&gt;This paper examines how LGBTIQ+ interpreters working on temporary appointments for international organizations have experienced the irruption of remote interpreting in their professional lives. Remote interpreting was introduced in international organizations during the pandemic and has maintained its presence afterwards. Taking a phenomenological approach, the chapter focuses on how LGBTIQ+ interpreters experienced the technological shift within the organizational culture of institutions striving for peace, dignity, and equality on a healthy planet, as the United Nations’ motto reads. The lived experiences shared by anonymous LGBTIQ+ interpreters coalesce in three impressionist narratives. The themes covered include the logistical arrangements involved in safeguarding interpreters’ security when travelling to countries that criminalize LGBTIQ+ individuals, their mental wellbeing within the work environment, and especially their collective action to improve their working conditions as both interpreters and members of the LGBTIQ+ community. Highlighting both favorable and adverse outcomes, remote interpreting has revealed challenges that impact interpreters irrespective of their gender identity but also others that impose an additional burden on LGBTIQ+ interpreters, a form of minority tax that spares gender-normative interpreters. The challenges identified compound a situation of intersectional oppression for LGBTIQ+ interpreters.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper examines how LGBTIQ+ interpreters working on temporary appointments for international organizations have experienced the irruption of remote interpreting in their professional lives. Remote interpreting was introduced in international organizations during the pandemic and has maintained its presence afterwards. Taking a phenomenological approach, the chapter focuses on how LGBTIQ+ interpreters experienced the technological shift within the organizational culture of institutions striving for peace, dignity, and equality on a healthy planet, as the United Nations’ motto reads. The lived experiences shared by anonymous LGBTIQ+ interpreters coalesce in three impressionist narratives. The themes covered include the logistical arrangements involved in safeguarding interpreters’ security when travelling to countries that criminalize LGBTIQ+ individuals, their mental wellbeing within the work environment, and especially their collective action to improve their working conditions as both interpreters and members of the LGBTIQ+ community. Highlighting both favorable and adverse outcomes, remote interpreting has revealed challenges that impact interpreters irrespective of their gender identity but also others that impose an additional burden on LGBTIQ+ interpreters, a form of minority tax that spares gender-normative interpreters. The challenges identified compound a situation of intersectional oppression for LGBTIQ+ interpreters.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Monzó-Nebot, Esther</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Universitat Jaume I</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Spain</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Western_Europe</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">monzo@uji.es</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">monzo@uji.es</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Monzó-Nebot, Esther</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">monzo@uji.es</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Central European Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">60.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">46.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">106</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1234</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fruttaldo, Antonio</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract presents an examination of the experiences of LGBTIQ+ interpreters with the shift to remote interpreting in international organisations. While the focus on this specific demographic and the phenomenological approach is commendable, several theoretical and methodological aspects require improvement to enhance the scholarly rigour of the paper. I have provided some comments/recommendations for revision that the author might consider addressing. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As previously said, the abstract presents an interesting examination of the experiences of LGBTIQ+ interpreters with the shift to remote interpreting in international organisations and, while the focus on this specific demographic is commendable, several theoretical and methodological aspects require improvement to enhance the scholarly rigour of the paper. For instance, the abstract lacks a detailed conceptual framework and it would therefore benefit from explicitly defining it on the basis of existing literature to provide a solid theoretical foundation. Indeed, there is no mention of prior research on remote interpreting or LGBTIQ+ interpreters and incorporating a literature review that situates the study within the broader context would strengthen the theoretical underpinnings. Additionally, the themes identified (i.e., logistical arrangements, mental well-being, collective action, etc.) are relevant but it would be helpful to articulate how these themes were derived. Are they based on pre-existing theory, or did they emerge from the data? Also, while a phenomenological approach is mentioned, the abstract does not detail how this approach was implemented. The author should have clarified this and justify its suitability for the research question. Finally, I think there&#039;s a mistake in the abstract when the author writes &quot;the chapter focuses on how LGBTIQ+ interpreters experienced&quot;: is this a paper that was then turned into a conference presentation? There&#039;s nothing wrong with it but the author should have acknowledged it. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1132</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Goble, Noah Zachary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission investigates how the proliferation of remote interpreting, as well as the larger technological shift in the structure of organizations employing interpreters, has affected LGBTIQ+ interpreters. It is interested in highlighting both adverse and favorable outcomes, and thus hopes to paint a complete picture of the complex second order consequences of this technological change among a specific population. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal is strong and specific, clearly communicating the areas investigated and providing useful information about conclusions drawn and connections made. The section laying out the “themes covered” was especially helpful, particularly for those less familiar with the subject matter. The specificity of the project is also a clear strength, enabling grounded and actionable conclusions. I believe the proposal could be improved by providing more information about the methodologies used for coming to the conclusions laid out, whether there were deep interviews or surveys involved or if any existing literature is interacted with. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1327</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Regan, Amanda</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper studies remote interpreting for international organizations and how this practice has challenged the impact of interpreters. It stands to make a contribution to the field of translation studies about LGBTIQ+ interpreters. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a really interesting proposal. I think it does a good job of outlining the phenomenological approach and themes revealed by the study. It&#039;s something I&#039;d be very interested in learning more about. My main criticism is that the abstract does not situate the proposal within the field of translation studies or DH. I am not familiar with the field the author is engaging with and it would have been useful to have some signposting that indicated how this paper engages with a larger field. It is also unclear to me what the applicability, significance, and value of the theoretical, methodological, and/or practical contribution to digital humanities is. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">46</ss:Data></Cell>
