    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Behind the Screen: Exploring the Realities of Being a Woman Social Media Influencer in Iran</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Women Influencers, Iran, Surveillance, Authoritarianism, Data Feminism</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Surveillance Studies&#10;Asia&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;social media analysis and methods&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;social media analysis and methods&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Surveillance Studies&#10;Feminist studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Social media platforms are important spaces for activists and influencers to challenge societal norms and advocate for change. However, in authoritarian countries like Iran, these people often face unique challenges, such as strict surveillance and censorship. By analyzing the content of Iranian women social media influencers accounts Published since 2019 through the lens of digital activism (Nasirpour 2016), surveillance theories (Wooley 2022), counterdata (D&#039;Ignazio 2024), and data feminism (D&#039;Ignazio and Klein 2020), this study seeks to understand their experience of operating in a restrictive political environment and the strategies these influencers employ to overcome the challenges they face and continue their digital presence. This study conducts a qualitative analysis of their Instagram profiles, examining the content of their posts, reels, and videos and documenting them using Storymap JS to understand the difficulties of Iranian women social media influencers. The study also incorporates an autoethnographic perspective, drawing upon the researcher&#039;s personal experiences as a social media influencer to counter the dominant narrative imposed by the authoritarian regime. It is noteworthy that this research adopts a multilingual and feminist approach to data collection and analysis in order to recognize the critical role that language plays in data feminism and analysis. The study draws on data sources in Farsi, the native language of the researchers and the country of Iran, allowing for a more nuanced understanding of the women&#039;s experiences and the broader social and political context in which they operate. This research contributes to the growing body of literature on digital influence in authoritarian contexts, the important role of the individuals who challenge societal norms despite facing constant surveillance, and the urgent memory-work to document, curate, create and analysis new archives through a feminist transnational perspective.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Social media platforms are important spaces for activists and influencers to challenge societal norms and advocate for change. However, in authoritarian countries like Iran, these people often face unique challenges, such as strict surveillance and censorship. By analyzing the content of Iranian women social media influencers accounts Published since 2019 through the lens of digital activism (Nasirpour 2016), surveillance theories (Wooley 2022), counterdata (D&#039;Ignazio 2024), and data feminism (D&#039;Ignazio and Klein 2020), this study seeks to understand their experience of operating in a restrictive political environment and the strategies these influencers employ to overcome the challenges they face and continue their digital presence. This study conducts a qualitative analysis of their Instagram profiles, examining the content of their posts, reels, and videos and documenting them using Storymap JS to understand the difficulties of Iranian women social media influencers. The study also incorporates an autoethnographic perspective, drawing upon the researcher&#039;s personal experiences as a social media influencer to counter the dominant narrative imposed by the authoritarian regime. It is noteworthy that this research adopts a multilingual and feminist approach to data collection and analysis in order to recognize the critical role that language plays in data feminism and analysis. The study draws on data sources in Farsi, the native language of the researchers and the country of Iran, allowing for a more nuanced understanding of the women&#039;s experiences and the broader social and political context in which they operate. This research contributes to the growing body of literature on digital influence in authoritarian contexts, the important role of the individuals who challenge societal norms despite facing constant surveillance, and the urgent memory-work to document, curate, create and analysis new archives through a feminist transnational perspective.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Esmaeili, Niloufar</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The University of Texas at San Antonio</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Niloufar.esmaeili@my.utsa.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Niloufar.esmaeili@my.utsa.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Esmaeili, Niloufar</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Niloufar.esmaeili@my.utsa.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">CST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">109</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1267</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shaikh, Hina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is promising study of digital activism, surveillance, and feminist data studies that also incorporates autoethnographic methods. The main focus is on Iranian women’s digital activism, including the researcher’s own experiences, to create counter archival practices.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This a very promising project and paper. I would recommend the author look into the work of Lisa Nakamura to place their work within the larger context of research into digital activisms, race, and gender. Additionally, it might be useful to think more about what is the work that “data” is doing as a theoretical concept within your work? Are you referring to data or do you mean to analyze digital cultures of activism/race etc? Both are valuable and important frameworks!&#10;&#10;I really appreciate the way the author is reciprocally framing vulnerability by incorporating autoethnography alongside analysis of social media posts/reels/videos. I would suggest considering what it means for the replication of people’s posts into academic work that cannot be deleted like social media posts can. In other words, how does your replication of social media activism into your academic work navigate the precarity of anti-authoritarian activism? &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1311</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Li, Simin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1. The topic is interesting and important. &#10;&#10;2.  I am curious why the author chooses Instagram as the case not other social media platforms. Is it because Instagram more popular in Iran? &#10;&#10;3.  I would like to know whether the &quot;the researcher&#039;s personal experiences&quot; are necessary to the research. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1158</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Silva Moore, Rosana</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&#10;This study makes significant contributions to the field of digital humanities. It offers a profound and thorough exploration of the challenges and strategies utilized by Iranian women social media influencers in maneuvering through a restrictive political environment.&#10;&#10;By delving into the experiences of social media influencers in Iran, the research sheds light on the convergence of digital activism, surveillance, and data feminisms within an authoritarian context. This analysis deepens our comprehension of how digital platforms operate in constrained political landscapes, providing valuable insights into the dynamics of power, resistance, and representation in authoritarian societies. Not only does this study contribute to the existing body of knowledge in digital humanities, but it also presents a nuanced examination of how individuals navigate and challenge digital spaces within authoritarian regimes.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This study offers some significant contributions to the field of digital humanities. I highlight the importance of analysis in an authoritarian context. By focusing on the experiences of social media influencers in Iran, the study provides valuable insights into the intersection of digital activism, surveillance, and data feminisms in a restrictive political environment. This enriches the understanding of the impact of digital platforms in authoritarian societies.&#10;&#10;Regarding the methodology, while the autoethnographic perspective can bring unique insights and personal narratives to digital humanities research, it also has certain weaknesses that could be important to pay attention to. Autoethnography is inherently subjective as it relies on personal experiences and interpretations. This subjectivity can introduce bias into the research process, impacting data collection, analysis, and the interpretation of findings. So, it is important to be mindful of their own biases and how they may influence the outcomes of the study.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
