    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Multilingualism as Infrastructural Imperative: Visibility, Accessibility, and Language Diversity in Digital Knowledge Commons</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital knowledge commons, digital research infrastructure, multilingualism, user experience, community buildling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Asia&#10;North America&#10;South America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;interface design, development, and analysis&#10;Communication studies&#10;Design studies&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia&#10;North America&#10;South America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;interface design, development, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Communication studies&#10;Design studies&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Anglocentrism continues to be a concern in DH, as well as in digital scholarship more generally—despite the realities of globalization and the abundance of non-English and multilingual DH initiatives. Indeed, digital scholarship and infrastructure are still shaped significantly not only by what, in 2016, Domenico Fiormonte termed “the indisputable Anglo-American hegemony in the academic research field,” but also the corresponding “partial or total invisibility” of non-Anglo-American DH. Our talk will address these issues vis-à-vis one of Fiormonte’s proposed solutions: “a new concept of knowledge as commons.” Specifically, we will discuss our research on—and development of—infrastructure to support language diversity and community building through the Canadian Humanities and Social Sciences Commons (hsscommons.ca). Led by the Implementing New Knowledge Environments (INKE) Partnership, this project is an in-development, not-for-profit hub for open scholarship in Canada and beyond. It combines elements of social networking sites, collaborative tools, and institutional repositories. While the site already supports both French and English, in recognition of Canada’s bilingual status and the valuable contributions of our Francophone colleagues, we are also working with partners from Mexico, Brazil, India, and the UAE to create a more inclusive multilingual interface capable of supporting Spanish, Portuguese, Hindi, and Arabic (that is, left-to-right and right-to-left languages, plus non-latin scripts). This work is central to INKE’s mandate to increase the accessibility and visibility of scholarship by digital means. As we suggest, this mandate compels us to interpret multilingualism as an infrastructural as well as a research imperative; as such, and in line with our commitment to open scholarship and the larger ethos of care it represents, we argue that any digital space purporting to support knowledge diversity across disciplinary and national contexts, as we aim to do, must actively work to provide tools to facilitate, publish, and promote research in languages other than English.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Anglocentrism continues to be a concern in DH, as well as in digital scholarship more generally—despite the realities of globalization and the abundance of non-English and multilingual DH initiatives. Indeed, digital scholarship and infrastructure are still shaped significantly not only by what, in 2016, Domenico Fiormonte termed “the indisputable Anglo-American hegemony in the academic research field,” but also the corresponding “partial or total invisibility” of non-Anglo-American DH. Our talk will address these issues vis-à-vis one of Fiormonte’s proposed solutions: “a new concept of knowledge as commons.” Specifically, we will discuss our research on—and development of—infrastructure to support language diversity and community building through the Canadian Humanities and Social Sciences Commons (hsscommons.ca). Led by the Implementing New Knowledge Environments (INKE) Partnership, this project is an in-development, not-for-profit hub for open scholarship in Canada and beyond. It combines elements of social networking sites, collaborative tools, and institutional repositories. While the site already supports both French and English, in recognition of Canada’s bilingual status and the valuable contributions of our Francophone colleagues, we are also working with partners from Mexico, Brazil, India, and the UAE to create a more inclusive multilingual interface capable of supporting Spanish, Portuguese, Hindi, and Arabic (that is, left-to-right and right-to-left languages, plus non-latin scripts). This work is central to INKE’s mandate to increase the accessibility and visibility of scholarship by digital means. As we suggest, this mandate compels us to interpret multilingualism as an infrastructural as well as a research imperative; as such, and in line with our commitment to open scholarship and the larger ethos of care it represents, we argue that any digital space purporting to support knowledge diversity across disciplinary and national contexts, as we aim to do, must actively work to provide tools to facilitate, publish, and promote research in languages other than English.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
