    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">110</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1023</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Esmaeili, Niloufar</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal discusses the problem of Anglocentrism in Digital Humanities (DH) by introducing a multilingual system for the Canadian Humanities and Social Sciences Commons (hsscommons.ca). The goal of this project is to promote language diversity within digital scholarship and including not only English and French but also Spanish, Portuguese, Hindi and Arabic.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal demonstrates a connection to the themes of the conference specifically delving into issues of anti-racism, postcolonial studies, and multilingualism in digital humanities. It effectively engages with related theories such as Fiormonte&#039;s exploration of Anglo-American hegemony and the concept of &quot;knowledge as a shared resource,&quot; though it could be strengthened by referencing additional scholars in the field. The proposal clearly outlines its framework and objectives providing a foundation for developing multilingualism in DH. Here are some recommendations for minor revisions: 1- Situate the work within existing multilingual DH projects and address the challenges encountered in developing multilingual projects. 2- Outline strategies for evaluating the effectiveness of multilingual projects. 3- A thorough explanation of the methodology employed could improve the proposal. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal fits perfectly within the conference&#039;s focus on multilingualism and decolonial strategies in DH. The broad scope and possible influence of the project position it as a strong candidate for acceptance. If approved it could be beneficial to explore pairing this talk with others that touch on related topics like language diversity in DH to form a panel or roundtable.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1295</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lindblad, Purdom</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper addresses the prominence of English as the language of digital scholarship and academic discourse by crafting a multilingual hub for Canadian open scholarship. This project contributes strategies for inclusive, multi-lingual infrastructure, open scholarship, and social networking. Significantly this work increases visibility and use of multi-lingual or non-English scholarship, arguing that language diversity is a research and infrastructure mandate.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper intercedes in the challenge of English-language hegemony of digital scholarship, citing the dual challenge of Anglo-American language dominance and the aligned invisibility of non-Anglo-American digital scholarship. A key strength of this paper is the combination of social and infrastructural interventions through the Canadian Humanities and Social Sciences Commons (hsscommons.ca), led by the Implementing New Knowledge Environments (INKE) Partnership. An additional strength of this proposal is the emphasis on developing, implementing, and regularly evaluating tools that facilitate, publish, and promote research in languages other than English.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1120</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kurzynski, Maciej</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission showcases the Canadian Humanities and Social Sciences Commons, a non-profit platform for open scholarship meant to support language diversity in digital scholarship in Canada and beyond. The project currently supports English and French, but the authors are also developing a more inclusive multilingual interface. The authors argue for multilingualism as an infrastructural and research imperative.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a well-written abstract, and the Canadian HSS Commons looks very promising. We definitely need more platforms that facilitate cross-cultural and multi-lingual collaboration, and the authors should be applauded for their efforts to de-center DH. The &quot;new concept of knowledge as commons&quot; will definitely speak to many like-minded scholars.&#10;&#10;While the project itself is valuable, however, the authors say that currently the platform supports only English and French, which are two of the most popular world languages. This contradicts, to some degree, the multilingual premise of the ACH2024 conference, according to which it is the underrepresented languages that should acquire more visibility. The authors argue that they are &quot;working with partners from Mexico, Brazil, India, and the UAE to create a more inclusive multilingual interface capable of supporting Spanish, Portuguese, Hindi,&quot; but there is relatively little in the abstract to substantiate this claim. In fact, 50% of the abstract is about the need to promote research in languages other than English, which is a well-known fact and simply a restatement of the conference&#039;s theme. Ideally, the abstract could mention one or two examples of existing non-English projects available through the platform as examples of multilingualism. It would be also very interesting to learn a bit more about the &quot;networking sites, collaborative tools, and institutional repositories&quot; that the platform offers.&#10;&#10;Another potential problem is the presentation format: the authors opted for &quot;individual paper,&quot; whereas a poster or a lightning talk would be more appropriate, in my view, to showcase the platform&#039;s current capabilities. Individual paper would be more suitable for a theoretical reflection about the &quot;knowledge as commons&quot; theory, but again this does not seem to be the focus here. Overall, it is a very interesting project and I look forward to future development promised here.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
