    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Playing With the Trouble: Moving Beyond Simulative Politics in Climate Change Games</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ecocriticism, game design, anthropocene, speculative design, collaborative practice</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;eco-criticism and environmental analysis&#10;Art history&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Environmental, ocean, and waterways studies&#10;Game studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;eco-criticism and environmental analysis&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Art history&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Environmental, ocean, and waterways studies&#10;Game studies&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Climate change games have proliferated in recent years, often with the goal of educating the public about the stakes of ignoring a warming planet. Most operate like a version of Model UN, where powerful politicians and leading scientists negotiate Earth’s future. Many treat ecological disaster as a sudden, dramatic event that is either utterly devastating or can be “won” with the right technology. Not many address climate change as gradual, already happening, and deeply grievable. Few feel centered on how the rest of us will experience it or already are.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Last year I participated in &lt;em&gt;Speculating the Environment&lt;/em&gt;, a Pratt Institute workshop that convened scientists, writers, and artists working on climate change in their professional and creative practices. Through it, I designed a collaborative storytelling game called &lt;em&gt;The Disappearing&lt;/em&gt;, which sets players in a fictional world where things are vanishing mysteriously. The game prompts participants to imagine how they and others respond to these profound changes, emotionally and practically. The game is played almost entirely asynchronously until the end, with each player inheriting the choices made by previous players.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Drawing on writers and scholars like Donna Haraway, Anna Lowenhaupt Tsing, Robin Wall Kimmerer, and Rebecca Solnit as well as hands-on research playing a variety of games, I will critique the landscape of current climate change games, present some of the (mostly non-climate-themed) games that inspired me, and offer my own game as a collaborative invitation and experimentation—an attempt at “playing with the trouble,&quot; so to speak.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Climate change games have proliferated in recent years, often with the goal of educating the public about the stakes of ignoring a warming planet. Most operate like a version of Model UN, where powerful politicians and leading scientists negotiate Earth’s future. Many treat ecological disaster as a sudden, dramatic event that is either utterly devastating or can be “won” with the right technology. Not many address climate change as gradual, already happening, and deeply grievable. Few feel centered on how the rest of us will experience it or already are.&#10;Last year I participated in Speculating the Environment, a Pratt Institute workshop that convened scientists, writers, and artists working on climate change in their professional and creative practices. Through it, I designed a collaborative storytelling game called The Disappearing, which sets players in a fictional world where things are vanishing mysteriously. The game prompts participants to imagine how they and others respond to these profound changes, emotionally and practically. The game is played almost entirely asynchronously until the end, with each player inheriting the choices made by previous players.&#10;Drawing on writers and scholars like Donna Haraway, Anna Lowenhaupt Tsing, Robin Wall Kimmerer, and Rebecca Solnit as well as hands-on research playing a variety of games, I will critique the landscape of current climate change games, present some of the (mostly non-climate-themed) games that inspired me, and offer my own game as a collaborative invitation and experimentation—an attempt at “playing with the trouble,&quot; so to speak.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
