    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jessicalynnbal@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jbal@gradcenter.cuny.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bal, Jessica Lynn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jbal@gradcenter.cuny.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">111</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1091</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Beverly-Porter, Diamond</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution of this proposal is its engagement with current research and critique of current methodologies and approaches to climate games.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> This submission could be improved by considering how climate change intersects with culture and race. Particularly engagement with the role/perspective of native communities as well as Black and Brown Communities.&#10;&#10;1.) Cutcha Risling-Baldy -http://www.cutcharislingbaldy.com/blog/on-telling-native-people-to-just-get-over-it-or-why-i-teach-about-the-walking-dead-in-my-native-studies-classes-spoiler-alert&#10;&#10;2.) Davidson, J. P. L., &amp; da Silva, F. C. (2022). Fear of a Black planet: Climate apocalypse, Anthropocene futures and Black social thought. European Journal of Social Theory, 25(4), 521-538. https://doi.org/10.1177/13684310211067980 &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1278</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Minot, Casie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission offers a compelling critique of current climate change games: most games of the genre present climate change as a global, political fall of humanity that can be restored completely with human agency and technology. Using relevant scholarship, the scholar highlights an important oversight in this narrative of climate change gameplay. Climate changes&#039; effects impact the everyday lives of individuals and local communities, and these impacts are, often, slow moving and hard to reverse.  From this, the submission offers methods, such as the workshop mentioned, in which this staple game narrative within the genre might be subverted through narrative structure and gameplay features.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission makes an important intervention in game studies, ecocriticism, and digital humanities as a whole. By historicizing narrative trends of global politics and player agency within climate change gameplay, the submission illustrates how this style of gameplay fails to recognize the deep, emotional toll of climate change as well as the potential irreversible, inherited concerns of the current climate. In doing so, the submission nods to how this style of gameplay might feed into common public narratives and attitudes around climate change. The submission then offers ways in which these gameplay tropes might be subverted through narrative structure, timing of play, and player interactions. They also place this submission into conversation with a healthy mix of contemporary and foundational scholars in these fields.&#10;&#10;Going forward, the submission might &quot;zoom out&quot; a bit more to establish a greater, more detailed sense of significance. The submission poses an exciting and rich conversation to be had about climate change narratives in gameplay. This might be more directly enriched by directly highlighting how this submission builds upon the scholars they cite to produce new research. Moreover, while the topic, methodology for subverting these tropes, and argument the submission poses certainly belongs within this area of studies, the submission might work to state its specific contributions to how their exploration extends or contributes to the realm of digital humanities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While I think this submission would do well as an individual paper, I could also see it as an engaging lightening talk given the submissions&#039; focus on a localized portion of the genre and their nod towards subversive solutions.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1107</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fitzgerald, Karina Marie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers a material output based on literature from Indigenous and feminist scholars and in collaboration with peer scholars. This is also a great exploration of the possibilities and potentials of games and gaming culture. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers potential for the future of game studies while citing specific examples of Indigenous and feminist scholarship as a framework for analysis. Designing a game as a response to existing game options and as a possible tool of futures imagination itself is embedded in the spirit of play and experimentation. I look forward to seeing how the author makes deeper connections to gaming literature, and existing examples of similar games informed by Indigenous and feminist theory. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
