    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Teach History and Languages with a Computer Game: 0 A.D. in the Classroom</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0 A.D., open source, FOSS, teaching, gaming</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;BCE-4th Century&#10;5th-14th Century&#10;software development, systems, analysis, and methods&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Game studies&#10;History&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Language acquisition&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">BCE-4th Century&#10;5th-14th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">software development, systems, analysis, and methods&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Education/Pedagogy&#10;Game studies&#10;History&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Language acquisition&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;0 A.D. is a cross-platform, scholarship-aware, and fully libre multiplayer historical real-time strategy (RTS) computer game that has been under continuous community development for over twenty years. As of May 2024, the base game features multiple ancient civilizations, all with believable architecture, attire, technologies, military techniques, and heroes – plus restored pronunciation of their original languages. Drawing from the experience of using 0 A.D. in my university-level Ancient Greek classroom, I begin by summarizing what 0 A.D. is, the game’s historical and linguistic trustworthiness, and how to use the game in-class for effective team building, historical discussion, and/or linguistic practice. Second, I explain the simplest, non-coding customization route that can make a world of difference in the classroom, namely, finding and installing realism-focused community gampeplay modifications. Third, I model how to use the game&#039;s built-in terrain editor to import real-world topological data and create special terrains for targeted historical or geographical lessons. Finally, I observe that the deep scholarly customizability that the open construction of 0 A.D. allows points to the broader potential of free and open source software for ancient history and language instruction. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0 A.D. is a cross-platform, scholarship-aware, and fully libre multiplayer historical real-time strategy (RTS) computer game that has been under continuous community development for over twenty years. As of May 2024, the base game features multiple ancient civilizations, all with believable architecture, attire, technologies, military techniques, and heroes – plus restored pronunciation of their original languages. Drawing from the experience of using 0 A.D. in my university-level Ancient Greek classroom, I begin by summarizing what 0 A.D. is, the game’s historical and linguistic trustworthiness, and how to use the game in-class for effective team building, historical discussion, and/or linguistic practice. Second, I explain the simplest, non-coding customization route that can make a world of difference in the classroom, namely, finding and installing realism-focused community gampeplay modifications. Third, I model how to use the game&#039;s built-in terrain editor to import real-world topological data and create special terrains for targeted historical or geographical lessons. Finally, I observe that the deep scholarly customizability that the open construction of 0 A.D. allows points to the broader potential of free and open source software for ancient history and language instruction.</ss:Data></Cell>
