    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1251</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tsui, Lik Hang</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission presents a unique and innovative approach to integrating the open-source historical real-time strategy game 0 A.D. into university-level ancient history and language instruction. By leveraging the game&#039;s historical and linguistic accuracy, the author demonstrates how 0 A.D. can be used for team building, historical discussion, and linguistic practice in educational settings. Additionally, it explores customization options and the potential of free and open-source software and accessible solutions for enhancing ancient history and language education.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The use of 0 A.D. as an educational tool in the college-level history classroom is novel and demonstrates a creative application of digital humanities and relevant digital tools and resources. The submission outlines a clear pedagogical framework and purpose, making it easy to understand the potential educational benefits of using this gamification approach. The focus on customization and the potential of open-source software for education is valuable and definitely relevant to our DH community. Including specific citations and describing the specific methodological approaches adopted could strengthen the academic rigor and relevance of the submission.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1304</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Giselle Pempedjian, Giselle</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission highlights the Integration of the historical real-time strategy game 0 A.D which features multiple ancient civilizations with historical and linguistic details into educational settings. It also highlights the potential for non-coding customizations and the use of the game’s terrain editor to create specialized educational content.  The game offers team building, historical discussions and linguistic practice.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission effectively outlines practical applications, such as team building, historical discussions, and linguistic practice. In addition, the potential for non-coding customizations and terrain editor use is effective.&#10;Providing more detailed examples of classroom implementation and demonstrating the impact of the game on the learning outcomes should be of great value.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1001</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lach, Pamella R.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission describes efforts to use computer games in the classroom to help achieve learning outcomes. It looks specifically at 0 A.D. as a platform for teaching ancient history and language.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The 0 A.D. game sounds intriguing as a pedagogical intervention, particularly in teaching ancient history. Virtual games and simulations are especially helpful for connecting students to the very distant past -- making it more relatable for them. There is a rich body of scholarship on pedagogical (historical) gaming—both digital and analog—and I hope the author is in dialogue with that work. I would be interested in hearing more about how teachers can modify the platform to meet their particular pedagogical needs; for instance, can this only be modified within the confines of Ancient Greece? Can it be expanded/extrapolated out to other ancient civilizations in other parts of the world (the Americas, Africa, Asia)? Which is to say, will scholars/teachers who focus on other regions or eras find this game/platform useful?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This might be a better fit as a poster, where the author can demo the platform in greater detail</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">6</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Accept as Poster</ss:Data></Cell>
