    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Raku for Multilingual Text Analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">multilingual, text analysis, NLP</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Software Studies&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;natural language processing&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Computer science&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Linguistics&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">natural language processing&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Software Studies&#10;Computer science&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Linguistics&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;I am proposing a poster on work I&#039;ve done utilizing the Raku programming language to support multilingual digital humanities, specifically computational text analysis on non-English texts. This poster will focus on my Raku package lemmatize, which can lemmatize text in 24 different languages, as well as my Raku script for detecting a text’s language, which likewise supports multilingual text processing and analysis.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;While support for multilingual digital humanities has been increasingly advocated for and discussed, including in a recent volume from Routledge, much of the work done to increase support for multilingual computational text analysis has been focused on programming languages already established as popular within the digital humanities, primarily Python. While Python is a great language for this work, with a robust community of users and available packages for performing multilingual DH work (e.g., NLTK and spaCy), this poster posits that humanities programmers, researchers, and digital humanists can benefit from expanding beyond the established realms of popular programming languages to explore the possibilities of other, less commonly used languages.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This poster will examine these Raku projects within this context, exploring the unique features of Raku that users within the humanities may find especially appealing. It will also address how the architecture and philosophy behind Raku naturally lend themselves to multilingual digital humanities work, and how the ideological foundations of a programming language and its design might be given importance within the lifecycle of a piece of humanities software.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am proposing a poster on work I&#039;ve done utilizing the Raku programming language to support multilingual digital humanities, specifically computational text analysis on non-English texts. This poster will focus on my Raku package lemmatize, which can lemmatize text in 24 different languages, as well as my Raku script for detecting a text’s language, which likewise supports multilingual text processing and analysis.&#10;While support for multilingual digital humanities has been increasingly advocated for and discussed, including in a recent volume from Routledge, much of the work done to increase support for multilingual computational text analysis has been focused on programming languages already established as popular within the digital humanities, primarily Python. While Python is a great language for this work, with a robust community of users and available packages for performing multilingual DH work (e.g., NLTK and spaCy), this poster posits that humanities programmers, researchers, and digital humanists can benefit from expanding beyond the established realms of popular programming languages to explore the possibilities of other, less commonly used languages.&#10;This poster will examine these Raku projects within this context, exploring the unique features of Raku that users within the humanities may find especially appealing. It will also address how the architecture and philosophy behind Raku naturally lend themselves to multilingual digital humanities work, and how the ideological foundations of a programming language and its design might be given importance within the lifecycle of a piece of humanities software.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Goodale, Ian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">UT-Austin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ian.goodale@austin.utexas.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ian.goodale@austin.utexas.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Goodale, Ian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ian.goodale@austin.utexas.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">CDT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">74.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">60.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">113</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1180</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karajgikar, Jajwalya</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission proposes the use of a less popular programming language Raku for its predilection towards multilingual research. It is a poster presentation which could also be a lightning talk. It makes the case for a different programming language to have a wider support group.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission is a promising piece of work that I would be interested in further learning about. It has potential benefits for the Digital Humanities community. I suggest enhancing the abstract by specifying the types of multilingual texts that can be analyzed using Raku. This will assist researchers in determining if it is suitable for their texts in various languages and scripts.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1145</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dombrowski, Quinn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission briefly describes work using the Raku programming language and developing a multilingual lemmatization package for multilingual text processing across 24 languages. It also mentions advantages of looking at programming languages outside the mainstream, though doesn&#039;t detail what those are.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This sounds like an interesting poster, and I know it&#039;s difficult with the limited length, but the submission as written feels like it&#039;s missing the substance of what would make it exciting! I had to look up Raku when reading this, and I&#039;m curious about what you see as the advantages of using both this in particular and less-widely-used programming languages in general for DH coding. You also reference the history and philosophy behind Raku without offering any details about what that&#039;s getting at. I&#039;d like to hear more, but for future proposals it&#039;d really help to be more explicit and specific about what you&#039;re getting at instead of leaving the reader to guess.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1241</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ahrenberg, Lars</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission will present the author&#039;s work on developing multilingual NLP tools in the programming language Raku, with a focus on lemmatization for 24 languages.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission refers to well-known systems for nlp such as NLTK and SpaCy but fails to explain what the author&#039;s systems can contribute that these systems cannot. The main claim is that DH researchers would &quot;benefit from expanding beyond the established realms of popular programming languages to explore the possibilities of other, less commonly used languages.&quot; There are many &#039;less commonly used languages&#039; so I would really have liked to see examples of more concrete benefits that Raku would offer, say, over Python. &#10;&#10;Some people are always eager to try out something new. For them this poster might be interesting. If the submission had pointed out that Raku belongs to the Perl family of programming languages, the numbers attracted may have been higher.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">60</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">-1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rejected</ss:Data></Cell>
