    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Unscalable Miscellaneous</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Black print culture, digital archive and preservation, the Black press</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;digital archiving&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Book and Print history&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;digital archiving&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African American/Black Studies&#10;Book and Print history</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Built upon the recent studies of digital humanities and Black print culture, this paper examines how unscalable archives reveal instability of preexisting data and demand constant revision of data as an evolving system through scrutiny. With the case of early Black newspapers, many of which have been categorized as “miscellaneous” and excluded from data structures that perpetuate the scarcity of the Black press even in the digital space, I illuminate the significant disruption of these “miscellaneous” newspapers to data. In this vein, I argue that the apparent lack of scalability of historically marginalized materials allow us to examine critically current data as an interpretative process of reimagination for data justice rather than a representative summary of archives. I focus on the digitization practice of historical Black newspapers, in order to claim their contribution to reshaping cultures of scale. Archive, categorized and preserved by institutions, is never a neutral repository of the past because most of these institutions were not immune to racism and settler colonialism. Even though historically overlooked and less-preserved prints like Black newspapers are fortunate enough to be archived and moved onto a digital space, digitizing them does not necessarily dismantle unjustly discriminative systems that delete the cosmic complexity and dynamics of Black experience because of the reductive structure of scalability. Going further from this problem, this paper suggests that historical Black newspapers resist the structure of scalability by productively disrupting seemingly representative data (like Dorothy Porter’s new cataloging system for Black-authored texts), and by expanding possibilities and presentations of scalability (like W.E.B. DuBois and his students’ data visualizations of African Americans in the U.S). &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Built upon the recent studies of digital humanities and Black print culture, this paper examines how unscalable archives reveal instability of preexisting data and demand constant revision of data as an evolving system through scrutiny. With the case of early Black newspapers, many of which have been categorized as “miscellaneous” and excluded from data structures that perpetuate the scarcity of the Black press even in the digital space, I illuminate the significant disruption of these “miscellaneous” newspapers to data. In this vein, I argue that the apparent lack of scalability of historically marginalized materials allow us to examine critically current data as an interpretative process of reimagination for data justice rather than a representative summary of archives. I focus on the digitization practice of historical Black newspapers, in order to claim their contribution to reshaping cultures of scale. Archive, categorized and preserved by institutions, is never a neutral repository of the past because most of these institutions were not immune to racism and settler colonialism. Even though historically overlooked and less-preserved prints like Black newspapers are fortunate enough to be archived and moved onto a digital space, digitizing them does not necessarily dismantle unjustly discriminative systems that delete the cosmic complexity and dynamics of Black experience because of the reductive structure of scalability. Going further from this problem, this paper suggests that historical Black newspapers resist the structure of scalability by productively disrupting seemingly representative data (like Dorothy Porter’s new cataloging system for Black-authored texts), and by expanding possibilities and presentations of scalability (like W.E.B. DuBois and his students’ data visualizations of African Americans in the U.S).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Woo, Jewon</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jwoowinter@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jwoowinter@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Woo, Jewon</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jwoowinter@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">114</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1226</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Spiro, Lisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper uses the case of digitized Black newspapers to examine the ways discriminatory practices undermine the complexity of Black experience, and it explores how they resist and expand notions of scalability.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper raises important questions about race and digital archives, using Black newspapers to interrogate ideas about scalability. It draws upon early twentieth-century scholars&#039; work on data visualization (DuBois) and cataloging (Dorothy Porter) to challenge and complicate scalability. I think this proposal would be strengthened if it better defined up front what is meant by scalability and what its significance is. While the proposal alludes to &quot;recent studies of digital humanities and Black print culture,&quot; it would be helpful to briefly ground this work in such studies. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1106</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Walton, Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper will discuss problems of scale and representation with respect to the archival preservation and digitization of historical black newspapers. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an important subject and one with significant implications for archivists and digital humanists. Scale and lack of detail (i.e., categorizing materials as &quot;miscellaneous&quot;) pose issues for preserving and categorizing the newspaper genre generally, and those issues are only further exacerbated by data racial injustices. The author makes it clear that digitization is not always enough to counteract these injustices and situates the historical black newspaper as a disruptive object. It is not completely clear what the specific aims of this paper are to be, however. This may be because the author does not identify a specific newspaper title or series or narrow to a specific city or region of the country, which would help to ground their broader argument and give audiences something concrete to engage with when considering these more theoretical issues. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I had a tough time following what the author actually intends to do in a twenty paper, but this is a good and interesting topic.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1075</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Poole, Carson Leigh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper highlights an often overlooked aspect of digital archival practice: that even digital archives, which are often seen as more &quot;objective&quot; than analog or tangible archives, cannot be separated from conversations of race, colonialism, and devaluation of historically marginalized materials. It blends digital archival practices, contemporary work being done in this subject, and issues of equity in archival practice. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I feel this paper is extremely timely and relevant. It addresses issues of how certain groups and their cultural output may be deemed &quot;miscellaneous&quot; when other groups&#039; works are deemed to have higher historical value. I feel some of the wording could be clearer—what does the paper mean by &quot;scalability&quot;, for example—but otherwise it is a very well thought out research project. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a definite YES from me. I think it is very relevant to both the conference and to contemporary digital humanities in general. The wording in the abstract is somewhat clunky at times but that does not diminish the quality and thoughtfulness of the topic. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
