    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In the last year, generative AI has been the new computer trend, one that its fans say will herald an era of new creative endeavors. However, the LLMs and algorithms have yet to be fully understood, further driving a theme of inaccessibility to today’s computing.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In the 1960s, Ted Nelson saw a very different future for computers. Coining the phrases hypertext and hypermedia, he promoted a computer-literate populace to take up computers against big companies and create a creative computer counterculture. He later published his manifesto on computer liberation in 1974, outlining his vision of empowered computing for and by the people, accessible to anyone and everyone. While idealistic, the framework defined a clear path and terms for a liberatory use of computers that can be traced back and synthesized with newer movements such as minimal computing and linked/open data.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;There are select projects from the convening decades that exemplify this vision. One such example is the 1989&#039;s Caper in the Castro, the first example of a gay video game. Ideas from Nelson&#039;s Computer Lib, as well as the strong political forces of Gay Liberation in the two decades preceding the game, collide to create a unique (hyper)text that lends itself well to an example of computing as an emancipatory practice. The analysis of the game through the dual lens of computer and gay liberation will explore the methods and themes that make the game truly revolutionary, as well as pull out strategies for changes in approaches to today&#039;s computing landscape.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In the last year, generative AI has been the new computer trend, one that its fans say will herald an era of new creative endeavors. However, the LLMs and algorithms have yet to be fully understood, further driving a theme of inaccessibility to today’s computing.&#10;In the 1960s, Ted Nelson saw a very different future for computers. Coining the phrases hypertext and hypermedia, he promoted a computer-literate populace to take up computers against big companies and create a creative computer counterculture. He later published his manifesto on computer liberation in 1974, outlining his vision of empowered computing for and by the people, accessible to anyone and everyone. While idealistic, the framework defined a clear path and terms for a liberatory use of computers that can be traced back and synthesized with newer movements such as minimal computing and linked/open data.&#10;There are select projects from the convening decades that exemplify this vision. One such example is the 1989&#039;s Caper in the Castro, the first example of a gay video game. Ideas from Nelson&#039;s Computer Lib, as well as the strong political forces of Gay Liberation in the two decades preceding the game, collide to create a unique (hyper)text that lends itself well to an example of computing as an emancipatory practice. The analysis of the game through the dual lens of computer and gay liberation will explore the methods and themes that make the game truly revolutionary, as well as pull out strategies for changes in approaches to today&#039;s computing landscape.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kerns, Halie Morgan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Binghamton University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">hkerns@binghamton.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">hkerns@binghamton.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kerns, Halie Morgan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">hkerns@binghamton.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Daylight Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">52.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">116</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1051</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Galvis, Elliot</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The examination of Caper in the Castro and framing with Ted Nelson&#039;s contributions are clearly delineated and useful, though the paper proposal is a little vague in its findings. I would recommend discarding the gesture to generative AI unless it is actually relevant as a comparison point in the examination of Caper in the Castro in the paper&#039;s analysis. It would be helpful to have a more explicit framing of what liberatory computing looks like today in addition to accessibility (other than aesthetics of counterculture). Further elaboration on the specific impacts of gay liberation movements on the game&#039;s development and hypertext would be useful as well.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1211</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rashid, Mohammed</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper uses Ted Nelson&#039;s framework of alternative modes of engaging with computers in Computer Lib/Dream Machines (1974) and the genealogy of gay liberation movements (in the West?) to explore Caper in the Castro (1989), one of the first hypertext based queer inclusive video games about a lesbian detective to show the revolutionary possibilities of hyper-text based queer games both around that decade but also its legacy today. The key argument of the paper is to explore how the game, through its use of hypertext, enables imagining alternative and emancipatory futures—the kind envisioned by both Ted Nelson and the gay liberation movement.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very interesting and important paper that explores the complex relationship between technological innovation and its social impact through the lens of queer/gay/lesbian worldmaking, especially leading up to the 1990s. As we all know, the emancipatory promises of the long 1990s that computers will be the great equalizers and solve social exclusion were largely false. Frameworks around computers used towards more emancipatory ends such as the ones championed by Ted Nelson is a good alternative here. I also think that your argument around thinking about Nelson&#039;s framework in tandem with the gay liberation movements at the time is crucial. And it is a good choice to explore a game like Caper in the Castro that is made by a transgender artist/maker, to show how hyper-text enabled the envisioning of alternative ways to think about computers. I am also very excited to see how you pull from this analysis to argue what we can do with computers today - especially in the time when generative AI poses so much socio-technical threat, something that you alluded to at the beginning of the abstract. &#10;&#10;I will also add, and I say this with care and love, that your abstract will undoubtedly benefit from some more robust theoretical underpinnings. You mention that you are drawing theoretically from Ted Nelson&#039;s work on hypertext and hypermedia, and the political landscape of gay liberation in the previous two decades. However, it is not clear from the abstract which gay liberation movements you will be drawing from. I am inclined to believe that your paper will draw from the gay liberation movement in the US - refering to the stonewall riots in 1969 and its legacy movements. Just suggesting that you may be a little more specific here as there have been gay liberation movements around the world and often western gay liberation movements are understood and communicated as the default and often times only gay liberation movement.&#10;&#10;Additionally, the major argument of the paper - that through the lens of Ted Nelson&#039;s emancipatory computer and the ethos of gay liberation, you will explore how the game is truly revolutionary. I am simply wondering if there is space and need for some clarity in regards to what you mean by revolutionary. Revolutionary in queer theory has a host of meanings - from Adelman&#039;s death drive to Munoz&#039;s pro-futurity - queer revolution and/or worldmaking resists easy categorization. Perhaps you may want to add one or two sentences around what your understanding of revolution is that is specifically coming out of this analysis of the game.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a good abstract and the audience will benefit from the analysis of hypertext based early work such as Caper in the Castro and these works explored alternative world-making. My only suggestion is that the paper requires a bit more theoretical clarity along with some clear &quot;so what&quot; arguments at the end. I have suggested these in the note to the author. Because of this, I think that the work will benefit from conversations emerging from being presented as a poster or a lightning talk rather than a full paper. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1214</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Nyikwagh, Felix</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution draws from historical events to underscore the need for democratizing technology access, promoting inclusivity, and creating a more equitable space for the practice of computing.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">By tracing how computing has evolved through the lens of Ted Nelson&#039;s concepts to modern applications, the author provides a rich historical context that offers significant insights. This offers a background to weave this discussion and deepen the understanding of the role of computing as a agent for liberation and addressing social challenges. However, you may consider making the connections between historical concepts and modern technological trends more explicit to strengthen your paper.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal shows considerable promise.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">52</ss:Data></Cell>
