    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Empowering Spanish Heritage Language Learners: A Digital and Place-Based Approach</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Spanish as a Heritage Language, Open Educational Resources, Digital Humanities, Place-Based Learning</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;open educational resources (OER)&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies&#10;Modern Languages</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital pedagogies&#10;open educational resources (OER)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies&#10;Modern Languages</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;To provide culturally and linguistically relevant Spanish as a Heritage Language (SHL) courses in the United States, many language programs are developing digital learning and teaching materials. These materials utilize various data sources, digital tools, methodologies, cultural practices, digital humanities platforms, and Open Educational Resources (OER). This approach fosters innovative knowledge production, preserving the local translingual and multilingual cultural heritages and identities of Heritage Learners (HL) of Spanish in both analog and online spaces. Current multilingual, decolonial, and postcolonial Digital Humanities (DH) initiatives address the digital age&#039;s challenges through the ethical production and representation of marginalized subjects, cultures, languages, and stories (Risam, 2019: 141). SHL sociolinguists further advocate for the development of critical language and cultural awareness among Spanish HLs, enabling them to understand the political, social, and economic power structures underlying language use and to validate and express their diverse cultural backgrounds, including US-based heritage cultures (Beaudrie &amp; Wilson, 2022: 67).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In this context, this presentation will discuss the development of a place-based Open Educational Resource (OER) designed for an introductory-level Spanish as a Heritage Language (SHL) course. This resource connects learning and teaching materials with digital technologies and tools while centering on personal, local, and regional cultural community knowledge. Through this, we encourage students to produce their own stories and knowledge resources in both analog and digital cultural records, fostering an appreciation and preservation of their trans and multilingual identities and cultural heritages. Furthermore, this presentation highlights the role of SHL and DH in fostering critical language and cultural awareness, empowering students to navigate and challenge systemic inequities.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">To provide culturally and linguistically relevant Spanish as a Heritage Language (SHL) courses in the United States, many language programs are developing digital learning and teaching materials. These materials utilize various data sources, digital tools, methodologies, cultural practices, digital humanities platforms, and Open Educational Resources (OER). This approach fosters innovative knowledge production, preserving the local translingual and multilingual cultural heritages and identities of Heritage Learners (HL) of Spanish in both analog and online spaces. Current multilingual, decolonial, and postcolonial Digital Humanities (DH) initiatives address the digital age&#039;s challenges through the ethical production and representation of marginalized subjects, cultures, languages, and stories (Risam, 2019: 141). SHL sociolinguists further advocate for the development of critical language and cultural awareness among Spanish HLs, enabling them to understand the political, social, and economic power structures underlying language use and to validate and express their diverse cultural backgrounds, including US-based heritage cultures (Beaudrie &amp; Wilson, 2022: 67).&#10;In this context, this presentation will discuss the development of a place-based Open Educational Resource (OER) designed for an introductory-level Spanish as a Heritage Language (SHL) course. This resource connects learning and teaching materials with digital technologies and tools while centering on personal, local, and regional cultural community knowledge. Through this, we encourage students to produce their own stories and knowledge resources in both analog and digital cultural records, fostering an appreciation and preservation of their trans and multilingual identities and cultural heritages. Furthermore, this presentation highlights the role of SHL and DH in fostering critical language and cultural awareness, empowering students to navigate and challenge systemic inequities.</ss:Data></Cell>
