    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1232</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Faerber-Ovaska, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author describes the creation of innovative OER materials for teaching SHL via digital and place-based pedagogies. They plan to integrate OER and digital humanities tools to connect learning materials with local / regional cultural knowledge, arguing that doing so could help students recognize the value of their translingual and multilingual identities. If critical language and cultural awareness can be developed in this way, it could help SHL learners recognize and push back against systemic inequities. Finally, encouraging students to produce their own digital and analog cultural records could be a way for SHL education to help students preserve their diverse cultural heritages. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The explanation of the presentation&#039;s scholarly context is extensive and sets the stage well. But the actual description of what was created &amp; will be presented -- what the OER material actually is -- leaves me wishing for more specific details to base this review on. Is the resource a website? A digital textbook? An annotated digital map? Putting a bit more about the nature of the instructional materials in the proposal would make it easier to understand the project and how the materials could be implemented. But I imagine that in the presentation itself, this will be revealed.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1066</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Walsh, Brandon</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The contribution discusses OER for Spanish language teaching  that is grounded in place-based experiences.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation looks very interesting! I think it points to an interesting tension and challenge for OER work — how can something be both universally relevant and applicable while also being hyper-local, specific, and grounded in personal experiences? I hope the authors will discuss this a bit more, because it sounds like the work presented here could be helpful for others working on OER in that regard. I also think it can prove to be especially challenging– how do we specifically make room for OER to be remixed by others to include their own specific needs and experiences without sacrificing the core goals of the original OER in the first place? And how do we help others technically facilitate these adaptations? I often find these are unresolved tensions for OER work, especially in my own. I put a lot of thought into putting the material out there but not so much into how to help others adapt and remix it for their own needs (and I don&#039;t think I&#039;m alone in that). &#10;&#10;These are, of course, not a critique of the abstract so much as suggested topics for discussion in the presentation. The work looks great, and I hope it is included in the program.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1141</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dabrowska, Monika</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is relevant from the point of view of Decolonizing Multilingual Pedagogies and the current challenges of language teaching in multilingual and multiethnic contexts for ethno-racial backgrounds students. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The study of the problem is interesting for the digital humanities community and relevant to the theme of the Conference. With that being said, I think there are ways that the Paper can be improved. The proposal is not particularly clear in terms of specific materials, digital tools and software, education level (only higher education?), geographic and sociocultural context. I suggest that the methodological approach should be further clarified, and more details regarding the use of didactics, tools, platforms, techniques and practices should be precised and added to the contributions. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
