    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Centering African Perspectives in Digital Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Africa, Archives, Metadata, Historical Memory, Digital Preservation</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;Africa&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital archiving&#10;meta-criticism (reflections on digital humanities and humanities computing)&#10;African/Africana Studies&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;History&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Africa&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;digital archiving&#10;meta-criticism (reflections on digital humanities and humanities computing)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;African/Africana Studies&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;History&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This roundtable brings together scholars working to develop digital humanities approaches grounded in African cultural contexts, histories, and epistemologies. The discussion will build upon the critical dialogues and initiatives highlighted at the 4th African Digital Humanities Symposium held in Accra, Ghana in February 2024. Focal areas will include the importance of language preservation amidst Africa&#039;s rich linguistic diversity; ethical and equitable representation of African cultures and histories in AI language models; the challenges of capturing oral, performative, and informal materials that make up a large part of African culture; the value of both large-scale digitization projects and smaller, curated projects tailored to specific audiences and needs; and infrastructures, funding, and collaboration among DH initiatives across the continent. Ultimately, the goal is to cultivate an African-centered digital humanities founded on preserving linguistic diversity, safeguarding cultural heritage, and an engaged use of technology sensitive to local contexts.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Relevance to Conference Focus:&lt;/strong&gt; This roundtable directly engages the conference&#039;s emphasis on anti-racist work, decolonial studies, Indigenous studies and multilingualism. The panelists will present African-oriented approaches that promote indigenous knowledge systems, maintain linguistic diversity, and increase access to cultural materials that are often overlooked or marginalized. Such approaches challenge the dominance of certain languages and cultures built into many technological tools.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Engagement with Relevant Scholarship:&lt;/strong&gt; The discussion will be grounded in a range of real-world initiatives from across the continent that model African DH praxis. For example, the 2024 Ghana Symposium featured projects focused on digital archives, culture and ephemera, artificial intelligence, African languages, and DH capacity building, among other areas. Examples of projects include Archivi.ng, the African Literary Metadata Project, the Poetry Africa Digital Map, the Yorùbá Name Project, and Digital Nollywood;  large-scale archival digitization at the Gambia National Center for Arts &amp; Culture and the Nketia Archives at the University of Ghana; and the establishment of DH Centers such as CEDHUL in Nigeria and SADiLaR in South Africa.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Framework and Purpose:&lt;/strong&gt; The roundtable is framed by the need to develop explicitly African-centered approaches to DH rooted in the continent&#039;s diverse languages, oral traditions, and local technological and cultural contexts. The session aims to highlight these approaches to a broader audience (the larger ACH community) and to stimulate thinking about how to keep these critical conversations going&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applicability, Significance, Value: &lt;/strong&gt;This roundtable foregrounds African perspectives against a mainstream DH field dominated by Anglo-European frameworks. The perspectives presented here have broad applicability for developing more pluralistic digital cultural heritage practices, challenging linguistic hegemony, and developing community-based DH approaches globally. African-centered DH frameworks enrich the entire DH field by introducing new concepts, methods and critical lenses, and raising important questions about the relationships between local and global cultural practices. These frameworks will further the development of more inclusive and representative digital initiatives that more accurately capture global cultural diversity.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Organization and Clarity: &lt;/strong&gt;This roundtable aims to offer a cohesive yet multi-faceted exploration of African-centered DH initiatives. The 75-minute session will be structured to allow ample time for both brief panelist framing and engaged audience discussion.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This roundtable brings together scholars working to develop digital humanities approaches grounded in African cultural contexts, histories, and epistemologies. The discussion will build upon the critical dialogues and initiatives highlighted at the 4th African Digital Humanities Symposium held in Accra, Ghana in February 2024. Focal areas will include the importance of language preservation amidst Africa&#039;s rich linguistic diversity; ethical and equitable representation of African cultures and histories in AI language models; the challenges of capturing oral, performative, and informal materials that make up a large part of African culture; the value of both large-scale digitization projects and smaller, curated projects tailored to specific audiences and needs; and infrastructures, funding, and collaboration among DH initiatives across the continent. Ultimately, the goal is to cultivate an African-centered digital humanities founded on preserving linguistic diversity, safeguarding cultural heritage, and an engaged use of technology sensitive to local contexts.&#10;Relevance to Conference Focus: This roundtable directly engages the conference&#039;s emphasis on anti-racist work, decolonial studies, Indigenous studies and multilingualism. The panelists will present African-oriented approaches that promote indigenous knowledge systems, maintain linguistic diversity, and increase access to cultural materials that are often overlooked or marginalized. Such approaches challenge the dominance of certain languages and cultures built into many technological tools.&#10;Engagement with Relevant Scholarship: The discussion will be grounded in a range of real-world initiatives from across the continent that model African DH praxis. For example, the 2024 Ghana Symposium featured projects focused on digital archives, culture and ephemera, artificial intelligence, African languages, and DH capacity building, among other areas. Examples of projects include Archivi.ng, the African Literary Metadata Project, the Poetry Africa Digital Map, the Yorùbá Name Project, and Digital Nollywood;  large-scale archival digitization at the Gambia National Center for Arts &amp; Culture and the Nketia Archives at the University of Ghana; and the establishment of DH Centers such as CEDHUL in Nigeria and SADiLaR in South Africa.&#10;Framework and Purpose: The roundtable is framed by the need to develop explicitly African-centered approaches to DH rooted in the continent&#039;s diverse languages, oral traditions, and local technological and cultural contexts. The session aims to highlight these approaches to a broader audience (the larger ACH community) and to stimulate thinking about how to keep these critical conversations going&#10;Applicability, Significance, Value: This roundtable foregrounds African perspectives against a mainstream DH field dominated by Anglo-European frameworks. The perspectives presented here have broad applicability for developing more pluralistic digital cultural heritage practices, challenging linguistic hegemony, and developing community-based DH approaches globally. African-centered DH frameworks enrich the entire DH field by introducing new concepts, methods and critical lenses, and raising important questions about the relationships between local and global cultural practices. These frameworks will further the development of more inclusive and representative digital initiatives that more accurately capture global cultural diversity.&#10;Organization and Clarity: This roundtable aims to offer a cohesive yet multi-faceted exploration of African-centered DH initiatives. The 75-minute session will be structured to allow ample time for both brief panelist framing and engaged audience discussion.</ss:Data></Cell>
