    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">118</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1081</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Haines, Chelsea</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This roundtable proposes to survey major digital humanities initiatives in Africa and discuss the practical, conceptual, and epistemological dimensions of African digital humanities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an excellent, well-thought out proposal that both incorporates a range of diverse digital humanities initiatives and focuses concretely on the specificities of African digital humanities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1121</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Risam, Roopika</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This roundtable will showcase the exciting and innovative work on digital humanities in several African countries. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I love the idea of sharing the important work from the African Digital Humanities Symposium at the ACH conference. This proposal also really takes advantage of the virtual format because it&#039;s bringing together folks from a variety of geographical locations and sharing insight from an in-person symposium with a (mostly) new, distributed audience. The variety of methods that will be presented will be of broad appeal. The framing in knowledge systems of African origin is important for attendees to see, as this roundtable is a great example of how to navigate tension between global and local. Something to just be sure to flag for ACH audiences is how &quot;African DH&quot; isn&#039;t a monolith, just as Africa is a continent rather than a country. Even though this should be obvious by now, we can&#039;t count on the audience to not, so it&#039;s just a point I recommend emphasizing in the roundtable.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1315</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tratarou, Adelina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The roundtable proposes a thoughtful and illuminating gathering of scholars dedicated to developing digital humanities methodologies rooted in African cultural traditions, histories, and epistemologies. Building upon the vital discussions from the 4th African Digital Humanities Symposium in Accra, Ghana, the roundtable will explore an array of pertinent themes, including language preservation, ethical representation in AI, and the challenges surrounding the digitization of oral and performative cultures.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an excellent roundtable that addresses current issues regarding the importance and implications of using DH for language preservation and the celebration of Africa&#039;s rich linguistic diversity. The roundtable&#039;s themes reflect the value of collaborative continental digitization projects, infrastructures, and funding for an ethical and equitable representation of African cultures, oral traditions, and indigenous histories in AI models through an African-centered approach to DH.&#10;&#10;The focal areas proposed for the session are both timely and critical. The emphasis on language preservation amidst Africa&#039;s remarkable linguistic diversity is particularly significant, as is the discussion of how AI language models can better account for and represent African cultures and histories. The presenters organized the roundtable with clarity and depth, demonstrating solid knowledge of and shedding light on the importance of both large-scale digitization initiatives and the value of tailored, community-centric projects. These discussions will not only highlight the pressing challenges faced by the digital humanities in Africa but also illustrate the rich potential for innovation within the field.&#10;&#10;However, one area where the roundtable could benefit from improvement is in the presenters&#039; engagement with existing scholarship. While the themes were well articulated, and the presenters were clear on their intention to ground their discussions on real-life case studies, a more direct dialogue with the current state of research would enhance the depth of the discussion. By critically situating their arguments within the broader context of digital humanities scholarship, the presenters could elevate their contributions, demonstrating a strong awareness of the field’s evolution and the ongoing debates that shape it.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
