    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Using Digital Projects to Teach about Latin American and US Hispanic Cultures</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Latin America, Hispanic, Latinx, Pedagogy, Culture, Active Learning</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;South America&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Latin American studies&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies&#10;Modern Languages</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;South America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Latin American studies&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies&#10;Modern Languages</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This presentation connects to the themes of the 2024 ACH conference by considering an approach to teaching on matters related to social justice in an international, bilingual context. Specifically, the presentation examines a model for studying Latin American and US Hispanic cultures through the use of open-access digital projects. Drawing on recent scholarship related to global and multilingual DH, we first establish a framework for thinking about Latin American and US Hispanic digital humanities as a category of scholarship with particular characteristics that reflect the history and current realities of Hispanic peoples in the Western Hemisphere. We then outline four major thematic groups into which many Latin American and US Hispanic DH projects can be organized— “Recovery and Repatriation,” “Reimagining Spaces,” “Accessing Unheard Voices,” and “Making Visible the Unseen.” We identify examples of current projects that intersect with each of these themes, suggesting ways that they can be employed in active, experiential ways in courses taught in either English or Spanish. We also consider ways that hands-on, public-facing digital humanities work related to Latin American and US Hispanic cultures can be integrated into courses of this type. The central argument of this presentation is that using digital projects to teach about the cultures of Latin America and Hispanics in the US can provide students with valuable insights, experiences, and skills that may not be available when addressing these topics in more traditional ways.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation connects to the themes of the 2024 ACH conference by considering an approach to teaching on matters related to social justice in an international, bilingual context. Specifically, the presentation examines a model for studying Latin American and US Hispanic cultures through the use of open-access digital projects. Drawing on recent scholarship related to global and multilingual DH, we first establish a framework for thinking about Latin American and US Hispanic digital humanities as a category of scholarship with particular characteristics that reflect the history and current realities of Hispanic peoples in the Western Hemisphere. We then outline four major thematic groups into which many Latin American and US Hispanic DH projects can be organized— “Recovery and Repatriation,” “Reimagining Spaces,” “Accessing Unheard Voices,” and “Making Visible the Unseen.” We identify examples of current projects that intersect with each of these themes, suggesting ways that they can be employed in active, experiential ways in courses taught in either English or Spanish. We also consider ways that hands-on, public-facing digital humanities work related to Latin American and US Hispanic cultures can be integrated into courses of this type. The central argument of this presentation is that using digital projects to teach about the cultures of Latin America and Hispanics in the US can provide students with valuable insights, experiences, and skills that may not be available when addressing these topics in more traditional ways.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">McCarl, Clayton</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Univ. of North Florida</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">clayton.mccarl@unf.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">clayton.mccarl@unf.edu, n01451679@unf.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">McCarl, Clayton;&#10;Manwell, Peri</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">clayton.mccarl@unf.edu;&#10;n01451679@unf.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern (New York)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">120</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1003</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fernandez, Sylvia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submissions highlights a case study of teaching with open access digital projects of Latin American and US Hispanic cultures, histories and representations. This pedagogy emphasises the use of bilingual content taught in English and Spanish courses and is fostering new ways of teaching using this type of digital projects that enable students to analyze and be knowledge producer adquiring new skills. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal presents a very needed approach to incorporate open access digital projects of Latin America and US Hispanic in Spanish and English courses and analyze them through a social justice approach for students to adquire new skills different from traditional ways of teaching these topics. The proposal lacks of engaging with relevant scholarship of multilingualism and social justice pedagogies to approach digital projects from non-Western contexts. It will be great to reference current scholarship from Latin America in regards to this areas of teaching and public engagement. I will recommend the authors to address how they are fostering a critical analysis ofthese projects considering the differences of producing digital scholarship from Latin American and Hispanic cultures. Looking forward to this presentation!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1110</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rutner, Jennifer</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper will share a model for studying Latin American and US Hispanic cultures through the use of open-access digital projects. The paper will outline a framework for categorizing and incorporating existing DH projects into undergraduate curriculum, as well as the learning outcomes and impact for students. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal is very strong, and meets the submission criteria for the ACH conference. Engaging DH projects in pedagogies and curriculums on Latin American and Caribbean studies not only exposes students to new methodologies, but allows &quot;non-traditional&quot; information sources to be considered. One strength is the inclusion of a framework for categorizing and evaluating DH projects according to the values of the field, including “Recovery and Repatriation,” “Reimagining Spaces,” “Accessing Unheard Voices,” and “Making Visible the Unseen.” This is an exemplary practice, and a fantastic example of how DH supports the diversification of methodologies in the humanities. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1250</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gauthereau, Lorena</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation is focused on digital pedagogy for the area of Latin American studies and US Latino studies, specifically focused on open-access projects.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this presentation will be extremely valuable as it will highlight how to integrate already-made digital projects into the classroom. I think this is a pedagogical topic that many attendees will find helpful as they seek new ways to integrate DH into the classroom in different ways. The abstract could be strengthened by including some examples of projects as well as defining the theoretical lens. Work such as this benefits from drawing from not just Western European DH theories, but also--and more importantly--from Latino and Latin American studies theory, Latino and Latin American DH theory, and multilingual DH theory.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
