    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Exploring Data Science Services and Training in US University Libraries: Best Practices, Challenges, and Strategies for Promoting Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data science, AI, US Libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;data modeling&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;data modeling&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;With the exponential rise in demand for data science skills, US university libraries have been involved in providing data science services. This study aims to explore services and training provided by data science units within US university libraries, identifying best practices, successful methods, and common challenges and exploring effective approaches for fostering diversity, equity, and inclusion within data science education. The study asks four research questions: What explains variations in data science services at US university libraries? Why are certain strategies successful, while others fall short? What makes data science units effective in adapting to increasing demand for providing AI training? How can diversity, equity, and inclusion be effectively promoted within data science? To answer these research questions, a mixed-methods approach will be used: Semi-structured interviews with key personnel from data science units in US university libraries to gain in-depth insights into their strategies, challenges, and experiences; Surveys to collect quantitative data on the services provided, user satisfaction, registration, attendance, and perceived effectiveness of various strategies; Quantitative data collection from internet sources, including web descriptions of services provided by university library data science units. The findings will contribute to the body of research in library data science, research training, and services, thereby advancing the existing knowledge in these areas. Moreover, this study extends to informing the development of effective strategies that enhance data science education and services within university libraries. The study addresses crucial aspects of the evolving needs of the job market, ensuring that educational and service strategies are aligned with equity principles.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">With the exponential rise in demand for data science skills, US university libraries have been involved in providing data science services. This study aims to explore services and training provided by data science units within US university libraries, identifying best practices, successful methods, and common challenges and exploring effective approaches for fostering diversity, equity, and inclusion within data science education. The study asks four research questions: What explains variations in data science services at US university libraries? Why are certain strategies successful, while others fall short? What makes data science units effective in adapting to increasing demand for providing AI training? How can diversity, equity, and inclusion be effectively promoted within data science? To answer these research questions, a mixed-methods approach will be used: Semi-structured interviews with key personnel from data science units in US university libraries to gain in-depth insights into their strategies, challenges, and experiences; Surveys to collect quantitative data on the services provided, user satisfaction, registration, attendance, and perceived effectiveness of various strategies; Quantitative data collection from internet sources, including web descriptions of services provided by university library data science units. The findings will contribute to the body of research in library data science, research training, and services, thereby advancing the existing knowledge in these areas. Moreover, this study extends to informing the development of effective strategies that enhance data science education and services within university libraries. The study addresses crucial aspects of the evolving needs of the job market, ensuring that educational and service strategies are aligned with equity principles.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
