    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Abbasov, Namig</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">namig.abbasov@asu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Mountain Standard Time(Phoenix)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">121</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1191</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Giannetti, Francesca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper uses a mixed method approach---semi-structured interviews and survey data---to improve our understanding of data science pedagogy delivered by academic library units.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper connects to the conference theme by including a diversity and equity question among their four research questions, namely how DEI may successfully be promoted in data science pedagogy. The author connects successful data science instruction to job readiness.&#10;&#10;A suggestion to define what data science means to the author. Does it include digital humanities or not? The author perhaps already perceives that &quot;data science&quot; could be construed as a faddish term, similar to the way &quot;digital humanities&quot; spiked in popularity ten or so years ago, and &quot;artificial intelligence&quot; is currently everywhere. Drawing lines of connection between any of these terms and future employability may be difficult. Also, is there be merit in learning this material beyond the instrumentalist aim of getting a job?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1024</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brooks, Mackenzie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The goal of this submission is to survey the services provided by US libraries in support of data science units in order to determine best practices and DEI appraoches. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I would be very interested in hearing about the results of this work - DS programs are growing at a rapid rate and it is essential for libraries to be involved. They have a lot to contribute to the field - in areas of DEI, ethics, collections, instruction, info/data/digital literacy, etc. &#10;&#10;The proposed project is ambitious though and I can easily imagine multiple papers from this survey and analysis work. If accepted, I would like to see more detail on the methods and framework selected, as well as the prior scholarship in the field. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1050</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shin, Lisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A paper that examines data science services within US academic libraries specifically looking at service variance, service delivery, AI, and EDI. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">An important study that examines data science programs in academic libraries through different lenses including EDI and AI. It may be too ambitious to cover all of these topics in a single study, but the findings would still be interesting and can be expanded upon on through future research. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
