    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Emerging Pathways to Supporting Digital Humanities Research on Copyrighted Literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">copyright, collections as data, digital libraries, text mining, cultural analytics</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;copyright, licensing, and permissions standards, systems, and processes&#10;cultural analytics&#10;digital libraries creation, management, and analysis&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Law and legal studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Literary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">copyright, licensing, and permissions standards, systems, and processes&#10;cultural analytics&#10;digital libraries creation, management, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cultural studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Law and legal studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Literary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This roundtable will explore emerging methods and practices for scholarly research on copyrighted corpora, with a focus on digital humanities projects involving library stewardship of contemporary literature datasets. Roundtable participants include librarians and scholars working at private and public U.S. universities (Stanford University, University of California Berkeley, Texas A&amp;M University, and Temple University) with relevant projects and experiences developing and sharing datasets of copyrighted collections.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Roundtable participants will first reflect on shifting digitization practices at their institutions over the last decade, with a focus on recent developments for expediting the creation of large datasets. This discussion will be framed by the presentation of findings-in-progress from the forthcoming IMLS-sponsored “Data Speculations: A National Forum on Library Digital Stewardship for Copyrighted Contemporary Culture.” Participants will then focus the conversation on projects funded in 2023 by the Mellon Foundation under their “Text and Data Mining: Demonstrating Fair Use” project, involving librarians and scholars leveraging recent exemptions to copyright law allowing their respective institutions to transform eBooks into digital corpora for research purposes.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Fall of 2024 is an opportune moment for this discussion: we anticipate a ruling from the U.S. Copyright Office on the 1998 Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA) exemptions 37 C.F.R. 201.40(b)(4 &amp; 5) around the time of the Association for Computers in the Humanities (ACH) conference. Exemptions to the DMCA for research purposes have enabled scholars, when supported by academic libraries, to quickly develop large datasets of texts and motion pictures for research purposes. However, limitations to the Exemption have forced researchers to work in silos, unable to preserve and share these datasets with other interested researchers. The awaited Copyright Office ruling may expand, or reduce, the scope of the DMCA exemption, and will certainly change how corpora of copyrighted collections will be developed, analyzed, and shared.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Research access to digital corpora of copyrighted materials is a longstanding concern to digital humanities practitioners and ACH members. As ACH’s letter supporting expansion of the DCMA exemption argues, the process of building these research corpora is non-trivial: “Even in the most ideal context of well-resourced institutions with robust data-storage and computational infrastructure, and staff expertise on both the library and computing side, these scholars have found the process &quot;slow, painful, and expensive&quot;, to quote the title of a forthcoming paper from the Stanford Literary Lab” (Dombrowski, 2023). Recently, the rise of GenerativeAI has heightened concerns over unauthorized or commercial access to digital corpora, presenting additional obstacles for researchers looking to do this work in risk-averse institutions.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This roundtable offers an opportunity for participants to share the background to their projects, lessons learned for curating copyrighted collections, and new possibilities for research opened up by the DMCA exemption. After a forty minute moderated discussion among the roundtable participants, for the remainder of the session, the audience will be invited to ask questions and share anecdotes relevant to building and analyzing copyrighted literary corpora. We aim for the discussion to raise more awareness about the rising demand, and ongoing obstacles, to working with copyrighted collections as data. By expanding the emerging community of practice at the intersection of copyright and cultural analytics, we hope these discussions can inform next steps in coordinating scholarly activities and advocacy.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This roundtable will explore emerging methods and practices for scholarly research on copyrighted corpora, with a focus on digital humanities projects involving library stewardship of contemporary literature datasets. Roundtable participants include librarians and scholars working at private and public U.S. universities (Stanford University, University of California Berkeley, Texas A&amp;M University, and Temple University) with relevant projects and experiences developing and sharing datasets of copyrighted collections.&#10;Roundtable participants will first reflect on shifting digitization practices at their institutions over the last decade, with a focus on recent developments for expediting the creation of large datasets. This discussion will be framed by the presentation of findings-in-progress from the forthcoming IMLS-sponsored “Data Speculations: A National Forum on Library Digital Stewardship for Copyrighted Contemporary Culture.” Participants will then focus the conversation on projects funded in 2023 by the Mellon Foundation under their “Text and Data Mining: Demonstrating Fair Use” project, involving librarians and scholars leveraging recent exemptions to copyright law allowing their respective institutions to transform eBooks into digital corpora for research purposes.&#10;Fall of 2024 is an opportune moment for this discussion: we anticipate a ruling from the U.S. Copyright Office on the 1998 Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA) exemptions 37 C.F.R. 201.40(b)(4 &amp; 5) around the time of the Association for Computers in the Humanities (ACH) conference. Exemptions to the DMCA for research purposes have enabled scholars, when supported by academic libraries, to quickly develop large datasets of texts and motion pictures for research purposes. However, limitations to the Exemption have forced researchers to work in silos, unable to preserve and share these datasets with other interested researchers. The awaited Copyright Office ruling may expand, or reduce, the scope of the DMCA exemption, and will certainly change how corpora of copyrighted collections will be developed, analyzed, and shared.&#10;Research access to digital corpora of copyrighted materials is a longstanding concern to digital humanities practitioners and ACH members. As ACH’s letter supporting expansion of the DCMA exemption argues, the process of building these research corpora is non-trivial: “Even in the most ideal context of well-resourced institutions with robust data-storage and computational infrastructure, and staff expertise on both the library and computing side, these scholars have found the process &quot;slow, painful, and expensive&quot;, to quote the title of a forthcoming paper from the Stanford Literary Lab” (Dombrowski, 2023). Recently, the rise of GenerativeAI has heightened concerns over unauthorized or commercial access to digital corpora, presenting additional obstacles for researchers looking to do this work in risk-averse institutions.&#10;This roundtable offers an opportunity for participants to share the background to their projects, lessons learned for curating copyrighted collections, and new possibilities for research opened up by the DMCA exemption. After a forty minute moderated discussion among the roundtable participants, for the remainder of the session, the audience will be invited to ask questions and share anecdotes relevant to building and analyzing copyrighted literary corpora. We aim for the discussion to raise more awareness about the rising demand, and ongoing obstacles, to working with copyrighted collections as data. By expanding the emerging community of practice at the intersection of copyright and cultural analytics, we hope these discussions can inform next steps in coordinating scholarly activities and advocacy.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
