    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wermer-Colan, Henry Alexander</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Temple University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">alwermercolan@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">alwermercolan@gmail.com, spotvin@tamu.edu, qad@stanford.edu, malgeehe@stanford.edu, rsamberg@berkeley.edu, jaszipeter@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wermer-Colan, Alex;&#10;Potvin, Sarah;&#10;Dombrowski, Quinn;&#10;Algee-Hewitt, Mark;&#10;Jaszi, Peter</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">alwermercolan@gmail.com;&#10;spotvin@tamu.edu;&#10;qad@stanford.edu;&#10;malgeehe@stanford.edu;&#10;jaszipeter@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST, CST, PST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">89.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">123</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1294</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Croxall, Brian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This panel will discuss the challenges of creating corpora of in-copyright literature. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a timely and strong proposal that focuses on the challenges associated with creating (and maintaining) corpora of in-copyright literature. This is something that DH scholars have worked with for decades, so it&#039;s not a new topic, but the authors provide context to highlight why this conversation is appropriate at the given moment. It&#039;s particularly interesting to see that the conversation is centered around library involvement in this practice rather than (as in my case) individual scholars working on their own and in the periphery.&#10;&#10;If I were to criticize one aspect of the proposal it is that the authors have spent so much time providing background and context that it&#039;s less clear what will be discussed during the panel. Do the organizers already have questions in mind for the 40-minute moderated discussion? Will presenters make opening statements and, if so, how long will they be? I know from experience that panels are one of the hardest things to wrangle, so more details would be appreciated here. &#10;&#10;But honestly, this is a strong proposal and I will absolutely be in attendance.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1118</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Forster, Chris</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This panel addresses the still thorny problem of copyright in relation to research corpora. It will provide an opportunity for librarians and scholars in this area to share the most recent developments in this area from a range of perspectives. This question is pressing both because of legal developments (rulings from the copyright office) and developments like &quot;AI.&quot;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a strong proposal for a roundtable that I would delighted to attend. While I assume that the HathiTrust model of research &quot;data capsules&quot; to allow research on copyright material would be one of the &quot;silos&quot; that are mentioned by the proposal, I would be interested in more fine-grained specifics about both the siloing, about its costs, and alternatives. &#10;&#10;While the proposal mentions &quot;texts and motion pictures,&quot; it seems to me that this discussion remains quite text-centric, even as other media become more important pressing. My suspicion is that the challenges facing researchers on film, for instance, would be much greater than those working on text.&#10;&#10;The proposal rightly notes that the rise of &quot;GenerativeAI&quot; complicates these matters---though it seems to me this complication is complicated indeed! For the rights of non-consumptive use that researchers rely on, and seek to expand, sound very much like the rights that contemporary AI companies are claiming. &#10;&#10;Finally, while the proposal does not explicitly highlight &quot;anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, and/or multilingualism,&quot; I would note that hurdles to work on in-copyright material may have the effect of &quot;whitening&quot; easily available research corpora, and so this roundtable&#039;s interest in expanding and easing access DOES have a social justice element that this proposal does not make explicit.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sounds great to me!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1182</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boehlert, Krystal</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This roundtable will discuss strategies for supporting digital scholarship projects and large data sets in an evolving copyright landscape.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This session will be very valuable for both scholars and technologists and library workers advocating for the shareability of these projects. I appreciate the nod to how AI is affecting institutions especially risk-averse organizations.&#10;&#10;You&#039;ve mentioned &quot;slow, painful, and expensive&quot; so I hope to see some inclusion of the cost constraints, specifically around storage as the field shifts between in-house and cloud solutions.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
