    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Exploring Ukrainian Language Collections in US Libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ukrainian language, Ukrainian refugees, mapping, collection development</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;bibliographic analysis&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization&#10;Anthropology&#10;Geography and Geo-Humanities&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Bibliographical Studies&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bibliographic analysis&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Anthropology&#10;Geography and Geo-Humanities&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Bibliographical Studies&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&#10;&lt;p&gt;Over 270,000 Ukrainians have come to the US since the February 2022 invasion of Ukraine. This has raised demand for Ukrainian language materials that some public libraries have struggled to meet. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This paper will describe how we used bibliographic data to build an interactive map to explore the current landscape of Ukrainian language collections in libraries, a preliminary step in our ongoing work to help libraries build Ukrainian collections to serve refugee communities. First, we compiled bibliographic and holdings data from OCLC records to determine the size of Ukrainian collections across OCLC member libraries. We used OCLC&#039;s information on library locations and types to build an interactive map of collection locations and sizes. We partnered with a high school student volunteer to assist with data collection and visualization. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The map is a user-friendly, intuitive interface for discovering libraries with strong Ukrainian collections, as well as geographic areas that are underserved. We plan to use it to inform further research on barriers to and strategies for collecting Ukrainian language materials, such as development and dissemination of a survey. The map is also publicly available as a tool to help Ukrainian communities and allies discover nearby collections and plan advocacy. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This presentation may be of interest to those interested in assisting Ukrainian refugee communities, preserving Ukrainian language and heritage, and in large-scale interlibrary collection assessment according to features like language. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Over 270,000 Ukrainians have come to the US since the February 2022 invasion of Ukraine. This has raised demand for Ukrainian language materials that some public libraries have struggled to meet. &#10;This paper will describe how we used bibliographic data to build an interactive map to explore the current landscape of Ukrainian language collections in libraries, a preliminary step in our ongoing work to help libraries build Ukrainian collections to serve refugee communities. First, we compiled bibliographic and holdings data from OCLC records to determine the size of Ukrainian collections across OCLC member libraries. We used OCLC&#039;s information on library locations and types to build an interactive map of collection locations and sizes. We partnered with a high school student volunteer to assist with data collection and visualization. &#10;The map is a user-friendly, intuitive interface for discovering libraries with strong Ukrainian collections, as well as geographic areas that are underserved. We plan to use it to inform further research on barriers to and strategies for collecting Ukrainian language materials, such as development and dissemination of a survey. The map is also publicly available as a tool to help Ukrainian communities and allies discover nearby collections and plan advocacy. &#10;This presentation may be of interest to those interested in assisting Ukrainian refugee communities, preserving Ukrainian language and heritage, and in large-scale interlibrary collection assessment according to features like language.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
