    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">PST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">81.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">124</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1257</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Burress, Theresa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This individual paper will describe a geospatial visualization of bibliographic data on Ukranian language collections in United States libraries; this project has the potential to provide essential information to libraries and institutions serving Ukrainian communities across the U.S.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This individual paper will describe a geospatial visualization of bibliographic data on Ukranian language collections in United States libraries; this project has the potential to provide essential information to libraries and institutions serving Ukrainian communities across the U.S. This abstract describes a compelling, creative geospatial project that will be of high interest to the broader DH community. It would be very helpful to the audience if the authors could also provide some background and context on whether/how this project builds on past geospatial visualizations of collections at this level. More information on how the methodology and approach was developed or adapted would also be valuable.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal seems original and very creative, with a purpose based in social justice and accessibility, thus very compelling. I did a quick search in a couple of databases, but didn&#039;t really see anything related.  So -- I would have loved to recommend this as a 10, but based on the criteria, the lack of literature review or theoretical underpinnings made it difficult to rate higher.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1237</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Baciu, Dan C.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&#10;&#10;&quot;Exploring Ukrainian Language Collections in US Libraries&quot; by Emily Sarah Cukier, Ruslan Mukhamedvaleev, and Gabriella Reznowski is a timely and significant contribution to the discourse on supporting refugee communities through library resources. As the abstract notes, the influx of over 270,000 Ukrainians into the United States since the 2022 invasion has created a pressing need for Ukrainian language materials, which many public libraries are currently unprepared to meet.&#10;&#10;The authors have undertaken a comprehensive approach to address this gap by using bibliographic data to build an interactive map, which serves as a crucial preliminary step in enhancing the accessibility of Ukrainian language collections. The methodology employed in the study is robust: compiling bibliographic and holdings data from OCLC records and leveraging OCLC&#039;s library location data to map out collection sizes and locations. This effort is particularly commendable given the challenges inherent in large-scale data aggregation and visualization.&#10;&#10;A notable aspect of the project is the involvement of a high school student in the data collection and visualization process. This not only highlights the collaborative spirit of the initiative but also underscores the importance of engaging younger generations in cultural preservation and community support efforts.&#10;&#10;The resulting interactive map is described as a user-friendly and intuitive tool that allows for easy discovery of libraries with significant Ukrainian collections. Its utility extends beyond academic circles to Ukrainian communities and their allies, facilitating both advocacy and practical access to resources. The authors’ future plans to use the map for further research on barriers and strategies for collecting Ukrainian materials are well-founded and promise to yield valuable insights.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Excellent abstract that we have recommended for acceptance. Perhaps the paper could benefit from a review of geographical discovery in collections of text, going beyond bibliographic data and using also geographic data decoded from text as done in Kajarekar 2023, Geospatial discovery in collections of text. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1191</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Giannetti, Francesca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper describes an activist intervention in which digital humanities methods (mapping of bibliographic data) were applied to an emerging community need: Ukranian language materials in public libraries for Ukranian refugees.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I appreciate the K-12 angle with the integration of a high school student volunteer and presumed heritage language speaker. I would be curious to know of any challenges or difficulties in working with OCLC data, since they tend to be rather chary of sharing (alas). I assume the project link has been held back to continue work, but please do share it during the presentation. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
