    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Performing Non-relationality and AI Ethics: A Critical Study on Movement, Mobility, and Posthuman Performativity in Delivery Algorithm</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">AI ethics, algorithmic justice, STS, deep learning, posthuman performativity, delivery algorithm, critical AI studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;Asia&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Performance studies: Dance &amp; Theatre&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Race Studies&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Performance studies: Dance &amp; Theatre&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This paper explores the ethics of artificial intelligence from a non-relational perspective, addressing the gap in current discussions in AI ethics. By examining algorithmic models in delivery platforms exploiting low-cost labor, identified as AI colonialism by Karen Hao (2022), the research emphasizes the need for de-anthropocentric AI and highlights challenges related to the opacity of deep neural networks. Based on Axelle Karera’s concept of “non-relationality”, I propose the concept of &quot;non-relationality&quot; to offer a critique on the discourse of AI colonialism regarding its potential anthropocentric politics. Through analyzing the food delivery case in Shanghai, this paper aims to generate decentralized sociotechnical imaginaries on AI and prompt a reconsideration of object-oriented mobility and reparative political possibility. Last but not least, I propose through the delivery case, performance studies offer a fluid space to discuss AI ethics.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper explores the ethics of artificial intelligence from a non-relational perspective, addressing the gap in current discussions in AI ethics. By examining algorithmic models in delivery platforms exploiting low-cost labor, identified as AI colonialism by Karen Hao (2022), the research emphasizes the need for de-anthropocentric AI and highlights challenges related to the opacity of deep neural networks. Based on Axelle Karera’s concept of “non-relationality”, I propose the concept of &quot;non-relationality&quot; to offer a critique on the discourse of AI colonialism regarding its potential anthropocentric politics. Through analyzing the food delivery case in Shanghai, this paper aims to generate decentralized sociotechnical imaginaries on AI and prompt a reconsideration of object-oriented mobility and reparative political possibility. Last but not least, I propose through the delivery case, performance studies offer a fluid space to discuss AI ethics.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wu, Menghang</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ohio State University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">wu.4899@osu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">wu.4899@osu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wu, Menghang</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">wu.4899@osu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">74.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">126</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1211</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rashid, Mohammed</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper uses Chinese food delivery platforms as case studies to show how their algorithmic models reappropriate AI and data colonialism. It claims to address a gap in current discussions around AI ethics, exploring it from non-relational perspective as opposed to tabular relations that are more rigid and therefore less flexible. The project puts forward a case for de-anthropocentric AI, which in the context of this paper, I am hoping is a more inclusive AI model. The paper also provides alternative possibilities that are more reparative from a performance studies perspective.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Firstly, very well written abstract. Outlining of the problem, theoretical framing, case study, and consideration for possible alternatives are very strongly portrayed. Exploring algorithmic models in delivery platforms and applications is not necessarily new, however, analyzing these platforms from the perspective of non-relational database approach is very interesting, and I am eager to see where this leads. I am also interested to see how the paper mobilizes Karera&#039;s concept of &quot;non-relationality&quot; to critique discourses of AI colonialism. &#10;&#10;The paper&#039;s analysis of food delivery cases in Shanghai and the claim to generate decentralized socio-technical imaginaries of AI and reparative political possibilities are also very intriguing. However, I am also wondering if it is the same platform that uses discourses of AI colonialism and participates in cheap labor exploitation, that is also faclitating alternative possibilities for ethical AI? Or are there different case studies, perhaps alternative platforms or applications that enable the possibility of more ethical possibilities? This much was not clear from the abstract.&#10;&#10;The trajectory towards performance studies as an inter-disciplinary space to discuss AI ethics, while very interesting, feels forced. What would the paper gain from this turn that is already not gained from analyzing the case studies. If there is substantial rationale, keep it. If not, the author may consider this as a different project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very intriguing paper. I urge the program committee to accept this paper as a full paper in panels on delivery platforms/applications, ethical AI, the philosophy of AI, and socio-technical systems. The complexity of the ideas requires a mode of unpacking that is not suitable for a lightning talk or a poster.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1180</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karajgikar, Jajwalya</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission is a examination of &quot;non-relationality&quot; in reference to AI colonialism via a food delivery case study and performance studies. It is a paper presentation which focuses on the geographical area of Shanghai in its case study.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a submission I am excited to learn more about. I would be interested in understanding more of the performance studies and case study connection to AI and non-relationality in some more detail in the abstract.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1248</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Knox, John Thomas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper engages with recent advances in AI technologies by offering a critique of some current AI technologies and use cases via a decolonizing framework.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am intrigued by the use of non-relationality here. I would be interested to learn more about the specific AI technologies and use cases that will be examined as well as more about how the concept of anthropocentricity is being utilized. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
