    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">How students are engaging in critical public and digital humanities efforts on Wikipedia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">open, pedagogy, humanities, equity, access</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;18th Century&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;History&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;open educational resources (OER)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">18th Century&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;open educational resources (OER)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African American/Black Studies&#10;History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;As digital humanities and other public-facing projects evolve, they must not only consider but directly address the ever-intensifying crisis of information access and integrity confronting the world. Pedagogical praxis can play a critical role in meeting the challenges of this rapidly changing information landscape. In this roundtable, you will hear from faculty at postsecondary institutions who have centered public humanities work into their courses by implementing assignments that enable students to contribute to Wikipedia. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In 2010, the Wikipedia Student Program launched and merged the rapidly developing movements of open knowledge with open pedagogy. Its program aimed to help students at institutions of higher education develop a range of critical skills while improving Wikipedia content. Facilitated by Wiki Education, which provides robust support, students from postsecondary institutions contribute to Wikipedia in course assignments. Since its inception, the program has only become more relevant as the looming information crisis has intensified. The program’s scope is such that over ten thousand students are contributing over ten million words to Wikipedia each year, and their impact can be seen in virtually every topic area&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The panelists represent the fields of Middle Eastern History, African-American Literature, and Jewish History. We will explore the power dynamics embedded within the collaborative production and dissemination of knowledge; the cultivation of a sense of  authorship, responsibility, and developing a public voice; Wikipedia’s limitations and biases; and issues surrounding access to knowledge and equity. We will consider the roles that  students can play in ensuring that content on Wikipedia is accurate, fair, and representative. We will consider how the process of contributing to Wikipedia can empower students by building their confidence as public intellectuals while providing them with opportunities for promoting social justice by presenting knowledge on topics that have  historically been left out of the record. The roundtable will also relate Wikipedia initiatives to debates over the rapidly growing production and dissemination of AI-generated content. Session attendees will learn how to integrate the Wikipedia assignment into their own humanities curricula while gaining a deeper understanding of the role that open knowledge and student-centered research and writing can play in public and digital humanities projects.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As digital humanities and other public-facing projects evolve, they must not only consider but directly address the ever-intensifying crisis of information access and integrity confronting the world. Pedagogical praxis can play a critical role in meeting the challenges of this rapidly changing information landscape. In this roundtable, you will hear from faculty at postsecondary institutions who have centered public humanities work into their courses by implementing assignments that enable students to contribute to Wikipedia. &#10; &#10;In 2010, the Wikipedia Student Program launched and merged the rapidly developing movements of open knowledge with open pedagogy. Its program aimed to help students at institutions of higher education develop a range of critical skills while improving Wikipedia content. Facilitated by Wiki Education, which provides robust support, students from postsecondary institutions contribute to Wikipedia in course assignments. Since its inception, the program has only become more relevant as the looming information crisis has intensified. The program’s scope is such that over ten thousand students are contributing over ten million words to Wikipedia each year, and their impact can be seen in virtually every topic area&#10; &#10;The panelists represent the fields of Middle Eastern History, African-American Literature, and Jewish History. We will explore the power dynamics embedded within the collaborative production and dissemination of knowledge; the cultivation of a sense of authorship, responsibility, and developing a public voice; Wikipedia’s limitations and biases; and issues surrounding access to knowledge and equity. We will consider the roles that students can play in ensuring that content on Wikipedia is accurate, fair, and representative. We will consider how the process of contributing to Wikipedia can empower students by building their confidence as public intellectuals while providing them with opportunities for promoting social justice by presenting knowledge on topics that have historically been left out of the record. The roundtable will also relate Wikipedia initiatives to debates over the rapidly growing production and dissemination of AI-generated content. Session attendees will learn how to integrate the Wikipedia assignment into their own humanities curricula while gaining a deeper understanding of the role that open knowledge and student-centered research and writing can play in public and digital humanities projects.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Blumenthal, Helaine</ss:Data></Cell>
