    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">helaine@wikiedu.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">helaine@wikiedu.org, hsharkey@sas.upenn.edu, sklein@chapman.edu, steve011@ua.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Blumenthal, Helaine;&#10;Sharkey, Heather J.;&#10;Klein, Shira;&#10;Steverson, Delia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">helaine@wikiedu.org;&#10;hsharkey@sas.upenn.edu;&#10;sklein@chapman.edu;&#10;steve011@ua.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Centarl, Pacific, GMT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">85.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">127</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1098</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Howard, Jacquelyne Thoni</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Provides various perspectives on integrating Wikipedia assignments in the classroom. It focuses on making students agentic co-educators and presents knowledge as constructed. I was intrigued by this point where they say they help students by &quot;building their confidence as public intellectuals while providing them with opportunities for promoting social justice by presenting knowledge on topics that have historically been left out of the record.&quot; </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I like that this topic is set up as a panel, where the audience can hear a variety of perspectives about assignment integrations. I also like how this panel focuses on centering the student experience in discussing not only what they contribute but also what they get out of the experience. I think focusing on how students become agentic co-educators through this assignment and how instructors present knowledge as constructed will resonate well with the audience. I was intrigued by this point where you say they help students by &quot;building their confidence as public intellectuals while providing them with opportunities for promoting social justice by presenting knowledge on topics that have historically been left out of the record.&quot;  I would be interested in knowing more about why teaching students to be &quot;public intellectuals&quot; is important in the context of modern society (maybe add some brief literature around this) and what kinds of topics are being covered by students (who or what work is being highlighted by students). </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1146</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Mello, Jr., Lawrence Joseph</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Round Table topic of “How students are engaging in critical public and digital humanities efforts on Wikipedia” involves many interesting facets that are not only important topics that align with this conference but also bring an essential light on the issue of how today and tomorrow’s students are viewed. The uniqueness of the panelists should lend to a very informative discussion and interaction with the audience. This is on top of the overall topic of today’s students engaging with such projects as the digital humanities efforts of Wikipedia, which should help shed a more positive light on the younger generation and their ability and compassion to involve their critical thinking skills in larger projects that affect people far beyond their world. I feel that those who attend will walk away from it better for attending and also have a greater appreciation for the humanities and the importance of making knowledge more accessible.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1231</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Otis, Jessica</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a roundtable on teaching with Wikipedia, specifically working with Wiki Edu to have students contribute to Wikipedia on a variety of historical topics. Some audience participation is expected.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is generally an interesting proposal. While it&#039;s unclear if it&#039;s breaking significant new ground in discussing work teachers and students have been already doing on Wikipedia, its participatory nature and its nod towards how AI is changing pedagogy will make it a worthy addition to the conference program. &#10;&#10;Because this proposal is framed as promoting student social justice work as public intellectuals, I think the roundtable will be strengthened by some acknowledgement and discussion of student privacy and safety while engaging with Wikipedia. I also hope in the roundtable itself, we will hear from both a student and instructor perspective on how the work has been going.  Lastly, I think it would be useful to be a bit more explicit about how the specific topics the panelists are working on connect students to and help them actively participate in anti-racist work, postcolonial or decolonial studies, and promoting multilingualism in the public humanities. This is not just because it&#039;s a review criteria/conference theme but also because the historical subject areas each panelist focuses on seem like they ought to lend themselves well to such discussions.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
