    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Visualizing Literary Data and Ann-Marie MacDonald&#039;s &quot;The Way the Crow Flies&quot;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Mapping, Literary Geography, Collaboration, Data Feminism</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Queer Studies&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;project design, organization, and management&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Geography and Geo-Humanities&#10;Literary studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">database creation, management, and analysis&#10;project design, organization, and management</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Queer Studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Geography and Geo-Humanities&#10;Literary studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Canadian author Ann-Marie MacDonald’s plays and novels appeal to diverse, global mass-market audiences; at the same time, her works challenge cultural norms about gender and sexual identities, the treatment of racialized, Indigenous, and disabled persons and communities, and which voices in Canada can be heard. “Mapping Ann-Marie MacDonald” (MAMM) is a Digital Humanities project funded through SSHRC’s IDG program (2023-2026), involving interdisciplinary collaborators, as well as the participation of the author.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Two questions driving the MAMM project are: how can solitary close reading activity be emulated in a collaborative DH environment and how can the data collection model be feminist? This presentation explores the interpretive results and visualization opportunities of a collaborative, integrated data collection process.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;A student RA team including members from English Literature, Digital Humanities, and Geography, worked with data collection tools aligning with Literary Geography concepts and purpose-built to collect the following spatial data:&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;ul&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Feature type and description (eg. encounter location, route-related location)&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Sense-of-place (how space is defined by human subjectivity)&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Georeferencing and Time referencing&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Focalization (from what perspective is the feature being described)&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Relational situation (what relations does the space allow)&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Narrative function (how is the description of space used to advance the narrative)&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;/ul&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The data collection process encouraged principles of data feminism, including making labour transparent and visible, and embracing an embodied practice of consensus-driven knowledge production. Constraints built into the tools led to an integrated yet distinct accounting of the literary representation of spatial practices, complex enough to be productively used in critical literary analysis.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Using Flourish and ArcGIS Online, we explore opportunities for critical analysis through visualization.  Analytical and visualization opportunities emerging from the data processing include visualizing plot development, sense of place, and relationality, as well as mapping narrative hot spots. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canadian author Ann-Marie MacDonald’s plays and novels appeal to diverse, global mass-market audiences; at the same time, her works challenge cultural norms about gender and sexual identities, the treatment of racialized, Indigenous, and disabled persons and communities, and which voices in Canada can be heard. “Mapping Ann-Marie MacDonald” (MAMM) is a Digital Humanities project funded through SSHRC’s IDG program (2023-2026), involving interdisciplinary collaborators, as well as the participation of the author.&#10;Two questions driving the MAMM project are: how can solitary close reading activity be emulated in a collaborative DH environment and how can the data collection model be feminist? This presentation explores the interpretive results and visualization opportunities of a collaborative, integrated data collection process.&#10;A student RA team including members from English Literature, Digital Humanities, and Geography, worked with data collection tools aligning with Literary Geography concepts and purpose-built to collect the following spatial data:&#10;Feature type and description (eg. encounter location, route-related location)&#10;Sense-of-place (how space is defined by human subjectivity)&#10;Georeferencing and Time referencing&#10;Focalization (from what perspective is the feature being described)&#10;Relational situation (what relations does the space allow)&#10;Narrative function (how is the description of space used to advance the narrative)&#10;The data collection process encouraged principles of data feminism, including making labour transparent and visible, and embracing an embodied practice of consensus-driven knowledge production. Constraints built into the tools led to an integrated yet distinct accounting of the literary representation of spatial practices, complex enough to be productively used in critical literary analysis.&#10;Using Flourish and ArcGIS Online, we explore opportunities for critical analysis through visualization.  Analytical and visualization opportunities emerging from the data processing include visualizing plot development, sense of place, and relationality, as well as mapping narrative hot spots.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gordon, Neta</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brock University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ngordon@brocku.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ngordon@brocku.ca, amauro@brocku.ca, eustundag@brocku.ca, tribaric@brocku.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gordon, Neta</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ngordon@brocku.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
