    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">128</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1141</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dabrowska, Monika</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is interesting as a practical experience of mapping literary spaces and literary research using digital humanities methods. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission highlights Ann-Marie MacDonald creativity as a woman author and in this case, the digital display of his novel is under analysis. While it does not include other authors, it still contributes to make diversity and women be more seen. The methodological approach and the digital tools are up to date and very interesting. I hope the authors will discuss a bit more, some concept used (types of location, relational situation) and, above all, the process of data extraction and curation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1278</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Minot, Casie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission presents a unique way of engaging with close reading through digital  technology, which maps out specific literary aspects of Ann-Marie MacDonald&#039;s oeuvre. From this, the submission wishes to gesture towards the ways in which their data collection was formed from feminist praxis and new insights regarding Macdonald&#039;s work.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission proposes an exciting look at Macdonald&#039;s plays and novels through the lens of digital humanities. From this, the submission gestures towards how using this lens presents significant inquiries regarding feminist data collection methods as well as how scholars might further learn about the formal literary qualities and societal themes of Macdonald&#039;s work. &#10;&#10;Going forward, the submission might first be revised to more specifically discuss what feminist data methodologies the project is pulling from. As the project mentions, data feminism prompts the scholars to implement certain visible labor practices and knowledge production methods. While these certainly give the reader a general idea of what the data collection process looked like, the image of this data collection and its resonance with feminism might be given further detail by highlighting what specific authors or branches of data feminism this work is pulling from. By doing so, not only is the author giving greater specificity to their work, but is also placing their project in direct conversation with other feminist data scholars and illuminating how exactly their work builds upon or transforms current work in the field.&#10;&#10;A similar note might be given to the ways in which literary elements were discussed in the abstract. At the moment, the submission excellently highlights that they try to execute a form of close reading using digital humanities tools, and they work to examine specific formal literary qualities that they have listed. The submitters might nod to specific literary and digital scholars alike to recognize why these specific factors, such as &quot;Feature type and description (eg. encounter location, route-related location) [;] Sense-of-place (how space is defined by human subjectivity) [;] Georeferencing and Time referencing [;] Focalization (from what perspective is the feature being described) [;] Relational situation (what relations does the space allow) [;] Narrative function (how is the description of space used to advance the narrative),&quot; were the most critical to track in their data collection over others. Moreover, a more direct statement about what exactly the project illuminated about  &quot;literary representation and spatial practices&quot; might help scholars understand the significance of the project even more as it relates to understanding MacDonald&#039;s work.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1248</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Knox, John Thomas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution describes how computational and feminist approaches and methods were utilized to analyze and visualize data associated with the work of author Ann-Marie MacDonald. The contribution describes the project&#039;s research questions and findings, as well as the team&#039;s collaborative approach.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution is highly relevant to the conference theme. The proposal outlines the stakes, goals, and work undertaken by the project team very well. I would be interested to learn more about the constraints imposed by the tools and how the team responded to those. Overall, this is a very strong proposal.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I  think this is a very strong proposal and I&#039;m excited to learn more about it.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
