    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Taking a Step Forward as a Future Digital Humanities Librarian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital humanities librarianship, student, digital humanities training, librarianship training, professional development</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital libraries creation, management, and analysis&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital libraries creation, management, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;As a new library sciences student at the University of Toronto, I have the chance to attend the Digital Humanities Summer Insitute held at the University of Victoria this summer. There, I received a scholarship to attend a course called &#039;Digital Humanities for Librarians.&#039; In the poster, I aim to describe the institute, the course, as well as my reflections and takeaways. I hope to pitch future project ideas that I learned from the program into my work at the Scholarly Communications &amp; Copyright Office, as well as my second position at the Health Sciences Library, both at the University of Toronto. Currently, I work on digitally curating open access journal packages for health science researchers and on a literature review on using AI for systemative review searches. I am excited to see what I learn from the summer institute to further develop these projects that I am currently involved in. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As a new library sciences student at the University of Toronto, I have the chance to attend the Digital Humanities Summer Insitute held at the University of Victoria this summer. There, I received a scholarship to attend a course called &#039;Digital Humanities for Librarians.&#039; In the poster, I aim to describe the institute, the course, as well as my reflections and takeaways. I hope to pitch future project ideas that I learned from the program into my work at the Scholarly Communications &amp; Copyright Office, as well as my second position at the Health Sciences Library, both at the University of Toronto. Currently, I work on digitally curating open access journal packages for health science researchers and on a literature review on using AI for systemative review searches. I am excited to see what I learn from the summer institute to further develop these projects that I am currently involved in.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shin, Lisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Toronto</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">lisa.shin@mail.utoronto.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">lisa.shin@mail.utoronto.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shin, Lisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">lisa.shin@mail.utoronto.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern / Toronto</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">54.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">74.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">130</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1201</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Naut Medina, Stephanie Marie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The primary contribution of this poster is to share the students’ experiences from the ‘Digital Humanities for Librarians’ course at their institution. It will reflect on their learning outcomes and key takeaways, and discuss potential future project ideas for their Health Science Library. The findings and learning outcomes demonstrate a mixed-methods approach that combines their previous experience at the University of Toronto with their most recent experience at the University of Victoria summer course. These findings have significant implications for library science and information technology, suggesting innovative ways in which AI systematic review searches could play a crucial role in curating Open Access journal packages</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I really liked your approach for this project! I think it is your methods go in accordance with abstract and you have a well main idea as to what you want your poster to be. I would have liked seeing more examples as to how are you are going to approach this poster. What kind of materials, or course load, you saw at the DH for librarians at the University of Victoria that stood out for you? And how are you going to connect it to your current work? What did you hoped to gain? And how are you applying those learning outcomes to this presentation? Overall, you have really good ideas for your poster. And I think, with a little more of examples and more details as to how are going to connect your experiences, and how it connects with DH overall. You can have a really well rounded poster. &#10;&#10;Keep up the good work! </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1001</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lach, Pamella R.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers a reflection on a weeklong course in Digital Humanities for Librarians and how some of the things learned might be applied to the author&#039;s current and future work. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I appreciate the author&#039;s enthusiasm about attending DHSI. Since this proposal was written prior to attending the class, it necessarily lacks specificity about particular aspects of DH librarianship that they intend to pursue/apply to their current work. Nonetheless, it models how learners at all career stages might reflectively approach an opportunity such as DHSI. I would encourage the author to situate this presentation more explicitly within the field of digital humanities/digital scholarship library work (i.e. trends in the field, things they&#039;d like to see DH/DS library workers address, etc.).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1122</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boyles, Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal certainly with themes around DH, librarianship, and AI.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Although this proposal certainly engages interesting themes around DH, librarianship, and AI, the abstract does not clearly outline how the presentation will contribute to ongoing conversations in these areas or engage any existing scholarship on these topics. One difficulty is that the contributor has not yet attended DHSI. I would recommend that they consider resubmitting to next year&#039;s conference with an abstract that outlines their experiences in the course, areas for growth they have identified, and what new theories/methods/ideas have developed from their work.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
