    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">What we think we teach when we teach DH: Digital Humanities and the Job Market</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">labor, jobs, political economy, careers</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;One of the original narratives within Digital Humanities proclaimed that infusing technological methods and training into the liberal arts curriculum would entice students confronting a shrinking job market in the age of neoliberal austerity after the 2008 financial crisis. For example, in a white paper entitled “The Promise of Digital Humanities,” prepared in 2009, we find this description: “It is imperative that we prepare our students—both undergraduate and graduate—to be competitive in the job market of the twenty-first century. Digital Humanities teaches students the critical thinking skills, media literacies, and technical knowledge necessary for success in the digital information age” (Presner and Johanson 2009). Even as such rhetoric proved effective in terms of mobilizing efforts and building programs, DH practitioners questioned its accuracy almost from the beginning (Waltzer 2012) in part because actual data about career success and satisfaction have been almost entirely missing. Our paper attempts to address this aporia. We assess the political economy of DH in its historical and contemporary moments before turning to our current project: a survey of current job satisfaction among post-graduates who pursued DH during their undergraduate studies. Our goal is to provide substantial data about the actual empirical results of DH training. But we also hope to use our paper to solicit feedback and new data for future expansions of the project. Rather than assess what we &lt;em&gt;do&lt;/em&gt; teach (Croxall and Jakacki 2023), we hope to initiate an important discussion about what we &lt;em&gt;think&lt;/em&gt; we teach when we teach DH.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">One of the original narratives within Digital Humanities proclaimed that infusing technological methods and training into the liberal arts curriculum would entice students confronting a shrinking job market in the age of neoliberal austerity after the 2008 financial crisis. For example, in a white paper entitled “The Promise of Digital Humanities,” prepared in 2009, we find this description: “It is imperative that we prepare our students—both undergraduate and graduate—to be competitive in the job market of the twenty-first century. Digital Humanities teaches students the critical thinking skills, media literacies, and technical knowledge necessary for success in the digital information age” (Presner and Johanson 2009). Even as such rhetoric proved effective in terms of mobilizing efforts and building programs, DH practitioners questioned its accuracy almost from the beginning (Waltzer 2012) in part because actual data about career success and satisfaction have been almost entirely missing. Our paper attempts to address this aporia. We assess the political economy of DH in its historical and contemporary moments before turning to our current project: a survey of current job satisfaction among post-graduates who pursued DH during their undergraduate studies. Our goal is to provide substantial data about the actual empirical results of DH training. But we also hope to use our paper to solicit feedback and new data for future expansions of the project. Rather than assess what we do teach (Croxall and Jakacki 2023), we hope to initiate an important discussion about what we think we teach when we teach DH.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Hannah, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Purdue University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">hannah8@purdue.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">hannah8@purdue.edu, stewa443@purdue.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Hannah, Matthew;&#10;Stewart, Spencer</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">hannah8@purdue.edu;&#10;stewa443@purdue.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">131</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1066</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Walsh, Brandon</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The talk describes work on a survey of job satisfaction and dh training for postgraduates as a means of addressing a gap in the literature about the relevance of digital humanities training to job market competitiveness. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This looks great and seems to address a noticeable gap in the literature and conversations about digital humanities professional development. One thought - &#10;&#10;To my reading of the abstract, there might be a slight slippage between job market competitiveness and career satisfaction. In other words, will a survey of post-graduates about job satisfaction and their DH training necessarily tell us _why those people were hired_? It seems like it could tell us one piece of the story but that we might also need data from people on hiring committees specifically about the ways that DH training parses to people in a position to evaluate candidates. &#10;&#10;I don&#039;t think this necessarily takes away from the usefulness of the study or of the talk, though, and I hope it will be included on the program. It&#039;s more a suggestion for further study to supplement this work and/or the subject of a slide or two. Hope to see the talk at the conference!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1304</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Giselle Pempedjian, Giselle</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal aims to provide substantial data on the real-world impact of DH training and seeks to engage the academic community for feedback and further data collection to relate it to the impact on the real-world.  It triggers a critical discussion on the effectiveness of Digital Humanities education.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The critical reflection is essential for an ongoing discussion, especially with the aim/potential of collecting new data, about the role and impact of Digital humanities in academia.&#10;Sharing the survey with other institution should expand the scope of the survey, thus provide more generalizable results and help improve the Digital humanities curricula based on the survey findings. This could correlate with what we teach, what the learners learn and what we think we teach.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1147</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Berger, Claudia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A study of the career outcomes of students who studied DH as undergrads</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a really interesting topic, and would love to hear more about how you are identifying students for your survey. Also I think it could be made more explicit, either in the title or earlier in the abstract, that this is specifically about undergraduate students.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
