    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Telling a Story with Data: shift in the Mediterranean Diet’s discourse from 1950-2020</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Mediterranean diet, data storytelling, keyword occurrences, topic modeling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;natural language processing&#10;History of Science&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Digital Storytelling&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Transatlantic studies&#10;Western/Southern European Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">natural language processing&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">History of Science&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Transatlantic studies&#10;Western/Southern European Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;As the Mediterranean Diet (MD) research has developed into an ever-growing voluminous record of thousands of documents in many different fields of inquiry, we are paradoxically experiencing public health outcomes that demonstrate how little effect this de-territorialized research has had on practices. This lightning talk presents the preliminary results of computational analysis of occurrences of MD keywords in a corpus of volumes published between 1950 and 2020 in English collected from the HathiTrust Digital Library. We have been interested in using natural language processing (NLP) techniques for computational textual analysis of digital archives. “The De-territorialized Food Narrative of the Mediterranean Diet: Creating and Analyzing a Digital Collection” project explores the model of applying Digital Humanities qualitative research methods.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Preliminary results depict the shift in the usage and the sense of the words “ancel keys” and “mediterranean diet” around 1985. We study it in connection with the Dietary Guidelines for Americans by questioning, for instance, if the publications tend to support “nutritionism” or the perils of analyzing our diet only in terms of discreet nutrients rather than considering it in a more holistic fashion. Our collaborative efforts contributed to the MD story by analyzing its representation patterns as a Euro-centric global model in contrast to place-based traditional diets. The next step is to explore how this project’s data repository can serve to introduce the digital library and tools available to work with texts as data to students in the “Mediterranean Lifestyle in Italy” and “Remapping Food Systems” undergraduate courses.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As the Mediterranean Diet (MD) research has developed into an ever-growing voluminous record of thousands of documents in many different fields of inquiry, we are paradoxically experiencing public health outcomes that demonstrate how little effect this de-territorialized research has had on practices. This lightning talk presents the preliminary results of computational analysis of occurrences of MD keywords in a corpus of volumes published between 1950 and 2020 in English collected from the HathiTrust Digital Library. We have been interested in using natural language processing (NLP) techniques for computational textual analysis of digital archives. “The De-territorialized Food Narrative of the Mediterranean Diet: Creating and Analyzing a Digital Collection” project explores the model of applying Digital Humanities qualitative research methods.&#10;Preliminary results depict the shift in the usage and the sense of the words “ancel keys” and “mediterranean diet” around 1985. We study it in connection with the Dietary Guidelines for Americans by questioning, for instance, if the publications tend to support “nutritionism” or the perils of analyzing our diet only in terms of discreet nutrients rather than considering it in a more holistic fashion. Our collaborative efforts contributed to the MD story by analyzing its representation patterns as a Euro-centric global model in contrast to place-based traditional diets. The next step is to explore how this project’s data repository can serve to introduce the digital library and tools available to work with texts as data to students in the “Mediterranean Lifestyle in Italy” and “Remapping Food Systems” undergraduate courses.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
