    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">133</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1237</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Baciu, Dan C.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&quot;Telling a Story with Data: Shift in the Mediterranean Diet’s Discourse from 1950-2020&quot; by Arina Melkozernova, Juliann Vitullo, Ryan Dubnicek, Daniel J. Evans, and Boris Capitanu is a compelling study that delves into the evolution of the Mediterranean Diet (MD) discourse over seven decades. This research is particularly noteworthy for its interdisciplinary approach, combining natural language processing (NLP) with digital humanities methodologies to analyze a vast corpus of texts from the HathiTrust Digital Library.&#10;&#10;The authors address an intriguing paradox: despite the extensive body of research on the Mediterranean Diet, public health outcomes suggest a disconnect between the academic discourse and practical dietary habits. This paper&#039;s preliminary results highlight a significant shift in the usage of key terms like &quot;Ancel Keys&quot; and &quot;Mediterranean Diet&quot; around 1985, offering insights into how the diet&#039;s narrative has evolved in relation to the Dietary Guidelines for Americans. This shift is analyzed through the lens of &quot;nutritionism&quot;—the reductionist view of diet focused solely on discrete nutrients rather than holistic dietary patterns.&#10;&#10;One of the study’s strengths is its application of NLP techniques to conduct a computational textual analysis of digital archives. This innovative approach allows the authors to uncover patterns and trends in the representation of the Mediterranean Diet that might not be immediately apparent through traditional qualitative methods. The collaborative nature of this project, drawing on expertise from multiple institutions, further enriches the analysis.&#10;&#10;The authors also explore the implications of their findings for educational purposes. By integrating their data repository into undergraduate courses such as &quot;Mediterranean Lifestyle in Italy&quot; and &quot;Remapping Food Systems,&quot; they aim to introduce students to the digital tools and methodologies used in this research. This educational component underscores the project&#039;s broader impact, highlighting its potential to influence future scholarship and teaching in the field.&#10;&#10;Moving forward, the conference presentation could benefit from more ample perspective in how the present NLP techniques compare to other techniques applied with HathiTrust data, for example wikification. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Congrats! Outstanding proposal. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1254</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Evans, Kenneth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk examines textual records related to the Mediterranean Diet to understand shifting linguistic and rhetorical patterns across time. The abstract provides some initial findings related to changing norms of eating practices in America.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an interesting proposal worthy of acceptance. The submission could have been strengthened with more specifics on &quot;the project,&quot; &quot;many different fields of inquiry,&quot; and references to existing products. For instance, the abstract mentions a corpus - how many records are being examined and where did HathiTrust collect them from? What are the nature and even location of the the undergraduate course mentioned? Who published the &quot;Dietary Guidelines for Americans,&quot; over what time period, and what is contained in those documents that enables the comparison to the corpus data?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1248</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Knox, John Thomas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution presents insights about discourse surrounding the Mediterranean diet derived using computational methods to analyze a large text corpus. In addition to presenting these preliminary results, the contribution describes how the dataset can be used in the classroom. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I thought this proposal did a good job of articulating the motivations and stakes of the project as well as how it can be connected to pedagogy. I would be interested to learn more about how the authors connect this work to the conference theme.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
