    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Protocols of Whiteness: Universalism, Individualism, and Control in the AT Protocol</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">race, social media, whiteness, federated networks</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;cultural analytics&#10;social media analysis and methods&#10;Communication studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cultural analytics&#10;social media analysis and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Communication studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Bluesky BPLLC is a public benefit corporation that is currently developing a new protocol for creating federated social media, the AT Protocol. Proponents of federation cite decentralization as a key benefit, asserting that it combats many of the dangers created by centralized corporate-owned platforms. Bluesky aims to utilize the decentralization federation to “turn social media into a shared public commons” that supports democratic society (Bluesky Team 2023). However, as Alexander Galloway demonstrates, decentralization is not the removal, but simply the relocation, of control. Control continues to reside in the protocol on which the network is built (Galloway 2004). Part of a larger project examining federated social networks, this paper argues that the AT Protocol mirrors key logics of whiteness, particularly the bifurcated relationship between the universal and the individual. Thus, the AT Protocol – both technically and discursively – perpetuates whiteness as a primary locus of control in resulting networks.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;I use CTDA, which combines analysis of discourse about technological artifacts, examination of their affordances, and relevant social theory to understand digital phenomena and culture. For the last two years, Bluesky PBLLC has operated a beta instance of a Twitter-style microblogging network (also named Bluesky). I examine the affordances of the Bluesky social media network alongside the twenty-seven posts to Bluesky’s blog between February 2022 and February 2024, in which the Bluesky team details their goals and rationales. This analysis is then contextualized by theorizations of whiteness drawn from critical race theory, critical studies of whiteness, and postcolonial studies.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bluesky BPLLC is a public benefit corporation that is currently developing a new protocol for creating federated social media, the AT Protocol. Proponents of federation cite decentralization as a key benefit, asserting that it combats many of the dangers created by centralized corporate-owned platforms. Bluesky aims to utilize the decentralization federation to “turn social media into a shared public commons” that supports democratic society (Bluesky Team 2023). However, as Alexander Galloway demonstrates, decentralization is not the removal, but simply the relocation, of control. Control continues to reside in the protocol on which the network is built (Galloway 2004). Part of a larger project examining federated social networks, this paper argues that the AT Protocol mirrors key logics of whiteness, particularly the bifurcated relationship between the universal and the individual. Thus, the AT Protocol – both technically and discursively – perpetuates whiteness as a primary locus of control in resulting networks.&#10;I use CTDA, which combines analysis of discourse about technological artifacts, examination of their affordances, and relevant social theory to understand digital phenomena and culture. For the last two years, Bluesky PBLLC has operated a beta instance of a Twitter-style microblogging network (also named Bluesky). I examine the affordances of the Bluesky social media network alongside the twenty-seven posts to Bluesky’s blog between February 2022 and February 2024, in which the Bluesky team details their goals and rationales. This analysis is then contextualized by theorizations of whiteness drawn from critical race theory, critical studies of whiteness, and postcolonial studies.</ss:Data></Cell>
