    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">85.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">134</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1275</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kilbane, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Employing CTDA, this paper critiques Bluesky&#039;s AT Protocol for the logics of whiteness it instantiates and perpetuates.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am very eager to hear this paper, which is clearly and compellingly introduced in this abstract. The shape of the paper is crisply delineated, and its wider stakes are sharply drawn. I am especially eager to learn how the baked-in protocols of control relate to the platform&#039;s uptake by users. That is, is it possible for users of Bluesy to circumvent and/or &quot;detourn&quot; these protocols? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">94</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1127</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Alvarez, Martha Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This work fully meets the objectives of this conference from the perspective of Digital Humanities, questioning the whiteness of socio-digital networks and the platforms on which they are hosted. This perspective raises questions from anti-racism and decolonial studies.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I find this research very relevant, I recommend your participation in the conference and I invite the authors to see examples of situations similar to those they present in their work in other latitudes and other social networks and compare the findings, this would greatly enrich their results. When they talk about &quot;relevant social theory&quot; it would be worth emphasizing the authors they are familiar with so that their audience has the same theoretical horizon.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1159</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Duguay, Michèle</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission proposes an analysis of the way Bluesky BPLLC&#039;s decentralization reproduces and perpetuates the logic of whiteness. The author relies on blog posts, literature in critical race theory and critical whiteness studies, and CTDA. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a promising submission on a topic relevant to the conference themes--the author&#039;s focus on highlighting whiteness and power is also an important contribution. The submission may benefit from more framing (why the Bluesky platform?) and more explicit discussion of the significance/applicability of the case study. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">66</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
