    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Examining hooksbot: Social Justice, Digital Publics, and Ethical Dilemmas in DH Projects</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">twitter, algorithms, race, gender, social media</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;Software Studies&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;3d printing, critical making&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;meta-criticism (reflections on digital humanities and humanities computing)&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3d printing, critical making&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;meta-criticism (reflections on digital humanities and humanities computing)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Race Studies&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;Software Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In 2015, I created hooksbot (http://twitter.com/hooksbot) in a workshop I led for colleagues and students. The bot posts a quote from &lt;em&gt;Homegrown: Engaged Cultural Criticism&lt;/em&gt; by bell hooks and Amalia Mesa-Bains each time that JP Morgan’s stock price rises by 1%. The quote is “we have to constantly critique imperialist white supremacist patriarchal culture because it is normalized by mass media and rendered unproblematic&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Nearly a decade later, despite changes to Twitter’s API and various services, the bot is still tweeting. At the time of this writing, it has close to 10,000 followers. A recent tweet reached over 30,000 Twitter users.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;On one hand, I am heartened that the account resonates with those left trying to occupy the digital public square of FKA Twitter. On the other, I am unsettled by the thought of hooks’ voice echoing through the haunted graveyard that is now x.com. I could deactivate the code that runs the account or delete the account entirely, but it is not quite that straightforward.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Drawing on works such as Safiya Noble’s &lt;em&gt;Algorithms of Oppression, &lt;/em&gt;Ruha Benjamin’s &lt;em&gt;Race After Technology, &lt;/em&gt;Joy Buolamwini’s &lt;em&gt;Unmasking AI, &lt;/em&gt;and hooks’ canon, I propose to examine the social justice framework of hooksbot. The questions around the bot’s continued operations gesture toward larger issues in DH such as ethically evaluating the lifecycle of DH projects, white allyship in relation to the work of women of color, and whether using the digital platforms of “imperialist white supremacist patriarchal culture” normalizes it and renders it unproblematic.  &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In 2015, I created hooksbot (http://twitter.com/hooksbot) in a workshop I led for colleagues and students. The bot posts a quote from Homegrown: Engaged Cultural Criticism by bell hooks and Amalia Mesa-Bains each time that JP Morgan’s stock price rises by 1%. The quote is “we have to constantly critique imperialist white supremacist patriarchal culture because it is normalized by mass media and rendered unproblematic&quot;.&#10;Nearly a decade later, despite changes to Twitter’s API and various services, the bot is still tweeting. At the time of this writing, it has close to 10,000 followers. A recent tweet reached over 30,000 Twitter users.&#10;On one hand, I am heartened that the account resonates with those left trying to occupy the digital public square of FKA Twitter. On the other, I am unsettled by the thought of hooks’ voice echoing through the haunted graveyard that is now x.com. I could deactivate the code that runs the account or delete the account entirely, but it is not quite that straightforward.&#10;Drawing on works such as Safiya Noble’s Algorithms of Oppression, Ruha Benjamin’s Race After Technology, Joy Buolamwini’s Unmasking AI, and hooks’ canon, I propose to examine the social justice framework of hooksbot. The questions around the bot’s continued operations gesture toward larger issues in DH such as ethically evaluating the lifecycle of DH projects, white allyship in relation to the work of women of color, and whether using the digital platforms of “imperialist white supremacist patriarchal culture” normalizes it and renders it unproblematic.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Knight, Kim Brillante</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">San Jose State University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kim.knight@sjsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kknight08@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kim.knight@sjsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Knight, Kim Brillante</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kim.knight@sjsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pacific</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">135</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1091</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Beverly-Porter, Diamond</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution of this proposal is it retrospective approach to changing landscape of digital media at the intersects of digital humanities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> This submission could be improved by considering how black bodies have been surveilled and resurrected within the contexts of digital media and spaces.&#10;&#10;1.) Sutherland, Tonia. Resurrecting the Black Body : Race and the Digital Afterlife. University of California Press, 2023.&#10;&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1040</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ferretti, Giulia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Starting with the case study of a bot implemented by the author of the paper, the abstract poses the problem of inhabiting a space, such as X&#039;s, increasingly controlled and subject to proprietary logics, and determining the life cycle of DH projects still living in that space.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is based on a real-world example and raises significant issues about the management of a DH project. The problem of finding a space for scientific communities to meet and exchange ideas, and the problem of when to realize that such a space is no longer habitable it is of central importance at the time when networked space is increasingly occupied by large digital companies.&#10;&#10;However, I think that the bot mentioned in the abstract should be contextualized as a DH project: what were the bot research goals?&#10;Even if the proposal research questions are clear and well-posed, the concrete strategies used to effectively answer them might have merited more in-depth consideration. I emphasize that the word count limit was probably one of the reasons why this aspect was not further explored.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposition raises very interesting and timely issues on which I would honestly like to hear a presentation. The submitted abstract, however, does not make it clear how these issues will be explored in the presentations. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1130</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Murphy, Emily Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution details the changing political context of the hooksbot and contextualizes it within hooks’s own thought as well as more recent critical race and digital culture scholarship by Safiya Noble and Ruha Benjamin.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very interesting proposal, and I especially like the way that it considers the changing contexts of a past project and how the politics, too, of that project may change over time. The proposal would have benefitted from a bit more “so what” related to its analytical claims, which would have helped me to evaluate how it would unfold methodologically. I am fascinated by the questions related to “ethically evaluating the lifecycle of DH projects, white allyship in relation to the work of women of color, and whether using the digital platforms of “imperialist white supremacist patriarchal culture” normalizes it and renders it unproblematic.” But I’d like a stronger sense of where the analysis might land, even in a short abstract like this one. &#10;&#10;The paper may benefit from some stronger grounding in scholarship on platform studies and project preservation, which might include the Endings project (https://endings.uvic.ca/). If this work is accepted as a longer paper, I would also be interested to see how it relates to some of Amy Earhart’s research on the digital recovery work of racialized women authors in the early 1990s (the recent chapter in the Digital Black Atlantic may be especially useful: https://www.upress.umn.edu/9781517910808/the-digital-black-atlantic/). &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I could see this paper as either a longer paper or a lightening talk. The abstract at the moment reads as a provocation, which would suit the lightening talk format, but if it had attended to some of the context and argumentation I discuss in my comments for the author I would be more confident recommending it for the individual paper format.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
