    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">What Can 30 Years of Conference Papers Tell Us About the Digital Humanities?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital humanities, Bibliometrics, Scholarly communication</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;bibliographic analysis&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;History of Science&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Bibliographical Studies&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bibliographic analysis&#10;database creation, management, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">History of Science&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Bibliographical Studies&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The humanities are characterized by questions associated with human values, interpretation, and expression. Conversely, the digital humanities (DH) pertain to the ways in which humans leverage media and computational methods for similar purposes. This paper presents a longitudinal dataset of Alliance of Digital Humanities Organizations conference papers presented between 1990 and 2020. I describe how I collected this dataset and provide descriptive statistics showing that, over time, DH has become more collaborative. Moving beyond bibliographic research that has historically focused on full-length, peer-reviewed journal articles, I describe a subset of 1,142 paper abstracts (~50% of my larger sample). I find that over the past three decades, DH scholars have increasingly written about topics not focused on text, they continue providing an inclusive venue for non-dominant disciplinary topics (e.g., pedagogy), and are increasingly preoccupied with ethics, minority groups, and at-risk populations. I conclude by sharing my dataset and its documentation so other researchers can study how the field continues to evolve.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The humanities are characterized by questions associated with human values, interpretation, and expression. Conversely, the digital humanities (DH) pertain to the ways in which humans leverage media and computational methods for similar purposes. This paper presents a longitudinal dataset of Alliance of Digital Humanities Organizations conference papers presented between 1990 and 2020. I describe how I collected this dataset and provide descriptive statistics showing that, over time, DH has become more collaborative. Moving beyond bibliographic research that has historically focused on full-length, peer-reviewed journal articles, I describe a subset of 1,142 paper abstracts (~50% of my larger sample). I find that over the past three decades, DH scholars have increasingly written about topics not focused on text, they continue providing an inclusive venue for non-dominant disciplinary topics (e.g., pedagogy), and are increasingly preoccupied with ethics, minority groups, and at-risk populations. I conclude by sharing my dataset and its documentation so other researchers can study how the field continues to evolve.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
