    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">52.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">136</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1254</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Evans, Kenneth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal offers an meta analysis of DH through ADHO conference reports, and offers some initial findings.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a thoughtful and straightforward proposal with clear aims, outcomes, and applicability to the conference.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1123</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Evans, Daniel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This work provides a &#039;distant read&#039; of 30 years of ADHO abstracts to highlight disciplinary shifts and growing trends in the field. The author lays out their method and shares some preliminary conclusions.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This work nicely compliments Weingart and Eichmann-Kalwara&#039;s 2017 study of ADHO abstracts. In continuing their work with presumably updated methods, it returns to larger questions about what are growing and waning topics in DH. I&#039;m interested in hearing if your findings and methods differ significantly from theirs.&#10;&#10;I was very interested in the marked shift away from text. Given this this year&#039;s ACH theme, I would also like to hear more about any trends in anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, and/or multilingualism. There were some gestures towards that in the abstract.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1031</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cukier, Emily Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper offers a landscape assessment of the field of digital humanities as depicted in ADHO conference papers. The author identifies trends of increased collaboration in the discipline, and increasing prevalence of themes including non-disciplinary topics, ethics, and marginalized groups. The contribution also includes sharing of the underlying dataset and documentation to allow others to perform their own investigations.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal makes clear the valuable contribution it makes to the field of DH as a reflection on the evolution of how DH projects are conducted and the rise of important topics over time, as well as its offer of a resource for others to conduct their own analyses.&#10;&#10;The proposal could be strengthened by revising the first two sentences to focus more on context rather than definitions - e.g., what is known or generally thought about who conducts DH on what subjects (or is this a knowledge gap?). It would also be helpful to see a more descriptive term for the types of textual analyses in the methods and keywords (e.g. - corpus linguistics? close reading?).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">52</ss:Data></Cell>
