    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Education/Pedagogy&#10;Caribbean Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Practitioners aiming to bring digital humanities (DH) into the classroom often run up against painful realities: what servers we have, what is possible in a semester, what tools are supported on campus. Reality, so often, restrains our pedagogy. This talk draws on speculative literatures and pedagogies to describe an approach to DH teaching that, instead, centers on imagining alternative learning communities and modalities. The presentation begins with a theory of speculative digital pedagogies drawing on the work of Kaiama L. Glover, Jessica Marie Johnson, Kelly Baker Josephs, and others. A teacher practicing this approach uses speculation as a shared space to critique their present academic, material, and methodological realities. The student inhabiting a learning space informed by speculative digital pedagogy will find themselves confronted with new pathways—new futures—for themselves as the work of the classroom changes their sense of what is possible. The interdisciplinary nature of DH can offer exposure to non-canonical readings often excluded in traditional curriculum, and our theory and practice of intentionally speculative digital pedagogies goes a step further, pushing instructors and students alike to critically explore how their own teaching and learning practices might be reimagined to include communities outside their typical purview. We conclude with a series of exercises and prompts to help digital humanists implement this approach in their teaching through alternative archival projects, iterative syllabus design, and imaginative professional development for students. DH work referenced will include &lt;em&gt;Stanford 2025&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;The DH RPG&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Ivanhoe&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;The Barbados Runaways&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;The Early Caribbean Digital Archive&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Practitioners aiming to bring digital humanities (DH) into the classroom often run up against painful realities: what servers we have, what is possible in a semester, what tools are supported on campus. Reality, so often, restrains our pedagogy. This talk draws on speculative literatures and pedagogies to describe an approach to DH teaching that, instead, centers on imagining alternative learning communities and modalities. The presentation begins with a theory of speculative digital pedagogies drawing on the work of Kaiama L. Glover, Jessica Marie Johnson, Kelly Baker Josephs, and others. A teacher practicing this approach uses speculation as a shared space to critique their present academic, material, and methodological realities. The student inhabiting a learning space informed by speculative digital pedagogy will find themselves confronted with new pathways—new futures—for themselves as the work of the classroom changes their sense of what is possible. The interdisciplinary nature of DH can offer exposure to non-canonical readings often excluded in traditional curriculum, and our theory and practice of intentionally speculative digital pedagogies goes a step further, pushing instructors and students alike to critically explore how their own teaching and learning practices might be reimagined to include communities outside their typical purview. We conclude with a series of exercises and prompts to help digital humanists implement this approach in their teaching through alternative archival projects, iterative syllabus design, and imaginative professional development for students. DH work referenced will include Stanford 2025, The DH RPG, Ivanhoe, The Barbados Runaways, and The Early Caribbean Digital Archive.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Walsh, Brandon</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Virginia</ss:Data></Cell>
