    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">walsh.brandon.michael@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">sjv5fn@virginia.edu, walsh.brandon.michael@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Viechweg, Seanna;&#10;Walsh, Brandon</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">sjv5fn@virginia.edu;&#10;walsh.brandon.michael@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">81.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">137</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1286</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sparks, Corey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Connects DH pedagogy to important work in digital African and Black diaspora studies. This suggests that &quot;speculative&quot; isn&#039;t inherently a marker of digital imagination but one that concerns community and identity.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This sounds amazing - the connections being made between DH pedagogy to important work in digital African and Black diaspora studies are important and compelling. My only concern is that the proposal is for an &quot;individual paper&quot;; I&#039;d be concerned that the 10-15 minute time frame for individual papers might be too much of a constraint for the scope suggested in the abstract. It sounds like in addition to walking people through the conceptual frameworks for &quot;speculative dh pedagogy&quot; there&#039;s also a plan to do some workshop-like work. Careful planning on how to cover all the bases will be tantamount within the proposed time frame.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I do see the abstract as articulating something really ambitious and interesting. Fitting in workshop stuff in the 10-15 minutes allotted for an individual paper could be really tough.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1098</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Howard, Jacquelyne Thoni</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal provides new frameworks for engaging students in digital humanities work and addresses limitations often experienced.  I am intrigued by the prompts that they will provide to allow for audience participation! </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am really intrigued by the method and projects that you describe.  I would love to sit in this session and learn what you mean by &quot;speculative&quot; and &quot;imagined&quot; and alternative frameworks for thinking about DH projects in the classroom.I am intrigued by the exercises and prompts that you will provide and liked how you mentioned &quot;alternative archival projects, iterative syllabus design, and imaginative professional development for students.&quot; All of this sounds to me like it focuses on flexibility, agentic education, and choice. I certainly want to learn more about your work because I am not really sure what those frameworks involve just from reading the proposal.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1232</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Faerber-Ovaska, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal describes a new &amp; open-ended approach to teaching digital humanities that uses speculative literatures and pedagogies to envision alternative classroom environments and new educational approaches. The authors propose to create new learning pathways by using those materials to critique and reimagine current academic and methodological realities. Theoretical grounding from scholars like Kaiama L. Glover and Jessica Marie Johnson is mentioned, along with something that looks especially interesting: practical exercises to implement this approach. The interdisciplinary nature of digital humanities, and the importance of including non-canonical readings are also emphasized.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&quot;Reality, so often, restrains [or constrains!] pedagogy&quot;. I hear you!! And I know what you mean. The approach you describe sounds refreshing/liberating, and your proposal is very interesting. If you can offer specifics on the practical implementation of speculative pedagogies in your classrooms, and what you know of their implementation in different types of educational settings, it would help your audience envision how this could be implemented. I hope you plan to include some specific examples of how these exercises and prompts have been applied in your own classrooms.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
