    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Introducing tmtyro: Simplified Workflows for Text-Mining Tyros</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">text mining, tool, beginner</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;software development, systems, analysis, and methods&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Literary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;software development, systems, analysis, and methods&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Literary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;We can learn a lot about texts by using tools for text mining. But despite the abundance of choice, these tools tend to lean one direction or another, asking us to pick between the too-cold option of accessible graphical interfaces that limit reproducibility or the too-hot alternative of code-based tools that expect prior expertise. The tmtyro package in R aims for somewhere in the middle, providing an intuitive set of functions that cater to novices while encouraging their growth.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;tmtyro simplifies many steps of text mining, from collecting and loading corpora to conducting analyses and creating visualizations. Developed to address the needs of students in an undergraduate course, it emphasizes reproducible methods without complex coding, and purpose-built functions allow beginners to focus on what they are doing instead of how they are doing it. Two steps are enough to load a folder of documents, tag parts of speech, lemmatize the text, and measure sentiment. An additional step is enough to visualize these results—or to change directions and build a topic model. By enabling quick experimentation and providing clear workflows, tmtyro helps users explore texts in depth and with confidence.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This presentation will introduce tmtyro, demonstrating its application in digital humanities research and showing how it fits in the space between beginner-friendly tools like databasic.io and Voyant and more specialized R packages like tidytext and quanteda. Attendees will learn how tmtyro can simplify text mining projects and support student learning with hands-on, accessible methods in the classroom.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">We can learn a lot about texts by using tools for text mining. But despite the abundance of choice, these tools tend to lean one direction or another, asking us to pick between the too-cold option of accessible graphical interfaces that limit reproducibility or the too-hot alternative of code-based tools that expect prior expertise. The tmtyro package in R aims for somewhere in the middle, providing an intuitive set of functions that cater to novices while encouraging their growth.&#10;tmtyro simplifies many steps of text mining, from collecting and loading corpora to conducting analyses and creating visualizations. Developed to address the needs of students in an undergraduate course, it emphasizes reproducible methods without complex coding, and purpose-built functions allow beginners to focus on what they are doing instead of how they are doing it. Two steps are enough to load a folder of documents, tag parts of speech, lemmatize the text, and measure sentiment. An additional step is enough to visualize these results—or to change directions and build a topic model. By enabling quick experimentation and providing clear workflows, tmtyro helps users explore texts in depth and with confidence.&#10;This presentation will introduce tmtyro, demonstrating its application in digital humanities research and showing how it fits in the space between beginner-friendly tools like databasic.io and Voyant and more specialized R packages like tidytext and quanteda. Attendees will learn how tmtyro can simplify text mining projects and support student learning with hands-on, accessible methods in the classroom.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
