    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Central / Chicago time zone</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">58.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">36.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">138</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1226</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Spiro, Lisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission introduces a new R package that balances simplicity and complexity in enabling users do text mining without trapping them in a black box.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">tmtyro sounds like a useful R package for simplifying--but not oversimplifying--text mining. The proposal is engaging and well-written. It demonstrates a knowledge of related work by referencing similar tools. It might be helpful to provide a few examples of how the tool can be used.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I imagine there would be good interest in this R package, so if it&#039;s not selected as a paper, I hope that it will be included as a lightning talk.&#10;&#10;While the paper may not deal explicitly with social justice issues, Grambling State University is an HBCU.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1249</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shoemaker, Tyler</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper introduces tmytro, a text mining framework in R that simplifies and&#10;standardizes corpus loading, tokenization, tagging, and analysis. The goal of&#10;this package is to work as an intermediary step between point-and-click&#10;interfaces and coding in an undergraduate classroom.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Framing tmtyro as a bridge between Voyant, etc. and R&#039;s many text mining&#10;packages nicely encapsulates both the package&#039;s functionality and the approach&#10;of this presentation. That the package may help with reproducibility is a big&#10;plus. Whether a walk-through of tmtyro would work best as a paper and not, say,&#10;as a workshop or poster is another question, however. As the abstract currently&#10;stands, I would recommend switching the format. &#10;&#10;Should this proceed as a paper, I would encourage substantive discussion about&#10;what the (extremely well-written) documentation for tmtyro calls the &quot;skills&#10;ramp.&quot; How has the presenter balanced the simplicity of the package&#039;s API with&#10;all the operations it abstractions? Difficult as data munging may be for&#10;beginners, interpretation starts there: how you tokenize, what stop words you&#10;remove, etc., are all determinative of the analytic outcome. So, how does using&#10;tmtyro in the classroom help us teach this aspect of the work?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1110</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rutner, Jennifer</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While this proposal is strong in terms of technical content, the author may consider connecting the use of this tool to the information that is being analyzed, and how it is being employed in an educational setting. The strengths of the proposal lie with the clear illustration of the pros and cons of a specific tool for analysis, and how it compares to other available tools, in the context of undergraduate education. This could prove valuable for other practitioners working with text-mining software. Unfortunately, there is not a clear connection between the proposal topic and the social justice themes of the conference. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This may be a suitable lightning talk, rather than a paper, based on subject matter. If possible, the applicant could resubmit the proposal, illustrating how the technology in question relates to the social justice frameworks of DH, and the sociopolitical implications of the work. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">36</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">-1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rejected</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell ss:StyleID="s22"><Data ss:Type="DateTime">2024-09-07T17:08:58.000</Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1000</ss:Data></Cell>
