    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Teaching and Researching Transborder and Latinx Digital Humanities at an HSI-R1 Institution in Texas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">pedagogy, humanities data, migration, gender violence, transborder dh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Spanish&#10;Critical Ethnic Studies&#10;Queer Studies&#10;North America&#10;South America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Digital Storytelling&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Hispanic Studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Spanish</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;South America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Ethnic Studies&#10;Queer Studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Hispanic Studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In recent years, digital humanities has shifted its focus here in the US and is now changing its recent, largely Eurocentric text-based scholarship to begin to address racial injustice and anti-colonialism (Martinez, Nieves and Tanks, 2024). This panel will discuss this new shift in current teaching and research of Transborder and Latinx digital humanities at a Hispanic Serving Institution R1 Institution at Texas. It is happening under a moment that state institutions in Texas are facing laws such as the anti-DEI, SB17, that although the ban doesn’t apply to academic course instruction and scholarly research, it prohibits training and activities conducted in reference to race, color, ethnicity, gender identity, or sexual orientation (Coronado, 2024).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The first presentation will go over the design, objectives, challenges and impacts of co-teaching two interdisciplinary courses of critical dh through an intersectional, feminist and anticolonial framework that examines factors of race, class, gender and sexuality across borders in a range of scales and time periods. The first course focused on missing data (D’Ignazio and Klein, 2020) and ground-up methods of counterdata (D’Ignazio 2024) by exploring and critically analyzing a selected group of border women’s literature text, archival material, databases and digital projects that address gender-based violence and feminicides at the US-Mexico border and globally. The second course focused on remixing, reassembling and reimagining the archive (Kreitz, 2017) and making and breaking methodologies through acts of dismantling, intervention and deconstruction (Boyles 2018) by learning, critiquing, and engaging in digital humanities practices and tools with a selected group of literary texts and archival sources centered in Latinas/os/xs historical and cultural (im)migration stories in the United States and across border.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Derived from these courses, the following speakers will present their current research on Transborder and Latinx Digital Humanities. The first delves in an analysis that intertwines South Texas culture and data on cases of gender-based violence against women reported in El Paso and San Antonio, Texas, in newspapers from the early 20th century. Building on the foundational work of countering feminicides (D’Ignacio 2024) El silencio que la voz de todas quiebra (Candia et al, 1999), Ellas tienen nombre (Ramirez), alongside records from the Esther Chávez Cano’s Collection and utilizing a feminist transborder dh methodology, a curated database of archival material contextualizes incidences of gender-based violence against women from 1900 to the 1940s. The second explores working with historical records and storytelling practices to deploy critical data and visualizations to narrate migration from a town in North Mexico,Viesca, Coahuila, focusing on the historical movements influenced economic opportunities, political upheavals, environmental changes, and cultural exchanges, while highlighting the interplay between migration and identity formation. This data work uses technology of recovery (Gallon 2016) to capture cultural expressions of Viesca&#039;s community, foster a sense of belonging and shedlight on the connected history among locals and diaspora intergenerational communities. The last presentation addresses issues of identity, sexuality, and migration status in Texas following the emergence of Latine Queerstories: Oral Testimonies of Migration, a digital project designed to humanize, preserve, and create a space for Latinx queer voices in Texas and across its geopolitical borders. These efforts tackle the urgent need to create safe digital spaces, challenge dominant narratives and fostering the creation of responsible data on Latinx queer sexuality and migration from Latin America. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In recent years, digital humanities has shifted its focus here in the US and is now changing its recent, largely Eurocentric text-based scholarship to begin to address racial injustice and anti-colonialism (Martinez, Nieves and Tanks, 2024). This panel will discuss this new shift in current teaching and research of Transborder and Latinx digital humanities at a Hispanic Serving Institution R1 Institution at Texas. It is happening under a moment that state institutions in Texas are facing laws such as the anti-DEI, SB17, that although the ban doesn’t apply to academic course instruction and scholarly research, it prohibits training and activities conducted in reference to race, color, ethnicity, gender identity, or sexual orientation (Coronado, 2024).&#10;The first presentation will go over the design, objectives, challenges and impacts of co-teaching two interdisciplinary courses of critical dh through an intersectional, feminist and anticolonial framework that examines factors of race, class, gender and sexuality across borders in a range of scales and time periods. The first course focused on missing data (D’Ignazio and Klein, 2020) and ground-up methods of counterdata (D’Ignazio 2024) by exploring and critically analyzing a selected group of border women’s literature text, archival material, databases and digital projects that address gender-based violence and feminicides at the US-Mexico border and globally. The second course focused on remixing, reassembling and reimagining the archive (Kreitz, 2017) and making and breaking methodologies through acts of dismantling, intervention and deconstruction (Boyles 2018) by learning, critiquing, and engaging in digital humanities practices and tools with a selected group of literary texts and archival sources centered in Latinas/os/xs historical and cultural (im)migration stories in the United States and across border.&#10;Derived from these courses, the following speakers will present their current research on Transborder and Latinx Digital Humanities. The first delves in an analysis that intertwines South Texas culture and data on cases of gender-based violence against women reported in El Paso and San Antonio, Texas, in newspapers from the early 20th century. Building on the foundational work of countering feminicides (D’Ignacio 2024) El silencio que la voz de todas quiebra (Candia et al, 1999), Ellas tienen nombre (Ramirez), alongside records from the Esther Chávez Cano’s Collection and utilizing a feminist transborder dh methodology, a curated database of archival material contextualizes incidences of gender-based violence against women from 1900 to the 1940s. The second explores working with historical records and storytelling practices to deploy critical data and visualizations to narrate migration from a town in North Mexico,Viesca, Coahuila, focusing on the historical movements influenced economic opportunities, political upheavals, environmental changes, and cultural exchanges, while highlighting the interplay between migration and identity formation. This data work uses technology of recovery (Gallon 2016) to capture cultural expressions of Viesca&#039;s community, foster a sense of belonging and shedlight on the connected history among locals and diaspora intergenerational communities. The last presentation addresses issues of identity, sexuality, and migration status in Texas following the emergence of Latine Queerstories: Oral Testimonies of Migration, a digital project designed to humanize, preserve, and create a space for Latinx queer voices in Texas and across its geopolitical borders. These efforts tackle the urgent need to create safe digital spaces, challenge dominant narratives and fostering the creation of responsible data on Latinx queer sexuality and migration from Latin America.</ss:Data></Cell>
