    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">139</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1268</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Juarez, Miguel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a strong presentation which addresses curricular and pedagogical development and analysis, database creation, management, and analysis, Digital Storytelling in a time in Texas when DEI efforts are under attack.&#10;&#10;The Fields of Study (and Engagement) include: Critical Ethnic Studies, Queer Studies, Feminist Studies, Border and Transborder studies, Hispanic Studies, and Latino/a/x/e Studies.  In a time when large Migrant streams are making their way north, this submission through DH presents informed DH ways of looking at these topics which are seemingly constant in current news coverage.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract states that the panel will discuss this new shift in current teaching and research of Transborder and Latinx digital humanities at a Hispanic Serving Institution R1 Institution at Texas.  How does the new shift in current teaching and research differ from not incorporating DH?&#10;&#10;It would have been good to have some examples of images to be presented to give evaluators a better understanding and/or amplification of the topics or even an example of the presentations.&#10;&#10;A lay person&#039;s definition (staying away from jargon) of Transborder and Latinx Digital Humanities would be good in future presentations.&#10;&#10;On the topic matter on the courses (course 1 and 2) it would have been ideal to explain why you selected specific topics over others. Were these topics meant to reinforce or expand on topics already taught in the humanities and/or in other areas of study?&#10;&#10;Finally, what were learning objectives of the two courses and how did you measure student learning? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">There needs to be a better explanation of learning objectives for the two courses as outlined in the class syllabus, as well as to show how student learning was facilitated and increased by incorporating DH.&#10;&#10;Examples of the syllabi would have shown how DH was incorporated into the teaching and learning and how were students were prepared or not prepared for the incorporation of DH.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1177</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Clawson, Corey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In the face of an increasingly hostile political environment attempting to stifle campus discussions of race, gender, and colonialism, the panel examines what is possible despite these attacks.  The panelists do so through a thoughtful examination of pedagogy grounded in critical digital humanities and resulting student work.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The panel proposal thoughtfully outlines a rich landscape of scholarship thinking through the challenges of thinking through race, class, gender, and the challenges of examining marginalized histories. Overall, the abstract illustrates a set of approaches that demonstrate the value of digital humanities in a moment wherein lawmakers attempt to stifle discussions regarding race, sexuality, and colonialism. The structure of the panel foregrounding anticolonial and critical methodologies with a presentation of the courses developed in this hostile atmosphere followed by a discussion of student work is intuitive and has the potential to offer a model for thinking through similar questions in oppressive political environs. &#10;&#10;Finally, the research derived from the courses is diverse in approach and focus, setting the stage for what I expect to be a fascinating discussion of applying the methodologies of the courses to the speakers&#039; respective interests. I&#039;m eager to hear about the logistics of the courses including assignments, the experiences of students developing projects, and how much they were able to accomplish during the term and how/if they continued this work.  &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1311</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Li, Simin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> the submission is a panel. Should it list all individual paper&#039;s title? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
