    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">How Generative AI Can Change the Process of Writing Historical Nonfiction</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Large language models (LLMs), generative ai, nonfiction, workflow, applied history</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;History&#10;History of Science&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Informatics&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">History&#10;History of Science&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Informatics&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Here I report on work-in-progess that incorporates Large Language Models (LLMs) into tools and workflows to support the writing of long-form nonfiction, particularly historical works. These tools and workflows constrain and even make use of the models&#039; tendency to &#039;hallucinate&#039;, they draw information and make inferences from verifiable structured data, and rigorously cite their sources. They are firmly grounded in the tools and techniques of the digital humanities: text encoding, the semantic web, linked open data, bibliography, databases, web APIs, text analysis, and text mining. There are two key differences, however. Rather than working with off-the-shelf tools or building them from the ground up, generative AI allows us to work from the top down. The techniques presented also make extensive use of the models&#039; ability to co-author code as well as prose. I explore the broader implications of such workflows for graduate training in history, peer evaluation, the scale and scope of conceivable projects, opportunities for collaboration, and new roles for the application of historical expertise in literature review across disciplines.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Here I report on work-in-progess that incorporates Large Language Models (LLMs) into tools and workflows to support the writing of long-form nonfiction, particularly historical works. These tools and workflows constrain and even make use of the models&#039; tendency to &#039;hallucinate&#039;, they draw information and make inferences from verifiable structured data, and rigorously cite their sources. They are firmly grounded in the tools and techniques of the digital humanities: text encoding, the semantic web, linked open data, bibliography, databases, web APIs, text analysis, and text mining. There are two key differences, however. Rather than working with off-the-shelf tools or building them from the ground up, generative AI allows us to work from the top down. The techniques presented also make extensive use of the models&#039; ability to co-author code as well as prose. I explore the broader implications of such workflows for graduate training in history, peer evaluation, the scale and scope of conceivable projects, opportunities for collaboration, and new roles for the application of historical expertise in literature review across disciplines.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Turkel, William J</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The University of Western Ontario</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">WILLIAM.J.TURKEL@GMAIL.COM</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">WILLIAM.J.TURKEL@GMAIL.COM</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Turkel, William J</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">WILLIAM.J.TURKEL@GMAIL.COM</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern (North America)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">140</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1269</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bell, Eamonn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk reports on the use of large language models (LLMs) to author historical non-fiction writing and will explore the consequences of these tools&#039; adoption on professional history-writing. The talk&#039;s distinctive aspects are its discussion of LLMs as &quot;top-down&quot; authoring tools and its emphasis on LLMs as authors of code.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal makes no links to the focal themes of the conference, though it may well be linked to these concerns if accepted (e.g. via themes of data justice or the politics of high-resource computing behind LLMs). There is some engagement with prior work, largely through name-checking; implicitly, a critical computing framework is discernible here, alongside a commitment to understanding the consequences of new technologies in professional humanities training. It is perhaps on this latter point the proposal is strongest and most compelling in the context of the conference, offering a practical illustration of how LLMs can/should be used by professional historians though the scope of the &quot;implications&quot; section is quite broad for a lightning talk. I would also encourage the development of the central claim that LLMs in this context are &quot;top-down&quot; reasoning tools, as this is currently underspecified in the proposal and seems like a promising if not immediately intuitive line of inquiry. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1073</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ciotola, Mark</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This talk concerns a lively topic of contemporary interest, the writing of history using AI tools.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The content proposed by this abstract might be overly ambitious for a lightning talk, so you might wish to use screen shots in lieu of any planned software demos. However, there should be time for a few examples of work product, and I encourage sharing those with the audience.&#10;&#10;I expect that tools that &quot;rigorously cite their sources&quot; will be of special interest to the audience, since this is a major criticism of some existing well-known tools. An example showing rigorous citing of a hallucination might be fascinating.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This sounds like an interesting, ambitious, timely topic. I would look forward to attending such a presentation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1198</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Visa, Sofia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author will discuss capabilities of generative AI software as co-author on writings in the field of history. It will be interesting to hear about good ways for using these new technological tools in writing about historical facts.&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author will discuss capabilities of generative AI software as co-author on writings in the field of history. It will be interesting to hear about good ways for using these new technological tools in writing about historical facts.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
