    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital History: Student Experimentation with Introductory DH Methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">history, pedagogy, introduction to DH, student work</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;18th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;History&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;Transatlantic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">18th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Education/Pedagogy&#10;History&#10;Transatlantic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;After learning basic skills in digital mapping and text analysis, intro history students at Grinnell College experimented with town of Grinnell census data to produce maps in ArcGIS Online and with primary sources in Voyant and Gale Digital Scholar Lab to produce text analysis. They used these experiences to reflect on data use, spatial history, digital fallibility, and the like. Later in the semester, students combined their mapping and text analysis skills by running Named Entity Recognition and doing subsequent mapping analysis of Olaudah Equiano’s 1789 memoir. This work around DH skill-building and digital assignments in an introductory class is the result of collaboration between a faculty member and various DH partners on campus, which has been an iterative process over many years. Presenters will discuss the pedagogical gains of melding introductory digital humanities and historical skills. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">After learning basic skills in digital mapping and text analysis, intro history students at Grinnell College experimented with town of Grinnell census data to produce maps in ArcGIS Online and with primary sources in Voyant and Gale Digital Scholar Lab to produce text analysis. They used these experiences to reflect on data use, spatial history, digital fallibility, and the like. Later in the semester, students combined their mapping and text analysis skills by running Named Entity Recognition and doing subsequent mapping analysis of Olaudah Equiano’s 1789 memoir. This work around DH skill-building and digital assignments in an introductory class is the result of collaboration between a faculty member and various DH partners on campus, which has been an iterative process over many years. Presenters will discuss the pedagogical gains of melding introductory digital humanities and historical skills.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Steelberg, Tierney</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Grinnell College</ss:Data></Cell>
