    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">141</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1049</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zoricic, Vera</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors contribute their collaborative experiences in a classroom setting where students used specific tools such as ArcGIS Online, Voyant, and Gale Digital Scholar Lab to perform digital mapping, text analysis, and Named Entity Recognition. The abstract&#039;s focus on collaboration is a benefit. Additionally, the sources used for analysis are particularly engaging.&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract would benefit from outlining the pedagogical outcomes and highlighting a theoretical framework for using digital tools. Examples of student work would also help illustrate the impact of using digital tools in the classroom.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1259</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Li, Yunxin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission provides a concrete example of an introductory Digital History course. Presenters will discuss the pedagogical gains of melding introductory digital humanities and historical skills, which is particularly important and much needed in a DH course. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission provides a concrete example of an introductory Digital History course. Presenters will discuss the pedagogical gains of melding introductory digital humanities and historical skills, which is particularly important and much needed in a DH course. To achieve this goal, I would suggest asking students to read and discuss some historical scholarship that uses DH methods.&#10;&#10;In addition to digital mapping and text analysis, I think network analysis and data visualization are also worth being included in this course, but only if the presenter feels the course needs more content. &#10;&#10;My other minor suggestion is to give students several options besides Olaudah Equiano’s 1789 memoir, which might enhance equity and fun. Students tend to be motivated when they can choose the content that they prefer and they can relate to. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1053</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Melkozernova, Arina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal discusses experiences of introductory digital humanities and historical skills and the pedagogical gains of combining them. This approach promotes an interdisciplinary mindset, shapes collaborative skills, and advocates for digital literacy by implementing close reading and distant reading practices. The submission can be accomplished in the time allotted (10-15 minutes).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal topic is connected to decolonial studies and culture because it applies the DH skills to the subsequent mapping analysis of Olaudah Equiano’s 1789 memoir. &#10; The project engages with digital pedagogies to introduce basic skills in digital mapping and text analysis. &#10;The purpose of the proposal is to discuss work around DH skill-building and digital assignments in an introductory class established through long-term collaboration between a faculty member and various DH partners on campus.&#10;The project offers a model for learning spatial and spatiotemporal analysis, modeling, visualization, text mining, and analysis in a meaningful and culturally significant way.&#10;The proposal includes an introduction outlining the purpose and objectives, the background, and expected outcomes. It touches on many disciplines, such as Digital History, Applied History, Environmental Humanities, and Transatlantic Studies, Cultural Geography, Indigenous Ecology, to name a few. The proposed pedagogical model for future learning is scalable and adaptable for diverse topics and disciplines.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
