    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Compulsive Compliance: AI, Contemporary Digital Art, and the Illusion of &quot;Opting Out&quot;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">art history, history, digital art, digital art history</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital art production and analysis&#10;Art history&#10;Computer science&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital art production and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Art history&#10;Computer science&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Contemporary Digital Art is a field first coined in the 1980s, though the first real &quot;digital art&quot; was created in the late 1960s, at the true dawn of the Computer Age. Since its inception, digital art has become a centerpiece for contemporary art, as its automation processes have seeped into traditional art practice. Computer numerical control (CNC) machines create drawings and prints from code, and web design is its own flourishing artistic subgenre. Internet aesthetics bleed into canvas paintings and vice versa. Perhaps most pertinent, of course, is art made by artificial intelligence (AI). AI art is the talk of the film, graphic design, and art industries; will AI take creatives&#039; jobs? Will it oversaturate the art market, to the point that it is impossible to tell the difference between &quot;real&quot; and generated art? These are relevant questions, but the question of this research is this: can we truly &quot;opt out&quot; of these artmaking practices? As automation creeps into creative spaces, there seem to be fewer ways for artists to truly create art untouched by computers, the Internet, or automation. This research is focused on this new form of artistic automation, and will use historical and present-day examples in order to parse out the idea that traditional and generative art can ever be separated now that it is increasingly merged together. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary Digital Art is a field first coined in the 1980s, though the first real &quot;digital art&quot; was created in the late 1960s, at the true dawn of the Computer Age. Since its inception, digital art has become a centerpiece for contemporary art, as its automation processes have seeped into traditional art practice. Computer numerical control (CNC) machines create drawings and prints from code, and web design is its own flourishing artistic subgenre. Internet aesthetics bleed into canvas paintings and vice versa. Perhaps most pertinent, of course, is art made by artificial intelligence (AI). AI art is the talk of the film, graphic design, and art industries; will AI take creatives&#039; jobs? Will it oversaturate the art market, to the point that it is impossible to tell the difference between &quot;real&quot; and generated art? These are relevant questions, but the question of this research is this: can we truly &quot;opt out&quot; of these artmaking practices? As automation creeps into creative spaces, there seem to be fewer ways for artists to truly create art untouched by computers, the Internet, or automation. This research is focused on this new form of artistic automation, and will use historical and present-day examples in order to parse out the idea that traditional and generative art can ever be separated now that it is increasingly merged together.</ss:Data></Cell>
