    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Poole, Carson Leigh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">carsonlpoole1@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pacific</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">55.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">46.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">143</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1083</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zou, Zhihui</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission discusses how human-generated and machine/AI-generated art could be separated in the modern world, especially when machine/AI-generated art is becoming more common in the industry.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The discussion of how web design could also be considered art is a wonderful topic because of the transition from code-based web design (using HTML, CSS, or RShiny, for example) to more user-friendly WordPress and Wix. The prerequisite for web design is lowering everyday. However, could we see a correlation between the transition to no-code culture and the rise of machine/AI-aided art production?&#10;&#10;The strength of this proposal is that it brings in the psychological perspective of the human confidence in &quot;yes I can definitely identify a human work and a machine work.&quot; A lot of times, the debate around digital art is not necessarily a technical one nor an artistic one but a psychological one that examines the audience.&#10;&#10;The proposal could be more specific about whether the &quot;opt-out&quot; is done on the artist&#039;s side or the audience&#039;s side. The proposal currently focuses on automation (which probably leans the work more toward the artist&#039;s side), but what choices do the audience have amid more and more artists are using automation?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This work is relevant for the connection between the art industry and technologies. I&#039;m very interested in hearing the details of this research. This work, however, is not specific enough regarding how it measures the degrees of &quot;opt-out.&quot; Is it a policy/legal question, a psychological question, a behavior question, or simply a philosophical question of how to define &quot;an artist&quot; and &quot;art&quot;?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1284</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rousseau, Paulina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission focuses on the generative AI in the production of art, focusing specifically on this new form of artistic automation, and aims to use historical and present-day examples in order to parse out the idea that traditional and generative art can never be separated.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The subject/topic of the proposal is a very pertinent one. The proposal would have benefitted from a stated connection to this year&#039;s conference focus (specifically to themes of anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, etc. &#10;&#10;Additionally, while an historical overview of the topic is briefly given, the proposal would have benefitted from engagement with relevant scholarship as well as a specific  methodological framework. Some specific examples of arguments to be made would have been appreciated as well.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract seemed to give a generalized overview of digital art without placing it within the scholarly conversation. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">46</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1081</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Haines, Chelsea</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission questions the role of AI automation in present and future artistic practices.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal focuses on a very compelling and timely subject, namely AI and automation in contemporary artistic practices. It asks if it is possible to separate computer-generated art from more traditional artistic practices today. While this line of questioning is certainly relevant, the proposal felt somewhat unfocused and general and it felt like the proposal could go in a number of directions, some of which were more related to each other than others (AI replacing creative jobs, automation, distinctions between computer-based art and other media). </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">48</ss:Data></Cell>
