    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A hybrid approach to digitizing and structuring complex print texts using AI</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data extraction, JSON, GPT, artificial intelligence, book history</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Book and Print history&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This paper presents a frontier approach to digitizing and structuring complex print materials, such as periodicals, magazines, and directories, by combining traditional techniques with artificial intelligence (AI). Leveraging the power of the Generative Pre-trained Transformer (GPT) language model, this method automates the conversion of unstructured text data into a structured JSON format, making it more accessible for computational analysis in digital humanities and book history research. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt; A case study demonstrates the potential of this approach using a collection of scanned print directories. The digitized texts undergo optical character recognition (OCR) and are then processed using data cleaning techniques, rule-based parsing, and the GPT-4-Turbo model to extract and structure relevant information. The implementation of a cross-referencing system enables the alignment of extracted information from multiple sources, despite variations in formatting and content. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt; This paper details the information extraction process, its formalization, and how complex print content can be more easily structured for analysis within digital humanities research. The significance of this research lies in its potential to rapidly and accurately extract knowledge from print texts, facilitating new avenues of inquiry. The encoding strategies employed are relevant for projects dealing with multi-layered information extraction and the development of structured datasets from unstructured historical texts. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper presents a frontier approach to digitizing and structuring complex print materials, such as periodicals, magazines, and directories, by combining traditional techniques with artificial intelligence (AI). Leveraging the power of the Generative Pre-trained Transformer (GPT) language model, this method automates the conversion of unstructured text data into a structured JSON format, making it more accessible for computational analysis in digital humanities and book history research. &#10; A case study demonstrates the potential of this approach using a collection of scanned print directories. The digitized texts undergo optical character recognition (OCR) and are then processed using data cleaning techniques, rule-based parsing, and the GPT-4-Turbo model to extract and structure relevant information. The implementation of a cross-referencing system enables the alignment of extracted information from multiple sources, despite variations in formatting and content. &#10; This paper details the information extraction process, its formalization, and how complex print content can be more easily structured for analysis within digital humanities research. The significance of this research lies in its potential to rapidly and accurately extract knowledge from print texts, facilitating new avenues of inquiry. The encoding strategies employed are relevant for projects dealing with multi-layered information extraction and the development of structured datasets from unstructured historical texts.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Graham, Nathan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Johns Hopkins University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nathan.graham@jhu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nathan.graham@jhu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Graham, Nathan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nathan.graham@jhu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
