    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">67.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">74.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">60.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">144</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1118</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Forster, Chris</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submissions discusses a novel method, using newly available technology, for moving from a digitized artifact to a more useful (structured) data format (here, JSON).&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This sounds like an interesting, and potentially very useful, presentation on ways to leverage GPT4 to improve digitized data. *How* useful, of course, will depend on the results. &#10;&#10;The focus here seems to be on structure (hence the importance of JSON as an output), but I wonder about the OCR step. My sense is that people have reported very good results with GPT-technologies for OCR correction, but the focus here seems to be on structuring the text data. I would also be interested in hearing whether and how GPT4 was useful for OCR correction.&#10;&#10;This proposal does not highlight or explicitly address the conference theme, but it does seem to me that proposals like this one have the potential to be quite useful in making data that has previously been overlooked to a range of digital humanities methods.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this could be a useful paper; I wonder a little if the scope wouldn&#039;t make more sense in a shorter format--as either a poster or a lightning talk. I don&#039;t have strong feelings on this, but if the gist is: using GPT4 to improve digitization, that sounds maybe a little short for a compelling paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">60</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1254</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Evans, Kenneth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal offers a big picture overview for employing emerging AI/ML tools to digitize complex print materials.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an important and timely proposal that will have wide applicability to DH. Documenting an open-source work flow, tool, or code to intelligently process complex records will enable the study of many, many documents. The proposal is clearly stated and likely to be of interest to many conference attendees.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1196</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Szydlowski, Nick</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal outlines a really interesting approach to dealing with data that has an underlying structure, but is currently stored as unstructured text or page images. Because the workflow for this approach seems to have been developed and to some extent tested, it would be very interesting to hear the details of the implementation and explore the benefits and pitfalls of this approach.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am most interested in hearing more about how this approach compares to alternate approaches, both in cost and labor-intensiveness, and in accuracy of the results. This abstract makes me very curious how this kind of approach compares on the one hand to &quot;old-fashioned&quot; scripting to create structured data and on the other hand to computational approaches that rely more fully on LLMs and maybe even eschew structured data entirely. Overall I think this is a really strong proposal and it only makes me want to hear more about this work.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
