    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The collective use and evaluation of generative AI tools in digital humanities research: Survey-based results</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital humanities, artificial intelligence, Generative AI, survey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;user experience design and analysis&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ethnographic analysis&#10;user experience design and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library and Information Science&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The advent of generative artificial intelligence (GenAI) technologies has transformed research, significantly impacting Digital Humanities (DH), a field closely tied to technological advancements. Literature shows GenAI’s support for various scientific research activities, including ideation, literature review, data collection, transcription, analysis, and academic writing (Van Noorden &amp; Perkel, 2023; Rahman et al., 2023). In DH, where interpretive and subjective human perspectives are vital, integrating GenAI presents nuanced challenges.  Humanities research’s critical engagement with complex cultural narratives, a task traditionally reliant on the intricate subtleties of human cognition and interpretive capacity, can potentially be reshaped by GenAI, posing questions about the balance between algorithmic effectiveness and the rich, often intangible human insights (Gefen et al., 2021; Rane, 2023; Karjus. 2023).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In this paper, we investigate GenAI in DH through the lens of Technology Adoption Theories, focusing on DH scholars’ perceptions and practices of GenAI in research. Specifically, we address two questions: (1) How do DH scholars adopt GenAI technologies to support various tasks in their research? (2) How do DH scholars perceive and evaluate the benefits, risks, and barriers of applying GenAI in DH research? We designed a Qualtrics-based survey and distributed it internationally via DH listservs from February 18 to March 20, 2024. From the 76 completed survey responses, we identified DH scholars’ rationales for adopting GenAI, the specific use cases and practices, and their views on GenAI’s benefits, risks, and impact on DH research. The survey results suggest that DH research communities hold divisive opinions towards the value of GenAI in research, with actual usage varying among individuals and across tasks. Our study is relevant to the ACH conference’s focus on AI and its consequences, and our survey-based analysis provides a foundation for further empirical research on the impact of GenAI on the evolution of DH scholarship.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The advent of generative artificial intelligence (GenAI) technologies has transformed research, significantly impacting Digital Humanities (DH), a field closely tied to technological advancements. Literature shows GenAI’s support for various scientific research activities, including ideation, literature review, data collection, transcription, analysis, and academic writing (Van Noorden &amp; Perkel, 2023; Rahman et al., 2023). In DH, where interpretive and subjective human perspectives are vital, integrating GenAI presents nuanced challenges. Humanities research’s critical engagement with complex cultural narratives, a task traditionally reliant on the intricate subtleties of human cognition and interpretive capacity, can potentially be reshaped by GenAI, posing questions about the balance between algorithmic effectiveness and the rich, often intangible human insights (Gefen et al., 2021; Rane, 2023; Karjus. 2023).&#10;In this paper, we investigate GenAI in DH through the lens of Technology Adoption Theories, focusing on DH scholars’ perceptions and practices of GenAI in research. Specifically, we address two questions: (1) How do DH scholars adopt GenAI technologies to support various tasks in their research? (2) How do DH scholars perceive and evaluate the benefits, risks, and barriers of applying GenAI in DH research? We designed a Qualtrics-based survey and distributed it internationally via DH listservs from February 18 to March 20, 2024. From the 76 completed survey responses, we identified DH scholars’ rationales for adopting GenAI, the specific use cases and practices, and their views on GenAI’s benefits, risks, and impact on DH research. The survey results suggest that DH research communities hold divisive opinions towards the value of GenAI in research, with actual usage varying among individuals and across tasks. Our study is relevant to the ACH conference’s focus on AI and its consequences, and our survey-based analysis provides a foundation for further empirical research on the impact of GenAI on the evolution of DH scholarship.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ma, Rongqian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Indiana University Bloomington</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rm56@iu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">fndedema@iu.edu, rm56@iu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ma, Rongqian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rm56@iu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">US Eastern Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">145</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1132</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Goble, Noah Zachary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission uses a widely distributed survey to investigate DH researchers’ reactions to the adoption of GenAI technologies. By garnering a wide variety of opinions from across the field, they help develop a vital foundation for further investigation.  &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission makes a compelling case for the import of its investigation, clearly laying out the particular relationship that the Digital Humanities as an academic project has to generative artificial intelligence. Methodologies are described specifically and concisely, giving a clear picture of the role their results play in developing this very new area of interest. I definitely felt a desire to see more of the results, and would suggest going further in depth into any particular patterns found among the responses and what their significance might be, but I understand wanting to save that for the presentation and paper itself. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1216</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ramakrishnan, Sharath Chandra</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The rise of publicly available AI trained on natural language poses a special consideration, for its use within the context of interpretative humanities where Text,  (archival and generative) is the central object of meaning making. This paper seeks to address this consideration, through the lens of questioning intentional research methods, and attitudes of digital humanities researchers when confronted with the choice of using Gen AI tools. I am curious to understand the main points of divisiveness within the community of academic researchers with respect to the adoption of emerging technologies for academic research. This is especially interesting in the case of emerging technologies such as Generative AI, that at once challenges and brings to question, the literary faculties and erudite skills in subjective, affective, reflective and expository writing that thus far have distinguished the role of humanities based scholars in academia. Implications of this paper might be considered to frame policies for produced academic work, by organizations like the NEH.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This study is promising, going by the questions it asks of DH practitioners regarding their attitudes towards using Gen AI tools for research. In my opinion, it would be interesting for the reader, if the authors discuss the generalizability or implications of their findings to the wider world of literature based research, in other traditional disciplines that share similar modes of inquiry and humanistic meaning making. Is there an aspect of GenAI&#039;s output that is of unique use to DH scholars when compared to practitioners in fields (like law, or library and information science scholars) who also use a humanistic interpretation of law and ethics.&#10;&#10;It would also be insightful to discuss the results of this study and the view of DH practitioners, regarding ways in which the use of new Gen AI tools is different or similar to previous work in DH that features the use intelligent algorithms and tools.  For instance, learning algorithms, like clustering, dimensionality reduction, graph-node presentations of information etc.. have featured as methodologies in previous DH work before the current generative AI wave.&#10;&#10; </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1142</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Stanton, Andrea</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a timely and thoughtful contribution to our understanding of current views of and uses / non-uses of generative AI among DH scholars / in DH projects. In my own experience, conversations around genAI and university academics have focused almost exclusively on teaching, primarily on students&#039; use of genAI but also on instructor use (and the ethical and learning / professional value of doing so). I appreciate this as a just-in-time, ground-up analysis of use and perspectives that focuses on a different area of academic work. &#10;&#10;Its also clearly and cogently written, which I believe will translate into a presentation of high interest and value for other conference attendees.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Overall assessment:&#10;&#10;This is a timely and thoughtful contribution to our understanding of current views of and uses / non-uses of generative AI among DH scholars / in DH projects. In my own experience, conversations around genAI and university academics have focused almost exclusively on teaching, primarily on students&#039; use of genAI but also on instructor use (and the ethical and learning / professional value of doing so). I appreciate this as a just-in-time, ground-up analysis of use and perspectives that focuses on a different area of academic work. &#10;&#10;Its also clearly and cogently written, which I believe will translate into a presentation of high interest and value for other conference attendees.&#10;&#10;Specific comments: I suspect you were limited by the abstract, but I&#039;d love to know how you are using Qualtrics and/or the specific survey questions to understand how DH views and usage vary by geographical location and personal and professional positionality. I&#039;d also love to know how you manage the possibility of someone filling out the survey more than once. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Hello! I&#039;m recommending this as a lightning talk because I think it could draw considerable participant interest. However, my recommendation is not intended to override whatever the authors / presenters listed as their preferred format. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
