    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Work of Art in the age of AI</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Art, reproduction, AI</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital art production and analysis&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital art production and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In the first of the three versions of his famous essay, “The work of Art in the Age of Its Technological Reproducibility,” Walter Benjamin outlines the historical processes behind art reproduction from the woodcut, to movable type, to photography. He writes that “For the first time, photography freed the hand from the most important artistic tasks in the process of pictorial reproduction tasks that now devolved upon the eye alone. And since the eye perceives more swiftly than the hand can draw, the process of pictorial reproduction was enormously accelerated, so that it could now keep pace with speech.” Photography emerged as a tool for both art reproduction but also art making. If photography freed the hand and relegated art making to the eye, then we might ask what role does algorithmic technology play in redefining art and art making. As Joanna Zylinska writes. “AI is here more than just a tooll. It becomes an active agent in shaping tastes, regulating markets and defining what counts as mainstream visuality. The work of art is therefore not just mechanically reproduced but also algorithmically produced.“ In this presentation, I will outline three provocations with regards to algorithmic art.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In the first of the three versions of his famous essay, “The work of Art in the Age of Its Technological Reproducibility,” Walter Benjamin outlines the historical processes behind art reproduction from the woodcut, to movable type, to photography. He writes that “For the first time, photography freed the hand from the most important artistic tasks in the process of pictorial reproduction tasks that now devolved upon the eye alone. And since the eye perceives more swiftly than the hand can draw, the process of pictorial reproduction was enormously accelerated, so that it could now keep pace with speech.” Photography emerged as a tool for both art reproduction but also art making. If photography freed the hand and relegated art making to the eye, then we might ask what role does algorithmic technology play in redefining art and art making. As Joanna Zylinska writes. “AI is here more than just a tooll. It becomes an active agent in shaping tastes, regulating markets and defining what counts as mainstream visuality. The work of art is therefore not just mechanically reproduced but also algorithmically produced.“ In this presentation, I will outline three provocations with regards to algorithmic art.</ss:Data></Cell>
