    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">147</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1088</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Polyck-O&#039;Neill, Julia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper advances a discussion, in the form of the author’s provocations, about the nature of art in the age of the algorithm. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract doesn’t provide sufficient detail as to the provocations the author wishes to advance, and as such, I’m left to deduce what they might be in relation to contextual quotes. Although I appreciate the limits of the parameters of the abstract and the usefulness of being so situated in and the overall relevance of the discussion, significantly more needs to be said about the content and arguments being advanced in the presentation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">36</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1263</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ministro, Bruno</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal explores the role of AI and algorithmic technology in redefining art making</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract proposes a timely reflection on AI, algorithmic culture and art making. This is a much-needed discussion, and I look forward to hearing a critical AI talk informed by media studies and the arts in the context of a digital humanities conference such as ACH. It is mentioned in the abstract that the proponent will &quot;outline three provocations with regards to algorithmic art.&quot; I would like to read more on these in the abstract because some details on this matter would help clarify the argument. Space was still available (200 words were used out of the 250 limit) to include at least a glimpse into what those three provocations are and why they matter to the argument.&#10;&#10;The proposal directly connects to the conference&#039;s scope through at least two topics mentioned in the CFP: &quot;AI and its consequences&quot; and &quot;Digital media, art, literature, history, music, film, and games.&quot; Even if the proposal&#039;s topic is not explicitly connected to the main conference focus on societal challenges in the digital humanities, it must be mentioned that a critical reflection on AI at the intersection of media studies and the arts is highly relevant today concerning societal challenges.&#10;&#10;Additionally, the proposal does not articulate explicitly its contribution&#039;s applicability, significance, and value to the digital humanities. I would suggest that the author&#039;s presentation focus on that for a minute, thus contributing to crossing bridges among different DH communities and enriching the field and discussions — as I am sure this presentation has the ability to.&#10;&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1255</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rudinsky, Joyce</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">application of Benjamin&#039;s &quot;technological reproducibility” to algorithmic art</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">needs more explanation of the &quot;provocations&quot;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I would have liked more info on what her ideas are but I looked at some of her work and I think she has the background to make this interesting</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">-1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rejected</ss:Data></Cell>
