    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Data Sanctorum: How the CoKL Database Project Extracts Meaning from Devotional Calendars</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Books of Hours, Devotional Calendars, Manuscripts, Databases</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;5th-14th Century&#10;15th-17th Century&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;manuscripts description, representation, and analysis&#10;Art history&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Theology and religious studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">5th-14th Century&#10;15th-17th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;manuscripts description, representation, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Art history&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Theology and religious studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Book of Hours was the prayer book for the laity from the High Middle Ages through the Renaissance, across the Latin West. One of the principle components of these manuscripts was a devotional calendar, containing holidays, saints&#039; days, and other observances. The Corpus Kalendarium Database, or CoKL DB(online at http://www.cokldb.org), is a publicly accessable, fully interlinked database of these calendars which allows users to see, compare and correlate the saints and feasts across manuscripts. Although still growing, it currently contains nearly 90,000 individual feast entries, representing more than 400 manuscript sources.&#10;These manuscripts are not just the Latin of the church, but the vernacular languages of the people, including French, Middle English, Dutch, and Italian. From these interlinked saints emerge local and transnational patterns only apparent with the application of modern digital techniques and technologies. This talk will discuss the underlying technology that supports the system, some of the discoveries made from this manuscript big data, and some of the ongoing work to use the database to localize uncatalogued manuscripts and identify genetic relationships among them</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Book of Hours was the prayer book for the laity from the High Middle Ages through the Renaissance, across the Latin West. One of the principle components of these manuscripts was a devotional calendar, containing holidays, saints&#039; days, and other observances. The Corpus Kalendarium Database, or CoKL DB(online at http://www.cokldb.org), is a publicly accessable, fully interlinked database of these calendars which allows users to see, compare and correlate the saints and feasts across manuscripts. Although still growing, it currently contains nearly 90,000 individual feast entries, representing more than 400 manuscript sources.&#10;These manuscripts are not just the Latin of the church, but the vernacular languages of the people, including French, Middle English, Dutch, and Italian. From these interlinked saints emerge local and transnational patterns only apparent with the application of modern digital techniques and technologies. This talk will discuss the underlying technology that supports the system, some of the discoveries made from this manuscript big data, and some of the ongoing work to use the database to localize uncatalogued manuscripts and identify genetic relationships among them</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
