    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">148</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1209</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">McEwan, John</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I can see enormous potential in this resource. I would be quite interested to hear about its current state of development and the underlying data model. The abstract hints at some of the research possibilities that the data offers, but without providing concrete information of the conclusions that the author has reached. I have no doubt that this online resource will be much easier to use that some of its print predecessors.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This resource has enormous potential to contribute to our understanding of medieval culture and to the digital humanities more generally. I was not previously aware of this project, so I would be quite interested to hear about its current state of development and the underlying data model. The abstract hints at some of the research possibilities that the data offers, but without providing much concrete information on the specific conclusions/discoveries. I have no doubt that this online resource will be much easier to use that some of its print predecessors. The abstract could be improved by including some explicit indications of how it aims to engage with the &#039;current state of the field&#039;. How does the user interface differ from some of its print predecessors? I&#039;d be very curious to know how the system handles ambiguous information, as I presume there are cases where saints are difficult to identify? Moreover, are there &#039;standard&#039; lists of saints that can serve as identifiers and are in use in this project, or has this project created its own list? I also wonder how the project approaches the problem of &#039;localizing&#039; manuscripts in both time and space when manuscripts can often be constructed over a period of time and can travel from place to place? I raise this questions simply to encourage the author to make more explicit the exciting implications of this work for the digital humanities more generally.   </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">60</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1106</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Walton, Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation will discuss the technology supporting the Corpus Kalendarium Database, which is a collection of the Book of Hours, and highlight some of the database&#039;s important revelations as well as the project&#039;s ongoing work to acquire more manuscripts. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a fascinating subject and impressive project. The author could have provided more detail about the specific discoveries they intend to highlight in their presentation, as those discoveries might help to tie this proposal more clearly to the conference theme. Likewise a little more specifics regarding the technology they intend to intend discuss would have been nice. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a cool project that could probably be shared as either a poster or lightning talk, which is not to say that there couldn&#039;t be a good paper from it. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1176</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Agostini, Caterina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper examines the Corpus Kalendarium Database, a devotional calendar database with multilingual, linked data.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper examines the Corpus Kalendarium Database, a devotional calendar database with multilingual, linked data. While handling materials from various areas, covering more than 1,000 years, the project opens up both detail-oriented analysis and panoramic overviews of saints devotion, linguistic traits, and even studies on manuscript origin and genealogies.&#10;&#10;Do you envision this paper as very technical for the study of scripts, linguistic variants, and material book history? Perhaps a survey of the main aspects could be given at the conference. Alternatively, perhaps, you might pursue a longue durée study of the devotion for one saint in particular. That reminds me of a recent exhibit at Notre Dame covered similar themes of devotion and pilgrimages, Mapping the Middle Ages: Marking Time, Space, and Knowledge by curator David Gura (https://cslc.nd.edu/news-and-events/events/2024/05/07/300652-exhibit-mapping-the-middle-ages-marking-time-space-and-knowledge/).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
