    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">AsteXT: BERT and the Changing Trends in 50 Years of Asian American Short Stories</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">BERT, Asian American Studies, Short Stories, Natural Language Processing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;natural language processing&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;natural language processing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The anthology &lt;em&gt;Aiiieeeee! An Anthology of Asian-American Writers&lt;/em&gt; (1974) significantly impacted the creation of an Asian American literature scholarship. In the past 50 years, scholars have conducted important work on Asian American novels or poems. However, the Asian American short story is an understudied topic. Amid the rise of online literary magazine publications today, more authors have the chance to publish their work. The AsteXT project builds a customized BERT language model that uses the Transformers model’s Encoder architecture to categorize Asian American short stories published between 1974 and 2024 according to publication year, genre, and work choices. The model will build the categorization method through TF-IDF, word embedding, and Naive Baynes classification functions. Like the novel and the poem, the short story is a vital venue for Asian American writers to express the impact of imperialism, cultural conflicts, immigration experience, and others. The AsteXT project seeks to bring these themes into conversation simultaneously. The project’s current hypothesis is that, as short story publication became more accessible to non-professional writers, the overall literary trend began curving toward a more experimental and less conventional one. I will use the AsteXT model&#039;s classification function to search for a correlation between publication year and the genres and themes encompassed in Asian American short stories.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;As the AsteXT project expands, the ultimate goal is to produce a Transformers Encoder-only architecture customized for the Asian American Studies communities at large and promote broader Digital Humanities engagement in this field.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The anthology Aiiieeeee! An Anthology of Asian-American Writers (1974) significantly impacted the creation of an Asian American literature scholarship. In the past 50 years, scholars have conducted important work on Asian American novels or poems. However, the Asian American short story is an understudied topic. Amid the rise of online literary magazine publications today, more authors have the chance to publish their work. The AsteXT project builds a customized BERT language model that uses the Transformers model’s Encoder architecture to categorize Asian American short stories published between 1974 and 2024 according to publication year, genre, and work choices. The model will build the categorization method through TF-IDF, word embedding, and Naive Baynes classification functions. Like the novel and the poem, the short story is a vital venue for Asian American writers to express the impact of imperialism, cultural conflicts, immigration experience, and others. The AsteXT project seeks to bring these themes into conversation simultaneously. The project’s current hypothesis is that, as short story publication became more accessible to non-professional writers, the overall literary trend began curving toward a more experimental and less conventional one. I will use the AsteXT model&#039;s classification function to search for a correlation between publication year and the genres and themes encompassed in Asian American short stories.&#10;As the AsteXT project expands, the ultimate goal is to produce a Transformers Encoder-only architecture customized for the Asian American Studies communities at large and promote broader Digital Humanities engagement in this field.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zou, Zhihui</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Duke University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">zhihui.zou@duke.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">zhihui.zou@duke.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zou, Zhihui</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">zhihui.zou@duke.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Standard Time (UTC-5)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">59.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">48.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">149</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1188</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Miller, Ben</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission proposes a model to identify possible thematic change over a 50 year period in Asian American short stories, a collection that has been understudied at scale.  The primary contribution of the submission is the application of a method to a new corpus and the insight that might provide relative to scholars studying and the community represented by this collection.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While the proposal does well in indicated the understudied nature of the collection, it doesn&#039;t provide details on that collection (any metric, such as how many stories, how many readers, how meaningful a cultural, literary, linguistic contribution internally or externally), on the origins of the model (from what works does it derive) or on how the model&#039;s outputs would be interpreted and connected to themes or other aspects that might change over the 50 year period represented by the two dates (from the publication of Aiiieeeee! to today), or on the corpus (is AsteXT an already available corpus?  what are the details of its collection, access, and scope).  While the project sounds meaningful and one I would enjoy learning about at ACH, the submission didn&#039;t have enough detail for the promise of the project to shine through.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">48</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1278</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Minot, Casie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers an exciting way to track publication trends across diverse writing communities and genres through using important forms of digital and technological categorization. More specifically, the submission leverages the power of computational methods and coding to categorize short stories published by Asian Americans between 1974 and 2024. It further shows how this intersection of identity and creative genre has transformed across generations, allowing scholars to see new ways to digital track trending themes, style, and other formal traits.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission provides an exciting glimpse into how scholars of history, literature, Asian American studies, and digital humanities might use computational tools to track certain themes and publication trends across certain years, decades, or generations. In this specific instance, the writer has detailed their methodology for the project and their hypothesis in great detail, which provides the reader a general understanding as to the project&#039;s relevance within academia and what it might offer scholars in the field. &#10;&#10;Going forward, the richness of what this project could offer scholars might be stated more directly and explicitly. The submission presents an exciting, new way to engage and sort through literary trends as intersecting with time period and identities, and a future revision might see a more direct statement highlighting this aspect and the project&#039;s importance to scholarship. Similarly, the submission might benefit by also placing their project&#039;s work in conversation with other contemporary scholars in the field to demonstrate how this project builds upon or reinvents something within the given fields their drawing upon, such as more recent research on Asian American literature and digital humanities literary projects. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1120</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kurzynski, Maciej</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project promises a BERT-based language model which the author wants to use to analyze Asian American short stories published between 1974 and 2024. The goal is to explore the changes in literary trends during this period.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project constitutes a valuable attempt to analyze Asian American fiction, short stories in particular, using computational methods of literary inquiry. The project is timely given the rising violence against Asian Americans in the US, and it is bound to increase our knowledge about an important but understudied aspect of Asian-American culture. &#10;&#10;However, the abstract in its current format contains a number of inaccuracies.&#10;&#10;The project description features numerous technical terms, but it does not provide a clear account as to how the author is going to combine them. For example, the author states that the AsteXT uses the Transformer Encoder architecture to categorize Asian American short stories, but then says that &quot;the model will build the categorization method through TF-IDF, word embedding, and Naive Baynes (sic) classification functions.&quot; These are contradictory approaches: BERT-like models transform textual data into vectors (embeddings), which can be then classified with some additional layer placed on top of the encoder. TF-IDF, on the other hand, considers tokens and words (or n-grams) in non-vectorized form (bag of words). Naive Bayes assumes independence between features, which might not hold true for BERT embeddings. One of the most suitable methods to analyze literary trends in large corpora, topic modeling, would be a much better choice.&#10;&#10;On another note, it is not clear as to how the customized BERT model will be different from the currently available, open-source English BERTs. Given that the bulk of Asian American fiction has been written in English, more explanation would be needed as to the need for yet another English BERT as well as the data used for training such a model. More specific information about the data sources should be included in the abstract.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
