    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Recognising and Rewarding Digital Scholarship: Towards a New Framework for the Publication and Evaluation of 3D Scholarly Editions</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3D, 3D scholarship, publication, peer review, mixed methods, research assessment</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;scholarly editing and editions development, analysis, and methods&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;scholarly editing and editions development, analysis, and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cultural studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;3D technologies for the digitisation, modelling, and simulation of data are being widely used in fields including heritage, history, archaeology, architecture, forensics, and engineering. However, the challenges of publishing 3D outputs as autonomous works of scholarship that are recognised and rewarded similarly to more traditional paradigms have been insufficiently addressed. In response to these challenges, our prior research (Schreibman and Papadopoulos, 2019; Papadopoulos and Schreibman, 2019) has proposed the creation of a framework for publishing 3D cultural heritage objects as 3D Scholarly Editions in which the 3D models essentially become the text of conventional publication paradigms. Experiments in the publication and peer review of interactive, multimodal scholarship by various journals and publishers (e.g., Journal of Digital History, Melusina Press, Stanford Digital Projects, Manifold, Digital Scholar, Quarto) highlight the evolving nature of scholarly communication. Such formats challenge the scholarly publication ecosystem in their FAIRness, recognition, and sustainability. Drawing from such attempts and considering the conceptual and methodological complexities that the evaluation and publication of such scholarship brings, PURE3D – through the NWO Open Science grant for OPER3D –&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;aims to provide an open and transparent publication and peer-review workflow&lt;em&gt;, &lt;/em&gt;ultimately becoming&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;a quality assured infrastructure that will enable the recognition of 3D Scholarship on a par with more traditional research outputs. Our presentation draws on a mixed-methods approach, including surveys, interviews, focus groups, and use case analyses, to explore the challenges and opportunities in publishing 3D scholarship. By situating our findings within broader initiatives aimed at reforming research assessment (e.g., DORA, CoARA, Recognition and Rewards), we aim to contribute to the ongoing discourse on enhancing the visibility, credibility, and impact of 3D scholarly works.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3D technologies for the digitisation, modelling, and simulation of data are being widely used in fields including heritage, history, archaeology, architecture, forensics, and engineering. However, the challenges of publishing 3D outputs as autonomous works of scholarship that are recognised and rewarded similarly to more traditional paradigms have been insufficiently addressed. In response to these challenges, our prior research (Schreibman and Papadopoulos, 2019; Papadopoulos and Schreibman, 2019) has proposed the creation of a framework for publishing 3D cultural heritage objects as 3D Scholarly Editions in which the 3D models essentially become the text of conventional publication paradigms. Experiments in the publication and peer review of interactive, multimodal scholarship by various journals and publishers (e.g., Journal of Digital History, Melusina Press, Stanford Digital Projects, Manifold, Digital Scholar, Quarto) highlight the evolving nature of scholarly communication. Such formats challenge the scholarly publication ecosystem in their FAIRness, recognition, and sustainability. Drawing from such attempts and considering the conceptual and methodological complexities that the evaluation and publication of such scholarship brings, PURE3D – through the NWO Open Science grant for OPER3D – aims to provide an open and transparent publication and peer-review workflow, ultimately becoming a quality assured infrastructure that will enable the recognition of 3D Scholarship on a par with more traditional research outputs. Our presentation draws on a mixed-methods approach, including surveys, interviews, focus groups, and use case analyses, to explore the challenges and opportunities in publishing 3D scholarship. By situating our findings within broader initiatives aimed at reforming research assessment (e.g., DORA, CoARA, Recognition and Rewards), we aim to contribute to the ongoing discourse on enhancing the visibility, credibility, and impact of 3D scholarly works.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
