    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cpapadopoulos84@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">k.papadopoulos@maastrichtuniversity.nl, alicia.walsh@maastrichtuniversity.nl, s.schreibman@maastrichtuniversity.nl, k.gillikinschoueri@maastrichtuniversity.nl</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Papadopoulos, Costas;&#10;Walsh, Alicia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">k.papadopoulos@maastrichtuniversity.nl;&#10;alicia.walsh@maastrichtuniversity.nl</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">CET</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">70.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">151</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1040</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ferretti, Giulia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal focuses on the issue related to the publication (and scientific recognition) of research involving 3D data digitization or modelling work. The challenge is to imagine new workflows for publishing 3D work and legitimizing these types of experiences as objects worthy of scientific relevance.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The topic explored by the article is absolutely relevant and concerns the legitimization by scientific communities of 3-D modelling and simulation, inscribed in the set of alternative forms and formats of knowledge to the traditional written text. &#10;&#10;The authors demonstrate a clear competence and understanding of the issues explored in the proposition. I would suggest, however, to better specify the disciplinary scope of the proposed work-flow: a 3D modelling in musicology may not have the same treatment nor the same epistemological background as a modelling in medicine, for example. The inherent diversity of such objects should, in my opinion, be taken into account during the presentation.&#10;Such clarification would also be useful from a methodological point of view, to specify the communities to which the interviews mentioned in the proposal will be submitted. &#10;&#10;Overall, however, this is a solid presentation that would deserve a space in the conference lineup.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1265</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Arbuckle, Alyssa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract proposes that 3D scholarly works are published as lone standing research outputs. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution considers multimodal scholarship and the challenges around publishing 3D scholarly objects, in particular. The presenters suggest that 3D cultural heritage objects be published as autonomous research products; they have developed a framework for doing so. This presentation will be valuable for ACH attendees as it considers the ways in which DH researchers can communicate their work in keeping with current and evolving publication and assessment standards. (A pressing topic that extends beyond 3D cultural heritage objects.) It will be interesting to understand better what is meant by the publishing framework becoming &quot;a quality assured infrastructure&quot;; of course, frameworks and infrastructures are quite different endeavours at very different scales. Speculation on how this transition would work, and how the infrastructure would interoperate with existing cultural heritage infrastructures, would be very welcome. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1136</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cary, Justin Robert</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shifting conventional publication paradigms to include more diverse texts, specifically 3D/object based publications such as 3D cultural heritage objects in order to enhance visibility, credibility and impact of 3D scholarly works. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission represents key movements in how the field considers not only what work is valued but how that work is viewed and what what mediums the work is viewed in.  Your research is crucial is shifting views and paradigms around scholarly research and creating a more inclusive field for viewing important 3D objects and materials as part of this scholarly, critically body of work.  This work is so important because often words on a page cannot accurately represent the deep and complex cultural and historical histories of so many people and a shifting of the medium and frame through which this scholarly work is done is required.  Thank you for this important work. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this would be an extremely valuable addition to the conference! </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
