    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Ebbs and Flows of Data: “Junk Data” and the Limits of Big Data Management in the Artist Archive</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital archives, mass digitization, artist archives, archive management</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital archiving&#10;digital libraries creation, management, and analysis&#10;Art history&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Media studies&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital archiving&#10;digital libraries creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Art history&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Media studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Following the digital and archival turns, arts and cultural organizations are transforming the ways their publics are interacting with their archives and special collections. Professionals in the GLAM sector (Galleries, Libraries, Archives and Museums) are working with computer scientists and digital humanities specialists to develop computational methods for the creation of accessible and comprehensive digital archives. These developments frequently seek to streamline mass-digitization processes to minimize labour demands while making previously inaccessible documents and information available to institutions and users more broadly. While these efforts have revolutionized key areas such as accessibility, records management, and impact and organizations such as the Digital Preservation Coalition develop standards and best practices, the real and possible effects of these leading-edge technological interventions remain understudied. What is lost to these processes and practices; what kinds of information are at risk of being elided in collections if we begin to rely wholesale on AI and other technological interventions to parse and sort through records and other “junk” materials such as spam email and other commonplace media in a media artist’s archive? Importantly, is there an analogue between these new digital practices and what is traditionally eliminated from an archive?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Looking to the delicate material relations of the Joyce Wieland archive and collection at York University and the Jo Spence archives at the Image Centre (Toronto, Canada) and Tate (UK) archives in conversation with archivists at these institutions, I consider the value of the mundane, material traces of the everyday in the media artist’s archive. I reflect on how innovative practices in digital archives currently obfuscate “junk data” that points to aspects of an artist’s private life and subjective experience and consider how mass digital methods might address and reconceptualize the relationship between an archival collection and what is most often discarded.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Following the digital and archival turns, arts and cultural organizations are transforming the ways their publics are interacting with their archives and special collections. Professionals in the GLAM sector (Galleries, Libraries, Archives and Museums) are working with computer scientists and digital humanities specialists to develop computational methods for the creation of accessible and comprehensive digital archives. These developments frequently seek to streamline mass-digitization processes to minimize labour demands while making previously inaccessible documents and information available to institutions and users more broadly. While these efforts have revolutionized key areas such as accessibility, records management, and impact and organizations such as the Digital Preservation Coalition develop standards and best practices, the real and possible effects of these leading-edge technological interventions remain understudied. What is lost to these processes and practices; what kinds of information are at risk of being elided in collections if we begin to rely wholesale on AI and other technological interventions to parse and sort through records and other “junk” materials such as spam email and other commonplace media in a media artist’s archive? Importantly, is there an analogue between these new digital practices and what is traditionally eliminated from an archive?&#10;Looking to the delicate material relations of the Joyce Wieland archive and collection at York University and the Jo Spence archives at the Image Centre (Toronto, Canada) and Tate (UK) archives in conversation with archivists at these institutions, I consider the value of the mundane, material traces of the everyday in the media artist’s archive. I reflect on how innovative practices in digital archives currently obfuscate “junk data” that points to aspects of an artist’s private life and subjective experience and consider how mass digital methods might address and reconceptualize the relationship between an archival collection and what is most often discarded.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
