    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">152</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1182</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boehlert, Krystal</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">What is lost using automation to make accessible large collections? Specifically looking at the friction between &quot;junk data&quot; or what the machine finds non-valuable and the mundane ephemera that make up an artist&#039;s life.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a fascinating question and I think a good time to pause and reflect on the archival silences that we are actively creating through AI and automations. If the research process requires human inferences, how does automation preclude certain threads of research. I&#039;m excited to hear more!&#10;&#10;I would be interested to hear if there was a particular collection that spurred this conversation? Would that identity or positionality help make a stronger connection to the conference theme?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1277</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karlin, Jojo</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission aims to address the materials that get winnowed in mass digitization of archival holdings. By looking at the tradeoffs made for wider findability, the author seeks to identify the &quot;mundane, material traces of the everyday in the media artist&#039;s archive.&quot; </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission treats a current and omnipresent subject: AI. A close look at the opportunities and dangers presented by AI in archival spaces would be very welcome at the ACH conference. While the objects discussed do not directly land within the global focus of the conference, the questions the author raises seem relevant across fields. My primary suggestion would be to address both methods (computer automated processes and historically manual processes) in terms of both what they save and discard, rather than comparing what one method affords to what the other obscures.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1307</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rehberger, Dean</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract outlines a critical examination of the impact of digital and computational methods on archival practices in the GLAM (Galleries, Libraries, Archives, and Museums) sector, particularly focusing on the potential loss of valuable information in the process of digitization and AI-assisted sorting.&#10;&#10;The author highlights several key points:&#10;&#10;1. Digital transformation in GLAM institutions: The abstract acknowledges the ongoing shift in how cultural organizations are making their archives and special collections accessible to the public through digital means.&#10;&#10;2. Collaboration between GLAM professionals and technologists: There&#039;s an emphasis on the partnership between GLAM sector professionals, computer scientists, and digital humanities specialists in developing computational methods for creating accessible digital archives.&#10;&#10;3. Benefits of mass digitization: The abstract recognizes the advantages of streamlined mass-digitization processes, including improved accessibility and broader availability of previously inaccessible material.&#10;&#10;4. Concerns about information loss: A critical question is raised about what information might be lost or overlooked when relying heavily on AI and other technological interventions to process and sort through archival materials.&#10;&#10;5. Focus on &quot;junk&quot; materials: The author expresses particular concern about the potential loss of seemingly mundane items like spam emails or other commonplace media in artists&#039; archives, which may hold significant value for understanding the artist&#039;s life and work.&#10;&#10;6. Case studies: The abstract mentions specific archives (Joyce Wieland at York University, Jo Spence at the Image Centre and Tate) as focal points for examining the value of everyday material traces in media artists&#039; archives.&#10;&#10;7. Reconceptualizing archival practices: The author suggests the need to reconsider how mass digital methods approach the relationship between what is preserved in an archival collection and what is typically discarded.&#10;&#10;This abstract effectively highlights the tension between the benefits of digital archival practices and the potential loss of nuanced, contextual information that may be overlooked by automated processes. It raises important questions about the future of archival practices in the digital age and calls for a more thoughtful approach to preserving the full spectrum of an artist&#039;s life and work.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Overall, this is a very strong proposal that addresses a very significant issue.  What I like best is the balance between traditional methods of exclusion and digital methods (in short, this is not a new and unique problem for the digital).  It should be a great presentation.  I would have been nice to have more of a balance in the abstract between the general introduction and the final brief paragraph on specific examples -- I think the specific examples will really help to ground the presentation.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a great proposal and very significant not only to DH but precisely for the topic of the conference -- how do we exclude when we are faced with so much? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
