    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Documenting Racism and Activism Using News Media: Virulent Hate&#039;s Evolving Approach</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Data Activism, Data Visualization, Asian Americans, COVID-19, Anti-Racism</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;History&#10;Media studies&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;History&#10;Media studies&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;What does it mean to collect data about social and political problems in real time? How do we produce public scholarship on racism and racial justice movements without exposing minoritized communities to the harms of datafication? Working with a team of undergraduate researchers, the Virulent Hate Project uses news media to identify, analyze, and map incidents of anti-Asian racism and anti-racist activism undertaken during the first two years of the COVID-19 pandemic. This paper considers how Virulent Hate&#039;s documentation process has evolved over the last four years, contending with a prolonged pandemic, a shifting political landscape, and an evolving understanding of the ramifications of our work.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In particular, this paper will reflect on the following points: our decision to document activism alongside racism; our efforts to ground our data visualizations in narrative rather than numerical analysis; our resistance to language that centers trends in &quot;hate crimes&quot; as the basis for tracking racism; and our approach to inclusive description. Our experiences with the Virulent Hate Project find theoretical grounding in Crooks &amp; Currie&#039;s conception of agonistic data practices, a form of data activism that centers affective and narrative analyses as a strategy for curtailing the misappropriation of curated data.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Overall, our project reveals the importance of continual self-reflection through the process of data curation and visualization, and offers interventions into digital public humanities, ethical approaches to data visualization, and more broadly, how to produce data-oriented public scholarship in relation to ongoing racial justice movements.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">What does it mean to collect data about social and political problems in real time? How do we produce public scholarship on racism and racial justice movements without exposing minoritized communities to the harms of datafication? Working with a team of undergraduate researchers, the Virulent Hate Project uses news media to identify, analyze, and map incidents of anti-Asian racism and anti-racist activism undertaken during the first two years of the COVID-19 pandemic. This paper considers how Virulent Hate&#039;s documentation process has evolved over the last four years, contending with a prolonged pandemic, a shifting political landscape, and an evolving understanding of the ramifications of our work.&#10;In particular, this paper will reflect on the following points: our decision to document activism alongside racism; our efforts to ground our data visualizations in narrative rather than numerical analysis; our resistance to language that centers trends in &quot;hate crimes&quot; as the basis for tracking racism; and our approach to inclusive description. Our experiences with the Virulent Hate Project find theoretical grounding in Crooks &amp; Currie&#039;s conception of agonistic data practices, a form of data activism that centers affective and narrative analyses as a strategy for curtailing the misappropriation of curated data.&#10;Overall, our project reveals the importance of continual self-reflection through the process of data curation and visualization, and offers interventions into digital public humanities, ethical approaches to data visualization, and more broadly, how to produce data-oriented public scholarship in relation to ongoing racial justice movements.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
