    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Technology of Survival: How Digital Humanities in Games and Afrofuturism can bridge the gap between culture and representation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Narrative, Game Aesthetics, Game Development, Game studies, Black studies, Science Fiction</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital archiving&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Design studies&#10;Game studies&#10;Media studies&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital archiving&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Race Studies&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Design studies&#10;Game studies&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In the mid-19th century Martin Delaney published what is considered the first African American science fiction novel &lt;em&gt;Blake; or the Huts of America&lt;/em&gt; as a serial in The Anglo-African Magazine. In culture, Science fiction is used as a tool for social commentary. The standard narrative design of the hero’s journey in a Western context is explicitly influenced by stereotypes of the other. Science fiction extracts from marginalized and non-Western cultures with colonial roots. alluded to by Indigenous scholars Eve Tuck &amp; K. Wayne Yang, in &lt;em&gt;&quot;Decolonization is Not a Metaphor&quot;&lt;/em&gt;   We see the intersects of race gender, and speculative fiction in the 20th-century work of Pauline Hopkins in &lt;em&gt;Of One Blood&lt;/em&gt; and W. E. B. Du Bois&#039;s 1920 story &lt;em&gt;The Comet&lt;/em&gt;. Both Black Sci-Fi Character works by Black sci-Fi authors are rendered invisible and hyper-visible through stereotypes and othering in sci-fi in games. Through this extraction and racialized otherness in science fiction Black Characters are rendered both invisible and hyper-visible through stereotypes and the usage of marginalized identities to inform narrative monstrosities through non-normative othering. Through these series of short games, I seek to remix our understanding of culture by intersecting concerns of race and gender as they relate to injustice and inequality. I do this by calling upon 1980s game aesthetics and leaning into text-based narratives; while simultaneously simplifying the game mechanics with text interest and on-screen puzzles. The creative works that have influenced my project include &lt;em&gt;Cyborg&lt;/em&gt; (1984) and &lt;em&gt;Méwilo &lt;/em&gt;(1987). &lt;em&gt;Cyborg&lt;/em&gt; is the core inspiration for this game series project&#039;s critical-making process and game mechanics. At the same time, &lt;em&gt;Méwilo&lt;/em&gt; informs the inclusion of culture and narrative design.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Run: a Sci-Fi Apocalypse Adventure&lt;/em&gt; is set in a future where Earth has colonized another planet. Throughout the game narrative the protagonist and the player are asked to consider what exactly reparation means and what is the price to be paid. &lt;em&gt;Run: Algorithms, AI, and Archives&lt;/em&gt; is set in an apocalypse future by human-designed technology. The last librarian and archivist in the apocalypse has been discovered. They have been tasked with keeping malicious code from destroying the last of human digital records. All Games in the series were made with Twine which utilized HTML JavaScript. Through this game both the protagonist and player are asked to consider the importance of archives and history in societies and culture. These games are an experimental short-form narrative game series with a Black protagonist and the first two in the game collection. I intend to create three more games for this series. The post-apocalypse has been of recent interest with scholars such as Lawrence Gross’s work &lt;em&gt;&quot;Post-apocalypse Stress Syndrome&quot;&lt;/em&gt; leading discourse on Indigenous epistemologies. For the scope and purpose of &lt;em&gt;The Run game series&lt;/em&gt;, I center Black thought and experience that are often rendered invisible. Through calling on the legacies of Black thought and centering of Afrofuturism these games examine sci-fi and fantasy themes and questions of gender race, social and economic injustice, and inequalities.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In the mid-19th century Martin Delaney published what is considered the first African American science fiction novel Blake; or the Huts of America as a serial in The Anglo-African Magazine. In culture, Science fiction is used as a tool for social commentary. The standard narrative design of the hero’s journey in a Western context is explicitly influenced by stereotypes of the other. Science fiction extracts from marginalized and non-Western cultures with colonial roots. alluded to by Indigenous scholars Eve Tuck &amp; K. Wayne Yang, in &quot;Decolonization is Not a Metaphor&quot;   We see the intersects of race gender, and speculative fiction in the 20th-century work of Pauline Hopkins in Of One Blood and W. E. B. Du Bois&#039;s 1920 story The Comet. Both Black Sci-Fi Character works by Black sci-Fi authors are rendered invisible and hyper-visible through stereotypes and othering in sci-fi in games. Through this extraction and racialized otherness in science fiction Black Characters are rendered both invisible and hyper-visible through stereotypes and the usage of marginalized identities to inform narrative monstrosities through non-normative othering. Through these series of short games, I seek to remix our understanding of culture by intersecting concerns of race and gender as they relate to injustice and inequality. I do this by calling upon 1980s game aesthetics and leaning into text-based narratives; while simultaneously simplifying the game mechanics with text interest and on-screen puzzles. The creative works that have influenced my project include Cyborg (1984) and Méwilo (1987). Cyborg is the core inspiration for this game series project&#039;s critical-making process and game mechanics. At the same time, Méwilo informs the inclusion of culture and narrative design.&#10;Run: a Sci-Fi Apocalypse Adventure is set in a future where Earth has colonized another planet. Throughout the game narrative the protagonist and the player are asked to consider what exactly reparation means and what is the price to be paid. Run: Algorithms, AI, and Archives is set in an apocalypse future by human-designed technology. The last librarian and archivist in the apocalypse has been discovered. They have been tasked with keeping malicious code from destroying the last of human digital records. All Games in the series were made with Twine which utilized HTML JavaScript. Through this game both the protagonist and player are asked to consider the importance of archives and history in societies and culture. These games are an experimental short-form narrative game series with a Black protagonist and the first two in the game collection. I intend to create three more games for this series. The post-apocalypse has been of recent interest with scholars such as Lawrence Gross’s work &quot;Post-apocalypse Stress Syndrome&quot; leading discourse on Indigenous epistemologies. For the scope and purpose of The Run game series, I center Black thought and experience that are often rendered invisible. Through calling on the legacies of Black thought and centering of Afrofuturism these games examine sci-fi and fantasy themes and questions of gender race, social and economic injustice, and inequalities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Beverly-Porter, Diamond</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Washington state university</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">d.beverly-porter@wsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">diamondebp@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">d.beverly-porter@wsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">BeverlyPporter, Diamond</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">d.beverly-porter@wsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pacific Daytime (PDT)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">74.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">54.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">154</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1052</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Coghill, KáLyn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The &quot;Run&quot; game series, comprised of &quot;Run: A Sci-Fi Apocalypse Adventure&quot; and &quot;Run: Algorithms, AI, and Archives,&quot; explores complex themes through experimental short-form narratives with a Black protagonist. Set in dystopian futures—one on a colonized planet and the other in a tech-driven apocalypse—the games challenge players to consider notions of reparation and the critical role of archives and history in society. Utilizing Twine with HTML and JavaScript, the series incorporates Black thought and Afrofuturism, addressing often marginalized perspectives and issues of gender, race, social, and economic injustice. Inspired by recent scholarly work like Lawrence Gross’s &quot;Post-apocalypse Stress Syndrome,&quot; the series aims to highlight Black experiences and contribute to discussions on sci-fi and fantasy within the context of post-apocalyptic narratives. The intention to expand the series with three more games further emphasizes a commitment to centering these underrepresented perspectives.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Run game series is notable for its thematic depth, which delves into complex issues such as reparation, the importance of archives, and socio-political challenges. These themes are explored through innovative short-form narratives featuring a Black protagonist. The series&#039; use of Twine with HTML and JavaScript demonstrates a creative technological integration and cultural relevance, incorporating Black thought and Afrofuturism to enrich the sci-fi and fantasy discourse. The series benefits from scholarly inspiration, notably Lawrence Gross&#039;s work, which adds academic weight. However, as an experimental series, it may face challenges in balancing thematic depth with player engagement and accessibility. The technical constraints of Twine could limit the complexity of interactive elements, and ensuring broad visibility and impact will require effective marketing. Additionally, maintaining narrative consistency while integrating diverse themes and executing successful expansions will be crucial for the series&#039; continued success. It may also be helpful to clarify how this installation will be set up at the conference or how folks will access or “experience” Run.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project is very unique and will be a great contribution to the conference. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1303</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Roy, Samya Brata</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission tries to look into the &#039;Run&#039; game series from the perspective of Black thought and experience that is often ignored. The author themselves intend to contribute to the game series to vocalize the questions of such human expression from a perspective of critical making.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The subject of the contribution fits very well with the theme of the conference. The abstract however could have engaged a little more with relevant research. It is lacking in terms of structural and methodological clarity and articulation. However, because it is an installation or a performative piece leaning towards critical making, I lean towards my decision of acceptance. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">54</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Grumbach, Liz</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This installation/performance seeks to remix aspects of games in order to surface questions of justice/injustice and Afrofuturist futures. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal for an installation that interrogates gender, race, and injustice via a Twine-based post-apocalyptic game is a promising experiment in how apocalyptic futures, science fiction, and Afrofuturist thought can present us with a productive mirror of our current moment. It is incredibly relevant to the conference theme, and the proposal cites inspirations and scholarship that inform the creation of this project. &#10;&#10;It would be beneficial if the proposal was direct about the social commentary that this sci-fi game will make. It&#039;s implicit that the intention is to present a Black protagonist (often otherwise make invisible and othered in sci-fi) at the center of a narrative about reparation and interrogate what that means, but how will the game mechanics and design choices allow for the exploration of indigenous and justice-oriented futures? As a brief example, the proposal mentions choosing 1980s game aesthetics; how is this design choice, in particular, a mechanism for interrogating justice and injustice? As a reader with deeper knowledge, I can surface for myself that perhaps the 1980s aesthetic was chosen because of the history of the social justice movement in the 1980s, or because the 1980s had some iconic science fiction games and movies that you intend to remix to purposefully tell another version of a story that previously othered Black characters. This proposal is incredibly promising, and I would encourage the organizers to accept it, with some revisions to the abstract. It&#039;s possible that the needed content is already here, and some light editing and reorganization would surface it.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">If there is no room in the program for this as an installation, I think it could join the poster session in WorkAdventure. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
