    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Grounding Exercises: Embodied Data and Visceralization of Online Accounts of Dissociative Experiences</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data visualization, critical making, disability studies, online communities, trauma</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;3d printing, critical making&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Disability and differently-abled studies&#10;Humanities Computing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3d printing, critical making&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Disability and differently-abled studies&#10;Humanities Computing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;“Grounding Exercises” is a series of data visceralizations and artistic representations of dissociative experiences. Dissociation is characterized by feelings of detachment or unreality of the self or surroundings. This disconnection between mind, body, feeling, or memory can result in out-of-body experiences, amnesia, or struggles with identity. Dissociative disorders are psychiatric in nature, often stemming from trauma or acute stress such PTSD (American Psychiatric Association 2013). For those who suffer, articulating the experience of disconnection can be challenging, not only due to the nature of the symptoms themselves, but also the internalized stigma and persistent sense of alienation. However, in online spaces, such as Reddit, sufferers find community with others, posting: “Does anyone else experience this?”&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;“Grounding Exercises” emphasizes the community’s resounding “yes,” their experiences of dissociation in their own words and efforts to connect and ground, translated via visceralized representations of those experiences at scale. In clinical psychology, particularly in the context of dissociation, “grounding” refers to strategies to reconnect with the present moment and physical senses. Drawing on the work of Kelly Dobson (Dobson 2016), “Grounding Exercises” follows this resistance to the extraction and alienation of data in its representation, but instead bringing interactive, sensory, and embodied experience to data. This installation focuses on the (dis)embodiment in depersonalization, using text analysis on Reddit communities. Looking closely at body parts, this analysis will look at symptoms, sentiments, and context of experiences. Visceralizations will combine sound, sculpture, and interactivity to engage viewers in (dis)embodiment and groundedness.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;American Psychiatric Association. (2013). Dissociative Disorders. In &lt;em&gt;Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders&lt;/em&gt; (5th ed.). https://doi.org/10.1176/appi.books.9780890425596.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Kelly Dobson. (2016). The Energy Propagated. https://cargocollective.com/TheEnergyPropagated.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">“Grounding Exercises” is a series of data visceralizations and artistic representations of dissociative experiences. Dissociation is characterized by feelings of detachment or unreality of the self or surroundings. This disconnection between mind, body, feeling, or memory can result in out-of-body experiences, amnesia, or struggles with identity. Dissociative disorders are psychiatric in nature, often stemming from trauma or acute stress such PTSD (American Psychiatric Association 2013). For those who suffer, articulating the experience of disconnection can be challenging, not only due to the nature of the symptoms themselves, but also the internalized stigma and persistent sense of alienation. However, in online spaces, such as Reddit, sufferers find community with others, posting: “Does anyone else experience this?”&#10;“Grounding Exercises” emphasizes the community’s resounding “yes,” their experiences of dissociation in their own words and efforts to connect and ground, translated via visceralized representations of those experiences at scale. In clinical psychology, particularly in the context of dissociation, “grounding” refers to strategies to reconnect with the present moment and physical senses. Drawing on the work of Kelly Dobson (Dobson 2016), “Grounding Exercises” follows this resistance to the extraction and alienation of data in its representation, but instead bringing interactive, sensory, and embodied experience to data. This installation focuses on the (dis)embodiment in depersonalization, using text analysis on Reddit communities. Looking closely at body parts, this analysis will look at symptoms, sentiments, and context of experiences. Visceralizations will combine sound, sculpture, and interactivity to engage viewers in (dis)embodiment and groundedness.&#10;American Psychiatric Association. (2013). Dissociative Disorders. In Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders (5th ed.). https://doi.org/10.1176/appi.books.9780890425596.&#10;Kelly Dobson. (2016). The Energy Propagated. https://cargocollective.com/TheEnergyPropagated.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dwyer, Kaylen</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tufts University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kaylen.dwyer@tufts.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kaylen.dwyer@tufts.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dwyer, Kaylen</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kaylen.dwyer@tufts.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ET</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">60.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">155</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1040</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ferretti, Giulia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This installation proposal focuses on the psychiatric topic of dissociative disorders and will be created starting from the textual analysis of Reddit discussions on this topic. &#10;The abstract proposes to create sensory experiences, with the intention of connecting, embodying, and then grounding such experiences of dissociation. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is very interesting, but I think the abstract should have clarified how the textual analyses mentioned will be carried out and how these analyses will be used for the purposes of the installation.&#10;&#10;The disease/ remedy and detachment/grounding duality that this proposal promises to explore is of particular interest. However, this duality poses the problem of making installation users who have never experienced dissociative disorders understand both the sense of the disorders and the sense of their remedy. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1289</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Traylor, Jordan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission contributes &quot;Grounding Exercises,&quot; a series of data visceralizations of dissociative experiences. Text analysis is performed on Reddit communities of those who experience dissociative experiences, focusing on depersonalization, which is combined with multimedia to engage viewers.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">It will be interesting to see how powerfully the data will be augmented or &quot;conceptualized&quot; by this multimedia experience proposed by the author. I am unfamiliar with Dobson&#039;s work, but I assume it is substantial enough to demonstrate adequate engagement with the literature. The abstract shows strong sociopolitical engagement by noting the internalization of stigma surrounding dissociative disorders and the use of online spaces to mitigate this stigma. I wonder how the techniques employed by the author to construct &quot;Grounding Exercises&quot; might be applied in augmenting other DH projects - this is something that can hopefully be expanded upon. As far as I can tell, the abstract bears no connection to antiracist work, Indigenous studies, etc., but it does present an interesting study on the culture of those with dissociative disorders.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">66</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1156</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Black, Michael</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation builds on past creative work on &quot;visceralization&quot;, producing new experiences related to feelings of dissociation and disconnection. It uses large-scale text analysis, primarily of Reddit posts/comments, to produce its interactive experience.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Even without a prior familiarity with work on &quot;visceralization,&quot; I was able to get a strong general sense of what the installation will provide to participants. The author has a very clear vision and does well at identifying the types of data within the larger corpus of Reddit comments/posts they want to focus on. Two areas where the author could articulate better are noting the stakeholders and broader intentions in media theory/design. The proposal is tagged as relevant to disability studies, for instance, but apart from reference to DSM definitions, its unclear what contributions the installation could make for that field (in theory or in practice). Similarly, there is only a single citation situating the work in media design. Given that machine learning is increasingly seen as in conflict with human-driven forms of work (esp. with the rise of genAI), newcomers from other areas of the humanities may want to know what this work says or how it responds to those debates.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">60</ss:Data></Cell>
