    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Increasingly, scholar-teachers want to bring data skills and data literacy into their classroom. Many researchers are integrating library services into faculty and student research workflows. However, simply dropping some digital or data activities into the 16 week semester is rarely a success without significant contextualization. Part of the larger Digital Borderlands in the Classroom initiative, generously funded by the Mellon Foundation, offers an opportunity for faculty with particular interests in the socio-cultural geography around the US-Mexico border to engage with digital skills, physical collections, and open educational practices. This is particularly of interest to us, as the University of Arizona is located approximately 70 miles from the US-Mexico border, and is a major hub of cross-cultural contact.We are conscious that in many cases, the history, culture, and geography of the US-Mexico border comes with its own data and privacy concerns, and we all bring different disciplinary knowledge to the table. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Building off our training in disciplines outside those of the first cohort - Jeff is trained in biology and Heather is trained in literary linguistics - we developed two days’ worth of programming around data literacy and digital literacy. We will discuss the development and execution of four separate sessions for the inaugural &lt;em&gt;Digital Borderlands in the Classroom &lt;/em&gt;cohort: an introduction to thinking with and about data, text as data, digital storytelling with Storymaps, and data visualization practices. For each session, we provided a framework for engaging with the topic, while encouraging faculty to explore their biases and expectations for the digital platforms. In this paper, we will discuss how &lt;em&gt;Digital Borderlands in the Classroom &lt;/em&gt;offers a model for digital pedagogy for scholars in the humanistic social sciences. We will offer some reflections on the complexities of working at the intersection of interdisciplinary research and multilingual materials.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Increasingly, scholar-teachers want to bring data skills and data literacy into their classroom. Many researchers are integrating library services into faculty and student research workflows. However, simply dropping some digital or data activities into the 16 week semester is rarely a success without significant contextualization. Part of the larger Digital Borderlands in the Classroom initiative, generously funded by the Mellon Foundation, offers an opportunity for faculty with particular interests in the socio-cultural geography around the US-Mexico border to engage with digital skills, physical collections, and open educational practices. This is particularly of interest to us, as the University of Arizona is located approximately 70 miles from the US-Mexico border, and is a major hub of cross-cultural contact.We are conscious that in many cases, the history, culture, and geography of the US-Mexico border comes with its own data and privacy concerns, and we all bring different disciplinary knowledge to the table. &#10;Building off our training in disciplines outside those of the first cohort - Jeff is trained in biology and Heather is trained in literary linguistics - we developed two days’ worth of programming around data literacy and digital literacy. We will discuss the development and execution of four separate sessions for the inaugural Digital Borderlands in the Classroom cohort: an introduction to thinking with and about data, text as data, digital storytelling with Storymaps, and data visualization practices. For each session, we provided a framework for engaging with the topic, while encouraging faculty to explore their biases and expectations for the digital platforms. In this paper, we will discuss how Digital Borderlands in the Classroom offers a model for digital pedagogy for scholars in the humanistic social sciences. We will offer some reflections on the complexities of working at the intersection of interdisciplinary research and multilingual materials.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Froehlich, Heather</ss:Data></Cell>
