    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">froehlich@arizona.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">froehlich@arizona.edu, jcoliver@arizona.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Froehlich, Heather</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">froehlich@arizona.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Arizona, Mountain Standard time.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">156</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1277</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karlin, Jojo</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission aims to share reflections from the interdisciplinary, multi-lingual pedagogy the authors undertook as part of the Digital Borderlands in the Classroom initiative. The initiative, geared towards faculty teaching the socio-cultural geography around the US-Mexico border. By reviewing the workshops on digital skills, physical collections, and open educational practices, the submission authors seek to share how their four sessions can help faculty integrate data work into their teaching.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission would be of great interest to the ACH community. Understanding how research and pedagogy incorporate data and computational techniques, especially in contexts where the materials and the practitioners are working across languages and political jurisdictions, would appeal to a wide range of scholars. Having a concretely defined dataset should help keep the presentation focused, but as much as possible, I encourage the authors to narrow the presentation to elicit a deeper conversation.&#10;&#10;The strengths of this submission include its focus on multi-lingual materials in complex situations as well as its attention to the issues that arise when data literacy is taught without deep integration into a course of study. The authors describe a specific context that would likely be relevant to many instructors at ACH.&#10;&#10;It would be helpful for the authors to clarify how their workshops were applied and evaluated by the participants.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1226</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Spiro, Lisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission provides a case study of integrating data literacy skills into classes about the US-Mexico border.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers insights into digital pedagogy, particularly in working with multilingual materials. It offers a potential model for a faculty training program on data concepts, data visualization, and text as data. The proposal could be strengthened by discussing related work and by providing assessment data about the effectiveness of its pedagogical methods.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1049</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zoricic, Vera</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors present a solid overview of their project and their developed sessions. The focus on geography and its socio-cultural relevance to the US-Mexico border is particularly engaging, as are the structured sessions. The authors&#039; interdisciplinary expertise in biology and literary linguistics enriches the initiative. They also stress the pedagogical relevance of the project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a substantial contribution that is highly relevant to the field. To improve the contribution, I suggest including key activities and learning outcomes. It would also be helpful if the authors included participants&#039; reflections and ideas for improvement based on feedback. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
