    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Western_Europe</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mikblogger.rainone@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mikblogger.rainone@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">RAINONE, MICHELE</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mikblogger.rainone@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rome, Italy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">34.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">157</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1092</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Froehlich, Heather</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Search Engine Optimization (SEO) has an affect on writing for the web (discoverability, response to algorithmic bias, etc). </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an intriguing submission and I believe it has strong potential to be very interesting to the conference. What is hurting the abstract the most, at least for me, is a lack of a coherent discussion of methodology -- I am not sure how the author intends to derive their results. Evidence of how this issue might affect e.g. underrepresented groups/communities online would have helped me a lot too, especially in light of the call for papers and the first assessment question. This strikes me as as an easy hook for why we would be interested in seeing this particular presentation.&#10;&#10;All that said, this topic feels especially timely as Google and other search engines are on this intense AI bender that is burying different kinds of results beyond the already established algorithmic sorting. I am curious about the proposed outcomes (especially as a syntactic issue: I have long suspected that we are dropping pronouns and conjunctions especially in article titles on the web for higher page ranking.) I wish the author tremendous luck with this research in the future and I look forward to seeing this as a publication elsewhere because I think it has high potential to be important. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">34</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1063</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lizama Mue, Yadira</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper reflects on the influence of search engines, particularly Google, in the success of web writing. This is a relevant point for content creators and editors. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Overall, the submission addresses a relevant and timely topic within the digital humanities. I recommend explaining or integrating specific examples or case studies to illustrate the points made. This will provide concrete evidence to support the arguments and enhance the presentation&#039;s practical relevance. I also recommend detailing the methodological approach of the paper. What type of experiments is the author conducting to draw conclusions about the influence of search engines on web writing practices? Is the author looking into a particular case study or data? Besides these improvements, I consider the presentation could significantly contribute to the scope of ACH 2024 and to the Digital Humanities in general. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1202</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tekgürler, Merve</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author studies how search engine optimization tactics influence web writing, precisely how use of specific keywords, impact of trends, and adherence to Google&#039;s guidelines complicate the way we think of web writing.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I found this question of the relationship between SEO and web writing really interesting because like the author points out, we tend to think of web writing as casual activity, especially in the DH setting, as if this is still the days of the HTML websites but it is actually not the case. &#10;First, I have one clarifying question. What is the language of the author&#039;s sources? The presentation language is posted as Italian but there is no indication in the submission about which language(s) the author is studying.&#10;Second, search ranking is a difficult problem because of Google&#039;s opacity, even with the guidelines there is not always a clear cut reason that doing A impacted ranking x much. So a lot of what we know about SEO/ranking is based on inference from experimental and experiential settings. It would be great if the author can clarify how they intent to build a causal (or not) relationship between the web writing contents and ranking, or is it sufficient that the web writers change their behavior/writing in line with SEO tactics? In other words, to what extent is the author studying SEO/Google&#039;s ranking and does it matter that the changes in writing had an observable impact on ranking or is it sufficient to see that the attitudes towards web writing changed as observed in the language of the texts?&#10;Thirdly, the author needs to write a more in-depth methods paragraph/note. Based on the keywords and my familiarity with NLP, I can infer that the author is going to conduct some kind of a text analysis, possibly (i am guessing here) on web writing datasets from different periods to narrow down to the impact of SEO. But I might be wrong. Either way, the abstract should include a more clear description of the data and the methods.&#10;Lastly, I would like to encourage the author to think about the intersectional dimensions of their research questions. How does search ranking intersect with non-English/non-Italian content? What about textual markers of geographical location, gender, race, political positionality, among other factors? What does studying the changes in writing wrt SEO tell us about SEO itself and the power dynamics that basically define what is worth showing in searches? Relatedly, I would be curious to see if the author interacted with the AI-augmented results that Google is forcing onto its users, out of personal curiosity.&#10;Overall, I think this is a great research question and one that has implications for all of us who are on the Internet. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
