    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital Art History and the Web: An Introduction to Web Archive Data Analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">web archives, digital art history</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital archiving&#10;Art history&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital archiving&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Art history</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Despite the abundance of artistic production online, there remains a scarcity of professional development opportunities for digital humanists and digital art historians who seek to work with web archives computationally (e.g., text and data mining, data visualization, network analysis). Moreover, the web has solidified as a medium for art materials over the last decade, but the amount of content and its ephemerality has increased as many galleries, arts organizations, and artists have been impacted by the pandemic. This has highlighted the importance of a preservation model that leverages shared infrastructure, expertise and collecting activities amongst art libraries to scale the extent of web-published, born-digital materials preserved and accessible for art scholarship and research. The Collaborative ART Archive (CARTA) is uniquely positioned to curate collections of ephemeral, web-based art resources primed for computational use. As a distributed group of 40+ art libraries that collectively curates and preserves at-risk web-based art history primary sources, CARTA has preserved and made accessible over 900 websites, totaling over 16 TB of data with continued growth. Unified access to the collaborative collecting effort is possible through the open access CARTA portal (https://carta.archive-it.org/).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;CARTA team members at the Internet Archive propose a short workshop or demonstration (90 mins) that introduces digital art historians and digital humanists to web archives as a primary source in computational research. It provides hands-on experience computationally analyzing data from CARTA collections using nonprofit services and open source tools like ARCH (Archives Research Compute Hub) and Palladio. Workshop participants will understand how ARCH can be used to build custom research collections relevant to a wide range of digital art history subjects; generate, access, and analyze research-ready datasets from collections; and publish and preserve these datasets.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Digital Art History and the Web: An Introduction to Web Archive Data Analysis builds upon prior experience providing professional development opportunities for scholars and professionals at the National Humanities Alliance Conference, Art Libraries Society of North America (ARLIS/NA) annual conference, the National Gallery of Art, and the BitCurator Forum. Participants in the proposed workshop will gain fluency in foundational web archive concepts as well as an introduction to common research methods.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Learning objectives:&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;-Learn about CARTA’s web archive primary sources, research use cases and how to support them in a way that promotes computational engagement, scholarship, and research for digital art historians&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;-Understand web archives as data and the web archival (WARC) file format for preservation and computational access&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;-Explore representative processes for analyzing computational research datasets with free and open source software&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Outline:&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;0:00: Welcome, introductions, learning objectives&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;0:10: CARTA overview&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;0:25: Web archives as data&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;0:45: ARCH demo&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;1:05: Palladio demo&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;1:20: Q&amp;A&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Despite the abundance of artistic production online, there remains a scarcity of professional development opportunities for digital humanists and digital art historians who seek to work with web archives computationally (e.g., text and data mining, data visualization, network analysis). Moreover, the web has solidified as a medium for art materials over the last decade, but the amount of content and its ephemerality has increased as many galleries, arts organizations, and artists have been impacted by the pandemic. This has highlighted the importance of a preservation model that leverages shared infrastructure, expertise and collecting activities amongst art libraries to scale the extent of web-published, born-digital materials preserved and accessible for art scholarship and research. The Collaborative ART Archive (CARTA) is uniquely positioned to curate collections of ephemeral, web-based art resources primed for computational use. As a distributed group of 40+ art libraries that collectively curates and preserves at-risk web-based art history primary sources, CARTA has preserved and made accessible over 900 websites, totaling over 16 TB of data with continued growth. Unified access to the collaborative collecting effort is possible through the open access CARTA portal (https://carta.archive-it.org/).&#10;CARTA team members at the Internet Archive propose a short workshop or demonstration (90 mins) that introduces digital art historians and digital humanists to web archives as a primary source in computational research. It provides hands-on experience computationally analyzing data from CARTA collections using nonprofit services and open source tools like ARCH (Archives Research Compute Hub) and Palladio. Workshop participants will understand how ARCH can be used to build custom research collections relevant to a wide range of digital art history subjects; generate, access, and analyze research-ready datasets from collections; and publish and preserve these datasets.&#10;Digital Art History and the Web: An Introduction to Web Archive Data Analysis builds upon prior experience providing professional development opportunities for scholars and professionals at the National Humanities Alliance Conference, Art Libraries Society of North America (ARLIS/NA) annual conference, the National Gallery of Art, and the BitCurator Forum. Participants in the proposed workshop will gain fluency in foundational web archive concepts as well as an introduction to common research methods.&#10;Learning objectives:&#10;-Learn about CARTA’s web archive primary sources, research use cases and how to support them in a way that promotes computational engagement, scholarship, and research for digital art historians&#10;-Understand web archives as data and the web archival (WARC) file format for preservation and computational access&#10;-Explore representative processes for analyzing computational research datasets with free and open source software&#10;Outline:&#10;0:00: Welcome, introductions, learning objectives&#10;0:10: CARTA overview&#10;0:25: Web archives as data&#10;0:45: ARCH demo&#10;1:05: Palladio demo&#10;1:20: Q&amp;A</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Seymore, Sarah Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Internet Archive</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">sarahbeth@archive.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">sarahbeth@archive.org, karlb@archive.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Seymore, Sarah Elizabeth;&#10;Blumenthal, Karl</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">sarahbeth@archive.org;&#10;karlb@archive.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pacific Standard Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">158</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1260</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ohya, Kazushi</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">There is no reason to deny the value of a workshop proposed by this&#10;paper. The value of this workshop should be defined by a number of&#10;participants. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">There is doubt on &quot;the web has solidified as a&#10;medium for art materials over the last decade&quot;.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1046</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wu, Menghang</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal addresses the scarcity of professional development opportunities for digital humanists and art historians by focusing on computational analysis of web archives. Emphasizing the importance of preserving web-based art, particularly post-pandemic, it showcases the Collaborative ART Archive (CARTA), which has preserved over 900 websites and 16 TB of data. The workshop offers hands-on experience with tools like ARCH and Palladio, building on CARTA’s expertise and previous professional development efforts, and aims to equip participants with foundational web archive concepts and research methods.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">To strengthen the proposal, I suggest enhancing its critical perspective and explicitly addressing the criteria related to any topic among anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectionality, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, and multilingualism. Additionally, the proposal should engage more deeply with relevant scholarship and offer a clearer theoretical, methodological, or pedagogical framework, alongside an explicit articulation of the sociopolitical implications of the work. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1099</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Nguyen, Linh My (Seth)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed session is a demo for the Collaborative ART Archive&#039;s online collections and ways to work with these collections using open-source tools. The proposed session has the potential to open up an extremely fruitful source for humanists and art historians working with Web content.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The methodologies that the workshop introduces can be used for proposals that fit this year&#039;s conference focus, but the proposal itself is only tangentially related to the theme of ACH 2024. 90 minutes is quite long for a virtual workshop; I would like to recommend a length of 75 minutes.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
