    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&quot;Stop Cop City&quot;: Tracking Urban Ecological Discourse Change</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital environmental humanities, civic studies, social movements, natural language processing, word embeddings</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;cultural analytics&#10;natural language processing&#10;semantic analysis&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Environmental, ocean, and waterways studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cultural analytics&#10;natural language processing&#10;semantic analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cultural studies&#10;Environmental, ocean, and waterways studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Over the last several years, the city of Atlanta, Georgia, U.S.A., long known as a “city in a forest,” has been forced into a reckoning with its relationship to its forests. The “Stop Cop City” protest movement arose in 2021 in opposition to a plan to build a police training facility and a movie studio on either side of an endangered creek inside of Atlanta’s largest remaining contiguous forest. Combining racial and environmental justice discourses, the movement has included civic petitions, public comments at city council meetings, and direct action by forest defenders. In the process, it has modified the way Atlanta talks about its natural spaces, from reviving Muscogee/Creek words for local rivers, to promoting a vision of urban ecology that bristles against Atlanta’s quickly growing, pro-Capital reputation. In this paper, I explore the use of word embeddings to capture this discourse change over time and reflect on what other natural language processing methods might be appropriate for future analysis. I rely on three datasets: a) a transcript of seventeen hours of voicemail public comments from September 2021, which I am producing using WhisperAI as part of Atlanta’s AIAI Interdisciplinary working group, b) a transcript of 15 hours of in-person public comments from May and June 2023, which has been produced by the same working group, and c) &lt;em&gt;Atlanta Journal Constitution&lt;/em&gt; newspaper articles from 2021 to 2024, which I access through Proquest’s TDM Studio.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Over the last several years, the city of Atlanta, Georgia, U.S.A., long known as a “city in a forest,” has been forced into a reckoning with its relationship to its forests. The “Stop Cop City” protest movement arose in 2021 in opposition to a plan to build a police training facility and a movie studio on either side of an endangered creek inside of Atlanta’s largest remaining contiguous forest. Combining racial and environmental justice discourses, the movement has included civic petitions, public comments at city council meetings, and direct action by forest defenders. In the process, it has modified the way Atlanta talks about its natural spaces, from reviving Muscogee/Creek words for local rivers, to promoting a vision of urban ecology that bristles against Atlanta’s quickly growing, pro-Capital reputation. In this paper, I explore the use of word embeddings to capture this discourse change over time and reflect on what other natural language processing methods might be appropriate for future analysis. I rely on three datasets: a) a transcript of seventeen hours of voicemail public comments from September 2021, which I am producing using WhisperAI as part of Atlanta’s AIAI Interdisciplinary working group, b) a transcript of 15 hours of in-person public comments from May and June 2023, which has been produced by the same working group, and c) Atlanta Journal Constitution newspaper articles from 2021 to 2024, which I access through Proquest’s TDM Studio.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
