    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">159</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1051</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Galvis, Elliot</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project pairs specific NLP tools and concrete datasets for an impactful, contemporary use case. The clarity of the proposal and its methods is a strength that would make for a strong presentation.&#10;&#10;My only recommendation would be to provide further context for the issues and methods used. E.g., it would be helpful to briefly include parallel environmental discourses prior to the Stop Cop City movement and scholarship on/critiques of the relevant NLP tools used in the author&#039;s analysis.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I strongly recommend accepting this paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1097</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wigard, Justin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission explores appropriateness of NLP for public discourse analysis related to Atlanta, Georgia, in connection with racial justice and environmental justice. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The need to analyze public discourse in Atlanta surrounding the &quot;Stop Cop City&quot; movement is clearly laid out, as is the rationale for using NLP to study larger amounts of data. One strength is the author&#039;s clear explanation of why we should attend to Atlanta as a key sociopolitical space within multiple framework, and the project is timely in its focus on this particular ongoing movement. &#10;&#10;Suggestions for improvement might be to offer brief mention of how this engages with or builds on specific, recent research, critical conversations, or theoretical frameworks in NLP / racial justice / environmental justice. That way, we can see exactly what guides this project, and how. &#10;&#10;Additionally, it might be helpful to see a brief gesture towards the findings. The abstract mentions exploring &quot;the use of word embeddings to capture this discourse change over time and reflect on what other natural language processing methods might be appropriate for future analysis.&quot; How does that discourse change over time? Even a short phrase? What did WhisperAI or TDM Studio reveal about analyzing public discourse in this way? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think the proposal is worth accepting, though perhaps as a poster or lightning talk. The project seems timely and worthwhile. As I noted in my review, it&#039;s just a little difficult to ascertain, from the proposal alone, some of the theoretical/methodological approaches, and whether the author has results. I am sure they do have clear approaches and results, so I  believe they would benefit from having a platform to share research and engage with peers. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1053</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Melkozernova, Arina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal challenges the DH practices by adding racial and Native American perspectives to examine the relationships with landscape (forest) and to capture Urban Ecological Discourse Change over time. The submission can be accomplished in the time allotted (10-15 minutes).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal topic is connected to decolonial studies, Indigenous studies, and culture because it analyzes the way Atlanta talks about its natural spaces, from reviving Muscogee/Creek words for local rivers to promoting a vision of urban ecology that bristles against Atlanta’s quick-growing, pro-Capital reputation. &#10; The project explores the use of word embeddings. It offers context from Cultural, Environmental, ocean, and waterways studies. &#10;The purpose of the proposal is to test methods of cultural analytics, natural language processing, and semantic analysis vs. the use of word embeddings for encoding meaning and relationships between words.&#10;The project will clarify what other natural language processing (NLP) methods might be appropriate for future analysis.&#10;The proposal includes an introduction outlining the purpose and objectives, the background, and expected outcomes. It will benefit from explaining the reasoning for using word embeddings regarding the human understanding of language and NLP problems.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
