    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">BCE-4th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;natural language processing&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Computer science&#10;Philology&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Discussions and publications on Artificial Intelligence within academia have largely focused on its pedagogical impact, the facility it gives students to engage with prohibited methods of completing assignments, and the difficulty it presents to faculty to maintain the integrity of the courses. This paper presents a pedagogical approach that transgresses while respecting disciplinary boundaries and transforms undergraduate education with the help of AI.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The Data-Driven Humanities Research Group is an experiential learning team working with undergraduate students of all disciplines on research topics that are humanities-focused but of interest to other fields. Specifically, students study closely and analyze ancient Greek and Latin texts through the lens of socio-cultural and political issues of historical and contemporary significance. To this end, computer and data science students work on the development of NLP algorithms, classical studies students work with the original texts, social science students shift through the data for their socio-cultural significance, and overall, each discipline has a unique interest that brings them together through the power and affordances of AI.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In the process, computer and data scientists discover the significance of data curation and the development of bias-free models and put themselves to the service of society. In turn, humanities students have the opportunity to confirm the relevance of the humanities and their contribution to the social good while learning about and working with AI. Finally, when it comes to disciplines outside of the humanities, such an expanded study of texts through AI affords them the opportunity to work with authors, works, and data, as well as ask research questions that would have otherwise been inaccessible to them.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In such a collaborative environment, the students transgress and transcend disciplinary boundaries, transform their education from credit requirement checkboxes to meaningful engagements, and become lifelong learners and conscious contributors to the world.&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Discussions and publications on Artificial Intelligence within academia have largely focused on its pedagogical impact, the facility it gives students to engage with prohibited methods of completing assignments, and the difficulty it presents to faculty to maintain the integrity of the courses. This paper presents a pedagogical approach that transgresses while respecting disciplinary boundaries and transforms undergraduate education with the help of AI.&#10;The Data-Driven Humanities Research Group is an experiential learning team working with undergraduate students of all disciplines on research topics that are humanities-focused but of interest to other fields. Specifically, students study closely and analyze ancient Greek and Latin texts through the lens of socio-cultural and political issues of historical and contemporary significance. To this end, computer and data science students work on the development of NLP algorithms, classical studies students work with the original texts, social science students shift through the data for their socio-cultural significance, and overall, each discipline has a unique interest that brings them together through the power and affordances of AI.&#10;In the process, computer and data scientists discover the significance of data curation and the development of bias-free models and put themselves to the service of society. In turn, humanities students have the opportunity to confirm the relevance of the humanities and their contribution to the social good while learning about and working with AI. Finally, when it comes to disciplines outside of the humanities, such an expanded study of texts through AI affords them the opportunity to work with authors, works, and data, as well as ask research questions that would have otherwise been inaccessible to them.&#10;In such a collaborative environment, the students transgress and transcend disciplinary boundaries, transform their education from credit requirement checkboxes to meaningful engagements, and become lifelong learners and conscious contributors to the world.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bozia, Eleni</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Florida</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bozia@ufl.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bozia@ufl.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bozia, Eleni</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bozia@ufl.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EDT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">51.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">60.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">40.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">160</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1240</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wevers, Melvin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">the presentation of a novel pedagogical approach that integrates Artificial Intelligence (AI) into humanities research and education.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal aligns with some aspects of the conference&#039;s focus, particularly in its innovative integration of AI with humanities research and its approach to multilingualism through the study of ancient Greek and Latin texts. To strengthen its relevance, the author could more explicitly articulate how this approach intersects with anti-racist work or decolonial studies, especially in the context of AI development and data analysis. While the abstract presents an innovative pedagogical framework centered on interdisciplinary collaboration and AI-assisted humanities research, it could benefit from more explicit engagement with current scholarship in the field of AI and digital humanities. To enhance the proposal, the author could more clearly state the theoretical underpinnings of this approach, elaborate on the specific methodologies employed in the AI-assisted analysis of ancient texts, and provide concrete examples of how this approach has led to new insights or research outcomes, demonstrating its tangible impact on the field</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract is rather generic and does not provide any engagement with state of the art, theory, or through specific examples. Therefore, it&#039;s difficult to assess its contribution, making lean to reject. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">40</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1286</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sparks, Corey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tackling AI in a productive, experimental way is a great way to address the common faculty fears regarding more instrumentalized ways students are assumed to use it.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract provides a strong articulation of speaking back to anxieties about AI and the classroom. It also argues for this engagement in an interdisciplinary context where students work within and across academic disciplines. It would be useful to see a stronger articulation of the specific affordances AI provides that work. Similarly, a more explicit statement/example of how students would use AI would be welcome.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">60</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1202</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tekgürler, Merve</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission deals with an interdisciplinary research group that combines AI and the Humanities, specifically Classics to gain new insights in classical studies through the use of AI. The author argues that this collaborative research environment is transgressive in pedagogy because it emphasizes how student can use AI instead of conceptualizing AI as a way of cheating.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Thank you for this really interesting project. I certainly agree that it is very important to think of AI beyond a potential cheating tool but I could not see from this submission how this research group is actually transgressive. The field of Classics and several other disciplines in the Humanities and Social Sciences already have research groups like the one that the author describes. While this group might be the first of its kind in Florida (I have no idea about the universities there), it is definitely not a unique formation in the academia in the Global North. I would recommend the author to further look for similar groups, CESTA and LitLab at Stanford, David Bamman&#039;s lab at Berkeley, and a Classics professor Chris Johanson&#039;s lab at UCLA come to my mind but there are certainly more groups than these. Second, the submission does not contain any concrete examples of the research conducted by this group. What Latin and Greek texts are being studied? What are some of the questions that are relevant for this group? What have they identified through the use of digital methods that they have otherwise not been able to? Third, in the third paragraph, the author uses the term bias-free models. How does the author define bias and bias-freeness? This is certainly a very controversial statement to even argue for the existence of bias-free models and the author needs to clearly define what they mean by that and how a model becomes bias-free when CS and Classics undergrads collaborate. In a similar vein, the concluding paragraph mentions that students &quot;transform their education from credit requirement checkboxes to meaningful engagements.&quot; This is again one of those statements that needs more concrete examples. Why was a Classics degree before this group not meaningful? How did it become meaningful with AI? Statements like these are closely related with various discursive and real-life attempts to undermine the value of humanities higher education and reduce it to its practical implications. I would strongly urge the author to revisit relevant literature. Overall, the underlying research group seems like a really cool initiative however the submission makes very big claims without showing any examples or connections to the broader field.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
