    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Citizen Humanities and Digital Public Humanities: A Collaborative Future</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Citizen Humanities, Citizen science, Digital Public Humanities, Digital Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Anthropology&#10;Archaeology&#10;Art history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Anthropology&#10;Archaeology&#10;Art history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In the mid-2000s the term Citizen Humanities began to be used in the academic field which refers to citizen science in the humanities (Google NGram Viewer). Although the term is relatively new, public participation in the humanities has a long tradition, ranging from the creation of dictionaries to the transcription and annotation of historical records, among others. The citizen humanities can be considered a fusion of Digital Humanities and Public Humanities; while Digital Humanities provide data, tools and techniques, the Public Humanities offer a means to engage diverse publics in research activities (Heinisch 2020: 1-2; Bocanegra 2020). The aim of this paper is to analyse public participation and engagement in humanities projects through a study of 473 international initiatives classified according to two models: PPS- Public participation strategies, and PES- Public engagement strategies. Thanks to the implementation of these two models, it has been possible to identify which participation and engagement activities are being carried out in this era of democratisation of research in the humanities, where web-based digital platforms and the crowdsourcing technique play a fundamental role. This study has considered theorisation about participatory processes from other areas, such as educational sciences, pioneers in analysing these participatory processes (Bonney et al., 1999; Simon 2010), but also from the field of humanities in terms of public engagement (Toscano 2021). Thanks to these studies it has been possible to configure the two classification models, giving us a complete picture, from the projects analysed, of how public participation is implemented and managed both within and outside the academic field. The results show an increasing use of Citizen Humanities, which consolidates a collaborative bridge between this participatory methodology and Digital Public Humanities. This study is part of the research project &#039;Crowdsourcing in History&#039; (Cohistoria.es) funded by the Ministry of Science, Innovation and Universities of Spain.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In the mid-2000s the term Citizen Humanities began to be used in the academic field which refers to citizen science in the humanities (Google NGram Viewer). Although the term is relatively new, public participation in the humanities has a long tradition, ranging from the creation of dictionaries to the transcription and annotation of historical records, among others. The citizen humanities can be considered a fusion of Digital Humanities and Public Humanities; while Digital Humanities provide data, tools and techniques, the Public Humanities offer a means to engage diverse publics in research activities (Heinisch 2020: 1-2; Bocanegra 2020). The aim of this paper is to analyse public participation and engagement in humanities projects through a study of 473 international initiatives classified according to two models: PPS- Public participation strategies, and PES- Public engagement strategies. Thanks to the implementation of these two models, it has been possible to identify which participation and engagement activities are being carried out in this era of democratisation of research in the humanities, where web-based digital platforms and the crowdsourcing technique play a fundamental role. This study has considered theorisation about participatory processes from other areas, such as educational sciences, pioneers in analysing these participatory processes (Bonney et al., 1999; Simon 2010), but also from the field of humanities in terms of public engagement (Toscano 2021). Thanks to these studies it has been possible to configure the two classification models, giving us a complete picture, from the projects analysed, of how public participation is implemented and managed both within and outside the academic field. The results show an increasing use of Citizen Humanities, which consolidates a collaborative bridge between this participatory methodology and Digital Public Humanities. This study is part of the research project &#039;Crowdsourcing in History&#039; (Cohistoria.es) funded by the Ministry of Science, Innovation and Universities of Spain.</ss:Data></Cell>
