    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">161</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1114</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">O&#039;Neil, Erica</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The presentation analyzes the field of Citizen Humanities by exploring 473 international public humanities projects with a focus on what participation and engagement look like across the field. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Excellent examination of an emerging field of engagement in the digital humanities. My only concern is that it is difficult to know what is being measured across the 473 studies as &quot;PPS- Public participation strategies and PES- Public engagement strategies&quot; are the listed models under examination but not explicated in terms of both metrics and the affordances of these models. Very pleased that the author is situating this examination within other informal learning models as well, as informal science learning (from the citizen science analog) is such a well-established field comparatively. Confident that based on the citations this will be an excellent addition to the program as it is situated internationally and citizen humanities democratizes knowledge production.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1277</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karlin, Jojo</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission looks at a range of international initiatives they classify as &quot;citizen humanities&quot; to address how public participation and public engagement strategies are working. The author employs methods from educational sciences to observe which participation and engagement activities are being carried out to democratize research in the humanities and how effective those activities are.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This international study will be of great interest to the members of ACH. The list of 473 participatory projects alone would be a great resource. The author&#039;s disciplinary assessment could offer helpful examples of effective participation.&#10;&#10;The submission does assume &quot;citizen humanities&quot; is a widely used term. Rather than circling the question of naming practices and whether and where these names are common, it would be helpful to have concrete examples of the types of participation included in the categories. If the terminology is critical for establishing a theory about the &quot;democratization of research,&quot; it might help to dedicate some portion of the presentation to the place of this type of research in a civic context.&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1075</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Poole, Carson Leigh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission gives insight into the field of &quot;citizen humanities&quot; and the intersection of public-participatory and more traditional humanities research methods. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very thoughtful and articulate paper abstract. It is clear, concise, and relevant. I would like the abstract to address whether this is strictly about Digital Humanities in academia or in the wider discipline; it says &quot;inside and outside&quot; academia but I would like to hear what the paper defines as &quot;outside&quot; academic contexts. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this paper would be a very welcome addition to the conference. It hits several of the points outlined in the scope of this year&#039;s themes. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
