    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sound Studio: Podcasting as a Modern Form of Scholarship, Pedagogy, and Community Building</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">podcasts, podcasting, digital storytelling, pedagogy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;History&#10;Sound Studies&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;History&#10;Sound Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Podcasting, as a kind of digital storytelling, is an emerging and increasingly popular mode of scholarly communication. Scholarly podcasting comes in many forms—from interview-style conversations and panel discussions to more narrative-driven shows—that span teaching, research, and creative activities. As scholars such as Beckstead, Cook, and McGregor urge in their recent book, &lt;em&gt;Podcast or Perish: Peer Review and Knowledge Creation for the 21st Century&lt;/em&gt;, podcasting holds the potential to transform the production and dissemination of knowledge.[1]&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Beginning in 2019, the National Humanities Center and the Digital Humanities Center at San Diego State University Library began hosting twice-annual podcasting institutes built around a team-based learning model. Our earliest institutes were exclusively focused on training graduate students interested in rethinking the shape and trajectory of their scholarship in more public-facing, digitally-inflected, and community-engaged ways. In recent years, we began offering a separate institute for faculty, library workers, academic staff, and independent scholars to pursue similar transformative opportunities with their work. Each virtual weeklong institute is an immersive, hands-on learning opportunity where participants are sorted into interdisciplinary and intra-university cohorts. Following a set of guided conversations and scaffolded workshops, participants collaborate to learn how to storyboard an idea, to create and collect audio content, and to edit narratives into entertaining, powerful podcasts. To date, we have trained more than 600 university faculty, staff, and graduate students.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The curricula combines digital humanities methods with the framework articulated in adrienne maree brown’s &lt;em&gt;Emergent Strategy: Shaping Change, Changing Worlds&lt;/em&gt; (2017). Together, they form an emergent humanities strategy whose goal is to transform scholarly praxis. Using the emergent humanities strategy, we encourage participants to challenge their own assumptions of scholarly practice while centering collaboration, generosity, and care. Each institute concludes with a listening party where we celebrate the individual episodes each learning cohort creates while reflecting on the learning community we created together through trust and process-oriented risk taking.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This alternate format session recreates our listening party by showcasing the success of several of our graduate student participants since completing the institute. The individuals featured in this sound studio experience have explored innovative ways of using podcasting in their scholarly practice that have opened new possibilities for careers in the humanities.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;We invite you to attend our sound studio to experience clips and trailers of podcast episodes developed by institute graduates who either act as professional podcasters, transmit their scholarship through podcasts, or use podcasts as pedagogy. We will begin our presentation by inviting you into the studio to ensure that you are well acquainted with the audio form. After listening to sound recordings by our group of presenters, we will host a discussion based on the following topics: podcasting as scholarship, podcasting and pedagogy, and a values-based podcasting curriculum. Threaded throughout these conversations, we will reflect on the ways in which we use podcasting in our community building.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;---&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;[1] Lori Beckstead, Ian M. Cook, and Hannah McGregor, &lt;em&gt;Podcast or Perish: Peer Review and Knowledge Creation for the 21st Century&lt;/em&gt;. Bloomsbury, 2024. See also the interactive “164 Resources on the Theory and Practice of the Podcasting Space” for a broad range of recent scholarship on podcasting: https://list.ly/preview/8zfe#plugin.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Podcasting, as a kind of digital storytelling, is an emerging and increasingly popular mode of scholarly communication. Scholarly podcasting comes in many forms—from interview-style conversations and panel discussions to more narrative-driven shows—that span teaching, research, and creative activities. As scholars such as Beckstead, Cook, and McGregor urge in their recent book, Podcast or Perish: Peer Review and Knowledge Creation for the 21st Century, podcasting holds the potential to transform the production and dissemination of knowledge.[1]&#10;Beginning in 2019, the National Humanities Center and the Digital Humanities Center at San Diego State University Library began hosting twice-annual podcasting institutes built around a team-based learning model. Our earliest institutes were exclusively focused on training graduate students interested in rethinking the shape and trajectory of their scholarship in more public-facing, digitally-inflected, and community-engaged ways. In recent years, we began offering a separate institute for faculty, library workers, academic staff, and independent scholars to pursue similar transformative opportunities with their work. Each virtual weeklong institute is an immersive, hands-on learning opportunity where participants are sorted into interdisciplinary and intra-university cohorts. Following a set of guided conversations and scaffolded workshops, participants collaborate to learn how to storyboard an idea, to create and collect audio content, and to edit narratives into entertaining, powerful podcasts. To date, we have trained more than 600 university faculty, staff, and graduate students.&#10;The curricula combines digital humanities methods with the framework articulated in adrienne maree brown’s Emergent Strategy: Shaping Change, Changing Worlds (2017). Together, they form an emergent humanities strategy whose goal is to transform scholarly praxis. Using the emergent humanities strategy, we encourage participants to challenge their own assumptions of scholarly practice while centering collaboration, generosity, and care. Each institute concludes with a listening party where we celebrate the individual episodes each learning cohort creates while reflecting on the learning community we created together through trust and process-oriented risk taking.&#10;This alternate format session recreates our listening party by showcasing the success of several of our graduate student participants since completing the institute. The individuals featured in this sound studio experience have explored innovative ways of using podcasting in their scholarly practice that have opened new possibilities for careers in the humanities.&#10;We invite you to attend our sound studio to experience clips and trailers of podcast episodes developed by institute graduates who either act as professional podcasters, transmit their scholarship through podcasts, or use podcasts as pedagogy. We will begin our presentation by inviting you into the studio to ensure that you are well acquainted with the audio form. After listening to sound recordings by our group of presenters, we will host a discussion based on the following topics: podcasting as scholarship, podcasting and pedagogy, and a values-based podcasting curriculum. Threaded throughout these conversations, we will reflect on the ways in which we use podcasting in our community building.&#10;---&#10;[1] Lori Beckstead, Ian M. Cook, and Hannah McGregor, Podcast or Perish: Peer Review and Knowledge Creation for the 21st Century. Bloomsbury, 2024. See also the interactive “164 Resources on the Theory and Practice of the Podcasting Space” for a broad range of recent scholarship on podcasting: https://list.ly/preview/8zfe#plugin.</ss:Data></Cell>
