    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Queer Encodings: An NLP Approach to Labeling of Queer Texts from American Book Challenges</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&quot;Queer studies&quot;, &quot;Book bans&quot;, &quot;Library and Information Science&quot;, &quot;Topic Models&quot;, &quot;Cultural Analytics&quot;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Queer Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;cultural analytics&#10;natural language processing&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Literary studies&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cultural analytics&#10;natural language processing&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Queer Studies&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Literary studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Attempts to ban books through complaints of “Sexually Explicit” content, “Body Description or Function”, or just “Homosexuality” have escalated dramatically in the United States in recent years. In response, many researchers and library organizations tag texts as LGBTQIA+ to illustrate the relationship between anti-trans panic and backlash to queer visibility with these book bans. But what makes a text queer? And how do both book banners and defenders constitute new definitions of queerness through their respective projects? Deploying a comparative approach of close reading and two &quot;distant&quot; reading methods represented by challenger complaints and topic models, this paper explores these constructions of queer(ness in) literature in the hopes of critically assessing how classification protects or endangers queer people and cultures.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;My project draws from computational frameworks–and critiques–from queer and feminist literary scholars, as well as critical catalogers. Methods include analysis of metadata from the American Library Association, fine-tuning large-language models to experiment with text-completion, and building topic models of challenged titles. Ultimately, I aim to excavate and challenge computationally-derived visions of what “queerness” means and what makes a “queer text” in the eyes of various projects and classifying strategies.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Attempts to ban books through complaints of “Sexually Explicit” content, “Body Description or Function”, or just “Homosexuality” have escalated dramatically in the United States in recent years. In response, many researchers and library organizations tag texts as LGBTQIA+ to illustrate the relationship between anti-trans panic and backlash to queer visibility with these book bans. But what makes a text queer? And how do both book banners and defenders constitute new definitions of queerness through their respective projects? Deploying a comparative approach of close reading and two &quot;distant&quot; reading methods represented by challenger complaints and topic models, this paper explores these constructions of queer(ness in) literature in the hopes of critically assessing how classification protects or endangers queer people and cultures.&#10;My project draws from computational frameworks–and critiques–from queer and feminist literary scholars, as well as critical catalogers. Methods include analysis of metadata from the American Library Association, fine-tuning large-language models to experiment with text-completion, and building topic models of challenged titles. Ultimately, I aim to excavate and challenge computationally-derived visions of what “queerness” means and what makes a “queer text” in the eyes of various projects and classifying strategies.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Galvis, Elliot</ss:Data></Cell>
