    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">elliotgalvis@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">elliotgalvis@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Galvis, Elliot</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">elliotgalvis@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">83.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">167</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1129</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shaarawi, Jihan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper employs an intersectional approach between digital humanities, queer studies, and library sciences in order to provide new insights into how queerness is constructed and contested in contemporary cultural battles over literature. This paper is advocating for more nuanced and protective classification strategies.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract is well-organized and clearly articulates the content of your paper. You effectively communicate the importance and novelty of your research as well as provide a the necessary cultural context to highlight the importance of your research.  &#10;Including a few key references will provide a clearer context on what the exact frameworks you&#039;re working with. You mention computational frameworks, what are the specific frameworks? How do they engage with your research? Have they been used in similar research before? Providing examples of a text analyzed or a specific instance of a book ban could help illustrate your points in a more powerful way. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract is relevant to the topic of the conference. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1309</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ryan C Dubnicek, Ryan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper seeks to understand the textual characteristics of queerness in literature through a combined approach of close (interpretation and critical theory) and distant (LLM-powered text masking, metadata analysis, and topic modeling) reading techniques, along with the relationship between a text and its queer traits and its classification in libraries. These questions are both perfect for a close and distant combined approach, and may help uncover ignored or unobserved traits of queer texts at a time when such art is being marginalized.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A bit about how this work and methodologies might benefit other types or classes of literature would be very welcome, and is the only limiting factor in my review (though I consider it a small one).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1248</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Knox, John Thomas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution uses close reading and computational methods to describe and analyze how queerness is constituted through the actions of individuals seeking to ban or defend &quot;queer&quot; books. The contribution also critiques the ways in which computational methods are used to define/classify &quot;queerness&quot; or &quot;queer texts.&quot;  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a highly relevant proposal and one that engages with a topic that is timely and of likely interest to conference participants. I think the combination of computational and close reading techniques is a strength. I am excited to learn more about how LLMs were utilized in this project. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Accept - Paper</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell ss:StyleID="s22"><Data ss:Type="DateTime">2024-09-07T17:13:59.000</Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Elliot Galvis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell ss:StyleID="s22"><Data ss:Type="DateTime">2024-06-03T23:42:08.000</Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">97</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">D3-S5-B</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">#19B: Digital Resistance and Social Justice (Papers)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell ss:StyleID="s22"><Data ss:Type="DateTime">2024-11-08T15:00:00.000</Data></Cell>
    <Cell ss:StyleID="s22"><Data ss:Type="DateTime">2024-11-08T16:15:00.000</Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Jucan, Ioana Bogdana (Emerson College)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">O&#039;Neil, Erica (Arizona State University)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper draws from my MA thesis in Digital Studies of Text and Culture at the University of Chicago examining computationally derived constructions of queerness as defined in and in response to book challenges in the US. In my paper, I hope to engage with the precarities and benefits for queer people and concepts of queerness in the information sciences and library research.&#10;&#10;This project relies on datasets from the American Library Association describing nearly 11,000 individual titles challenged in public and school libraries from 2010-2023. In conducting my analysis, I examine a corpora of 200 digital texts in the University of Chicago’s Textual Optics Lab and the University of Kansas’ History of Black Writing representing a subset of the ALA titles challenged more than once during the covered period. The texts found in the History of Black Writing corpus represent a majority of the queer texts included in my corpora, particularly those published after 2000. Given the critiques and contributions of digital humanities and computational text analysis leveled by BIPOC researchers, my paper will also pay attention to the forces of anti-Black racism at the heart of many of these challenges. I will also try to briefly acknowledge the differences in encodings of race and queerness and point to work by Jean Richard So and Safiya Noble. Most immediately, my paper will engage with the methodology and proposals of Matthew Warner’s 2023 article “A Queer Way of Counting: Bibliography and Computational Approaches to the Queer Novel” given our overlapping use of UChicago’s Textual Optics Lab’s corpus and Warner’s engagement with the strengths and pitfalls of cultural analytics and computational approaches for queer literary studies.</ss:Data></Cell>
