    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Reinventing the Scholarly Monograph in the Digital Age</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">publishing, notebook</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;15th-17th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;systems and information architecture and usability&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">15th-17th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;systems and information architecture and usability</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In 2022, De Gruyter Verlag and the Center for Contemporary and Digital History (C2DH) of the University of Luxembourg formed a partnership to develop a new digitally-born scholarly monograph series. The goal of the new series is to offer a sustainable publishing platform to scholars engaging with digitally born materials, such as webcontent, datasets, and interactive visualizations. My presentation will demonstrate the first prototype of our publishing platform; furthermore, it will discuss the challenges and open questions of the development process by situating them in contemporary scholarly discourse on the future of digital publishing (Dodds, 2019; ; Forgues &amp; Liarte, 2016). First, I will discuss the base technology, customized JupytherBook (Chen &amp; Asta, 2022), underlying the digital platform that C2DH and De Gruyter Verlag jointly develop. Second, I will address the embedding of research code in a digital monograph; specifically, I will focus on problems related to security and scalability in the context of digital publishing (Mulvany, 2024). Finally, I will focus on the challenges that the direct inclusion of large datasets into a scholarly monograph involves; here my focus will be on copyright management and accuracy; I will for instance address the question of how an editor can “proofread” a dataset and verify its academic quality (Pierce et al., 2019). As a whole, throughout the presentation the audience will hear about those new opportunities that the digital publication process opens.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In 2022, De Gruyter Verlag and the Center for Contemporary and Digital History (C2DH) of the University of Luxembourg formed a partnership to develop a new digitally-born scholarly monograph series. The goal of the new series is to offer a sustainable publishing platform to scholars engaging with digitally born materials, such as webcontent, datasets, and interactive visualizations. My presentation will demonstrate the first prototype of our publishing platform; furthermore, it will discuss the challenges and open questions of the development process by situating them in contemporary scholarly discourse on the future of digital publishing (Dodds, 2019; ; Forgues &amp; Liarte, 2016). First, I will discuss the base technology, customized JupytherBook (Chen &amp; Asta, 2022), underlying the digital platform that C2DH and De Gruyter Verlag jointly develop. Second, I will address the embedding of research code in a digital monograph; specifically, I will focus on problems related to security and scalability in the context of digital publishing (Mulvany, 2024). Finally, I will focus on the challenges that the direct inclusion of large datasets into a scholarly monograph involves; here my focus will be on copyright management and accuracy; I will for instance address the question of how an editor can “proofread” a dataset and verify its academic quality (Pierce et al., 2019). As a whole, throughout the presentation the audience will hear about those new opportunities that the digital publication process opens.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Toth, Gabor Mihaly</ss:Data></Cell>
