    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">gabor.toth@maximilianeum.de</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">gabor.toth@maximilianeum.de</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Toth, Gabor Mihaly</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">gabor.toth@maximilianeum.de</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Standard Western European</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">168</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1093</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dwyer, Kaylen</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal addresses challenges related to sustainable and scalable scholarly publishing of digitally born materials with a specific focus on large datasets, interactive visualizations, and managing the copyright implications bound up in that process, additionally addressing issues in the editorial process and verifying data as readers. The work is relevant to contemporary issues in the digital humanities and fits into the conference broadly, even if it is not part of the conference focus. Issues related to sustainability and scalability further the aims of feminist project management even if that is not directly touched on. Such new and accessible approaches to publishing digital scholarly monographs are a necessary and significant contribution to the field of DH.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal at first seems to focus on the publishing platform’s technical development. The shift to copyright management at the very end seems a like a major shift in topic, though both these topics are significant to the project and your contribution. How the presentation will balance the first and second parts (platform development/sustainability and copyright/editorial process) could possibly be clarified a little.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I could not rate highly since it is not part of the conference focus, but still feel it is relevant and would be valuable to have.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1271</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Coble, Zach</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal describes a new publishing platform, with an emphasis on publishing data, code, and visualization.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal discusses the development of a useful and valuable book series and publishing platform. The platform&#039;s ability to display code, data, and visualizations will certainly be of interest to conference participants, as they respond to growing needs for these features in our publishing environments. The author mentions the platform will be sustainable, and it would be helpful to provide additional evidence in support of this. Many publishing experiments have focused on rendering the media du jour (video, timelines, etc), but often become obsolete as technology changes. As a partnership with an established publishing house, what measures are in place to ensure these books will still be accessible in 5 years?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">It fits the conference description of Individual Papers, and could also work as a lightning talk. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1265</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Arbuckle, Alyssa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract proposes a talk on an emerging collaborative publishing initiative between De Gruyter Verlag and the Center for Contemporary and Digital History. The author outlines the initiative, as well as the topics to be discussed: challenges of digital publishing, technology used, specificities of digital monographs, security, scalability, copyright, and quality control. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed paper will be of interest to ACH attendees who are engaged with digital publishing, which is likely to be just about everyone (in one way or another). The presentation promises to raise questions that are timely and pertinent for the consideration of the communication of digital humanities work. This is especially valuable as the discipline has, as of yet, not found a way to &quot;break free&quot; from the monograph and is still grappling with how to reconcile the expectation for a longform textual publication with the realities of DH work. Undoubtedly, the author will be asked about open access and should be prepared to discuss this project within those terms. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
