    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Dark Lady in the Machine: The Shakespearean Sonnet, Racial Bias, and AI</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shakespearean sonnets, racial bias, training data, generative AI, formalism</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;15th-17th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;Literary studies&#10;Philology&#10;Science, Technology, and Society&#10;Western/Southern European Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">15th-17th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Literary studies&#10;Philology&#10;Science, Technology, and Society&#10;Western/Southern European Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This paper brings together Shakespeare’s sonnets, bias in training data, and AI for formalist inquiry. Sonnets have had a place in AI history since Alan Turing’s seminal essay “Computing Machinery and Intelligence,” which privileges the Shakespearean sonnet as one standard for measuring intelligent machine behavior. Many AI models are now trained to generate Shakespearean sonnets, including Lau et al.’s 2018 Deep-speare, OpenAI’s 2022 ChatGPT, and Agnew et al.’s 2023 model. Racial bias in training datasets continues to be an urgent concern, as Google Gemini’s recent, failed attempts at data diversity remind us once again. Seemingly distant from these developments, race and racialization in English sonnet sequences have been subjects of critical debate since the 1990s, notably manifested in the work of Margreta de Grazia and Kim Hall. Previous scholarship only partially intersects Shakespearean sonnets, training bias, and AI. However, all three are necessary for whetting our theories about the Shakespearean sonnet within computational formalism(s), which tend(s) to focus less on poetic forms. My case study models a way of using text-to-image models like Stable Diffusion (SD) to transform and analyze Sonnets 127-154 (i.e., the “Dark Lady sonnets”). The paper’s emphasis on bias in training datasets and SD’s hallucinations in representing the “Dark Lady” is guided by the principle that AI should be regarded as a means to &lt;em&gt;more&lt;/em&gt; questions, not answers. My deliberately oblique approach highlights how Shakespeare’s manipulation of the sonnet’s formal mechanics and his participation in early modern racial matrices are inextricable procedures.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper brings together Shakespeare’s sonnets, bias in training data, and AI for formalist inquiry. Sonnets have had a place in AI history since Alan Turing’s seminal essay “Computing Machinery and Intelligence,” which privileges the Shakespearean sonnet as one standard for measuring intelligent machine behavior. Many AI models are now trained to generate Shakespearean sonnets, including Lau et al.’s 2018 Deep-speare, OpenAI’s 2022 ChatGPT, and Agnew et al.’s 2023 model. Racial bias in training datasets continues to be an urgent concern, as Google Gemini’s recent, failed attempts at data diversity remind us once again. Seemingly distant from these developments, race and racialization in English sonnet sequences have been subjects of critical debate since the 1990s, notably manifested in the work of Margreta de Grazia and Kim Hall. Previous scholarship only partially intersects Shakespearean sonnets, training bias, and AI. However, all three are necessary for whetting our theories about the Shakespearean sonnet within computational formalism(s), which tend(s) to focus less on poetic forms. My case study models a way of using text-to-image models like Stable Diffusion (SD) to transform and analyze Sonnets 127-154 (i.e., the “Dark Lady sonnets”). The paper’s emphasis on bias in training datasets and SD’s hallucinations in representing the “Dark Lady” is guided by the principle that AI should be regarded as a means to more questions, not answers. My deliberately oblique approach highlights how Shakespeare’s manipulation of the sonnet’s formal mechanics and his participation in early modern racial matrices are inextricable procedures.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Oh, Unjoo Margaret</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Stanford University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ujoh@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ujoh@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Oh, Unjoo Margaret</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ujoh@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pacific Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">169</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1286</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sparks, Corey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract smartly connects AI&#039;s longstanding Shakespeare foundations with issues of training models&#039; racial biases as well as long histories of race and racism registered through the most canonical of poetic forms written by the most canonical of Western poets. Furthermore, it does so through experimentation, seeking to open up questions about and within these vast topics.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper engages in DH &quot;Shakespeare problem,&quot; as Laura Estill calls it - a problem that &quot;both stems from and reifies Shakespeare’s centrality to the canon of English literature.&quot; The key way that this paper takes a critical lens is through considering race and racism, a now-established lens in Shakespeare studies. And more specifically, the paper experiments with remediation via AI in order to register issues of race and racism in AI training models and in Shakespeare&#039;s sonnets. The final sentence of the abstract could be honed or clarified just a bit more since it&#039;s not clear to what extent the products of the AI remediation really just tell us about stable diffusion&#039;s training models and how those products tell us about the form of the sonnet.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1242</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Vasyutinsky Shapira, Daria</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author studies the application of AI to Shakespeare’s sonnets, namely, using text-to-image models like Stable Diffusion (SD) to transform and analyze Sonnets 127-154 (i.e., the “Dark Lady sonnets”).  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dear author, I read your abstract with pleasure. The ideas you express are innovative and promising. I am looking forward to hearing your presentation. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1092</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Froehlich, Heather</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shakespeare&#039;s writing, especially his sonnets are an established way to measure AI success. This paper will explore a text-to-image generation of the Dark Lady sonnets as 1) a means to assess AI&#039;s ability to render poetic language and 2) to explore how form affects racial realizations in generative formats.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper is extremely well grounded - I really appreciated the nod to scholarship in the primary domains of generative artificial intelligence models and its position of providing a means of testing means of established criticisms of racial issues in the Renaissance. (I am very happy to see Margreta de Grazia and Kim Hall cited directly here.) The discussion of how AI performs on the Dark Lady sonnets is a bit shrouded in secrecy but this feels appropriate given their reception as there are many conflicting theories around them. And Shakespearean sonnets as a form are relatively programmatic, given their structure (feet/rhymes/structure) that are especially predictable.  So this feels like a particularly interesting angle to take for AI generation, especially as drivers of description prompt engineering.&#10;&#10;The author proposes an exploration of computational formalisms, which are presumably to be taken as different than literary/stylistic formalism. While I know 250 words is not a whole ton of space and the majority of the word count is (understandably) preoccupied with setting the stage for the primary research question, I would have loved to see a detail describing computational vs stylistic form here, but I don&#039;t consider that a make or break here. This feels like an exciting moment for making the case of how (and when) AI is not matching potential expectations and what that means for scholars of race in both the past and the present. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
