    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ioana_jucan@emerson.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ioana.b.jucan@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ioana_jucan@emerson.edu, yz5528@nyu.edu, anelson@nyu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Jucan, Ioana Bogdana</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ioana_jucan@emerson.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">US/Eastern Standard Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">58.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">170</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1083</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zou, Zhihui</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission is an interactive chat program focusing on the idea of commerce and monetary trade in human social psychology. The program&#039;s central theme urges users to connect technological innovations with environmental impacts and implications.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Connecting environmental factors and technological innovations is the main strength of this project. As users, we often ignore or simply are not aware of the resources needed to power our machines. What is also outstanding is, if I&#039;m interpreting correctly, how a scale is built into the machine so that the machine could decide on a scale the quality of the answer instead of a boolean yes/no.&#10;&#10;If the medium of interaction is further specified, that would be very helpful. The submission mentions theater performances, but it also mentions a conversation. So is the program a chat bot (input: words, output: words)? Or does it take another type of input or generates another type of output.&#10;&#10;It would be nice if the details of building the four personas are provided. When building the data bases, do the four personas interact with each other (as in, are their data bases completely independent of each other or are there cross-overs)? Are the personas designed around quantitative data around environmental studies or qualitative information?&#10;&#10;In addition, does the team have a system to record the machine&#039;s results and interpret the results? For example, recording how the machine responded when given X amount of water, and how it differs when given Y amount.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">For an art installation submission, the proposal is slightly vague in its methodologies and medium of presentation. However, the concept is promising.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1255</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rudinsky, Joyce</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">An installation or performance that uses chatbots </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The chatbot weaving cliches, occasional nonsense and cryptic insights is interesting, but it is not clear how the project works as either an installation or performance. I would like to hear more about the concept such as how do the questions (i.e. pay for water) and different personalities support the critique of hidden biases and shadowed impulses. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Although this uses timely issues, the abstract doesn&#039;t say how the project engages with the ideas other than a quirky chatbot.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">58</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1147</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Berger, Claudia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a really interesting format/project. I like that is makes the price of using the oracle explicit, and I am curious if there is either a way for participants to log if they either do not want/or cannot pay the price? Some sort of refusal system or something. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
