    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cut-Copy-Paste Constructionism: Teaching Encoding and Text Mining with Erasure</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">encoding, text-mining, erasure, creative criticism, constructivist pedagogy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Literary studies&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Literary studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;A long-standing divide in computational text analysis is between encoding and text-mining.&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; Encoding adds information to text that remains in-context; text-mining’s power comes from abstracting away from context. The ability to decide between these two approaches, or to make decisions about combining them, is a foundational learning outcome in computational text analysis coursework. They are also interlinked concepts essential to creative humanist inquiry writ large, notably utilized in poetry by M. NourbeSe Philip (&lt;em&gt;Zong!&lt;/em&gt;) and Solmaz Sharif (&lt;em&gt;Look&lt;/em&gt;). Building on the work of Christopher Ohge and Charlotte Tupman, we argue that situating these practices only within the context of the ‘digital’ humanities forecloses on their wider application.&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;“Cut-Copy-Paste Constructionism” reports on our experiment in DH erasure-poetry pedagogy. Using art supplies, students ‘erased’ words as a means of experimenting with and visualizing encoding and text-mining processes, making high-conceptual decisions around encoding and text-mining with low technical barriers to entry. We propose that using physical media (including variation in marker and paint opacity, and the ability to cut, fold, and move strips of paper) affords a non-binary, constructionist approach to encoding and text-mining that encourages experimental play and creative criticism. Embodying and enacting encoding and text-mining processes allows for what Danny Snelson calls a “poetics of the search,” a playful, performance-based approach to digital humanities inquiries, and provides pathways into both the digital and the humanities.&lt;sup&gt;3&lt;/sup&gt;  &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;ol&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Bauman, Syd, David Hoover, Karina van Dalen-Osam, and Wendell Piez. 2012. “Text Analysis Meets Text Encoding.” In &lt;em&gt;Digital Humanities 2012 Conference Abstracts&lt;/em&gt;. University of Hamburg: University of Hamburg Press.&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Ohge, Christopher, and Charlotte Tupman. 2020. “Encoding and Analysis, and Encoding As Analysis, in Textual Editing.” In &lt;em&gt;Routledge International Handbook of Research Methods in Digital Humanities&lt;/em&gt;, 1st ed. Routledge.&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Snelson, Daniel Scott. &quot;Contingent Reading: A Poetics of the Search.&quot; &lt;em&gt;ASAP/Journal &lt;/em&gt;7, no. 2 (2022): 385-407.&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;/ol&gt;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A long-standing divide in computational text analysis is between encoding and text-mining.1 Encoding adds information to text that remains in-context; text-mining’s power comes from abstracting away from context. The ability to decide between these two approaches, or to make decisions about combining them, is a foundational learning outcome in computational text analysis coursework. They are also interlinked concepts essential to creative humanist inquiry writ large, notably utilized in poetry by M. NourbeSe Philip (Zong!) and Solmaz Sharif (Look). Building on the work of Christopher Ohge and Charlotte Tupman, we argue that situating these practices only within the context of the ‘digital’ humanities forecloses on their wider application.2&#10;“Cut-Copy-Paste Constructionism” reports on our experiment in DH erasure-poetry pedagogy. Using art supplies, students ‘erased’ words as a means of experimenting with and visualizing encoding and text-mining processes, making high-conceptual decisions around encoding and text-mining with low technical barriers to entry. We propose that using physical media (including variation in marker and paint opacity, and the ability to cut, fold, and move strips of paper) affords a non-binary, constructionist approach to encoding and text-mining that encourages experimental play and creative criticism. Embodying and enacting encoding and text-mining processes allows for what Danny Snelson calls a “poetics of the search,” a playful, performance-based approach to digital humanities inquiries, and provides pathways into both the digital and the humanities.3  &#10;Bauman, Syd, David Hoover, Karina van Dalen-Osam, and Wendell Piez. 2012. “Text Analysis Meets Text Encoding.” In Digital Humanities 2012 Conference Abstracts. University of Hamburg: University of Hamburg Press.&#10;Ohge, Christopher, and Charlotte Tupman. 2020. “Encoding and Analysis, and Encoding As Analysis, in Textual Editing.” In Routledge International Handbook of Research Methods in Digital Humanities, 1st ed. Routledge.&#10;Snelson, Daniel Scott. &quot;Contingent Reading: A Poetics of the Search.&quot; ASAP/Journal 7, no. 2 (2022): 385-407.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Nomura, Nichole Misako</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nnomura@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nnomura@stanford.edu, messarra@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Nomura, Nichole Misako;&#10;Messarra, Luca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nnomura@stanford.edu;&#10;messarra@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">PST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">79.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">90.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">171</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1066</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Walsh, Brandon</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper describes using physical media to encourage students to physically modify poetry and, in so doing, explore high-level concepts around text mining and encoding</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This looks really interesting! I absolutely love the idea, and I think it&#039;s a great way of thinking through these concepts with students. A couple thoughts - &#10;&#10;The connections to text mining and encoding were not immediately clear from the abstract, but you&#039;re obviously working with a word limit. So in the presentation itself I might just make it clear what the specific connections to text mining and encoding the students draw from the activity. It&#039;s not hard for me to imagine, but I found myself doing a bit more connecting the dots on my own than you might want. &#10;&#10;The connection to the conference goals of &quot;anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, and/or multilingualism&quot; are perhaps a bit tenuous at present, but I think there are ways for you to get there! You might think about how the engagement with multimedia and physical crafting helps to encourage different kinds of learners, different educational backgrounds, different teaching contexts, under-resourced communities, and the like. I think you could meaningfully draw out those connections without losing the core of the work. &#10;&#10;I hope to see you at the conference! </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1245</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sempere, Anindita Basu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal takes a typical DH text analysis framework and offers a way for students to engage these ideas through physical and playful means.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The description of DH text analysis methodology is succinctly and well-framed. The pedagogical approach of using physical materials is also compelling. It would be helpful to know more about how students are using erasure -- are they composing erasure poems (which is often a deeply political act), or are they using erasure in a different way? What kinds of questions are the students engaging through this practice? The political aspects of erasure poetry may be a way to engage the conference theme more directly.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1226</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Spiro, Lisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper presents a playful method of exploring the dynamics of text encoding and mining via physical media.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper introduces an inventive method for teaching text encoding and mining--using physical media to obscure words. It provides a clear framework for its work, well-grounded in the literature. The paper could be even stronger if it highlighted what is revealed through these methods and what impact they have had in the classroom. Also, I&#039;m a bit confused how erasure of text can be considered an analogue version of text encoding, which (as the abstract claims) is typically additive.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">6</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Accept as Poster</ss:Data></Cell>
