    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rhuskey@ou.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rhuskey@ou.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Huskey, Rebecca K.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rhuskey@ou.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Central standard time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">31.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">44.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">24.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">172</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1083</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zou, Zhihui</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission wishes to discuss the harmful effects of applying AI.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission discusses the very relevant topic of the negative effects of AI and engages with related scholarship. However, for the format of Lightning Talk, the submission is not specific enough on what type of negative effect will be discussed. Negative effects of technology comes in many different forms and shapes, as the submission mentions, but each form or shape needs its own scrutiny. Combining all negative effects of technology and AI into a Lightning Talk might not provide the enough space and time to fully engage with this topic.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission is way too broad for a Lightning Talk and probably too broad for an Individual Paper, even.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">26</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1269</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bell, Eamonn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution seems to be a call for the importance of expertise in the history of technology and applied morals in the future of computation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The talk has evident relevance to the focal conference themes, though these are somewhat latent in the proposal, despite its clear motivation by an interest in justice in the machine age. The engagement with the cited literature is somewhat superficial, as it is not clear in the proposal precisely what is adopted from this prior work (though it is clearly relevant). The proposal sets out some relevant general context and framing from the outset; the cases mentioned appear relevant but their relation to recent developments in AI is left for the reader to fill in themselves and/or are not clearly linked to outcomes of the proposed work. The proposal reaches the most clear statement of its thesis in the final sentence, but itself is somewhat generic (i.e. a straightforward assertion of the value of expertise) and is therefore somewhat limited as a whole. The strengths of this proposal lie in the evident importance of its topic to the author; its weaker points include its dependence on generalities. This proposal should be developed further so that its case the case for &quot;why this, why now&quot; is more explicit, and better grounded in existing works around interdisciplinary collaboration within the conference field of DH.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">44</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1114</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">O&#039;Neil, Erica</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author proposes to talk about why AI needs ethicists and humanists, presumably given its potential impact on humanity.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">If accepted for a lightning talk, the proposal would be strengthened by engaging with some background framing for the subject of investigation: 1. What is AI? It is often used as a cultural/marketing catch-all term (like it is in this proposal), rather than defining the impact or difference between personalized algorithmic recommendation systems or large language models integration or deep learning, etc. There are so many definitions of AI and ways that tools are developed and deployed, and the proposal would benefit from honing in on what the subject of investigation is. 2. Ethicists and humanists are already involved in discussions of AI, across all life stages--design, development, and deployment. An entire field of critical technology studies exists across media studies and science and technology studies programs--so the suggestion that ethicists and humanists need to be involved in some stage of the technological development lifecycle (it&#039;s unclear from the proposal) is odd, as they already are integral to not only the critique of technology, but the more thoughtful engagement with communities who will be impacted, policy recommendations across topical areas, and in the direct development of these tools. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I would not accept. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">24</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
