    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&quot;Jane Austen&#039;s Desk,&quot; An NEH Digital Project for the Public</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Jane Austen, Public Humanities, Digital Archives, Mansfield Park</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;18th Century&#10;19th Century&#10;project design, organization, and management&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;Literary studies&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Transatlantic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">18th Century&#10;19th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">project design, organization, and management&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Book and Print history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;Literary studies&#10;Transatlantic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;“Jane Austen&#039;s Desk&quot; (or &quot;JAD&quot;) is an NEH Digital Project for the Public created by the non-profit organization, the Jane Austen Collaborative. It is a public humanities project that simulates an imaginative version of Austen’s writing space as a hub for hosting historical, literary, and material content in an interactive manner. JAD-beta depicts March 30th, 1813, when Austen had just published &lt;em&gt;Pride and Prejudice&lt;/em&gt; and was composing &lt;em&gt;Mansfield Park&lt;/em&gt;. This precise historical moment invites engagement with issues surrounding female authorship and mobility and the transatlantic slave trade; our thematic focus emphasizes her global connections and challenges the stereotype of Austen as a primarily domestic, feminine writer. Besides establishing a thematic foundation for our intervention in Austen studies, the JAD prototype deploys a variety of DH content and features, including: digital editions of &lt;em&gt;Pride and Prejudice&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;Mansfield Park&lt;/em&gt;; editions of five texts Austen alludes to in her letters from early 1813; digitized copies of “circulating library” catalogs to which Austen had access; newspaper articles that appeared during that time; an interactive family tree; an interactive illustrated globe depicting Austen’s family members&#039; travels; and story-maps tracking her brothers on two naval adventures. All this is housed in Omeka and presented in a custom-built site featuring hand-drawn illustrations, animations, and multimedia. As co-creator, I would relish the opportunity to share JAD in a “poster,” lightning talk, or installation at ACH 2024. I plan to provide a walkthrough and interactive opportunities for attendees, with the aim of testing the feasibility and appeal of our features and receiving general feedback.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">“Jane Austen&#039;s Desk&quot; (or &quot;JAD&quot;) is an NEH Digital Project for the Public created by the non-profit organization, the Jane Austen Collaborative. It is a public humanities project that simulates an imaginative version of Austen’s writing space as a hub for hosting historical, literary, and material content in an interactive manner. JAD-beta depicts March 30th, 1813, when Austen had just published Pride and Prejudice and was composing Mansfield Park. This precise historical moment invites engagement with issues surrounding female authorship and mobility and the transatlantic slave trade; our thematic focus emphasizes her global connections and challenges the stereotype of Austen as a primarily domestic, feminine writer. Besides establishing a thematic foundation for our intervention in Austen studies, the JAD prototype deploys a variety of DH content and features, including: digital editions of Pride and Prejudice and Mansfield Park; editions of five texts Austen alludes to in her letters from early 1813; digitized copies of “circulating library” catalogs to which Austen had access; newspaper articles that appeared during that time; an interactive family tree; an interactive illustrated globe depicting Austen’s family members&#039; travels; and story-maps tracking her brothers on two naval adventures. All this is housed in Omeka and presented in a custom-built site featuring hand-drawn illustrations, animations, and multimedia. As co-creator, I would relish the opportunity to share JAD in a “poster,” lightning talk, or installation at ACH 2024. I plan to provide a walkthrough and interactive opportunities for attendees, with the aim of testing the feasibility and appeal of our features and receiving general feedback.</ss:Data></Cell>
