    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">173</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1053</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Melkozernova, Arina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The project shows a good model of public humanities collaboration for co-creating an engaging narrative that reimagines issues surrounding female authorship and mobility and the transatlantic slave trade and questions stereotypes. The poster presents work on a relevant topic.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal describes Jane Austen&#039;s Desk as an immersive environment that helps the audience reimagine issues surrounding female authorship and mobility and the transatlantic slave trade. &#10; The project invests in archives, deploys DH methods, and offers context from Book and Print History, Cultural studies, History, Literary Studies, and Transatlantic studies.&#10;The purpose of the proposal is to establish a thematic foundation for their intervention in Austen studies.&#10;Setting a public humanities project that simulates an imaginative version of Austen’s writing space as a hub for hosting historical, literary, and material content in an interactive manner has great potential for archivists, community educators, and the use of inclusive pedagogy.&#10;The proposal includes an introduction outlining the purpose and objectives, the background, and expected outcomes. It brings attention to the responsibilities of the artist for their creative outcome. The lens of gender inequality emphasizes the resilience of the feminine writer. However, including an analysis of the power relations and privileges in this context would make the proposal stronger.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1231</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Otis, Jessica</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Creates a website of content Jane Austen would have been engaging with circa March 30, 1813.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission describes a fascinating project that would be a great poster at the conference. I didn&#039;t score this abstract as high as I feel like the project deserves because I judged the abstract to not be as explicit/clear in addressing the various review criteria as necessary to give a higher score. &#10;&#10;E.g. the abstract mentions &quot;challeng[ing] the stereotype of Austen as a primarily domestic, feminine writer&quot; but not how the project illuminates Austen&#039;s connections to (unnamed) &quot;issues surrounding female authorship and mobility and the transatlantic slave trade.&quot;  Are they connected through the newspapers? Through her brothers&#039; travels? Through her letters? And what issues in particular are we talking about here? Similarly, the choice of date - March 30th, 1813 - is only situated in the context of her domestic writing (just published Pride and Prejudice) and left unexplained in terms of mobility or the transatlantic slave trade. &#10;&#10;More explicit description of the issues, date choice, and other similar points alluded to in the abstract would have made this a stronger and more compelling submission.  Also, not connected to the review criteria but relevant to this as an NEH DPP project, I would have liked to hear more about what public this project is for and how they are expected to engage with it.  However the project itself is a fascinating one, with great breadth and potential, and I would recommend accepting this poster.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I feel like the abstract assumed I would know a lot more about the minutia of Austen studies than I do vs. explaining the importance of their intervention in Austen studies.  I&#039;m also not clear how this is a DPP project and so mentioned that, even though it&#039;s not really part of the review criteria.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1309</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ryan C Dubnicek, Ryan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This poster shows a digital project that seeks to recreate and share Jane Austen&#039;s desk--both a representation of her work, its context, both personal and societal, and her own papers. Beyond the subject matter of Austen, which is fascinating, this project also serves as interesting incite into cultural heritage platforms and how to engage with digital audiences, both practically and conceptually.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This sounds like a great poster for a fascinating project. I&#039;d be interested in seeing some of the practical information about design and implementation highlighted in the poster or as part of a presentation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
