    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Towards a Concientizando Comunidades Colectiva: Bridging critical digital humanities with ethnic studies to responsibly create translingual community archives in Texas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">critical Latinx digital humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Digital Storytelling&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Ethnic studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Ethnic studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Within colonial analog and digital archives there is the need to expand the canons of U.S. and Chicanx/Latinx historiographies by focusing on feminist leaders/activists/organizers/educators, specifically women who have contributed to consciousness-raising and social transformation locally, nationally and across borders. In this panel, four presenters will go over the process, objectives and ethics of building a digital repository that works to document, preserve and make accessible the contributions of women within education, public policy and social movements that have influenced communities in Texas and across the border. Through feminist praxis and community engagement, Concientizando Comunidades Colectiva recovers the memories of women focusing on movements, leadership, and activism and the archival practices of women of color to shed light on underrepresented, untold, or marginalized narratives. In their presentation, “Decolonizing Fiesta San Antonio through Xicana/x Cultural Activism,” the first presenter discusses community efforts to contest settler colonial narratives and practices embedded in San Antonio’s Fiesta, a 10-day citywide public celebration that commemorates settler colonialism in Texas. The second presenter highlights the leadership and strategies of the women who run Mexican American studies programs in major cities in Texas through the use of oral histories. The third presentation explores the human rights movement against gender-based violence and feminicides in el Paso del Norte Region (Chihuahua, Texas and New Mexico). The fourth presenter offers an introduction to mija archival methods and how we can look to our mothers’ work with family archives as entry points to understanding ourselves within a larger, San Antonio meta-narrative, one that often silences and excludes women of color. These efforts function not only as a multimodal digital archive and pedagogical tool to be used in K-20 classrooms and higher education, but also as a template for community members and future leaders to turn to when organizing and engaging in their own forms of resistance within and across borders. This digital feminist archive contains models of feminist leadership and organizing from the ground-up and highlight ethical practices to push back against the violent colonial research practices that contribute to forms of extraction, opportunism, surveillance, intellectual colonialism, misogyny, and capitalist interests within communities of color. The creation of alternative digital archives of leadership and activism in Texas will be a site of knowledge transformation by documenting and making accessible in ethical ways narratives and materials that speak to the efforts against colonial and neocolonial violence towards indigenous and communities of color in Texas. Overall, this alternative digital archive sums the efforts present in postcolonial digital humanities to remediate the colonial violence, write back to colonial histories, and fill gaps in knowledge that remain a legacy of colonialism (Risam 2019).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Within colonial analog and digital archives there is the need to expand the canons of U.S. and Chicanx/Latinx historiographies by focusing on feminist leaders/activists/organizers/educators, specifically women who have contributed to consciousness-raising and social transformation locally, nationally and across borders. In this panel, four presenters will go over the process, objectives and ethics of building a digital repository that works to document, preserve and make accessible the contributions of women within education, public policy and social movements that have influenced communities in Texas and across the border. Through feminist praxis and community engagement, Concientizando Comunidades Colectiva recovers the memories of women focusing on movements, leadership, and activism and the archival practices of women of color to shed light on underrepresented, untold, or marginalized narratives. In their presentation, “Decolonizing Fiesta San Antonio through Xicana/x Cultural Activism,” the first presenter discusses community efforts to contest settler colonial narratives and practices embedded in San Antonio’s Fiesta, a 10-day citywide public celebration that commemorates settler colonialism in Texas. The second presenter highlights the leadership and strategies of the women who run Mexican American studies programs in major cities in Texas through the use of oral histories. The third presentation explores the human rights movement against gender-based violence and feminicides in el Paso del Norte Region (Chihuahua, Texas and New Mexico). The fourth presenter offers an introduction to mija archival methods and how we can look to our mothers’ work with family archives as entry points to understanding ourselves within a larger, San Antonio meta-narrative, one that often silences and excludes women of color. These efforts function not only as a multimodal digital archive and pedagogical tool to be used in K-20 classrooms and higher education, but also as a template for community members and future leaders to turn to when organizing and engaging in their own forms of resistance within and across borders. This digital feminist archive contains models of feminist leadership and organizing from the ground-up and highlight ethical practices to push back against the violent colonial research practices that contribute to forms of extraction, opportunism, surveillance, intellectual colonialism, misogyny, and capitalist interests within communities of color. The creation of alternative digital archives of leadership and activism in Texas will be a site of knowledge transformation by documenting and making accessible in ethical ways narratives and materials that speak to the efforts against colonial and neocolonial violence towards indigenous and communities of color in Texas. Overall, this alternative digital archive sums the efforts present in postcolonial digital humanities to remediate the colonial violence, write back to colonial histories, and fill gaps in knowledge that remain a legacy of colonialism (Risam 2019).</ss:Data></Cell>
