    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Speculative Librarianship, Speculative Publishing: Reimagining the Review and Publishing Process for Critical Digital (Library) Scholarship</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital publishing, digital humanities peer-review, digital librarianship, critical librarianship</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;open access methods&#10;scholarly editing and editions development, analysis, and methods&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;open access methods&#10;scholarly editing and editions development, analysis, and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In June 2024, the &lt;em&gt;Journal of Critical Digital Librarianship &lt;/em&gt;(JCDL) published a special issue centered on speculative digital librarianship. The special issue called for librarians to dream big about the future of digital library work unhindered by budgets, current technology, or established practices. Beyond content, editors asked authors to think unconventionally about the very format of their articles, hoping that by soliciting research and reflections in the form of fiction, audio recordings, or visual artwork we could expand the ways in which we communicate with each other as professionals. But reimagining how digital technologies can be used to write, review, and publish scholarship brought unique challenges: editors grappled with questions about how to edit an article with no textual document, or what standards to use for reviewing fiction in a publication that does not ask its writers to be established fiction writers. As digital humanities scholars continue to seek publishing venues for scholarship in non-traditional formats, we have seen a rise in new peer-review infrastructure over the past few years. To address recent changes in the landscape of DH peer review and publishing, this roundtable will center the question of how we might reimagine what an accessible scholarly journal looks like while maintaining the quality and rigor expected of a peer-reviewed academic publication. JCDL special issue editors will share how they adapted traditional academic publishing to allow for a range of novel submission formats and will facilitate a dialogue with participants on strategies for reviewing and publishing non-textual scholarly work. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In June 2024, the Journal of Critical Digital Librarianship (JCDL) published a special issue centered on speculative digital librarianship. The special issue called for librarians to dream big about the future of digital library work unhindered by budgets, current technology, or established practices. Beyond content, editors asked authors to think unconventionally about the very format of their articles, hoping that by soliciting research and reflections in the form of fiction, audio recordings, or visual artwork we could expand the ways in which we communicate with each other as professionals. But reimagining how digital technologies can be used to write, review, and publish scholarship brought unique challenges: editors grappled with questions about how to edit an article with no textual document, or what standards to use for reviewing fiction in a publication that does not ask its writers to be established fiction writers. As digital humanities scholars continue to seek publishing venues for scholarship in non-traditional formats, we have seen a rise in new peer-review infrastructure over the past few years. To address recent changes in the landscape of DH peer review and publishing, this roundtable will center the question of how we might reimagine what an accessible scholarly journal looks like while maintaining the quality and rigor expected of a peer-reviewed academic publication. JCDL special issue editors will share how they adapted traditional academic publishing to allow for a range of novel submission formats and will facilitate a dialogue with participants on strategies for reviewing and publishing non-textual scholarly work.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Starry, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Pittsburgh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rachel.starry@pitt.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rachel.starry@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rachel.starry@pitt.edu, emz42@cornell.edu, Janina.Mueller@mcphs.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Starry, Rachel;&#10;Zinger, Emily;&#10;Mueller, Janina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rachel.starry@pitt.edu;&#10;emz42@cornell.edu;&#10;Janina.Mueller@mcphs.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">91.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">176</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1024</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brooks, Mackenzie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors seek to reimagine the processes and products of a DH academic journal and reflect on a recent special issue. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fascinating! I often see calls for non-traditional formats in more conventional journals, but rarely see the actual non-traditional formats come to publication. Appreciate that this submission wants to reflect on process and challenges of carrying out this issue. Would be curious about previous scholarly work in this area? Where else are we seeing a new peer review infrastructure and are there other editorial comments on that process? Probably JITP or PH at bare minimum? &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1190</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Michael, Krystyna</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission aims to discuss the challenges and opportunities of innovative scholarly methods in the realm of digital librarianship. The roundtable will discuss the possibilities posed by scholarship in non-traditional formats such as fiction, audio recordings, or visual artwork, and the importance of developing new peer-review and editorial processes to facilitate new forms of scholarship while still maintaining the quality and rigor expected of peer-reviewed work. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a great proposal that hits on some of the key opportunities and challenges of evolving forms of scholarship. As our conception of what should count as scholarship changes, a major topic in the digital humanities where scholarly work often looks very different than it does in other fields, so, too, must our methods and models of evaluation - and yet they haven&#039;t yet. I think this topic will generate a lot of interest and productive conversations. One suggestion is to further develop the connection between this topic and social justice, anti-racist work. I think you can make the argument that developing a system for valuing non-traditional scholarly work as scholarship is an anti-racist initiative, but it needs to be developed and linked to histories of traditional scholarship and its tendency to be discriminatory and exclusive. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Love this proposal!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1279</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rogers, Katina L</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission addresses a key need in DH scholarship: the tension between the increasingly creative and innovative work that scholars are producing on one hand, and the legacy infrastructure that is not always equipped to handle that creativity on the other. I think this session will be of great interest to many ACH participants.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I&#039;m very glad to see this submission! I&#039;m in the midst of editing a special journal issue that intentionally tried to push some of the boundaries within the journal system, and it hasn&#039;t been easy. Your abstract doesn&#039;t specifically discuss the ways in which it engages with feminist, anti-racist, decolonial work—I think the connection is there, though, so I would simply recommend giving it some additional thought and making sure to foreground it in your session.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
