    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital Humanities vs. Zero-Based Budgeting: Innovation, Sustainability, and Austerity in College Libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital history, austerity, pedagogy, program management, digital scholarship</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;History&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;History&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Starting a new digital scholarship project, collaboration, or program is exciting. Ending a library digital scholarship program is complicated. The Digital Scholarship Center at the Sojourner Truth Library is one example of what happens when ambitious faculty and librarians push the innovation:budget capacity of a small state college. The SUNY system is nearing a $1 billion deficit, and zero-based budgeting is being implemented system-wide. This shift has had an immediate impact on how resources are allocated. This presentation will cover the ups, downs, “pauses” and closing of the Digital Scholarship Center at the SUNY New Paltz library, from the perspective of one former program Coordinator.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Participants will hear about the founding of the Digital Scholarship Center, the struggles to find an ethical and sustainable program model, exciting collaborations with faculty and students, developing and the reality of failing to acquire the golden combination of hard-money funding and full-time staffing. Despite robust efforts to create high-impact educational opportunities for student employees, engaging faculty in new methods and critical pedagogy, creating unique digital projects, and tracking every data-point to demonstrate value--institutional support is never guaranteed.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This session relates to the theme of “critical ideologies and digital pedagogy.” Librarians and faculty worked to establish and grow a sustainable and ethical program structure, a transparent budget process, and librarian support for critical DH pedagogy on campus. Support for this work, which challenged dominant structures and practices, was lacking institution-wide. Diverse audiences will benefit from the programmatic-level discussion of the intersection of the worsening financial crisis in higher education and the future of Digital Humanities work.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Learning outcomes: Understand key components of developing an ethical and sustainable DH program plan. Understand increasingly prevalent environmental factors that limit DH innovation in academic libraries. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Starting a new digital scholarship project, collaboration, or program is exciting. Ending a library digital scholarship program is complicated. The Digital Scholarship Center at the Sojourner Truth Library is one example of what happens when ambitious faculty and librarians push the innovation:budget capacity of a small state college. The SUNY system is nearing a $1 billion deficit, and zero-based budgeting is being implemented system-wide. This shift has had an immediate impact on how resources are allocated. This presentation will cover the ups, downs, “pauses” and closing of the Digital Scholarship Center at the SUNY New Paltz library, from the perspective of one former program Coordinator.&#10;Participants will hear about the founding of the Digital Scholarship Center, the struggles to find an ethical and sustainable program model, exciting collaborations with faculty and students, developing and the reality of failing to acquire the golden combination of hard-money funding and full-time staffing. Despite robust efforts to create high-impact educational opportunities for student employees, engaging faculty in new methods and critical pedagogy, creating unique digital projects, and tracking every data-point to demonstrate value--institutional support is never guaranteed.&#10;This session relates to the theme of “critical ideologies and digital pedagogy.” Librarians and faculty worked to establish and grow a sustainable and ethical program structure, a transparent budget process, and librarian support for critical DH pedagogy on campus. Support for this work, which challenged dominant structures and practices, was lacking institution-wide. Diverse audiences will benefit from the programmatic-level discussion of the intersection of the worsening financial crisis in higher education and the future of Digital Humanities work.&#10;Learning outcomes: Understand key components of developing an ethical and sustainable DH program plan. Understand increasingly prevalent environmental factors that limit DH innovation in academic libraries.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
