    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">177</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1193</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chassanoff, Alexandra</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This poster presentation proposes to tell the story of a digital scholarship program in an academic library setting, from  its inception to its sunsetting. The author is the former Program Coordinator, and proposes to share first-hand knowledge of the successes and challenges the program faced, as it struggled to adapt to the higher ed financial crisis.     </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This poster presentation will make an important contribution to a much needed larger conversation about academic digital humanities work and responsible, sustainable project sunsetting. It aims to share insights from the experiences of the former program coordinator, making it a prime opportunity to share important &quot;lessons learned&quot; that are applicable to other efforts in academic library settings. The proposal submission has done a nice job of highlighting a number of different areas of topical focus to be covered. Because of this, care should be taken in presenting to make sure focus is maintained and to prevent scope creep from derailing coverage of critical points. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal submission has done a nice job of highlighting a number of different areas of topical focus to be covered - but because of this wide range of topics, this poster might work better as a lightning talk.  Either way, care should be taken in presenting to make sure focus is maintained and to prevent scope creep from derailing coverage of critical points. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1122</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boyles, Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution discusses the challenges of implementing and sustaining a DH program with a low (or sometimes no) budget. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal engages the very important and pressing topic of sustaining DH programs at institutions where budgets for DH work are dwindling or nonexistent. Given the budget strain many programs are feeling in the wake of COVID-19 and ever-decreasing state funding, this presentation has a lot to offer many conference attendees. Of particular interest is the ethical model that the author has implemented--how do you maintain a code of ethics when you are facing labor and resource deficits? How do you ensure that people are treated well? My only concern about this presentation is that it is tackling a lot of topics--maybe consider paring down to ensure that you have enough time to dig into each topic in detail.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1081</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Haines, Chelsea</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission critically examines problems related to long-term funding prospects for digital humanities projects in universities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation highlights an important but often overlooked aspect of digital humanities work: long-term funding. While institutions are often excited about the prospect of starting digital humanities projects, they are often hampered by lack of secure funding sources (as this abstract points out) and leads to incomplete and thwarted projects. At the same time, it is unclear how this presentation could address lessons, solutions, or alternate modes of thinking those involved in digital humanities initiatives should consider when launching new projects.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
