    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Litigating Irishness&lt;/em&gt; is a database of legal disputes surrounding land tenure and property rights that proliferated in early modern Ireland. The project uses these records as a lens for examining the strategies of negotiation employed by the Irish aristocracy in the face of escalating discrimination: flexibilities of legal representation, sites of arbitration, legal vocabularies, and more. Those flexibilities were mechanisms for contesting colonial logics that sought to reorder Irish society through the imposition of increasingly rigid categories. However, those flexibilities produce challenges for the digital humanist, whose processes of encoding likewise impose categories that sometimes, albeit inadvertently, echo the colonial logics of the early modern legal system. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This paper will explore multilingualism as a strategy of negotiation, examining both its historical contexts and its ramifications for the current digital project. For early modern litigants, multilingual contexts constituted a barrier between colonizer and colonized in both directions. However, documentation from court cases over land and assets also reveals multilingualism as a strategy of negotiation, as a means of metering the flow of information in contested spaces. Engaging with multilingualism in &lt;em&gt;Litigating Irishness&lt;/em&gt; presents a number of related challenges related to identifying and encoding multilingual practices. But underlying all these issues of praxis, there are thorny theoretical questions about whether the logic of databases is fundamentally incompatible with the efforts of colonized people to escape and move between the categories imposed on them. This paper will explore some of the theoretical, ethical, and practical considerations for encoding flexibility.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Litigating Irishness is a database of legal disputes surrounding land tenure and property rights that proliferated in early modern Ireland. The project uses these records as a lens for examining the strategies of negotiation employed by the Irish aristocracy in the face of escalating discrimination: flexibilities of legal representation, sites of arbitration, legal vocabularies, and more. Those flexibilities were mechanisms for contesting colonial logics that sought to reorder Irish society through the imposition of increasingly rigid categories. However, those flexibilities produce challenges for the digital humanist, whose processes of encoding likewise impose categories that sometimes, albeit inadvertently, echo the colonial logics of the early modern legal system. &#10;This paper will explore multilingualism as a strategy of negotiation, examining both its historical contexts and its ramifications for the current digital project. For early modern litigants, multilingual contexts constituted a barrier between colonizer and colonized in both directions. However, documentation from court cases over land and assets also reveals multilingualism as a strategy of negotiation, as a means of metering the flow of information in contested spaces. Engaging with multilingualism in Litigating Irishness presents a number of related challenges related to identifying and encoding multilingual practices. But underlying all these issues of praxis, there are thorny theoretical questions about whether the logic of databases is fundamentally incompatible with the efforts of colonized people to escape and move between the categories imposed on them. This paper will explore some of the theoretical, ethical, and practical considerations for encoding flexibility.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Smith, Margaret K.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Southern Illinois University Edwardsville</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">margars@siue.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">margars@siue.edu, Ocp035@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Smith, Margaret K.;&#10;Perez, Olivia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">margars@siue.edu;&#10;Ocp035@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Central (Chicago)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">83.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">178</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1282</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Middle, Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract proposes to demonstrate ways in which multilingual flexibility might be effectively and sensitively represented in a database.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal clearly articulates its relevance to the themes of multilingualism and colonialism, and how they apply to the presentation topic.&#10;&#10;Background information is included about the subject area under discussion, to provide a clear context within which the work has been conducted.&#10;&#10;The aims and implications of the work are well articulated. I would be interested to hear more explicitly about the methodologies applied, but assume this would be included in the presentation.&#10;&#10;Overall, this proposal is highly relevant to the conference themes and there is much that the Digital Humanities community could learn from this study.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1209</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">McEwan, John</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital Humanities deals with people and their values, assumptions, and beliefs, which are often difficult to model in ways that are amenable to computation. What is exciting about this submission is that it does an excellent job of articulating, in a clear and concise fashion, how a humanities research question serves to inspire the authors&#039; self-conscious reflection on the strengths and limitations of database systems designed to facilitate humanities research. The authors aim to ensure that the nuances and complexity of their sources are not effaced by the demands of computation. Nonetheless, that is difficult to accomplish given the nature of their sources that themselves seek to impose an order on a colonized population.      </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Historical research and historical data can provide a wonderful set of problems for digital humanities research. This abstract does an excellent job of articulating how historical research leads into reflection on the strengths and limitations of different approaches to data modelling. I am curious to know to what extent the historical documentation has been digitized and is machine readable? How large a corpus is the study addressing? Could you explicitly mention previous work on these sources and/or on other projects that have aimed to make searchable/ accessible large collections of judicial materials. Implicit in the proposal is a critical and thoughtful reaction to such projects as the Anglo-American Legal Tradition or even the Old Bailey online that have made available large bodies of early-modern judicial materials from the British Isles. However, the abstract does an excellent job of identifying a digital humanities research question and indicating how the paper will advance the conversation.   </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1231</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Otis, Jessica</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution explores issues surrounding multilingualism and colonialism that arise out of creating a database of Irish property rights/land tenure cases from the early modern period</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a fascinating project and a well-written abstract. I do see room for improvement though in more explicit engagement with relevant scholarship/the current state of the field. This is especially true with respect to the final question of whether databases (and which kind? each one has its own affordances) are fundamentally incompatible with studying the agency of colonized people in these legal contexts. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
