    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Agile Archiving: Applying DAM Strategies to Cultural Heritage Collections</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital asset management, archiving, data retention, digital collections, content creation</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital archiving&#10;digital libraries creation, management, and analysis&#10;metadata standards, systems, and methods&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital archiving&#10;digital libraries creation, management, and analysis&#10;metadata standards, systems, and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Many grassroots web projects house increasingly large collections but struggle to develop effective and efficient sustainability strategies that can ensure their long-term usability. This lightning talk proposal explores the presenter’s experience developing and implementing an asset lifecycle plan and associated data retention schedule as a digital asset management (DAM) librarian in the private tech sector. The volume of data that we share and store in born-digital collections is continually increasing—growth that inhibits content searchability and incurs unnecessary storage costs. Further, as the requirements for digital content adapt and change, legacy digital content often is left lacking robust metadata, resulting in inconsistent search performance and diminished possibilities for content analytics and research insights. To address these issues, the presenter’s team began developing policies and procedures for the retention and purging of digital assets from our active web environment, constructing a data lifecycle plan to provide guidance on asset archiving practices. Examining the successes and shortcomings of this process, the presenter will then connect these take-aways to cultural heritage and community archiving projects, providing attendees with effective strategies to manage their digital content.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Many grassroots web projects house increasingly large collections but struggle to develop effective and efficient sustainability strategies that can ensure their long-term usability. This lightning talk proposal explores the presenter’s experience developing and implementing an asset lifecycle plan and associated data retention schedule as a digital asset management (DAM) librarian in the private tech sector. The volume of data that we share and store in born-digital collections is continually increasing—growth that inhibits content searchability and incurs unnecessary storage costs. Further, as the requirements for digital content adapt and change, legacy digital content often is left lacking robust metadata, resulting in inconsistent search performance and diminished possibilities for content analytics and research insights. To address these issues, the presenter’s team began developing policies and procedures for the retention and purging of digital assets from our active web environment, constructing a data lifecycle plan to provide guidance on asset archiving practices. Examining the successes and shortcomings of this process, the presenter will then connect these take-aways to cultural heritage and community archiving projects, providing attendees with effective strategies to manage their digital content.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Petersen, Andy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ESRI</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">andyjp.lib@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">andyjp.lib@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boyles Petersen, Andy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">andyjp.lib@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Standard Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">67.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">70.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">64.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">179</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1024</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brooks, Mackenzie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Submission intends to present DAM approaches from a private tech company for use by GLAM organizations and their digital project content management.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The subject of this submission is deeply relevant to the larger DH community. I would be curious to see the overlaps between approaches and resources between a private corporation and the academic or non-profit world. Personally, I find ESRI products to be pretty difficult to navigate from a content management perspective, so would be very interested in hearing about management approaches. That being said, this is an ongoing area of interest for GLAM institutions and would like to see acknowledgement of existing scholarship or best practices.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Abstract suggests a lightning talk, but submission type is individual paper. Could go either way. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1182</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boehlert, Krystal</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A data lifecycle plan with policies and procedures for managing new and legacy digital assets.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Connecting your strategies to cultural heritage and community archiving projects will be incredibly valuable. The strengths will be in the development and implementation details of your policies that shape workflows and decisions. Sometimes it&#039;s hard to know where to start that program administration.&#10;&#10;I&#039;m curious to hear if and how GIS data are managed differently than other digital assets. That would be a unique perspective for the digital humanities communities that work with mapping data and web assets.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1289</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Traylor, Jordan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk will communicate the author&#039;s work in developing a data lifecycle plan to help handle the &quot;aging&quot; of legacy digital content as new born-digital content evolves in size and requirements - and how this plan, born in the private tech sector, can be applied to cultural heritage projects.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The prospect of applying a private-sector-based data lifecycle plan to help sustain the long-term usability of community digital archives sounds promising. A sound lifecycle plan should have numerous insights into the maintenance of a community/cultural archive; but I am curious as to what adaptations might need to be made to the policies and procedures as this plan leaves its private sector roots, or, in other words, how this connection mentioned by the authors might be made. The proposal is strong in its theoretical framework, presenting an analytical view of data lifecycle policies, and anticipating the changing forms and procedures involved in born-digital content. It also recognizes the importance of robust metadata. The proposal also well articulates the applicability of this lifecycle plan to DH in general, with an eye towards community and cultural archiving projects. The proposal lacks any discussion on potential antiracist, Indigenous, ethnic, etc. themes or applications, though it is relevant insofar as empowering community archives with new strategies can contribute to this kind of work.</ss:Data></Cell>
