    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Towards a Community-Based, Platform-Specific Theory of Algorithmic Governance: The Algorithmic Folk Theories Project</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Folk Theories, Digital Cultures, Social Media, TikTok, Community-Engaged Research</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;social media analysis and methods&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Sociology&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;social media analysis and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Sociology&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The Algorithmic Folk Theories Project is a co-creative, equal partnership between the ASU Lincoln Center for Applied Ethics and the Online Content Creator Association (OCCA) to gather community-based knowledge, or folk theories, that TikTok content creators use to understand and resist algorithmic bias. Folk theories are “the culturally available symbolic resources that people use to make sense of their own media and information practices” (Toff and Nielsen, 2018) and have been used to understand user attitudes toward algorithms (Dogruel, 2021; Lomborg and Kapsch, 2019; Ytre-Arne and Moe 2020) and perceptions of content curation and moderation (Eslami et al., 2016; Moran et al., 2022; Ye and Zhao, 2023). This theoretical lens provides insight into the relationship between algorithms, agency, and identity, particularly in relationship to marginalized communities–who are the focus of this project. The project team’s humanistic research on digital cultures engages folks theories as the knowledge infrastructure content creators use to imagine the forces that impact their everyday lives: algorithmic content curation and opaquely-defined moderation.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This poster will present the results of the current phase of the project (funded by NEH-ODH from 2023-24), which gathered and analyzed 20 interviews from TikTok content creators, who discussed diverse, social identity-based experiences on the app. We present content analysis of narratives, approaches, and understandings (i.e. folk theories) they use to navigate the oppressive forces of algorithmic culture. We also introduce results from a comparative analysis between these folk theories and current academic theories of algorithmic governance to explore overlapping concepts and themes.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Algorithmic Folk Theories Project is a co-creative, equal partnership between the ASU Lincoln Center for Applied Ethics and the Online Content Creator Association (OCCA) to gather community-based knowledge, or folk theories, that TikTok content creators use to understand and resist algorithmic bias. Folk theories are “the culturally available symbolic resources that people use to make sense of their own media and information practices” (Toff and Nielsen, 2018) and have been used to understand user attitudes toward algorithms (Dogruel, 2021; Lomborg and Kapsch, 2019; Ytre-Arne and Moe 2020) and perceptions of content curation and moderation (Eslami et al., 2016; Moran et al., 2022; Ye and Zhao, 2023). This theoretical lens provides insight into the relationship between algorithms, agency, and identity, particularly in relationship to marginalized communities–who are the focus of this project. The project team’s humanistic research on digital cultures engages folks theories as the knowledge infrastructure content creators use to imagine the forces that impact their everyday lives: algorithmic content curation and opaquely-defined moderation.&#10;This poster will present the results of the current phase of the project (funded by NEH-ODH from 2023-24), which gathered and analyzed 20 interviews from TikTok content creators, who discussed diverse, social identity-based experiences on the app. We present content analysis of narratives, approaches, and understandings (i.e. folk theories) they use to navigate the oppressive forces of algorithmic culture. We also introduce results from a comparative analysis between these folk theories and current academic theories of algorithmic governance to explore overlapping concepts and themes.</ss:Data></Cell>
