    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">180</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1311</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Li, Simin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">an ongoing and meaningful digital practice in the fighting with algorithmic bias</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I understand this is the presentation of the result of the a phase of the project so the value of the theoretical, methodological, and/or practical contribution may not be deep enough. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1233</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kashyap, Deepika</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This poster presentation investigates the relationship between algorithms and folk theories — particularly how marginalized communities express themselves and navigate algorithmic cultures that are influenced by human biases. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors of this poster presentation have clearly explained why it is important to study the relationships between algorithmic cultures and folk theories. This poster has a clear theoretical and methodological approach. &#10;It also offers a valid argument that algorithmic culture is oppressive, and further investigation into the topic can enrich the burgeoning literature in digital humanities. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The poster is well articulated. The authors of this poster have clearly argued why it is important to study the relationships between algorithmic culture and folk theories. Also, it has a strong theoretical and methodological approach. &#10;I strongly recommend this poster for this conference. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1316</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Meneses, Luis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Algorithmic Folk Theories Project gathers community-based knowledge, or folk theories, that TikTok content creators use to understand and resist algorithmic bias. This poster will present the results of the current phase of the project, which gathered and analyzed 20 interviews from TikTok content creators, who discussed diverse, social identity-based experiences on the app.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an interesting submission: it provides (much needed) insights into the relationship between algorithms, agency, and identity, particularly in relationship to marginalized communities. &#10;&#10;The research questions and the background are clearly laid out. However, more details on the analysis and results would have made this a stronger submission. Assuming that the proposal is accepted, I would suggest highlighting these details in the poster. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
