    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Integrating Folk and Academic Knowledges: Algorithmic Justice, Social Media, and Community-First Research</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">algorithm studies, algorithmic justice, collaboration, community partnerships, project management</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;social media analysis and methods&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;social media analysis and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The “Algorithmic Folk Theories” Project brings together academic researchers and digital content creators to identify and analyze folk theories regarding algorithmic content curation and moderation on TikTok in order to identify opportunities and strategies for combating the spread of mis/disinformation and hate speech on the platform. For this roundtable, we bring together researchers from Arizona State University’s Lincoln Center for Applied Ethics (LCAE) with our community researcher and liaison from the Online Content Creator Association (OCCA) to briefly present project findings from the current phase of the project (2023-24), reflect on the challenges and successes of academic-community partnerships, and invite conference attendees into conversation with the aim of shaping best practices for research on algorithmic justice rooted in a community-first approach.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Our project focuses not on social media influencers, but instead content creators with medium to large-size audience communities (between 1,500 and 500,000 followers). Users and content creators on TikTok are highly engaged in the production of folk theories about the algorithm, drawing on anecdote, speculation, and aggregated personal experience to form their own informal research networks (Karizat et al., 2021), similar to but different from Citizen Science networks. Given that algorithmically-driven bias and misinformation are often brought to light through the efforts of users, these folk theories contain valuable insights. For example, in 2021, it was TikTok creator Ziggi Tyler who uncovered an error that flagged any mention of Black people as “inappropriate” in the biographical description field of the Creator Marketplace (Ghaffary, 2021). Upon gathering these folk theories (interviews conclude June 2024), we will synthesize them with extant academic theory and methodologies to identify potential points of overlap and generate cross-professional vocabularies to facilitate trust and understanding for future ethical collaborations between experts and non-academics in the field of algorithm studies. Those analyses will reveal instances of overlapping narratives, and produce a shared vocabulary that will allow academics and community members to more effectively collaborate to intervene in the spread of mis/disinformation on TikTok and other social media platforms.  &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;During this roundtable, the project team, who have been in active collaboration since 2020, will first discuss how the creation of shared vocabularies unveils insights into how priorities and discourses operate in both academic and community groups. We will then briefly reflect on the care-based project management needed to ensure that academic-community collaborations and professional mentorship are rooted in an ethic of “hospitality, generosity, reciprocity, foresight, and responsibility” (Losh, 2018). We will then devote a significant amount of time to audience participation, shaping conversation around the following interventions/provocations:&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;ul&gt;&#10;&lt;li dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;How can we form ethical academic-community partnerships with algorithmic justice as a guiding principle?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;How do we speak across and/or bridge expertise by forming new best practices for collaboration that account for individual capacities and lived experiences?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;How can we challenge existing hierarchical understandings of “knowledge production” in the academy by intentionally integrating the “folk knowledges” of those most impacted by algorithmic bias?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;/ul&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The current phase of this project (2023-2024) is supported by a grant from the National Endowment for the Humanities.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The “Algorithmic Folk Theories” Project brings together academic researchers and digital content creators to identify and analyze folk theories regarding algorithmic content curation and moderation on TikTok in order to identify opportunities and strategies for combating the spread of mis/disinformation and hate speech on the platform. For this roundtable, we bring together researchers from Arizona State University’s Lincoln Center for Applied Ethics (LCAE) with our community researcher and liaison from the Online Content Creator Association (OCCA) to briefly present project findings from the current phase of the project (2023-24), reflect on the challenges and successes of academic-community partnerships, and invite conference attendees into conversation with the aim of shaping best practices for research on algorithmic justice rooted in a community-first approach.&#10;Our project focuses not on social media influencers, but instead content creators with medium to large-size audience communities (between 1,500 and 500,000 followers). Users and content creators on TikTok are highly engaged in the production of folk theories about the algorithm, drawing on anecdote, speculation, and aggregated personal experience to form their own informal research networks (Karizat et al., 2021), similar to but different from Citizen Science networks. Given that algorithmically-driven bias and misinformation are often brought to light through the efforts of users, these folk theories contain valuable insights. For example, in 2021, it was TikTok creator Ziggi Tyler who uncovered an error that flagged any mention of Black people as “inappropriate” in the biographical description field of the Creator Marketplace (Ghaffary, 2021). Upon gathering these folk theories (interviews conclude June 2024), we will synthesize them with extant academic theory and methodologies to identify potential points of overlap and generate cross-professional vocabularies to facilitate trust and understanding for future ethical collaborations between experts and non-academics in the field of algorithm studies. Those analyses will reveal instances of overlapping narratives, and produce a shared vocabulary that will allow academics and community members to more effectively collaborate to intervene in the spread of mis/disinformation on TikTok and other social media platforms.  &#10;During this roundtable, the project team, who have been in active collaboration since 2020, will first discuss how the creation of shared vocabularies unveils insights into how priorities and discourses operate in both academic and community groups. We will then briefly reflect on the care-based project management needed to ensure that academic-community collaborations and professional mentorship are rooted in an ethic of “hospitality, generosity, reciprocity, foresight, and responsibility” (Losh, 2018). We will then devote a significant amount of time to audience participation, shaping conversation around the following interventions/provocations:&#10;How can we form ethical academic-community partnerships with algorithmic justice as a guiding principle?&#10;How do we speak across and/or bridge expertise by forming new best practices for collaboration that account for individual capacities and lived experiences?&#10;How can we challenge existing hierarchical understandings of “knowledge production” in the academy by intentionally integrating the “folk knowledges” of those most impacted by algorithmic bias?&#10;The current phase of this project (2023-2024) is supported by a grant from the National Endowment for the Humanities.</ss:Data></Cell>
