    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">181</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1211</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rashid, Mohammed</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This roundtable focuses on a discussion by project collaborators and audiences around the contribution of &#039;folk theories&#039; about the role of algorithms in content curation, distribution, and moderation in Tiktok, ultimately exploring its importance towards community-based approaches to tackling mis/disinformation and algorithmic bias. Discussions center around the production of folk-theories on algorithms and how they create situated and ethical knowledges and collaborative approaches to resist and intervene in the dissemination of fake news and mis/disinformation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The &quot;Algorithmic Folk Theories&quot; project sounds like a very important contribution to today&#039;s world of digital citizenship, and I am sure the audience and project collaborators will greatly benefit from the exchange that will unfold in the round-table discussions. I am particularly excited to learn that there are more and more projects that foreground participatory ethical contributions in tactically challenging the algorithmic work fuelling dissemination of dis/misinformation that also often lead to, among other things, hate-speech, fake news, propaganda, click-bait, and imposter content. The provocations that will guide the interactions with the audience are also exciting, contributing to a more collaborative and community-based approach to algorithmic (critical) media literacy based on folk knowledges. We absolutely need this common vocabulary that will better enable academics, content creators, content archivists, and other stake-holders to imagine a more ethical and equitable digital platform future.&#10;&#10;Hopefully, by the end of the discussions, there will also be some guidelines on how more communities could practice, participate in, and collaborate in such interventions.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Strongly recommending this round-table discussion to be accepted. There is much to learn from the experiences of the project collaborators and their discussion around developing ethical and community based interventions to traditional, hierarchical, and oppressive algorithmic practices on social media platforms. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1275</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kilbane, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This roundtable proposes to introduce the “Algorithmic Folk Theories” project, a collaboration between academics and medium-to-large-size content creators that aims to identify and analyze folk theories regarding algorithmic content curation and moderation on TikTok. Their aim is to combat the spread of mis/disinformation and hate speech on the platform. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This roundtable seems poised to introduce conference attendees to a fascinating, well-staked, and potentially groundbreaking DH collaboration. I am very eager to know more about the &quot;extant academic theory and methodologies&quot; the authors intend to employ, and keenly interested, too, in how these theoretical vocabularies will interface with the &quot;folk&quot; vocabularies of content creators. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1311</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Li, Simin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Looking forward to see the findings and sharing from the round table discussion and I also wonder the scale of the stake holders. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
