    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Using Computational Mapping Tools to Demonstrate the Diverse Birth Countries of New Voters in the Mary Eliza Project Dataset</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">choropleth map, computational mapping tools, digital humanities, public history, changing national boundaries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Ethnic Studies&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Global&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization&#10;Digital Storytelling&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Ethnic Studies&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The Mary Eliza Project is a public humanities initiative that illuminates the diversity of women who registered to vote in the  transcribed volumes of General Registers of Women Voters from the City of Boston (August to October 1920). This paper presentation discusses how a choropleth map of the New Voters birth countries created in Tableau Public serves the project.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The map provides an easy-to-understand  visual  to demonstrate that only 80% of the New Voters were born in the United States, with the rest born in other countries including what is now the Republic of Ireland,nations formerly controlled by Russia, and nations under colonial rule that have since gained independence. Interpretive programming around the map often includes surprise by the audience about the diversity of birth nations and is followed by a discussion of the moments of frustration and ethical decisions encountered in creating the map. This often includes a discussion of how the paid transcription team researched the recorded birthplace of the New Voter to determine the current nation reflected in the Registries. In many cases, decisions needed to be made about how to interpret the phonetic recording of the birth town by the Boston-based clerk in 1920, often hearing a town name in an unfamiliar dialect or accent. This paper presentation considers both the research labor required and the need to manipulate mapping software to create maps to demonstrate the birth nation diversity of the New Voters. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Mary Eliza Project is a public humanities initiative that illuminates the diversity of women who registered to vote in the transcribed volumes of General Registers of Women Voters from the City of Boston (August to October 1920). This paper presentation discusses how a choropleth map of the New Voters birth countries created in Tableau Public serves the project.&#10;The map provides an easy-to-understand visual to demonstrate that only 80% of the New Voters were born in the United States, with the rest born in other countries including what is now the Republic of Ireland,nations formerly controlled by Russia, and nations under colonial rule that have since gained independence. Interpretive programming around the map often includes surprise by the audience about the diversity of birth nations and is followed by a discussion of the moments of frustration and ethical decisions encountered in creating the map. This often includes a discussion of how the paid transcription team researched the recorded birthplace of the New Voter to determine the current nation reflected in the Registries. In many cases, decisions needed to be made about how to interpret the phonetic recording of the birth town by the Boston-based clerk in 1920, often hearing a town name in an unfamiliar dialect or accent. This paper presentation considers both the research labor required and the need to manipulate mapping software to create maps to demonstrate the birth nation diversity of the New Voters.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
