    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">182</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1267</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shaikh, Hina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author is presenting a paper on the creation of a choropleth map of 1920s New Voters in the City of Boston. The author will explain the series of decisions that led to the map’s creation as well as the transformation of complicated data into a mapping software. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author proposes an interesting paper that details the complicated sets of decisions to make a clear computational map. The series of methodological concerns the author cites are very relevant and important for any person within digital humanities, and especially for those who analyze or use computational mapping. &#10;&#10;While I am sure they address some or all of these concerns within the actual paper, my suggestions here begin with clearly stating the argument in terms of ethnic studies or data science/data studies. Perhaps one way to clearly connect the analysis to ethnic studies is through marking the ambiguity of unreliable data/research on ethnicities/national boundaries as a core feature within the oversimplified racial logics of the 1920s United States. I’m also excited to hear how the author intends to incorporate ambiguous data within the final paper presentation and whether the ambiguous data allows for a different engagement with computational map-making. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1305</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Elizabeth Parke, Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper grapples with the limitations between software (Tableau), archival documents, and how to ethically work between these two modes of scholarship in the context of a public DH project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The attention to the tools and methods used in the project is commendable. The importance of labour in DH projects and how to best navigate the grey areas that confront scholars in archival work is also laudable. Additional clarification is needed when referring to &quot;...discussion of the moments of frustration and ethical decisions&quot; Where were these the conversations are taking place? As part of the project&#039;s design? Or during exhibition of the digital map? Lastly, the paper abstract could more deeply attend to larger questions around the interfaces of software and archives to suggest good practices and guidance for other scholars in different fields. How might place names and their variants be captured for reuse in other projects during this era and in similar places? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
