    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">75.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">183</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1053</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Melkozernova, Arina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The project promoting AI literacy is very timely. However, the proposal is not explicit and relies on reviewing the project website, which contains assignment ideas about promoting AI literacy among numerous populations, regardless of which language they speak. The proposal shows great potential for creatively engaging a global audience. The submission can be accomplished in the time allotted (10-15 minutes).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal will address AI literacy among diverse populations regardless of their culture and language. The ideas about applying Digital Storytelling to historically diverse personas (culture, gender, and time period) connect the proposal to anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, and/or multilingualism. &#10; The relevant scholarship includes History, Science, Technology, and Society but is not discussed in the proposal. The website has a notice of a plan to design assignments that emphasize the importance of both rigorous historical research and sound citation practices.&#10;This project examines the rise of artificial intelligence (AI) and its potential implications for historical records. The first goal of this project is to promote AI literacy among numerous populations, regardless of which language they speak. The proposal does not explain the transition from the purpose to implementation.&#10;The second goal is to identify whether the Digital Humanities community can leverage AI for educational, artistic, or political purposes. – the project website has assignment ideas, but Digital Humanities methods and theories are missing from the proposal.&#10;The proposal includes an introduction outlining the purpose and objectives, the background, and expected outcomes. It advocates for a diverse audience impacted by AI. Exploring Indigenous AI at the local and global scale by including land acknowledgment (servers’ locations, etc.) is the best way to position your research as a decolonizing practice, which will make the proposal stronger. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1046</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wu, Menghang</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution of this research is to fill the gap in engaging both critical AI studies and performance studies, and the example is indeed a great research object. In addition, it contributes to AI pedagogy and can be applied in education, which has been a very surging field recently. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The idea is very interesting, could you engage with current relative scholarship more deeply? I felt you didn&#039;t articulate your idea enough here, maybe in the next version extend this research abstract more in detail. Thinking engage scholarship in media studies, performance studies and critical AI studies.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this research idea is interesting, but the author indeed need to write it better</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1315</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tratarou, Adelina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper outlines the experience of designing and publishing a digital humanities project that investigates the rise of artificial intelligence (AI) and its potential implications for the historical record. The key highlight of the project - a three-minute video featuring a deepfake Abraham Lincoln reciting the Gettysburg Address in nine different languages - will make for an innovative and engaging practical case study that conference participants will appreciate.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The primary objectives of the project are to promote AI literacy across diverse populations and to explore the ways in which the Digital Humanities community can harness AI for educational, artistic, and political purposes. This proposal effectively outlines these objectives, content, and potential impact of the project that sits at the intersection of digital humanities, history, and AI, making it a valuable contribution to this academic conference. It offers valuable insights into the use of AI in educational and cultural contexts and its potential implications for history. Some discussion on how the project might advance anti-discriminatory historical work and bring to light marginalized perspectives through increased access would enhance the paper’s relevance to the overarching themes of the conference. Additionally, it would be fascinating to learn more directly how the project will contribute to the advancement of both historical and DH scholarship on the subject. This paper will generate meaningful discussion and contribute to the ongoing discussions on the relationship between AI and digital humanities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
