    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Human Text vs. Machine Text: A Cognitive-Stylometric Perspective on Maoism, Literature, and Engineered Languages</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ideological discourse analysis, linguistic engineering, China, predictive processing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Mandarin&#10;Asia&#10;20th Century&#10;cultural analytics&#10;rhetorical analysis&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Literary studies&#10;Political science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Mandarin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cultural analytics&#10;rhetorical analysis&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Literary studies&#10;Political science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The arrival of large language models (LLMs) has provoked an urgent search for stylistic markers that could differentiate machine text from human text, but while the human-like appearance of machine text has captivated public attention, the reverse phenomenon—human text becoming machine-like—has raised much less concern. This conceptual lag is surprising given the ample historical evidence of state-backed attempts to regulate human thought. The present article leverages the predictive power of LLMs to compare the statistical properties of Maospeak, a language style that emerged during the Mao Zedong’s era in China (1949-1976), with the style of canonical modern Chinese writers, such as Eileen Chang (1920-1995) and Mo Yan (1955-). The low perplexity of Maospeak, as computed across different open-source Chinese GPT models, suggests that the impact of ideologies on language can be compared to likelihood-maximization text-generation techniques which reduce the scope of valid sequence continuations. Ideological discourse is more &quot;&lt;em&gt;n&lt;/em&gt;-gramic,&quot; featuring long, strongly lexicalized phrases which do not allow for variability in their immediate linguistic contexts. These findings have cognitive implications: whereas engineered languages such as Maospeak hijack the predictive mechanisms of human cognition by narrowing the space of linguistic possibilities, literature resists such cognitive constraints by dispersing the probability mass over multiple, equally valid paths. Exposure to diverse language data counters the influences of ideologies on our linguistically mediated perceptions of the world and increases the perplexity of our imaginations.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The arrival of large language models (LLMs) has provoked an urgent search for stylistic markers that could differentiate machine text from human text, but while the human-like appearance of machine text has captivated public attention, the reverse phenomenon—human text becoming machine-like—has raised much less concern. This conceptual lag is surprising given the ample historical evidence of state-backed attempts to regulate human thought. The present article leverages the predictive power of LLMs to compare the statistical properties of Maospeak, a language style that emerged during the Mao Zedong’s era in China (1949-1976), with the style of canonical modern Chinese writers, such as Eileen Chang (1920-1995) and Mo Yan (1955-). The low perplexity of Maospeak, as computed across different open-source Chinese GPT models, suggests that the impact of ideologies on language can be compared to likelihood-maximization text-generation techniques which reduce the scope of valid sequence continuations. Ideological discourse is more &quot;n-gramic,&quot; featuring long, strongly lexicalized phrases which do not allow for variability in their immediate linguistic contexts. These findings have cognitive implications: whereas engineered languages such as Maospeak hijack the predictive mechanisms of human cognition by narrowing the space of linguistic possibilities, literature resists such cognitive constraints by dispersing the probability mass over multiple, equally valid paths. Exposure to diverse language data counters the influences of ideologies on our linguistically mediated perceptions of the world and increases the perplexity of our imaginations.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kurzynski, Maciej</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lingnan University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Hong Kong S.A.R. (China)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">maciej.kurzynski@ln.edu.hk</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">makurz@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">maciej.kurzynski@ln.edu.hk</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kurzynski, Maciej</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">maciej.kurzynski@ln.edu.hk</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">GMT+8</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">64.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">185</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1013</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fu, Yaming</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission provides a novel cognitive-stylometric analysis of Maospeak compared to canonical modern Chinese literature, demonstrating how ideological language engineering affects linguistic variability and cognitive processes, while emphasizing the role of literature in resisting cognitive constraints imposed by such engineered languages.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is highly relevant to the conference focus, engaging with important discussions on machine and human text, ideological language, and cognitive-stylometry. It offers a clear framework and purpose, demonstrating significant applicability and value to digital humanities. However, explicit citations are not included in the abstract, which could enhance its scholarly grounding. The author could also provide more detailed descriptions of the large language models used, including specifics on the measurement of perplexity and the process of lexicalization analysis, and explain how the study contributes to our understanding of the interaction between language, cognition, and ideology.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1309</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ryan C Dubnicek, Ryan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper seeks to identify how ideological, and extrapolating, societal contexts can influence how artists speak in the written word. They study Maospeak, and its complexity in both historical and contemporary Chinese literature, reflecting on how patterns of speak shift and how outside influences can manifest in textual meaning and characteristics.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is tough, as LLMs are ever-emerging as a topic, but more engagement with other work in this realm, especially how machines influence artistic expression and how we can interpret machine study of the complexity and characteristics of language. For instance, how would an LLM trained only on period-specific sets of documents react to the texts you are analyzing, and how are other scholars interpreting LLM-powered literary study? More plainly, how much are LLMs teaching us about the language of literature as opposed to identifying trends in texts?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1280</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">LIU, Ming-Wei</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is really an excellent abstract in delivering the author’s remarkable insight: &#10;The author has well illustrated his insights to demonstrate the making of modern PRC’s general speaking the traits. Maospeak that he found to convey the secrets that mold nowadays Chinese people of their stylish patterns whether them acted similar or odd to the rest of the world. This would contribute to theoretical understanding in many ways as it turned out related to “Chinaness” in the themes.&#10;&#10;*&#10;Indeed, Mao’s speak has eliminated certain rhetorical elements, of the facts, reasoning etc while other metaphorical alterations emphasized to the audience, the population mass. Thus it may be led into a realm of wonder, as the author suggests, could it be laid in-between human language and machine-like language?  Of course, the author’s efforts shed on cognitive-stylometric analysis in terms of moaspeak or Maoism. However, if Mao’s literature to be compared to Eileen Chang, as far as to Mo Yan is another catalogue for further discussion.&#10;&#10;In the abstract, the author’s closing remark that puts &quot;Maospeak hijack the predictive mechanisms of human cognition by narrowing the space of linguistic possibilities, ... increases the perplexity of our imaginations.&quot; &#10;That reflects Maospeak has formed a language pattern on the one hand. On the other, to the author’s perplexity, that would have turned out in Aristotle’s notion, a collapse of communication. For its failing deliverance of the de fecto facts on some occasions and leading the audience’s pathematic pathos into metaphors that could be foreign to the audience’s knowledge. For example, “running into communism” is rather of a metaphorical statement than a de facto description. &#10;&#10;As Mao has created a newer manner of speak, which being able to deliver his freshly acquired of the insights transformed into certain metaphorical statements. And many furthers that some authors given, such as population mass was the term employed to confuse the decision maker’s dictatorship &#10;are found with certain possibility in Maospeak. In other words, as I will address here in my humble realization. Owing to Mao’s authoritative position, that stood superior to all, which may be the reason for his being able to validate his language in his canonical statement whereas a poetic perplexity arrayed in a parallel stance — not only in present age could also be still in Mao’s era.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is really an excellent abstract in delivering the author’s remarkable insight: &#10;The author has well illustrated his insights to demonstrate the making of modern PRC’s general speaking the traits. Maospeak that he found to convey the secrets that mold nowadays Chinese people of their stylish patterns whether them acted similar or odd to the rest of the world. This would contribute to theoretical understanding in many ways as it turned out related to “Chinaness” in the themes.&#10;&#10;Indeed, Mao’s speak has eliminated certain rhetorical elements, of the facts, reasoning etc while other metaphorical alterations emphasized to the audience, the population mass. Thus it may be led into a realm of wonder, as the author suggests, could it be laid in-between human language and machine-like language?  Of course, the author’s efforts shed on cognitive-stylometric analysis in terms of moaspeak or Maoism. However, if Mao’s literature to be compared to Eileen Chang, as far as to Mo Yan is another catalogue for further discussion.&#10;&#10;In the abstract, the author’s closing remark that puts &quot;Maospeak hijack the predictive mechanisms of human cognition by narrowing the space of linguistic possibilities, ... increases the perplexity of our imaginations.&quot; &#10;That reflects Maospeak has formed a language pattern on the one hand. On the other, to the author’s perplexity, that would have turned out in Aristotle’s notion, a collapse of communication. For its failing deliverance of the de fecto facts on some occasions and leading the audience’s pathematic pathos into metaphors that could be foreign to the audience’s knowledge. For example, “running into communism” is rather of a metaphorical statement than a de facto description. &#10;&#10;As Mao has created a newer manner of speak, which being able to deliver his freshly acquired of the insights transformed into certain metaphorical statements. And many furthers that some authors given, such as population mass was the term employed to confuse the decision maker’s dictatorship &#10;are found with certain possibility in Maospeak. In other words, as I will address here in my humble realization. Owing to Mao’s authoritative position, that stood superior to all, which may be the reason for his being able to validate his language in his canonical statement whereas a poetic perplexity arrayed in a parallel stance — not only in present age could also be still in Mao’s era.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
