    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">maciej.kurzynski@ln.edu.hk</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">makurz@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">amgilki@stanford.edu, maciej.kurzynski@ln.edu.hk</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kurzynski, Maciej</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">maciej.kurzynski@ln.edu.hk</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">GMT+8</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">90.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">186</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1013</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fu, Yaming</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission provides a nuanced understanding of state power and violence in post-1949 China by combining qualitative and quantitative methods to analyze the People’s Liberation Army Daily, showcasing how digital humanities tools can uncover new insights into historical and sociopolitical phenomena.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal focuses on the People’s Liberation Army Daily (Jiefangjun Bao) and explores the legitimation and distribution of state violence in post-1949 China. The topic intersects with postcolonial and decolonial studies, given the historical and political context of China during this period. It is highly relevant to the conference focus, engaging with multiple fields of study and offering a clear framework and purpose. &#10;To improve the proposal, the author could provide more detailed explanations of the quantitative methods and tools used, such as the specifics of the collocation analysis and the fine-tuning process of the BERT model. Besides, the author could elaborate on the sociopolitical implications of the findings, detailing how the study&#039;s insights could influence contemporary understandings of state violence and propaganda.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1275</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kilbane, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Combining close reading with quantitative analysis of representations of violence, this paper explores how state power is rhetorically legitimated in the People’s Liberation Army Daily (1956-1989). </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper exhibits a clear rationale for its research questions, an intriguing archive, a compelling methodological approach, and a well-staked sense of its relationship to the field. I would be eager to hear it! </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1125</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Isasi, Jennifer</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation will showcase an analysis of the &quot;People’s Liberation Army Daily&quot; with a combination of close reading and historical analysis with quantitative conceptuality and text mining, in particular, collocation analysis and LLM use for sentiment and topic analysis. By using these DH methods, the authors engage in conversation with the larger sociological and political studies, the fields of literature and art history. In all, they will present on their findings. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very clearly articulated proposal on using, amongst other approaches, text mining method to study historical periodicals in Chinese. I believe it will be of much value to the conference and I look forward to learning more. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
