    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Creative Futures: Techne and Artificial Intelligence in the Creative Process</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">techne, creative computing, rhetoric, digital humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital art production and analysis&#10;rhetorical analysis&#10;Art history&#10;Computer science&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital art production and analysis&#10;rhetorical analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Art history&#10;Computer science&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The idea that AI can be creative is contentious, with varied opinions among engineers and computer scientists. While engaging with these debates, my focus is on a humanities-centered approach to creativity: aesthetics, output, and affect. Rather than offering a reductionist view, I leverage my expertise in digital humanities to explore this complex topic using techne as a guide.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This presentation begins by examining the history of techne to validate its relevance in understanding AI creativity. Though linguistically similar to “technology,” techne is not interchangeable with it. Techne refers to skill, process, and means of production—attributes integral to an individual’s expertise. In contrast, technology enhances techne but remains distinct from it. For my purposes, technology serves to achieve techne, acting as a tool to enhance skills and complete processes.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;I propose shifting the question from “can computers be creative?” to “can computers act creatively?” This distinction is crucial. If creativity implies emotional self-awareness, then “being creative” is a philosophical question about translating internal emotional states—qualities unique to humans. Conversely, “acting creatively” focuses on what computers actually do. Without self-awareness or expressive capabilities, computers’ creative outputs must be evaluated based on the end product.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Thus, computers can act creatively, not by merely copying styles, but by producing aesthetically pleasing works. Examples of computers acting creatively blur the lines of creativity—robots mimicking artists by grasping paintbrushes illustrate this point. Studies show humans struggle to distinguish between human-made and AI-generated art, suggesting an inherent bias against computer-generated art despite its indistinguishability.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;As a humanist, I do not aim to fully grasp the mathematics or coding behind AI creativity. Instead, I investigate the interdisciplinary applications of AI’s creative potential, examining its ability to create meaningful art, music, and writing. This exploration highlights the unique intersection of humanities and technology in the evolving landscape of creativity.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The idea that AI can be creative is contentious, with varied opinions among engineers and computer scientists. While engaging with these debates, my focus is on a humanities-centered approach to creativity: aesthetics, output, and affect. Rather than offering a reductionist view, I leverage my expertise in digital humanities to explore this complex topic using techne as a guide.&#10;This presentation begins by examining the history of techne to validate its relevance in understanding AI creativity. Though linguistically similar to “technology,” techne is not interchangeable with it. Techne refers to skill, process, and means of production—attributes integral to an individual’s expertise. In contrast, technology enhances techne but remains distinct from it. For my purposes, technology serves to achieve techne, acting as a tool to enhance skills and complete processes.&#10;I propose shifting the question from “can computers be creative?” to “can computers act creatively?” This distinction is crucial. If creativity implies emotional self-awareness, then “being creative” is a philosophical question about translating internal emotional states—qualities unique to humans. Conversely, “acting creatively” focuses on what computers actually do. Without self-awareness or expressive capabilities, computers’ creative outputs must be evaluated based on the end product.&#10;Thus, computers can act creatively, not by merely copying styles, but by producing aesthetically pleasing works. Examples of computers acting creatively blur the lines of creativity—robots mimicking artists by grasping paintbrushes illustrate this point. Studies show humans struggle to distinguish between human-made and AI-generated art, suggesting an inherent bias against computer-generated art despite its indistinguishability.&#10;As a humanist, I do not aim to fully grasp the mathematics or coding behind AI creativity. Instead, I investigate the interdisciplinary applications of AI’s creative potential, examining its ability to create meaningful art, music, and writing. This exploration highlights the unique intersection of humanities and technology in the evolving landscape of creativity.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lacey, Kim</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Saginaw Valley State University</ss:Data></Cell>
