    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">krlacey@svsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">krlacey@svsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lacey, Kim</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">krlacey@svsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">65.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">70.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">60.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">187</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1193</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chassanoff, Alexandra</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation aims to provoke new ways for thinking about the creative endeavors of AI and the potential of humanities applications to encourage new understandings about computational expressiveness. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation uses techne as a lens for reframing arguments debating the question &quot;can computers be creative?&quot; In advocating for this shift, the presenter proposes to set the stage for an alternative - exploring the creative potential of AI by or through examination of its techne.  I think this is a compelling and important theoretical shift to engage with but given the format of the session, it will be crucial for the presenter to use 2-3 examples from digital humanities scholarship to either support this alternative framing or to clarify expected outcomes.  As it reads now, I wasn&#039;t quite sure of which direction this presentation would go in and I think examples will help the presenter find footing with the audience on these meaningful questions. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Though the presenter claims expertise in DH, there is no mention of other scholarship in the area. Specifically, I&#039;m thinking of Johanna Drucker&#039;s theoretical work on performativity and computation as creative expression. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">66</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1083</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zou, Zhihui</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission aims to provide a reframing of how we associate computers with creativity by giving more attention to the end of creativity instead of focusing solely on the intention or means.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission provides a nice reframing of &quot;creativity&quot; when most of the philosophical debates around the creativity-technology topic being the intention or means to achieve creativity. Bringing in the result and end product of creativity is something that not many discourses are considering. This submission can help in filling this gap.&#10;&#10;With that said, I do think the work could focus a bit more at developing how &quot;techne&quot;  enters the conversation. Despite that looking at &quot;computers acting creatively&quot; could be a new direction compared to &quot;is computers creative,&quot; solely focusing on this changing question might cause the discussion to be too broad without a technological perspective to help anchor it down. By pinning on one term, &quot;techne&quot;, the discussion might be better structured and producing a more actionable conclusion.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1198</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Visa, Sofia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Interesting proposal for distinguishing between (1) technology as a tool for creating music, art, writing, and (2) technology as being creative in the way humans are. The author argues that we should explore the first avenue which is proven via results produced by technology. The second [possible] trait, namely technology being self-aware the way humans are, is more difficult to explore and possibly not a concern nor a desirable achievement of technology.&#10;&#10;This is interesting, I would like to hear more, but I suspect this idea [of self-awareness in AI] has been discussed before. Therefore, a few refences would connect this remark with existing similar ideas.&#10;&#10;Where is the entire paper? I was able to read only the abstract.  &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Interesting proposal for distinguishing between (1) technology as a tool for creating music, art, writing, and (2) technology as being creative in the way humans are. The author argues that we should explore the first avenue which is proven via results produced by technology. The second [possible] trait, namely technology being self-aware the way humans are, is more difficult to explore and possibly not a concern nor a desirable achievement of technology.&#10;&#10;This is interesting, I would like to hear more, but I suspect this idea [of self-awareness in AI] has been discussed before. Therefore, a few refences would connect this remark with existing similar ideas.&#10;&#10;Where is the entire paper? I was able to read only the abstract.  </ss:Data></Cell>
