    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital Edition Pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">static sites, pedagogy, documentation, collaboration</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;scholarly editing and editions development, analysis, and methods&#10;text encoding and markup language creation, deployment, and analysis&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">scholarly editing and editions development, analysis, and methods&#10;text encoding and markup language creation, deployment, and analysis&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Education/Pedagogy&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The last few years have seen exciting advancements in the technology of digital editions. The development of CETEICean, a JavaScript library for transforming TEI into HTML Custom Elements, has lowered barriers for those looking to launch a digital edition. Coupled with static site generators and a larger ethos of minimal computing, it is now possible to conduct standards-compliant scholarly editing using a modern web stack. However, as Quinn Drombrowski points out in the DH Quarterly special issue on minimal computing, &quot;minimizing computing maximizes labor.&quot; Both technical and emotional labor are required in these collaborative digital projects. Drombrowski argues that the the benefits of these technologies are not accessible to most scholars without technical support. Stronger documentation and infrastructure is necessary. This paper offers two case studies in pedagogical infrastructure for building static site digital editions. The first is a long-term collaboration between a Romance languages scholar and a digital humanities librarian to produce a comparative edition of four different texts, a translation, and reading interface featuring a IIIF viewer. The team built their skills together over time, through techniques like pair programming, formal training through institutes, and expert consultation. The second case study covers the creation of a digital editions course for undergraduates that included book history, scholarly editing, archival research, as well as a deep dive into HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. One of the goals of this course was to get a sense of where undergraduates struggled or were particularly engaged in order to develop thorough documentation for use by others. In a world of big data and machine learning, there is still room for small handcrafted projects like digital editions. Beyond the value of the texts themselves, a static site edition can be an instructive vehicle for intentionally building new skills for all participants.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The last few years have seen exciting advancements in the technology of digital editions. The development of CETEICean, a JavaScript library for transforming TEI into HTML Custom Elements, has lowered barriers for those looking to launch a digital edition. Coupled with static site generators and a larger ethos of minimal computing, it is now possible to conduct standards-compliant scholarly editing using a modern web stack. However, as Quinn Drombrowski points out in the DH Quarterly special issue on minimal computing, &quot;minimizing computing maximizes labor.&quot; Both technical and emotional labor are required in these collaborative digital projects. Drombrowski argues that the the benefits of these technologies are not accessible to most scholars without technical support. Stronger documentation and infrastructure is necessary. This paper offers two case studies in pedagogical infrastructure for building static site digital editions. The first is a long-term collaboration between a Romance languages scholar and a digital humanities librarian to produce a comparative edition of four different texts, a translation, and reading interface featuring a IIIF viewer. The team built their skills together over time, through techniques like pair programming, formal training through institutes, and expert consultation. The second case study covers the creation of a digital editions course for undergraduates that included book history, scholarly editing, archival research, as well as a deep dive into HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. One of the goals of this course was to get a sense of where undergraduates struggled or were particularly engaged in order to develop thorough documentation for use by others. In a world of big data and machine learning, there is still room for small handcrafted projects like digital editions. Beyond the value of the texts themselves, a static site edition can be an instructive vehicle for intentionally building new skills for all participants.</ss:Data></Cell>
