    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">188</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1294</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Croxall, Brian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author will discuss the creation of digital editions in the context of two pedagogical case studies. The paper builds on recent advancements in technology, such as CETEICean. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very strong proposal to discuss the pedagogy involved in the creation of digital editions. The proposal does a lot in very little space (the latter of which is not under the control of the author, naturally) and should therefore be commended. I have a good sense of what will be discussed (two different case studies focused on the creation of digital editions). There are small references to others who are working in this space and it is clear that the author is familiar with the latest advancements in the space. Given the fact that one of the case studies focuses on comparative and translation studies (at least in part), this even is a good fit for the theme of the conference. &#10;&#10;I would definitely go out of my way to attend this talk.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1191</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Giannetti, Francesca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper presents two case studies of pedagogical approaches to digital editing with the TEI with the aim of improving documentation of minimal computing approaches in this area of practice.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author heeds Quinn Dombrowski&#039;s call for more documentation of minimal computing projects to ease the learning curve for other would-be editors/publishers. I appreciate that the two case studies involve different audiences---undergraduate students and a collaborative team comprised of a faculty member and a librarian---as well as the selection of technologies: TEI XML, HTML, CSS, JavaScript, IIIF. The treatment of a multi-lingual edition supports the conference focus. I look forward to hearing the results of this work.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1196</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Szydlowski, Nick</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Among the strengths of this proposal is its reporting back of real-world results from projects based on minimal computing principles. Having used Wax for projects myself, I think a discussion of how and when these tools are practical in production and in the classroom is overdue. In particular assessing whether the tools align in practice with the theoretical commitments and claims that inform their design would be a meaningful contribution.&#10;&#10;I also like that the proposal includes both pedagogical and research applications, as a way of identifying the strengths and weaknesses of the tools in each context. Additionally, I think highlighting JavaScript based solutions is another positive contribution, particularly as it relates to minimal computing.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a relevant and timely proposal. The comments below point out some issues I would be interested in hearing more about as you go from proposal to presentation.&#10;&#10;I might like to see the framework for assessing these tools more fleshed out in a final presentation. If minimal computing is to mature as a method, it will be important to address how minimal computing interacts with other potential commitments - for instance, in design, how does minimal computing interact with user experience design, or in pedagogy, are the skills taught through minimal computing projects the ones that most benefit students. Those are just examples, but I think it would be interesting to hear the author’s perspective on how minimal approaches complement or complicate other aspects of the projects.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
