    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Accessible Archiving: Building Multilingual Tools with Community Partners</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">community archiving, decolonial, software development, mutual aid</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital archiving&#10;Galleries and Museum studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital archiving&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Galleries and Museum studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The Archivo de Respuestas Emergencias de Puerto Rico / Emergency Response Archive of Puerto Rico (AREPR) is a collaborative digital humanities project funded by a grant from the Mellon Foundation (2020-present). AREPR employs the decolonial practice of post-custodial archiving to record stories of mutual aid organizations and individuals surviving and responding creatively to stratified disasters that have impacted the Puerto Rican archipelago in the last five years. AREPR works with grassroots community organizations across Puerto Rico to highlight and share the role of mutual aid in disaster response.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;To do so, our team has collaborated with our community partners to develop community archives, a particularly powerful tool for documenting and responding to humanitarian crises. Our approach has expanded traditional community archiving praxis, which tends to focus on collection development and management, to include the (re)design of the platforms and technologies used to house materials. In the past two years, AREPR has developed Multilingual, an Omeka S theme that is freely available for other groups to use. This theme and the corresponding Omeka S modules that we produced for AREPR simplify the process of developing and sustaining bilingual digital projects for scholars across the disciplines by providing free, easy-to-use tools for displaying archival and cultural heritage materials across languages.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Offering an exciting case study for how to utilize these innovative software extensions in digital humanities projects, this presentation will demonstrate how community-first approaches to archiving and tool development make it possible to build reciprocal relationships that allow for collaborative and mutually beneficial knowledge production. While the experiences outlined in this presentation focus on the Archivo de Respuestas Emergencias de Puerto Rico (AREPR), they also draw attention to the ways in which archival practices can be reinvented and reimagined to create new opportunities for community engagement and social activism.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Archivo de Respuestas Emergencias de Puerto Rico / Emergency Response Archive of Puerto Rico (AREPR) is a collaborative digital humanities project funded by a grant from the Mellon Foundation (2020-present). AREPR employs the decolonial practice of post-custodial archiving to record stories of mutual aid organizations and individuals surviving and responding creatively to stratified disasters that have impacted the Puerto Rican archipelago in the last five years. AREPR works with grassroots community organizations across Puerto Rico to highlight and share the role of mutual aid in disaster response.&#10;To do so, our team has collaborated with our community partners to develop community archives, a particularly powerful tool for documenting and responding to humanitarian crises. Our approach has expanded traditional community archiving praxis, which tends to focus on collection development and management, to include the (re)design of the platforms and technologies used to house materials. In the past two years, AREPR has developed Multilingual, an Omeka S theme that is freely available for other groups to use. This theme and the corresponding Omeka S modules that we produced for AREPR simplify the process of developing and sustaining bilingual digital projects for scholars across the disciplines by providing free, easy-to-use tools for displaying archival and cultural heritage materials across languages.&#10;Offering an exciting case study for how to utilize these innovative software extensions in digital humanities projects, this presentation will demonstrate how community-first approaches to archiving and tool development make it possible to build reciprocal relationships that allow for collaborative and mutually beneficial knowledge production. While the experiences outlined in this presentation focus on the Archivo de Respuestas Emergencias de Puerto Rico (AREPR), they also draw attention to the ways in which archival practices can be reinvented and reimagined to create new opportunities for community engagement and social activism.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boyles, Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">clboyles@iu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">clboyles@iu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boyles, Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">clboyles@iu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Standard Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">189</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1193</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chassanoff, Alexandra</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper shares the work undertaken by Emergency Response Archive of Puerto Rico (AREPR), a multi-disciplinary, multi-lingual project dedicated to archiving community-driven responses to disaster recovery in Puerto Rico over the last five years.  This presentation proposes to share more about the project&#039;s commitment to a community-first orientation, demonstrating the viability and value of this approach as decolonial archiving practice.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation proposes to share insights from a multi-disciplinary, community-driven, collaborative project documenting the experiences of Puerto Rican community members and mutual aid organizations as they navigate disaster events and recovery over the last five years. There are a number of strengths to the submitted contribution, with the most significant arguably being the overall importance and value of sharing perspectives from technical projects that enact decolonial practice through community-first emphases. There is a lot that could potentially be covered in this presentation, which also might be its weakness- given the wide ranging potential content in the case study, there is risk for scope creep. To avoid this, it will be important for the presenter(s) to focus on 2-3 specific areas related to archiving with a community-first orientation. For example, sharing insights with regards to successful outreach strategies for generating community partnerships or describing how a community-first orientation influenced the development of metadata in the Omeka S. template. I also think it will be useful to hear from the presenter about some of the challenges in doing this work - what kinds of pitfalls should similarly focused projects be wary of? What worked or didn&#039;t work? Finally, I would encourage the presenter to incorporate discussions of sustainability - including strategies for maintaining the artifacts and stories as well as the potential for responsible sunsetting. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">There is a lot of interesting and relevant content that can be covered in this presentation (community-first approaches in archiving; finding and sustaining community partners; development of a multilingual template in Omeka) and I think it will be important for the presenter to commit to 2-3 specific areas of case study work. I would also want to make sure their assertions about the use of postcustodial approach (rather than this just being a decolonial approach) are well-supported in the presentation - given that postcustodial archiving is a specific methodology and set of archival practices, it would be advantageous for the presenter to make sure to cover these aspects in detail from the case. However, I recognize that this is an overly nuanced comment from an archival studies scholar and that I may not be the typical ACH audience member (I don&#039;t think!)  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1311</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Li, Simin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I don&#039;t see much theoretical or methodological framework in the abstract but it must exist in the explicit practice/tool. The author may introduce the limits of the traditional archiving praxis and highlight the creativity of the tool are being used. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1289</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Traylor, Jordan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission discusses the author&#039;s construction of Multilingual, a theme for Omeka S that is tailor-made for building and maintaining bilingual digital projects. The author describes how their project moved beyond normal community archiving praxis (collection development and management) to redesign platforms for this kind of work.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper demonstrates deep relevance to the conference&#039;s theme of antiracist, Indigenous, and decolonial work in numerous ways: developing a tool out of post-custodial archiving, using that tool to facilitate bilingual archiving, and showing how a &quot;community-first&quot; archiving approach (i.e. one that is reciprocal and not transactional) can lead to these kinds of flourishing accessibilities. More accessibility can engage more communities in archiving. The use of open source platforms like Omeka and the publication of Multilingual as a free tool demonstrate the author&#039;s commitment to accessibility and reusability. This should have broad applications to DH generally, as it can empower or inspire other community archiving projects. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1</ss:Data></Cell>
