    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Enhancing Programming Historian&#039;s Multilingual Reach: Creating a Semi-Automated Multilingual DH Vocabulary Table</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Multilingualism, Translation, Journals, Pedagogical Resources, Linguistic Justice</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;text encoding and markup language creation, deployment, and analysis&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Translation studies&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">text encoding and markup language creation, deployment, and analysis&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Education/Pedagogy&#10;Translation studies&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In a digital humanities landscape dominated by English, multilingualism and translation are a major challenge for research and teaching. Over the years, various initiatives have demonstrated that providing resources in multiple languages diversifies the community and creates more just opportunities. This approach visibilizes research and communities, makes digital methodologies accessible to non-English speakers, and simultaneously enhances the understanding of technical English (Rojas Castro et al., 2019; Fiormonte, 2021; Papastamkou et al., 2021; Allés-Torrent and Rio Riande, 2020; Alves, 2021). However, translating digital humanities terminology and methods is inherently complex due to variations in tools, scientific traditions, and geolinguistic factors (Isasi et al., 2023).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Programming Historian&lt;/em&gt; publishes peer-reviewed lessons on diverse humanities themes and digital methodologies in English, Spanish, French and Portuguese (in launching order). This multilingual approach can be leveraged to significantly improve the didactic quality of the lessons (Isasi and Rojas Castro, 2021; Risam, 2018). Thus, by aligning translations of lessons to identify technical and methodological concepts and examining translation methodologies based on the origin and educational objectives of translators, we aim to create a comprehensive translation guide. This guide will be both descriptive, informing the audience about current usage and variations in translating technical and methodological concepts, and prescriptive, providing recommendations and standards for translators to follow, ensuring the consistency and readability in translations.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This paper presents the process of creating an automatically generated and human-reviewed concept table aligned across all languages. Through this vocabulary, we offer insights to enhance educational effectiveness and foster cross-linguistic understanding and visibility in digital humanities.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In a digital humanities landscape dominated by English, multilingualism and translation are a major challenge for research and teaching. Over the years, various initiatives have demonstrated that providing resources in multiple languages diversifies the community and creates more just opportunities. This approach visibilizes research and communities, makes digital methodologies accessible to non-English speakers, and simultaneously enhances the understanding of technical English (Rojas Castro et al., 2019; Fiormonte, 2021; Papastamkou et al., 2021; Allés-Torrent and Rio Riande, 2020; Alves, 2021). However, translating digital humanities terminology and methods is inherently complex due to variations in tools, scientific traditions, and geolinguistic factors (Isasi et al., 2023).&#10;Programming Historian publishes peer-reviewed lessons on diverse humanities themes and digital methodologies in English, Spanish, French and Portuguese (in launching order). This multilingual approach can be leveraged to significantly improve the didactic quality of the lessons (Isasi and Rojas Castro, 2021; Risam, 2018). Thus, by aligning translations of lessons to identify technical and methodological concepts and examining translation methodologies based on the origin and educational objectives of translators, we aim to create a comprehensive translation guide. This guide will be both descriptive, informing the audience about current usage and variations in translating technical and methodological concepts, and prescriptive, providing recommendations and standards for translators to follow, ensuring the consistency and readability in translations.&#10;This paper presents the process of creating an automatically generated and human-reviewed concept table aligned across all languages. Through this vocabulary, we offer insights to enhance educational effectiveness and foster cross-linguistic understanding and visibility in digital humanities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
