    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">j.isasi@psu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">matthias.gille-levenson@ens-lyon.fr, celian.ringwald@inria.fr, marie.flesch@gmail.com, j.isasi@psu.edu, riva.quiroga@uc.cl, david.valentine@umontreal.ca, sofia.papastamkou@uni.lu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Flesch, Marie;&#10;Isasi, Jennifer;&#10;Quiroga, Riva</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">marie.flesch@gmail.com;&#10;j.isasi@psu.edu;&#10;riva.quiroga@uc.cl</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">190</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1018</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Monzó-Nebot, Esther</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract addresses a critical issue in the field of digital humanities: the dominance of English and the challenges posed by multilingualism and translation. It focuses on the multilingual terminology used by Programming Historian.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract addresses a critical issue in the field of digital humanities: the dominance of English and the challenges posed by multilingualism and translation. The emphasis on diversifying resources to create equitable opportunities and making digital methodologies accessible to non-English speakers underscores the relevance and significance of this research. This aligns well with the current push towards inclusivity and accessibility in academia.&#10;&#10;The proposed creation of a comprehensive &quot;translation guide&quot; through aligning translations of lessons is promising. However, there is a lack of clarity about the methods and overall goal: “examining translation methodologies based on the origin and educational objectives of translators, we aim to create a comprehensive translation guide.” The project appears to focus on creating a multilingual glossary, yet there is no further explanation about the “origin and educational objectives of translators.” Have the researchers conducted interviews with the translators working for Programming Historian? Why are their origin and educational objectives, rather than their experience in different environments or engagement with academic work, considered relevant? What specific information will be drawn from their origin and educational objectives to inform the final &quot;translation guide&quot;? Why is the journal&#039;s selection and editing of translators not considered in the research? What guidelines will be provided beyond purportedly equivalent terms and usage?&#10;&#10;The proposal, although interesting, risks conflating terminological and translational research. A clearer specification of methods and translation-specific aspects would enhance the proposal. A translation-specific framework, such as Toury&#039;s translational norms, may help refocus the proposal within the field of translation studies. Otherwise, the proposal seems to be framed more as multilingual terminology development rather than translation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">66</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1252</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Priani Saiso, Ernesto</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Translating technical concepts of digital humanities from English to other languages involves a significant linguistic and conceptual challenge for the multilingual diversification of DH. The proposal presents the process of generating a table of concepts translated into the four languages in which the Programming Historian operates to create a vocabulary that standardizes and facilitates teaching digital humanities in various languages.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Programming Historian is one of the most important multilingual pedagogical resources in global DH. The development of a multilingual vocabulary of methodological and technical concepts in DH is significant work both conceptually and linguistically. In this sense, I believe that the presentation should show not only the process but also the discussions it generates, to better understand the conceptual consequences of creating this vocabulary.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1202</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tekgürler, Merve</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission presents the translation guide project by Programming Historian, which is a part of the organizations efforts to increase the availability of multilingual resources in DH. They created a comprehensive translation guide of concepts and technical terms, aligned across English, Spanish, French and Portuguese, which are languages currently supported by the organization. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think it is a fantastic contribution and a very important topic that I am sure it will engage many people. The submission is very clear and I know what to expect as potential audience. As an active member of the multilingual DH community (and still under the influence of the DH2024 SIG meeting), I have two questions that I would like to invite the authors to engage with. &#10;One, all 4 languages of Programming Historian are quite similar languages in terms of syntax and they are rather well-resourced within the broader context of computational text analysis. How does a language with very different syntax like Turkish or Basque or Hungarian or Cherokee complicate translation of methods and concepts? What happens when common practices in an approach don&#039;t actually work for a given language? Ottoman Turkish does not really follow the assumptions of Zipfian distribution and stopwords without text normalization, so we can&#039;t do statistical topic modeling without custom pre-processing. But many method write ups about topic modeling will likely state that one can safely get rid of the top 100/some number most frequent words to create meaningful topics. This applies to more or less all agglutinative languages. How can we account for incompatibility of method and language while translating these concepts?&#10;Two, while all concepts are translatable, starting from European languages still imposes some ideas about what those concepts are meant to entail. Something as straightforward as having grammatical cases in a language is actually not that simple. If you ask someone who was educated in Turkey, Turkish has 5 cases. If you ask someone who learnt Turkish in Germany, Turkish has 6 cases. The starting point of translation matters for what a concept means. I am especially thinking about the prescriptive part of the project and how what we teach and center is very different based on the language(s) that we come from. I think it is becoming increasingly important to reflect on what it means for multilingual efforts to be coming out of European languages.&#10;I am very much looking forward to this talk!&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
