    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Is gaming resistant to enshittification? Industry trends and the indie gaming renaissance</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gaming, enshittification, digital communities, resistance, advocacy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;bibliographic analysis&#10;cultural analytics&#10;rhetorical analysis&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Game studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bibliographic analysis&#10;cultural analytics&#10;rhetorical analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Race Studies&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Game studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;There has been a surge in recent years of independent video game development; now referred to as the ‘indie game renaissance,’ an explosion of creation and digital releases from smaller studios and developers that wildly vary in aesthetic, play mechanics, and genres—in contrast with AAA game developers like Microsoft and Sony. Some of the most popular names in video games over the last decade come from indie developers: The popular Five Nights at Freddy’s horror franchise, the online multiplayer Among Us, and more recently the award-winning Baldur’s Gate 3, which relied on crowdfunding and early-access player investment to reach completion. And within the indie game renaissance, creators and publishers have been enabled to bring forward a new wave of diversity in their games, including representations of people of color, disability, and queerness, that historically have been excluded from the broader definition of gaming and the stereotypical ‘gamer.’&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;But massive mergers, like Microsoft’s $75B acquisition of Activision Blizzard in 2023, threaten the now-thriving indie game industry, and with it the innumerable diverse and varied works that indie developers afford us, and the pockets of community for marginalized gamers. What might we lose, in a world where only major publishers own the digital landscape for gaming? And, can the indie game industry, and the lessons and strategies they employ, foster resistance in gaming culture to the enshittification of video games? This preliminary analysis will seek to explore how the history of video game culture and more recent case studies suggest alternate possibilities for the future of gaming.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">There has been a surge in recent years of independent video game development; now referred to as the ‘indie game renaissance,’ an explosion of creation and digital releases from smaller studios and developers that wildly vary in aesthetic, play mechanics, and genres—in contrast with AAA game developers like Microsoft and Sony. Some of the most popular names in video games over the last decade come from indie developers: The popular Five Nights at Freddy’s horror franchise, the online multiplayer Among Us, and more recently the award-winning Baldur’s Gate 3, which relied on crowdfunding and early-access player investment to reach completion. And within the indie game renaissance, creators and publishers have been enabled to bring forward a new wave of diversity in their games, including representations of people of color, disability, and queerness, that historically have been excluded from the broader definition of gaming and the stereotypical ‘gamer.’&#10;But massive mergers, like Microsoft’s $75B acquisition of Activision Blizzard in 2023, threaten the now-thriving indie game industry, and with it the innumerable diverse and varied works that indie developers afford us, and the pockets of community for marginalized gamers. What might we lose, in a world where only major publishers own the digital landscape for gaming? And, can the indie game industry, and the lessons and strategies they employ, foster resistance in gaming culture to the enshittification of video games? This preliminary analysis will seek to explore how the history of video game culture and more recent case studies suggest alternate possibilities for the future of gaming.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
