    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Computational Gender Flailing: How Queer Identities Glitch Algorithmic Classifications</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cultural values and data, queer data, algorithmic criticism, data criticism</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Queer Studies&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;natural language processing&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Literary studies&#10;Transgender and non-binary studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;natural language processing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Queer Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Literary studies&#10;Transgender and non-binary studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Many fields challenge the idea that technology is unidirectional, apolitical, and inevitable— the idea of technological determinism (Benjamin, 2019; Winner, 1986). Cultural values mold how data is imagined, arranged, and, ultimately, used (Ruberg, 2020). Affective, embodied, and continually felt histories of oppression and power underpin our contemporary assumptions about what data is, and shapes “who counts, in what ways, and why” (Wernimont, 2018). Using two case studies, one based on a student survey and the other derived from the textual page, we ask: 1) In what ways do the repetition and repeatability of certain demographic categories contribute to the performativity of gender? and 2) How are trans identities represented by humans and interpreted by algorithmic agents? Our first case study consists of asking middle and high school students the question “Who am I?” 20 times with space for free response. Each response elicits a reflection on identity, which we built into a categorization schema and compared against school-provided demographic data. Our second study examines issues with algorithmically classifying gender identities in a common DH tool: BookNLP. BookNLP is a pipeline for entity identification and coreference optimized for book-length documents. Because BookNLP infers a referential gender classification based on pronouns, it misrepresents trans characters. Riffing on Lauren Berlant’s “genre flailing” and building on queer and trans theory scholars such as Marquis Bey, Joan Lubin, and others, we propose “computational gender flailing” as a framework for understanding how computational programs and algorithms breakdown or glitch when faced with “complex” identity markers.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Works Cited&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Berlant, L. (2018) “Genre Flailing.” Capacious: Journal for Emerging Affect Inquiry, https://doi.org/10.22387/CAP2018.16.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Ruberg, Bo (2020). “Data for queer lives: How LGBTQ gender and sexuality identities challenge norms of demographics.” Big Data and Society, https://doi.org/10.1177/2053951720933&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Wernimont J (2018) Numbered Lives: Life and Death in Quantum Media. MIT Press.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Many fields challenge the idea that technology is unidirectional, apolitical, and inevitable— the idea of technological determinism (Benjamin, 2019; Winner, 1986). Cultural values mold how data is imagined, arranged, and, ultimately, used (Ruberg, 2020). Affective, embodied, and continually felt histories of oppression and power underpin our contemporary assumptions about what data is, and shapes “who counts, in what ways, and why” (Wernimont, 2018). Using two case studies, one based on a student survey and the other derived from the textual page, we ask: 1) In what ways do the repetition and repeatability of certain demographic categories contribute to the performativity of gender? and 2) How are trans identities represented by humans and interpreted by algorithmic agents? Our first case study consists of asking middle and high school students the question “Who am I?” 20 times with space for free response. Each response elicits a reflection on identity, which we built into a categorization schema and compared against school-provided demographic data. Our second study examines issues with algorithmically classifying gender identities in a common DH tool: BookNLP. BookNLP is a pipeline for entity identification and coreference optimized for book-length documents. Because BookNLP infers a referential gender classification based on pronouns, it misrepresents trans characters. Riffing on Lauren Berlant’s “genre flailing” and building on queer and trans theory scholars such as Marquis Bey, Joan Lubin, and others, we propose “computational gender flailing” as a framework for understanding how computational programs and algorithms breakdown or glitch when faced with “complex” identity markers.&#10;Works Cited&#10;Berlant, L. (2018) “Genre Flailing.” Capacious: Journal for Emerging Affect Inquiry, https://doi.org/10.22387/CAP2018.16.&#10;Ruberg, Bo (2020). “Data for queer lives: How LGBTQ gender and sexuality identities challenge norms of demographics.” Big Data and Society, https://doi.org/10.1177/2053951720933&#10;Wernimont J (2018) Numbered Lives: Life and Death in Quantum Media. MIT Press.</ss:Data></Cell>
