    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1052</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Coghill, KáLyn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This study challenges the notion of technology as unidirectional, apolitical, and inevitable by exploring how cultural values influence data representation and usage. It uses two case studies to investigate (1) how the repetition and repeatability of demographic categories contribute to the performativity of gender and (2) how trans identities are represented and interpreted by algorithmic agents. The first case study asks middle and high school students to answer &quot;Who am I?&quot; 20 times to reflect on identity, which is then compared with existing demographic data. The second case study critiques the BookNLP tool, which misrepresents trans characters due to its reliance on pronoun-based gender classification. The study introduces “computational gender flailing,” a concept derived from queer and trans theory, to understand how algorithms struggle with complex identity markers.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The study effectively challenges technological determinism by illustrating how cultural values and histories shape data representation. It introduces the innovative concept of “computational gender flailing,” grounded in queer and trans theory, providing a fresh perspective on algorithmic limitations. The practical insights from the case studies reveal how demographic categories and algorithms influence gender identity representation. However, the findings&#039; scope and generalizability may be limited by the specific contexts of the student survey and BookNLP tool (how are you sure these students know about gender or have a comprehensive understanding of gender identities to complete the survey?). Additionally, greater methodological clarity regarding the development of the categorization schema would enhance the understanding of the first case study. Furthermore, while the critique of BookNLP is valuable, exploring alternative methods or tools to address algorithmic misrepresentation could strengthen the discussion.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1190</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Michael, Krystyna</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission explores the relationship between lived queer identities and algorithmic classifications. It looks at the ways queer identities trip up and complicate classification structures within programs and projects. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical approaches to understanding data and the relationship between culture and technology are a cornerstone of digital humanities work. This paper promises to make an interesting contribution to those conversations and does a great job of situating itself within the theoretical literature. I suggest the authors be sure to explain the selection of studies and their relevance to each other as a pair, as that is not immediately evident in the proposal. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1277</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karlin, Jojo</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission uses two case studies to address how repetition and repeatability of demographic categories enable gender performance and to assess how human trans identities are algorithmically interpreted. By examining a qualitative survey of high school students beside gender categories assigned by BookNLP, the authors propose a concept of &quot;computational gender flailing.&quot;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">By comparing a schema drawn from collected data about identity and statistically assigned categories used in a readily available tool, the authors of this paper will find great discussion and interest at ACH. As disparate as the objects and methods of study in the two cases, the combination of methods under a theoretical frame may prove generative. &#10;&#10;One area to consider addressing is how data about trans identity is used once gathered, like visibility or legislative action? Is there a responsible way to categorize that provides any meaningful basis of comparison? Does the defiance of categories play into the analysis? And does the risk of replicating categories outweigh the impulse to understand categories?&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
