    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Book digitization from the ground up: Creating a corpus for text analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digitization, text analysis, corpus, NLP, OCR</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;natural language processing&#10;optical character recognition and handwriting recognition&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;natural language processing&#10;optical character recognition and handwriting recognition</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This poster will report on the progress of a book digitization project begun in 2020 which has the end goal of becoming an online text analysis corpus for use by researchers. Initiated during a substantial book weeding project at Middle Tennessee State University’s Walker Library from 2019-2020, the titles selected for digitization had a pre-1925 copyright and were in the subject areas of education and psychology. To date, over 950 print holdings have been scanned and digitized using the optical character recognition (OCR) engine Tesseract. These images were later analyzed through natural language processing (NLP) tools such as n-gram models, named entity recognition (NER), and transformer-based models. This effort has produced a list of the highest confidence topics and named entities for each book, and this listing will aid researchers as a pathfinder to each book’s most salient topics. The poster will feature a chronological summary of each phase of the project, highlighting lessons learned, and will discuss future research implications of the project.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This poster will report on the progress of a book digitization project begun in 2020 which has the end goal of becoming an online text analysis corpus for use by researchers. Initiated during a substantial book weeding project at Middle Tennessee State University’s Walker Library from 2019-2020, the titles selected for digitization had a pre-1925 copyright and were in the subject areas of education and psychology. To date, over 950 print holdings have been scanned and digitized using the optical character recognition (OCR) engine Tesseract. These images were later analyzed through natural language processing (NLP) tools such as n-gram models, named entity recognition (NER), and transformer-based models. This effort has produced a list of the highest confidence topics and named entities for each book, and this listing will aid researchers as a pathfinder to each book’s most salient topics. The poster will feature a chronological summary of each phase of the project, highlighting lessons learned, and will discuss future research implications of the project.</ss:Data></Cell>
