    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A skills-based approach to creating sustainable DH websites with Quarto</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">open source, website, quarto, minimal computing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This talk discusses the use of Quarto to create sustainable Digital Humanities websites. Quarto is an open-source publishing tool based on Markdown that enables the integration of text and Python, R, Julia, and Observable code to create presentations, dashboards, articles, books, and websites. This talk will show the process for creating Digital Humanities websites using Quarto through the experience of teaching a Master&#039;s level course on Public History and Digital Humanities. During a semester long course, students with minimal Digital Humanities experience upon entering the course created Quarto websites for their final projects. The use of Quarto provided an opportunity for an emphasis on open-source tools and technical skills. Students learned Markdown, how to navigate the command line, git, and R on the path to making websites published through GitHub Pages. The talk will focus on the significance given to learning skills over a project-based approach. The use of well documented, widely used, open-source tools makes Quarto websites a sustainable way for students and scholars to publicize their scholarship through a process in which they maintain control. This places the power in the hands of individuals and scholars, while minimizing techical dependencies that harm the sustainability of Digital Humanities websites.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This talk discusses the use of Quarto to create sustainable Digital Humanities websites. Quarto is an open-source publishing tool based on Markdown that enables the integration of text and Python, R, Julia, and Observable code to create presentations, dashboards, articles, books, and websites. This talk will show the process for creating Digital Humanities websites using Quarto through the experience of teaching a Master&#039;s level course on Public History and Digital Humanities. During a semester long course, students with minimal Digital Humanities experience upon entering the course created Quarto websites for their final projects. The use of Quarto provided an opportunity for an emphasis on open-source tools and technical skills. Students learned Markdown, how to navigate the command line, git, and R on the path to making websites published through GitHub Pages. The talk will focus on the significance given to learning skills over a project-based approach. The use of well documented, widely used, open-source tools makes Quarto websites a sustainable way for students and scholars to publicize their scholarship through a process in which they maintain control. This places the power in the hands of individuals and scholars, while minimizing techical dependencies that harm the sustainability of Digital Humanities websites.</ss:Data></Cell>
