    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Technological Advancements and the Erosion of Free Speech: An Analysis of the Language of State-Controlled Digital Surveillance in Egypt</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">International law, surveillance, Egypt</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Arabic&#10;Arab and Arab American Studies&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Africa&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;scholarly editing and editions development, analysis, and methods&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Law and legal studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Arabic</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Africa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;scholarly editing and editions development, analysis, and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Arab and Arab American Studies&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Law and legal studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In the context of rapid societal and technological transformations, the intersection of digital surveillance and freedom of speech has become a critical area of concern, particularly in regions experiencing political turbulence due to post colonial struggle. This paper examines how technological advancements in Egypt are leveraged to control and restrict freedom of speech. Through a multidisciplinary approach, this study explores the ramifications of state-controlled digital technologies on civil liberties, considering the broader implications of an infrastructure built by colonial histories, and analyzing the ways that cybercrime law is used as a tool for digital surveillance.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;By analyzing the language of Egypt&#039;s cybercrime law of 2018, the paper delves into the mechanisms of digital surveillance, assessing their role in curbing dissent and monitoring public discourse. The research highlights the challenges faced by activists, journalists, and citizens in navigating an increasingly controlled digital environment.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The paper highlights the need for robust discussions on the ethical deployment of AI and digital tools, advocating for policies that protect free speech while addressing the complexities of digital governance. This paper contributes to the broader discourse on digital media in the SWANA region, digital public humanities, and humanistic approaches to data law, offering insights into the role of digital technologies in shaping governance.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In the context of rapid societal and technological transformations, the intersection of digital surveillance and freedom of speech has become a critical area of concern, particularly in regions experiencing political turbulence due to post colonial struggle. This paper examines how technological advancements in Egypt are leveraged to control and restrict freedom of speech. Through a multidisciplinary approach, this study explores the ramifications of state-controlled digital technologies on civil liberties, considering the broader implications of an infrastructure built by colonial histories, and analyzing the ways that cybercrime law is used as a tool for digital surveillance.&#10;By analyzing the language of Egypt&#039;s cybercrime law of 2018, the paper delves into the mechanisms of digital surveillance, assessing their role in curbing dissent and monitoring public discourse. The research highlights the challenges faced by activists, journalists, and citizens in navigating an increasingly controlled digital environment.&#10;The paper highlights the need for robust discussions on the ethical deployment of AI and digital tools, advocating for policies that protect free speech while addressing the complexities of digital governance. This paper contributes to the broader discourse on digital media in the SWANA region, digital public humanities, and humanistic approaches to data law, offering insights into the role of digital technologies in shaping governance.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shaarawi, Jihan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jshaarawi@ucdavis.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jihan.shaarawi@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jshaarawi@ucdavis.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shaarawi, Jihan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jshaarawi@ucdavis.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pacific Standard Time (PST)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">64.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">199</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1139</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">van Zaanen, Menno</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission aims to dive into the relationship between the language of Egypt&#039;s cybercrime law and its impact on freedom of speech. In particular, it focuses on the use of digital surveillance in the context of controlling and restricting freedom of speech.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I believe the research described is interesting and highly relevant, especially given the current situation where digital surveillance is becoming relatively cheap and with the increased effectiveness of artificial intelligence approaches in surveillance (which has its own biases which may have a negative effect). Limiting the scope to Egypt is fine as it provides a specific case, which can potentially be generalized to other regions.&#10;&#10;What I believe can be made stronger is a more explicit description of the methodology.  The submission mentions a &quot;multidisciplinary approach&quot;, but it is unclear what disciplines are involved.  In the same line, it is a bit unclear what &quot;analyzing the language of Egypt&#039;s cybercrime law&quot; really means.  Is this going to be a linguistic analysis or an analysis more from a legal perspective?  How is this analysis linked to the impact (or influence) of the law on the limitation of freedom of speech?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1295</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lindblad, Purdom</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author examines the parallel development of digital surveillance and challenges to freedom of speech. Through the analysis of Egypt&#039;s 2018 cybercrime law, the author analyses the tools of digital surveillance and the use of such tools to monitor and limit public discourse. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author outlines the challenges and stakes of digital surveillance&#039;s monitoring and suppression of public discourse. The framing and significance of the topic is excellent. Centering the talk on Egypt&#039;s 2018 cybercrime law will keep the talk grounded even as it engages the spirals of related topics - AI, challenges faced by different public actors (activists, journalists, citizens), policy work, and digital governance. This is a huge - and critical topic - with significant contributions to public humanities, data law, and digital tools. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1310</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Alvarez, Maira Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper examines how technological advancements in Egypt are leveraged to control and restrict freedom of speech. Through a multidisciplinary approach, this study explores the ramifications of state-controlled digital technologies on civil liberties, considering the broader implications of an infrastructure built by colonial histories, and analyzing the ways that cybercrime law is used as a tool for digital surveillance.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract presents an important topic that various countries/communities are facing when it comes to surveillance and the integration of technologies to perform the monitoring of masses, groups, individuals, etc. This work would be great for discussions at ACH 2024 regarding AI and cybercrime law(s).&#10;&#10;Here are some recommendations to strengthen the abstract and presentation if accepted.&#10;&#10;The abstract does not mention what are the multidisciplinary approaches to the study. &#10;&#10;One of the goals mentioned is to examine technological advancements, but other than AI, there is no mention of specific technologies that contribute to this control. I suggest the author considers this so readers can identify some of the technologies that contribute to this control, especially if it’s being connected to a cybercrime law.&#10;&#10;The author mentions that “the paper delves into the mechanisms of digital surveillance, assessing their role in curbing dissent and monitoring public discourse.” I recommend the author to include the “How” this monitoring takes place. Is it using AI to gather facial recognition data through surveillance cameras, store personal information from private and public institutions, etc.? A line would suffice to clear this statement.&#10;&#10;Towards the end, the abstract mentions that this work “contributes to the broader discourse on digital media in the SWANA region.” It would be useful to include the “Why” in this particular region to clarify and highlight the importance/urgency/contribution. Again, a line would suffice. &#10;&#10;Overall is a great proposal that opens much-needed conversations.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">None</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
