    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The poisoned well: Tracking text reuse in trans-antagonistic legislation</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">natural language processing, text reuse, government transparency, law, transgender rights</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;attribution studies and stylometric analysis&#10;data publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Law and legal studies&#10;Political science&#10;Transgender and non-binary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">attribution studies and stylometric analysis&#10;data publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Law and legal studies&#10;Political science&#10;Transgender and non-binary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In March 2023, a corpus of communications between legislators and lobbyists, principally regarding two attempts to pass transgender youth transition treatment bans in 2019, was made available to academics and journalists. This study investigates the degree to which the language refined in these communications has influenced trans-antagonistic bills proposed in the United States between 2019 and 2024, using sequence-alignment detection algorithms.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Text reuse methods have been successfully deployed to trace the flow and diffusion of policy ideas in legislatures through bill-to-bill and model-legislation-to-bill comparisons. This study builds on existing work by categorically expanding the source corpus to include non-legislative documents, such as correspondences, through which political and legal ideology can be disseminated. By tracing parallel passages from communications to bills, we identify cases where a small set of coordinated actors directly shaped state and federal laws with respect to transgender rights: preliminary results for a sample of the bills (&lt;em&gt;N&lt;/em&gt; = 190 bills) show 94 passage pairs that indicate meaningful borrowings between the corpora.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;We intend to expand the target corpus to include all trans-antagonistic legislation matching the above criteria. Furthermore, the correspondences, bills, and resultant detected reuses will be integrated into a publicly-available database with search, browse, and visualization functionality; our aim is to provide a high-quality, accessible repository of the bills’ contents, as well as an interpretable visualization of detected reuses, for researchers working on queer policy and advocacy, dehumanization research, systemic transphobia, and other social justice issues.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In March 2023, a corpus of communications between legislators and lobbyists, principally regarding two attempts to pass transgender youth transition treatment bans in 2019, was made available to academics and journalists. This study investigates the degree to which the language refined in these communications has influenced trans-antagonistic bills proposed in the United States between 2019 and 2024, using sequence-alignment detection algorithms.&#10;Text reuse methods have been successfully deployed to trace the flow and diffusion of policy ideas in legislatures through bill-to-bill and model-legislation-to-bill comparisons. This study builds on existing work by categorically expanding the source corpus to include non-legislative documents, such as correspondences, through which political and legal ideology can be disseminated. By tracing parallel passages from communications to bills, we identify cases where a small set of coordinated actors directly shaped state and federal laws with respect to transgender rights: preliminary results for a sample of the bills (N = 190 bills) show 94 passage pairs that indicate meaningful borrowings between the corpora.&#10;We intend to expand the target corpus to include all trans-antagonistic legislation matching the above criteria. Furthermore, the correspondences, bills, and resultant detected reuses will be integrated into a publicly-available database with search, browse, and visualization functionality; our aim is to provide a high-quality, accessible repository of the bills’ contents, as well as an interpretable visualization of detected reuses, for researchers working on queer policy and advocacy, dehumanization research, systemic transphobia, and other social justice issues.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
