    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">91.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">200</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1026</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kerns, Halie Morgan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Main contributions include new methods, models, corpora, and data for studying anti-trans legislation. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is very relevant to the conference focus and would add significant value to the field of study. It is an innovative approach, and I believe conference go-ers would benefit greatly from hearing about the process and outcomes. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1321</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Yang, Funing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper presents an investigation on the language being communicated that influenced the trans-antagonistic bills between 2019 and 2024 with sequence-alignment detection algorithms, as well as contribution to a public database. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper presents a clearly formulated proposal with the algorithms employed in the study as well as the corpus and has a strong relevance to the conference theme and overall digital humanities efforts on queer studies. To make the proposal even stronger, there could be a clearer argument on the &quot;why&quot; of the project. Would love to hear more about the algorithms and the corpus being used in the study in the conference. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1327</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Regan, Amanda</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an incredibly important submission that uses text reuse algorithms to study the proliferation of trans-antagonistic legislation. It expands on previous studies using text reuse to study legislation by also including non-legislative documents where ideology is more readily disseminated. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is an incredibly strong abstract and important submission. I have two specific pieces of feedback. 1) The authors say, &quot;Text reuse methods have been successfully deployed to trace the flow and diffusion of policy ideas in legislatures through bill-to-bill and model-legislation-to-bill comparisons. This study builds on existing work by categorically expanding the source corpus to include non-legislative documents, such as correspondences, through which political and legal ideology can be disseminated.&quot; This is fascinating. Is the existing work you reference work specifically on text reuse as a methodology, or is there other work looking specifically at transphobic legislation, and the contribution here is to apply it to a broader corpus beyond just legislative documents? Either way, this is an important study, but I think this point and your contribution could be made a little clearer. 2) I want to know more about your corpus. Where does the correspondence come from? What states are you pulling information from, and what are the outlines of your collection guidelines?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
