    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">“Speculative Pedagogy with Twine”</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">critical digital pedagogy, hypertext narrative, speculation</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;Asia&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Game studies&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing&#10;Digital Storytelling&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia&#10;Europe&#10;North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;Digital Storytelling&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Game studies&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Since the open-access hypertext narrative platform Twine (twinery.org) was released in 2009, it has been consistently applied as a teaching tool in diverse, academic and non-academic communities. It has received, however, only sparse critical attention for its utility in classroom communities (Salter and Moulthrop 2021). Indeed, the under representation of Twine in theories of DH pedagogy reveals another need in this scholarly field: to consider the ways that media specificity of teaching tools might shape pedagogy.&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This paper presentation is occasioned by the authors’ work as editors on a collection, &lt;em&gt;EnTwine: A Critical and Creative Companion to Teaching With Twine&lt;/em&gt;, currently under advance contract, which features authors from library sciences, humanities, fine arts, elementary education, rhetoric and composition, traditional and computer sciences, industrial practice, GLAM, professional game design, and university administration. These contributors write from contexts as diverse as the Global South and the Global North, marginalized activist communities and university classrooms. From this experience, we theorize Twine as a speculative pedagogical tool, drawing from critical making and public and critical pedagogy. Twine offers what Jentery Sayers calls a “tendency towards speculation” (8), towards new ways of building, accessing, and disseminating knowledge, and new ways of imagining the world around us. Twine can reveal the speculative foundations of critical pedagogy itself, which Tomas Boronski articulates as “a utopian spirit of thinking of the world differently” (22). Speculation with and in Twine combines many different kinds of interactions—with technology, with process, with communities.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Since the open-access hypertext narrative platform Twine (twinery.org) was released in 2009, it has been consistently applied as a teaching tool in diverse, academic and non-academic communities. It has received, however, only sparse critical attention for its utility in classroom communities (Salter and Moulthrop 2021). Indeed, the under representation of Twine in theories of DH pedagogy reveals another need in this scholarly field: to consider the ways that media specificity of teaching tools might shape pedagogy.&#10;This paper presentation is occasioned by the authors’ work as editors on a collection, EnTwine: A Critical and Creative Companion to Teaching With Twine, currently under advance contract, which features authors from library sciences, humanities, fine arts, elementary education, rhetoric and composition, traditional and computer sciences, industrial practice, GLAM, professional game design, and university administration. These contributors write from contexts as diverse as the Global South and the Global North, marginalized activist communities and university classrooms. From this experience, we theorize Twine as a speculative pedagogical tool, drawing from critical making and public and critical pedagogy. Twine offers what Jentery Sayers calls a “tendency towards speculation” (8), towards new ways of building, accessing, and disseminating knowledge, and new ways of imagining the world around us. Twine can reveal the speculative foundations of critical pedagogy itself, which Tomas Boronski articulates as “a utopian spirit of thinking of the world differently” (22). Speculation with and in Twine combines many different kinds of interactions—with technology, with process, with communities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Murphy, Emily Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of British Columbia-Okanagan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">emily.murphy@ubc.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">emily.murphy@ubc.ca, lai-tze.fan@uwaterloo.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Murphy, Emily Christina;&#10;Fan, Lai-Tze</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">emily.murphy@ubc.ca;&#10;lai-tze.fan@uwaterloo.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">PST and EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">70.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">201</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1245</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sempere, Anindita Basu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Using Twine in a classroom context as a tool for speculation and to engage in critical pedagogy through practice.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The forthcoming collection sounds really fascinating given the diversity of contributors and pedagogical contexts. There have been various presentations on classroom uses of Twine at past DH conferences, and it would be valuable to look at patterns and possibilities at a larger scale.&#10;&#10;I&#039;d be particularly interested in hearing about the different contexts in which these tools have been used and to see examples of projects or assignments that demonstrate both new ways of building knowledge and student engagement with critical pedagogy as a concept.&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1232</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Faerber-Ovaska, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal describes the use of the hypertext narrative platform “Twine” as a teaching tool. The authors, drawing on their editorial work for a soon-to-be published collection, make a case for Twine&#039;s potential as a tool for speculative pedagogy. They emphasize Twine&#039;s ability to foster critical and creative thinking by allowing students to interact with technology and narrative in new ways, and its potential affordances in diverse educational contexts, from the Global South to university classrooms. The authors promise to share practical exercises and theoretical insights on integrating Twine into digital humanities education in their presentation. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very interesting proposal. Personally, I&#039;m a fan of social annotation as a way to enable students to interact with and talk back to a text. Twine seems like a relative of SA, but maybe also like the inverse: instead of enabling interaction with others&#039; work, is it a way to enable the *public* to interact with and shape their experience of one&#039;s own work? I need to learn more about it! I&#039;d like to attend this presentation.&#10;&#10;If I were in the audience of your presentation, I&#039;d want to learn about how to manage my students&#039; learning curve for using Twine. And I&#039;d be curious to learn more about who the typical readers and interactors are for this platform. My only reservation is that based on a preliminary tour of the Twine platform, it appears the learning curve for students to adopt and use Twine could be pretty steep. That might limit the kinds of students and classrooms this approach would work for. But, after all, a conference is a place for new and cutting-edge ideas to be shared, so maybe that issue is not a problem.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1278</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Minot, Casie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission offers unique look at a Twine as a medium for speculation, one that has gone understudied in its use in students&#039; cultivation of knowledge and imagination in the classroom environment. The submission then gestures an exciting new avenue for research, particularly how specific media tools, like Twine, inform pedagogy.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission eloquently outlines its exigence, the specific facet of the tool the authors wish to explore through the presentation, and how this finding might impact current scholarship on digital media&#039;s impact on pedagogy. Overall, this is a strong submission that should excite scholars interested between the relationship between digital media and pedagogy in theory and in classroom praxis.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
