    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Design Studio: Towards Repair/Refusal in the Digital Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">design, design thinking, digital archives, reparative practices, digital reparative archives</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;digital archiving&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;Design studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;digital archiving&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Design studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Even as we conducted our Design Studio at the ACH2023 virtual conference, we were aware of the instinct towards and failure of repair. Nurturing the energy and offerings of the 2023 roundtable, the 2023/2024 ASU Design Studio Cohort, and our current Working Group on reparative digital archives, this is what we have learned: We move towards repair by building new infrastructure that supports access and promotes social joy. We mobilize proactively, instead of reactively, to emergent events that need archiving, such as SUCHO and Torn Apart/Separados. We experiment with reparative practices by stewarding meaningful ephemera beyond the material (conversation, movement, embodied actions).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Yet, war, gun violence, wildfires, heat waves, the continuing legacy and impacts of racism, and the onset of novel, global pandemics have forced us to confront the limits of repair. One emergent lesson: repair is not always possible. ‘The knife-edge of compassion’ can be refusal. Our institutions continue to rush us back to “pre-pandemic normal,” and our workplaces push us to restore a world that never existed. In these moments, refusal to reproduce and sanction infrastructures of social misery offers opportunities to connect in solidarity and resistance (Sutherland et al., 2023; Boyles et al., 2023). Refusal in digital humanities is broadly theorized as a strategy to hold multiplicity in harmony, to represent and respect difference, autonomy, and collective power. What would it mean to move beyond restoration and integrate refusal as a guiding principle of DH work? &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This 1 hour and 30-minute alternative format experience will explore the possibilities and challenges of refusal within reparative digital practices. This will be a speculative exercise in design, repair &amp; refusal, and generating insights through iterative collaboration. By adapting the Lincoln Center for Applied Ethics Design Studio Model, we infuse a community-centered, embodied mode of knowledge production into a traditional mode of knowledge production: the academic conference. We seek to surface and collectively address questions such as: What does it mean to engage in refusal? How does refusal shape our relationality with ourselves, our communities, and our environment? How does refusal offer capaciousness in the face of the unrepairable?  How can we engage refusal in a world that constantly seeks compliance and conformity? &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The structure of this offering will consist of conversational “movements” that first invoke divergent ideas and stories from participants, and then trace convergent themes and aspirational questions. The first movement will reflect on the benefits and limitations of repair to illuminate the connections between repair and refusal. The second movement will invite participants to reflect on the relationship between repair and refusal: how is refusal embodied in practices of repair; when do they fail; and what potential might these opportunities and reckonings have? The third movement will hold space for converging concepts from the previous two movements to guide digital practices of repair and refusal. Facilitators Boyles, Grumbach, and Lindblad will lead the exercises and capture audience members&#039; contributions to produce a digital record of “refusal” at ACH2024.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Even as we conducted our Design Studio at the ACH2023 virtual conference, we were aware of the instinct towards and failure of repair. Nurturing the energy and offerings of the 2023 roundtable, the 2023/2024 ASU Design Studio Cohort, and our current Working Group on reparative digital archives, this is what we have learned: We move towards repair by building new infrastructure that supports access and promotes social joy. We mobilize proactively, instead of reactively, to emergent events that need archiving, such as SUCHO and Torn Apart/Separados. We experiment with reparative practices by stewarding meaningful ephemera beyond the material (conversation, movement, embodied actions).&#10;Yet, war, gun violence, wildfires, heat waves, the continuing legacy and impacts of racism, and the onset of novel, global pandemics have forced us to confront the limits of repair. One emergent lesson: repair is not always possible. ‘The knife-edge of compassion’ can be refusal. Our institutions continue to rush us back to “pre-pandemic normal,” and our workplaces push us to restore a world that never existed. In these moments, refusal to reproduce and sanction infrastructures of social misery offers opportunities to connect in solidarity and resistance (Sutherland et al., 2023; Boyles et al., 2023). Refusal in digital humanities is broadly theorized as a strategy to hold multiplicity in harmony, to represent and respect difference, autonomy, and collective power. What would it mean to move beyond restoration and integrate refusal as a guiding principle of DH work? &#10;This 1 hour and 30-minute alternative format experience will explore the possibilities and challenges of refusal within reparative digital practices. This will be a speculative exercise in design, repair &amp; refusal, and generating insights through iterative collaboration. By adapting the Lincoln Center for Applied Ethics Design Studio Model, we infuse a community-centered, embodied mode of knowledge production into a traditional mode of knowledge production: the academic conference. We seek to surface and collectively address questions such as: What does it mean to engage in refusal? How does refusal shape our relationality with ourselves, our communities, and our environment? How does refusal offer capaciousness in the face of the unrepairable? How can we engage refusal in a world that constantly seeks compliance and conformity? &#10;The structure of this offering will consist of conversational “movements” that first invoke divergent ideas and stories from participants, and then trace convergent themes and aspirational questions. The first movement will reflect on the benefits and limitations of repair to illuminate the connections between repair and refusal. The second movement will invite participants to reflect on the relationship between repair and refusal: how is refusal embodied in practices of repair; when do they fail; and what potential might these opportunities and reckonings have? The third movement will hold space for converging concepts from the previous two movements to guide digital practices of repair and refusal. Facilitators Boyles, Grumbach, and Lindblad will lead the exercises and capture audience members&#039; contributions to produce a digital record of “refusal” at ACH2024.</ss:Data></Cell>
