    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">93.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">202</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1265</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Arbuckle, Alyssa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission proposes a longer, facilitated, participatory session (&quot;design studio&quot;) on the topic of refusal in DH and the broader socioeconomic  / -political contexts the field operates in. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed session on refusal in DH and academia more broadly is sure to be of interest to ACH attendees. The content is timely and relevant to the aims of the conference as well as to pressing discussions happening inside and beyond academia. This session is sure to provoke challenging but important conversations about the role of DH and its practitioners in the wider world, including the ways we communicate and structure our work, and how we are developing our field culturally. Facilitating a session such as this virtually will likely bear its own challenges around trust-building, connection, and communal emotional regulation, but that is not a reason to not pursue this important work. If not already intended, it would be useful to bring in the work of Natalie Loveless, namely her work on &quot;generative refusal&quot; in How to Make Art at the End of the World: a Manifesto for Research-Creation.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1017</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Donea, Magdalena</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A 90-minute semi-structured &quot;speculative exercise&quot; in which collaborative refusal is instrumentalized in the context of an academic conference, thereby leading to new insights and potential new practices of engaging with academic work more mindfully and care-fully. As a practical exercise it is difficult to summarize the contribution of this session just yet, although how it plays out will be interesting and hopefully engaging.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Although this may be a limitation of the space available for an abstract, I am curious about the term &quot;refusal&quot; and whether it is meant here in its popular/colloquial sense, or in the more specific sense deriving from e.g., Indigenous Studies (Audra Simpson&#039;s &quot;Mohawk Interruptus&quot; (2014) comes to mind, along with associated terms such as ethnographic refusal and epistemic refusal). It would be interesting to know more about the theoretical underpinnings of the word.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I very much look forward to attending this session and hope that you will accept it.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1147</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Berger, Claudia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The role of refusal in DH and how we can make that refusal visible. Not just what we do with DH but what we choose to not do. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This sounds like such a rich activity and will be so important to have at the conference. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I really want to join this so I hope it is accepted!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
