    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Introducing Multilingual MetaNet: A cross-linguistic database of metaphors, semantic frames, and syntactic constructions across varieties of English, French, and Spanish</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">conceptual metaphor theory, frame semantics, corpus linguistics, cross-linguistic analysis, computational linguistics, ontology</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;natural language processing&#10;annotation structures, systems, and methods&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Linguistics&#10;Translation studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">database creation, management, and analysis&#10;natural language processing&#10;annotation structures, systems, and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African American/Black Studies&#10;Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Linguistics&#10;Translation studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Accurate automated metaphor identification requires ontological resources. We introduce multilingual MetaNet, a MediaWiki-based database for cross-linguistic metaphor analysis. Based on Conceptual Metaphor Theory, Frame Semantics, and Construction Grammar, its language coverage includes metaphors, frames, syntactic constructions, and example sentences for American and Mexican Spanishes; Hexagonal and Canadian Frenches; and Canadian and American Englishes, including a sub-corpus of African American English. We outline our approach to scaffolding the development of ontologies for new language varieties, which addresses both &quot;the principle that metaphor discovery can only happen over large and diverse linguistic data sets&quot; (David 2017: 575) and biases introduced &quot;by metaphor research done in English and by English linguistic resources&quot; (Despot et al. 2019: 129).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;African American English, and Canadian English and French are distinctive varieties with unique syntax and semantics, yet there is virtually no work on metaphor in these varieties; research centres on General American English, British English, and European French. Similarly, little work has been done on metaphoric variation in Latin American Spanishes, compared to the large Castilian Spanish literature. Documenting semantic and constructional variation across these languages will enable improved automated metaphor identification, translation, and cross-linguistic analysis; as well as provide a more nuanced sociolinguistic portrait of regional linguistic variation. MetaNet currently has over 16,000 example sentences comprising ~170,000 words. It provides a reference tool for linguists, translators, and others studying metaphor; and an ontological resource for improving NLP technologies for under-studied varieties. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, the dataset will be publicly available soon.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;References&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;David, O. 2017. &quot;Computational approaches to metaphor: The case of MetaNet.&quot; &lt;em&gt;The Cambridge Handbook of Cognitive Linguistics&lt;/em&gt;. 574-589.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Despot, K., et al. 2019. &quot;MetaNet.HR: Croatian metaphor repository.&quot; &lt;em&gt;Metaphor and Metonymy in the Digital Age: Theory and Methods for Building Repositories of Figurative Language.&lt;/em&gt;123-146.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Accurate automated metaphor identification requires ontological resources. We introduce multilingual MetaNet, a MediaWiki-based database for cross-linguistic metaphor analysis. Based on Conceptual Metaphor Theory, Frame Semantics, and Construction Grammar, its language coverage includes metaphors, frames, syntactic constructions, and example sentences for American and Mexican Spanishes; Hexagonal and Canadian Frenches; and Canadian and American Englishes, including a sub-corpus of African American English. We outline our approach to scaffolding the development of ontologies for new language varieties, which addresses both &quot;the principle that metaphor discovery can only happen over large and diverse linguistic data sets&quot; (David 2017: 575) and biases introduced &quot;by metaphor research done in English and by English linguistic resources&quot; (Despot et al. 2019: 129).&#10;African American English, and Canadian English and French are distinctive varieties with unique syntax and semantics, yet there is virtually no work on metaphor in these varieties; research centres on General American English, British English, and European French. Similarly, little work has been done on metaphoric variation in Latin American Spanishes, compared to the large Castilian Spanish literature. Documenting semantic and constructional variation across these languages will enable improved automated metaphor identification, translation, and cross-linguistic analysis; as well as provide a more nuanced sociolinguistic portrait of regional linguistic variation. MetaNet currently has over 16,000 example sentences comprising ~170,000 words. It provides a reference tool for linguists, translators, and others studying metaphor; and an ontological resource for improving NLP technologies for under-studied varieties. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, the dataset will be publicly available soon.&#10;References&#10;David, O. 2017. &quot;Computational approaches to metaphor: The case of MetaNet.&quot; The Cambridge Handbook of Cognitive Linguistics. 574-589.&#10;Despot, K., et al. 2019. &quot;MetaNet.HR: Croatian metaphor repository.&quot; Metaphor and Metonymy in the Digital Age: Theory and Methods for Building Repositories of Figurative Language.123-146.</ss:Data></Cell>
