    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">AVAnnotate: Curating Mutlilingual Digital Exhibits with IIIF, GitHub, and Jekyll</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Audio, Video, Archives, Annotation</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;South America&#10;Global&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;metadata standards, systems, and methods&#10;annotation structures, systems, and methods&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Media studies&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;South America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">metadata standards, systems, and methods&#10;annotation structures, systems, and methods&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;AVAnnotate is an application and workflow, designed by Dr. Tanya Clement and Brumfield Labs, which allows users to build digital exhibits of annotated audiovisual artifacts. AVAnnotate connects open source tools for annotation (such as Audacity or PRAAT), public code and document repositories (GitHub), and the AVAnnotate web application to create and share IIIF manifests and annotations. In this workshop, we will teach participants how to use AVAnnotate to make audio and video (AV), and their interpretations, more discoverable and usable by teaching them the workflow and application components of the most recent version of the software. First, the basics of the software—creating IIIF manifests, navigating GitHub, publishing and sharing annotations using Jekyll—will be reviewed alongside innovative AVAnnotate projects that have been developed over the past year and are applicable to researchers, teachers, librarians and archivists, and students in DH. This includes a bilingual digital exhibit developed by PhD candidate Vera Burrows, entitled “Radio Venceremos, the Rebel’s Radio Station,” which features recordings from Radio Venceremos (“Radio We Will Overcome”), a popular clandestine radio station from the mountains of Morazan, El Salvador, during the eleven year Salvadoran Civil War (1981-1992). In this example, we will teach participants how to use AVAnnotate to build bilingual and multilingual digital exhibits. The second half of the workshop will be devoted to teaching the newest version of the AVAnnotate workflow through participants building their own projects with the software and having a static website of annotated AV uploaded by the end of the workshop.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This workshop is for beginners and requires no prior experience with AVAnnotate, affiliated digital tools, or audiovisual material. We only suggest that participants bring a laptop and headphones, and, optionally, their own AV material to annotate. Altogether, this workshop on AVAnnotate will share necessary information for participants to understand how the newest version of the software may aid in their current research/scholarship and the following steps for creating their own AVAnnotate project.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">AVAnnotate is an application and workflow, designed by Dr. Tanya Clement and Brumfield Labs, which allows users to build digital exhibits of annotated audiovisual artifacts. AVAnnotate connects open source tools for annotation (such as Audacity or PRAAT), public code and document repositories (GitHub), and the AVAnnotate web application to create and share IIIF manifests and annotations. In this workshop, we will teach participants how to use AVAnnotate to make audio and video (AV), and their interpretations, more discoverable and usable by teaching them the workflow and application components of the most recent version of the software. First, the basics of the software—creating IIIF manifests, navigating GitHub, publishing and sharing annotations using Jekyll—will be reviewed alongside innovative AVAnnotate projects that have been developed over the past year and are applicable to researchers, teachers, librarians and archivists, and students in DH. This includes a bilingual digital exhibit developed by PhD candidate Vera Burrows, entitled “Radio Venceremos, the Rebel’s Radio Station,” which features recordings from Radio Venceremos (“Radio We Will Overcome”), a popular clandestine radio station from the mountains of Morazan, El Salvador, during the eleven year Salvadoran Civil War (1981-1992). In this example, we will teach participants how to use AVAnnotate to build bilingual and multilingual digital exhibits. The second half of the workshop will be devoted to teaching the newest version of the AVAnnotate workflow through participants building their own projects with the software and having a static website of annotated AV uploaded by the end of the workshop.&#10;This workshop is for beginners and requires no prior experience with AVAnnotate, affiliated digital tools, or audiovisual material. We only suggest that participants bring a laptop and headphones, and, optionally, their own AV material to annotate. Altogether, this workshop on AVAnnotate will share necessary information for participants to understand how the newest version of the software may aid in their current research/scholarship and the following steps for creating their own AVAnnotate project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
