    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">trentwintermeier@utexas.edu, turnersam@utexas.edu, tclement@utexas.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wintermeier, Trent;&#10;Turner, Sam;&#10;Clement, Tanya</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">trentwintermeier@utexas.edu;&#10;turnersam@utexas.edu;&#10;tclement@utexas.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">CST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">62.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">205</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1294</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Croxall, Brian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This workshop will teach participants how to use AVAnnotate to create exhibits of annotated audio/visual materials.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I first want to say that I think it&#039;s difficult to evaluate a workshop proposal with the same framework that would be used for an individual research presentation. The rubric that I have been given is not really suited to this; consequently, the scores that I have given are lower than the quality of the proposal simply because I am being asked to score the wrong things. This is not the fault of the authors and I *do* recommend that the workshop be accepted. &#10;&#10;The proposal could be strengthened with a sentence (or even a half sentence) about the utility of annotating audiovisual materials. I realize that this may sound old-fashioned (e.g., would I ask this question about annotating poetry?), but it would help to establish the case for the workshop and make clear the audience that will be wanting to participate.&#10;&#10;I would also welcome more detail about how the workshop will happen. A lesson plan of sorts would be useful for evaluating the proposal. But that seems to fall outside the scope of what the conference organizers have asked of authors. &#10;&#10;I would have liked to see a bit more about how the presenters plan to assist people while the workshop is remote. Have they done something like this before and do they therefore know where the barriers are for participants having a good experience? I am thinking about challenges that I frequently face in workshops where participants may not, for example, know how to navigate the file structure of their own computer to access the files they were hoping to use in the workshop. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1253</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ford, Linsey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission proposes a beginner-level workshop to teach participants how to use AVAnnotate to make audio and video. Projects developed over the past year using the product will also be featured, as a way to &quot;teach participants how to use AVAnnotate to build bilingual and multilingual digital exhibits.&quot;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed workshop is relevant to digital humanities, and the open source tools and projects mentioned sound interesting and engaging.&#10;Though the workshop will feature bilingual and multilingual digital exhibits, which adheres to the conference theme, the abstract could have more clearly outlined the theoretical, methodological, or pedagogical framework of the workshop.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1319</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bago, Petra</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors introduce an intriguing tool for annotating audiovisual artifacts, which they will also demonstrate and teach for use in digital exhibits.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This workshop proposal is both timely and valuable, offering participants an excellent opportunity to learn how to effectively use AVAnnotate for creating and sharing annotated audiovisual artifacts. The hands-on approach, coupled with the use of real-world examples like the &quot;Radio Venceremos&quot; project, ensures that attendees will leave with practical skills applicable to their own research and scholarship. The accessibility of the workshop, requiring no prior experience, further enhances its appeal, making it a highly recommended addition to the conference program. I have no recommendations for improvement.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">/</ss:Data></Cell>
