    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">AI Literacy as Equity in First-Year Writing: A Year With Generative AI</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">AI Literacy, Equity, Digital Literacy, Writing, First-Year Writing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;Design studies&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Design studies&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In 2023-2024, UNC Charlotte&#039;s Writing, Rhetoric &amp; Digital Studies faculty piloted the use of generative AI tools in first-year writing courses. Our goal was to explore how students and instructors approach AI for writing and pedagogy. This lightning talk shares how we have expanded our thinking around AI tools to critically examine AI&#039;s digital literacy implications. Our model positions AI literacy as an essential component of classroom equity and in this talk we plan to share our findings around ongoing development of ethical, cultural, and equity-based frameworks for students that help them understand what AI tools are, how they work, and what using them means. Our lightning talk will highlight several key focal points of our work with generative AI tools in FYW including the qualitative data we collected, patterns of student AI usage, crucial considerations about the environmental impact of AI use, supporting faculty as they integrate AI into their teaching pedagogy and building collaborative AI use models with students. This approach creates a literacy-as-equity framework by understanding the technology&#039;s workings, implications, and collaborative possibilities. Moving beyond just using AI tools, we hope to empower students and faculty to critically navigate this emerging space through an equity-driven literacy framework and the outcome of the pilot program has provided key insights into how this goal can be achieved through critical and careful implementation of Generative AI tools. This presentation will be digitally interactive and encourage audience participation and discussion through QR codes and a Padlet Wall.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In 2023-2024, UNC Charlotte&#039;s Writing, Rhetoric &amp; Digital Studies faculty piloted the use of generative AI tools in first-year writing courses. Our goal was to explore how students and instructors approach AI for writing and pedagogy. This lightning talk shares how we have expanded our thinking around AI tools to critically examine AI&#039;s digital literacy implications. Our model positions AI literacy as an essential component of classroom equity and in this talk we plan to share our findings around ongoing development of ethical, cultural, and equity-based frameworks for students that help them understand what AI tools are, how they work, and what using them means. Our lightning talk will highlight several key focal points of our work with generative AI tools in FYW including the qualitative data we collected, patterns of student AI usage, crucial considerations about the environmental impact of AI use, supporting faculty as they integrate AI into their teaching pedagogy and building collaborative AI use models with students. This approach creates a literacy-as-equity framework by understanding the technology&#039;s workings, implications, and collaborative possibilities. Moving beyond just using AI tools, we hope to empower students and faculty to critically navigate this emerging space through an equity-driven literacy framework and the outcome of the pilot program has provided key insights into how this goal can be achieved through critical and careful implementation of Generative AI tools. This presentation will be digitally interactive and encourage audience participation and discussion through QR codes and a Padlet Wall.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cary, Justin Robert</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The University of North Carolina Charlotte</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jcary1@charlotte.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jcayr1@charlotte.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jcary1@charlotte.edu, Cat.Mahaffey@charlotte.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cary, Justin Robert;&#10;Mahaffey, Cat</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jcary1@charlotte.edu;&#10;Cat.Mahaffey@charlotte.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Standard Time (EST)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">87.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">207</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1232</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Faerber-Ovaska, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal&#039;s authors conducted a study on how they integrated GAI tools in first-year writing courses at their institution.Their presentation promises to include qualitative data, student usage patterns, and environmental considerations of AI. Based on their findings, they make a case for AI literacy as an essential component of classroom equity in terms of ethical, cultural, and equity-based frameworks. Their findings on AI tool implementation have useful, much-needed implications for adapting pedagogical strategies.  The focus on equity-driven AI literacy and the interactive nature of the presentation should make it a great session.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Great topic -- this looks very interesting! The fact that your proposal is based on an empirical study of GAI use in your classrooms (rather than a more speculative proposal) adds so much value. It sounds like in the course of your implementation study, you emphasized aspects I also consider very important: ensuring that students gain critical AI literacy, and supporting student agency as they learn about, and learn how to use, AI tools in support of their writing. Findings from this study will surely be useful in informing instructor practices, and also could help faculty developers understand what kinds of support would help instructors adapt to a world with AI.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Definitely accept this one!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1115</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kitchings, Laura</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a case study showing how a pilot program teaching AI tools to first-year students expanded the pedagogical framework of the program to include AI literacy. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposed lighting talk details how and why teaching AI literacy should improve student outcomes in first-year writing courses. The strong proposal needs more information about what led UNC Charlotte&#039;s Writing, Rhetoric &amp; Digital Studies faculty to move from teaching generative AI tools to a program focused on AI literacy. A quick breakdown of the demographics of the students is needed, especially as conference participants will likely try to adapt the program for their students. A demographic breakdown may place this talk more firmly as anti-racism work. The planned use of interactive tools strengthens the proposal. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1325</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Champagne, Ashley</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">GenerativeAI and its impact on writing and digital literacy is a critical topic of interest to many. As many other universities and researchers are experimenting with approaches, it would be interesting and very helpful to hear how the author&#039;s work in experimenting with utilizing AI in first-year writing went. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is very strong, and I&#039;m very excited to hear about your work. One thing I have noticed in working in AI and digital humanities is that different universities (e.g. RI versus community college) have vastly different approaches and needs when it comes to AI. It might be helpful in your talk to give some context to your university and how your approach might be helpful for universities in similar contexts (but also how might it be useful to others --- e.g. community colleges?)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">15</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Accept - Lightning</ss:Data></Cell>
