    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The impact of misinformation during the flooding in the South of Brazil</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">social media analysis, fake news, misinformation</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Portuguese&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;South America&#10;Contemporary&#10;eco-criticism and environmental analysis&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;social media analysis and methods&#10;Anthropology&#10;Environmental, ocean, and waterways studies&#10;Ethnography&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Portuguese</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">South America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">eco-criticism and environmental analysis&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;social media analysis and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Anthropology&#10;Environmental, ocean, and waterways studies&#10;Ethnography&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The catastrophic flooding in Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil, in 2024 marked one of the most severe natural disasters in the region&#039;s history. Triggered by the increasing rainfall, the flooding resulted in extensive destruction across the state, displacing over 600,000 people, causing the death of more than 150 individuals, and leaving many more unaccounted for. The damaged infrastructures, with roads, bridges, and telecommunications networks being destroyed. Amidst the chaos of the physical environment, the virtual sphere saw the phenomenon of misinformation, complicating the authorities’ efforts and causing public distress.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This study aims to evaluate the impact of fake news and explore the dynamics of its spread during the Rio Grande do Sul floods across various online platforms. Specifically, it seeks to understand how misinformation affected public perception, response efforts, and overall crisis management. The research is based on monitoring social media in Brazilian Portuguese, search engines, and media portals as primary data sources.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The methodology involves a mixed-methods approach, integrating both quantitative and qualitative analyses. Quantitative analysis involves text processing techniques such as topic analysis intended to categorize the most relevant themes. This involved collecting a vast corpus of data from social media platforms like TikTok, X, Facebook, and Instagram, as well as from search engine results and news articles. The qualitative analysis focused on exploring the most shared and impactful content using content analysis techniques.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Initial findings indicate that fake news played an important role in shaping public perception and response during the floods. Misinformation ranged from exaggerated reports of damage and casualties to false information about relief efforts and safety measures. This not only fueled panic and confusion among the public but also hindered the efforts of emergency services by spreading incorrect information about accessible routes and available resources.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The catastrophic flooding in Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil, in 2024 marked one of the most severe natural disasters in the region&#039;s history. Triggered by the increasing rainfall, the flooding resulted in extensive destruction across the state, displacing over 600,000 people, causing the death of more than 150 individuals, and leaving many more unaccounted for. The damaged infrastructures, with roads, bridges, and telecommunications networks being destroyed. Amidst the chaos of the physical environment, the virtual sphere saw the phenomenon of misinformation, complicating the authorities’ efforts and causing public distress.&#10;This study aims to evaluate the impact of fake news and explore the dynamics of its spread during the Rio Grande do Sul floods across various online platforms. Specifically, it seeks to understand how misinformation affected public perception, response efforts, and overall crisis management. The research is based on monitoring social media in Brazilian Portuguese, search engines, and media portals as primary data sources.&#10;The methodology involves a mixed-methods approach, integrating both quantitative and qualitative analyses. Quantitative analysis involves text processing techniques such as topic analysis intended to categorize the most relevant themes. This involved collecting a vast corpus of data from social media platforms like TikTok, X, Facebook, and Instagram, as well as from search engine results and news articles. The qualitative analysis focused on exploring the most shared and impactful content using content analysis techniques.&#10;Initial findings indicate that fake news played an important role in shaping public perception and response during the floods. Misinformation ranged from exaggerated reports of damage and casualties to false information about relief efforts and safety measures. This not only fueled panic and confusion among the public but also hindered the efforts of emergency services by spreading incorrect information about accessible routes and available resources.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
