    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">95.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">208</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1233</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kashyap, Deepika</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper examines the impact of fake news and misinformation on digital platforms during natural disasters — how this misinformation creates confusion and panic among the public, disrupting emergency services.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper clearly explains how fake news and misinformation impact emergency services during natural calamities. &#10;This paper is well-designed, with strong theoretical and methodological approaches. The author has clearly articulated the argument of the study and provided sufficient materials to develop it into a full paper. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper is of a very high standard. I strongly recommend this paper. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1308</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wymer, Kathryn C</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This discussion of fake news is timely and can add greatly to our understanding of the social media landscape. Since the analysis relies on Portuguese social media, it can strengthen our understanding of DH beyond English-language studies. There has been a great deal of fake news study in the U.S. sphere, so considering the Brazilian context will offer good insights for comparison.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this proposal sounds excellent. I have read a fair amount about social media and fake news in an English-language (and usually U.S.-centric) context, so it is exciting to learn more about Brazilian Portuguese studies of this phenomenon. My main question is whether this is really a panel or whether it is an individual presentation. I only saw one author, so perhaps this has been mislabeled.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">My main question is whether this is really a panel or whether it is an individual presentation. I only saw one author, so perhaps this has been mislabeled. I think I recommend this as a paper acceptance rather than a panel.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1142</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Stanton, Andrea</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution offers a multi-platform, mixed methods survey and analysis of the impact of misinformation and &#039;fake news&#039; on citizen and governmental responses to the 2024 flooding in southern Brazil. It provides a deeply situated case study that will allow conference participants to both learn about the specificities of the case study while also learning from it as an example of how to do similar work when investigating the impact of misinformation on communities in their own research contexts. &#10;&#10;I am not entirely sure how the paper will assess the impact of this misinformation,  but think that this is either due to my own poor reading or to space limitations in the abstract.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Overall assessment, as shared with the conference organizers: &#10;This contribution offers a multi-platform, mixed methods survey and analysis of the impact of misinformation and &#039;fake news&#039; on citizen and governmental responses to the 2024 flooding in southern Brazil. It provides a deeply situated case study that will allow conference participants to both learn about the specificities of the case study while also learning from it as an example of how to do similar work when investigating the impact of misinformation on communities in their own research contexts. &#10;&#10;I am not entirely sure how the paper will assess the impact of this misinformation,  but think that this is either due to my own poor reading or to space limitations in the abstract.&#10;&#10;Specific comments: I think that my lack of clarity on the following points is simply due to space constraints in the abstract, but I would appreciate understanding how you determined the appropriate platforms to survey. I would also appreciate understanding, as noted above, how you determine impact: number of reposts, number of views, explicit response in governmental communication, etc. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I&#039;m not specifically recommending this as a poster or lightning talk, but I would endorse doing so if the presenter prefers either format.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
