    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">More Than Meets the AI: NEH Support for the Digital Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Funding, Grants, External Support, US Federal Government, and Infrastructure</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;meta-criticism (reflections on digital humanities and humanities computing)&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">meta-criticism (reflections on digital humanities and humanities computing)&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Book and Print history&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The National Endowment for the Humanities (NEH) is the largest federal funder of digital humanities programs and projects. Through our grant programs, we support projects across the spectrum, from the digitization of humanities collections to scholarly research using digital methods, from pedagogical and public engagement projects to developing digital infrastructure for scholarly communication. We also participate in international research funding opportunities, such as those supported through the Trans Atlantic Platform, and represent the humanities in US governmentwide technology initiatives, including through our &lt;em&gt;Humanities Perspectives on Artificial Intelligence&lt;/em&gt; special call. Every area listed in the scope for this conference’s call has been and can be supported by the NEH.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This session will build on last year’s “NEH Funding for the Digital Humanities: Finding Your Fit” ACH 2023 conference session. Staff members from across the agency will provide information about our newest funding opportunities and Endowment-wide special initiatives, such as the &lt;em&gt;American Tapestry: Weaving Together Past, Present, and Future and the Humanities&lt;/em&gt;. We will also update you on any changes to longstanding programs that support digital humanities scholarship, pedagogy, public engagement, preservation, and infrastructure development, including those that that expand NEH funding opportunities for historically underserved scholars, communities, and institutions. The proposed session will give attendees the chance to learn from Endowment representatives about the many NEH funding opportunities that encourage or allow digitally inflected work, including several ones on the intersection of the humanities and artificial intelligence.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This session will also be an opportunity for the NEH staff to hear from you. We would welcome the chance to learn from session participants about barriers that may exist for support for the digital humanities, including participation in artificial intelligence initiatives, at their institutions and for applying for NEH funding or external grant funding more broadly.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The National Endowment for the Humanities (NEH) is the largest federal funder of digital humanities programs and projects. Through our grant programs, we support projects across the spectrum, from the digitization of humanities collections to scholarly research using digital methods, from pedagogical and public engagement projects to developing digital infrastructure for scholarly communication. We also participate in international research funding opportunities, such as those supported through the Trans Atlantic Platform, and represent the humanities in US governmentwide technology initiatives, including through our Humanities Perspectives on Artificial Intelligence special call. Every area listed in the scope for this conference’s call has been and can be supported by the NEH.&#10;This session will build on last year’s “NEH Funding for the Digital Humanities: Finding Your Fit” ACH 2023 conference session. Staff members from across the agency will provide information about our newest funding opportunities and Endowment-wide special initiatives, such as the American Tapestry: Weaving Together Past, Present, and Future and the Humanities. We will also update you on any changes to longstanding programs that support digital humanities scholarship, pedagogy, public engagement, preservation, and infrastructure development, including those that that expand NEH funding opportunities for historically underserved scholars, communities, and institutions. The proposed session will give attendees the chance to learn from Endowment representatives about the many NEH funding opportunities that encourage or allow digitally inflected work, including several ones on the intersection of the humanities and artificial intelligence.&#10;This session will also be an opportunity for the NEH staff to hear from you. We would welcome the chance to learn from session participants about barriers that may exist for support for the digital humanities, including participation in artificial intelligence initiatives, at their institutions and for applying for NEH funding or external grant funding more broadly.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
