    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">menno.vanzaanen@nwu.ac.za</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0000-0003-1841-2444</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Social network analysis in multilingual literary works</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">literary analysis, social networks, translation</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;19th Century&#10;electronic literature, production and analysis&#10;natural language processing&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Linguistics&#10;Literary studies&#10;Translation studies&#10;Comparative and World Literature&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">electronic literature, production and analysis&#10;natural language processing&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Linguistics&#10;Literary studies&#10;Translation studies&#10;Comparative and World Literature&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;One important aspect in literary analysis is how characters in stories interact and relate to each other (Krug 2020). These relations and social networks can be identified manually (using a close reading approach), but advances in natural language processing allow for the automatic extraction of such networks (Elson, et al. 2010, van de Ven, et al. 2018) using a distant reading approach (Moretti 2003).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Given that social networks are inherent to a story, one would expect that translations yield the same or similar networks. If the network structure is different between translations, readers may experience the story differently. Our research explores the impact of translation on the story’s social networks.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;To extract a social network from a text, we identify the characters in the story using spaCy’s named entity recognizers, which can handle multiple languages. Characters co-occuring in a sentence are assumed to have a relation with each other. Here we follow the approach by van de Ven, et al. (2018), which results in weights based on frequency for both characters and their relationships. These networks are visualized and global statistics (e.g., density) are computed.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;We analyze two Mark Twain books, “Adventures of Tom Sawyer” and “Adventures of Huckleberry Finn” and their translations into German and Polish, and show that the social networks of the translations are not isomorphic. Further analysis shows that this may be due to linguistic differences (e.g., using a name versus a pronoun) as well as possible differences in translation.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">One important aspect in literary analysis is how characters in stories interact and relate to each other (Krug 2020). These relations and social networks can be identified manually (using a close reading approach), but advances in natural language processing allow for the automatic extraction of such networks (Elson, et al. 2010, van de Ven, et al. 2018) using a distant reading approach (Moretti 2003).&#10;Given that social networks are inherent to a story, one would expect that translations yield the same or similar networks. If the network structure is different between translations, readers may experience the story differently. Our research explores the impact of translation on the story’s social networks.&#10;To extract a social network from a text, we identify the characters in the story using spaCy’s named entity recognizers, which can handle multiple languages. Characters co-occuring in a sentence are assumed to have a relation with each other. Here we follow the approach by van de Ven, et al. (2018), which results in weights based on frequency for both characters and their relationships. These networks are visualized and global statistics (e.g., density) are computed.&#10;We analyze two Mark Twain books, “Adventures of Tom Sawyer” and “Adventures of Huckleberry Finn” and their translations into German and Polish, and show that the social networks of the translations are not isomorphic. Further analysis shows that this may be due to linguistic differences (e.g., using a name versus a pronoun) as well as possible differences in translation.</ss:Data></Cell>
