    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">menno.vanzaanen@nwu.ac.za</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">a.chmarzynska.318@studms.ug.edu.pl, j.komosa.347@studms.ug.edu.pl, a.potrykus.748@studms.ug.edu.pl, s.os.275@studms.ug.edu.pl, katarzyna.raca@ug.edu.pl, t.was.124@studms.ug.edu.pl, karolina.rudnicka@ug.edu.pl, menno.vanzaanen@nwu.ac.za</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">van Zaanen, Menno</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">menno.vanzaanen@nwu.ac.za</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">UTC+2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">64.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">210</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1249</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shoemaker, Tyler</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract nicely situates the authors&#039; work on social network analysis and&#10;provides a clear description of the work they&#039;ve undertaken to use this method&#10;in the context of differences between translations. The way they&#039;ve built these&#10;networks and derived metrics from them all make sense. But while using networks&#10;of character co-occurrences is an intriguing approach to translation, it&#10;remains somewhat unclear why the approach is apt for the topic, and what the&#10;approach will show. Some kind of theoretical articulation that grounds this&#10;analysis seems implicit here, and I cannot make out what this might be. Why use&#10;network analysis in place of content-based metrics, or, say sentiment analysis?&#10;How do we specify readers experiencing the story differently? Or consider plot:&#10;are those &quot;possible differences in translation,&quot; which the authors allude to at&#10;the end of their abstract, support for some kind of narrative-theoretic&#10;reflection on this? Should the paper be presented at the conference, I would&#10;recommend the theoretic reasoning and stakes of this analysis be made much more&#10;explicit.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">66</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1228</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wilkens, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Authors compare inferred character networks in two novels by Mark Twain and in their translations from English.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">An interesting problem re: translatability of character network structures. The proposal could be improved using a more advanced approach to character relation extraction. Cooccurrence in a sentence suggests relation, but it would be useful to use dependency-parsed relations or to train a model to identify types of relation. Dependency relations could be extracted with minimal additional work from the existing method. As it stands, it is difficult to say whether the identified differences are primarily linguistic or have to do with active changes in translation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Not much here. Better as a poster or lightening talk to collect participant feedback.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1092</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Froehlich, Heather</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">How do two 2 very popular Mark Twain books show variation in social networks for the characters in translation (English to German and Polish)? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The premise of this paper is really interesting: we see lots of social network analyses but rarely do we see social network analysis of two novels that are clearly related (Adventures of Tom Sawyer, Adventures Huckleberry Finn) to observe character closeness in the complete cycle. And adding in the translation element means that by definition readers in different languages will encounter a slightly different &#039;version&#039; of both novels. &#10;&#10;The use of German and Polish are surely somewhat informed by the authors of this paper, and a nod as to why these two languages are specifically interesting to us would be useful (what do they have common/what are their differences that are grammatically meaningful here?). The rest of the proposal, using spaCy to identify named entities and the subsequent data visualization process, are all relatively common activities. There must be some more recent/foundational citations to draw from on the social network analysis methods but I&#039;m just being nitpicky on that.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
