    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital Quilombos: Resistence and Re-existence in Search of Justice</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Quilombos, Blackness, Resitence, Re-Existence, Data, Justice</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Spanish&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;North America&#10;South America&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Contemporary&#10;network analysis and graphs theory and application&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Latin American studies&#10;Caribbean Studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Spanish</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;South America&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;network analysis and graphs theory and application&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Race Studies&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Latin American studies&#10;Caribbean Studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This paper aims to discuss how contemporary Black communities in the Americas are creating digital quilombos that search for justice at diverse levels: social, data, digital, historical, racial, and environmental among others. The communication will focus on trans-border and transnational collaborations carried out between activist communities in Brazil, Colombia and the US, and scholars who have developed process of co-creation. These communities, in connection with scholars and other practitioners, have been using digital tools to create archives, maps, visualizations, through which they can keep their own memories, connect with other communities with shared experiences, and carry out processes of accountability to question structures of power. Like historical quilombos, these digital quilombos (communities who use digital tools to resist colonial impositions-including those carried out through technology-, but whose agendas go beyond the digital realm) become creative systems to propose, imagine and create alternative worlds.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Quilombos must be considered not only as spaces formed by runaways but as location in which new forms of existence, community and humanity were created. In that sense, quilombismo or the actions carried out by quilombos was a form of resistance and re-existence (Siqueira, 2021). The communities highlighted throughout the presentation will showcase a close connection with the dynamic developed by historical quilombos, but in the context of algorithmic and data colonial impositions. These communities, in collaboration with scholars, will create hybrid spaces (digital and analog) to resist, re-exist and re-create new ways to be human in a extractive and dehumanizing digital world.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper aims to discuss how contemporary Black communities in the Americas are creating digital quilombos that search for justice at diverse levels: social, data, digital, historical, racial, and environmental among others. The communication will focus on trans-border and transnational collaborations carried out between activist communities in Brazil, Colombia and the US, and scholars who have developed process of co-creation. These communities, in connection with scholars and other practitioners, have been using digital tools to create archives, maps, visualizations, through which they can keep their own memories, connect with other communities with shared experiences, and carry out processes of accountability to question structures of power. Like historical quilombos, these digital quilombos (communities who use digital tools to resist colonial impositions-including those carried out through technology-, but whose agendas go beyond the digital realm) become creative systems to propose, imagine and create alternative worlds.&#10;Quilombos must be considered not only as spaces formed by runaways but as location in which new forms of existence, community and humanity were created. In that sense, quilombismo or the actions carried out by quilombos was a form of resistance and re-existence (Siqueira, 2021). The communities highlighted throughout the presentation will showcase a close connection with the dynamic developed by historical quilombos, but in the context of algorithmic and data colonial impositions. These communities, in collaboration with scholars, will create hybrid spaces (digital and analog) to resist, re-exist and re-create new ways to be human in a extractive and dehumanizing digital world.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Arriaga, Eduard</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Clark University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">earriaga@clarku.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">earriaga@alumni.uwo.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">earriaga@clarku.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Arriaga, Eduard</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">earriaga@clarku.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ET</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">211</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1177</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Clawson, Corey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed paper will offer an overview of digital quilombos, drawing on the legacies of enslavement, colonialism, and resistance to engage in practices of reimagination and liberation using digital tools/methodologies to pursue racial, digital, and environmental justice.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Given the liberatory significance of quilombos, the framework of digital ones &quot;becom[ing] creative systems to propose, imagine and create alternative worlds&quot; is intriguing and exciting . It speaks deeply to the legacy of legacy of resistance, redefinition, and bringing new possibilities into relief. The proposed paper is deeply significant to the objectives of ACH. I&#039;m eager to learn more about the digital projects, public digital humanities approaches, and the transnational scope/dimensions of the work. I&#039;m left wondering how these digital quilombos are networked and connected across language and geography in addition to the historical and liberatory ties to historical quilombos. Again, the paper is of great value to this conference&#039;s objectives but also more broadly to the role digital humanities might play in the pursuit of global racial justice</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1197</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brault, Chloé</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper strikes a nice balance between historical modes of resistance and contemporary justice initiatives. This balance is reflected in the title of the paper. I am interested to learn more about &quot;co-creation&quot; between activist groups and scholars. In this way, the paper speaks directly to the conference themes. I see this paper of being of great interest to scholars in Cultural Studies first, and also to social scientists working in Critical Race Studies, African American/Black Studies, Cultural studies, Latin American studies, and/or Caribbean Studies. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I unfortunately struggle to understand the network analysis, graphs theory and application, and data science angles of this contribution. I see an opportunity to provide analysis of digital-borne collaborations using networks, graphs, and data science more broadly, but I would need more details on what exactly is being analyzed and how. What digital tools and/or methods is the author using in their analysis? What are the affordances of these tools/ methods? What are their limitations? &#10;&#10;If the paper is not meant to be primarily analytic, but expository, I would still need to understand what is being described. The proposal would be greatly improved with the brief discussion of an example of an archive, map, and/or vizualization. How did the author access this digital object? How did the author build their corpus and metadata more broadly? Does the author have access to prepatory materials for digitally published objects, like code or correspondences between collaborating parties? Does the author have access to user interaction data, like user comments or visitor tracking data? Did the author seek permission to analyze these objects? Did the author conduct ethnographic interviews? Is there an IRB? &#10;&#10;I am interested in the public humanities appeal of this work. However, I would need to understand who the interested publics would be. Other historical quilombo groups and/or active quilombos? Historically maroon communities elsewhere? The general public in Brazil, Columbia, and the United States? Depending on how the author accessed their corpus, I also wonder about the ethics of presenting and publishing this type of work. I imagine that digital-quilombo-activist projects could attract negative attention from local law enforcement in some participating contexts and/or cause participating parties grief. Relatedly, I would like to learn about other venues the author wishes to present their research.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1003</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fernandez, Sylvia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal discusses how Black communities in Brasil, Colombia and the United States are creating digital quilombos (hybrid spaces), a collaborative work between, scholars and commity members to use digital to tools to archive, visualize and take ownership of processes of accountability to question structures of power.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal is bringing to the forefront necessary collaborations between scholars and black community members in the Americas to create spaces of resistance and solidarity to produce their own data, stories, geographical representations, archives among other creative materials with the aims to resist colonial impositions including those carried out through technology.This will be a very important presentation and I will incourage the author to consider addressing the aspect of language in the creation of this hybrid spaces. I am also thinking it will be important to address the relevant scholarship of indigenous communities who have been doing this type of work in the Americas, as well as the aspect of transborder and transnational collaborations as to the ethics, practices to foster and protocols to follow. Very looking forward to this presenation in conversation with other presenters. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
