    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">212</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1049</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zoricic, Vera</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract for a lightning talk presents a unique approach to digital activism and social justice. The collaborative approach makes this contribution relevant and promises strong engagement. An intersectional lens offers an essential contribution to the fields.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk promises strong engagement. It focuses on critical aspects of digital activism and social justice through artwork and has the potential to serve as a blueprint for other institutions and organizations. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1075</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Poole, Carson Leigh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract discusses themes of social justice and equitable curation practices via Omeka. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a strong topic; however, I would like to see how this Georgia College and State University (GCSU) curatorial and archival project is connected to (or is a commentary of) general museum, curatorial, or archival practices. For example, I think it would strengthen and deepen the project&#039;s scope if it addressed wider social, political, and cultural issues that inform GCSU&#039;s Art of Social Engagement exhibition. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this would be a good addition to the conference, but I feel as though the scope is a little too narrow so I gave it 8/10 on the acceptance scale. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1001</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lach, Pamella R.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission describes a social justice digital exhibit, &quot;Art of Social Engagement.&quot;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission describes an interesting social justice themed digital exhibit that pulls from library collections and makes use of digital humanities tools/methods (Omeka, data visualizations, mapping, etc.). These kinds of exhibits are a great way to highlight not only the strength of a particular collection, but also the skills and expertise of a broad range of DH practitioners. I appreciate that the author notes how this exhibit can serve as a model for similar exhibits. I&#039;d want to hear more about this. In what ways are they making their work adaptable to other institutions and/or local collections? For example, if students contributed to this exhibit through their coursework, are the assignment(s) shared in Omeka so that other instructors can re-use them? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This might make for a nice poster, which would allow the author to show off more parts of the exhibit in a more dynamic way.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
