    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Exploring US Latina Woman Literature: a case study of a digital collection</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Latino/a Studies, Chicano/a Studies, Women&#039;s Writing, Feminist Studies, Critical Rice Theory</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Spanish&#10;North America&#10;South America&#10;20th Century&#10;digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;meta-criticism (reflections on digital humanities and humanities computing)&#10;software development, systems, analysis, and methods&#10;Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Literary studies&#10;Latin American studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Spanish</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;South America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;meta-criticism (reflections on digital humanities and humanities computing)&#10;software development, systems, analysis, and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Literary studies&#10;Latin American studies&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The aim of this presentation is to critically discuss the project of creating a digital corpus that houses the literary production of Latina/Chicana authors in the United States, published by Arte Público Press (University of Houston, https://artepublicopress.com/) over the past forty-plus years (1980 – 2024). The project, titled “US Latin American Writers Published by Arte Público Press,” created with Collection Builder (https://dhcast.github.io/US-Latina/), compiles 142 fiction and non-fiction texts across all genres (narrative, poetry, dramatic texts, essays, interviews, albums) and provides a mapping of the literary works of US Latinas, which, despite their vast and diverse production, are little known or ignored by the public and literary studies in the United States. The presentation provides a reflection on the possibilities and limitations of a digital exhibition generated with &lt;em&gt;Collection Builder&lt;/em&gt;, an open-source tool based on static web technology developed by the University of Idaho. This tool allows for the visualization of printed books as digital objects, highlights key themes and tags, generates maps, etc. It specifically analyzes the practical challenges related to data stewardship, regarding gender, race, class, and ethnicity within the framework of ethnic studies, feminist studies, and digital decolonization methodologies, referencing “A U.S. Latinx Digital Humanities Manifesto” (Baeza Ventura, Cotera, García Merchant, Gauthereau, and Villarroel in: &lt;em&gt;Debates in the Digital Humanities&lt;/em&gt;, L. Klein &amp; M. Gold, University of Minnesota Press, 2023). Overall, this proposal exemplifies the integration of marginalized perspectives and voices in the digital space and promotes equity and justice in the digital representation of Latina/Chicana literatures.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The aim of this presentation is to critically discuss the project of creating a digital corpus that houses the literary production of Latina/Chicana authors in the United States, published by Arte Público Press (University of Houston, https://artepublicopress.com/) over the past forty-plus years (1980 – 2024). The project, titled “US Latin American Writers Published by Arte Público Press,” created with Collection Builder (https://dhcast.github.io/US-Latina/), compiles 142 fiction and non-fiction texts across all genres (narrative, poetry, dramatic texts, essays, interviews, albums) and provides a mapping of the literary works of US Latinas, which, despite their vast and diverse production, are little known or ignored by the public and literary studies in the United States. The presentation provides a reflection on the possibilities and limitations of a digital exhibition generated with Collection Builder, an open-source tool based on static web technology developed by the University of Idaho. This tool allows for the visualization of printed books as digital objects, highlights key themes and tags, generates maps, etc. It specifically analyzes the practical challenges related to data stewardship, regarding gender, race, class, and ethnicity within the framework of ethnic studies, feminist studies, and digital decolonization methodologies, referencing “A U.S. Latinx Digital Humanities Manifesto” (Baeza Ventura, Cotera, García Merchant, Gauthereau, and Villarroel in: Debates in the Digital Humanities, L. Klein &amp; M. Gold, University of Minnesota Press, 2023). Overall, this proposal exemplifies the integration of marginalized perspectives and voices in the digital space and promotes equity and justice in the digital representation of Latina/Chicana literatures.</ss:Data></Cell>
