    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">monika.dabrowska@unir.net</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">monika.dabrowska@unir.net</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dabrowska, Monika</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">monika.dabrowska@unir.net</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Latino/a Studies, Chicano/a Studies, Women&#039;s Writing, Feminist Studies, Critical Rice Theory</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">94.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">214</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1003</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fernandez, Sylvia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal discusses the development of a digital collection that houses the literary production of Latina/Chicana authors in the United States, published by Arte Público Press (University of Houston, https://artepublicopress.com/) over the past forty-plus years (1980 – 2024). The author aims to address the challenges related to data stewardship, regarding gender, race, class, and ethnicity within the framework of ethnic studies, feminist studies, and digital decolonization methodologies.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission presents the important work happening in the present of  creating digital spaces to represent and visualized  stories of marginalized communities such as Latina/Chicana literatures. I will encourage the author to acknowledge other smaller and local presses that have been publishing this type of literatue and discuss the protocols followed of not including them and what this means to amfliying in a certain way digital spaces. It will be important to provide other examples of similar projects such as Cartografia de Escritoras Mexicanas and the feminist work that is being carried out through this type of digital efforts. Looking forward to hearing from this great project. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1197</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brault, Chloé</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal is exemplary, offering context, a problem, and proposed solution in the scholar&#039;s area of expertise, as well as an evaluation of a computational tool for digital collection through a case study. This paper will be of great interest broadly accross literary studies, and Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x, Cultural, and Feminist studies. This paper will also be of interest to scholars new to DH methods, given the out-of-the box nagture of the tool described, and more experienced scholars, given the presentation of the case study. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A minor point: I do not see relevance of this proposal with Latin American Studies separate from Latino/a/x studies. &#10;&#10;Regarding key words: I also struggle to understand the intervention in terms of &quot;systems, and methods, meta-criticism (reflections on digital humanities and humanities computing), software development, systems, analysis, and methods.&quot; Nonetheless, the scholar&#039;s engagement of relevant literature in the abstract itself is convincing. &#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1012</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lu, Qi</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The research topic and content are highly innovative and align well with the corresponding module. The corpus selected for the study is sufficiently representative and appropriate for the research objectives. However, I recommend that the methodology section be elaborated on during the presentation to provide a clearer understanding of the approach taken.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
