    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ethical Data Curation: African American Periodicals 1900-1928</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African American, Poetry, Periodicals, Gender, Archives</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;data publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Literary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Race Studies&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Literary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;With support of a grant from the Mozilla Foundation, we created a collection of poetry published in magazines by African American writers in the early twentieth century. The collection currently contains about 750 poems, all of which are out of copyright in the U.S., with the bulk of the poetry published in fourteen different magazines, including both Black-oriented and edited magazines like &lt;em&gt;The Crisis, Opportunity&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;Black Opals&lt;/em&gt; as well as ‘mainstream’ (predominantly White) magazines like &lt;em&gt;Survey Graphic&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;The Liberator&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;Palms&lt;/em&gt;. The dataset includes information on authors’ biographies, poetic form, topics and themes, the names of editors (including guest editors and co-editors), as well as republication information. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;As editor of the project, I will discuss how and why this dataset was created. One key driving concern is the sense that these materials have been, to begin with, overlooked, and the &quot;archive gap&quot; with respect to texts by minoritized individuals persists, with knock-on effects in other DH subfields, including computational DH. This project aims to help correct that archive gap, both in terms of making texts available for researchers and students, but also by carefully reading and tagging individual poems around important thematics and historically relevant events. Some preliminary quantitative queries will also be explored, including the proportion of African American women publishing poetry in magazines during this period, network effects, the institutional gatekeepers structuring prestige and canonization, and the divergence between predominantly White and predominantly Black publications with respect to editorial policy. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">With support of a grant from the Mozilla Foundation, we created a collection of poetry published in magazines by African American writers in the early twentieth century. The collection currently contains about 750 poems, all of which are out of copyright in the U.S., with the bulk of the poetry published in fourteen different magazines, including both Black-oriented and edited magazines like The Crisis, Opportunity, and Black Opals as well as ‘mainstream’ (predominantly White) magazines like Survey Graphic, The Liberator, and Palms. The dataset includes information on authors’ biographies, poetic form, topics and themes, the names of editors (including guest editors and co-editors), as well as republication information. &#10;As editor of the project, I will discuss how and why this dataset was created. One key driving concern is the sense that these materials have been, to begin with, overlooked, and the &quot;archive gap&quot; with respect to texts by minoritized individuals persists, with knock-on effects in other DH subfields, including computational DH. This project aims to help correct that archive gap, both in terms of making texts available for researchers and students, but also by carefully reading and tagging individual poems around important thematics and historically relevant events. Some preliminary quantitative queries will also be explored, including the proportion of African American women publishing poetry in magazines during this period, network effects, the institutional gatekeepers structuring prestige and canonization, and the divergence between predominantly White and predominantly Black publications with respect to editorial policy.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Singh, Amardeep</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lehigh University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">amsp@lehigh.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">amardeep@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">amsp@lehigh.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Singh, Amardeep</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">amsp@lehigh.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
