    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">216</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Grumbach, Liz</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation (submitted as a panel, but likely meant to be a paper) will present on a collection/archive of African American poetry from the early twentieth century, the dataset(s) created from them, quant/qual analysis undertaken on that data, and how this project seeks to identify and fill the &quot;archive gap&quot;.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an excellent proposal that clearly articulates the project, how the presentation will be structured at ACH24, and the importance of bridging the &quot;archive gap&quot; (a term that I believe the author coined in previous scholarship) in our profession. I am especially excited to hear about both the creation of the archive and the computational analysis undertaken by the author. This proposal is well written, evidences a deep understanding of the field, and is relevant to the conference theme.&#10;&#10;While this will absolutely be explored in the presentation, it would be excellent to hear more about the process of coding and tagging texts for further qualitative/quantitative analysis, as well as what technologies were used to explore the data. I also wonder what archival scholarship the author sees this work being in conversation with (again, this is likely to be explored in the presentation).&#10;&#10;This abstract was submitted as a &quot;panel&quot; in ConfTool, but the proposal seems to be for a paper, and I would recommend it for acceptance as a paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This was submitted on the panel track, but I believe it should be considered/accepted as an individual paper. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1032</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Woo, Jewon</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation not only introduces us to the important project on (re)discovering poetry published in the early 20th century periodicals, but also examines the archival practice of digital archive, data creation, computational methods, and literary canonization. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation not only introduces us to the important project on (re)discovering poetry published in the early 20th century periodicals, but also examines the archival practice of digital archive, data creation, computational methods, and literary canonization. Although publishing a literary text in (Black-authored/edited) periodicals was most available for writers of color and other underrepresented groups who might have less access to a publisher, periodical poetry as well as other literary texts like serialized fictions has been overlooked in our consideration of literature. Professor Singh&#039;s project can demonstrate how critically we need to reconsider archival practice that has been boosted by various digital tools yet to be reviewed in the constellation of early 20th-century American literature. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1020</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Jensen, Graham</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As the author notes, and as other modernist critics working in this area would attest, this submission addresses a noteworthy archival gap. Because it moves beyond the (onerous and complex) work of digitization to also consider how digitized texts might be analyzed computationally, it is well positioned to make welcome contributions in each of the areas identified in the submission’s “Disciplines” field. Finally, its generic focus on poetry and poetic form sets it apart from several existing projects focusing more broadly on early twentieth-century periodicals.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a compelling proposal, and the project it outlines holds great promise in terms of facilitating future research (both in DH and in literary studies). More specifically, I applaud the author’s stated desire not only to make this body of poems by African American writers more accessible, but also to flag—if only as “preliminary quantitative queries”—some of the theoretical lines of inquiry that the dataset may support. Additionally, the scope of the research is both ambitious and yet reasonably focused, given the size of the dataset and the kinds of metadata it includes.  There is much to admire here.&#10;&#10;For the presentation itself, I would suggest that the author include further discussion of the dataset’s source(s). For instance, were the poems drawn from existing projects or collections (since some magazines, such as The Crisis, have already been digitized as part of initiatives such as the Modernist Journals Project), or did they come from print sources that the author—working alone or with the support of libraries—digitized for this project specifically? If the former, I would be interested to hear more about any data cleaning or transformation work that was required; if the latter, I would be interested to hear more about the project’s digitization workflow and relationship with partnered libraries housing the original materials (but the fact that these questions of provenance were not addressed explicitly in the submission abstract is quite understandable, given space constraints). Of note, the abstract does gesture effectively to several significant critical gaps in modernist studies and literary studies more generally (while also tackling head-on the issue of DH’s whiteness, à la the critical DH work of Tara McPherson, Alan Liu, and many others). However, since the submission’s central argument hinges on the existence of an archival gap, it would be worth considering how the availability of the project’s 750 poems in existing—if distributed—digital collections may or may not necessitate a slight modulation of this claim. &#10;&#10;Some other questions that could be worthy of consideration but may not be as central to the author’s interests or the project’s mandate include the following:&#10;- In what form or file format(s) will the published poems be shared? What kind of collection framework or tools will be used?&#10;- Will the discussion of the dataset and “network effects” address the transnational aspects of the dataset or project (if applicable)? If so, it could be worth positioning the project’s journals in relation to similar journals published outside of the United States.&#10;- How does this project overlap with, or intentionally depart from existing periodical projects such as the Modernist Journals Project (https://modjourn.org/), the Blue Mountain Project (https://bluemountain.princeton.edu/bluemtn/cgi-bin/bluemtn), or the Modernist Magazines Project (http://www.modernistmagazines.com/)?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Is this meant to be a panel and not a paper? Although this submission is flagged as a panel, only one presenter is noted (as far as I can tell), so I wanted to flag this in case there was a mistake in categorization and it would make the most sense as a paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
