    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">217</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1197</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brault, Chloé</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper uses cutting-edge transformer architecture in an non-English environment, which in and of itself speaks to the themes of the conference. The substance of the sociological analysis will be broadly interesting to Critical Race, Feminist, Sociology, Latin American, and Data science/data studies, as cited by the authors. This research will also be of interest to Communications and Science and Technology scholars. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I look forward to learning more from these researchers. However, without further details on how the author&#039;s collected their data, I am concerned about the ethics of the data collection and more broadly about the validity of the study. How did the authors access the five Telegram chats described? Were the members of Telegram chats aware and consenting to the collection of their data? Was an IRB involved? If the researchers were members of the Telegram chats themselves, how did they reconcile conflict of interest? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1199</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Stevens, Nikki</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The study presents the results of a mixed-method study of Brazilian Telegram chats.  The authors present both computational information gathering and socio-anthropological insights into the culture of racism and hatred in Brazil. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an incredibly important topic and the authors&#039; approach does make sense.  I&#039;m personally unclear on how the results are reflective of the system architecture of the Telegram network, beyond a result calling for more &quot;content moderation.&quot;  However, I am optimistic that this will become clear in their presentation. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1041</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Abbasov, Namig</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors primarily contribute to study of hate speech on social media, using text analysis methods. The use of BERTopic for topic modeling is a good idea as traditional topic modeling methods like LDA is performing poorly in short text from social media. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The use of social media for the study of hate speech is a great idea. This study provides a great contribution and I would love to read more about it. I would suggest the authors to justify the use of topic modeling method for semantic similarity. They can stress out underlying BERT embeddings or also consider the possible use of word embeddings.   </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors conduct an important study of hate speech using social media data. They also use the text analysis methods that become possible after the introduction of the novel Transformer architecture. I think it will be a great addition to the Conference. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
