    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Mathematical Analysis of Paper Classification Performance Based on Paper Characteristics</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">paper analysis, paper feature, paper classification</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Japanese&#10;Asia&#10;Europe&#10;Global&#10;5th-14th Century&#10;15th-17th Century&#10;image processing and analysis&#10;manuscripts description, representation, and analysis&#10;Art history&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Japanese</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia&#10;Europe&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">5th-14th Century&#10;15th-17th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">image processing and analysis&#10;manuscripts description, representation, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Art history&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In the analysis of paper used in ancient documents and paintings, focusing on Western paper, it is possible to finely classify a large amount of Western paper due to the diversity of watermark patterns. In the field of informatics, methods for extracting watermark patterns as digital images are being researched. Unfortunately, paper produced in Arab and Asian regions typically does not have watermark patterns.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In fields such as cultural heritage science, the characteristics of paper are mainly analyzed based on the identification of raw materials (such as fibers and starch grains), the density of laid lines, the width of chain lines, and the size of the paper. Such data are sometimes used as metadata in digital archives. However, the range of values for these attributes is limited, and they are characterized by a lack of diversity. Therefore, it is not possible to finely classify a large number of papers using these attributes.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In this presentation, we theoretically demonstrate that chain line patterns are a characteristic of paper with diversity. Furthermore, chain line patterns are patterns created by the papermaking screen, and due to the limitations imposed by the usage period (or lifespan) of the papermaking screen, papers with the same papermaking screen pattern are relatively close in production period and are likely to have been produced in the same location, possessing properties similar to watermark patterns.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In the analysis of paper used in ancient documents and paintings, focusing on Western paper, it is possible to finely classify a large amount of Western paper due to the diversity of watermark patterns. In the field of informatics, methods for extracting watermark patterns as digital images are being researched. Unfortunately, paper produced in Arab and Asian regions typically does not have watermark patterns.&#10;In fields such as cultural heritage science, the characteristics of paper are mainly analyzed based on the identification of raw materials (such as fibers and starch grains), the density of laid lines, the width of chain lines, and the size of the paper. Such data are sometimes used as metadata in digital archives. However, the range of values for these attributes is limited, and they are characterized by a lack of diversity. Therefore, it is not possible to finely classify a large number of papers using these attributes.&#10;In this presentation, we theoretically demonstrate that chain line patterns are a characteristic of paper with diversity. Furthermore, chain line patterns are patterns created by the papermaking screen, and due to the limitations imposed by the usage period (or lifespan) of the papermaking screen, papers with the same papermaking screen pattern are relatively close in production period and are likely to have been produced in the same location, possessing properties similar to watermark patterns.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sakamoto, Shouji</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Japan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">sakamoto@mac.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">sakamoto313@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">sakamoto@mac.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sakamoto, Shouji</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">sakamoto@mac.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">GMT+9  (from Japan)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">219</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1242</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Vasyutinsky Shapira, Daria</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author studies paper produced in Arab and Asian regions, used for historical documents and paintings. Such paper typically does not have watermark patterns. The author researchers chain line patterns are patterns created by the papermaking screenchain line patterns (patterns created by the papermaking screen) of such paper to help date the historical documents and the place of copying. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dear author, your research is essential for studying historical documents written on paper without watermarks. I&#039;m looking forward to studying your poster. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1259</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Li, Yunxin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission introduces an approach to analyze Asian paper based on chain line patterns, instead of watermark patterns which applies better to European paper. It thus contributes to the decolonization of the field of cultural heritage science and helps advance the classification of Asian paper. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission introduces an approach to analyze Asian paper based on chain line patterns, instead of watermark patterns which applies better to European paper. It thus contributes to the decolonization of the field of cultural heritage science and helps advance the classification of Asian paper. &#10;&#10;The contribution of the project and its relevance to existing scholarship is clearly articulated. However, to explain it to those outside the field of cultural heritage science, I would suggest further clarifying the different methods of paper making, whether similar ideas have been proposed, and how likely this theoretical model can be applied. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1312</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Torabi, Katayoun</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Although there are several areas in the proposal that need some clarification, I think that this project makes an important contribution by examining ways in which non-Western paper used in ancient documents and paintings can be classified and analyzed. The author explains that whereas watermarks make this kind of analysis easier in the West, other methods must be utilized in Arab and Asian regions. I think that non-Western book production is an important, but still a largely unexplored field of study.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I recommend that this proposal be accepted for this year’s conference because, as I explained above, I think that examining non-Western methods of book production is important and needs more attention. There are, however, some points that I would like to see clarified if this project is accepted for this conference. First, it would be very helpful for the author to provide information about which non-Western countries and what specific timeframe are the focus of this study. Second, the title includes the words “mathematical analysis.” A couple of sentences about the mathematical analysis, digital methods, and/or tools the author plans to use to examine or visualize the data would help clarify things a bit. Third, it would be a good idea for the author to define some of the more field-specific terms mentioned in the abstract for those unfamiliar with book or print history. For example, in the abstract the author states, “In fields such as cultural heritage science, the characteristics of paper are mainly analyzed based on the identification of raw materials (such as fibers and starch grains), the density of laid lines, the width of chain lines, and the size of the paper.” They do an excellent job of explaining what “raw materials” are. It might be helpful to add a brief explanation in parenthesis for “laid lines” and “chain lines” here as well. And finally, it would be helpful if the author could include some of the scholarly sources they are drawing from/engaging with for this study.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
