    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Linguistic Justice for Digitally-Disadvantaged Languages</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">multilingual, Unicode, keyboard design, translation</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;interface design, development, and analysis&#10;Modern Languages&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;interface design, development, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Modern Languages&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;For reading and writing the Latin alphabet, as used for English, the technical landscape has &quot;just worked” for several decades. To this day, writing and reading digital text in other scripts can be a struggle – or even impossible for some scripts. Usable digital text for most languages requires that several things be in place: official codepoints in the Unicode standard, an input method (e.g. keyboard layouts), at least one font available across all platforms and devices. Each step of this process is time-consuming, and draws on specific expertise: knowledge of the Unicode proposal process, experience with UI/UX as well as a familiarity with the user community. It can take years, or even a decade, for all these pieces to be created and made available to user communities, not least because there is little commercial incentive to undertake this work. This is a serious issue for social justice, and one that several digital humanists, including David Birnbaum, Deborah Anderson, and Anushah Hossain have been involved in addressing.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In this talk, student interns who have worked with SILICON (Stanford Initiative on Language Inclusion and Conservation in Old and New Media) will demystify the little-known processes behind making scripts available digitally, as well as their efforts to address the many instances of the &quot;dongle problem&quot; (per Tom Mullaney) in the mostly-volunteer ecology of Unicode, where good work comes to a halt due to a small but meaningful barrier. It will conclude with a description of how digital humanists committed to linguistic justice can get involved with the work of the Unicode Consortium.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;(Note: internship program is starting at the end of August; will add the students who are interested in co-presenting their work on projects including user testing for a Navajo keyboard &amp; creating a quickstart guiden at end of summer.)&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">For reading and writing the Latin alphabet, as used for English, the technical landscape has &quot;just worked” for several decades. To this day, writing and reading digital text in other scripts can be a struggle – or even impossible for some scripts. Usable digital text for most languages requires that several things be in place: official codepoints in the Unicode standard, an input method (e.g. keyboard layouts), at least one font available across all platforms and devices. Each step of this process is time-consuming, and draws on specific expertise: knowledge of the Unicode proposal process, experience with UI/UX as well as a familiarity with the user community. It can take years, or even a decade, for all these pieces to be created and made available to user communities, not least because there is little commercial incentive to undertake this work. This is a serious issue for social justice, and one that several digital humanists, including David Birnbaum, Deborah Anderson, and Anushah Hossain have been involved in addressing.&#10;In this talk, student interns who have worked with SILICON (Stanford Initiative on Language Inclusion and Conservation in Old and New Media) will demystify the little-known processes behind making scripts available digitally, as well as their efforts to address the many instances of the &quot;dongle problem&quot; (per Tom Mullaney) in the mostly-volunteer ecology of Unicode, where good work comes to a halt due to a small but meaningful barrier. It will conclude with a description of how digital humanists committed to linguistic justice can get involved with the work of the Unicode Consortium.&#10;(Note: internship program is starting at the end of August; will add the students who are interested in co-presenting their work on projects including user testing for a Navajo keyboard &amp; creating a quickstart guiden at end of summer.)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dombrowski, Quinn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Stanford University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">qad@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">amgao@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gao, Audrey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">amgao@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">US west coast</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">220</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1126</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ElKattan, Alia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This talk explains the sometimes complex processes that go into unicode development and digital language inclusion, and it explains how they can intertwine with access and inclusion for underrepresented languages.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Really interesting work, would be interesting to also include a larger picture perspective of the political, economic, or social forces that determine what languages we invest in for digital development.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1211</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rashid, Mohammed</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed paper will discuss the process of digital production of less dominant language scripts and explore their distribution processes. It will also discuss ways in which DH scholars interested in linguistic justice and inclusion can get involved in the SILICON project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The SILICON project is doing very important work, and DH folks and scholars interested in linguistic justice and inclusion will benefit from the discussions that emerge from this talk. &#10;&#10;I am a bit unclear about the project collaborators, and I think that part could be better articulated. It appears that there will be interns who have not worked on the project yet who will be co-presenting sections of the work. Will they be co-presenting with the principal investigator or co-presenting among themselves? I would be very interested to hear about the development of the project in tandem with the Navajo keyboard project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I recommend this talk be included, and I suggest that this talk may benefit from the modality of a poster presentation since student project collaborators will be presenting their work in progress to an audience. The modality of a poster may provide opportunities for more effective discussions and robust feedback.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1158</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Silva Moore, Rosana</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The relevance of this discussion lies in its exploration of the challenges and processes involved in making diverse scripts digitally accessible, which is crucial for promoting linguistic justice and social equity in our increasingly digital world. The Latin alphabet has enjoyed a robust technical infrastructure, making it easy for English speakers to read and write. However, many languages still struggle with digital representation due to the lack of official Unicode codepoints, inadequate input methods, and limited font availability.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission addresses an important and underrepresented issue in the digital landscape—linguistic diversity and the challenges of making various scripts accessible. Highlighting social justice as a core theme resonates with contemporary discourses on inclusivity. While the contribution discusses the problems broadly, it could benefit from specific examples or case studies that illustrate the successes and failures in digitizing particular scripts. This would provide a more concrete understanding of the challenges at hand.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
