    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Crafting Digital Humanities: Data Physicalizations with Textiles</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Data visualization, critical making, textiles, data, data physicalization</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;3d printing, critical making&#10;embodied, wearable &amp; haptic technologies development and analysis&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3d printing, critical making&#10;embodied, wearable &amp; haptic technologies development and analysis&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;There has been a growth recently in integrating crafting into digital humanities research, particularly within the #DHMakes community. This approach builds upon the call from Natalia Cecire in 2011 to reimagine the metaphors used to describe digital humanities work, noting the “distinctly white, male, blue-collar” terms like “digging”, “mining”, and “building”, and suggesting that using, instead, metaphors like weaving, cooking, knitting and other metaphors might indeed shift the field. More than simply adopting a more expansive set of terms in order to shift the discourse, this approach takes them literally: what if we represented data through craft?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This panel will focus on different approaches to using specifically textiles for data visualization, or data physicalization. Data physicalization, which is the process of creating physical data visualizations, gives us an opportunity to put our values into action with our research. Data physicalization can be a way to embody data feminism and other critical data practices: it is a slower data practice, our labor is front and center in the process (D&#039;Ignazio and Klein 2020), and we can cultivate a more intimate relationship with the data (Cleghorn 2019). And by creating physicalizations with textiles, we can particularly celebrate and highlight computation’s historical relationship with textile production and the digital’s reliance on cables and fibers. Our work with textiles consists of (machine) knitting, crochet, spinning, felting, weaving, quilting, and embroidery, but much of this work could be applied to other fiber-based methods as well. While we each approach the method of data textiles differently, we hope to display the versatility of this method and weave connections between our projects.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Presentations in this panel will cover a range of topics, and experiences, with using textiles as a canvas for data. One talk will share a self-described “non-crafty” person’s journey into this subfield, and how they got over their discomfort with a new technology by embodying the values they try to teach: embracing messy imperfection, being comfortable taking riskings, and finding joy in the process. One talk will discuss quilting and embroidery as mediums to make story-telling maps, and the use of NFC tags in turning textiles into digitally interactive objects. One talk will explore the connections that are made when using natural fibers and natural dyeing as the medium for environmental humanities topics. One talk will share the experiences of turning an unloved computer lab into a Textile Makerspace and supporting and teaching researchers to use textiles as a way to think about their data differently. And the last talk takes a curatorial perspective, examining how data physicalization offers a counter to the “information overload” found in so many contemporary museum exhibitions.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;All five of these presentations will also document the process of making the visualizations to demystify this method and encourage other practitioners to experiment with crafted digital humanities projects. With data physicalizations the process is often just as important as the final product and we want to shed light on the labor and decisions that would otherwise be unseen.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Cecire, Natalia. 2011. “Introduction: Theory and the Virtues of Digital Humanities”. Journal of Digital Humanities, vol. 1, no. 1, winter 2011. https://journalofdigitalhumanities.org/1-1/introduction-theory-and-the-virtues-of-digital-humanities-by-natalia-cecire/&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Cleghorn, Ripley. 2019. “Why You Should Close the Computer for Your Next Data Visualization.” Nightingale (blog). October 2, 2019. https://medium.com/nightingale/why-you-should-close-the-computer-for-your-next-data-visualization-3636663d0b35.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;D’Ignazio, Catherine, and Lauren F. Klein. 2020. Data Feminism. Cambridge, MA, USA: MIT Press.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">There has been a growth recently in integrating crafting into digital humanities research, particularly within the #DHMakes community. This approach builds upon the call from Natalia Cecire in 2011 to reimagine the metaphors used to describe digital humanities work, noting the “distinctly white, male, blue-collar” terms like “digging”, “mining”, and “building”, and suggesting that using, instead, metaphors like weaving, cooking, knitting and other metaphors might indeed shift the field. More than simply adopting a more expansive set of terms in order to shift the discourse, this approach takes them literally: what if we represented data through craft?&#10;This panel will focus on different approaches to using specifically textiles for data visualization, or data physicalization. Data physicalization, which is the process of creating physical data visualizations, gives us an opportunity to put our values into action with our research. Data physicalization can be a way to embody data feminism and other critical data practices: it is a slower data practice, our labor is front and center in the process (D&#039;Ignazio and Klein 2020), and we can cultivate a more intimate relationship with the data (Cleghorn 2019). And by creating physicalizations with textiles, we can particularly celebrate and highlight computation’s historical relationship with textile production and the digital’s reliance on cables and fibers. Our work with textiles consists of (machine) knitting, crochet, spinning, felting, weaving, quilting, and embroidery, but much of this work could be applied to other fiber-based methods as well. While we each approach the method of data textiles differently, we hope to display the versatility of this method and weave connections between our projects.&#10;Presentations in this panel will cover a range of topics, and experiences, with using textiles as a canvas for data. One talk will share a self-described “non-crafty” person’s journey into this subfield, and how they got over their discomfort with a new technology by embodying the values they try to teach: embracing messy imperfection, being comfortable taking riskings, and finding joy in the process. One talk will discuss quilting and embroidery as mediums to make story-telling maps, and the use of NFC tags in turning textiles into digitally interactive objects. One talk will explore the connections that are made when using natural fibers and natural dyeing as the medium for environmental humanities topics. One talk will share the experiences of turning an unloved computer lab into a Textile Makerspace and supporting and teaching researchers to use textiles as a way to think about their data differently. And the last talk takes a curatorial perspective, examining how data physicalization offers a counter to the “information overload” found in so many contemporary museum exhibitions.&#10;All five of these presentations will also document the process of making the visualizations to demystify this method and encourage other practitioners to experiment with crafted digital humanities projects. With data physicalizations the process is often just as important as the final product and we want to shed light on the labor and decisions that would otherwise be unseen.&#10;Cecire, Natalia. 2011. “Introduction: Theory and the Virtues of Digital Humanities”. Journal of Digital Humanities, vol. 1, no. 1, winter 2011. https://journalofdigitalhumanities.org/1-1/introduction-theory-and-the-virtues-of-digital-humanities-by-natalia-cecire/&#10;Cleghorn, Ripley. 2019. “Why You Should Close the Computer for Your Next Data Visualization.” Nightingale (blog). October 2, 2019. https://medium.com/nightingale/why-you-should-close-the-computer-for-your-next-data-visualization-3636663d0b35.&#10;D’Ignazio, Catherine, and Lauren F. Klein. 2020. Data Feminism. Cambridge, MA, USA: MIT Press.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
