    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cberger@sarahlawrence.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">claudiaeberger@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cberger@sarahlawrence.edu, evergreen.gabriella@gmail.com, qad@stanford.edu, plach@sdsu.edu, KayleighPerkov@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Berger, Claudia;&#10;Evergreen, Gabriella;&#10;Dombrowski, Quinn;&#10;Lach, Pamella R;&#10;Perkov, Kayleigh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cberger@sarahlawrence.edu;&#10;evergreen.gabriella@gmail.com;&#10;qad@stanford.edu;&#10;plach@sdsu.edu;&#10;KayleighPerkov@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">some ET some PT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">97.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">221</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1050</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shin, Lisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Very unique panel featuring scholars exploring ways to incorporate digital humanities research in crafts and other physical creative activities. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Always looking forward to hearing about different and unique ways to communicate and learn about research in the DH area! </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1093</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dwyer, Kaylen</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal clearly defines how physical, embodied, and slow data practices shift the discourse on labor practices in the digital humanities and call attention to the sometimes invisible processes of working with data. This panel embodies intersectional feminist work through both its topic and application, offering multiple examples for how scholars can embed feminist practice through scholarship, service, and craft.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal identifies that current language in DH is situated in white/male/blue collar terms, but it might be good to explain how that negatively impacts the field, especially with regard to the impact of using blue collar/working class terminology. This might slightly improve the clarity around communicating the significance and value of the work being done.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1314</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Susan Garfinkel, Susan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed session directly addresses ACH&#039;s interest in bringing a broadened diversity of content, method, and theoretical perspectives to digital humanities, by exploring the growing area of data physicalization through a set of experiences related to textiles. As the authors clearly state: &quot;This panel will focus on different approaches to using specifically textiles for data visualization, or data physicalization. Data physicalization, which is the process of creating physical data visualizations, gives us an opportunity to put our values into action with our research.&quot; They go on to explain that: &quot; Data physicalization can be a way to embody data feminism and other critical data practices: it is a slower data practice, our labor is front and center in the process, and we can cultivate a more intimate relationship with the data.&quot; The five participants will each address these issues through example, uniting their theoretical concerns with practice-based engagement in DH workin order to &quot;display the versatility of this method and weave connections between our projects.&quot; The authors also seek to demystify some of the methods used and decisions made in taking on textile-based maker project. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I look forward to attending this session! Data physicalization is an important next step for those of us thinking about making within the larger set of DH practices, and by focusing on one area of making, textile production, this session offers continuity of practices along with a variety of experience on the ground. &#10;&#10;The authors might consider ways to clarify and strengthen the connection between the possibly gendered nature of metaphors used in DH (too often “distinctly white, male, blue-collar”) and the reason to leap from some alternate non-white-male metaphors right into actual #DHmakes projects. Understanding that the panel is focused on practice rather than theory, I would still think this is a rich and porous boundary to explore a bit more deeply.&#10;&#10;I also wonder if there is room to consider textile making as an artistic or craft-aesthetic practice, and what may be operating here that makes the described practices DH and research and scholarship as well as or instead of aesthetic or practical production. I think about this especially because at ACH we are in part trying to explore or broaden DH beyond what has long been a social-scientific paradigm despite the DH label, into something that not only uses humanities data, but uses humanities approaches to the data as well. Artwork that engages data does, after all, seem to sit on the other side of the humanities along a continuum of areas and practices that engage the digital in some way and could well prove itself another useful foil in exploring the work of non-white-male making. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The adoption of &quot;data physicalization&quot; as a concept in DH making is a fairly recent and important development to share with the ACH community of practice.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
