    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Holographic Universe; Or How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love VR</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Virtual reality, language learning, application analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;South America&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;mobile applications development and analysis&#10;Anthropology&#10;Archaeology&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;Central American and Central American Studies&#10;Comparative and World Literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America&#10;South America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;mobile applications development and analysis&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Anthropology&#10;Archaeology&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;Central American and Central American Studies&#10;Comparative and World Literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;            From October of 2022 to the present, the VR Classroom—started as the VR Club for Language Learning—has had over 700 participants, mainly students, use either Meta Quest 2 or Meta Quest 1 headsets to augment the language learning experience. Through this time, I—along with co-founder Jhonatan Carmona and Isidoro Villa—have utilized a number of different video games and other virtual reality focused applications for the sake of bolstering language learning namely: YouTube VR, Lost Recipes, the Italian Cooking Application, ImmerseMe, Victory XR, and Language Lab. Each of these applications have their own purpose in the language learning classroom and thus can be weaved together throughout the semester to create a cohesive virtual reality component for the L2 classroom.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;            This presentation plans to discuss the creation of the VR Club and its transition to the VR Classroom, the trials-and-tribulations of using VR within a classroom environment, and how each of the aforementioned applications pair with language learning goals. The story of the VR Classroom is an important one to document and make available for other programs to learn from all the effort we have gone through overcoming the challenges we have been faced with from the start such as room and boundary organization, how to properly lesson plan for VR, and what happens when applications you rely on become unavailable. This has been paired with recognizing the power of the fictional that comes with VR (Juul 2019) and understanding how to mediate immersion and the benefits for learning it can give (Gaugne et al 2011, Murray 2016). VR has proved itself to be a worthwhile component to help with cultural, listening, and speaking goals, especially as it breaks the mold  the traditional classroom and brings students unique experiences.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">            From October of 2022 to the present, the VR Classroom—started as the VR Club for Language Learning—has had over 700 participants, mainly students, use either Meta Quest 2 or Meta Quest 1 headsets to augment the language learning experience. Through this time, I—along with co-founder Jhonatan Carmona and Isidoro Villa—have utilized a number of different video games and other virtual reality focused applications for the sake of bolstering language learning namely: YouTube VR, Lost Recipes, the Italian Cooking Application, ImmerseMe, Victory XR, and Language Lab. Each of these applications have their own purpose in the language learning classroom and thus can be weaved together throughout the semester to create a cohesive virtual reality component for the L2 classroom.&#10;            This presentation plans to discuss the creation of the VR Club and its transition to the VR Classroom, the trials-and-tribulations of using VR within a classroom environment, and how each of the aforementioned applications pair with language learning goals. The story of the VR Classroom is an important one to document and make available for other programs to learn from all the effort we have gone through overcoming the challenges we have been faced with from the start such as room and boundary organization, how to properly lesson plan for VR, and what happens when applications you rely on become unavailable. This has been paired with recognizing the power of the fictional that comes with VR (Juul 2019) and understanding how to mediate immersion and the benefits for learning it can give (Gaugne et al 2011, Murray 2016). VR has proved itself to be a worthwhile component to help with cultural, listening, and speaking goals, especially as it breaks the mold the traditional classroom and brings students unique experiences.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
