    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">222</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1114</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">O&#039;Neil, Erica</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal will detail the creation of the VR Classroom project for language learning higher education courses, with lessons learned during creation, integration, and continuing sustainability. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation is an interesting approach to integrating technology into a language learning setting, but would be strengthened by presenting evidence that substantiates the author&#039;s claims that VR is a value addition to students&#039; learning experience and goals. Addressing how to access these technologies in the most cost-efficient and equitable manner would also ensure that the broadest number of conference attendees could benefit from this project example. During presentation, I would also request that the authors also invite the audience into their experience by explaining jargon specific to their field of teaching, such as the L2 classroom. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1110</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rutner, Jennifer</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal covers the creation of a VR Classroom, the challenges of piloting new VR pedagogies, how the technology was employed in the context of language learning goals. The paper will also include the programmatic process of creating a VR classroom, and adapting VR technologies to support learning outcomes. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal has particular strengths in connecting the application of VR technology to learning outcomes for language classes, which falls under the theme of multilingualism. The proposal includes clear articulation of the applicability and practical value of using VR in a classroom setting. While the proposal focuses on technology and pedagogy, it would benefit from deeper connection to the conference themes regarding marginalized communities and/or critical DH theory. The proposal sufficiently references current scholarship on the topic, indicating a framework for working the technology. The authors are encouraged to consider including a more focused discussion of the sociopolitical implications of employing VR technology within the context of multilingual education. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal could be re-scaled to fit a lightning talk, but meets the criteria for an individual paper. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1207</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">King, Joey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Submitter has thoroughly outlined how the induction of VR in the classroom-- utilizing VR technology such as Meta Quest 1 and 2-- offers an immersive experience for students in language acquisition. The author draws from scholarship to explain &quot;how to mediate immersion and the benefits [in] learning&quot; a language.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper has great potential in highlighting ways in which a technology (such as VR) can be utilized in the classroom to not only acquire new language skills but also help students better immerse themselves within a specific cultural context that will ultimately aid in the development of deeper understanding of cultures that heretofore may have been unfamiliar to them. Highlighting the immersive nature of VR, and by drawing on scholarship that supports these claims, will help show the ways in which students can achieve the goals set forth in the classroom as it relates to acquiring new language skills. &#10;Some questions to consider: how has the institution (U of A) supported the use of VR? What types of pushback have been observed in regards to this approach to language acquisition? What obstacles and barriers must be confronted; such as financial constraints (for students and/or the institution) and how have those been overcome? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
