    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ghost Futures: Coral Bleaching Data Physicalization</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data physicalization, design, critical making, environmental data, climate change</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;3d printing, critical making&#10;eco-criticism and environmental analysis&#10;mixed-media analysis&#10;Design studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3d printing, critical making&#10;eco-criticism and environmental analysis&#10;mixed-media analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Design studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Data physicalization is a growing creative area that focuses on data representation through the creation of physical objects, both complementing and providing an alternative to visual, sonic, and narrative techniques. From early forms of stone counting and clay tablets to models made of wood, wire, and string to contemporary expressions of data in the forms of weaving, quilting, knitting, and\]sculpture, data physicalization has taken many unique forms. As an artist and designer, I am especially interested how we might represent environmental and climate data with an emphasis on expression, emotion, interpretation, and form. There are many data visualizations that highlight complex climate data, which can provide important information, however often in limited ways that adhere to conventions around visual design that are shaped primarily by a design tradition that has historically been dominated by white, western perspectives. Importantly, data physicalization offers us a broader and more humanistic way to engage with data that intentionally relies more on interpretation, emotion, affect, and interaction with evocative objects, and has the capacity to communicate data in more diverse, culturally relevant, and pluralistic ways.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;My proposed installation, Ghost Futures, is a data physicalization that explores coral bleaching and global heating data from the past 40 years. By weaving these data sets together, literally and figuratively, I use yarn, thread, and beads to build a visually engaging object. The piece utilizes reused objects and recycled materials, including an old radiator cover, which acts as a frame to hold the yarn that is woven between a metal grid to create a pattern that represents each year of data through color-coded, naturally dyed textiles. Within each section of yarn (each year) both colorful and white beads are utilized to represent the severity of various coral bleaching events that have happened over the past several decades. It is my hope that the piece connects viewers to climate data in a way that challenges conventions around computational data visualizations and expectations around what data can do and what kind of information it can provide. The piece is meant to function both as a piece of art and a critical design that encourages people to bring their own perspectives while finding meaning within a novel tangible interaction.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Data physicalization is a growing creative area that focuses on data representation through the creation of physical objects, both complementing and providing an alternative to visual, sonic, and narrative techniques. From early forms of stone counting and clay tablets to models made of wood, wire, and string to contemporary expressions of data in the forms of weaving, quilting, knitting, and\]sculpture, data physicalization has taken many unique forms. As an artist and designer, I am especially interested how we might represent environmental and climate data with an emphasis on expression, emotion, interpretation, and form. There are many data visualizations that highlight complex climate data, which can provide important information, however often in limited ways that adhere to conventions around visual design that are shaped primarily by a design tradition that has historically been dominated by white, western perspectives. Importantly, data physicalization offers us a broader and more humanistic way to engage with data that intentionally relies more on interpretation, emotion, affect, and interaction with evocative objects, and has the capacity to communicate data in more diverse, culturally relevant, and pluralistic ways.&#10;My proposed installation, Ghost Futures, is a data physicalization that explores coral bleaching and global heating data from the past 40 years. By weaving these data sets together, literally and figuratively, I use yarn, thread, and beads to build a visually engaging object. The piece utilizes reused objects and recycled materials, including an old radiator cover, which acts as a frame to hold the yarn that is woven between a metal grid to create a pattern that represents each year of data through color-coded, naturally dyed textiles. Within each section of yarn (each year) both colorful and white beads are utilized to represent the severity of various coral bleaching events that have happened over the past several decades. It is my hope that the piece connects viewers to climate data in a way that challenges conventions around computational data visualizations and expectations around what data can do and what kind of information it can provide. The piece is meant to function both as a piece of art and a critical design that encourages people to bring their own perspectives while finding meaning within a novel tangible interaction.</ss:Data></Cell>
