    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">77.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">90.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">54.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">223</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1136</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cary, Justin Robert</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission serves as both an incredibly expressive and important artistic artifact while simultaneous representing the important scholarly work of physically representing the visualization of data physically.  Specifically, this submission focuses on the impact of coral bleaching and global heating, visualizing data from the past 40 years in an artistic installation using reused objects and recycled materials.   </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I was so impressed, excited and privileged to be able to read your work.  This project sounds so important and so beautiful; I was moved by the way you have merged and mixed so many different disciplines here; art, craft, research, history, data, science, technology, humanities; these all come together to create something unique and distinct and it feels like you are really pushing the boundaries of what can be done with academic, data driven research here.  I love the artistic framework you have presented and I think this is such an incredible way to think about how to engage audiences in such important work.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Very impressive work here; I think this should for sure find a place at the conference. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1073</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ciotola, Mark</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Using physical and other recycled media to create physical representations of environmental data.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a potentially interesting and distinctive exhibit. Part of its value is how well it faithfully depicts the data, while part is in how the tangible nature adds secondary meaning. It is also hoped that the physical, 3D nature could make data visualization more tactile and available to the visually-impaired.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This exhibit could be great or awful, depending on how well it is constructed and how well it rigorously reflects data. It does not really involve computers or an advancement in data science, but it could nevertheless be thought-provoking and add visual variety to the usual sorts of posters and exhibits. The physical, 3D nature could make data visualization more tactile and available to the visually-impaired.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">54</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1108</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Moro, Jeffrey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission engages the environmental digital humanities through the design practice of data physicalization. It argues that data physicalization has advantages over other methods of data visualization/representation particularly on the grounds of expression and emotion -- that a crafted object can &quot;speak&quot; both to the underlying data that substantiates its design as well as the emotional valences of such data, which are all too often lost in translation into visual forms. Its case study uses coral bleaching data in tandem with techniques of weaving and beading. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I value this submission and strongly encourage its acceptance. I think it does two things that are vital for digital humanities today: first, to engage with practices of critical making, design, and craftsmanship in ways that enrich our field&#039;s thinking about data (how information becomes data, through what kinds of culturally situated practices, through what kinds of work, and with what kinds of expertise -- none of which are the exclusive province of electronic computation or white, Western knowledge work); and second, to bring those practices to bear on the environmental humanities. I have no reservations about the project as such; I recommend only that the creator bring more specificity to the claim that data physicalization &quot;offers us a broader and more humanistic way to engage with data that intentionally relies more on interpretation, emotion, affect, and interaction.&quot; What kinds of emotions are evoked through this work? Whose emotions -- that of the creator, the audience, communities of practice, et.c -- are instantiated in its creation? And how does interaction achieve specific scholarly goals that are not adequately captured by &quot;traditional&quot; techniques such as reading/viewing/etc. Bringing a clearer perspective to bear on the question of how data physicalization does things differently than data visualization will, I think, improve the project&#039;s capacity to speak to the wide-ranging audiences of the DH conference. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I have no other comments beyond my strong endorsement of this proposal. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
