    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cultural Appropriation in AI-Generated Art</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">AI, ChatGPT, Image Generation, Cultural Appropriation, Chinese Characters</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Asia&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital art production and analysis&#10;image processing and analysis&#10;Art history&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital art production and analysis&#10;image processing and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Art history&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This paper delves into the complexities and challenges of cultural and linguistic appropriation within Anglophone AI culture, particularly through the lens of image generation technologies. Building on the work of scholars like Safiyah Noble, Timnet Gebru, Emily Bender, and Joy Buolamwini, who have highlighted algorithmic injustices such as racism, misogyny, and bias in large language models, this study focuses on the misinterpretation and misuse of non-Anglophone cultures, using Chinese calligraphy as a case study.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In Chinese art, calligraphy and painting are deeply interconnected, with calligraphic aesthetics emphasizing elements like &quot;spirit resonance&quot; (气韵) and &quot;use of space&quot; (留白). These critical aspects are often neglected by AI models that rely on edge detection and feature extraction, leading to a significant loss of artistic essence and cultural meaning. The technical challenges of processing text in images, which include dealing with stylized fonts and artistic variations, further complicate the accurate representation of such texts. Consequently, models like Transformers tend to generate text as mere shapes, stripping away the underlying meaning.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;A practical example of this issue is observed with the DALL·E plugin in ChatGPT, where symbols generated to represent Chinese characters were neither legible nor understandable. Such inaccuracies, if unchecked, can propagate through social and professional contexts, causing significant cultural misunderstandings and potential harm. Similar issues are noted with Japanese and Korean texts, while Western languages such as English/French/Spanish/Italian are generally represented with fewer errors.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The paper underscores the importance of incorporating diverse cultural perspectives in the training of large AI models. It calls for modifications in attention mechanisms, rigorous output reviews, and the involvement of humanists from various cultural backgrounds to ensure high-quality and culturally sensitive training data. Addressing these issues is crucial for preventing the ongoing harm to cultural preservation and ensuring respectful and accurate representation in AI-generated content.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper delves into the complexities and challenges of cultural and linguistic appropriation within Anglophone AI culture, particularly through the lens of image generation technologies. Building on the work of scholars like Safiyah Noble, Timnet Gebru, Emily Bender, and Joy Buolamwini, who have highlighted algorithmic injustices such as racism, misogyny, and bias in large language models, this study focuses on the misinterpretation and misuse of non-Anglophone cultures, using Chinese calligraphy as a case study.&#10;In Chinese art, calligraphy and painting are deeply interconnected, with calligraphic aesthetics emphasizing elements like &quot;spirit resonance&quot; (气韵) and &quot;use of space&quot; (留白). These critical aspects are often neglected by AI models that rely on edge detection and feature extraction, leading to a significant loss of artistic essence and cultural meaning. The technical challenges of processing text in images, which include dealing with stylized fonts and artistic variations, further complicate the accurate representation of such texts. Consequently, models like Transformers tend to generate text as mere shapes, stripping away the underlying meaning.&#10;A practical example of this issue is observed with the DALL·E plugin in ChatGPT, where symbols generated to represent Chinese characters were neither legible nor understandable. Such inaccuracies, if unchecked, can propagate through social and professional contexts, causing significant cultural misunderstandings and potential harm. Similar issues are noted with Japanese and Korean texts, while Western languages such as English/French/Spanish/Italian are generally represented with fewer errors.&#10;The paper underscores the importance of incorporating diverse cultural perspectives in the training of large AI models. It calls for modifications in attention mechanisms, rigorous output reviews, and the involvement of humanists from various cultural backgrounds to ensure high-quality and culturally sensitive training data. Addressing these issues is crucial for preventing the ongoing harm to cultural preservation and ensuring respectful and accurate representation in AI-generated content.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
