    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African Building Heritage Project: a Praxis on Data Storytelling and Digital Memory</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Post Colonial Africa; Benin; Archives; Geospatial; Photogrammetry</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;French&#10;postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;Africa&#10;18th Century&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;digital archiving&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;African/Africana Studies&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;Transatlantic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;French</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Africa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">18th Century&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;digital archiving&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African/Africana Studies&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;Transatlantic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The African Building Heritage Project is an international and multidisciplinary team that is currently comprised of scholars in the United States and Benin. The American team is comprised of seven people: Killion Mokwete (Architecture), Patricia Davis (Communications/Cultural Studies), Jessica Parr (History/Archives), Bahare Sanaie-Movahed (GIS/Remote Sensing Specialist), Halima Haruna (History PhD Student), and Gavin Gershman (Architecture undergrad student). Dr. Franck Ogou, Director of L&#039;Ecole du Patrimoine African, leads the Porto Novo-based team. This project entails the production of 3D models (using LIDAR data produced with a laser-guided LEICA drone system) of historically significant at-risk sub-Saharan African buildings and georeferences them to produce a searchable web database in ESRI’s ArcGIS software. This geospatial archive uses technology as a preservation and access tool, to promote the study of African architecture and to preserve digital facsimiles of buildings that are at-risk due to climate change, resource limitations, and other challenges. The project is expected to create a model for future collaborations with local academics and community members in other sub-Saharan African locations, and one that specifically centers the communities that the project will document. This has been particularly important given recent conversations in Public History, Museum Studies, and Heritage Studies regarding ownership of cultural knowledge and artifacts for cultures and countries in the Global South. The project includes fieldwork from trips to Benin in December 2023 and June 2024 to scan 5 buildings, including a nineteenth century mosque built by Afro-Brazilian returnees. In addition to the ties to Brazil, Benin is an important cultural/intellectual root for Haitians in Haiti and elsewhere in the African Diaspora. The models the field work produces will be pushed to ESRI using the Drone2ArcGIS software and other ESRI packages, and the data modeling will come through Survey123. We have also begun using phone-based photogrammetry to document artifacts associated with the buildings in order to tell wholistic stories about them and the communities they serve. The presentation will include some pre-recorded content in French from our Beninois collaborators.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The African Building Heritage Project is an international and multidisciplinary team that is currently comprised of scholars in the United States and Benin. The American team is comprised of seven people: Killion Mokwete (Architecture), Patricia Davis (Communications/Cultural Studies), Jessica Parr (History/Archives), Bahare Sanaie-Movahed (GIS/Remote Sensing Specialist), Halima Haruna (History PhD Student), and Gavin Gershman (Architecture undergrad student). Dr. Franck Ogou, Director of L&#039;Ecole du Patrimoine African, leads the Porto Novo-based team. This project entails the production of 3D models (using LIDAR data produced with a laser-guided LEICA drone system) of historically significant at-risk sub-Saharan African buildings and georeferences them to produce a searchable web database in ESRI’s ArcGIS software. This geospatial archive uses technology as a preservation and access tool, to promote the study of African architecture and to preserve digital facsimiles of buildings that are at-risk due to climate change, resource limitations, and other challenges. The project is expected to create a model for future collaborations with local academics and community members in other sub-Saharan African locations, and one that specifically centers the communities that the project will document. This has been particularly important given recent conversations in Public History, Museum Studies, and Heritage Studies regarding ownership of cultural knowledge and artifacts for cultures and countries in the Global South. The project includes fieldwork from trips to Benin in December 2023 and June 2024 to scan 5 buildings, including a nineteenth century mosque built by Afro-Brazilian returnees. In addition to the ties to Brazil, Benin is an important cultural/intellectual root for Haitians in Haiti and elsewhere in the African Diaspora. The models the field work produces will be pushed to ESRI using the Drone2ArcGIS software and other ESRI packages, and the data modeling will come through Survey123. We have also begun using phone-based photogrammetry to document artifacts associated with the buildings in order to tell wholistic stories about them and the communities they serve. The presentation will include some pre-recorded content in French from our Beninois collaborators.</ss:Data></Cell>
