    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">225</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1239</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kunnuji, Joseph</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an intriguing project with the potential to highlight lesser-known histories, particularly those from Francophone Africa. The abstract could be improved by citing the scholarly works that the project engages with and by clearly stating the exact findings that will be presented at the conference. Overall, it is an excellent project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an intriguing project with the potential to highlight lesser-known histories, particularly those from Francophone Africa. The abstract could be improved by citing the scholarly works that the project engages with and by clearly stating the exact findings that will be presented at the conference. Overall, it is an excellent project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1307</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rehberger, Dean</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract for &quot;The African Building Heritage Project&quot; outlines an international and multidisciplinary initiative focused on preserving sub-Saharan African buildings at risk due to various challenges, including climate change and resource limitations. The project involves collaboration between scholars from the United States and Benin, led by Dr. Franck Ogou from L&#039;Ecole du Patrimoine African in Porto Novo.  To help review this panel, it may help to break out the parts that are more difficult to understand in the compact abstract format.&#10;&#10;Team Composition&#10;The American team includes:&#10;- Killion Mokwete (Architecture)&#10;- Patricia Davis (Communications/Cultural Studies)&#10;- Jessica Parr (History/Archives)&#10;- Bahare Sanaie-Movahed (GIS/Remote Sensing Specialist)&#10;- Halima Haruna (History PhD Student)&#10;- Gavin Gershman (Architecture undergrad student)&#10;&#10;Project Goals and Methods&#10;The project aims to produce 3D models of historically significant buildings using LIDAR data collected with a LEICA drone system. These models will be georeferenced and integrated into a searchable web database using ESRI&#039;s ArcGIS software. The geospatial archive will serve as a preservation tool and promote the study of African architecture.&#10;&#10;Fieldwork and Data Collection&#10;Fieldwork includes trips to Benin in December 2023 and June 2024 to scan five buildings, including a nineteenth-century mosque built by Afro-Brazilian returnees. The project also uses phone-based photogrammetry to document artifacts associated with these buildings, aiming to tell holistic stories about the buildings and their communities.&#10;&#10;Broader Impact&#10;The project seeks to create a model for future collaborations with local academics and community members in other sub-Saharan African locations. It emphasizes the importance of centering the communities documented, aligning with recent discussions in Public History, Museum Studies, and Heritage Studies about the ownership of cultural knowledge and artifacts in the Global South.&#10;&#10;Presentation&#10;The presentation will include pre-recorded content in French from Beninois collaborators, highlighting the project&#039;s collaborative and inclusive approach.&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In summarizing the abstract, I parsed it into the different categories of a panel presentation: team, project goals and methods, field work and data collection, and broader impacts, because I think the primary value for this conference and the DH audience would be the broader impacts.  The DH audience will always find the technology cool, particularly in this case that shows the clear value of LIDAR and mapping.  But the ethics implicit in the broader impacts: The project seeks to create a model for future collaborations with local academics and community members in other sub-Saharan African locations. It emphasizes the importance of centering the communities documented, aligning with recent discussions in Public History, Museum Studies, and Heritage Studies about the ownership of cultural knowledge and artifacts in the Global South -- are a key component of this panel and should be a focus for this conference.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">It is a bit outside of the normal scope of the DH conference but the work is an excellent example of how field work needs to be done in more ethical ways -- in the face of the very important need to save things before lost to climate change.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1310</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Alvarez, Maira Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project entails the production of 3D models (using LIDAR data produced with a laser-guided LEICA drone system) of historically significant at-risk sub-Saharan African buildings and georeferences them to produce a searchable web database in ESRI’s ArcGIS software. This geospatial archive uses technology as a preservation and access tool, to promote the study of African architecture and to preserve digital facsimiles of buildings that are at-risk due to climate change, resource limitations, and other challenges.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Overall, this is an excellent project focused on preservation of African architecture, culture and artifacts. This could bring great discussion regarding the technology implemented and strategies to execute such work.&#10;&#10;However, there are a few recommendations for the authors to consider for the proposal.&#10;&#10;1. Incorporation of Scholarly Works: The proposal would benefit from incorporating references to relevant scholarly works by situating the project within existing literature.&#10;&#10;2. Ethical Practices and Challenges: The authors note that the project aims to develop a model for future collaborations with local academics and community members in other sub-Saharan African locations, emphasizing the importance of centering the communities documented. This focus is particularly relevant in light of ongoing discussions in Public History, Museum Studies, and Heritage Studies about the ownership of cultural knowledge and artifacts from the Global South. It would be valuable to mention the ethical practices followed in the current documentation and to address the challenges encountered. Such information would enrich the panel discussion and research process, especially considering the proposal’s emphasis on technology.&#10;&#10;3. Documentation Process and Community Engagement: The proposal mentions fieldwork trips to Benin in December 2023 and June 2024 to document five buildings, including a nineteenth-century mosque constructed by Afro-Brazilian returnees. Additionally, it highlights Benin&#039;s significance as a cultural and intellectual root for the African Diaspora. To strengthen the proposal, it would be beneficial to provide more details about the process of selecting these buildings, the importance of their documentation, and the nature of engagement with the local communities. Information about obtaining permits, accessing sites, and any challenges faced would also connect with the previous point on ethical practices.&#10;&#10;I look forward to learning more about this project!&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This panel has potential, but the score is impacted by two key issues that I hope they resolve if accepted: insufficient information about the scholarship involved and unclear processes regarding the cultural artifacts. The current focus leans heavily towards the implementation of technology, which detracts from a more balanced discussion. &#10;&#10;I don’t have any problems accepting the panel.</ss:Data></Cell>
