    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">226</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1111</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Starry, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission outlines the development and outcomes of a course titled &quot;Social Justice in the Digital Humanities,&quot; reflecting on how we incorporate (and teach our students to incorporate) social justice frameworks and ethical considerations into digital humanities research.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper and the case-study/course it proposes to discuss would be an excellent contribution to this conference as the submission highlights issues of ethics and social justice in DH research and pedagogy.&#10;&#10;I would have liked to see more explicit definitions of &quot;social justice&quot; as these can vary across cultural contexts, as well as a more clear explanation of the connection of legal frameworks like copyright to the more ethical considerations of privacy, access, and ownership of content created by marginalized communities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1304</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Giselle Pempedjian, Giselle</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution of the submission is the development of a course on the #dariahTeach platform titled “Social Justice in the Digital Humanities.” It aims to highlight existing work and inspire future scholarship in digital humanities through a social justice lens. It addresses key ethical issues, showcases global case studies, and integrates relevant theories to promote best practices and ethical research.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission is valuable in its approach to integrating justice into digital humanities education through the #dariaTeach platform and highlighting and considering critical ethical issues. &#10;Adding concrete and specific examples of best practices and recommendations should be of great value.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1020</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Jensen, Graham</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission usefully pulls together scholarship and case studies on highly topical issues. In doing so, it promises to help shape the field of DH in ways that make it more attentive to social justice as a framework than can and should be brought to the fore in discussions of ethics, privacy, and copyright (as mentioned in the proposal), but also to considerations of knowledge diversity, Indigenous knowledges, bibliodiversity, and more.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a strong and compelling paper. I have very few suggestions for improvement, but I&#039;ll offer those here for the authors to consider if the submission is accepted for ACH 2024.&#10;&#10;The abstract mentions that “[t]he inspiration for this research came out of initiatives underway at many institutions to diversify the curriculum...”. Some of those initiatives have been lauded and appear to have created real, positive change. However, the abstract also alludes to theoretical discussions where, as I understand it (and I may be mistaken), other institutional initiatives have been criticized for coopting diversity, equality, and inclusion as part of an empty rhetorical gesture or form of virtue signalling within increasingly neoliberal university environments. That tension between theory/principles and implementation may be worth expanding on in the presentation (if that was not already part of the authors’ plan).&#10;&#10;In the paper itself, I would also look forward to learning more details about the course in its current form. For example, given that OER was listed among both the submission’s methods and keywords, is this course free, and—since the submission also alludes to licensing issues—will it be licensed in such a way as to allow for re-use? Will traditional knowledge (TK) labels be discussed (see, e.g., https://localcontexts.org/labels/traditional-knowledge-labels/)?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">N/A</ss:Data></Cell>
