    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The proposal introduces Indigo3D, an innovative XSLT-based 3D data-visualization tool designed to transform TEI (Text Encoding Initiative) documents. This transformative tool, which was created by the author at the University of Nebraska, presents an exploration of the results of MorphAdorner tagging, along with three-dimensional color-coded tree-animations, applied to 112 TEI-encoded texts by prominent Early Modern playwrights, including Shakespeare, Marlowe, Jonson, Middleton, and Shirley.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;As technology continues to shape the landscape of humanities research, this proposal unveils Indigo3D, a new tool that merges 3D visualization with morphological annotation. Tailored to work seamlessly with TEI documents, Indigo3D enhances textual analysis and enables an exciting avenue for fresh exploration and artistic visualization. Indigo3D&#039;s integration with Northwestern University&#039;s MorphAdorner is a key feature. MorphAdorner provides an extensive range of morphological annotations, including sentence splitting, tokenization, lemmatization, and part-of-speech tagging. Indigo3D leverages this wealth of linguistic information to create a bridge between traditional linguistic analysis and 3D visualization.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;We present an exploration of the results obtained by combining MorphAdorner tagging with semantic analysis applied to 112 TEI-encoded texts. These texts, primarily sourced from the Text Creation Partnership and Northwestern’s WordHoard, include works by Shakespeare, Marlowe, Jonson, Middleton, and Shirley. The immediate analysis focuses on comparing the presence of specific semantic characteristics within these texts, providing insights into linguistic patterns and stylistic nuances. We are presently extending our ambitions to include plays by Gertrude Stein and Langston Hughes, along with the novels of Willa Cather. This expansion involves the utilization of extensive textual holdings in TEI from the University of Nebraska&#039;s Center for Digital Research in the Humanities.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal introduces Indigo3D, an innovative XSLT-based 3D data-visualization tool designed to transform TEI (Text Encoding Initiative) documents. This transformative tool, which was created by the author at the University of Nebraska, presents an exploration of the results of MorphAdorner tagging, along with three-dimensional color-coded tree-animations, applied to 112 TEI-encoded texts by prominent Early Modern playwrights, including Shakespeare, Marlowe, Jonson, Middleton, and Shirley.&#10;As technology continues to shape the landscape of humanities research, this proposal unveils Indigo3D, a new tool that merges 3D visualization with morphological annotation. Tailored to work seamlessly with TEI documents, Indigo3D enhances textual analysis and enables an exciting avenue for fresh exploration and artistic visualization. Indigo3D&#039;s integration with Northwestern University&#039;s MorphAdorner is a key feature. MorphAdorner provides an extensive range of morphological annotations, including sentence splitting, tokenization, lemmatization, and part-of-speech tagging. Indigo3D leverages this wealth of linguistic information to create a bridge between traditional linguistic analysis and 3D visualization.&#10;We present an exploration of the results obtained by combining MorphAdorner tagging with semantic analysis applied to 112 TEI-encoded texts. These texts, primarily sourced from the Text Creation Partnership and Northwestern’s WordHoard, include works by Shakespeare, Marlowe, Jonson, Middleton, and Shirley. The immediate analysis focuses on comparing the presence of specific semantic characteristics within these texts, providing insights into linguistic patterns and stylistic nuances. We are presently extending our ambitions to include plays by Gertrude Stein and Langston Hughes, along with the novels of Willa Cather. This expansion involves the utilization of extensive textual holdings in TEI from the University of Nebraska&#039;s Center for Digital Research in the Humanities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pytlik Zillig, Brian Leslie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Nebraska</ss:Data></Cell>
