    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bzillig1@unl.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bzillig1@unl.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pytlik Zillig, Brian Leslie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bzillig1@unl.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Central Standad Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">62.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">48.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">227</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1241</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ahrenberg, Lars</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution is the presentation of a new tool that takes TEI documents as input and offers  3d rendering of morphological annotation. The primary data to be visualized are English drama and literature from the University of Nebraska&#039;s Center for Digital Research in the Humanities.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The way I understand the tool is that it enables 3d visualizations of TEI-encoded historic literature. The authors claim that this will provide &quot;an exciting avenue for fresh exploration and artistic visualization&quot;. Although the authors promise to show the value of the tool for displaying semantic characteristics of texts they do not provide any examples of what 3d-rendering could give a user that 2d-visualisation can&#039;t apart from the esthetics. The submission would be more convincing with such concrete examples.&#10;&#10;It was not clear to me whether the use of the term Indigo in the name of the tool refers to the Indigo Renderer or ehther the tool was entirely developed in-house.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">48</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1287</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kreutel, Jörn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The contribution presents a 3D visualisation tool intergrated with TEI via XSLT and aims at demonstrating it given the morphological and semantic analysis of a range of selected texts of English literature.&#10; </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3D visualisations of the outcomes of analysis of any kind appears an interesting option for giving intuitive and handleable access to complex analysis results in the area of DH. In this sense, the contribution&#039;s relevance hints beyond its particular employment in the area of text analysis. With regards to the latter, it would have been desirable for the authors to briefly mention, even to an audience with a wide range of interests like the one of ACH 2024, some particularly striking aspect of the analyses that have been carried out rather than just mentioning the generic outcome of &quot;providing insights into linguistic patterns and stylistic nuances&quot;. Further, focusing on particular advantages of 3D vs. 2D visualisation in the given area of application would further strengthen the authors&#039; argument. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In case the contribution is not accepted as an individual paper it would deserve being accepted as a poster presentation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1139</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">van Zaanen, Menno</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission describes the introduction of a 3d visualization tools that can take annotated text as input. It provides a novel way of visualizing the structure (as annotated using TEI) of the text.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Even though the submission describes an interesting tool (as it is difficult to get a good sense of what &quot;happens&quot; in larger texts), there seems to be quite a bit of repetition in the submission.  E.g., &quot;The proposal introduces Indigo3D&quot; versus &quot;this proposal unveils Indigo3D&quot;.  I believe that these aspects of the submission can be made more compact which will then leave more space to describe what one sees when analyzing a text using the tool.&#10;&#10;In a linguistic context, morphology relates to the structure within words. This does not include structure as the result of &quot;sentence splitting, tokenization, lemmatization, and part-of-speech tagging&quot; as these are above the word level. Removing the term morphology and replacing it with linguistic structure (or something similar) will make the text more concrete (if I understand what the tool does).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">60</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
