    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Mutable Type</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3D printing, movable type, letterpress</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;North America&#10;15th-17th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;3d printing, critical making&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;Art history&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Design studies&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">15th-17th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3d printing, critical making&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Art history&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Design studies&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This lightning talk provides an overview of an exercise on 3D printing movable type based on historic or archival specimens and examples. This process was incorporated into the class Cultural Heritage in the Digital Age and drew from the university’s special collections and archival materials to identify woodcut initials and historically significant typography. Students learned to digitize and prepare their initials and typography for 3D printing and/or laser engraving in accordance with movable type conventions and dimensions. The resulting type was then used in a selection of hand presses to produce prints. Students engaged with ideas and methods related to critical making and reflections on how printing technologies impact design. Students were also asked to reflect on the reciprocity between the analogue and the digital as it related to their moveable type projects and how different typographic experiments and glitched processes impacted their final designs.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk provides an overview of an exercise on 3D printing movable type based on historic or archival specimens and examples. This process was incorporated into the class Cultural Heritage in the Digital Age and drew from the university’s special collections and archival materials to identify woodcut initials and historically significant typography. Students learned to digitize and prepare their initials and typography for 3D printing and/or laser engraving in accordance with movable type conventions and dimensions. The resulting type was then used in a selection of hand presses to produce prints. Students engaged with ideas and methods related to critical making and reflections on how printing technologies impact design. Students were also asked to reflect on the reciprocity between the analogue and the digital as it related to their moveable type projects and how different typographic experiments and glitched processes impacted their final designs.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Reay, Danielle</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Drew University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">dreay@drew.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">dreay@drew.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Reay, Danielle</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">dreay@drew.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">62.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">50.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">228</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1293</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tew, Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk will present an experiential learning exercise on creating moveable type through 3D printing.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think these points criteria are a bit much for lightning talks.That’s why those scores are relatively low but my overall recommendation is high. If this proposal is accepted, I would like to hear student feedback on the exercisie, how successful the exercise was from the instructor’s perspective, and what resources were required to do this activity. Photos would also be great.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">50</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1286</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sparks, Corey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract clearly details a critical making activity undertaken with students that combines using archival materials to create models to be used for 3D printing.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract is clear and concise, suggesting a strong sense of scope and purpose which lends itself to the lightning talk format. The articulation of steps students take in archival research, making, and reflection is well done. While the abstract could do more to explicitly connect the work to &quot;to anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, and/or multilingualism,&quot; they key presence of reflection and the critical dimensions of the making imply such engagement. Further articulation of the kinds of archives educators might turn to in doing this kind of work could make more explicit, for example, anti-racist, intersectional feminist, or queer studies dimensions.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1230</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">MacKenzie, James</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A review of a course-based exercise fusing modern &quot;maker&quot; technology with an exploration of historical printing technology. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This will make a great lightning talk: an interesting teaching project that fuses &quot;maker&quot; tech with historical printing technology. There are some examples of similar projects/approaches I&#039;ve seen described elsewhere (see Jacobs in RBM 19.1, 2018). You may wish to talk a bit about how your approach extends or builds on earlier efforts. Practical takeaways (shared models? plans) for your audience would be most helpful. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">My final score for this evaluation looks bad, but is mostly due to the poor score in the &quot;relevance&quot; question. I think this would be fine as either a poster or, as proposed, a lightning talk. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
