    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Can DH give MPhil/PhD students of English studies Autonomy and Purpose in Research in Pakistan? Or is it Digital Dystopia?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital humanities, digital dystopia, English studies, autonomy, Pakistani students</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;Asia&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;electronic literature, production and analysis&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Literary studies&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;electronic literature, production and analysis&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Literary studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;With Digital Humanities (DH) being very much in the humanities’ air, I am alarmed by this new whiff called digital dystopia. I hear academics in English studies translating digital humanities into digital imperialism surveilling people of colour and their coloured literature in English. In doing so, ironically, they are borrowing terms from DH: like ‘Black Digital Feminism’, ‘Digital Imperialism’, ‘Racial Literacy’, ‘Digital Intersectionality’, ‘Digital Cultures’, ‘People of Colour’, and ‘Gendered Data’. There are some who find digital humanities to be a traitor in English studies who intends to sabotage the grand narratives of writers of colour and their position in the Global South; there are others who are shouting out to be wary of this paperless space of DH because it is taking us away from the fine aesthetics of hard bound English literary texts, or literatures in English, and their literariness.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Interestingly, the humanities critics warning us of digital dystopia are necessitating the need for digital humanities in English studies in Pakistan. These critics are making use of the digital literary spaces to voice their opinions on the Englishness of literature in the digital age. They are choosing to publish their manuscripts digitally because of the following reasons: first, digitalized literary texts are a quick way to get published and known, as the digital page and its meta-data make one unforgettable to a global audience; secondly, approaching big white publishers has always challenged the perseverance of writers of colour.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Since this use and abuse of digital humanities is going hand in hand, it brings me to think about this matter from a broader perspective within the discipline of English Studies. In Pakistani universities, we encourage original research in MPhil and Phd research programmes. Where does this original research in English literature begin from in a third-world country?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">With Digital Humanities (DH) being very much in the humanities’ air, I am alarmed by this new whiff called digital dystopia. I hear academics in English studies translating digital humanities into digital imperialism surveilling people of colour and their coloured literature in English. In doing so, ironically, they are borrowing terms from DH: like ‘Black Digital Feminism’, ‘Digital Imperialism’, ‘Racial Literacy’, ‘Digital Intersectionality’, ‘Digital Cultures’, ‘People of Colour’, and ‘Gendered Data’. There are some who find digital humanities to be a traitor in English studies who intends to sabotage the grand narratives of writers of colour and their position in the Global South; there are others who are shouting out to be wary of this paperless space of DH because it is taking us away from the fine aesthetics of hard bound English literary texts, or literatures in English, and their literariness.&#10;Interestingly, the humanities critics warning us of digital dystopia are necessitating the need for digital humanities in English studies in Pakistan. These critics are making use of the digital literary spaces to voice their opinions on the Englishness of literature in the digital age. They are choosing to publish their manuscripts digitally because of the following reasons: first, digitalized literary texts are a quick way to get published and known, as the digital page and its meta-data make one unforgettable to a global audience; secondly, approaching big white publishers has always challenged the perseverance of writers of colour.&#10;Since this use and abuse of digital humanities is going hand in hand, it brings me to think about this matter from a broader perspective within the discipline of English Studies. In Pakistani universities, we encourage original research in MPhil and Phd research programmes. Where does this original research in English literature begin from in a third-world country?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">CHEEMA, AMNA UMER</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">UNIVERSITY OF THE PUNJAB</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pakistan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">aminaumer@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">aminaumer@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">CHEEMA, AMNA UMER</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">aminaumer@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global South</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">52.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">32.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">230</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1163</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Nguyen, Cindy Anh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">insightful invitation into digital humanities in English studies in Pakistan, and problematizing DH use/abuse</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This topic is of critical importance to decenter global north narratives of DH; Yet I think it would be helpful if the author situated more context and specific examples/areas of inquiry in which they will focus the analysis of digital dystopia and use/abuses of DH in the case of Pakistan. I hope to see this presentation, especially with additional context of method and scope!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1130</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Murphy, Emily Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Traces the emergence of a concepts of “digital dystopia” and considers its implications for graduate training in English Literature scholarship in Pakistan. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">There is real potential in this topic that is very worthwhile to develop. The author identifies some of the ways that criticism of DH often uses the same terms developed within the field and the ways that digital publishing and DH have shifted the politics of and representation in literary publishing. Especially as DH has been so dominated by white and global north disciplines and scholars, it’s reasonable to ask what some of these shifts might mean for training and research in Pakistani universities. &#10;&#10;To improve the abstract, I suggest that the authors refine the question that they’d like to ask. Since the abstract lands with a question about graduate training, I suggest that the authors flesh out a critical framework that addresses existing research related to DH training in the global South. Scholars like Angel David Nieves, Alex Gil, Kush Patel, and Roopika Risam would be great places to start. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">My expertise is in digital pedagogy and curriculum development. As I work in Canada, I am less familiar with the application of these fields in Pakistan. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">32</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1303</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Roy, Samya Brata</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The contribution tries to identify the conflict of digital humanities with traditional streams like English Studies in Pakistan. It also tries to make an argument about original research in Pakistani universities that DH can facilitate. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract highlights an important point in talking about the situation of DH within English Studies in Pakistan and is something that suits very well with the theme of the conference. However, the abstract could have benefitted from citing some relevant scholarship especially the likes of Matthew Kirschenbaum, Roopika Risam, etc. As the author seems to be speaking from experience, the auto-ethnographic perspective or respective framework could have been laid out better as well.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">52</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">-1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rejected</ss:Data></Cell>
