    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Speech, Song, and the Gender Binary in AudioSet</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gender, Voice, Speech, Datasets, AudioSet, MusicCaps</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Queer Studies&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;cultural analytics&#10;music and sound digitization, encoding, and analysis&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Musicology&#10;Transgender and non-binary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;cultural analytics&#10;music and sound digitization, encoding, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Queer Studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Musicology&#10;Transgender and non-binary studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This paper explores points of epistemic tension between the conceptualizations of gender and voice in audio captioning datasets and humanistic approaches to the voice. Using the annotated audio dataset AudioSet (2017), including the MusicCaps (2023) subset, we contend that the critical study of gender labeling in datasets present a fruitful opportunity to rethink and redefine the relationship between gender and voice.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;NLP and audio analysis tools are applied to AudioSet samples, which consist of manually annotated verbal descriptions of 10-second audio clips, to assess how gender is represented in the data. We sample all clips with gender-related captions for the singing voice in the 5.5k sample MusicCaps subset and create a similar-sized speech dataset from the remaining AudioSet samples. With these data we highlight three assumptions about gender in AudioSet: 1) the assumption of a gender binary; 2) an immutable, one-to-one mapping between biological sex and voice; and 3) that an individual’s gender identity is knowable through their voice.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The paper challenges these assumptions by putting them in dialogue with recent work in voice studies, trans* studies, and musicology. Amidst calls for more inclusive AI models that reduce the reification of gender stereotypes, we propose three potential critically-informed approaches to gender in audio dataset creation: 1) encoding vocalist-generated gender labels, 2) using timbral and pitch descriptors instead of gender; and 3) opting out of “datafying” gender for the sake of privacy and opacity, drawing on Sterne and Sawhney’s recent intervention (2022).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper explores points of epistemic tension between the conceptualizations of gender and voice in audio captioning datasets and humanistic approaches to the voice. Using the annotated audio dataset AudioSet (2017), including the MusicCaps (2023) subset, we contend that the critical study of gender labeling in datasets present a fruitful opportunity to rethink and redefine the relationship between gender and voice.&#10;NLP and audio analysis tools are applied to AudioSet samples, which consist of manually annotated verbal descriptions of 10-second audio clips, to assess how gender is represented in the data. We sample all clips with gender-related captions for the singing voice in the 5.5k sample MusicCaps subset and create a similar-sized speech dataset from the remaining AudioSet samples. With these data we highlight three assumptions about gender in AudioSet: 1) the assumption of a gender binary; 2) an immutable, one-to-one mapping between biological sex and voice; and 3) that an individual’s gender identity is knowable through their voice.&#10;The paper challenges these assumptions by putting them in dialogue with recent work in voice studies, trans* studies, and musicology. Amidst calls for more inclusive AI models that reduce the reification of gender stereotypes, we propose three potential critically-informed approaches to gender in audio dataset creation: 1) encoding vocalist-generated gender labels, 2) using timbral and pitch descriptors instead of gender; and 3) opting out of “datafying” gender for the sake of privacy and opacity, drawing on Sterne and Sawhney’s recent intervention (2022).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Duguay, Michèle</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mduguay@fas.harvard.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mduguay@fas.harvard.edu, johanna.devaney@brooklyn.cuny.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Duguay, Michèle;&#10;Devaney, Johanna</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mduguay@fas.harvard.edu;&#10;johanna.devaney@brooklyn.cuny.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">83.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">231</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1199</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Stevens, Nikki</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors are evaluating gender classification in voice datasets and arguing for an updated, trans-informed handling of gender in this context. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is important work - the gender binary (or perhaps in this case also the sex binary) reappears in datasets across disciplines and domains.  The authors support their argument with an evaluation of how gender has historically been treated in these datasets. I am glad to see that they also offer design interventions, including moving away from gender labels entirely and moving towards descriptions of the quality and characteristics of the voice itself. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1107</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fitzgerald, Karina Marie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission uses quantifiable data outputs from existing technologies to highlight flaws in the way that audio data is interpreted, and the consequences of how data is sorted using these technologies can be framed through a lens of queer studies and gender and sexuality studies. Rethinking our assumptions about one&#039;s voice and gender is a critical discussion of gender studies, uniquely paired with musicology theory.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a strong proposal with great potential depending on the results and interpretation of the data sets. Significant findings can have an impact on the scholarship of gender studies, where research has largely been focused on human interpretations of one&#039;s gender in association with one&#039;s voice. Turning a critical eye to artificially intelligent tools and their mechanics of evaluating data is critical to the discussion of non-binary means of data evaluation and the significance data interpretations have in larger social and cultural contexts. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1234</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fruttaldo, Antonio</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract presents a compelling study on the epistemic tensions between conceptualisations of gender and voice in audio captioning datasets.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While the study is promising, several theoretical and methodological aspects need refinement to enhance its scholarly rigour. For examples, the abstract introduces key concepts such as &quot;epistemic tension&quot; and &quot;gender labeling&quot; but these concepts need clearer definitions and theoretical grounding. Also, the study spans multiple disciplines, including NLP, audio analysis, voice studies, trans* studies, and musicology. In this sense, the abstract would benefit from a more explicit discussion of how these interdisciplinary perspectives will be integrated. For example, how will insights from trans* studies inform the critique of gender labeling in audio datasets? There is also a brief mention of &quot;recent work in voice studies, trans* studies, and musicology&quot; but the abstract lacks a substantive engagement with existing literature. Indeed, a more thorough literature review that situates the study within current debates on gender and voice in data annotation and AI ethics will provide a clearer theoretical background.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
