    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sweet Like Justice: Using Digital Humanities to Amplify Marginalized Voices</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">exhibits, digital exhibits, civil rights, academic libraries, black history</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;project design, organization, and management&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;History&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">project design, organization, and management&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African American/Black Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;History&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&#10;&lt;p&gt;As a part of a public land-grant institution, Mississippi State University (MSU) Libraries strive to support teaching and research on campus and beyond by providing equitable and inclusive access to services and resources. This fundamental goal is echoed in the work of several librarians who seek to uplift the voices of traditionally marginalized communities in their professional practice, specifically within the context of digital spaces.  &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;For instance, a student-centered project takes place every semester in collaboration with students taking EN 3414: Critical Writing and Research for Literary Studies. Students in this course must complete weekly library instruction where they are taught research skills necessary for their discipline. Using these skills, students work symbiotically to create both physical and digital exhibits using archival materials to tell a cohesive story about a historical event or period. This project has proven popular with students because they feel emotionally connected to the materials they study, diversify their skillsets, and leave the course with tangible evidence of their work that is accessible to wide-ranging audiences.  &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In addition to student-curated projects, the library hosts digital exhibits designed by librarians to document the struggles and triumphs of Black Mississippians in their ongoing fight for justice. One exhibit created for the local NAACP showcased documents related to Fannie Lou Hamer, while another celebrated “Black Heroes of Mississippi” by highlighting a new figure each day of the month. The library also hosts a digital exhibit called “Against All Odds: The First Black Legislators in Mississippi,” where students, researchers, and genealogists can find information about the Black men who served as state and national legislators during Reconstruction. The exhibit is used each summer to facilitate research in a class at the Mississippi Governor’s School, an academic camp for high school students. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p lang=&quot;en-us&quot; xml:lang=&quot;en-us&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Finally, the Libraries have also supported community-engaged digital projects spearheaded by campus groups. In Spring 2024, the Digital Ethnic Studies class, using materials housed at MSU Libraries’ Division of Archives and Special Collections and in consultation with members of the local NAACP chapter, created “A Black Physician’s Story: The Douglas Conner Digital Project” to tell the story of one of Starkville’s most beloved Civil Rights figures. In addition to the website, the students also planned a community event to promote the project and educate the public not only about Douglas Conner but also about archives, collecting cultural memory, and digital projects.  &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In this roundtable, librarians KC New, DeeDee Baldwin, and Carrie P. Mastley will center discussion around these projects to stimulate conversations about making library resources more accessible as well as prioritizing projects that amplify the voices of the traditionally marginalized. The speakers will outline the intricacies of each project, successes, and lessons learned. The presenters hope their discussion stimulates new ideas for incorporating social justice-centered digital projects in library practice.    &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As a part of a public land-grant institution, Mississippi State University (MSU) Libraries strive to support teaching and research on campus and beyond by providing equitable and inclusive access to services and resources. This fundamental goal is echoed in the work of several librarians who seek to uplift the voices of traditionally marginalized communities in their professional practice, specifically within the context of digital spaces. &#10;For instance, a student-centered project takes place every semester in collaboration with students taking EN 3414: Critical Writing and Research for Literary Studies. Students in this course must complete weekly library instruction where they are taught research skills necessary for their discipline. Using these skills, students work symbiotically to create both physical and digital exhibits using archival materials to tell a cohesive story about a historical event or period. This project has proven popular with students because they feel emotionally connected to the materials they study, diversify their skillsets, and leave the course with tangible evidence of their work that is accessible to wide-ranging audiences. &#10;In addition to student-curated projects, the library hosts digital exhibits designed by librarians to document the struggles and triumphs of Black Mississippians in their ongoing fight for justice. One exhibit created for the local NAACP showcased documents related to Fannie Lou Hamer, while another celebrated “Black Heroes of Mississippi” by highlighting a new figure each day of the month. The library also hosts a digital exhibit called “Against All Odds: The First Black Legislators in Mississippi,” where students, researchers, and genealogists can find information about the Black men who served as state and national legislators during Reconstruction. The exhibit is used each summer to facilitate research in a class at the Mississippi Governor’s School, an academic camp for high school students. &#10; &#10;Finally, the Libraries have also supported community-engaged digital projects spearheaded by campus groups. In Spring 2024, the Digital Ethnic Studies class, using materials housed at MSU Libraries’ Division of Archives and Special Collections and in consultation with members of the local NAACP chapter, created “A Black Physician’s Story: The Douglas Conner Digital Project” to tell the story of one of Starkville’s most beloved Civil Rights figures. In addition to the website, the students also planned a community event to promote the project and educate the public not only about Douglas Conner but also about archives, collecting cultural memory, and digital projects. &#10;In this roundtable, librarians KC New, DeeDee Baldwin, and Carrie P. Mastley will center discussion around these projects to stimulate conversations about making library resources more accessible as well as prioritizing projects that amplify the voices of the traditionally marginalized. The speakers will outline the intricacies of each project, successes, and lessons learned. The presenters hope their discussion stimulates new ideas for incorporating social justice-centered digital projects in library practice.   </ss:Data></Cell>
