    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">dbaldwin@library.msstate.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">dbaldwin@library.msstate.edu, cmastley@library.msstate.edu, knew@library.msstate.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Baldwin, DeeDee;&#10;Mastley, Carrie P.;&#10;New, KC</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">dbaldwin@library.msstate.edu;&#10;cmastley@library.msstate.edu;&#10;knew@library.msstate.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Central</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">232</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1291</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pollock, Caitlin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution of this submission is how academic libraries and librarians can support digital humanities projects that highlight Black history and engage student learning through technological support and access to library&#039;s collections. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think the idea of this panel is a good one but I think I would like to see more details on practices, challenges, workflows etc that the library or librarians either faced or created in order to better work with digital humanities social justice projects that would be discussed in the roundtable. I want to hear more about how the libraries interacted with these projects and what they learned that make the process better. This would have strengthened the abstract by providing an opportunity to show how the authors have engaged with scholarship related to these types of library DH projects or social justice works. It is possible to do digital projects on Black history and for the project not to engage with social justice and anti-racism. How did the library engage with anti-racism etc, doing these projects? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1110</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rutner, Jennifer</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal outlines three collaborative projects that &quot;seek to uplift the voices of traditionally marginalized communities in their professional practice, specifically within the context of digital spaces.&quot; The proposal includes discussion of three such projects--one incorporated into a English course, one created by librarians which features black history content, and one community-collaboration also featuring black history content. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This very strong proposal is relevant to the social justice themes of the conference, and provides solid examples of how librarians can prioritize diverse pedagogical approaches when creating DH projects. The community in which this library is situated has a strong connection to local Black history, and that is centered in the projects discussed. While the proposal focuses on discussion of the projects, it could benefit from more directly articulating the frameworks being employed, and the theoretical (anti-racist, cultural studies, de-colonial, etc.) context for the work. Overall, this proposal is a strong example of the practical ways that librarians can employ critical DH methods to engage students, faculty, and community members in de-colonizing local history. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This round table is well-positioned to engage librarians who are interested in diversifying their pedagogical frameworks for digital projects, instruction, and community engagement. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1268</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Juarez, Miguel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Seeks to amplify the marginalized voices of the region.&#10;&#10;The proposed panel seeks to stimulate new ideas for incorporating social justice-centered digital projects in library practice.  &#10;&#10;Has the group heard of the Social Responsibilities Round table (SRRT) of the American Library Association?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Proposal doesn&#039;t fully explain what are the &quot;digital exhibits designed by librarians.&quot;  &#10;&#10;Examples of the digital spaces would have helped by offering examples.&#10;&#10;Are the student-curated projects the result of courses?  If so, what courses?&#10;&#10;A lot is going on in this proposal which is not fully explained.&#10;&#10;The Digital Humanities aspects of these presented needed to be presenting higher to the top, as well as better, as better explained and named.  &#10;&#10;Do students gain experience by working on digital projects or are they more of the purview of the librarians and perhaps their student staffs?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The content proposal is rich, but how do these areas translate into searchable products that can be used by students and community members for teaching, learning and documentation of history?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
