    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In SoliDHarity: Forming, Practicing, and Defending our Values</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">activism, libraries, digital humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Higher education is under attack now more than ever. It can be all too easy for the digital humanities practitioner to feel caught between external threats to the spirit of our work and internal friction from our failing institutions. This workshop offers participants the opportunity to meet these difficulties with a digital humanities practice that recommits to community values and the actions to support them. Each of us has engaged in intentional design and community building to create spaces for working in digital humanities through a set of shared values. While much of our work is based in libraries, our collective efforts to organize our labor around shared principles extend well beyond the library. In this session, we will share our experiences developing and enacting community values, with an emphasis on ways of transforming values into action/praxis in a range of institutional and community contexts.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Workshop activities will include guided writing prompts, scenario discussions, environmental resource scans, and the development of toolkits for rapid response to institutional crises. Case studies will be drawn from the facilitators’ own experiences with collective action, social media harassment, conflict resolution, administrative retaliation, accountability practices, prioritizing individual and collective well-being, knowing when to fight and when to step back, and more. By the end of our time together, workshop participants will be equipped to better communicate the values at the heart of their digital humanities practice and be better prepared to defend them with action.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Higher education is under attack now more than ever. It can be all too easy for the digital humanities practitioner to feel caught between external threats to the spirit of our work and internal friction from our failing institutions. This workshop offers participants the opportunity to meet these difficulties with a digital humanities practice that recommits to community values and the actions to support them. Each of us has engaged in intentional design and community building to create spaces for working in digital humanities through a set of shared values. While much of our work is based in libraries, our collective efforts to organize our labor around shared principles extend well beyond the library. In this session, we will share our experiences developing and enacting community values, with an emphasis on ways of transforming values into action/praxis in a range of institutional and community contexts.&#10;Workshop activities will include guided writing prompts, scenario discussions, environmental resource scans, and the development of toolkits for rapid response to institutional crises. Case studies will be drawn from the facilitators’ own experiences with collective action, social media harassment, conflict resolution, administrative retaliation, accountability practices, prioritizing individual and collective well-being, knowing when to fight and when to step back, and more. By the end of our time together, workshop participants will be equipped to better communicate the values at the heart of their digital humanities practice and be better prepared to defend them with action.</ss:Data></Cell>
