    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pixel Puppeteers</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sock Puppets, Online Identity, Deception, Online Communities, Digital Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;cultural analytics&#10;rhetorical analysis&#10;Gender and sexuality studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cultural analytics&#10;rhetorical analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gender and sexuality studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Traditionally, digital sock puppets are defined as online accounts created under deceptive pretenses for malicious use. Yet as this practice becomes more common, and the lines that define online identity blur, this rigid definition may no longer be of use. Instead, this research complicates the narrative, challenging the idea that all digital deception is malicious. Using a robust critical rhetorical inquiry this research seeks to understand the wide variety of uses for sock puppets, including but not limited to, self-promotion, anonymous slander, astroturfing, category deception, observation, and attention seeking, and the ways that these online behaviors impact both the puppet master and the online communities they infiltrate.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Traditionally, digital sock puppets are defined as online accounts created under deceptive pretenses for malicious use. Yet as this practice becomes more common, and the lines that define online identity blur, this rigid definition may no longer be of use. Instead, this research complicates the narrative, challenging the idea that all digital deception is malicious. Using a robust critical rhetorical inquiry this research seeks to understand the wide variety of uses for sock puppets, including but not limited to, self-promotion, anonymous slander, astroturfing, category deception, observation, and attention seeking, and the ways that these online behaviors impact both the puppet master and the online communities they infiltrate.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
