    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">48.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">26.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">237</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1107</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fitzgerald, Karina Marie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers a newer and more nuanced entry into the research on digital sock puppets. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This entry has potential for an interesting discussion on the use of digital sock puppets, but fails to clearly articulate relevance to gender and sexuality studies. More context about the rhetorical inquiry strategies that draw upon gender and sexuality theory would be helpful in understanding the direction of this submission, or perhaps it needs to be re-categorized.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">52</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1159</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Duguay, Michèle</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission explores the variety of contexts in which digital sock puppets are used. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission is relevant to the conference themes, but would benefit from more framing and more engagement with secondary literature. More details on these topics would clarify the project&#039;s contribution to gender and sexuality studies. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">26</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1207</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">King, Joey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal aims to interrogate the intents, purposes and implications of online digital sock puppets, and seeks to disrupt the idea that &quot;all digital deception is malicious&quot;  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a interesting topic for lightning talk and has potential to align more closely with multiple aspects of the conference themes, particularly if the submitter focuses on ways in which online digital sock puppets have been found to combat racist ideologies online as well as support marginalized communities. Drawing on existing scholarship related to digital sock puppets will strengthen this talks rhetorical framework in solidifying how these online personas have come to be understood as malicious. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">66</ss:Data></Cell>
