    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Migrants and the State: Machine Learning and Digital Access to Government Migration Records</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Immigration, Machine Learning, Archives, Metadata</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;South America&#10;Global&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;data modeling&#10;digital archiving&#10;metadata standards, systems, and methods&#10;History&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;South America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data modeling&#10;digital archiving&#10;metadata standards, systems, and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">History&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&#10;&lt;p&gt;This paper focuses on the interdisciplinary digital history project, “Migrants and the State” (M/S) which is currently in the prototype stage with funding from a NEH Digital Humanities Advancement Grant. M/S harnesses the power of machine learning large image models (LIM) and large language models (LLM) to build a scalable collection of government immigration documents known as A-Files. This paper seeks to introduce the project to the ACH community by providing a brief overview of the technical and intellectual aspects of the machine learning techniques, cataloging structure, and public facing components. We hope to engage the audience regarding the project’s scope, methodology, and progress while probing logistical obstacles and ethical concerns.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;A-files contain a wide variety of documents—often transnational and multilingual in scope. Each file serves as a portfolio generated by the state for migrants who enter the U.S. and encounter immigration agencies. They are specific to mmigrant, while reflecting mechanisms of state power international migration bureaucracies. These documents provide insights into individual and community migrant stories, the administrative state, the U.S. and international migration bureaucracies, immigration policy, and global mechanisms of surveillance and control. They offer exceptional potential for humanities research and community history projects.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;There are over ninety million A-Files held by the U.S. immigration bureaucracy. Every five years, the United States Citizenship and Immigration Service deposits hundreds of thousands of A-files that enter the public domain with National Archive and Record Administration (NARA). Minimal catalog information renders the contents of A-files opaque, and only a tiny fraction of them have been digitized and made available publicly through NARA’s website. Obtaining individual digitized A-files is possible, but only through cumbersome and costly individual requests. M/S aims to make A-Files available to researchers and community stakeholders so they can gain power over the rich information these records contain.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper focuses on the interdisciplinary digital history project, “Migrants and the State” (M/S) which is currently in the prototype stage with funding from a NEH Digital Humanities Advancement Grant. M/S harnesses the power of machine learning large image models (LIM) and large language models (LLM) to build a scalable collection of government immigration documents known as A-Files. This paper seeks to introduce the project to the ACH community by providing a brief overview of the technical and intellectual aspects of the machine learning techniques, cataloging structure, and public facing components. We hope to engage the audience regarding the project’s scope, methodology, and progress while probing logistical obstacles and ethical concerns.&#10;A-files contain a wide variety of documents—often transnational and multilingual in scope. Each file serves as a portfolio generated by the state for migrants who enter the U.S. and encounter immigration agencies. They are specific to mmigrant, while reflecting mechanisms of state power international migration bureaucracies. These documents provide insights into individual and community migrant stories, the administrative state, the U.S. and international migration bureaucracies, immigration policy, and global mechanisms of surveillance and control. They offer exceptional potential for humanities research and community history projects.&#10;There are over ninety million A-Files held by the U.S. immigration bureaucracy. Every five years, the United States Citizenship and Immigration Service deposits hundreds of thousands of A-files that enter the public domain with National Archive and Record Administration (NARA). Minimal catalog information renders the contents of A-files opaque, and only a tiny fraction of them have been digitized and made available publicly through NARA’s website. Obtaining individual digitized A-files is possible, but only through cumbersome and costly individual requests. M/S aims to make A-Files available to researchers and community stakeholders so they can gain power over the rich information these records contain.</ss:Data></Cell>
