    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rbzw@nyu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bryan@chronologicllc.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rbzw@nyu.edu, ellen.noonan@nyu.edu, sibylle.fischer@nyu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zehngut-Willits, Richard Bryan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rbzw@nyu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">64.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">238</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1291</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pollock, Caitlin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I thought your abstract was well-written and laid out the digital history project well. I think your abstract would have been strengthened by expanding a little on some of the ethical and privacy concerns in the project. Furthermore, I would have liked to see (especially with those concerns) how this project critically engages, and may critique LLM and machine learning with such a sensitive project. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1083</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zou, Zhihui</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission presents a program that analyses large amount of immigration files using language and image models.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project sounds really relevant and helpful to immigration history, and I&#039;m very much looking forward to reading more about it.  &#10;&#10;I would like the project to be a bit more specific with the intention and where LIM and LLMs are applied. For example, some questions that I would like to know answers to are: For LLM, are you using Transformers? If yes, are you using decoder, encoder, or both, and why? How are information provided to the LLM you are using? Same question format for LIM. The reason why I&#039;m asking is that due to LIM and LLM&#039;s popularity, a project needs to be specific with why and how they are using a large model. Because Machine Learning could perform statistical and quantitative research, but not all statistical research needs Machine Learning.&#10;&#10;The proposal right now gives a good view of the history side of the research. If more could be said about the technological side and how analyses (statistics? data science?) are conducted, it would be a much stronger proposal. Regardless, as is, I am looking forward to it.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1228</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wilkens, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">An overview of work in progress to digitize a large corpus of immigration-related documents from the United States. Authors argue that these documents constitute a potentially valuable historical research archive and observe that such data is generally either not available or prohibitively expensive to collect and to process.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is an interesting and potentially very valuable project. I&#039;d like to see it at the conference. The proposal would be much stronger if it contained any hints of preliminary results, or even of methodological and technical details. The scores here aren&#039;t higher, simply because there&#039;s not much on which to base an evaluation. &#10;&#10;The contribution might work best as a poster, which would allow for deeper conversations between the authors and the scholars they most want to reach. A poster would also be the most appropriate form for a project at so early a stage of development.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Definitely a poster, not a fully developed paper. I&#039;d like to see it accepted as a poster.</ss:Data></Cell>
