    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Teaching the Digital Humanities in the Age of AI</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">pedagogy, digital humanities, AI, critical making</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;3d printing, critical making&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3d printing, critical making&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Services built off of sophisticated large language models (LLMs) can often easily produce convincing written and image outputs. Using simple prompts, students can frequently complete basic assignments without needing to read or understand the original sources or consult anything beyond the service itself. This ease has caused significant anxiety in academic circles. Many have felt they need to redesign their course structures, update objectives, and change how assignments are completed. In response, many educational organizations and conferences have gathered resources, created guidelines, and called for greater digital literacy, emphasis on critical AI engagement, and a shift to human-in-the-loop design patterns to better educate themselves and others on how ethical usage might be possible in and out of the classroom.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This panel gathers, reports on, and speaks from experience with AI in the classroom. Critical AI engagement begins with the earlier progress on Critical Making, a term coined by Matt Ratto (Ratto, 2011) bridging traditional research and making, crafting, or art, and is also called research-creation (Loveless, 2019). The emphasis in critical making and research-creation is on the process of crafting artistic scholarship, rather than on a final, polished product. By introducing students to digital tools and the basics of procedural generation that precedes the AI text generators of today, students can better understand and critique the use (and misuse) of this technology. Tools like Tracery (Compton et al., 2014) offer a low barrier to entry for novices to grasp procedural generation basics. ChatBots like Botpress (Botpress GPT-Native Engine, n.d.) take generation a step further, using generative AI to interpret websites and documents added to its knowledge base. Panelists share their strategies for student success that include encouraging students to experiment rather than providing prescriptive instructions for assignments, and discuss how the emphasis of process over product allows students to take risks that build their confidence.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Each panelist will share a variety of methods that can be used in digital humanities coursework and beyond to help students gain critical AI literacy skills. We describe how we guide students to tinker and create with different digital tools, from bots to games to interactive narratives and more. Two of the panelists have incorporated the Critical Making research process into their courses at the graduate and undergraduate levels with positive outcomes and have an open-access book in press that aligns with this talk. The discussion will include innovative applications in music, virtual reality, and computational creativity, offering insights into how AI is reshaping the future of artistic expression and learning methodologies. We advocate for continued pedagogy that supports digital literacy as well as work that retains a human-in-the-loop workflow.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;References&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Botpress GPT-native Engine: Build next-generation chatbots. (n.d.). Retrieved June 6, 2024, from https://botpress.com/features/gpt-native-engine&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Loveless, N. (2019). How to Make Art at the End of the World: A Manifesto for Research-Creation. Duke University Press.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Ratto, M. (2011). Critical Making: Conceptual and Material Studies in Technology and Social Life. The Information Society, 27(4), 252–260. https://doi.org/10.1080/01972243.2011.583819&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Strauß, S. (2021). “Don’t let me be misunderstood”: Critical AI literacy for the constructive use of AI technology. TATuP - Zeitschrift Für Technikfolgenabschätzung in Theorie Und Praxis, 30(3), 44–49. https://doi.org/10.14512/tatup.30.3.44&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Services built off of sophisticated large language models (LLMs) can often easily produce convincing written and image outputs. Using simple prompts, students can frequently complete basic assignments without needing to read or understand the original sources or consult anything beyond the service itself. This ease has caused significant anxiety in academic circles. Many have felt they need to redesign their course structures, update objectives, and change how assignments are completed. In response, many educational organizations and conferences have gathered resources, created guidelines, and called for greater digital literacy, emphasis on critical AI engagement, and a shift to human-in-the-loop design patterns to better educate themselves and others on how ethical usage might be possible in and out of the classroom.&#10;This panel gathers, reports on, and speaks from experience with AI in the classroom. Critical AI engagement begins with the earlier progress on Critical Making, a term coined by Matt Ratto (Ratto, 2011) bridging traditional research and making, crafting, or art, and is also called research-creation (Loveless, 2019). The emphasis in critical making and research-creation is on the process of crafting artistic scholarship, rather than on a final, polished product. By introducing students to digital tools and the basics of procedural generation that precedes the AI text generators of today, students can better understand and critique the use (and misuse) of this technology. Tools like Tracery (Compton et al., 2014) offer a low barrier to entry for novices to grasp procedural generation basics. ChatBots like Botpress (Botpress GPT-Native Engine, n.d.) take generation a step further, using generative AI to interpret websites and documents added to its knowledge base. Panelists share their strategies for student success that include encouraging students to experiment rather than providing prescriptive instructions for assignments, and discuss how the emphasis of process over product allows students to take risks that build their confidence.&#10;Each panelist will share a variety of methods that can be used in digital humanities coursework and beyond to help students gain critical AI literacy skills. We describe how we guide students to tinker and create with different digital tools, from bots to games to interactive narratives and more. Two of the panelists have incorporated the Critical Making research process into their courses at the graduate and undergraduate levels with positive outcomes and have an open-access book in press that aligns with this talk. The discussion will include innovative applications in music, virtual reality, and computational creativity, offering insights into how AI is reshaping the future of artistic expression and learning methodologies. We advocate for continued pedagogy that supports digital literacy as well as work that retains a human-in-the-loop workflow.&#10;References&#10;Botpress GPT-native Engine: Build next-generation chatbots. (n.d.). Retrieved June 6, 2024, from https://botpress.com/features/gpt-native-engine&#10;Loveless, N. (2019). How to Make Art at the End of the World: A Manifesto for Research-Creation. Duke University Press.&#10;Ratto, M. (2011). Critical Making: Conceptual and Material Studies in Technology and Social Life. The Information Society, 27(4), 252–260. https://doi.org/10.1080/01972243.2011.583819&#10;Strauß, S. (2021). “Don’t let me be misunderstood”: Critical AI literacy for the constructive use of AI technology. TATuP - Zeitschrift Für Technikfolgenabschätzung in Theorie Und Praxis, 30(3), 44–49. https://doi.org/10.14512/tatup.30.3.44</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
