    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Central Florida</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ekj@ucf.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">dlcox8@ilstu.edu, ekj@ucf.edu, jtm@ucf.edu, anastasia@ucf.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cox, Dan;&#10;Johnson, Emily K.;&#10;Murray, John T.;&#10;Salter, Anastasia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">dlcox8@ilstu.edu;&#10;ekj@ucf.edu;&#10;jtm@ucf.edu;&#10;anastasia@ucf.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern (Florida, USA)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">241</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1286</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sparks, Corey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The panel uses a critical making pedagogical framework to address the problems and possibilities of AI in the classroom. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Continued thinking about creative pedagogical answers to AI is welcome, and the use of critical making processes as a foundation for that thinking is a strength of this panel. Having scholars discuss specific pedagogical practices is also welcome, as it seems many are looking for concrete answers to the &quot;problem&quot; of AI. Some discussion of institutional contexts would strengthen the contributions, as institutions&#039; varying responses to AI may lend support to or put constraints on the kinds of things other scholars may be able to do in the classroom.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1111</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Starry, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Thank you for this highly relevant and thorough proposal, particularly for the depth of engagement with relevant literature and the ongoing conversations around this topic. Too many conference submissions that I&#039;ve read in the past year about AI and higher ed repeat the same hand-wringing without any substantive/critical engagement, so it is very appreciated that you point to highly relevant sources and describe how panelists will dig into specific methods for supporting AI literacy acquisition in different contexts. I am particularly interested to learn about the critical making component of your pedagogical strategies!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1136</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cary, Justin Robert</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submissions offers insights into how AI is &#039;reshaping the future of artistic expression and learning methodologies&#039; and provides panelists who will speak from experience with using AI in classroom settings in a variety of engaging ways to help students learn about AI from both a practical point of view and a historical one.  Critical Making will be used here as a key framework connecting Digital Humanities pedagogy to practical teaching techniques for AI application in classroom environments.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As a teaching and scholar who has also spent the last several years deeply invested in AI literacy and digital humanities, your proposal sounds incredible and deeply resonant for me. The Critical Making framework seems like a perfect fit for this work and I think it serves the field of Digital Humanities so well to think about AI through this lens; how can students become Critical Makers and use these tools in the most ethical, critical, transparent and collaborative ways possible in order to imbue a humanistic habitus into their work while maintaining a connection to the technology that drives the making. This presentation sounds brilliant and thank you so much for doing this work!   </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As someone who has worked in this field for the past few years as well, this presentation sounds really well designed and researched and I think it would make for an excellent lightning talk. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
