    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">“The Racial Justice Archive”: Researching Police Brutality and Advocating for the Victims in Boston’s Communities of Color</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Police Brutality, Black Studies, Latino Studies, Public Sociology, Digital Advocacy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Spanish&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;History&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Spanish</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Race Studies&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;History&#10;Latino/a/x/e Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Police brutality is an ever-present threat to young people of color around the nation. While Franklin Lynch, Willie Bennett, and Michael Cox may only be a list of names to some, to Black Bostonians, these are the names of but a few of their beloved family and friends who have suffered the pains of death, beatings, wrongful arrest, and public defamation at the hands of the Boston Police Department. This year’s Association for Computers and the Humanities conference offers us an opportunity to showcase the archival research we’ve conducted that broadly speaks to several of this year’s themes, including anti-racist work, cultural and critical ethnic studies, intersectionality, postcolonial studies, among others, and will serve as a forum through which we can solicit expert feedback on how to grow the project in a new digital and public direction.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;We call ourselves the “Racial Justice Laboratory.” We are an intergenerational team of researchers from underrepresented backgrounds devoted to experimenting with new social science theories and qualitative research methods year-round. We draw inspiration from the insights of DuBoisian sociological inquiry, create opportunities for active community engagement, and seek to produce findings that are directly applicable to public policy. One of our ongoing projects is the construction of the “Racial Justice Archive” (RJA). While our research is ongoing, the RJA will be a database of firsthand facts and evidence on numerous cases involving police civil rights violations, such as excessive force, unlawful search and seizure, and/or differential punishment, that occurred in the Black and Latino communities of Greater Boston between the 1970s and 1990s. Currently, this is a collection of primary data sources from local university archives, including newspaper articles and video recorded interviews from local news outlets, such as the Boston Globe, the Bay State Banner, and WGBH, and national papers, such as the New Times and Washington Post, and photographs, manuscripts, and government and legal papers. And it also includes undergraduate student generated blog posts, essays, and podcasts focused on related issues.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Our goal with the RJA is to create a digital and public-facing resource for students, community members, activists, and lawmakers. One of our next steps will be to create several public “exhibits” focusing on notable historical cases. We envision these exhibits as taking on one of several forms, including curated galleries, digital and interactive maps, oral history interviews, original artworks, original research, and/or theatrical performances. However, while our team have interdisciplinary backgrounds, from criminology and sociology to history and literature, few of us have any training or familiarity with the current digital tools available with which to showcase our important work. In addition to describing the critical need for such a digital resource, this 75-minute roundtable discussion will explore the opportunities and challenges of building the RJA, and, because this is a project-in-process, the audience will have the opportunity to offer us feedback and suggestions for next steps.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Police brutality is an ever-present threat to young people of color around the nation. While Franklin Lynch, Willie Bennett, and Michael Cox may only be a list of names to some, to Black Bostonians, these are the names of but a few of their beloved family and friends who have suffered the pains of death, beatings, wrongful arrest, and public defamation at the hands of the Boston Police Department. This year’s Association for Computers and the Humanities conference offers us an opportunity to showcase the archival research we’ve conducted that broadly speaks to several of this year’s themes, including anti-racist work, cultural and critical ethnic studies, intersectionality, postcolonial studies, among others, and will serve as a forum through which we can solicit expert feedback on how to grow the project in a new digital and public direction.&#10;We call ourselves the “Racial Justice Laboratory.” We are an intergenerational team of researchers from underrepresented backgrounds devoted to experimenting with new social science theories and qualitative research methods year-round. We draw inspiration from the insights of DuBoisian sociological inquiry, create opportunities for active community engagement, and seek to produce findings that are directly applicable to public policy. One of our ongoing projects is the construction of the “Racial Justice Archive” (RJA). While our research is ongoing, the RJA will be a database of firsthand facts and evidence on numerous cases involving police civil rights violations, such as excessive force, unlawful search and seizure, and/or differential punishment, that occurred in the Black and Latino communities of Greater Boston between the 1970s and 1990s. Currently, this is a collection of primary data sources from local university archives, including newspaper articles and video recorded interviews from local news outlets, such as the Boston Globe, the Bay State Banner, and WGBH, and national papers, such as the New Times and Washington Post, and photographs, manuscripts, and government and legal papers. And it also includes undergraduate student generated blog posts, essays, and podcasts focused on related issues.&#10;Our goal with the RJA is to create a digital and public-facing resource for students, community members, activists, and lawmakers. One of our next steps will be to create several public “exhibits” focusing on notable historical cases. We envision these exhibits as taking on one of several forms, including curated galleries, digital and interactive maps, oral history interviews, original artworks, original research, and/or theatrical performances. However, while our team have interdisciplinary backgrounds, from criminology and sociology to history and literature, few of us have any training or familiarity with the current digital tools available with which to showcase our important work. In addition to describing the critical need for such a digital resource, this 75-minute roundtable discussion will explore the opportunities and challenges of building the RJA, and, because this is a project-in-process, the audience will have the opportunity to offer us feedback and suggestions for next steps.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tanks, Cassie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Northeastern University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">tanks.c@northeastern.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">LG.Freierman001@umb.edu, daniel.gascon@umb.edu, samwill@bu.edu, tanks.c@northeastern.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Freierman, LG;&#10;Gascon, Daniel;&#10;HurkaRobles, Anna;&#10;Williams, Sam;&#10;Tanks, Cassie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">LG.Freierman001@umb.edu;&#10;daniel.gascon@umb.edu;&#10;daniel.gascon@umb.edu;&#10;samwill@bu.edu;&#10;tanks.c@northeastern.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern United States</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">70.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">60.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">242</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1197</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brault, Chloé</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution speaks directly to the conference theme, and will be of great interest to many disciplinary and professional groups working in digitial activism and advocacy. The roundtable format seems perfect, especially if it can bring in participants from different professional ranks. I already see promise in how the contributors describe the group as &quot;intergenerational.&quot; </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Again: I already see promise in how the contributors describe the group as &quot;intergenerational.&quot; &#10;&#10;To go further: I would however ask these researchers to specify the types of involvement for each researcher, their role in the lab/project, their disciplinary background, the prior knowledge and experience they bring to the project, and their institutional and/or academic rank. This type of introduction would allow for the group to be more precise in its collective strengths, and also create the opportunity to specify what type of feedback they are seeking. A specification of what they mean by &quot;expert&quot; would be important. Guiding questions could be helpful, in addition to examples of exempliary projects with features that they would like to build on using digital tools for RJA/ this project. &#10;&#10;To get the group started: I see productive similarities with these related projects at Stanford: Say Their Names-- No More Names (https://news.stanford.edu/stories/2020/09/say-names-no-names-exhibit-stanford-libraries) and especially Know Systemic Racism (https://sites.google.com/stanford.edu/knowsystemicracism/home). The success of the Stanford projects, which is ongoing to my knowledge, stems from broad collaboration led by librarians, but centering undergraduate and community college researchers, a few of whom were incarcerated while working on the project. &#10;&#10;Are there features of this project that seem resonant? Embedded interactive tools that are particularly striking? Features that would definitely not work for RJA? Visualizations that are particularly striking? Data and/or metadata schemas that bare similarities as to motivate a collaboration with these peer researchers or a similar group in the future? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">60</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1287</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kreutel, Jörn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors of the contribution represent the &quot;Racial Justice Archive&quot;, which collects documentation on police brutality from various sources and aims at making it available to a wider audience using digital tools and channels, among others. As the project&#039;s members are not particularly experienced with the latter, the motivation of the roundtable is to exchange ideas with the DH community with respect to which methods and tools might be appropriate given the group&#039;s objectives.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Given the objectives described in the submission, the roundtable format with audience participation appears highly appropriate. However, the authors could have been slightly more concrete with regard to the particular issues, from their points of view, for which feedback from the DH community is desirable.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1310</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Alvarez, Maira Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract “solicits expert feedback on how to grow the project in a new digital and public direction.” Its goal is to create a digital and public-facing resource for students, community members, activists, and lawmakers. They intend to make several public “exhibits” focusing on notable historical cases. They envision these exhibits as taking on one of several forms, including curated galleries, digital and interactive maps, oral history interviews, original artworks, original research, and/or theatrical performances. In addition, their discussion will explore the opportunities and challenges of building the RJA, and, because this is a project-in-process, the audience will have the chance to offer feedback and suggestions for the next steps.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This RJA is a project that documents valuable material for the public. Here are some recommendations to improve the proposal and presentation if accepted.&#10;&#10;It would be useful to indicate what type of feedback are you looking for to direct the conversation and be more productive.&#10;&#10;I recommend including a line or two of the experts that you are already consulting (librarians, archivist, educators, etc.), so the audience can have a sense on how to formulate their feedback and use the time efficiently.&#10;&#10;Also, it would be great to know the timeline you are working with. Again, that is useful when seeking feedback. &#10;&#10;Overall, be more concrete on what you are looking for when it comes to feedback to better administer the time for the roundtable. This would help to have a productive discussion and hopefully possible collaborations with the experts you seek.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">None</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
