    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Mapping out Cultural Identity in the digital age: An analysis of iintsomi (isiXhosa folktales)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cultural Identity, Oral literature, Digital transformation, Orality, Transmedia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Africa&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital archiving&#10;African/Africana Studies&#10;Folklore studies&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Africa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital archiving&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African/Africana Studies&#10;Folklore studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;While language and culture are ever-changing and evolving, they still remain an important factor to&lt;br /&gt;our identities as individuals and ethnic groupings. Stephanie Rudwick (2006) notes that,&lt;br /&gt;“Globalisation and increasing levels of intercultural communication have led to the emergence of&lt;br /&gt;more multilingual and hybrid linguistic cultures…”. This results in individuals speaking one or more&lt;br /&gt;other languages besides their mother tongue and merge certain elements of the cultural lifestyles of&lt;br /&gt;other people with their own. The importance of cultural identity and the need to preserve and restore&lt;br /&gt;our cultural heritage in literatures as cultures are becoming more hybrid is of significance. Orality and&lt;br /&gt;transmedia make a conceptual framework to consider in the preservation and transmission of&lt;br /&gt;indigenous African and originally rural activity of oral literatures that remain in our memories. In the&lt;br /&gt;landscape of globalisation and technological advancement that continues to take over old traditions at&lt;br /&gt;a fast pace, the intentions for this study are to explore the concept of orality in its capacity to reveal&lt;br /&gt;deep embedded indigenous knowledge reflected through iintsomi (isiXhosa folktales). The study&lt;br /&gt;questions the way(s) in which iintsomi could be preserved through digital mediums is pertinent,&lt;br /&gt;through transmedia as a model. The problem stems from the observation that most of the scholarly&lt;br /&gt;work included in this research depends on outdated sources since there has not been much recent&lt;br /&gt;work done in the study of oral literature specifically, iintsomi. Jordan (1974) asserts that the history of&lt;br /&gt;literature of the Southern Africans began long before the advent of the Europeans. The Africans gave&lt;br /&gt;artistic utterance to their deepest thoughts and feelings about things and thus, the identity of African&lt;br /&gt;people is rooted in their “utterances”. This paper further accounts for iintsomi as a cultural heritage&lt;br /&gt;and a tool for vital messaging of indigenous knowledge of the Xhosa people which the isiXhosa&lt;br /&gt;folktales carry.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While language and culture are ever-changing and evolving, they still remain an important factor to&#10;our identities as individuals and ethnic groupings. Stephanie Rudwick (2006) notes that,&#10;“Globalisation and increasing levels of intercultural communication have led to the emergence of&#10;more multilingual and hybrid linguistic cultures…”. This results in individuals speaking one or more&#10;other languages besides their mother tongue and merge certain elements of the cultural lifestyles of&#10;other people with their own. The importance of cultural identity and the need to preserve and restore&#10;our cultural heritage in literatures as cultures are becoming more hybrid is of significance. Orality and&#10;transmedia make a conceptual framework to consider in the preservation and transmission of&#10;indigenous African and originally rural activity of oral literatures that remain in our memories. In the&#10;landscape of globalisation and technological advancement that continues to take over old traditions at&#10;a fast pace, the intentions for this study are to explore the concept of orality in its capacity to reveal&#10;deep embedded indigenous knowledge reflected through iintsomi (isiXhosa folktales). The study&#10;questions the way(s) in which iintsomi could be preserved through digital mediums is pertinent,&#10;through transmedia as a model. The problem stems from the observation that most of the scholarly&#10;work included in this research depends on outdated sources since there has not been much recent&#10;work done in the study of oral literature specifically, iintsomi. Jordan (1974) asserts that the history of&#10;literature of the Southern Africans began long before the advent of the Europeans. The Africans gave&#10;artistic utterance to their deepest thoughts and feelings about things and thus, the identity of African&#10;people is rooted in their “utterances”. This paper further accounts for iintsomi as a cultural heritage&#10;and a tool for vital messaging of indigenous knowledge of the Xhosa people which the isiXhosa&#10;folktales carry.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Twani, Khanyisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Zululand</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">South Africa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sub-Saharan_Africa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kisatwani@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">202181627@stu.unizulu.ac.za</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kisatwani@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Twani, Khanyisa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">kisatwani@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">SAST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">52.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">243</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1239</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kunnuji, Joseph</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an exciting work in progress on the storytelling tradition of the Xhosa people. Including a digital intervention to archive and document iintsomi would have made the study more fitting for a DH conference. Moreover, the idea of cultural hybridity is problematic as it assumes cultural purity. Aiming to safeguard or preserve a cultural practice has its merits without suggesting that borrowing from other cultural groups is a new or negative phenomenon.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an exciting work in progress on the storytelling tradition of the Xhosa people. Including a digital intervention to archive and document iintsomi would have made the study more fitting for a DH conference. Moreover, the idea of cultural hybridity is problematic as it assumes cultural purity. Aiming to safeguard or preserve a cultural practice has its merits without suggesting that borrowing from other cultural groups is a new or negative phenomenon.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Including a digital intervention to archive and document iintsomi would have made the study more fitting for a DH conference.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">52</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1307</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rehberger, Dean</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The study focuses on the concept of orality and its role in preserving indigenous knowledge, specifically through iintsomi (isiXhosa folktales). It aims to investigate how these traditional narratives can be maintained and transmitted using digital media and transmedia models. The research addresses a gap in contemporary scholarship on oral literature, noting that much of the existing work relies on outdated sources. By examining the historical and cultural significance of iintsomi, the study emphasizes their value as a repository of indigenous knowledge and a means of expressing the identity of the Xhosa people.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Overall, this is a wonderful proposal for a study and it is very important, particularly for the audience of this conference.  It is important to understand that by examining the historical and cultural significance of iintsomi, one can truly understand that importance of building a repository of indigenous knowledge as a means of expressing the identity of the Xhosa people.  &#10;&#10; However, it would strengthen the proposal a good deal to engage with not only the literature on iintsomi -- and the problematics of colonial collecting, but other similar studies of indigenous folk tale collection and the problematics of oral history.  Most important, it would be really nice to see more of the work of the author and her analysis and work on the folktales -- why it is so important to do digital capture of a from that is as much about performance as it is about the words spoken.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While a fantastic topic for study and important to the conference audience (particularly given the topic), the claim that there is no recent work on oral literature [particularly iintsomi (isiXhosa folktales)] is really problematic.  There is a good deal of work by South African scholars on the topic (in South African publications) and the problems of colonial collectors as well as on contemporary collection techniques of oral tales that are as much performance as language that can be transcribed on paper.    In short, it seems like a lot of general frame and one dated reference to Jordon, while there is a good deal of recent work on folktales and the problematics of collecting oral stories.  Most important, there is nothing here about what the author will say about the digital collection of tales.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">58</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1310</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Alvarez, Maira Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal questions the ways in which iintsomi could be preserved through digital mediums, given the lack of current sources. &#10;&#10;A recommendation to the author is to consider looking for projects that have faced similar challenges. Often, it&#039;s the researchers who need to produce the documentation by working with the communities. As the author states, &quot;iintsomi is a cultural heritage and a tool for vital messaging of Indigenous knowledge of the Xhosa people which the isixhosa folktales carry.&quot; It is important not to forget the community when doing scholarly work. Not being able to find current or multiple publications on the topic does not mean that such language or culture is nonexistent or less valuable; on the contrary, it demonstrates the urgency in the research at hand. One project that comes to mind is Ticha, https://ticha.haverford.edu/es/. &#10;&#10;This proposal offers a great opportunity to discuss challenges that underrepresented communities often encounter and how we can find ways to approach, resolve, and overcome some of these struggles. I would like to thank the author for bringing these discussions to platforms such as ACH.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal questions the ways in which iintsomi could be preserved through digital mediums, given the lack of current sources. &#10;&#10;A recommendation to the author is to consider looking for projects that have faced similar challenges. Often, it&#039;s the researchers who need to produce the documentation by working with the communities. As the author states, &quot;iintsomi is a cultural heritage and a tool for vital messaging of Indigenous knowledge of the Xhosa people which the isixhosa folktales carry.&quot; It is important not to forget the community when doing scholarly work. Not being able to find current or multiple publications on the topic does not mean that such language or culture is nonexistent or less valuable; on the contrary, it demonstrates the urgency in the research at hand. One project that comes to mind that can serve as an example of how to approach digital medium documentation and indigenous knowledge is Ticha, https://ticha.haverford.edu/es/. &#10;&#10;This proposal offers a great opportunity to discuss challenges that underrepresented communities often encounter and how we can find ways to approach, resolve, and overcome some of these struggles. I would like to thank the author for bringing these discussions to platforms such as ACH.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">No additional comments.</ss:Data></Cell>
