    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">244</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1135</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Clarete, Livia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract proposes a system that could integrate LLMs with the author&#039;s project (Conjecturator).  The goal is to leverage LLMs to generate text and reasons for hypotheses, still using human review as the last step of the decision making process. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Using ML/LLMs to support academic discussions by providing a framework for hypotheses analysis is quite relevant, as it would enhance research discussions and academic usability. However, the proposal doesn&#039;t clearly articulate the process and the deliverables of the tool.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The topic is very interesting and relevant. However, there is no clear plan or process for implementation, nor a description of the output of the proposed tool.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">46</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1228</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wilkens, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Author proposes to use generative AI to create candidate hypotheses for evaluation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal would be improved with specific examples of generated hypotheses and some discussion of how to steer outputs toward relevance. There aren&#039;t any citations to the literature on AI. I half suspect this is an AI-generated submission, except that AI would likely include more detail.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Would be a straight reject except that it&#039;s Juola.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">32</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1327</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Regan, Amanda</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Conjecturator sounds like an interesting tool and I can certainly see applicability for it as a pedagogical tool. However, I find the abstract to be a bit confusing. The author notes that the Conjecturator had not been widely adopted. Its unclear if the tool has been revised due to advances in LLMs and NLP. Are these general observations about the potential of these advances for data science in libraries? Or have these led to specific advancements for the Conjecturator? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">40</ss:Data></Cell>
