    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Emerging Genres on Goodreads: A Graphic Biographies Case Study</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">web scraping, Goodreads, platforms, cultural analytics, comics</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;cultural analytics&#10;social media analysis and methods&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cultural analytics&#10;social media analysis and methods&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Book and Print history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Research on social-media platform Goodreads focuses on categories like periodicity, genre, readership emerge in user-created metadata. For instance, Bourrier and Thelwall note that reading Victorian literature is shaped equally by academic as online reading communities, while the evaluation of outliers shifts towards contemporary gendered reading. Walsh and Antoniak demonstrate how folksonomic tagging affordances permit the “classics” to emerge as a vernacular genre, shifting the ways that reception studies understands canonicity. And English et al. find that readers are polarized in their consumption of “prestige” and “bestseller” works, a trend that holds in genre fiction, where science fiction, detective fiction, and chick-lit readerships are mutually exclusive. Goodreads’ categorization affordances have shaped the way that scholars approach contemporary reading. But how might we understand the relationship of Goodreads to emerging genres? Can Goodreads teach us about contemporary reading for categories whose metadata is inconsistent?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;            We approach these questions through a case study on the emergence of a genre of graphic novel biographies, which has seen the publication of over 300 titles since the year 2000. This genre has yet to differentiate itself from the autobiographical and semi-fictional graphic narratives. It enjoys a broad readership on Goodreads, but the conventions for folksonomic tagging and lay review appear inconsistent. We must therefore approach the metadata structures of Goodreads obliquely, finding strategies to understand the digital construction of reading while a genre and its readership are still emerging. We detail the mixed manual and automated process that the project undertook to trace this emerging genre.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Research on social-media platform Goodreads focuses on categories like periodicity, genre, readership emerge in user-created metadata. For instance, Bourrier and Thelwall note that reading Victorian literature is shaped equally by academic as online reading communities, while the evaluation of outliers shifts towards contemporary gendered reading. Walsh and Antoniak demonstrate how folksonomic tagging affordances permit the “classics” to emerge as a vernacular genre, shifting the ways that reception studies understands canonicity. And English et al. find that readers are polarized in their consumption of “prestige” and “bestseller” works, a trend that holds in genre fiction, where science fiction, detective fiction, and chick-lit readerships are mutually exclusive. Goodreads’ categorization affordances have shaped the way that scholars approach contemporary reading. But how might we understand the relationship of Goodreads to emerging genres? Can Goodreads teach us about contemporary reading for categories whose metadata is inconsistent?&#10;            We approach these questions through a case study on the emergence of a genre of graphic novel biographies, which has seen the publication of over 300 titles since the year 2000. This genre has yet to differentiate itself from the autobiographical and semi-fictional graphic narratives. It enjoys a broad readership on Goodreads, but the conventions for folksonomic tagging and lay review appear inconsistent. We must therefore approach the metadata structures of Goodreads obliquely, finding strategies to understand the digital construction of reading while a genre and its readership are still emerging. We detail the mixed manual and automated process that the project undertook to trace this emerging genre.</ss:Data></Cell>
