    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Chymistry of Isaac Newton</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">manuscripts, encoding, bibliography, Newton, alchemy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;15th-17th Century&#10;18th Century&#10;bibliographic analysis&#10;manuscripts description, representation, and analysis&#10;text encoding and markup language creation, deployment, and analysis&#10;History of Science&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">15th-17th Century&#10;18th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bibliographic analysis&#10;manuscripts description, representation, and analysis&#10;text encoding and markup language creation, deployment, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">History of Science&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Bibliography in The Chymistry of Isaac Newton (Alex Wingate, Cassidy Polack, Maddie Keyser, and Seth Cope)&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The bibliography team composed of the bibliography editor and three current citation encoders will outline in their paper their work encoding Newton’s citations and their print and manuscript alchemical sources in TEI. While Newton was assiduous in using citations in his alchemical manuscripts, tracing the 10,000+ citations to their sources and encoding them consistently requires specific infrastructures and processes given the variations in Newton’s form of citation and the 120+ sources Newton relied on that were published in even more editions. Nevertheless, this careful encoding will provide more evidence to the Chymistry team in dating Newton’s manuscripts, since a manuscript cannot have been finished before its latest source was published. The team will discuss the infrastructures, processes, and challenges of the citation encoding work and some preliminary analyses of the citation corpus to reveal characteristics of Newton’s alchemical knowledge base.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p lang=&quot;en-us&quot; xml:lang=&quot;en-us&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p lang=&quot;en-us&quot; xml:lang=&quot;en-us&quot;&gt;Text encoding in The Chymistry of Isaac Newton (Caterina Agostini)&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p lang=&quot;en-us&quot; xml:lang=&quot;en-us&quot;&gt;This case study presents current work at The Chemistry of Isaac Newton (http://www.chymistry.org/), based at Indiana University Bloomington and funded by the National Science Foundation. Drawing from Isaac Newton&#039;s alchemical manuscripts housed at the Huntington Library, the presenter discusses transcription and encoding of multilingual data and metadata. In this session exploring TEI (Text Encoding Initiative) encoding, the speaker will outline current practices, workflows, and future designs related to multilingual texts accompanied by alchemical and astrological drawings. The task of producing an edition of Newton&#039;s texts presents inherent complexity, as it involves transcending simplistic categorization to effectively integrate visual elements and ensure accessibility for text encoding, as well as facilitating compatibility with screen readers and search functions. Digital resource creation, curation, and engagement require the development of case-specific management to facilitate scholarly preservation and interaction with cultural heritage materials in English, French, Latin, and Hebrew passages that Newton quoted. In that context, interpreting Newton’s references to the history of alchemical pursuits has advanced knowledge of philosophical concepts of nature.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bibliography in The Chymistry of Isaac Newton (Alex Wingate, Cassidy Polack, Maddie Keyser, and Seth Cope)&#10;The bibliography team composed of the bibliography editor and three current citation encoders will outline in their paper their work encoding Newton’s citations and their print and manuscript alchemical sources in TEI. While Newton was assiduous in using citations in his alchemical manuscripts, tracing the 10,000+ citations to their sources and encoding them consistently requires specific infrastructures and processes given the variations in Newton’s form of citation and the 120+ sources Newton relied on that were published in even more editions. Nevertheless, this careful encoding will provide more evidence to the Chymistry team in dating Newton’s manuscripts, since a manuscript cannot have been finished before its latest source was published. The team will discuss the infrastructures, processes, and challenges of the citation encoding work and some preliminary analyses of the citation corpus to reveal characteristics of Newton’s alchemical knowledge base.&#10;Text encoding in The Chymistry of Isaac Newton (Caterina Agostini)&#10;This case study presents current work at The Chemistry of Isaac Newton (http://www.chymistry.org/), based at Indiana University Bloomington and funded by the National Science Foundation. Drawing from Isaac Newton&#039;s alchemical manuscripts housed at the Huntington Library, the presenter discusses transcription and encoding of multilingual data and metadata. In this session exploring TEI (Text Encoding Initiative) encoding, the speaker will outline current practices, workflows, and future designs related to multilingual texts accompanied by alchemical and astrological drawings. The task of producing an edition of Newton&#039;s texts presents inherent complexity, as it involves transcending simplistic categorization to effectively integrate visual elements and ensure accessibility for text encoding, as well as facilitating compatibility with screen readers and search functions. Digital resource creation, curation, and engagement require the development of case-specific management to facilitate scholarly preservation and interaction with cultural heritage materials in English, French, Latin, and Hebrew passages that Newton quoted. In that context, interpreting Newton’s references to the history of alchemical pursuits has advanced knowledge of philosophical concepts of nature.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Agostini, Caterina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Indiana University Bloomington</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cagostin@iu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cagostin@iu.edu, alewinga@iu.edu, cpolack@iu.edu, mjkeyser@iu.edu, sscope@iu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Agostini, Caterina;&#10;Wingate, Alex;&#10;Polack, Cassidy;&#10;Keyser, Maddie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cagostin@iu.edu;&#10;alewinga@iu.edu;&#10;cpolack@iu.edu;&#10;mjkeyser@iu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EDT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">58.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">38.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">246</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1186</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chagué, Alix</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission for a panel is focused on two interventions: &#10;- one will present the role of TEI for the transcription and the encoding of the corpus of manuscripts and prints, including drawings, from Isaac Newton on Alchemy analyzed within the context of the Chemistry of Isaac Newton project, &#10;- the second one will present the specific challenges of the encoding and identification of the bibliographical references in this corpus as well as the strategy and infrastructure put in place and leading to preliminary analysis of the corpus of citations.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think the work presented may have strengths and applicability that I missed due to a lack of contextualization in the proposal. However, I was able to collect more information from browsing the project&#039;s website, as the URL was provided in the abstract. The information collected on the website influenced a part of my evaluation. &#10;&#10;Justification of the points awarded:&#10;- The corpus under scrutiny is multilingual in the sense that it includes texts in English, French, Latin and Hebrew. Aside from that, it does not explicitly connect to themes such as anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, or multilingualism: the proposal topic appears to be primarily focused on historical and textual analysis of Isaac Newton&#039;s alchemical manuscripts, particularly through the lens of TEI encoding and manuscript dating.&#10;- In general, the proposal lacks a clear explanation on the context of this project and of the sources presented. While I am aware of the limitations inherent to the submission format, I think this presentation could have been grounded a little more in its scholarship context (are there similar edition projects, mixing text and images and/or facing the challenges of multilingualism, that this project takes inspiration from? Is it the first project working to such extent on scientific citations? Aside from TEI, are there any other technological choices that could have been included in the presentation (ad-hoc platform development, reuse of a framework already developped for another project, etc)? The project&#039;s website allowed me to find that the digital edition is built as a static website using TEI, XSLT and web technologies. I think the use of this technologies should be discussed, in particular considering that more and more scholars advocate for a better understanding of the longterm conservation of digital editions (see for example: Turska, M., Cummings, J., &amp; Rahtz, S. (2016). Challenging the Myth of Presentation in Digital Editions. Journal of the Text Encoding Initiative, Issue 9, Article Issue 9. https://doi.org/10.4000/jtei.1453)&#10;- The proposal refers to using TEI for the encoding of the corpus and to processes applied to identify and encode the citations in this corpus. I think this can be an important methodological contribution if the workflow and its shortcoming or strength is presented in sufficient details. The statement of purpose is not fully explicit but encoding and analyzing Newton&#039;s citations to date his alchemical manuscripts accurately would indeed contribute to scholarly understanding of Newton&#039;s alchemical knowledge base. This proposal does not explicitly articulate sociopolitical implications such as broader societal impacts or ethical considerations related to Newton&#039;s work.&#10;- I regret that more details was not provided on the workflow and technological choices involved in the two presentations for this project as they would undoubtedly help strengthen the significance of this presentations. While the proposal discusses the use of TEI encoding and its implications for dating Newton&#039;s manuscripts, it could benefit from more explicit connection to broader disciplinary implications and practical applications within digital humanities.&#10;&#10;Lastly, the guidelines for reviewers invite to consider panels as an &quot;engaging session that facilitates dialogue between presentations that are largely independent, highlighting connections between projects, methods or themes.&quot; I wonder if this panel would gain strength were it to include presentations from other edition projects sharing methodological challenges with the The Chymistry of Isaac Newton project. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">If a change of format is considered, this panel should be turned into not just one but two lightening talks (one for each presentation included in the panel proposition).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">38</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1230</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">MacKenzie, James</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Provides a description of particular challenges (re: Early Modern citations, multilingual content) in the context of a major text encoding initiative.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This promises to be an excellent panel, discussing a major text encoding project. You&#039;ve outlined and described the specific problems clearly, as well as the team&#039;s contributions. One small note: the URL provided in the abstract wasn&#039;t resolving properly for me when I was reviewing the submission. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1231</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Otis, Jessica</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This panel consists of two papers on the work of the Chymistry of Isaac Newton project, one focused on multi-lingual text encoding of complex manuscripts and the other focused on citation encoding and manuscript dating.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Both proposed papers are interesting and have the potential to contribute more generally to the digital humanities community by exploring the use of TEI with a complex corpora. The panel proposal as a whole would be strengthened by more clearly articulating how the two papers combine to create a greater whole. How are they interconnected, beyond both being part of the same larger DH project? What are the big takeaways that the panel as a whole will address, as opposed to each individual paper?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This doesn&#039;t feel like a full panel to me and the two papers might be combined with other proposed papers on TEI or the history of science to make a stronger, more well-rounded panel. They also might be split up and put in two different panels to have a similar effect.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">66</ss:Data></Cell>
