    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Toward A Digital Museum Ethics</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">museum studies, museum ethics, digitization, digital humanities, equity</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;Anthropology&#10;Art history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Anthropology&#10;Art history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Museums are increasingly striving to meet the demands of our online age by adopting a range of digital initiatives from virtual collections and exhibitions to XR experiences inside and outside the museum’s walls. These initiatives often equate increased digital access with democratization and the reduction of socioeconomic and cultural barriers that historically excluded many publics from the museum. The uneven execution of these projects, however, begs scrutiny of this assumption as well as the practical and ethical complexities of museum digitization projects.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This roundtable brings together digital humanities and museum studies scholars and professionals for a discussion on core ethical issues that museums face as they strive toward a digital future. How do museum digitization projects overlap and diverge from similar initiatives in libraries and archives? Can digital technologies help museums transition from their traditional role as arbiters of knowledge and taste to places of co-creation and shared meaning making? Or does digitization actually entrench the museum’s authority?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The conversation will focus on how digital museum ethics relates to distinct but overlapping groups of stakeholders. First, we will address the audiences museums seek to engage through new technologies. What kinds of access does digitization provide audiences who have been historically excluded or marginalized? What continued material or structural barriers are museums overlooking in their attempts to be more inclusive and how can they be meaningfully addressed? How can museums harness inclusive or universal design so that technologies like online databases can be responsive to a wide range of interests and knowledge?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Second, we will discuss technological barriers and general anxieties many museums face as they digitize. According to a 2020 ICOM report, 86% of museums see digitization as a top priority, but only 24% see themselves as reaching their digitization goals. Subject matter experts, specialists and technologists are often needed by museums for digitization efforts to succeed and monetary costs can be prohibitive for museums of any size. Established museum protocols may impact digitization efforts as well as accessibility related to technology, objects and collections. Further, digital reproductions can confuse the relationship between original and copy—by no means a new phenomenon—but one that has been accelerated by digitization and advancements in XR.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Finally, we will explore how museum studies can prepare emerging and future museum professionals to engage with this rapidly changing landscape. How are emerging museum professionals educated or trained to ask ethical, equitable, and access questions related to digitization? The primary audience for digitizing some collections may be driving an increase in the online audience and presence of the institution. However, how do current and future museum professionals shield (or reveal) complicated ethical questions from the public as well as source communities? How does digital heritage operate similarly and differently from tangible or intangible heritage? How does digitization complicate or engage discussions around repatriation/rematriation? Additionally, as museums seek to digitize objects that may be sensitive in nature, how does digitization impact the ability of humans to decay with dignity in addition to their objects and cultural production held in (digital) perpetuity? Are museums reproducing images of people, objects, or practices that should not be seen? Further, as the pace of technological change increases, how should museum workers contend with technological obsolescence and material decay?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Museums are increasingly striving to meet the demands of our online age by adopting a range of digital initiatives from virtual collections and exhibitions to XR experiences inside and outside the museum’s walls. These initiatives often equate increased digital access with democratization and the reduction of socioeconomic and cultural barriers that historically excluded many publics from the museum. The uneven execution of these projects, however, begs scrutiny of this assumption as well as the practical and ethical complexities of museum digitization projects.&#10;This roundtable brings together digital humanities and museum studies scholars and professionals for a discussion on core ethical issues that museums face as they strive toward a digital future. How do museum digitization projects overlap and diverge from similar initiatives in libraries and archives? Can digital technologies help museums transition from their traditional role as arbiters of knowledge and taste to places of co-creation and shared meaning making? Or does digitization actually entrench the museum’s authority?&#10;The conversation will focus on how digital museum ethics relates to distinct but overlapping groups of stakeholders. First, we will address the audiences museums seek to engage through new technologies. What kinds of access does digitization provide audiences who have been historically excluded or marginalized? What continued material or structural barriers are museums overlooking in their attempts to be more inclusive and how can they be meaningfully addressed? How can museums harness inclusive or universal design so that technologies like online databases can be responsive to a wide range of interests and knowledge?&#10;Second, we will discuss technological barriers and general anxieties many museums face as they digitize. According to a 2020 ICOM report, 86% of museums see digitization as a top priority, but only 24% see themselves as reaching their digitization goals. Subject matter experts, specialists and technologists are often needed by museums for digitization efforts to succeed and monetary costs can be prohibitive for museums of any size. Established museum protocols may impact digitization efforts as well as accessibility related to technology, objects and collections. Further, digital reproductions can confuse the relationship between original and copy—by no means a new phenomenon—but one that has been accelerated by digitization and advancements in XR.&#10;Finally, we will explore how museum studies can prepare emerging and future museum professionals to engage with this rapidly changing landscape. How are emerging museum professionals educated or trained to ask ethical, equitable, and access questions related to digitization? The primary audience for digitizing some collections may be driving an increase in the online audience and presence of the institution. However, how do current and future museum professionals shield (or reveal) complicated ethical questions from the public as well as source communities? How does digital heritage operate similarly and differently from tangible or intangible heritage? How does digitization complicate or engage discussions around repatriation/rematriation? Additionally, as museums seek to digitize objects that may be sensitive in nature, how does digitization impact the ability of humans to decay with dignity in addition to their objects and cultural production held in (digital) perpetuity? Are museums reproducing images of people, objects, or practices that should not be seen? Further, as the pace of technological change increases, how should museum workers contend with technological obsolescence and material decay?</ss:Data></Cell>
