    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">247</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1182</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boehlert, Krystal</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A series of complex and intertwined ethical considerations for museum digitization and access.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">These are all important considerations for museums and folks working in cultural heritage digitization. I appreciate that you&#039;ve foregrounded the various stakeholders and communities, and you finish out the conversation with an eye towards future professionals and education. This will lead to a very strong and fruitful conversation!&#10;&#10;When looking to structural and technological barriers within museums, will there also be a discussion around labor and contingent positions?&#10;&#10;You may want to clarify if the audience discussion will be scheduled after the speakers finish or embedded into the conversation as a whole.&#10;&#10;Each of the questions presented in the abstract is very rich and could be it&#039;s own session. It may be helpful to summarize some larger themes to structure the conversation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1207</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">King, Joey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Roundtable seeks to engage in a robust conversation around museum digitization. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposed roundtable has the potential to be incredibly engaging with the themes of the conference by focusing on ways in which digital humanities and museum studies-- forged together-- can combat various cultural issues of marginalization, preservation of cultures, and expanding the basic framework of museum studies contemporarily. Beyond statistical analysis, what does current scholarship show in regards to the adaption of digitization and what barriers do the submitters see in terms of museums reaching their digitization goals? Are their unintended consequences to museum digitization? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1110</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rutner, Jennifer</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This exceptionally strong proposal clearly responds to the themes and priorities of the conference, highlighting frameworks including postcolonial critiques of museum practices, the ethics of digitization, implicit and explicit bias in the funding of digitization projects, the training of future museum professionals, and the impact of digitization and museum practices on the communities they serve. A concrete statement of purpose is included, and the questions posed in the proposal are engaging and critically relevant to the future of the field. Presented as a round table, this topic and discussion could bring valuable perspective about the future of digitization projects to the field. This proposal is relevant for institutions of all sizes that are engaged in digitization projects. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
