    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rearticulating the United Nations: The United Nations as a technology.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Refugee, Migrants, United Nations, Technology, Data Capture</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Africa&#10;Global&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;mixed-media analysis&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;African/Africana Studies&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Indigenous methodologies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Africa&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mixed-media analysis&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Indigenous methodologies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Race Studies&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;African/Africana Studies&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Feminist studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Rearticulate (transitive verb)&lt;br /&gt;   a: to give further utterance or expression to&lt;br /&gt;   b: to reassemble and join together some of (the bones comprising the skeleton of a dead animal)&lt;br /&gt;Founded in 1945 at the end of World War II, the United Nations (UN), with it’s six principle organs,[1] specialized organizations and agencies, is charged with maintaining international peace and security, and fostering cooperation among nations. Despite this charge, between 1945 and 2024, there have been 82[2] recorded wars and 20[3] recorded genocides. Given that international peace and cooperation continues to remain illusive, it is important reexamine the work of the United Nations. Using the UN archive as well as the work of Black and African feminist scholars, this paper aims to reexamine the United Nations work with African refugees and migrants, by rearticulating the United Nations as a technology. By recasting the United Nations as technology this paper aims to show how the work of the UN with African refugees and migrants mirrors the work of an unjust technology — rendering the most vulnerable among us invisible while capturing large amounts of data. In examining the UN as an unjust technology, this paper will also offer recommendations on how the UN can function as a just technology leading us closer to world free of wars and genocide. &lt;br /&gt;￼&lt;br /&gt;[1] The Six Main Organs of the United Nations are: &lt;br /&gt;1. The General Assembly&lt;br /&gt;2. The United Nations Security Council&lt;br /&gt;3. The Economic and Social Council&lt;br /&gt;4. The International Court of Justice&lt;br /&gt;5. The Secretariat&lt;br /&gt;6. The United Nations Trusteeship Council: It should be noted that the Trusteeship is now defunct after suspension of it’s operations in 1994&lt;br /&gt;[2] This count, which is still being updated excludes wars fought for independence from colonial powers&lt;br /&gt;[3] This count includes the ongoing genocide in Palestine.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rearticulate (transitive verb)&#10;   a: to give further utterance or expression to&#10;   b: to reassemble and join together some of (the bones comprising the skeleton of a dead animal)&#10;Founded in 1945 at the end of World War II, the United Nations (UN), with it’s six principle organs,[1] specialized organizations and agencies, is charged with maintaining international peace and security, and fostering cooperation among nations. Despite this charge, between 1945 and 2024, there have been 82[2] recorded wars and 20[3] recorded genocides. Given that international peace and cooperation continues to remain illusive, it is important reexamine the work of the United Nations. Using the UN archive as well as the work of Black and African feminist scholars, this paper aims to reexamine the United Nations work with African refugees and migrants, by rearticulating the United Nations as a technology. By recasting the United Nations as technology this paper aims to show how the work of the UN with African refugees and migrants mirrors the work of an unjust technology — rendering the most vulnerable among us invisible while capturing large amounts of data. In examining the UN as an unjust technology, this paper will also offer recommendations on how the UN can function as a just technology leading us closer to world free of wars and genocide. &#10;￼&#10;[1] The Six Main Organs of the United Nations are: &#10;1. The General Assembly&#10;2. The United Nations Security Council&#10;3. The Economic and Social Council&#10;4. The International Court of Justice&#10;5. The Secretariat&#10;6. The United Nations Trusteeship Council: It should be noted that the Trusteeship is now defunct after suspension of it’s operations in 1994&#10;[2] This count, which is still being updated excludes wars fought for independence from colonial powers&#10;[3] This count includes the ongoing genocide in Palestine.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ross, Janet Nalubega</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nalubega@paracelsus.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nalubega@paracelsus.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ross, Janet Nalubega</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nalubega@paracelsus.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">CDT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">48.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">62.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">28.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">248</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1121</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Risam, Roopika</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper aims to explore the United Nations as a technology, asking how it might be reformed to function as a just technology.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The idea of exploring the United Nations as a technology is a compelling one, as is, of course, the question of how the United Nations might be reformed towards the cause of justice. One of the primary challenges of the abstract, as currently written, is that there isn&#039;t sufficient articulation or framing of what the author means by &quot;technology&quot; -- what definition(s) of technology are being deployed here, and what are the elements of the conception, structure, operations of the United Nations that position it within the definition of a technology. (I&#039;m not disputing the claim itself, only that there isn&#039;t enough setup to be able to follow the claim.) The keywords suggest there&#039;s mixed-media analysis and text mining involved in this research, but the abstract doesn&#039;t give a sense of the methodology that will be used to explore the sources described and to arrive at the conclusions and recommendations. Even within the word count limits of the abstract, there would have still been room for the author to provide a bit more framing that would have made this proposal stronger. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">28</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1239</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kunnuji, Joseph</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper presents a critical reappraisal of the role of the UN in brokering and maintaining global peace. It is indeed an important contribution at a time when wars and conflicts seem pervasive without a clear path through arbitration.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper presents a critical reappraisal of the role of the UN in brokering and maintaining global peace. It is indeed an important contribution at a time when wars and conflicts seem pervasive without a clear path through arbitration. The abstract can be improved by briefly highlighting how &quot;technology&quot; is conceptualized in the paper. Additionally, it is unclear how DH is featured in the paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">It is unclear how DH is featured in the paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">54</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1317</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Olsen, Calvin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper looks to rearticulate the six-organ United Nations organization as a technology and demonstrate that said technology is an unjust technology in relation to the treatment of African refugees and migrants.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The overaching idea of this proposal is complex in the best ways. It resonates deeply with the conference topic, and it presents the early stages of a very important work. The abstract does not quite live up to the idea it presents, making it somewhat difficult to foresee the direction the presentation might take. Among others, there is mention of scholarship of Black and African feminist scholars, but neither names nor concepts are included; and there is a list of the UN&#039;s six &quot;organs&quot;, but beyond the title and the definition of &quot;rearticulate&quot; (which is a fantastic word choice based on both definitions) no connections are made between them or the topic. As a reviewer, my interest is most certainly piqued, but the interesting dots still need more connecting. This would obviously happen more as the paper is developed, but the current abstract is still in need of a specific direction. To successfully establish everything listed in the abstract would likely take much longer than 10-15 minutes, so as currently constituted a discussion-based format might be more edifying for all interested parties.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am somewhat familiar with the author&#039;s previous work, and this feels like a stretch. Not that the stretch couldn&#039;t be made, but the idea presented here seems quite massive to the point that it hits the conference topic(s) by default rather than by targeted decisions.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">-1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rejected</ss:Data></Cell>
