    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Integrating Historical Orthophotography and Commercial Drone Technology into Oral History Praxis: Reflections on Interdisciplinary Approaches and the Genesis of the Family Farm Preservation Project</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">GIS, Orthophotography, Oral History, Spatial History, Mapping</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization&#10;Geography and Geo-Humanities&#10;History&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Geography and Geo-Humanities&#10;History&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Family farms are disappearing and with them their histories and roles in local communities. As historians like Donald J. Pisani have noted, over the past century, forces ranging from agricultural industrialization and consolidation to urbanization and competing on a global market have contributed to the decline of the family farm. The number of farms peaked in 1935 with 6.8 million farms nationwide, which has declined to roughly 2 million in 2022 (Keller).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This individual presentation offers an overview of the Family Farm Preservation Project (FFPP), which seeks to preserve the history of these farms and associated lifeways. The project utilizes GIS technology, historical aerial imagery of landscapes, and commercial drone footage to discuss and capture via recorded oral histories the evolution of their farmlands/dairies from the 1930s to the present. These conversations also address the challenges of sustaining farms across multiple generations, exporting livestock to other states, Latinx migrant labor, farms’ relationships with local communities and the environment, and recommendations to preserve lifeways. The presentation considers the current state of the project and efforts to expand beyond its pilot phase including development of a website showcasing these histories.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This presentation will conclude by reflecting on what public history and extension (public-facing agricultural, home industry, and natural resources education services based in research) professionals can learn from one another, as well as the challenges of undertaking interdisciplinary work bound internal review boards. FFPP presents an opportunity to incorporate drone-captured photography to explicate public histories of the environment and people’s relationships with land inhabited over several decades. By incorporating oral history methods, agricultural professionals are able to identify cross-generational trends while adopting the “dialogue-driven approach” pioneered by John Kuo Wei Tchen and other public humanities scholars to center the voices of farmers in conveying their stories and advocating on their behalf.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Family farms are disappearing and with them their histories and roles in local communities. As historians like Donald J. Pisani have noted, over the past century, forces ranging from agricultural industrialization and consolidation to urbanization and competing on a global market have contributed to the decline of the family farm. The number of farms peaked in 1935 with 6.8 million farms nationwide, which has declined to roughly 2 million in 2022 (Keller).&#10;This individual presentation offers an overview of the Family Farm Preservation Project (FFPP), which seeks to preserve the history of these farms and associated lifeways. The project utilizes GIS technology, historical aerial imagery of landscapes, and commercial drone footage to discuss and capture via recorded oral histories the evolution of their farmlands/dairies from the 1930s to the present. These conversations also address the challenges of sustaining farms across multiple generations, exporting livestock to other states, Latinx migrant labor, farms’ relationships with local communities and the environment, and recommendations to preserve lifeways. The presentation considers the current state of the project and efforts to expand beyond its pilot phase including development of a website showcasing these histories.&#10;This presentation will conclude by reflecting on what public history and extension (public-facing agricultural, home industry, and natural resources education services based in research) professionals can learn from one another, as well as the challenges of undertaking interdisciplinary work bound internal review boards. FFPP presents an opportunity to incorporate drone-captured photography to explicate public histories of the environment and people’s relationships with land inhabited over several decades. By incorporating oral history methods, agricultural professionals are able to identify cross-generational trends while adopting the “dialogue-driven approach” pioneered by John Kuo Wei Tchen and other public humanities scholars to center the voices of farmers in conveying their stories and advocating on their behalf.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
