    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">249</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1053</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Melkozernova, Arina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors&#039; use of GIS methods and a “dialogue-driven approach” in their project about preserving family farms to visualize cross-generational trends sounds innovative. The project can potentially explore the relationships between farmers and their land, which is essential for representing their voices. The submission can be accomplished in the time allotted (10-15 minutes).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is connected to anti-racist work and culture and critical ethnic studies by addressing ‘Latinx migrant labor, farms’ relationships with local communities and the environment, and recommendations to preserve lifeways.’&#10;The proposal adopted the oral history methods  such as ‘the “dialogue-driven approach” pioneered by John Kuo Wei Tchen.’&#10;The project aims to discuss and capture the evolution of the farmlands/dairies from the 1930s to the present. The public history framework and extension (public-facing agricultural, home industry, and natural resources education services based on research) stimulate the knowledge exchange between professionals, as well as the challenges of undertaking interdisciplinary work bound internal review boards. Using geospatial methods such as GIS technology, historical aerial imagery of landscapes, and commercial drone footage for mapping recorded oral histories will empower communities by making their intergenerational land management visible.&#10;The proposal contributes to public histories of the environment and people’s relationships with land inhabited over several decades by implementing a digital humanities approach for building geospatial arguments.&#10;The proposal includes an introduction outlining the purpose and objectives, the background, methodology, and expected outcomes. It advocates for holistic research practice by making farming communities’ voices heard. Looking at the decline in the rate of family farms/lifeways in relation to their demographics and gender diversity and discussing land acknowledgment is crucial for the history of family farms. The proposal lacks the authors’ positionality and critical analysis of white privilege, food sovereignty, and settler colonialism in the context of land ownership, which will make the proposal stronger. There is a potential for expanding the analysis of the geospatial data to compare biodiversity conservation efforts between family farms and Indigenous communities and demonstrate their cumulative impact on the local economy. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1254</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Evans, Kenneth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal introduces a project documenting the history and culture family farms in the U.S. through aerial imagery, drone footage, and oral histories. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Thoughtful and interesting proposal worthy of acceptance. More specifics on the state of the pilot project (is there an extant website, how many oral histories, how much footage and imagery, etc?) would have strengthened the proposal. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1001</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lach, Pamella R.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission uses the Family Farm Preservation Project (FFPP) as a lens for discussing public digital humanities/history work that combines oral histories, GIS data, historical images, and contemporary drone-captured imagery.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission features a project that makes use of oral histories, GIS data, historical images, and contemporary drone-captured imagery in documenting histories related to family farming, particularly amidst local and global shifts in geopolitics, economic policies, and migration. The project holds methodological appeal for public historians, digital humanists, cultural heritage practitioners, and environmental humanists. I would be curious to see how the authors grapple with questions related to region, class, race, Indigeneity, etc.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">If there&#039;s not enough room for this as an individual paper, it could also work as a poster</ss:Data></Cell>
