    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Engaging Students in Developing Ethical Digital Research Skills through a Library Certificate Program</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital pedagogy, digital librarianship, digital cultural heritage, labor, ethics</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In 2023, the University of California, Riverside Library developed and implemented a new Digital Scholarship Summer Certificate program for undergraduates. This program was intended to provide an opportunity for  students to gain archival and digital research skills by engaging deeply with primary sources that specifically highlight student activism and BIPOC student voices at UCR. The program consisted of 6 workshops that roughly followed the digital project lifecycle, from archival research and imaging in the archives, to metadata and data management, performing OCR and text analysis, and finally creating digital exhibits.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Not only did we hope to make the invisible labor of digital humanities scholars and library workers visible, but we also wanted students to understand the ethical decisions that go into creating research materials and how they, as scholars, must make decisions about their research outputs. As a result, students were broadly introduced to concepts of digital cultural heritage, such as considering ethical dimensions of digitizing archival materials, and digital public humanities, through the final assignment of developing a digital exhibit plan. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Presenters will share the goals of our digital scholarship certificate program, lessons learned, and some surprising outcomes. We will also share our approach to instruction and community building embedded in the program.  In summary, this paper explores one institution’s approach to incorporating a focus on ethics and labor into a digital humanities learning opportunity for undergraduate students.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In 2023, the University of California, Riverside Library developed and implemented a new Digital Scholarship Summer Certificate program for undergraduates. This program was intended to provide an opportunity for students to gain archival and digital research skills by engaging deeply with primary sources that specifically highlight student activism and BIPOC student voices at UCR. The program consisted of 6 workshops that roughly followed the digital project lifecycle, from archival research and imaging in the archives, to metadata and data management, performing OCR and text analysis, and finally creating digital exhibits.&#10;Not only did we hope to make the invisible labor of digital humanities scholars and library workers visible, but we also wanted students to understand the ethical decisions that go into creating research materials and how they, as scholars, must make decisions about their research outputs. As a result, students were broadly introduced to concepts of digital cultural heritage, such as considering ethical dimensions of digitizing archival materials, and digital public humanities, through the final assignment of developing a digital exhibit plan. &#10;Presenters will share the goals of our digital scholarship certificate program, lessons learned, and some surprising outcomes. We will also share our approach to instruction and community building embedded in the program. In summary, this paper explores one institution’s approach to incorporating a focus on ethics and labor into a digital humanities learning opportunity for undergraduate students.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
