    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">250</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1284</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rousseau, Paulina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution summarizes the program, the Digital Scholarship Summer Certificate program for undergraduates, which intended to provide an opportunity for students to gain archival and digital research skills by engaging deeply with primary sources that specifically highlight student activism and BIPOC student voices. The authors will highlight how the goals of the program to make the invisible labor of digital humanities scholars and library workers visible, and have students understand the ethical decisions that go into creating research materials and how they, as scholars, must make decisions about their research outputs. The session will also highlight pedagogical decisions to emphasize a focus on ethics and labor into a digital humanities learning opportunity for undergraduate students.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a well written proposal that emphasizes pedagogical approaches, which are sometimes overlooked. Some additional reference to scholars engaged in similar work would have strengthened the proposal somewhat, however the proposal is well written, relates clearly to the conference focus, and is also unique in its emphasis. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This could potentially be a lightening talk, however this is a strong contribution as it looks at pedagogy, which is sometimes overlooked. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1026</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kerns, Halie Morgan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">To discuss a summer digital scholarship certificate progam for undergraduate students implemented by UC Riverside. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Undergraduates are often left out of the digital scholarship conversation, and the proposed paper seems like a wonderful example of remedying that. I appreciate both the ethical and practical angles they discuss; it seems to be a very well-rounded approach. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1294</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Croxall, Brian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation will discuss a Digital Scholarship Summer Certificate for undergraduate students at UC Riverside. Students worked with archival materials that focused on student activism and BIPOC voices.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation will discuss a certificate program that ran at UC Riverside in 2023. In a small space, the authors convey the scope of the skills students engaged with across six workshops as well as the sorts of materials that the students were working with. It sounds like an exciting program. &#10;&#10;This proposal is short due to the requirements of the conference. While space is at a premium, I would like to have a sense that the authors are aware of other efforts in this space. The DHRIFT project at CUNY Grad Center could be an important touchstone, for example. &#10;&#10;I have a few questions. First, was the program repeated in 2024? I understand that the abstract might have been submitted before it ran, but giving a sense of continuity seems important. If the program was a one-time-only experience, why was it not green-lit for a second time. Second, alongside learning particular skills, did the students produce anything concrete? In other words, was an exhibit mounted following the workshop? Have there been opportunities for the students to put their skills into practice following the workshop?&#10;&#10;On the whole, however, this is a strong proposal, and I would be sure to be in the audience.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
