    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">251</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1017</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Donea, Magdalena</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Roundtable discussion focusing on the liberatory and anticolonial potential of digital communication tools, methods and practices in a prison education program.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As a praxis-focused roundtable, this seems timely and engaging. The abstract is light on some details - courses included, technologies and pedagogical frameworks in use - but overall this is a necessary conversation that promises to cross several disciplinary boundaries. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This would be an especially strong entry into the conference, given the difficulty of doing this kind of work and the dearth of resulting scholarship on the subject. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1098</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Howard, Jacquelyne Thoni</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This round table provides an opportunity for educators teaching in Pelican Bay State Prison to discuss opportunities and challenges while teaching DH / Digital Communications in a prison system that limits communication and digital modalities. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I applaud your work and willingess to share about this important topic! I think many will find this round table to be educational and important to DH work.  From reading your proposal, I am curious if you plan to use minimal computing theories and frameworks or draw upon other theories and experiences. I also want to learn more about the student experience and connection when teaching DH to students experiencing incarceration. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1234</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fruttaldo, Antonio</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract outlines a roundtable discussion on facilitating a Digital Humanities/Digital Communication course at Pelican Bay State Prison, highlighting the complications and opportunities in such a unique educational setting.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While the topic is timely and significant, several theoretical and methodological aspects need refinement to enhance the roundtable&#039;s scholarly rigour and clarity of discussion. In particular, the roundtable spans multiple disciplines, including communication studies, digital humanities, and prison education. The abstract would benefit from a more explicit discussion of how these interdisciplinary perspectives will be integrated. For example, how will theories from digital humanities inform the discussion on facilitating digital communication courses in prison? Also, there is no mention of prior research on prison education, digital communication or the challenges of digital access in prison settings. Integrating a literature review that situates the discussion within the broader context of these fields will provide a clearer theoretical discussion. The abstract outlines the purpose of the roundtable as learning and sharing insights about best practices and strategies to support student engagement and learning. However, it does not clearly state the specific questions or objectives that will guide the discussion. The abstract only mentions a &quot;facilitated roundtable discussion&quot; but does not detail the facilitation approach. How will the discussion be structured? What methods will be used to ensure active participation and meaningful exchange of ideas among participants?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
