    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Algorithmic Colonialism: Digital Humanists’ Voices in the Fight against Colonialism in our Data-Driven World</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">colonialism, data, algorithms, global, exploitation</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;Africa&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;History&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Philosophy&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Africa&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital activism and advocacy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;History&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Philosophy&#10;Border and Transborder studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In this proposal, I will summarize a 15 minute presentation I would like to give about the role digital humanists can play in combatting algorithmic colonialism. To parapharse Abeba Birhane, this type of colonialism, in our current age of algorithms, relies on &quot;invisible and nuanced mechanisms&quot; in the technology we use everyday, as opposed to the &quot;brute physical force&quot; of colonialism of the past.&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; Of course, colonialism still involves physical force, but her observation points to what makes colonialism in our digital world different from the past, &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;I will organize my presentation into two parts. First, I will offer an introduction to the topic of algorithmic colonialism geared towards a general audience using academic sources, such as Dr. Birhane’s recent research, and articles published by journalists that will give my audience a sense of the everyday, practical implications of algorithmic colonialism. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The second part of my presentation will comment on the fact that the discourse on alogrithmic colonialism – and, more generally, data ethics – is dominated by researchers from STEM fields and journalists. I will present my argument to an audience of digital humanists about why their voices are missing from this discourse. My academic background is in history and philosophy, and I plan on ending my presentation with a brief list of ways that academics from my fields can contribute to the discussion about algorithmic colonialism and data ethics. I will encourage my audience to think of ways that they can contribute to that discussion, as well. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;1 Birhane, Abeba, &#039;Algorithmic Colonization of Africa&#039;, in Stephen Cave, and Kanta Dihal (eds), &lt;em&gt;Imagining AI: How the World Sees Intelligent Machines&lt;/em&gt; (Oxford, 2023; online edn, Oxford Academic, 22 June 2023), https://doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780192865366.003.0016, accessed 7 June 2024.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In this proposal, I will summarize a 15 minute presentation I would like to give about the role digital humanists can play in combatting algorithmic colonialism. To parapharse Abeba Birhane, this type of colonialism, in our current age of algorithms, relies on &quot;invisible and nuanced mechanisms&quot; in the technology we use everyday, as opposed to the &quot;brute physical force&quot; of colonialism of the past.1 Of course, colonialism still involves physical force, but her observation points to what makes colonialism in our digital world different from the past, &#10;I will organize my presentation into two parts. First, I will offer an introduction to the topic of algorithmic colonialism geared towards a general audience using academic sources, such as Dr. Birhane’s recent research, and articles published by journalists that will give my audience a sense of the everyday, practical implications of algorithmic colonialism. &#10;The second part of my presentation will comment on the fact that the discourse on alogrithmic colonialism – and, more generally, data ethics – is dominated by researchers from STEM fields and journalists. I will present my argument to an audience of digital humanists about why their voices are missing from this discourse. My academic background is in history and philosophy, and I plan on ending my presentation with a brief list of ways that academics from my fields can contribute to the discussion about algorithmic colonialism and data ethics. I will encourage my audience to think of ways that they can contribute to that discussion, as well. &#10;1 Birhane, Abeba, &#039;Algorithmic Colonization of Africa&#039;, in Stephen Cave, and Kanta Dihal (eds), Imagining AI: How the World Sees Intelligent Machines (Oxford, 2023; online edn, Oxford Academic, 22 June 2023), https://doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780192865366.003.0016, accessed 7 June 2024.</ss:Data></Cell>
