    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Understanding Models of Community-Institutional Partnership for Digital Cultural Knowledge</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Community archives, sustainability, digital archives, digital preservation, cultural heritage</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Galleries and Museum studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Galleries and Museum studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Communities have long developed, maintained, and protected their own cultural records through community archives, local history organizations, and other informal and formal efforts. Public- and community-engaged digital humanities initiatives have participated in this widespread phenomenon of community-based curation for decades. In parallel, libraries, archives, museums, and academic institutions are increasingly adopting participatory and community-centered approaches (Stevens et al., 2013; Shilton &amp; Srinivasan, 2007; Benoit III &amp; Eveleigh, 2019). These institutions have adopted models for involving communities in the collection (Meyerson et al., 2024), description (Frick &amp; Profitt, 2022), representation, and preservation of their heritage, and for returning ownership and control to originary communities in some cases (Stevens et al., 2013). Community-institutional partnership in digital cultural heritage is a burgeoning area of research and practice, yet there is little research providing an empirical overview of the shape and contours of this landscape. How do community-institutional partnerships produce and sustain digital cultural knowledge? What are the gaps in research and practice? This paper addresses these questions through a systematic, state-of-the-art review (Grant &amp; Booth, 2009) of community-institutional partnerships in digital cultural heritage collections and initiatives. The study identifies the objectives and approaches of approximately 250 active community partnerships with a variety of institutions, predominantly in the United States. Offering a framework of approaches to community partnership, this paper characterizes how such partnerships contribute to maintaining a more accurate, ethical, just, and sustainable digital cultural record, and identifies challenges and gaps in practice in need of further research.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Communities have long developed, maintained, and protected their own cultural records through community archives, local history organizations, and other informal and formal efforts. Public- and community-engaged digital humanities initiatives have participated in this widespread phenomenon of community-based curation for decades. In parallel, libraries, archives, museums, and academic institutions are increasingly adopting participatory and community-centered approaches (Stevens et al., 2013; Shilton &amp; Srinivasan, 2007; Benoit III &amp; Eveleigh, 2019). These institutions have adopted models for involving communities in the collection (Meyerson et al., 2024), description (Frick &amp; Profitt, 2022), representation, and preservation of their heritage, and for returning ownership and control to originary communities in some cases (Stevens et al., 2013). Community-institutional partnership in digital cultural heritage is a burgeoning area of research and practice, yet there is little research providing an empirical overview of the shape and contours of this landscape. How do community-institutional partnerships produce and sustain digital cultural knowledge? What are the gaps in research and practice? This paper addresses these questions through a systematic, state-of-the-art review (Grant &amp; Booth, 2009) of community-institutional partnerships in digital cultural heritage collections and initiatives. The study identifies the objectives and approaches of approximately 250 active community partnerships with a variety of institutions, predominantly in the United States. Offering a framework of approaches to community partnership, this paper characterizes how such partnerships contribute to maintaining a more accurate, ethical, just, and sustainable digital cultural record, and identifies challenges and gaps in practice in need of further research.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
