    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nwise@umd.edu, kfenlon@umd.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wise, Nikki;&#10;Fenlon, Katrina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nwise@umd.edu;&#10;kfenlon@umd.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern - New York</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">87.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">253</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1122</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boyles, Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation proposes a systematic review of the field of community-institutional partnerships in cultural heritage work. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As someone who runs a community archive that is community-institutional partnership, I am fascinated by this proposal. While there the field would benefit from a clearer picture of how this work looks, I also would love to know more about the presenter&#039;s methodology and the perceived benefits of this work. For example, how will you identify the gaps in current practice? Also, there are community-institutional partnerships that implement vastly different models around ownership, communication, relationship-building, digital praxis, etc.--how will those differences be accounted for? Also, how do you think an overview of existing work can and will encourage people to adopt new practices? I hope to hear the answers to these and many other questions at the conference!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1257</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Burress, Theresa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This study documents a systematic review of community-institutional partnerships developed by digital cultural heritage institutions, in order to provide a better understanding of common frameworks and approaches, as well as identifying challenges and gaps in practice that call for further research.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This systematic review will provide an aggregation of existing case studies and common practices related to community-GLAM institution partnership, which will be a valuable addition to the practitioner literature in this area. In particular, it will be interesting to see the trends with respect to partnerships with underserved communities, and how the partnerships value all stakeholders in an equitable, just manner.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a very solid proposal, and don&#039;t have any substantive critiques.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1099</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Nguyen, Linh My (Seth)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal provides an overview of common approaches and objectives in digital cultural heritage partnerships between communities and institutions. It has the potential to be an important resource for both academics and cultural workers.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a high-quality proposal. It would be beneficial to include, in addition to the objectives and approaches of these partnerships, their results: is the resource in question continuously maintained? Is the resource used within the community? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
