    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This presentation reflects on a first year of teaching digital humanities and critical information studies at a public research driven university through a lens of labor, decolonial worldbuilding, and disability justice. I highlight small everyday tactics of organizing instructional labor informed by a commitment to structural transformation of universities as sites of producing ‘good students’ and ‘good laborers.’ I invite students into the curriculum design process as an invitation into worldbuilding just, dreamy, substantive futures that nourish and affirm. I reflect on how teaching digital humanities courses around methodologies of project management, decolonial libraries and critical historical fabulations created the opportunity to take a slower, mindful, critical approach to labor–who we are, why and how we do what we do, and what type of relationships we nurture in the process. I facilitated specific assignments and transparent reflexive modes of communication in a frenzied pursuit of an alternative to the current status quo, a current world marked by invisibilized labor and erasure of disabled whole selves; students and instructors carrying a hegemonic weight of capitalistic linear time defined by benchmarks, grades, evaluations, outcomes, and pursuit of transferable skills that exist in an impossible market. Drawing wisdom from communities of laboring scholar activists and artists, I conclude this presentation with aspirational models for teaching and researching digital humanities that centers the whole selves of students and instructors as part of the world and committed to decolonial futures. Ultimately, this semi-public professional presentation is an invitation for others to dream along with me, to share tactics, and to welcome the space for justice oriented praxis and epistemological shifts in the research-teaching, scholar-activist binary.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation reflects on a first year of teaching digital humanities and critical information studies at a public research driven university through a lens of labor, decolonial worldbuilding, and disability justice. I highlight small everyday tactics of organizing instructional labor informed by a commitment to structural transformation of universities as sites of producing ‘good students’ and ‘good laborers.’ I invite students into the curriculum design process as an invitation into worldbuilding just, dreamy, substantive futures that nourish and affirm. I reflect on how teaching digital humanities courses around methodologies of project management, decolonial libraries and critical historical fabulations created the opportunity to take a slower, mindful, critical approach to labor–who we are, why and how we do what we do, and what type of relationships we nurture in the process. I facilitated specific assignments and transparent reflexive modes of communication in a frenzied pursuit of an alternative to the current status quo, a current world marked by invisibilized labor and erasure of disabled whole selves; students and instructors carrying a hegemonic weight of capitalistic linear time defined by benchmarks, grades, evaluations, outcomes, and pursuit of transferable skills that exist in an impossible market. Drawing wisdom from communities of laboring scholar activists and artists, I conclude this presentation with aspirational models for teaching and researching digital humanities that centers the whole selves of students and instructors as part of the world and committed to decolonial futures. Ultimately, this semi-public professional presentation is an invitation for others to dream along with me, to share tactics, and to welcome the space for justice oriented praxis and epistemological shifts in the research-teaching, scholar-activist binary.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
