    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">254</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1081</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Haines, Chelsea</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation offers decolonial pedagogical methods for the digital humanities classroom.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very strong proposal that outlines critical ideas of how to reshape the classroom through decolonial methods and horizontal frameworks. One aspect to consider highlighting more for the presentation itself is how the digital humanities classroom may differ from a traditional humanities classroom (or not) and how your pedagogical approach may shift depending on the subject and framework of the course and/or university environment.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1129</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shaarawi, Jihan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation centers on pedagogical methods of teaching digital humanities. The author is encouraging a collaborative, justice-driven praxis that centers the students. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract is very clear in its objectives and purpose. The project also sounds very exciting (as a fellow instructor). &#10;Clearer structure of the presentation would be beneficial. Clearly lay out your objectives, methods, and outcomes for a stronger understanding of the work being presented. &#10;Clarifying jargon would also be helpful, for example “critical historical fabulations” and “ capitalistic linear time&quot; sound like fascinating concepts but I don&#039;t have a clear sense of how they fit into this project. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">94</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1107</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fitzgerald, Karina Marie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers a praxis for approaching classroom instruction through a decolonial and anticolonial framework, seeking new pedagogical approaches to traditions of higher education.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very strong proposal for discussion of and critical inquiry into the traditional teachings of higher education, and how we might imagine anti-colonial, postcolonial, accessible and more diverse futures for academia. I also appreciate that this praxis-based approach turns toward a pedagogy that is hopeful and seeks human flourishing; offering tangible models for other educators as a response to hegemonic norms in academia, while also remaining imaginative and playful in the spirit of experimentation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
