    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">58.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">80.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">30.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">255</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1026</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kerns, Halie Morgan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Making DS work more accessible for all is no easy endeavor, and those committed to this work would benefit from hearing how Gale has done it. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1095</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bozia, Eleni</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The presentation proposes to present the Gale Digital Scholar Lab and its affordances for DH scholars and students. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors propose to discuss the Gale Digital Lab, arguing that it contributes to accessibility and equity in the field of digital humanities. However, I am not sure whether a for-profit database can argue for its promotion of equity and accessibility. &#10;&#10;I do not doubt that organized collections of data as well as access to tools that can assist DH scholars and students of all skills to process their data are of immense value to the community. However, I believe that the ACH community would have benefited more had the authors presented alongside one of their users. This way, they would have showcased the value of their product, there would have been a research principle/question behind the presentation, and overall, the talk would not just look like a product advertisement.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am not sure how the program committee feels about such a (for-profit) presentation. In case the conference is open to such proposals, I marked the possibility of this being a poster or a lighting talk. &#10;&#10;I believe it will be more appropriate given that the abstract reads like a product promotion, even though the authors claim that their work showcases the collaboration between industry and scholars.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">30</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1317</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Olsen, Calvin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The presenters demonstrate the DH practices being implemented by the Gale Digital Scholar Lab in academic and industry sectors. They introduce the Gale Research Showcase and the testing methodologies that keep academic partners intricately involved in all processes.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract offers an excellent breakdown of the context in which the Gale Digital Scholar Lab is currently functioning. It does not spend enough time connecting that context to the topical underpinnings of the conference generally, however. The authors mention that Gale has lowered the barrier to entry, but any specific connection is left out of the abstract. It seems that the practical outcomes and DH-community feedback will do quite a bit of the work, but there is no particularly mention of the student participation growth promised by the title. If a rewrite of the abstract were possible, I would suggest a condensing of the first to paragraphs into one small paragraph and an expansion on the communities and practitioners that would benefit from what&#039;s hinted at in the second half. This paper would be an interesting inclusion in an ACH conference generally--it&#039;s just not quite cemented itself as a frontrunner for this year&#039;s particular iteration.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">66</ss:Data></Cell>
