    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Facilitating Campus Collaboration in Digital Humanities Research</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">research, interviews, digital humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital research infrastructures development and analysis&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;With a growing interest in digital humanities on campus, a library fellowship was created to assess this interest and develop a strategy to meet these needs. The aim was to develop a plan to better support faculty needs. The ultimate goal is to further digital humanities research at the University of North Carolina at Charlotte.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The primary focus of the fellowship was to create an environmental scan of digital humanities centers, in order to determine what resources other universities offer. Resources include tools, physical spaces, and support networks. We focused primarily on peer institutions and other North Carolina universities and reached out to digital humanities related staff and faculty at these institutions. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Another integral part of this project was speaking with university stakeholders, including librarians, library staff, and faculty interested in digital humanities. The interviews asked library staff and teaching faculty from various departments to determine what kinds of projects they have worked and want to work on, what tools and software they use or are interested in using, the challenges they face, and what they want to see come out of this fellowship. The total sampling included over 20 participants. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Upon completion of our research and interviews, we assessed the findings to discover trends that can be implemented by the library to best support faculty’s research and teaching. The end-product includes an analysis of the data collected and a list of next steps. These recommendations will address both short-term and long-term goals for the library and the university.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">With a growing interest in digital humanities on campus, a library fellowship was created to assess this interest and develop a strategy to meet these needs. The aim was to develop a plan to better support faculty needs. The ultimate goal is to further digital humanities research at the University of North Carolina at Charlotte.&#10;The primary focus of the fellowship was to create an environmental scan of digital humanities centers, in order to determine what resources other universities offer. Resources include tools, physical spaces, and support networks. We focused primarily on peer institutions and other North Carolina universities and reached out to digital humanities related staff and faculty at these institutions. &#10;Another integral part of this project was speaking with university stakeholders, including librarians, library staff, and faculty interested in digital humanities. The interviews asked library staff and teaching faculty from various departments to determine what kinds of projects they have worked and want to work on, what tools and software they use or are interested in using, the challenges they face, and what they want to see come out of this fellowship. The total sampling included over 20 participants. &#10;Upon completion of our research and interviews, we assessed the findings to discover trends that can be implemented by the library to best support faculty’s research and teaching. The end-product includes an analysis of the data collected and a list of next steps. These recommendations will address both short-term and long-term goals for the library and the university.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
