    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chinook l The Use of Advanced Digital Technologies in Visa Processing in Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chinook, Canada Immigration, Digital Technologies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;Informatics&#10;Law and legal studies&#10;Political science&#10;Sociology&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Informatics&#10;Law and legal studies&#10;Political science&#10;Sociology&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Canada’s immigration system has seen a dramatic increase in applications for visas and permits in the last ten years. In response, Canada’s department of Immigration, Refugees, and Citizenship Canada (IRCC) developed Chinook, a Microsoft Excel-based tool to improve productivity of officers by gathering and displaying information in a user-friendly fashion. The IRCC claims that this tool does not use AI and that a human officer always makes the final decision. Critics of the tool have argued that its development was not transparent and that its design can hide important information. (​​Steinman &amp; Barandereka 2023) In this paper we will begin by discussing what Chinook does given the evidence we have (as the IRCC is not open about the functioning of the too). Then we will do a close reading of Chinook, ultimately arguing that there are some troubling aspects to the design of Chinook that encourage officers to make quick decisions and provide templated feedback. We will conclude by discussing the Canadian Government’s positioning when it comes to their ethics of automation and compare this to the design of this key tool. “Dark patterns” in software design can have an impact on fairness and human rights in software-assisted decision making processes.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Steinman, R. M. and N.-E. Barandereka (2023). &quot;Chinook: Immigration Canada’s new tool for immigration applications.&quot; Spotlight Can-Asia. https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/blogs/spotlight-can-asia/chinook-immigration-canadas-new-tool-immigration-applications (Accessed 2024-06-04)&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada’s immigration system has seen a dramatic increase in applications for visas and permits in the last ten years. In response, Canada’s department of Immigration, Refugees, and Citizenship Canada (IRCC) developed Chinook, a Microsoft Excel-based tool to improve productivity of officers by gathering and displaying information in a user-friendly fashion. The IRCC claims that this tool does not use AI and that a human officer always makes the final decision. Critics of the tool have argued that its development was not transparent and that its design can hide important information. (​​Steinman &amp; Barandereka 2023) In this paper we will begin by discussing what Chinook does given the evidence we have (as the IRCC is not open about the functioning of the too). Then we will do a close reading of Chinook, ultimately arguing that there are some troubling aspects to the design of Chinook that encourage officers to make quick decisions and provide templated feedback. We will conclude by discussing the Canadian Government’s positioning when it comes to their ethics of automation and compare this to the design of this key tool. “Dark patterns” in software design can have an impact on fairness and human rights in software-assisted decision making processes.&#10;Steinman, R. M. and N.-E. Barandereka (2023). &quot;Chinook: Immigration Canada’s new tool for immigration applications.&quot; Spotlight Can-Asia. https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/blogs/spotlight-can-asia/chinook-immigration-canadas-new-tool-immigration-applications (Accessed 2024-06-04)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Farhangfar, Zahra</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University Of Alberta</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">zfarhang@ualberta.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">zfarhang@ualberta.ca, sawafta@ualberta.ca, yasmeen@ualberta.ca, grockwel@ualberta.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Farhangfar, Zahra</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">zfarhang@ualberta.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">GMT-6</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">90.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">74.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">257</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1018</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Monzó-Nebot, Esther</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution of this submission is a critical analysis of the Chinook tool used by the Canadian immigration system. The authors provide the following key contributions:&#10;&#10;-    Examination of Chinook’s Functionality: Analyzing what Chinook does based on available evidence, highlighting the lack of transparency from the IRCC about the tool’s detailed workings.&#10;-   Critical Evaluation: Identifying and discussing potential design flaws in Chinook that may encourage immigration officers to make quick decisions and rely on templated feedback, which could impact fairness and thoroughness.&#10;-   Ethical Implications: Comparing the Canadian Government’s stated ethical positions on automation with the practical design and implications of Chinook, particularly in terms of fairness and human rights.&#10;-   Discussion of “Dark Patterns”: Exploring how certain design patterns in Chinook could negatively affect decision-making processes, potentially leading to unjust outcomes.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission addresses the increasingly important issue of automation in immigration systems, which is a timely and relevant topic given the global increase in migration and the adoption of technology in public administration in a neoliberal context. The proposal promises a thorough critical analysis of the Chinook tool, raising important questions about transparency, decision-making processes, and ethical considerations. By discussing the ethical implications and potential “dark patterns” in software design, the paper has the potential to contribute to the broader discourse on fairness and human rights in automated decision-making systems. The comparison between the Canadian Government’s ethical stance on automation and the practical implementation of Chinook adds depth to the analysis, highlighting potential discrepancies between policy and practice.&#10;&#10;The analysis is constrained by the limited information available about the inner workings of Chinook, which might affect the depth and comprehensiveness of the critique. Some arguments may be speculative due to the lack of detailed data on Chinook’s operations, potentially weakening the overall impact of the conclusions. The proposal could benefit from empirical data (drawn from interviews) or case studies demonstrating the actual impact of Chinook on decision-making processes, which would strengthen the arguments made. Incorporating empirical data or case studies to illustrate how Chinook has affected immigration decisions in practice may involve interviews with immigration officers or analysis of decision-making trends since Chinook’s implementation. The focus on design flaws and ethical implications could be broadened to include purported benefits to adequately identify the underlying ideologies.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1235</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Poluru, Ramesh</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This innovative tool allows for a greater volume of cases to process, however, it also raises several concerns about its transparency and fairness.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Limited discussion on the concerns about its transparency and fairness</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1115</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kitchings, Laura</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A close reading of an immigration Excel-based tool shows it encourages immigration officers to give quicker, AI-assisted feedback with less consideration than the individual occasion may warrant. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The strong proposal shows how the reliance on the tool leads to problems that may have had long-lasting impacts on immigration to Canada. The details of Chinook and the claims of the IRCC should be presented later in the abstract with a stronger focus on the work (the close reading) done by the presenters. Focusing on the work and findings will allow for a better consideration by other conference participants of the human rights implications of immigration officials heavily relying on a non-transparent “software-assisted decision-making process” to make decisions that significantly impact the lives of marginalized individuals and communities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
