    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Crowdsourcing and &#039;AI&#039; projects in memory organisations often set out to &#039;enhance&#039; information about collections to improve discoverability through actions like adding tags and annotations to documentation. Ingesting enhanced data appropriately and responsibly into collections management and discovery platforms (hereafter &#039;CMS&#039;) is a key but difficult factor in crowdsourcing projects and in operationalising AI. Responding to the ACH2024 call, we report on the success and shortcomings of data management shared by over 60 projects. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In early 2023, our interdisciplinary team observed that  struggles crowdsourcing and participatory projects experience integrating data created or enriched by online volunteers into CMS (Ridge, Ferriter, and Blickhan 2023) may be shared by projects using AI to enhance or create data (Kasprzik 2023, Krc and Schlaack 2023).  Our previous research on enriched data and collections platforms surfaces project realities and shortcomings of technical infrastructure for this work (Brumfield and Brumfield 2021; Ridge, Blickhan, Ferriter et al. 2021; Van Hyning and Jones 2021). &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Enriched metadata is &#039;data about a cultural heritage object ... that augment, contextualise or rectify the authoritative data made available by cultural heritage institutions&#039; (Europeana Initiative 2023). Reported barriers to ingesting enriched data include lack of technical skills, and restrictive formats or data management infrastructure. Institutional politics caused roadblocks, including lack of dedicated staff time and complex data standards. And projects often adopt design assumptions of existing infrastructure, which may not easily incorporate this type of data.  &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt; &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Reflecting on key barriers, we observe that assigning this work and management to those in precarious positions is not equivalent to institutional investment. That these programs are promoted as efficient and cost effective reflect organisational decisions around resource management and commitment. Our generous survey responses call us to interrogate these systems and methods. We invite collaboration to reimagine approaches and interventions to transform infrastructures of humanities knowledge.  &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Crowdsourcing and &#039;AI&#039; projects in memory organisations often set out to &#039;enhance&#039; information about collections to improve discoverability through actions like adding tags and annotations to documentation. Ingesting enhanced data appropriately and responsibly into collections management and discovery platforms (hereafter &#039;CMS&#039;) is a key but difficult factor in crowdsourcing projects and in operationalising AI. Responding to the ACH2024 call, we report on the success and shortcomings of data management shared by over 60 projects. &#10; &#10;In early 2023, our interdisciplinary team observed that struggles crowdsourcing and participatory projects experience integrating data created or enriched by online volunteers into CMS (Ridge, Ferriter, and Blickhan 2023) may be shared by projects using AI to enhance or create data (Kasprzik 2023, Krc and Schlaack 2023). Our previous research on enriched data and collections platforms surfaces project realities and shortcomings of technical infrastructure for this work (Brumfield and Brumfield 2021; Ridge, Blickhan, Ferriter et al. 2021; Van Hyning and Jones 2021). &#10; &#10;Enriched metadata is &#039;data about a cultural heritage object ... that augment, contextualise or rectify the authoritative data made available by cultural heritage institutions&#039; (Europeana Initiative 2023). Reported barriers to ingesting enriched data include lack of technical skills, and restrictive formats or data management infrastructure. Institutional politics caused roadblocks, including lack of dedicated staff time and complex data standards. And projects often adopt design assumptions of existing infrastructure, which may not easily incorporate this type of data.  &#10; &#10;Reflecting on key barriers, we observe that assigning this work and management to those in precarious positions is not equivalent to institutional investment. That these programs are promoted as efficient and cost effective reflect organisational decisions around resource management and commitment. Our generous survey responses call us to interrogate these systems and methods. We invite collaboration to reimagine approaches and interventions to transform infrastructures of humanities knowledge.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
