    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">258</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1257</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Burress, Theresa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper builds on previous research regarding enriched metadata to explore key barriers for projects that aim to ingest enriched data into collections management and discovery platforms. Among the barriers include equitable labor practices, and the authors provide a critique and call to reimagine approaches to design more equitable workflows and systems.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper builds on previous research regarding enriched metadata to explore key barriers for projects that aim to ingest enriched data into collections management and discovery platforms. Among the barriers include equitable labor practices, and the authors provide a critique and call to reimagine approaches to design more equitable workflows and systems. One point of confusion in the abstract is the role of crowdsourced vs. AI-produced enriched data. It will be helpful to better understand whether the paper intends to (1) discuss implications from their experience with crowdsourced data projects -- and how the implications might be relevant for AI-based projects -- or (2) whether the authors have some experience with each type of project and are making connections between direct experiences in both arenas.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors mention AI enriched metadata a couple of times, but really aren&#039;t clear as to whether they have direct experience with this type of technology/project, and I think more clarity in this would be useful for evaluating the strength of the proposal.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1237</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Baciu, Dan C.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&quot;Barriers to Bust? Exploring Constraints, Knowledge, &amp; Infrastructure in Enriched Data Project Management&quot; by Meghan Ferriter, Samantha Blickhan, and Mia Ridge offers a critical examination of the challenges faced by crowdsourcing and AI projects in memory organizations. The paper highlights significant issues related to the integration of enriched data into collection management systems (CMS), emphasizing the complexities and institutional barriers encountered.&#10;&#10;The interdisciplinary approach of the authors, incorporating perspectives from digital humanities, library science, and museum studies, enriches the analysis. By drawing on insights from over 60 projects, the paper provides a comprehensive overview of the technical and organizational obstacles in managing enriched metadata. The recognition of enriched metadata as essential for augmenting and contextualizing cultural heritage objects underscores the importance of this work.&#10;&#10;One of the paper&#039;s key strengths is its identification of the primary barriers to successful data integration: technical skills deficits, restrictive data formats, inadequate infrastructure, and institutional politics. These insights are crucial for understanding why many crowdsourcing and AI projects struggle to achieve their goals. The authors&#039; reflection on the precarious positions of those assigned to manage these projects highlights the need for greater institutional investment and support.&#10;&#10;The paper focuses on crowdsourcing. Towards a broader based response, it could benefit from a review of methods that have been applied for enriching textual data, algorithmically. A possible example is enriching text data to facilitate geospatial discovery in collections of text. &#10;&#10;Overall, &quot;Barriers to Bust?&quot; is a valuable contribution to the field of digital humanities, offering important critiques and insights that can inform future projects. It serves as a call to action for institutions to reconsider their resource allocation and commitment to integrating enriched data, ultimately aiming to transform the infrastructures of humanities knowledge.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Thank you for the submission! I’m looking forward to the examples and your review and interpretation. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1248</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Knox, John Thomas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper discusses and compares the benefits and challenges associated with crowdsourced/participatory data enrichment and possible uses of AI for data enrichment, especially for digitized collections. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I believe this paper will be of interest to ACH participants and is very timely given its treatment of novel uses of AI technologies. I am excited to learn more about what the authors have learned about crowdsourced data enrichment projects and how these insights are applied to current and/or prospective AI data enrichment projects. I think one thing that would make the paper especially compelling would be providing some discussion of concrete examples of AI generated data enrichment. Looking forward to this presentation!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a great fit and interesting topic. Would be a good fit for wherever we can fit it in.</ss:Data></Cell>
