    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Introducing Students to Intentional and Practical Bibliodiversity Using Digital Library Tools and Skills</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Information Literacy, Non-Western sources, Open Access resources, strategic searching</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;bibliographic analysis&#10;digital libraries creation, management, and analysis&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bibliographic analysis&#10;digital libraries creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Education/Pedagogy&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Extensive scholarship documents the need for a researcher to look outside their own information ecosystem to learn about and incorporate diverse viewpoints. However, there are significantly fewer resources dedicated to teaching the researcher how to do this, and the process of finding bibliodiverse sources is not something that a student or researcher does naturally. This presentation will offer a sampling of techniques to help the student discover scholarship and popular sources written and published outside North America and Western Europe. By leveraging search features in the library&#039;s existing collection of subscription databases as well as incorporating open access resources and resources available on the open web, the presenter will demonstrate how promoting bibliodiversity does not need to burden already tight library budgets. Furthermore, the presenter will provide practical examples on how to teach students about information privilege and the importance of diversifying their information ecosystems. By demonstrating the dramatic difference in the diverse sources available in typical databases versus the number of those sources that appear on the first page of results, the presenter will underscore the need for teaching students to be intentional in their searching habits and citation patterns. The presenter will pair theoretical concepts with pragmatic skills such as how to locate, search and use sources in target languages to strengthen the student&#039;s learning and academic work. With this practical and theoretical backing, an attendee will be equipped to promote bibliodiversity at their institution without significant financial investment. The aim is to empower a librarian to diversify the voices and perspectives that their students encounter during research.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Extensive scholarship documents the need for a researcher to look outside their own information ecosystem to learn about and incorporate diverse viewpoints. However, there are significantly fewer resources dedicated to teaching the researcher how to do this, and the process of finding bibliodiverse sources is not something that a student or researcher does naturally. This presentation will offer a sampling of techniques to help the student discover scholarship and popular sources written and published outside North America and Western Europe. By leveraging search features in the library&#039;s existing collection of subscription databases as well as incorporating open access resources and resources available on the open web, the presenter will demonstrate how promoting bibliodiversity does not need to burden already tight library budgets. Furthermore, the presenter will provide practical examples on how to teach students about information privilege and the importance of diversifying their information ecosystems. By demonstrating the dramatic difference in the diverse sources available in typical databases versus the number of those sources that appear on the first page of results, the presenter will underscore the need for teaching students to be intentional in their searching habits and citation patterns. The presenter will pair theoretical concepts with pragmatic skills such as how to locate, search and use sources in target languages to strengthen the student&#039;s learning and academic work. With this practical and theoretical backing, an attendee will be equipped to promote bibliodiversity at their institution without significant financial investment. The aim is to empower a librarian to diversify the voices and perspectives that their students encounter during research.</ss:Data></Cell>
