    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">259</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1024</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brooks, Mackenzie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution provides practical approaches for teaching students how to incorporate diverse perspectives in their research practices.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission seems widely applicable to anyone conducting their own research or working with students on research projects. Appreciate the focus on pedagogy and practical tips while advancing anti-racist work. Also glad to see approaches that do not just involve adding additional subscriptions.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1293</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tew, Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper is geared towards university library professionals and presents practical methods for teaching students why and how they should diversify their bibliographic sources.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I really appreciate how this proposal targets library professionals but the topic is applicable to all scholars and encourages us to think critically about how we know what we know and how far we know what we’re missing. I think the presentation would benefit from some references to other scholarship on this. I am also curious to know how they address sources in different languages, especially for student researchers and the librarians helping them who may not have linguistic proficiency. I really appreciate the emphasis of library budget as well. As a fellow library professional, this presentation really interests me personally and I hope to see it at the conference.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1147</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Berger, Claudia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I personally think this is a really needed information skill, but I wonder if the connection to DH more specifically could be made in the abstract. Maybe by connecting to some of the literature on Global DH and the Anglophone bias within the DH community. This is absolutely a skill that needs to be focused on more, and I also think it would work well as a hands on activity/workshop. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I don&#039;t want to be gatekeeper-y, but I would like to see more explicit connections to DH. I am not sure I see why it was proposed for this conference, but that isn&#039;t to say folks attending wouldn&#039;t see the value of this contribution. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">-1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rejected</ss:Data></Cell>
