    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">AI Literacy Efforts in the Library</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">library, AI literacy, collections as data, critical making</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;optical character recognition and handwriting recognition&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;South Asian Studies&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;optical character recognition and handwriting recognition&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library and Information Science&#10;South Asian Studies&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Inspired by Media Studies and Digital Humanities concepts like media literacy, collections as data, and critical making, the Penn Libraries&#039; Artificial Intelligence Literacy Interest Group was launched this year as a teach-in space where participants will discuss critical AI &amp; technology considerations, striving for nuanced, informed understanding approach of the capacious possibilities and social implications of the tools that are becoming ubiquitous as of 2024. The themes for these sessions included multidisciplinarity, gender, labour, and environmental considerations. This was in the form of student debates, interacting with multilingual historical special collections that are relevant to the history of computation, and literacy themed zines. Attendees wove their sentiments around AI collaboratively on a loom.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;One workshop in this series in October 2024 will be on performing multilingual Handwritten Text Recognition on the South Asian manuscripts in the special collections and comparing tools like Google Cloud Vision API and e-Scriptorium in a more technical and pedagogical manner. This lightning talk will introduce a brief overview of these multimodal sessions that can hopefully generate discussions on the role of the library as a space for discussions and learning the applications of AI tools critically.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Inspired by Media Studies and Digital Humanities concepts like media literacy, collections as data, and critical making, the Penn Libraries&#039; Artificial Intelligence Literacy Interest Group was launched this year as a teach-in space where participants will discuss critical AI &amp; technology considerations, striving for nuanced, informed understanding approach of the capacious possibilities and social implications of the tools that are becoming ubiquitous as of 2024. The themes for these sessions included multidisciplinarity, gender, labour, and environmental considerations. This was in the form of student debates, interacting with multilingual historical special collections that are relevant to the history of computation, and literacy themed zines. Attendees wove their sentiments around AI collaboratively on a loom.&#10;One workshop in this series in October 2024 will be on performing multilingual Handwritten Text Recognition on the South Asian manuscripts in the special collections and comparing tools like Google Cloud Vision API and e-Scriptorium in a more technical and pedagogical manner. This lightning talk will introduce a brief overview of these multimodal sessions that can hopefully generate discussions on the role of the library as a space for discussions and learning the applications of AI tools critically.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karajgikar, Jajwalya</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Pennsylvania</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jajwalyak@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jajk@upenn.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jajwalyak@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karajgikar, Jajwalya</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jajwalyak@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST/EDT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">77.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">98.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">260</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1051</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Galvis, Elliot</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed Lightning Talk will present on the effective and critical pedagogical uses for Google Cloud Vision and e-Scriptorium for performing OCR on multilingual South Asian hand-written manuscripts. The substance of the Lightning Talk will emerge from the October 2024 workshop session for the Penn Library Artificial Intelligence Literacy Interest Group.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The format and focus of the workshop organized by submitter sounds fascinating. There are significant contributions it offers for approaching pedagogy of Digital Humanities, Text Analysis, and multilingual digital tools. The biggest challenge for the would seem to be how to fit (or at least preview) the relevant material in the 5-minute format.&#10;&#10;I would recommend being explicit (but brief) in defining the concepts from Media Studies and Digital Humanities and their relevance for the talk. Similarly, more explicit claims for the importance of the University Library in particular for hosting discussions of AI tools would be useful (if this is a claim the submitters still want to make).&#10;&#10;Presenters will have to think very carefully about how to allocate space within the presentation given the scope of tools being presented, the introduction of the the Penn Libraries&#039; Artificial Intelligence Literacy Interest Group, and the multidisciplinary. scholarship the submission points to. There are a lot of very interesting contributions here and fitting them within the Lightning Talk format will be challenging. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think ideally the findings from the workshop series could be adapted into a longer format but understand this submission might have been proposed as such given the timeline for the workshop.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1205</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shukla, Nishanshi Atulkumar</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution of this paper is highlighting efforts of AI literacy at Penn Library. The lightening talk gives an overview of their workshop.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract is well crafted but might benefit from more details on multilingual Handwritten Text Recognition on the South Asian manuscripts and how those sessions will be addressed in the lightening talk.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">98</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1262</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Hara, Shoichiro</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library contributions to AI literacy efforts through discussing the library&#039;s role and critically learning the applications of AI tools.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1. It was difficult for the reviewer to evaluate this abstract due to the lack of specific descriptions.&#10;&#10;2. The abstract states that a workshop will use multilingual handwritten text recognition on the South Asian manuscripts in the special collections. However, since the collection is not specified, it is difficult for the reviewer to determine whether this is appropriate for the purpose of this abstract. The nature of the collections may significantly impact the evaluation of the methods and results in the research.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">15</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Accept - Lightning</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell ss:StyleID="s22"><Data ss:Type="DateTime">2024-09-07T17:39:44.000</Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Jajwalya Karajgikar</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell ss:StyleID="s22"><Data ss:Type="DateTime">2024-06-07T17:39:59.000</Data></Cell>
