    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Open Education Publishing and Social Justice</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital Humanities, Digital Pedagogy, Digital Publishing, Open Educational Resources, Open Digital Pedagogy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;Computer science&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Computer science&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This session looks at the role open publishing can play in redressing the tendency for Open Educational Resources (OER) to continue to reflect the unconscious biases and structural inequalities of older generations of scholarship even as they increase access to higher education by reducing textbook costs for students. OER initiatives typically put more emphasis on the adoption of no-cost OER materials than on the creation of them; they tend to provide incentives for faculty to adopt OER content for their courses and to abandon costly textbooks that drive students into debt. Faculty thus often depend on OER repositories and create “remixes” of the material they offer to build out their own OER materials. OER repositories, however, often replicate the existing western canon, reinscribing historical colonialist biases and white-male perspectives into new digital classroom spaces.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;What is needed to remedy this situation is an effort to diversify not only the materials we teach with, but also the educational technology and the pedagogical models through and with which we use and create OER. In this panel, we share our experiences building and sustaining open educational resource platforms that support an alternative model of OER creation. We will present our work at the City University of New York on The CUNY Academic Commons, founded in 2009, a WordPress-based publishing and networking platform that hosts over 49,000 members, 32,000 sites, and 2,900 courses; and Manifold, a publishing platform collaboratively created by the CUNY Graduate Center, the University of Minnesota Press, and Cast Iron Coding, which is used by over 30 publishers, libraries, and digital humanities centers across the world. These projects bring together the vibrant work on digital pedagogy and technology-focused criticism in the digital humanities with the ethos of open access materials in OER initiatives to create opportunities for faculty to build OER that go beyond offering students free textbooks. On these platforms, faculty are able to create OER projects that radically diversify teaching materials and bring students in as co-creators of knowledge. Open education publishing such as that which is supported by the Commons and Manifold encourages faculty to engage their students as co-authors and co-creators, fashioning publications that build out from the lives of students into the world. DH publication projects designed to incorporate the voices of students realize the pedagogical principles of active learning, whereby instructors guide students through the process of knowledge creation instead of imparting knowledge through passive means such as lectures. Further, this approach to OER creation works towards the social justice goals of disrupting the canon by producing reusable materials that reflect the voices and interests of the United State’s increasingly diverse student population.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;On this panel:&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Matthew K Gold will discuss building infrastructure at the institutional level&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Laurie Hurson will discuss building open educational resources&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Krystyna Michael will discuss student contributions and/ as social justice&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Jojo Karlin will discuss student self publishing&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This session looks at the role open publishing can play in redressing the tendency for Open Educational Resources (OER) to continue to reflect the unconscious biases and structural inequalities of older generations of scholarship even as they increase access to higher education by reducing textbook costs for students. OER initiatives typically put more emphasis on the adoption of no-cost OER materials than on the creation of them; they tend to provide incentives for faculty to adopt OER content for their courses and to abandon costly textbooks that drive students into debt. Faculty thus often depend on OER repositories and create “remixes” of the material they offer to build out their own OER materials. OER repositories, however, often replicate the existing western canon, reinscribing historical colonialist biases and white-male perspectives into new digital classroom spaces.&#10;What is needed to remedy this situation is an effort to diversify not only the materials we teach with, but also the educational technology and the pedagogical models through and with which we use and create OER. In this panel, we share our experiences building and sustaining open educational resource platforms that support an alternative model of OER creation. We will present our work at the City University of New York on The CUNY Academic Commons, founded in 2009, a WordPress-based publishing and networking platform that hosts over 49,000 members, 32,000 sites, and 2,900 courses; and Manifold, a publishing platform collaboratively created by the CUNY Graduate Center, the University of Minnesota Press, and Cast Iron Coding, which is used by over 30 publishers, libraries, and digital humanities centers across the world. These projects bring together the vibrant work on digital pedagogy and technology-focused criticism in the digital humanities with the ethos of open access materials in OER initiatives to create opportunities for faculty to build OER that go beyond offering students free textbooks. On these platforms, faculty are able to create OER projects that radically diversify teaching materials and bring students in as co-creators of knowledge. Open education publishing such as that which is supported by the Commons and Manifold encourages faculty to engage their students as co-authors and co-creators, fashioning publications that build out from the lives of students into the world. DH publication projects designed to incorporate the voices of students realize the pedagogical principles of active learning, whereby instructors guide students through the process of knowledge creation instead of imparting knowledge through passive means such as lectures. Further, this approach to OER creation works towards the social justice goals of disrupting the canon by producing reusable materials that reflect the voices and interests of the United State’s increasingly diverse student population.&#10;On this panel:&#10;Matthew K Gold will discuss building infrastructure at the institutional level&#10;Laurie Hurson will discuss building open educational resources&#10;Krystyna Michael will discuss student contributions and/ as social justice&#10;Jojo Karlin will discuss student self publishing</ss:Data></Cell>
