    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">261</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1111</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Starry, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This panel will explore educational technology and pedagogy frameworks for the creation and use of OER within the context of open publishing infrastructure.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Thank you for this panel proposal which addresses a highly relevant topic and need across disciplines and institution types. My only suggestion for improving the submission would be to more explicitly cite the sources/evidence for the assertions of how OER are currently created/used by faculty (where are those observations coming from?). </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1291</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pollock, Caitlin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I really enjoyed this abstract. The topic is really interesting and the abstract is laid out well. I appreciated how much detail the authors managed to fit into the abstract. I do think the abstract could have been strengthened by understanding its particular connection to digital humanities. OER is bigger than the humanities, and OER isn&#039;t always digital humanities even when about humanities topics. I think I would have liked a clear statement (could probably just be a sentence) about the implication for this work on the digital humanities (pedagogy or otherwise). </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1024</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brooks, Mackenzie</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This panel addresses the issue of OER projects continuing to replicate biases and Western perspectives while also addressing their goal of reducing textbook costs. The panel relies on two main platforms as examples, but will share their student-centered approaches to building OERs that advance social justice goals.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Strong submission that accurately addresses the range of factors (human, technical, institutional) in producing OER in a social justice framework. Appreciate the emphasis on pedagogy and centering student voices. Curious about the role of funding models in this work, as my own state regularly incentivizes OER creation through grant programs. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
