    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Modeling Modernisms</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">modernist studies, ethnic modernisms, word embeddings</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Ethnic Studies&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;cultural analytics&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Literary studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cultural analytics&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Ethnic Studies&#10;Literary studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In literary studies, labeling an author a &quot;modernist&quot; was long synonymous with claims of exceptional artistry, innovation, and cultural value. While this label was initially applied to a small group of largely white and male writers, recent generations of scholars have fought to shift the definition of modernism to a historical period, thereby expanding relevant styles and themes (Goldstone). Using word embedding models, we can approach this definitional debate at the level of the corpus: Do modernists and non-modernists talk about different things, the same things in different ways, or the same things in similar ways? How we answer this question has implications for the continued work of modernist studies in developing historicized approaches to literary production in this period, which in turn informs how writers from race-, gender-, and class-marginalized positions will be considered in this field.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This paper will discuss: &lt;br /&gt;1) Building three corpora to model early twentieth-century US prose--novels by modernists, novels by writers not considered modernist, and popular magazine discourse. The initial categorization of data into modernist and non-modernist in many ways determines the outcome of the investigation (Nelson). I will discuss methods of categorization and the definitional framework I developed. &lt;br /&gt;2) Word embeddings as a method of modeling the discursive spaces of these corpora (Blankenship).&lt;br /&gt;3) Initial findings of representational lag of consumer technology as a marker of literary discourse.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Blankenship, Avery. “What We Didn’t Know a Recipe Could Be:  Political Commentary, Machine Learning Models, and the Fluidity of Form in Nineteenth-Century Newspaper Recipes.” &lt;em&gt;Journal of Cultural Analytics&lt;/em&gt;, vol. 9, no. 1, Apr. 2024, https://doi.org/10.22148/001c.115371.&lt;br /&gt;Goldstone, Andrew. &quot;Modernist Studies Without Modernism.&quot; *OSF*, 2019, https://doi:10.17605/OSF.IO/FRCYS.&lt;br /&gt;Nelson, Laura K. &quot;Situated Knowledges and Partial Perspectives: A Framework for Radical Objectivity in Computational Social Science and Computational Humanities.&quot; _New Literary History_, vol. 54 no. 1, 2022, p. 853-877. _Project MUSE_, [https://doi.org/10.1353/nlh.2022.a898331](https://doi.org/10.1353/nlh.2022.a898331).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In literary studies, labeling an author a &quot;modernist&quot; was long synonymous with claims of exceptional artistry, innovation, and cultural value. While this label was initially applied to a small group of largely white and male writers, recent generations of scholars have fought to shift the definition of modernism to a historical period, thereby expanding relevant styles and themes (Goldstone). Using word embedding models, we can approach this definitional debate at the level of the corpus: Do modernists and non-modernists talk about different things, the same things in different ways, or the same things in similar ways? How we answer this question has implications for the continued work of modernist studies in developing historicized approaches to literary production in this period, which in turn informs how writers from race-, gender-, and class-marginalized positions will be considered in this field.&#10;This paper will discuss: &#10;1) Building three corpora to model early twentieth-century US prose--novels by modernists, novels by writers not considered modernist, and popular magazine discourse. The initial categorization of data into modernist and non-modernist in many ways determines the outcome of the investigation (Nelson). I will discuss methods of categorization and the definitional framework I developed. &#10;2) Word embeddings as a method of modeling the discursive spaces of these corpora (Blankenship).&#10;3) Initial findings of representational lag of consumer technology as a marker of literary discourse.&#10;Blankenship, Avery. “What We Didn’t Know a Recipe Could Be: Political Commentary, Machine Learning Models, and the Fluidity of Form in Nineteenth-Century Newspaper Recipes.” Journal of Cultural Analytics, vol. 9, no. 1, Apr. 2024, https://doi.org/10.22148/001c.115371.&#10;Goldstone, Andrew. &quot;Modernist Studies Without Modernism.&quot; *OSF*, 2019, https://doi:10.17605/OSF.IO/FRCYS.&#10;Nelson, Laura K. &quot;Situated Knowledges and Partial Perspectives: A Framework for Radical Objectivity in Computational Social Science and Computational Humanities.&quot; _New Literary History_, vol. 54 no. 1, 2022, p. 853-877. _Project MUSE_, [https://doi.org/10.1353/nlh.2022.a898331](https://doi.org/10.1353/nlh.2022.a898331).</ss:Data></Cell>
