    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rodrigues, Liz</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">rodrigue8@grinnell.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Central Standard Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">96.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">36.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">263</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1228</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wilkens, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Results overview (details to come) of study using (static?) word embeddings to differentiate standard literary modernism from other literature of the period.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is very light on methodological details and gives no hint of results. Both of these are hard to provide in so short an abstract, but their absence makes it very hard to evaluate the strength of the proposal. I suspect the paper will be good an interesting, but methods (and corpus selection, as the author notes) will be key, and there&#039;s not much present on either front.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Probably needs to be a full paper if the research comes off. Otherwise, a poster could be OK if the work remains more proposal than completed study.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">36</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1309</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ryan C Dubnicek, Ryan</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper will use word embeddings and corpus-collection to seek to identify traits of literary modernism and to uncover how different authors, of varying social, racial, and gender classes, conform or resist to the larger modernism trend.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal is very well-written and concise! The project is both clear and understandable, using established methods, but novel in application and ambitious in research questions. If I had to give one point of advice, I&#039;d say that LLMs are lurking in the shadows as potential actors in this type of research. However, word embedding models are themselves quite complex and powerful, and LLMs need not be in every research project! Very well done, and I look forward to the presentation and full paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1275</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kilbane, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Poised to make contributions both to modernist studies and DH, this paper investigates definitions/classifications of &quot;modernist&quot; by modeling (using word embeddings) early twentieth-century US prose by &quot;modernists,&quot; non-modernists, and popular magazine writers. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper proposal is well-situated vis-a-vis urgent questions in the field of modernist studies, and it lays out a clear DH framework for answering those questions. As it currently stands, the proposal doesn&#039;t say a great deal about its findings--I am very much intrigued by this suggestion of a &quot;representational lag of consumer technology as a marker of literary discourse&quot;!--but I will just have to attend the talk to find out more! </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
