    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Futurist Archive: Documenting What Should Not be Documented</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Futurism, Marinetti, Boccioni, archive, database</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital archiving&#10;Art history&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Film and cinema arts studies&#10;History&#10;Literary studies&#10;Western/Southern European Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital archiving</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Art history&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Film and cinema arts studies&#10;History&#10;Literary studies&#10;Western/Southern European Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This presentation considers my ongoing project, &lt;em&gt;The Futurist Archive&lt;/em&gt;, which will be the first &lt;em&gt;catalogue raisonné&lt;/em&gt; for Italian Futurism available online to the public. The mission of the project is two-fold: it facilitates Futurist scholarship by providing equal, free access to research materials, and it serves as a pedagogical tool that can introduce the public to Futurism. However, the project is ironically antithetical to Futurism, since Marinetti and others wished for their works to be destroyed, even though the actions of curators and artists’ families have proven otherwise. With the help of existing projects by Futurist scholars—including those by Alberto Dambruoso and Giovanni Lista, as well as Daniele Imperi’s website, https://ftmarinetti.it/—and connections made with auction houses and artists’ descendents, I am pursuing &lt;em&gt;The Futurist Archive&lt;/em&gt; for its sociocultural and pedagogical potential and attempting to document the Futurists’ collective experience. Futurism was founded in 1909 by Filippo Tommaso Marinetti as an artistic, literary, and cultural movement; under Marinetti’s leadership, the Futurists praised simultaneity, dynamism, speed, technology, violence, and patriotism. The Futurists operated in Italy and France, as well as published many works bilingually in Italian and French, meaning that &lt;em&gt;The Futurist Archive&lt;/em&gt; relies on data from multilingual sources. Although it is first being compiled as a data set, &lt;em&gt;The Futurist Archive&lt;/em&gt; will take the form of a static website for long-term sustainability, with thousands of web pages displaying data pertinent to each object at hand, such as title, year, medium, and current location.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation considers my ongoing project, The Futurist Archive, which will be the first catalogue raisonné for Italian Futurism available online to the public. The mission of the project is two-fold: it facilitates Futurist scholarship by providing equal, free access to research materials, and it serves as a pedagogical tool that can introduce the public to Futurism. However, the project is ironically antithetical to Futurism, since Marinetti and others wished for their works to be destroyed, even though the actions of curators and artists’ families have proven otherwise. With the help of existing projects by Futurist scholars—including those by Alberto Dambruoso and Giovanni Lista, as well as Daniele Imperi’s website, https://ftmarinetti.it/—and connections made with auction houses and artists’ descendents, I am pursuing The Futurist Archive for its sociocultural and pedagogical potential and attempting to document the Futurists’ collective experience. Futurism was founded in 1909 by Filippo Tommaso Marinetti as an artistic, literary, and cultural movement; under Marinetti’s leadership, the Futurists praised simultaneity, dynamism, speed, technology, violence, and patriotism. The Futurists operated in Italy and France, as well as published many works bilingually in Italian and French, meaning that The Futurist Archive relies on data from multilingual sources. Although it is first being compiled as a data set, The Futurist Archive will take the form of a static website for long-term sustainability, with thousands of web pages displaying data pertinent to each object at hand, such as title, year, medium, and current location.</ss:Data></Cell>
