    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">264</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1106</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Walton, Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk will discuss the author&#039;s ongoing work on the Futurist Archive, highlighting the project&#039;s sociologic and pedagogical potential and discussing its structure and sustainability. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This sounds like an impressive and important project. The author does a nice job alluding to some of the theoretical challenges of pursuing this kind of work given the nature of the content (Futurism), though perhaps more could be said about their ultimate prioritization of the pedagogical/sociocultural over Futurism&#039;s essential ethos. Audiences will no doubt be interested in the structural challenges of dealing with a multilingual archive. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1120</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kurzynski, Maciej</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk showcases the author&#039;s ongoing project, The Futurist Archive, a website featuring a comprehensive, annotated dataset of artifacts related to Futurism.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project has the potential to connect scholars of Italian Futurism across borders and languages. The proposed website could aggregate information about cultural artifacts from various locations (primarily Italy and France) on a single platform, facilitating Futurist scholarship and rekindling public interest in Futurism.&#10;&#10;The abstract should ideally provide more details about the structure of the dataset, modality of artifacts (texts, images, or everything?), website design, the project&#039;s timeline, etc. The abstract says that the website will be &quot;static,&quot; but not much beyond that; this choice is pragmatic, but raises questions about how the project will handle updates and new findings over time. Rather than &quot;thousands of web pages,&quot; perhaps one dynamic webpage that draws information from a database would be a better choice? It is also not clear whether the author has already started building the dataset. How many items have been collected so far? Where will it be shared?&#10;&#10;Inclusion of such details could make this promising abstract much stronger and more suitable for a DH-focused conference.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1315</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tratarou, Adelina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission presents an intriguing and innovative project, “The Futurist Archive,” which aims to create the first online annotated catalog for Italian Futurism. The dual mission of the project is commendable: it not only aims to advance Futurist scholarship by offering equitable and free access to research materials but also serves as an educational resource to engage the public with Futurism. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">One of the key strengths of this project lies in its commitment to democratizing access to cultural resources, thus fostering a deeper understanding of Futurism among both scholars and enthusiasts. By highlighting the paradox of a project that both preserves and promotes a movement whose main figures sought destruction of their materials, the author invites a critical examination of the legacy and impact of Futurism, making it a thought-provoking contribution to both art history and contemporary discourse on language and data, multilingualism, and digital preservation of formal and informal collections. Moreover, the presentation promises to provoke discussions about the nature of preservation versus intention in the art world, an angle that is often overlooked. This reflective approach adds layers of meaning and relevance to the project, encouraging attendees to engage with the material in a more nuanced way.&#10;&#10;While the project’s ambitious scope might present challenges related to comprehensive coverage and the potential for interpretations of Futurism to evolve over time, these concerns could actually enhance the richness of the discourse surrounding the archive. Addressing such challenges could lead to a more robust and dynamic project that continually adjusts to the evolving understanding of Futurism. A more comprehensive historical contextualization of the movement and engagement with the overarching framework of digital humanities scholarship could prompt the scholar to examine the position of Italian Futurism alongside similar global movements, such as Indigenous Futurisms and the cosmologies they implied. This comparative analysis may reveal the unique potential of these movements to offer alternative paradigms of sociopolitical life and empowerment to a diverse range of users. &#10;&#10;Lastly, the scholar demonstrates solid knowledge of both the research material and the digital tools required for the project, offering a compelling case for the importance of curating and accessing historical art movements in ways that align with contemporary values of inclusivity and education. The project holds great promise for sparking meaningful conversations about the dual roles of preservation and interpretation in the arts.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
