    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A Digital Monograph is a Book: Multi-Layered Narratives as an Apparatus for Telling the Story of Digital Research</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">hypertext, argument, digital scholarship, digital publication, narrative</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;data publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;History&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;digital publishing projects, systems, and methods&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African American/Black Studies&#10;History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;“The form of historical narrative has mutated over and over again in the last several centuries,” Anthony Grafton argued, “because historians have tried to find new ways to tell the story of their research as well as those of their subjects, on separate levels and at different tempos.” While the digital medium has been used to extend the possibilities of archives, exhibits, and audio recordings, few monographs have been created in the digital medium. However, beginning in 2016, Stanford University Press, with the support of the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation, published a series of digital monographs. Several were longform historical arguments of the scale we associate with a book, including my &lt;em&gt;Harlem in Disorder: A Spatial History of How Racial Violence Changed in 1935&lt;/em&gt; (https://harlemindisorder.org), released on March 5, 2024. Constructed in Scalar, it is a multi-layered, hyperlinked narrative that connects different scales of analysis: individual events, aggregated patterns, and a chronological narrative.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This paper discusses this digital monograph as a book, not in terms of its difference from print publications. The layers linked to the chronological narrative can be understood as an extension of the research apparatus that footnotes provided in print needed to make transparent the interpretations involved in data handcrafted from uncertain and ambiguous sources. I will argue that such a framing is key to highlighting how digital publication is needed not just by those using digital tools and methods but also by scholars using digital research practices, such as digitized sources, databases and digital cameras, that have transformed how historians find sources and how much evidence they gather. I will also address the obstacles I have encountered in having &lt;em&gt;Harlem in Disorder&lt;/em&gt; treated as a book notwithstanding that it was peer-reviewed and published by a university press with ISBN &amp; OCLC numbers.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">“The form of historical narrative has mutated over and over again in the last several centuries,” Anthony Grafton argued, “because historians have tried to find new ways to tell the story of their research as well as those of their subjects, on separate levels and at different tempos.” While the digital medium has been used to extend the possibilities of archives, exhibits, and audio recordings, few monographs have been created in the digital medium. However, beginning in 2016, Stanford University Press, with the support of the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation, published a series of digital monographs. Several were longform historical arguments of the scale we associate with a book, including my Harlem in Disorder: A Spatial History of How Racial Violence Changed in 1935 (https://harlemindisorder.org), released on March 5, 2024. Constructed in Scalar, it is a multi-layered, hyperlinked narrative that connects different scales of analysis: individual events, aggregated patterns, and a chronological narrative.&#10;This paper discusses this digital monograph as a book, not in terms of its difference from print publications. The layers linked to the chronological narrative can be understood as an extension of the research apparatus that footnotes provided in print needed to make transparent the interpretations involved in data handcrafted from uncertain and ambiguous sources. I will argue that such a framing is key to highlighting how digital publication is needed not just by those using digital tools and methods but also by scholars using digital research practices, such as digitized sources, databases and digital cameras, that have transformed how historians find sources and how much evidence they gather. I will also address the obstacles I have encountered in having Harlem in Disorder treated as a book notwithstanding that it was peer-reviewed and published by a university press with ISBN &amp; OCLC numbers.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Robertson, Stephen</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">George Mason University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">srober30@gmu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">srober30@gmu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Robertson, Stephen</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">srober30@gmu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Washington, DC (GMT-4)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">75.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">52.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">265</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1020</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Jensen, Graham</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission promises to make two significant contributions: (1) it introduces a research output that advances discussion in its particular academic fields (history, African American/Black Studies), and; (2) in doing so, it provides a model that—regardless of their own disciplinary background or interests—could help other scholars navigate the still-pressing challenges associated with publishing digital monographs. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers a clear, articulate, and compelling case study that could be of great interest to other DH scholars, including those approaching issues of digital monograph publication from completely different disciplinary perspectives. For this reason but also other reasons not outlined here, it would be a strong addition to the ACH 2024 program. Many participants (myself included) would likely be interested simply in learning more about the process of working through the peer review process with a university press for a born-digital publication. &#10;&#10;While the abstract focuses on Stanford UP’s digital monographs series and the author’s experiences working with that press for the publication of Harlem in Disorder, a presentation based on this abstract would ideally gesture—if only briefly—beyond Stanford to trace the history of digital monograph publication elsewhere. For example, the author mentions the Mellon Foundation, whose Scholarly Communications program goes back to at least 2013, and the Implementing New Knowledge Environments Partnership and other initiatives investigating the digital future of the book go back to 2008 and earlier (see, e.g., https://onlineacademiccommunity.uvic.ca/mcriinke/publications/). Many other university presses and platforms besides have similarly explored the viability of digital monograph publication with varying degrees of success (and also radically different digital affordances and approaches to the presentation of academic texts and paratexts). The author could easily situate their specific project in relation to these other initiatives with relative ease, and also with great effect.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">N/A</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1321</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Yang, Funing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper discusses digital monograph and the chronological narrative as a framing device for the digital monograph from a book&#039;s perspective with the example of Harlem in Disorder.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper covers an intriguing topic and shows engagement with the current scholarship. To make the proposal stronger, perhaps more relevant scholarship could be discussed, or, point out the lack of such. I am not quite familiar with the exact topic being presented but would love to hear more on the multi-layered chronological narrative approach to understand monograph as a book, and if there are multiple examples to illustrate this argument it will also be helpful.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">52</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1310</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Alvarez, Maira Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission promises to make two contributions: 1) “highlighting how digital publication is needed not just by those using digital tools and methods but also by scholars using digital research practices,” and 2) “address the obstacles encountered in having Harlem in Disorder treated as a book.”</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is clear and offers an interesting topic for scholars interested in digital monograph publications, regardless of their field of study. It would be a great addition to ACH 2024.&#10;&#10;I would encourage the author to revisit their statement, “few monographs have been created in the digital medium,” and include some of their research to support this statement. This would give the audience a better understanding of the struggle and complexities of digital monograph publications and expand beyond Stanford’s Mellon initiative. &#10;&#10;Also, it would be interesting to know what made the author decide to publish under Stanford UP instead of another press with digital monograph publications. Was it the author’s field of study? The review process? These are also questions scholars face when considering publications, especially digital monographs, and are part of the publication process and intertwine with the proposal. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I believe it would be a great addition to ACH 2024.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
