    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I Have No Mind and I Must Write: Philosophical Examination of Large Language Models</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Large Language Models, ChatGPT, hallucinations, epistemology, theory of mind</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;data modeling&#10;natural language processing&#10;Computer science&#10;Informatics&#10;Linguistics</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;data modeling&#10;natural language processing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Computer science&#10;Informatics&#10;Linguistics</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Large Language Models are among the newest and most controversial tools in the digital humanists&#039; shed, but many of the controversies create more heat than light.  This paper discusses, in nonmathematical terms, the technical foundations that underly LLMs such as ChatGPT, and explains the type of tasks that an LLM can and can&#039;t actually solve.  in particular, LLMs lack both a theory of mind and a theory of truth, which create corresponding weaknesses in their answers.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;We suggest that one of the best ways to understand LLMs is to refactor our understanding of the answers that they provide.  When an LLM is asked a question, it does not answer the question itself.  Instead, it answers the related question &lt;em&gt;What would an answer to this question look like?&lt;/em&gt; This explains both how and why these models can write with such fluency and sophistication, while at the same time explaining why the answers are so fundamentally flawed.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Large Language Models are among the newest and most controversial tools in the digital humanists&#039; shed, but many of the controversies create more heat than light. This paper discusses, in nonmathematical terms, the technical foundations that underly LLMs such as ChatGPT, and explains the type of tasks that an LLM can and can&#039;t actually solve. in particular, LLMs lack both a theory of mind and a theory of truth, which create corresponding weaknesses in their answers.&#10;We suggest that one of the best ways to understand LLMs is to refactor our understanding of the answers that they provide. When an LLM is asked a question, it does not answer the question itself. Instead, it answers the related question What would an answer to this question look like? This explains both how and why these models can write with such fluency and sophistication, while at the same time explaining why the answers are so fundamentally flawed.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Juola, Patrick</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Duquesne University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">pjuola@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">juola@mathcs.duq.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">pjuola@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Juola, Patrick</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">pjuola@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Time (New York)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">62.5</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">72.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">52.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">266</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1241</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ahrenberg, Lars</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission offers an analysis of the workings of Large Language Models including the technical and philosophical foundations and an analysis of tasks that they can and cannot solve.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think the characterisation of LLMs that the author offers is very adequate and shows promise of a very interesting talk. However, the abstract is overly negative towards the value of outputs from LLMs as, quite often, the answers are not &#039;fundamentally flawed&#039; but rather helpful. LLMs are a bit like machine translation systems, they don&#039;t always get it right, but often produce something that a user can understand and improve.&#10;&#10;The author does not really address the conference focus or other relevant scholarship but the topic is of fundamental importance to DH so I think the submission deserves a place in the program nevertheless.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1139</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">van Zaanen, Menno</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission describes an approach to get a better understanding of the workings of LLMs, not in a computational way, but in a way to try to understand their behavior. This is an interesting approach as it aims to get a better understanding of the areas that LLMs are good at but at the same time it can identify those tasks that it does not perform well.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The approach proposed in this submission is interesting as it aims to provide a better understanding of the behavior of LLMs.  In that sense it is related to explainable AI, but again, not from a computational approach. Contrasting the proposed approach to those of explainable AI will be interesting and relevant (which is currently not in the submission).&#10;&#10;My main critique deals with the difficulty of completeness.  This has to do with &quot;LLMs lack both a theory of mind and a theory of truth&quot;.  Even though I agree, there is a lot of discussion on whether symbolic representations are required for full general AI (or not). Reasoning about numbers for instance is currently not one of the strengths of LLMs as this (seems to) require(s) symbolic representations. There may, of course, be additional areas that are currently missing that can influence how LLMs behave.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">52</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1321</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Yang, Funing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission discusses the technical foundations for state-of-the-art LLMs and their inherent flaws that they lack a theory of mind and a theory of truth by refactoring our understanding of the models as well as the formulation process for their answers.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper contribute some fresh critical insights towards understanding LLMs, their prevelance, and their fundamental flaws, which fits the current stream of NLP development as well as the impact on humanists and our society in general well. I understand the abstract is limited, but more engagement with current scholarship will be helpful to frame the proposal in this setting, and would also be helpful to see a more expansive view (or more elaborations) on the topics you will address.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">72</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1196</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Szydlowski, Nick</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers a very succinct and clear way of describing the way the practical limitations of LLMs like ChatGPT that use a transformer model. The shorthand &quot;what would an answer to this question look like&quot; is a helpful way of understanding the output of these models.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a strong proposal that contains a clear and helpful way of describing the output of LLMs but I am hesitating in attempting to review it because I&#039;m not sure how to interpret the framing of the proposal. The proposal offers what seems to me to be a middle ground between fully anthropomorphized mental models of LLMs (attributions of sentience, use of terms like &quot;hallucination&quot;) and more literal or technical models (stochastic parrots, mathematical descriptions). I think what might be most helpful to me in the final presentation is a clear sense of when this particular mental model or description of LLMs is useful and explanatory.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">-1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rejected</ss:Data></Cell>
