    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital archiving&#10;Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;digital archiving&#10;Digital Storytelling</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chicano/a/x, Latino/a/x Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This project is called Hermanas y Heridas which translates to Sisters and Wounds. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;My research is focused on the grief surrounding the death of my mother Mary Lou who in her absence gave me the life of a writer. I have used my writing to heal and create bonds with other Mexican American women who’ve lost their mothers, my hermanas in grief. We shared stories and created a tapestry of identity as survivors of loss. This groundwork holds the stories of brown girls in their grief. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;I chose to upset traditional notions of the archive and create space for this chasm using the digital collections podium Omeka. Throughout, I lean on the Coyolxauhqui Imperative as well as Theory in the Flesh to frame this quest. In the assembly and data collection journey, new values were born. I learned to know my mother again, to preserve her memory, and honor her by offering others the chance to know her. Her life could and should become a digital collection where her activism, her love of writing, and ferocity of spirit could be displayed as knowledge; this is cultural wealth. She was my Chicana archetype and this is her museum.  If you have ever lost someone dear to you then you understand that you will forever be in pursuit of their memory. Throughout I have documented physical items, literature that informs our experiences, our prose, and photographs. I map the grief experience by documenting my mother&#039;s life and my growth as a writer. It is a mere starting point and a work in process. I am still learning how this will unfold but I know what is possible with this digital archive, I can extend this experience to other Chicanas who have lost their mothers. In the future, Hermanas y Heridas will be a digital community archive where Chicanas can chase the memory of their mothers, offering others the opportunity to know them. Women from all around the world can have a way to connect and create community in a way that is not possible with a traditional archive. This project embraces loss, portrays present love, and creates space for brown girl grief.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project is called Hermanas y Heridas which translates to Sisters and Wounds. &#10;My research is focused on the grief surrounding the death of my mother Mary Lou who in her absence gave me the life of a writer. I have used my writing to heal and create bonds with other Mexican American women who’ve lost their mothers, my hermanas in grief. We shared stories and created a tapestry of identity as survivors of loss. This groundwork holds the stories of brown girls in their grief. &#10;I chose to upset traditional notions of the archive and create space for this chasm using the digital collections podium Omeka. Throughout, I lean on the Coyolxauhqui Imperative as well as Theory in the Flesh to frame this quest. In the assembly and data collection journey, new values were born. I learned to know my mother again, to preserve her memory, and honor her by offering others the chance to know her. Her life could and should become a digital collection where her activism, her love of writing, and ferocity of spirit could be displayed as knowledge; this is cultural wealth. She was my Chicana archetype and this is her museum. If you have ever lost someone dear to you then you understand that you will forever be in pursuit of their memory. Throughout I have documented physical items, literature that informs our experiences, our prose, and photographs. I map the grief experience by documenting my mother&#039;s life and my growth as a writer. It is a mere starting point and a work in process. I am still learning how this will unfold but I know what is possible with this digital archive, I can extend this experience to other Chicanas who have lost their mothers. In the future, Hermanas y Heridas will be a digital community archive where Chicanas can chase the memory of their mothers, offering others the opportunity to know them. Women from all around the world can have a way to connect and create community in a way that is not possible with a traditional archive. This project embraces loss, portrays present love, and creates space for brown girl grief.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
