    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The People&#039;s Data: Building New Deal Knowledge Infrastructure through Crowdsourcing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">New Deal, Public Humanities, Mapping</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Geography and Geo-Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data, object, and artifact preservation&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;spatial and spatio-temporal analysis, modeling, and visualization</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Geography and Geo-Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;In 1933, at the height of the Great Depression, newly elected President Roosevelt established a series of over 60 agencies that radically transformed the U.S. built environment, enacting unprecedented investments in architecture, artworks, public space, archives, infrastructure, and many other programs for the American people. When funding for the New Deal shuttered shortly after the U.S. entered World War II, a period of neglect, forgetting, and suppression of New Deal records began. Ninety years later, the New Deal legacy continues to impact ordinary people and scholars across the humanities. In the absence of a museum, peer-reviewed journal, scholarly society, or government agency devoted to producing knowledge of the New Deal’s vast legacy, Living New Deal (LND) leads the effort to assembe a representative data sample and national map of over 18,500 New Deal sites and 35,000 related images, making unconventional data available to researchers. Its high-traffic website also creates a digital public history space, encouraging dialogue and timely debates about the challenges the country faced in the 1930s and still faces today: housing affordability, climate resiliency, various forms of discrimination, underfunded infrastructure and services, and economic recovery. As LND pivots to engage with the DH community, this paper considers the value and challenges of collecting crowdsourced data from ordinary people. It also explores how crowdsourcing illuminates the New Deal&#039;s physical and intangible legacies, and brings interdisciplinary, critical, and accessible perspectives on our own historic moment and its debates over labor, class, race, social justice, and the future of American democracy.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In 1933, at the height of the Great Depression, newly elected President Roosevelt established a series of over 60 agencies that radically transformed the U.S. built environment, enacting unprecedented investments in architecture, artworks, public space, archives, infrastructure, and many other programs for the American people. When funding for the New Deal shuttered shortly after the U.S. entered World War II, a period of neglect, forgetting, and suppression of New Deal records began. Ninety years later, the New Deal legacy continues to impact ordinary people and scholars across the humanities. In the absence of a museum, peer-reviewed journal, scholarly society, or government agency devoted to producing knowledge of the New Deal’s vast legacy, Living New Deal (LND) leads the effort to assembe a representative data sample and national map of over 18,500 New Deal sites and 35,000 related images, making unconventional data available to researchers. Its high-traffic website also creates a digital public history space, encouraging dialogue and timely debates about the challenges the country faced in the 1930s and still faces today: housing affordability, climate resiliency, various forms of discrimination, underfunded infrastructure and services, and economic recovery. As LND pivots to engage with the DH community, this paper considers the value and challenges of collecting crowdsourced data from ordinary people. It also explores how crowdsourcing illuminates the New Deal&#039;s physical and intangible legacies, and brings interdisciplinary, critical, and accessible perspectives on our own historic moment and its debates over labor, class, race, social justice, and the future of American democracy.</ss:Data></Cell>
