    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1279</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rogers, Katina L</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission makes valuable connections between data analysis, collective voice, and social fabric on a topic that is highly relevant to our current political moment.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Thank you for this excellent proposal, and for bringing this website to my attention. The topic will be highly relevant at the time that the conference takes place, and will likely raise meaningful discussions about crowdsourced data, social infrastructure, and more. I would ideally like to see a little more in the abstract about the crowdsourced piece, as it seems to be the focus of the session but isn&#039;t given a significant amount of space in the abstract, but I trust it will be very much present in the session itself.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">If space is tight, I think this *could* be accepted as a lightning talk since it&#039;s more presentation-based (as opposed to discussion-based), but my first choice would be to accept it as a full paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1245</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sempere, Anindita Basu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Living New Deal project has assembled an extensive collection of materials about the New Deal as a &quot;digital public history space&quot; in part through crowdsourcing. The authors propose to discuss the crowdsourcing aspect of the project both practically and as a way of understanding the lasting effects of the New Deal.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Living New Deal project is ambitious and exciting, and learning about your experiences of working with crowdsourced materials at this scale would be valuable. In terms of a presentation, it would be helpful to hear about both outreach and data collection. How did you engage local communities? What kind of material did you solicit? How did you turn what community members sent into &quot;data&quot; that can be shared in a consistent manner?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1017</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Donea, Magdalena</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper&#039;s focus on crowdsourced data from &quot;ordinary people&quot; represents a strong antidote to the usual large, uncritical, un-traceable data &quot;from nowhere&quot; that a project of this magnitude might have otherwise been tempted to construct.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
