    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A Public Digital Humanities Center for San José: Fostering Belonging and Innovation in a Joint-Use Library</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital humanities centers, public humanities, collaboration, community-led, community engagement</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Galleries and Museum studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Galleries and Museum studies&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Library is a joint-use library, serving as the university library for San José State University as well as the main branch of the City of San José Public library system. This unique institution represents an ideal location for developing a Public Digital Humanities Center, with the goal of connecting academic digital humanists with community practitioners, arts and heritage organizations, and local populations. Funded by an NEH Infrastructure grant, King Library’s Public Digital Humanities Center will open in 2024 led by three partners - the university library, the College of Humanities and Arts, and the public library.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Throughout the spring of 2024, these partners conducted Community Conversations, soliciting input from city and university communities regarding the types of activities, programs, and initiatives the Center could help build and support. Conversations included focus groups and cognitive mapping activities.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In addition to providing invaluable insights and input into the requirements and expectations of our many diverse stakeholders, these Community Conversations highlighted the challenge of building a community-focused center using conceptual frameworks - such as “digital humanities” - that many community members, both inside and outside the university, were encountering for the first time. While the planning team is developing concrete outreach strategies to address this challenge, this input will also inform the development of the center’s mission, governance, and operational philosophy.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;This presentation will share the planning process of a collaborative Public Digital Humanities Center, offering insight into the expectations and ambitions of digital scholars and community collaborators.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. Library is a joint-use library, serving as the university library for San José State University as well as the main branch of the City of San José Public library system. This unique institution represents an ideal location for developing a Public Digital Humanities Center, with the goal of connecting academic digital humanists with community practitioners, arts and heritage organizations, and local populations. Funded by an NEH Infrastructure grant, King Library’s Public Digital Humanities Center will open in 2024 led by three partners - the university library, the College of Humanities and Arts, and the public library.&#10;Throughout the spring of 2024, these partners conducted Community Conversations, soliciting input from city and university communities regarding the types of activities, programs, and initiatives the Center could help build and support. Conversations included focus groups and cognitive mapping activities.&#10;In addition to providing invaluable insights and input into the requirements and expectations of our many diverse stakeholders, these Community Conversations highlighted the challenge of building a community-focused center using conceptual frameworks - such as “digital humanities” - that many community members, both inside and outside the university, were encountering for the first time. While the planning team is developing concrete outreach strategies to address this challenge, this input will also inform the development of the center’s mission, governance, and operational philosophy.&#10;This presentation will share the planning process of a collaborative Public Digital Humanities Center, offering insight into the expectations and ambitions of digital scholars and community collaborators.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
