    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nszydlowski@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nick.szydlowski@sjsu.edu, christina.mune@sjsu.edu, samantha.cramer@sjlibrary.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Szydlowski, Nick;&#10;Mune, Christina;&#10;Cramer, Samantha</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nick.szydlowski@sjsu.edu;&#10;christina.mune@sjsu.edu;&#10;samantha.cramer@sjlibrary.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pacific USA</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">79.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">64.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">269</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1111</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Starry, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission describes the planning process for a Public Digital Humanities Center that intends to connect academic digital humanities practitioners with community members and local organizations.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an interesting proposal and one that would make a great addition to the conference program, as many digital humanists conduct public humanities work and could benefit from hearing your reflections on how you&#039;re seeking to improve collaborations and communications with community partners.&#10;&#10;I would have liked to see a bit more reference to how the work of planning this particular public DH center relates to the literature and practice of developing DH centers in the US over the past 3 decades - how does what you&#039;re doing in San Jose connect to how other institutions have developed DH centers that are open to local communities?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1147</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Berger, Claudia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A report from an uniquely situated center</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I would love to see more about how scholarship/conversations in the field are helping to guide the work you are doing. Are there any frameworks you are using? Both from digital humanities and public humanities. I think this is a really important perspective, I just would like to see the grounding in previous work a little more explicit. Additionally I assume there are some DEI connections in your work, but it could also be more explicit. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Could be accepted as is, but it doesn&#039;t quite fit the rubric which impacts the score. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1122</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boyles, Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation discusses the practice of developing a DH center at a joint-use library.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation is very compelling. Not only does it address how to engage the public with ideas and practices pertaining to DH, but also it outlines a new form of institutional-community partnership. I would be particularly excited to hear more about the focus groups with community members--what about DH was interesting to them? what kinds of things did they want to do or not want to do? Are there effective strategies for building DH community through a joint-use library? I hope to hear more about this work at the conference!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
