    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Community-driven approaches to historic data: The case of racial covenant clauses</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">community archives; civic engagement; participatory technology; digital archives;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;crowdsourcing&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;crowdsourcing&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cultural studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;While the history of redlining is increasingly well-known, the similarly widespread practice of encoding racially restrictive covenants on property deeds has received significantly less attention. Though no longer enforceable by law, crowdsourced collaborations among civic data enthusiasts, librarians and archivists, humanities scholars, and public records administrators have raised awareness about the role of covenants and their impact.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In this paper, we describe our approach and share reflections from &quot;Hacking into History&quot;,a four-year community-driven project aimed at telling the story and impact of racial covenants in Durham, North Carolina. In particular, we focus our discussion on how digitization of these formerly analog records invokes ethical questions for communities and offers new possibilities and insights for regional and national understanding of how race was weaponized to restrict property ownership across the United States. We conclude by sharing strategies for successful community-driven approaches to local and regional data projects, and advocate for their value as pathways for extending community-building efforts.  &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While the history of redlining is increasingly well-known, the similarly widespread practice of encoding racially restrictive covenants on property deeds has received significantly less attention. Though no longer enforceable by law, crowdsourced collaborations among civic data enthusiasts, librarians and archivists, humanities scholars, and public records administrators have raised awareness about the role of covenants and their impact.&#10;In this paper, we describe our approach and share reflections from &quot;Hacking into History&quot;,a four-year community-driven project aimed at telling the story and impact of racial covenants in Durham, North Carolina. In particular, we focus our discussion on how digitization of these formerly analog records invokes ethical questions for communities and offers new possibilities and insights for regional and national understanding of how race was weaponized to restrict property ownership across the United States. We conclude by sharing strategies for successful community-driven approaches to local and regional data projects, and advocate for their value as pathways for extending community-building efforts.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
