    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">270</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1291</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pollock, Caitlin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Community-driven projects that decenter the university is an important facet of digital humanities. I did think that abstract felt rushed. The abstract could be strengthened with more details about racial covenants, crowd-sourced event, etc to give a framing for the project. I also think it would be interested to know some details as to how the stories of racial covenants would be told beyond just digitization. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1294</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Croxall, Brian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation will discuss a community-driven project on the topic of racial covenants in Durham, North Carolina. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation certainly fits within the scope of the conference&#039;s theme, and I think it&#039;s a presentation that would appeal to a number of attendees. &#10;&#10;With that being said, I think that the authors could have provided more detail throughout. First, if the history of redlining has become more well known thanks to scholarship perhaps those scholars could be mentioned in a passing parenthetical? So&#039;s *Redlining Culture* is just one example that easily came to mind. Second, the authors could explain what racial covenants are since they &quot;ha[ve] received significantly less attention&quot; than redlining. (I happened to know since my neighborhood recently worked to remove such a covenant.) Third, I would like to know more about the project. What sorts of ethical questions are raised by digitization? Are they the sorts of questions that normally arise from digitization or is there something specific about not wanting to digitize racially insensitive materials? I am told that this project is about &quot;telling [a] story&quot; but I&#039;m unclear how the story is being told or what the story is.&#10;&#10;I fully believe that this is an interesting project and probably worthy of inclusion in the conference. But I would also like to see the authors do more to articulate what they are going to be discussing. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1001</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lach, Pamella R.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission addresses ways of engaging in community-driven local and regional social justice data projects. Using their &quot;Hacking into History&quot; digital project about the impacts of racially-restrictive covenants in Durham, NC, it offers strategies for undertaking similar community-building projects in other places.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission focuses on a community-partnered project to digitize and share data about racially-restrictive covenants—and the historical and contemporary discrimination they wrought. Given how widespread covenants were (and how many are technically still on the books though no longer enforced) the &quot;Hacking into History&quot; project is deeply relevant and applicable to communities across the country. I appreciate that the authors intend to share some of the ethical challenges in working with these datasets, and would be curious to hear recommendations for how community members might use the data from this or similar local projects to advocate for tangible change.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
