    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The Personal Correspondence from the Rutgers College War Service Bureau is an ongoing pedagogical project to teach digital editing with the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) markup to students. The edition takes a trauma theory lense to its sources to explore questions relating to to the social construction of self and the gendering of survivor/victimhood narratives. These World War I letters encompass many vivid and diverse perspectives on the war experience, from men of different military ranks and socio-economic backgrounds, to chaplains, medical personnel, women working in the war effort, and women left at home. We have focused on a subset of letters that shed light on the topics of mental illness (shell shock), Spanish influenza, physical injury, death, loneliness, and grief. The social codes of the era often mean that these topics only reveal themselves in gaps or ellipses; we as editors interpret the correspondent as lonely when, for example, he repeatedly asks for or shares news of multiple classmates. The TEI is excellent for recording formal textual features but is rarely used to encode interpretive understandings (Cummings 2023; Singer 2013). We as editors struggled with how and where to locate our interpretations, whether at the level of the text, the letter, or as prefatory material, which is to say only peripherally connected to the markup. I use the process of creating this edition as a departure point for meditating on the difficulty of integrating theory with digital method, which is a feature of digital humanities projects that are legible to and advance scholarly disciplines.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Works Cited&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Cummings, James. 2023. “The Present and Future of Encoding Text(s).” In &lt;em&gt;The Bloomsbury Handbook to the Digital Humanities&lt;/em&gt;, 137–45. London: Bloomsbury Publishing.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Singer, Kate. 2013. “Digital Close Reading: TEI for Teaching Poetic Vocabularies.” &lt;em&gt;Journal of Interactive Technology &amp; Pedagogy&lt;/em&gt;, no. 3 (May).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Personal Correspondence from the Rutgers College War Service Bureau is an ongoing pedagogical project to teach digital editing with the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) markup to students. The edition takes a trauma theory lense to its sources to explore questions relating to to the social construction of self and the gendering of survivor/victimhood narratives. These World War I letters encompass many vivid and diverse perspectives on the war experience, from men of different military ranks and socio-economic backgrounds, to chaplains, medical personnel, women working in the war effort, and women left at home. We have focused on a subset of letters that shed light on the topics of mental illness (shell shock), Spanish influenza, physical injury, death, loneliness, and grief. The social codes of the era often mean that these topics only reveal themselves in gaps or ellipses; we as editors interpret the correspondent as lonely when, for example, he repeatedly asks for or shares news of multiple classmates. The TEI is excellent for recording formal textual features but is rarely used to encode interpretive understandings (Cummings 2023; Singer 2013). We as editors struggled with how and where to locate our interpretations, whether at the level of the text, the letter, or as prefatory material, which is to say only peripherally connected to the markup. I use the process of creating this edition as a departure point for meditating on the difficulty of integrating theory with digital method, which is a feature of digital humanities projects that are legible to and advance scholarly disciplines.&#10;Works Cited&#10;Cummings, James. 2023. “The Present and Future of Encoding Text(s).” In The Bloomsbury Handbook to the Digital Humanities, 137–45. London: Bloomsbury Publishing.&#10;Singer, Kate. 2013. “Digital Close Reading: TEI for Teaching Poetic Vocabularies.” Journal of Interactive Technology &amp; Pedagogy, no. 3 (May).</ss:Data></Cell>
