    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">271</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1146</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Mello, Jr., Lawrence Joseph</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper &quot;The pain point of integrating theory with digital method: reflections on editing war letters from a trauma theory perspective&quot; presents a compelling exploration of World War I through a unique lens, focusing on aspects often overlooked in mainstream historical narratives. By examining primary source letters from specific groups, the research offers a nuanced perspective on the conflict, emphasizing the trauma and mental illness experienced by those who lived through it. This approach humanizes historical figures and provides deeper insights into the psychological toll of war. Additionally, the study exemplifies the critical role of primary sources in historical analysis, allowing for an unfiltered view of the war experience. By integrating trauma theory with digital methodologies, the paper showcases the potential of interdisciplinary research to uncover new perspectives on historical events. It is a valuable example for researchers and students, illustrating how to effectively utilize primary sources to construct a comprehensive understanding of history. Ultimately, this study not only enhances our knowledge of World War I but also highlights the importance of examining historical events through the personal experiences of those who lived them, demonstrating how theoretical frameworks and digital methods can reveal new dimensions in historical research.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1186</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chagué, Alix</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission offers to present reflections on the difficulty to integrate theoretical interpretations in a digital edition. This reflection is grounded in the experience gained with the edition project conducted by the Personal Correspondence from the Rutgers College War Service Bureau. The theoretical interpretation which the authors wish to integrate in the digital edition emerge from the analysis of the corpus through the lense of trauma theory.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">to be detailed:&#10;&#10;Justification for the points awarded:&#10;- while the proposition and the presented project touch on issues of social construct and gender, which can intersect with intersectional feminism, it does not explicitly mention or directly connect with the anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, and/or multilingualism. The proposal&#039;s primary connection is to trauma theory and gender studies, with potential intersections in intersectional feminism.&#10;- the proposal explicitly engage with relevant scholarship and offers context within fields it engages in. It also discusses the challenges of integrating interpretive understandings into digital editions, reflecting broader issues within the digital humanities. &#10;- the abstract outlines a clear pedagogical and theoretical framework (utilizing TEI markup for teaching digital editing and applying trauma theory to analyze World War I letters) although these seem to be the focus of the project in the context of which the proposed reflection takes place. Furthermore, the abstract provides a concrete statement of purpose and touches on sociopolitical implications, such as the social construction of self and gendered narratives, though these implications could be more explicitly articulated.&#10;- the proposal highlights the practical use of TEI markup for teaching digital edition, the methodological challenge of integrating interpretive understandings within digital editions, and the theoretical application of trauma theory to historical correspondence. These elements collectively emphasize its relevance and contribution to the digital humanities field.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1293</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tew, Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper presents a digital edition of TEI-encoded wartime letters used as an experiential teaching tool in the university classroom. The edition takes a trauma theory lens and confronts the challenges to interpreting and encoding emotion in the letters.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a great project and the way the abstract is written I believe it will be a very strong presentation. The project described is strong as a pedagogical exercise in combining theory and experience. The abstract is strong in its clarity and thoroughness. I look forward to hearing more about this project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
