    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Effects of Generative AI on Student Learning in the Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">AI, ChatGPT, pedagogy, composition, essay writing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Education/Pedagogy&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The Pedagogy AI Research (PAIR) Group has been studying generative AI since 2022, before the launch of ChatGPT, because we believe these programs represent the most significant change to educational practice in the humanities since the invention of the Internet. Our first SSHRC-supported study, “Can instructors detect AI-generated papers? Postsecondary writing instructor knowledge and perceptions of AI,” found that even highly experienced writing instructors are unable to distinguish between student-written and AI-generated papers and concluded that it is both impractical and arguably unethical to police the use of generative AI in university classes.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;We are proposing to present the findings of our follow-up study at ACH 2024. Our new project considers one of the primary pedagogical concerns with permitting the use of generative AI to complete assignments: will its use compromise student learning? We hypothesize that students who used generative AI to write an essay would exhibit lower levels of comprehension and recall of that information compared with students who did not use generative AI. While our study is still underway, the preliminary results confirm our hypothesis that students who use ChatGPT to complete a written assignment learn less, understand less, and remember less about the topic than students who write an assignment on their own. However, there is a spectrum of learning loss across students who used generative AI, suggesting that instructors can potentially mitigate this loss with their pedagogical decisions. We will thus conclude our presentation by offering suggestions for how humanities instructors can best support student learning within this new cultural milieu where student use of generative AI is endemic.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Pedagogy AI Research (PAIR) Group has been studying generative AI since 2022, before the launch of ChatGPT, because we believe these programs represent the most significant change to educational practice in the humanities since the invention of the Internet. Our first SSHRC-supported study, “Can instructors detect AI-generated papers? Postsecondary writing instructor knowledge and perceptions of AI,” found that even highly experienced writing instructors are unable to distinguish between student-written and AI-generated papers and concluded that it is both impractical and arguably unethical to police the use of generative AI in university classes.&#10;We are proposing to present the findings of our follow-up study at ACH 2024. Our new project considers one of the primary pedagogical concerns with permitting the use of generative AI to complete assignments: will its use compromise student learning? We hypothesize that students who used generative AI to write an essay would exhibit lower levels of comprehension and recall of that information compared with students who did not use generative AI. While our study is still underway, the preliminary results confirm our hypothesis that students who use ChatGPT to complete a written assignment learn less, understand less, and remember less about the topic than students who write an assignment on their own. However, there is a spectrum of learning loss across students who used generative AI, suggesting that instructors can potentially mitigate this loss with their pedagogical decisions. We will thus conclude our presentation by offering suggestions for how humanities instructors can best support student learning within this new cultural milieu where student use of generative AI is endemic.</ss:Data></Cell>
