    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">272</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1245</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sempere, Anindita Basu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper addresses the use of generative AI by students in humanities classrooms. As expected, their study finds that students who use generative AI to produce assignments do not understand or retain topics very well. They will offer ways that instructors might adapt pedagogical practices to mitigate different types of learning loss.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Although the paper does not directly engage the conference theme, this is a major issue for all humanities instructors and highly relevant to conference attendees. While a great deal of discussion about generative AI currently focuses on how to use it in the classroom or how to identify/discourage its use, I appreciate the practicality of this paper: regardless of how instructors feel, students will use generative AI. How do we make sure they still learn the material? &#10;&#10;I am curious about the different types of learning loss the authors have identified, and I believe the paper will lead to a rich and interesting discussion.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1232</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Faerber-Ovaska, Rachel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal investigates the impact of GAI tools on student learning in postsecondary writing courses. The authors, from the Pedagogy AI Research Group, found that instructors often cannot distinguish between AI-generated and student-written papers. Their follow-up study suggests that using AI to complete assignments leads to lower comprehension and recall among students. Their preliminary results support this hypothesis, but also suggest that pedagogical strategies could mitigate learning loss. This is an important, timely research study that promises to provide practical recommendations for integrating AI in a way that supports (rather than harming) student learning and equity. Evidence-based, practical recommendations on effectively teaching writing in the age of AI are sorely needed right now.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is the kind of information we need right now! Composition instructors at my institution are wrestling with the problem of teaching students to think and to write in an environment where it&#039;s tempting &amp; easy for students to resort to AI-based shortcuts. The evidence-based suggestions you promise to share on how instructors can adapt their pedagogical approaches to our new AI-infused context (without trying to ban it -- futile!) will be greatly appreciated. Incidentally, your proposal made me think of Bastani, Hamsa et al.&#039;s recent study, Generative AI Can Harm Learning. I wonder if your study and theirs produced similar findings -- it sounds like maybe they did.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While I don&#039;t see a direct connection to the themes of &quot;connected to anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, and/or multilingualism,&quot; still I think it&#039;s very important work, and would be helpful for attendees. After all, mitigating GAI-induced learning loss is a goal that will help all the disciplines.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1156</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Black, Michael</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation looks to build upon past research on the use of generative AI in classrooms. In particular, this presentation examines the potential for learning loss, presents preliminary data showing that such loss does occur when students use generative AI to complete projects (compared to students who do not use it), and considers way that instructors could mitigate that loss.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While the single citation of the the authors&#039; previous study is doing a lot of work here, the proposal is overall clear in its aims and what it provide those in the audience. Debates over the quality of AI-produced text seem like they will never see firm resolution (esp. given the varying contexts of work, professional expectations, disciplinary norms related to writing, etc), addressing its use from the perspective of &quot;learning loss&quot; seems a much more effective tactic. Learning loss is likely behind a lot of concern over its use from instructors in the humanities, particularly in writing studies. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">60</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
