    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Better Living Through Paperwork: Using the Tools of Bureaucracy to Imagine Radical Futures</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">imagination, infrastructure studies, remix, speculative methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;media archaeology&#10;Design studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">media archaeology</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Design studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Across the country, student protesters who are insisting on better worlds are being met with riot police and mass arrests. As state, bureaucratic, and administrative forces increasingly constrain what is possible both within the academy and for our communities, it has become increasingly urgent to resist the erosion of our collective imaginations for what is possible. Indeed, calls for change often invoke what Lily Irani describes as “minimum viable futures - the least common denominator people can agree on without resorting to a longer, slower mass politics&quot; (Irani, 2019, p. 210).  Can we refuse to settle for minimum viable futures and find pathways to magnificently livable, kind, and communal futures instead?  &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;In Better Living Through Paperwork, we argue that is not a deliberate settling, but rather an atrophying of our collective imaginations. We invoke Arjun Appadurai’s (1996) imagination as “an organized field of social practice,” and put it in conversation with both the theories and practices of infrastructure and bureaucracy (p. 31).  Drawing Herd and Moynihan’s administrative burden, and Dean Spade’s administrative violence, we foreground the ways that the quotidian practices of “business as usual” are constricting our capacities to dream infinite alternatives. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;While Ruth Wilson Gilmore (2024) quips that abolition “requires us to change one thing: everything,” Gilmore also reminds us that we cannot make all of those changes at once - we must start by practicing radical imagination with the infrastructures around us. We turn our radical imagination to the mundane: the flow charts, org charts, performance assessments and annual reports of bureaucracy. These are tools used by states, corporations and organizations to build the structures and paradigms that oppress us.  Can we use them in the service of our own liberation? &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Better Living Through Paperwork is an invitation to exercise our imagination with and against common bureaucratic formalisms. The roundtable will open with a discussion of bureaucratic paperwork and the way the fields, organization and hierarchy constrain what we can imagine to be possible, along with an overview of collage and to remix methods employed by artists to examine societal structures and re-imagine futures. From there, participants will use a curated collection of source material with collage and remix strategies to re-imagine existing paperwork with fields and structures that create affordances for the worlds we want. Using this common and familiar language, we will facilitate a space for scholars in varied disciplines to reflect on their own practices, discover new space for growth and encourage more ambitious moves toward justice.We envision participants sharing this work back to a repository of speculative works, hosted on Humanities Commons. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;While we honor and value the academy’s role in supporting “deep critique,” that way of &quot;thinking beneath and beyond liberal legalist approaches to social problems&quot; (Ashar, 2016, p. 217) we follow abolitionist legal scholar Amna Akbar (2018) who reminds us that we are living in “a moment calling for a radical imagination, where the scale of deep critique is matched with a scale of grand vision” (p.9)&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Across the country, student protesters who are insisting on better worlds are being met with riot police and mass arrests. As state, bureaucratic, and administrative forces increasingly constrain what is possible both within the academy and for our communities, it has become increasingly urgent to resist the erosion of our collective imaginations for what is possible. Indeed, calls for change often invoke what Lily Irani describes as “minimum viable futures - the least common denominator people can agree on without resorting to a longer, slower mass politics&quot; (Irani, 2019, p. 210). Can we refuse to settle for minimum viable futures and find pathways to magnificently livable, kind, and communal futures instead? &#10;In Better Living Through Paperwork, we argue that is not a deliberate settling, but rather an atrophying of our collective imaginations. We invoke Arjun Appadurai’s (1996) imagination as “an organized field of social practice,” and put it in conversation with both the theories and practices of infrastructure and bureaucracy (p. 31). Drawing Herd and Moynihan’s administrative burden, and Dean Spade’s administrative violence, we foreground the ways that the quotidian practices of “business as usual” are constricting our capacities to dream infinite alternatives. &#10;While Ruth Wilson Gilmore (2024) quips that abolition “requires us to change one thing: everything,” Gilmore also reminds us that we cannot make all of those changes at once - we must start by practicing radical imagination with the infrastructures around us. We turn our radical imagination to the mundane: the flow charts, org charts, performance assessments and annual reports of bureaucracy. These are tools used by states, corporations and organizations to build the structures and paradigms that oppress us. Can we use them in the service of our own liberation? &#10;Better Living Through Paperwork is an invitation to exercise our imagination with and against common bureaucratic formalisms. The roundtable will open with a discussion of bureaucratic paperwork and the way the fields, organization and hierarchy constrain what we can imagine to be possible, along with an overview of collage and to remix methods employed by artists to examine societal structures and re-imagine futures. From there, participants will use a curated collection of source material with collage and remix strategies to re-imagine existing paperwork with fields and structures that create affordances for the worlds we want. Using this common and familiar language, we will facilitate a space for scholars in varied disciplines to reflect on their own practices, discover new space for growth and encourage more ambitious moves toward justice.We envision participants sharing this work back to a repository of speculative works, hosted on Humanities Commons. &#10;While we honor and value the academy’s role in supporting “deep critique,” that way of &quot;thinking beneath and beyond liberal legalist approaches to social problems&quot; (Ashar, 2016, p. 217) we follow abolitionist legal scholar Amna Akbar (2018) who reminds us that we are living in “a moment calling for a radical imagination, where the scale of deep critique is matched with a scale of grand vision” (p.9)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Stevens, Nikki</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">MIT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nikkilstevens@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">paula.l.olson@dartmouth.edu, molly.c.morin@dartmouth.edu, nikkilstevens@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Olson, Paula;&#10;Morin, Molly;&#10;Stevens, Nikki</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">paula.l.olson@dartmouth.edu;&#10;molly.c.morin@dartmouth.edu;&#10;nikkilstevens@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">95.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">273</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1040</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ferretti, Giulia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract proposes the holding of a roundtable to discuss the Better Living Through Paperwork project. The project builds on the idea that the collective imagination, which is social in nature, is limited in its revolutionary nature by administrative and bureaucratic cumbersomeness, which often delimits what is possible to do and achieve. This proposition is intended to provide space for a discussion of how such administrative and bureaucratic practices can change so that they can make social and imaginative change.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Very well articulated and presented work, which could be a fertile field for questioning everyday practices and rethinking their impact on our way of thinking and being in the world.&#10;I would have perhaps recommended specifying specific communities of reference (humanities? dh? social sciences?), to ensure that the discussion will not overly derive. In other words, the notion of &quot;community&quot; mentioned in the text is generic and should be questioned as a homogeneous entity.&#10;Finally, moreover, I believe that the &quot;liberation&quot; envisioned in the text does not come about through the selection of some alternative practices (which might become the dominant one, and thus potentially oppressive with respect to diversity), but precisely through the reflection and constant questioning of such practices.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">94</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1058</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Smith, Nancy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Better Living Through Paperwork is a timely roundtable that aims to draw connections between bureaucratic and administrative forces that often act in conflict with activism, protest, and other liberatory practices. The roundtable focuses on what we can do to create radical and imaginative change in a world that is designed to push us toward &quot;business as usual.&quot; This roundtable is very participatory and asks people to bring their own perspectives and ideas while collectively making a repository of speculative works.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an excellent proposal and the ideas feel especially relevant as we are in a political moment that requires us to challenge the status quo and develop new ways of addressing our most pressing issues. The format of a roundtable makes sense for the ideas explored and I can imagine a lot of generative and collective conversation happening around bureaucratic paperwork and its power in preventing change. One question I had is if the focus of this is around academic administrative processes or more business-oriented practices. In the abstract, it sounded like it could be both, and it would be interesting to articulate the way paperwork functions differently (or similarly) across different areas. For example, within STEM fields vs. the humanities, or within the tech industry vs. the government. It would be great to highlight in a bit more detail what the methods are that will be used within the workshop (collage and remixing are just a bit vague). Overall, I think this workshop will spark curiosity and challenge people to think creatively about justice-oriented futures. I really appreciate the interactive nature of it as well as the use of art in relation to political change. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1272</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Jacob, Arun</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The project proposal highlights the emancipatory potential of bureaucracy when used in service of abolitionist radical futurities. The logic of a combatant mobilizing the weight and strength of their opponent to one&#039;s advantage rather than countering each blow directly is an appealing prospect to this reader. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The conceptual thinking and design methodologies being suggested here are very inspiring, and this reader can clearly see how this would make for an engaging roundtable with fruitful discussions. Perhaps if the authors considered including exemplars and/or deliverables, use-cases where this thinking could germinate and mobilized, that would be very helpful to the audience. i.e. Is there a teaching and learning activity around this mode of analysis that could be brought to life in a classroom, in a union organizing drive, in a community centre, daycare centre, senior&#039;s facility centre, etc? Having the speculative design ideas interface with real-world scenarios would make for a very inspiring and engaging talk. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Perhaps the authors could highlight how their work could be anchored in the field of Digital Humanities through an exemplar that highlights their research methodology and design aesthetics. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
