    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Queer machines : a posteriori concepts and identity deconstructions</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Human-machine, Materialism, Queer platforms, Python, JSON</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Italian&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;Queer Studies&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Media studies&#10;Philosophy&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Italian</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Queer Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Media studies&#10;Philosophy&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;To be queer is to stand on the threshold, valuing the fecundity of ambiguity (Klotz &amp; Whithaus, 2015). Queer thought thus implies a deconstruction of concepts as monolithic, a priori entities. In this context, ideas and conceptual forms exist only materially engendered somewhere, as the always-in-construction results of a series of material and localized forces (Hayles, 2005). This presentation aims to show how digital technologies can be queer, resisting any definitive disambiguation effort. Adopting an action-research approach, I will argue this hypothesis from two creation experiments that I carried out over the past year.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt; The first consists of a Python script that reduces any text to the fundamental set of shapes, colors, and directionalities perceived by infants at 12 months, according to Inhelder et Piaget (1966). Such script generates texts that are paradoxical and entirely unrelated to the source text. It shows how Python can enable an a posteriori introduction of meaning, rather than merely reducing specific terms to general concepts. This project  demonstrates how conceptual forms can result from material sets of knowledge and technologies.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt; The second project involves a RESTful web service that I developed to organize some fundamental concepts from my doctoral thesis. Here I will show how the tree structure imposed by JSON format compels us to deconstruct and break down the individual traits of the concepts or objects we want to define. REST and JSON reject the possibility of monolithic and immutable identities, showing the queer potential of machines: platforms, databases and scripts can still stand on the threshold.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Hayles, N. Katherine. 2005. &lt;em&gt;My Mother Was a Computer: Digital Subjects and Literary Texts&lt;/em&gt;. Chicago: University of Chicago.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Inhelder, Bärbel, Jean Piaget. 2012. &lt;em&gt;La psychologie de l’enfant&lt;/em&gt;. Paris: PUF. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&#10;Klotz, Sarah, Carl Whithaus. 2015. Gloria Anzaldúa’s Rhetoric of Ambiguity and Antiracist Teaching. &lt;em&gt;Composition Studies&lt;/em&gt; 43 (2). &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">To be queer is to stand on the threshold, valuing the fecundity of ambiguity (Klotz &amp; Whithaus, 2015). Queer thought thus implies a deconstruction of concepts as monolithic, a priori entities. In this context, ideas and conceptual forms exist only materially engendered somewhere, as the always-in-construction results of a series of material and localized forces (Hayles, 2005). This presentation aims to show how digital technologies can be queer, resisting any definitive disambiguation effort. Adopting an action-research approach, I will argue this hypothesis from two creation experiments that I carried out over the past year.&#10; The first consists of a Python script that reduces any text to the fundamental set of shapes, colors, and directionalities perceived by infants at 12 months, according to Inhelder et Piaget (1966). Such script generates texts that are paradoxical and entirely unrelated to the source text. It shows how Python can enable an a posteriori introduction of meaning, rather than merely reducing specific terms to general concepts. This project demonstrates how conceptual forms can result from material sets of knowledge and technologies.&#10; The second project involves a RESTful web service that I developed to organize some fundamental concepts from my doctoral thesis. Here I will show how the tree structure imposed by JSON format compels us to deconstruct and break down the individual traits of the concepts or objects we want to define. REST and JSON reject the possibility of monolithic and immutable identities, showing the queer potential of machines: platforms, databases and scripts can still stand on the threshold.&#10;Hayles, N. Katherine. 2005. My Mother Was a Computer: Digital Subjects and Literary Texts. Chicago: University of Chicago.&#10;Inhelder, Bärbel, Jean Piaget. 2012. La psychologie de l’enfant. Paris: PUF. &#10;Klotz, Sarah, Carl Whithaus. 2015. Gloria Anzaldúa’s Rhetoric of Ambiguity and Antiracist Teaching. Composition Studies 43 (2).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ferretti, Giulia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Université de Montréal</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">giulia.ferretti@umontreal.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">giulia.ferretti@umontreal.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ferretti, Giulia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">giulia.ferretti@umontreal.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">70.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">58.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">274</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1130</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Murphy, Emily Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Uses participation-action and research-creation methods to demonstrate how digital technologies “stand on the threshold” of queerness. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I find this abstract’s consideration of queerness in technology and how action-research or research-creation might demonstrate technology’s resistance of “any definitive disambiguation effort” really compelling. Research-creation is an appropriate framework for experimental research in applied queered approaches to digital technology. &#10;&#10;I would suggest that the presentation present only one of these experiments and flesh out a theoretical and analytical framework specific to that experiment only. Including both experiments risks being too disjointed, when it would be more effective to draw out the discussion of just one of these interesting experiments.  &#10;&#10;I suggest incorporating scholarly research that more directly addresses the queer research-creation framework that the author is interested in. Klotz and Whithaus discuss pedagogy, while Hayles’s monograph is not explicitly about queerness. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">If this contribution is considered, I would suggest that one of the two experiments be featured as a poster. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">58</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1091</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Beverly-Porter, Diamond</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution of this proposal is its relevancy to the intersection of digital humanities and technology.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a strong proposal. &quot;This presentation aims to show how digital technologies can be queer, resisting any definitive disambiguation effort.&quot; However It could be improved with a bit more specificity with how technologies are queer in its refusals to be categorized.&#10;&#10;This submission could be improved by considering:&#10;&#10;1.) Sender, Katherine, and Adrienne Shaw, editors. Queer Technologies : Affordances, Affect, Ambivalence. Routledge, 2017.&#10;&#10;2.) Blas, Z., Cárdenas, M. Imaginary computational systems: queer technologies and transreal aesthetics. AI &amp; Soc 28, 559–566 (2013). https://doi.org/10.1007/s00146-013-0502-y&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1316</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Meneses, Luis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation aims to show how digital technologies can be queer, resisting any definitive disambiguation effort. Adopting an action-research approach, the author will argue this hypothesis using two experiments.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an interesting proposal, that is very relevant to scope of the conference. It also does present a different view on software and the tools that we use as digital humanists. &#10;&#10;Having said that, I would have liked to see more details specifically stated: the methodology used, and the contributions to the scholarship in DH. These details could have been omitted because of the word count of the proposal, but I am sure they will be mentioned in the actual presentation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
