    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cancel Culture in Online Sex Work Communities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cancel Culture, Sex Work, Digital Safety, Systemic Bias, Public Sphere</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Queer Studies&#10;North America&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;social media analysis and methods&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Ethnography&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;social media analysis and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Queer Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Ethnography&#10;Feminist studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Online communities always have a unique relationship with “cancel culture,” but sex-work focused spaces have particularly embraced the practice of calling out and rejecting abusive and problematic behavior. This study aims to analyze the dynamics of “cancel culture” within an online sex-work community on X (formerly Twitter) through a combination of deep interview-based ethnography and broader surveys. The research investigates two angles: first, how community members may engage in canceling behaviors as a form of self-policing to maintain safety and integrity, given their shared vulnerability in discussing intimate aspects of their lives and sharing personal images; and second, how a heavily self-policing community may reinforce existing dynamics of power especially for marginalized identity groups. Through in-depth interviews, the ethnographic component delves into the personal experiences of both perpetrators and targets of canceling, exploring their motivations, perceptions of justice, and understandings of canceling’s role in their communities. The broader survey seeks to quantify the prevalence of cancel culture, the overall sentiment towards this practice within the community, and feelings around community vulnerability and online harassment. This study will engage with Michel Foucault&#039;s theories on surveillance and power, Nancy Fraser&#039;s critique of the public sphere, and &lt;em&gt;Cancel culture can be collectively validating for groups experiencing harm &lt;/em&gt;by Traversa, Tian and Wright, along with other relevant research. By examining the mechanisms through which “cancel culture” operates in these communities, we can understand both systemic biases that may exist in the way it is implemented, and potential benefits in terms of community-enforced digital safety. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Generative AI was used in the drafting process of the above abstract; very little of the original output survives in the final text.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Online communities always have a unique relationship with “cancel culture,” but sex-work focused spaces have particularly embraced the practice of calling out and rejecting abusive and problematic behavior. This study aims to analyze the dynamics of “cancel culture” within an online sex-work community on X (formerly Twitter) through a combination of deep interview-based ethnography and broader surveys. The research investigates two angles: first, how community members may engage in canceling behaviors as a form of self-policing to maintain safety and integrity, given their shared vulnerability in discussing intimate aspects of their lives and sharing personal images; and second, how a heavily self-policing community may reinforce existing dynamics of power especially for marginalized identity groups. Through in-depth interviews, the ethnographic component delves into the personal experiences of both perpetrators and targets of canceling, exploring their motivations, perceptions of justice, and understandings of canceling’s role in their communities. The broader survey seeks to quantify the prevalence of cancel culture, the overall sentiment towards this practice within the community, and feelings around community vulnerability and online harassment. This study will engage with Michel Foucault&#039;s theories on surveillance and power, Nancy Fraser&#039;s critique of the public sphere, and Cancel culture can be collectively validating for groups experiencing harm by Traversa, Tian and Wright, along with other relevant research. By examining the mechanisms through which “cancel culture” operates in these communities, we can understand both systemic biases that may exist in the way it is implemented, and potential benefits in terms of community-enforced digital safety. &#10;Generative AI was used in the drafting process of the above abstract; very little of the original output survives in the final text.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
