    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">94.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">275</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1052</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Coghill, KáLyn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This study examines the dynamics of &quot;cancel culture&quot; within an online sex-work community on X (formerly Twitter), using a combination of deep interview-based ethnography and broader surveys. It investigates two main aspects: how community members use canceling behaviors as a form of self-policing to maintain safety and integrity and how such practices may reinforce existing power dynamics, particularly affecting marginalized groups. The ethnographic component explores the personal experiences of both perpetrators and targets of canceling, focusing on their motivations and perceptions of justice. The survey aims to quantify the prevalence and sentiment of cancel culture within the community and assess feelings about vulnerability and online harassment. The study engages with theories from Michel Foucault on surveillance and power, Nancy Fraser on the public sphere, and additional research on the validation aspects of cancel culture. The goal is to understand systemic biases in cancel culture implementation and its potential benefits for community-enforced digital safety.&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The comprehensive approach is appropriate for the research. Doing interviews and ethnography allows the researcher to center the voices of sex workers. Some additional information on the survey design and interview process could enhance understanding of how data is collected and analyzed. It would also benefit the researcher to engage with Meredith Clark&#039;s work on Cancel Culture. There could be some potential biases around the study, and the researcher should consider how their perspectives might influence interpretations of cancel culture and its impacts.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1211</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rashid, Mohammed</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The talk explores the dynamics of &quot;cancel culture&quot; in online sex-work communities, specifically drawing on ethnographic data (through interviews and surveys) from an X/Twitter based online sex-work community. Foregrounding theoretical perspectives around power, surveillance, counter-publics, digital affect, and online harassment, the talk aims to investigate how &#039;cancel culture&#039; in online communities is both a community policing mechanism to keep vulnerable communities safe online, as well as an apparatus that reinforces longstanding modes of oppression against minority communities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a wonderfully put together abstract. The arguments are clear and the methodology is precise. I also want to say good job on the theoretical perspectives you are engaging with in the talk. &#10;&#10;I do want to share a couple of theoretical suggestions that you may already be aware of, and I strongly believe they will make the arguments more robust. &#10;&#10;In your engagement with Foucault&#039;s ideas of surveillance and power, I wonder if you may want to consider more recent developments around these issues, particularly from Black feminist thought - see Simone Browne, Ruha Benjamin, and Catherine Squires. Catherine Squires work on multiple counter-publics may also be a useful extension on Nancy Fraser&#039;s critique of the public-sphere. Recently, Sarah Jackson and Daniel Kreiss have an article on &quot;defensive publics&quot; which I think may be very useful to the arguments you make here. Finally, wondering if in your arguments around online harassment you speak about Alice Marwick&#039;s work who makes a case for how networked and&#10;online harassments stems from a need to enforce established social order. Is there a particular social order which &quot;cancel culture&quot; in online sex-work communities uphold, oppose, endorse (or something else?)&#10;&#10;Wishing you all the best with the paper, the talk, and the overall project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project is proposed as a lightning talk. I also think that it will do well as a panel paper on topics such as Cancel Culture, Online Sex Work, Digital Affect, Online Publics and Counter-publics, Online Hate and Harrasment.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1018</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Monzó-Nebot, Esther</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This study provides a comprehensive analysis of &quot;cancel culture&quot; within an online sex-work community on X (formerly Twitter). The main contributions are:&#10;1.	Deep interview-based ethnography: The research uses in-depth interviews to explore personal experiences of both perpetrators and targets of canceling, revealing motivations, perceptions of justice, and the role of canceling in the community.&#10;2.	Broader surveys: Surveys quantify the prevalence of cancel culture, community sentiment towards the practice, and feelings about vulnerability and online harassment.&#10;3.	Dual focus analysis: The study investigates how cancel culture is used for self-policing to maintain safety and integrity and how it might reinforce existing power dynamics, especially for marginalized groups.&#10;4.	Theoretical engagement: The research engages with theories from Michel Foucault on surveillance and power, Nancy Fraser’s critique of the public sphere, and relevant works on cancel culture to contextualize its findings.&#10;5.	Understanding mechanisms and biases: By examining the implementation mechanisms of cancel culture, the study aims to uncover systemic biases and highlight potential benefits for community-enforced digital safety.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The combination of deep interview-based ethnography and broader surveys is a major asset of the proposal, enabling an understanding of cancel culture dynamics within the sex-work community on X. By concentrating on a specific online community, the study can offer detailed insights into the object of study, the unique ways cancel culture operates in sex-work spaces. The dual focus on self-policing for safety and the reinforcement of power dynamics highlights the complexity of cancel culture, acknowledging both its protective and potentially problematic aspects. The study’s emphasis on marginalized identity groups within the sex-work community addresses important issues of power and vulnerability, making the research socially relevant and impactful.&#10;&#10;The depth of the ethnographic interviews is a strength, but they might not capture the full diversity of experiences within the community, potentially leading to oversimplified conclusions about the prevalence and sentiment towards cancel culture. Triangulating findings with other data sources or employing neutral questioning techniques and explicitly acknowledging the limitations can contribute to a more robust presentation of the results. &#10;Additionally, the authors may want to highlight how researching a vulnerable community like sex workers requires careful ethical considerations, and clarify issues of consent and confidentiality considered in the research.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
