    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">boltt@lafayette.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">boltt@lafayette.edu, pramit.chaudhuri@austin.utexas.edu, jdexter@fas.harvard.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bolt, Thomas J;&#10;Dexter, Joseph</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">boltt@lafayette.edu;&#10;jdexter@fas.harvard.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">GMT -4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">276</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1243</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Camps, Jean-Baptiste</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very interesting abstract, that adresses important question in stylometric research, especially when dealing with premodern data. The question of the distinction (and respective strength or features) of generic vs idiolectal variation has for instance not attracted enough contributions yet. From what it is possible to judge from a simple abstract, the approach, methodology and knowledge of the field seem sound.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a very interesting abstract, that adresses important question in stylometric research, especially when dealing with premodern data. The question of the distinction (and respective strength or features) of generic vs idiolectal variation has for instance not attracted enough contributions yet. From what it is possible to judge from a simple abstract, the approach, methodology and knowledge of the field seem sound.&#10;&#10;Here are a few questions or suggestions to improve it further:&#10;&#10;- «use machine learning to identify the characteristic features of each genre»: what type of methods did you use ? You mention dimensionality reduction and machine learning, but I would be curious to know more (and perhaps a justification of the choice, beyond the reference).&#10;- Have you looked into stylometric analyses of genre vs. idiolect, or variation between voices in a single work, already published for other period of time, other languages, etc. ? It would be very interesting to refer to it and discuss your findings in light of the (small) existing literature on the topic.&#10;- What are the chronological boundaries (and precise constitution) of the corpus ? Could diachronic variation impact your results ?&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1308</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wymer, Kathryn C</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project adds to multilingual DH through an analysis of a Latin-language literary corpus. The authors apply tools more commonly used in analyzing modern language to a premodern set of texts.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I&#039;m really excited about this one! I have a good friend who works extensively in Latin and has long used the many digital editions of Latin texts. Latin is an excellent choice for working with text analysis tools. I&#039;m interested to learn more about what the early Latin corpus lacks in terms of NLP applications and also to learn what it is that these researchers have done in their analysis.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I love this application of multilingual DH to a premodern language corpus!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1095</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bozia, Eleni</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors propose to present stylometric analysis for the analysis of Latin literary texts. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract is very well written. The authors offer an overview of relevant work, the exigency for such work in premodern languages, and their specific contribution to the study of Latin. &#10;&#10;Their coverage is coherent, and their argument is well articulated. The work they have done thus far and the results they propose to present seem very plausible. Specifically, I &#10;believe that they should stand the test of philological accuracy while reaching a level of automation, speed, and number of studied texts/authors that you cannot have with traditional manual work.&#10;&#10;Overall, their work seems very promising and in the right direction for advancing classical studies. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Very good work that should be presented and encouraged given that there are not too many researchers who focus on premodern languages. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
