    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Poster Review of Tree.fm</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Environmental Humanities, review, digital media, crowdsourced.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;crowdsourcing&#10;eco-criticism and environmental analysis&#10;Environmental, ocean, and waterways studies&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">crowdsourcing&#10;eco-criticism and environmental analysis&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Environmental, ocean, and waterways studies&#10;Library and Information Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This poster serves as a case study in how to critically review environmental digital projects by using a digital humanities lens. In this poster, I will analyze the platform Tree.fm and how it functions within the larger scope of environmental preservation amidst the climate crisis. This project highlights the critiques and nuances in how to review and approach an environmental digital platform with a Digital Humanities lens and scope. Tree.fm showcases the potential of digital humanities in addressing the climate crisis and fosters an understanding and appreciation of our current environmental landscape and precarities. Tree.fm effectively provides access to unique soundscapes, and it has a range of methods for long-term digital preservation. These aspects underscore the ongoing challenges faced by digital projects in ensuring the longevity and accessibility of their content. This poster fulfills the conference theme by reviewing an environmental digital platform within the context of the Anthropocene. Tree.fm, represents a significant contribution to environmental visualization, offering users a way to critically engage with the natural world. It aims to highlight Tree.fm’s unique approach towards preserving forest sounds by demonstrating effective digital preservation methods. As the platform encourages users to appreciate and engage with nature in innovative ways by emphasizing its role in environmental soundscape and climate awareness. Furthermore, this poster serves as a bridge between technology, nature, and community, making it a valuable contribution to both academic and environmental consciousness spaces and shows how Digital Humanities can play a part in tackling and engaging with the climate crisis.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This poster serves as a case study in how to critically review environmental digital projects by using a digital humanities lens. In this poster, I will analyze the platform Tree.fm and how it functions within the larger scope of environmental preservation amidst the climate crisis. This project highlights the critiques and nuances in how to review and approach an environmental digital platform with a Digital Humanities lens and scope. Tree.fm showcases the potential of digital humanities in addressing the climate crisis and fosters an understanding and appreciation of our current environmental landscape and precarities. Tree.fm effectively provides access to unique soundscapes, and it has a range of methods for long-term digital preservation. These aspects underscore the ongoing challenges faced by digital projects in ensuring the longevity and accessibility of their content. This poster fulfills the conference theme by reviewing an environmental digital platform within the context of the Anthropocene. Tree.fm, represents a significant contribution to environmental visualization, offering users a way to critically engage with the natural world. It aims to highlight Tree.fm’s unique approach towards preserving forest sounds by demonstrating effective digital preservation methods. As the platform encourages users to appreciate and engage with nature in innovative ways by emphasizing its role in environmental soundscape and climate awareness. Furthermore, this poster serves as a bridge between technology, nature, and community, making it a valuable contribution to both academic and environmental consciousness spaces and shows how Digital Humanities can play a part in tackling and engaging with the climate crisis.</ss:Data></Cell>
