    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1257</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Burress, Theresa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal describes a case study in how to critically review environmental digital projects through a digital humanities lens. The proposal will engage with a digital platformc called Tree.fm, analyzing its position within environmental and climate studies. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a compelling proposal that aims to analyze a digital audio platform focusing on environmental sounds through the lens of DH and the broader field of environmental humanities/climate studies. It would be helpful if the authors explicitly engage with the relevant scholarship regarding critical review of DH platforms and projects. I look forward to seeing their poster.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">60</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1295</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Lindblad, Purdom</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The poster outlines criteria and strategies to evaluate digital work with considerations of sustainability, access, and preservation while surfacing current environmental precarities and challenges. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal strongly positions the key needs and contributions to the review and evaluation of environmental digital humanities projects. The author outlines the Tree.fm project, goals, and stakes clearly and compellingly. The proposal could be improved through the situation of the project and poster within the current literature of environmental digital humanities. The strengths of the proposal are many, including the bridge work between community, experience, nature, and technology. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal will make a great poster, but could also be a compelling lightning talk. Not sure of author&#039;s capacity, but a lightning talk could draw more visitors to the poster, which has the potential to be a strong contribution to the conference.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1319</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bago, Petra</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author presents an interesting endeavor to potentially propose a model on how to critically review environmental digital projects through a digital humanities lens.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author presents an intriguing endeavor to propose a model for critically reviewing environmental digital projects through a digital humanities lens. This approach is necessary for future reviews of such projects. However, there are two areas that could be improved. First, the author does not clearly introduce the Tree.fm project, the subject of the study, making it difficult to understand how to critically review the project. Second, the author only outlines the final goal of the paper without detailing the methodology. What are the elements of the critical review that the author has identified? How has the author reached these conclusions? These questions, raised at the beginning of the abstract, remain unanswered by the end. Additionally, the abstract&#039;s structure interchanges these points, contributing to its lack of clarity.&#10;&#10;To improve this abstract, I suggest the author clearly and concisely present the project under study. Next, they should articulate the study&#039;s goal. Finally, I recommend that the author highlight some of the most interesting elements identified for conducting a critical review of such projects.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">36</ss:Data></Cell>
