    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Building a Computational Minor for Arts and Humanities</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">computing for arts and humanities; generative AI; design of an interdisciplinary minor</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Experimental Humanities&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;curricular and pedagogical development and analysis&#10;Computer science&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">curricular and pedagogical development and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Experimental Humanities&#10;Computer science&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Within a panel or roundtable session, we would like to contribute on the larger conversation about &lt;strong&gt;“Digital and computational approaches to humanistic research and pedagogy”.&lt;/strong&gt; We will be sharing ideas about designing an interdisciplinary minor titled &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Minor in AI Computing for Arts and Humanities.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This minor adds a computational component to students interested in applying modern computing tools to solve tasks across Arts and Humanities. The minor provides two main benefits – gives students knowledge of and experience with cutting edge technology in their respective fields and provides additional opportunities to explore the intersection of Humanities, Social Sciences, and Arts and technology.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The students will learn to use generative AI ethically and effectively for building computational solutions for solving problems in arts and humanities. Within this minor, students will:&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;1.            apply a basic programming language such as Python for text and image processing.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;2.            use computing tools for organizing data (concepts form database or web design or statistics).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;3.            apply generative AI tool for addressing research questions in their own field (accomplished via a project-based course).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;4.            apply computing tools for data visualization.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;5.            understand ethical problems in computing and AI.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Keywords: computing for arts and humanities; generative AI; design of an interdisciplinary minor&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Participants from the College of Wooster: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;ul type=&quot;disc&quot;&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Ahmet Atay, Professor of Global Media and Digital Studies&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Caitlyn Deeter, Educational Technologist&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Christa Craven, Professor of Anthropology and Women&#039;s Gender &amp; Sexuality Studies&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Dan Palmer, Professor of Computer Science&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Evan Riley, Associate Professor of Philosophy&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Ibra Sene, Associate Professor of History&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Jennifer Hayward, Professor of English&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Katherine Holt, Associate Professor of History&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Mareike Herrmann, Professor of German Studies&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Marina Mangubi, Professor of Studio Art&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Miriam Kilimo, Assistant Professor of Africana Studies&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Nii Nikoi, Professor of Global Media and Digital Studies&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;li&gt;Sofia Visa, Professor of Computer Science&lt;/li&gt;&#10;&lt;/ul&gt;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Within a panel or roundtable session, we would like to contribute on the larger conversation about “Digital and computational approaches to humanistic research and pedagogy”. We will be sharing ideas about designing an interdisciplinary minor titled Minor in AI Computing for Arts and Humanities.&#10;This minor adds a computational component to students interested in applying modern computing tools to solve tasks across Arts and Humanities. The minor provides two main benefits – gives students knowledge of and experience with cutting edge technology in their respective fields and provides additional opportunities to explore the intersection of Humanities, Social Sciences, and Arts and technology.&#10;The students will learn to use generative AI ethically and effectively for building computational solutions for solving problems in arts and humanities. Within this minor, students will:&#10;1.            apply a basic programming language such as Python for text and image processing.&#10;2.            use computing tools for organizing data (concepts form database or web design or statistics).&#10;3.            apply generative AI tool for addressing research questions in their own field (accomplished via a project-based course).&#10;4.            apply computing tools for data visualization.&#10;5.            understand ethical problems in computing and AI.&#10;Keywords: computing for arts and humanities; generative AI; design of an interdisciplinary minor&#10;Participants from the College of Wooster: &#10;Ahmet Atay, Professor of Global Media and Digital Studies&#10;Caitlyn Deeter, Educational Technologist&#10;Christa Craven, Professor of Anthropology and Women&#039;s Gender &amp; Sexuality Studies&#10;Dan Palmer, Professor of Computer Science&#10;Evan Riley, Associate Professor of Philosophy&#10;Ibra Sene, Associate Professor of History&#10;Jennifer Hayward, Professor of English&#10;Katherine Holt, Associate Professor of History&#10;Mareike Herrmann, Professor of German Studies&#10;Marina Mangubi, Professor of Studio Art&#10;Miriam Kilimo, Assistant Professor of Africana Studies&#10;Nii Nikoi, Professor of Global Media and Digital Studies&#10;Sofia Visa, Professor of Computer Science</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
