    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Open Culture for Ancient Heritage: Collections, Digitization and Licensing Towards a More Accessible Future</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ancient heritage, cultural heritage, open licenses, digitization, accessibility</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;BCE-4th Century&#10;5th-14th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;copyright, licensing, and permissions standards, systems, and processes&#10;digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;Archaeology&#10;Art history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Galleries and Museum studies&#10;History&#10;Law and legal studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">BCE-4th Century&#10;5th-14th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">copyright, licensing, and permissions standards, systems, and processes&#10;digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Archaeology&#10;Art history&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Galleries and Museum studies&#10;History&#10;Law and legal studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Of all movements experiencing an «open» wave – among them scientific publishing and education –, culture promises to be one with great impact, with Creative Commons advocating for a UNESCO «Recommendation» on Open Culture. This viewpoint tends to focus on institutional holdings (see Wallace/McCarthy’s «Open GLAM Survey» since 2018) rather than on accessibility to object types across institutions worldwide.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Papyri, like most ancient heritage objects, have a storied history of movement. Whether illicitly trafficked today or obtained and exported from their country of origin in a colonial environment a century ago, antiquities remain among the most difficult to trace «commodities» on the art market. With ancient heritage collections often forming a part of larger institutionalized entities, such as museums, libraries, galleries and private collections, they are dependent on decisions made for the larger entity.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This is especially true regarding open licenses for digitized artefacts, usually subject to an institution’s overall policy on the topic, as well as its understanding and proper implementation of these legal tools. A comparative dataset of institutions housing papyri in 39+ countries can therefore be categorized into stages of digitization, stages of openness, and stages of &lt;em&gt;conveying&lt;/em&gt; openness (or a lack thereof).&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This paper addresses the issue of licensing digitizations of artworks out of copyright (see the UK’s recent THJ v Sheridan 2023), the various avenues chosen by custodians of ancient heritage items when it comes to online accessibility of its digitizations, and a selection of «gold standard» cases that might serve as a blueprint for others.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Of all movements experiencing an «open» wave – among them scientific publishing and education –, culture promises to be one with great impact, with Creative Commons advocating for a UNESCO «Recommendation» on Open Culture. This viewpoint tends to focus on institutional holdings (see Wallace/McCarthy’s «Open GLAM Survey» since 2018) rather than on accessibility to object types across institutions worldwide.&#10;Papyri, like most ancient heritage objects, have a storied history of movement. Whether illicitly trafficked today or obtained and exported from their country of origin in a colonial environment a century ago, antiquities remain among the most difficult to trace «commodities» on the art market. With ancient heritage collections often forming a part of larger institutionalized entities, such as museums, libraries, galleries and private collections, they are dependent on decisions made for the larger entity.&#10;This is especially true regarding open licenses for digitized artefacts, usually subject to an institution’s overall policy on the topic, as well as its understanding and proper implementation of these legal tools. A comparative dataset of institutions housing papyri in 39+ countries can therefore be categorized into stages of digitization, stages of openness, and stages of conveying openness (or a lack thereof).&#10;This paper addresses the issue of licensing digitizations of artworks out of copyright (see the UK’s recent THJ v Sheridan 2023), the various avenues chosen by custodians of ancient heritage items when it comes to online accessibility of its digitizations, and a selection of «gold standard» cases that might serve as a blueprint for others.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Landau, Victoria Gioia Désirée</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Basel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Switzerland</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Western_Europe</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">victoria.landau@unibas.ch</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">victoria.landau@unibas.ch</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Landau, Victoria Gioia Désirée</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">victoria.landau@unibas.ch</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">CET (UTC+1)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">71.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">40.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">279</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1290</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gearhart, Julia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presenter will share how various institutions across the globe make their papyri collections discoverable and accessible online. A background on sharing digital heritage objects, customs and recent law will be presented. The methods of institutional access will be shared as well as those the presenter believes should serve as standards for others. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I&#039;m really excited about this paper. Papyri can sometimes exist in this grey area between text and object that can be a) difficult to classify within an institution and b) hard to display online. I&#039;m thinking of archaeological squeezes as being similar. So this is indeed a challenging area of librarians, archivists, technologists and scholars. And this presentation is a good opportunity to talk about these challenges, what is working and what isn&#039;t. It sounds as though it may include some visualizations of the data, which would be a great benefit in seeing the landscape of the issue in a simplified way. I&#039;m very glad to see the global perspective, and I hope the presenter will consider also the resources (and lack of resources) for this work at some of the institutions discussed. Can the &quot;blueprint&quot; cases be mirrored with little funding or staff? </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1182</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Boehlert, Krystal</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">An overview of digitization and licensing issues, specifically with ancient artifacts in institutional collections.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">One of the core strengths of this paper will be in the analysis of the dataset on digitization and licensing. Considerations of how broad institutional policies affect item level openness is an important and valuable contribution. I also appreciate sharing a &quot;golden standard&quot; for institutions to work towards. &#10;&#10;I would like to see more indication of what makes papyri different than other collection items, i.e. the age or provenance as factors in copyright status, for those who are less familiar with copyright and licensing. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1095</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bozia, Eleni</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The contribution proposes to present the pipeline that museums and other institutions follow for the digitization and accessibility of papyri and other historical artifacts, attempting to come up with some fundamental legal and ethical steps to be followed by everyone. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The abstract is not very coherently written. The topic is very promising, but it is very hard to follow its overall presentation.&#10;&#10;The abstract lacks structure and clarity. It is never clarified how the author has knowledge of the inner workings of these collections and the institutions&#039; decisions. &#10;&#10;The author should have also provided some more information about the case studies and the points that they intend to make, and whether the presentation will focus on papyri or other artifacts as well. There seems to be a back-and-forth. &#10;&#10;Overall, the author has not managed to present their argument/points clearly.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As far as I can tell, the topic should be of interest as it deals with potential behind-the-scenes digitization decisions and potential downsides. &#10;&#10;My main concern is with the author&#039;s inability to express themselves clearly. So, I am not sure whether what I understood about the contribution is indeed accurate. &#10;&#10; </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">40</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
