    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">LLMs for Translation? Historical Texts and Contemporary Ideas of AI Safety</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence, machine translation, ottoman turkish, AI safety, digital history</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Asia&#10;Europe&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;15th-17th Century&#10;18th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;natural language processing&#10;semantic analysis&#10;Anthropology&#10;Computer science&#10;History&#10;Translation studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia&#10;Europe&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">15th-17th Century&#10;18th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;natural language processing&#10;semantic analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Anthropology&#10;Computer science&#10;History&#10;Translation studies&#10;Data science/data studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Large Language Models (LLMs) can be prompted to perform tasks for which they have not been explicitly trained, including machine translation (MT). MT is a sequence-to-sequence task that typically requires parallel data in form of sentence pairs from source and target languages in training. General-purpose LLMs, on the other hand, are autoregressive models, not specifically trained for translation. Yet, models like OpenAI&#039;s GPT-4 or Google&#039;s Gemini are commonly tested on translation benchmarks and deployed for real-life translation use cases due to their high performance and adaptability. This paper explores Gemini&#039;s performance on translating an 18th century Ottoman Turkish manuscript, Prisoner of the Infidels: The Memoirs of Osman Agha of Timişoara into English. This manuscript recounts the experiences of an Ottoman subject, Osman Agha, who spent 11 years as a prisoner of war in Austria. His account contains depictions of warfare and violence, which trigger the safety settings of Gemini, leading the model to flag some passages as harmful and not translate them. These safety settings consist of four categories of harm: hate speech, dangerous content, harassment and sexually explicit content. In our initial tests between 14% to 21% of Osman Agha&#039;s memoirs were not translated due to the flagging of one or more of these four categories. Gemini’s hard-coded refusal to translate these materials is not merely an issue for historians. Warfare is not an historical artefact. There are ongoing conflicts today in which contemporary people become victims of violence, just like Osman. By investigating how his account is treated by Gemini, we can shed light on how implementations for AI safety silence certain accounts despite the model’s relatively high translation accuracy. In the age of AI, machine translation is no longer a technical problem but a social one.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Large Language Models (LLMs) can be prompted to perform tasks for which they have not been explicitly trained, including machine translation (MT). MT is a sequence-to-sequence task that typically requires parallel data in form of sentence pairs from source and target languages in training. General-purpose LLMs, on the other hand, are autoregressive models, not specifically trained for translation. Yet, models like OpenAI&#039;s GPT-4 or Google&#039;s Gemini are commonly tested on translation benchmarks and deployed for real-life translation use cases due to their high performance and adaptability. This paper explores Gemini&#039;s performance on translating an 18th century Ottoman Turkish manuscript, Prisoner of the Infidels: The Memoirs of Osman Agha of Timişoara into English. This manuscript recounts the experiences of an Ottoman subject, Osman Agha, who spent 11 years as a prisoner of war in Austria. His account contains depictions of warfare and violence, which trigger the safety settings of Gemini, leading the model to flag some passages as harmful and not translate them. These safety settings consist of four categories of harm: hate speech, dangerous content, harassment and sexually explicit content. In our initial tests between 14% to 21% of Osman Agha&#039;s memoirs were not translated due to the flagging of one or more of these four categories. Gemini’s hard-coded refusal to translate these materials is not merely an issue for historians. Warfare is not an historical artefact. There are ongoing conflicts today in which contemporary people become victims of violence, just like Osman. By investigating how his account is treated by Gemini, we can shed light on how implementations for AI safety silence certain accounts despite the model’s relatively high translation accuracy. In the age of AI, machine translation is no longer a technical problem but a social one.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
