    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mtekgurl@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mtekgurl@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tekgürler, Merve</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">mtekgurl@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pacific</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">71.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">36.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">280</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1237</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Baciu, Dan C.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&quot;LLMs for Translation? Historical Texts and Contemporary Ideas of AI Safety&quot; by Merve Tekgürler explores the intriguing intersection of machine translation (MT) and AI safety, focusing on the performance of large language models (LLMs) like Google&#039;s Gemini in translating historical texts. This paper offers a compelling examination of the limitations and challenges posed by AI safety protocols in the context of historical translation.&#10;&#10;Tekgürler&#039;s study centers on the translation of an 18th-century Ottoman Turkish manuscript, &quot;Prisoner of the Infidels: The Memoirs of Osman Agha of Timișoara.&quot; This manuscript presents a unique challenge due to its depictions of warfare and violence, which trigger Gemini&#039;s safety settings. The finding that 14% to 21% of the memoirs were not translated due to these safety flags highlights a significant issue: the balance between AI safety measures and the need for accurate and complete historical translations.&#10;&#10;The paper effectively underscores the point that machine translation is not merely a technical challenge but a social one. The refusal of the model to translate certain passages due to hard-coded safety settings raises important questions about the accessibility of historical narratives and the potential silencing of important accounts. This is particularly relevant in contemporary contexts where similar issues of violence and conflict persist.&#10;&#10;One of the paper&#039;s strengths is its interdisciplinary approach, incorporating insights from digital humanities, history, and computer science. This broad perspective enriches the analysis and situates the technical challenges within a broader socio-cultural framework. However, the paper could benefit from a more detailed discussion of potential solutions or alternatives to current AI safety protocols that could better balance the need for safety with the imperative to preserve historical accuracy.&#10;&#10;Additionally, while the focus on a specific historical text provides a clear and concrete example, expanding the study with concrete present-day examples might help make the point about present-day relevance.&#10;&#10;Overall, &quot;LLMs for Translation? Historical Texts and Contemporary Ideas of AI Safety&quot; is a thought-provoking paper that raises critical questions about the role of AI in historical translation and the implications of AI safety measures. It makes a significant contribution to the discourse on machine translation and AI ethics, and it will be of interest to scholars in digital humanities, history, and AI research.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Thank you for this excellent abstract! By circumstance, I was born near Timișoara. My team recently embarked on a small project testing censorsing in text-image models. Feel free to reach out if this interests you at books ad yahoo dot com. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1241</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ahrenberg, Lars</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper reports on a study of translating an18th century Ottoman Turkish manuscript, Prisoner of the Infidels: The Memoirs of Osman Agha of Timişoara into English by Google&#039;s Gemini system. The main finding is that large parts are not translated because of its content leading to the conclusion that &quot;In the age of AI, machine translation is no longer a technical problem but a social one.&quot;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The study reports results from one translation of one text of one system and draws a very general conclusion from this. The main observation is that the system does not translate large parts of the input text due to its violent or otherwise harmful content. In terms of percentages the numbers are high leaving the translation almost useless for the historian not familiar with the language of the origin. Still this is a rather superficial observation which could easily be remedied technichally giving support to the common observation that adapted LLM-based systems work better than generic ones for many tasks.&#10;&#10;I would encourage the author to compare Gemini with other systems and evaluate the results on more aspects than one, including such aspects as mistranslations and word omissions.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">36</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1083</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zou, Zhihui</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper studies how the mathematical logic behind machine learning and LLMs could affect historians&#039; workflow due to hard-coded settings created not due to technical reasons but social ones.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract sounds like it includes a lot of potential in inter-industry conversations because it inspired the conversation about who has the power to determine the settings of language models. I believe this is such an important topic for digital humanities projects because many humanists often apply tools without knowing how they were built.&#10;&#10;It would be helpful if the abstract could explain whether the paper&#039;s goal is to describe the issue of translation or propose a solution to an issue. Since I don&#039;t think the abstract clearly explains what actions are taken after discovering this issue in translation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
