    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Ethnic Studies&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;North America&#10;20th Century&#10;natural language processing&#10;text mining and analysis&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Literary studies&#10;Comparative and World Literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">natural language processing&#10;text mining and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Ethnic Studies&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Literary studies&#10;Comparative and World Literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Between 1968 and 1971, Pierre Vallières got all the good press he and the&lt;br /&gt;Quebec separatist movement wanted with &lt;em&gt;White N-words of America&lt;/em&gt;. In the&lt;br /&gt;decades since, critics called Vallières&#039; first book a “classic” and an “integral&lt;br /&gt;part of Quebec history.” By 2019 however, those who continued to utter the&lt;br /&gt;title in full in Canadian universities and on public radio and television started to&lt;br /&gt;face denunciation. Complaints led to putative cancellations, followed by&lt;br /&gt;investigations, new legislation regarding hateful anti-Black language on&lt;br /&gt;publicly funded media, and finally, arguments against censorship in the name&lt;br /&gt;of free speech.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;We used computational tools--including Principal Component Analysis, word shift graphs, topic modeling--to define &lt;em&gt;which&lt;/em&gt; language around Vallières’ book changed between the 1970s and 2020s, and &lt;em&gt;which&lt;/em&gt; stayed the same. Our initial findings allowed us to argue that by the 2020s, Vallières’ book had become untouchable, a litmus test for freedom of expression and willingness to stand up for and defend Quebec culture. We then used word embeddings to measure &lt;em&gt;how &lt;/em&gt;the language surrounding Vallières&#039; book changed between the 1970s and the 2020s. The output from word2vec and Paired Pointwise Mutual Information scores allowed us to count computationally associations between discrete words, and measure what changed the most in those associations over time, and build on our initial analysis. We established historical trends as well as outliers to these trends, and speculated as to &lt;em&gt;why&lt;/em&gt; some language changed and other language stayed the same.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Our findings shed light on Vallières&#039; letters, which we consulted in the archives, wherein he insisted repeatedly to his publisher that his book should be titled nothing other than &lt;em&gt;White N-Words of America. &lt;/em&gt;Thus, we ultimately argue that Vallières would have to wait five decades for the press to register, report, and insist on, the violent power of his book&#039;s title.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Between 1968 and 1971, Pierre Vallières got all the good press he and the&#10;Quebec separatist movement wanted with White N-words of America. In the&#10;decades since, critics called Vallières&#039; first book a “classic” and an “integral&#10;part of Quebec history.” By 2019 however, those who continued to utter the&#10;title in full in Canadian universities and on public radio and television started to&#10;face denunciation. Complaints led to putative cancellations, followed by&#10;investigations, new legislation regarding hateful anti-Black language on&#10;publicly funded media, and finally, arguments against censorship in the name&#10;of free speech.&#10;We used computational tools--including Principal Component Analysis, word shift graphs, topic modeling--to define which language around Vallières’ book changed between the 1970s and 2020s, and which stayed the same. Our initial findings allowed us to argue that by the 2020s, Vallières’ book had become untouchable, a litmus test for freedom of expression and willingness to stand up for and defend Quebec culture. We then used word embeddings to measure how the language surrounding Vallières&#039; book changed between the 1970s and the 2020s. The output from word2vec and Paired Pointwise Mutual Information scores allowed us to count computationally associations between discrete words, and measure what changed the most in those associations over time, and build on our initial analysis. We established historical trends as well as outliers to these trends, and speculated as to why some language changed and other language stayed the same.&#10;Our findings shed light on Vallières&#039; letters, which we consulted in the archives, wherein he insisted repeatedly to his publisher that his book should be titled nothing other than White N-Words of America. Thus, we ultimately argue that Vallières would have to wait five decades for the press to register, report, and insist on, the violent power of his book&#039;s title.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brault, Chloé</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Stanford University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cbmack@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cbmack@stanford.edu, clarehx@stanford.edu, qad@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Brault, Chloé</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cbmack@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">PST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">90.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">94.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">281</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1083</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Zou, Zhihui</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project uses word embedding and other statistical methods to quantitatively measure how the press and public changed their perception toward Pierre Vallières&#039;s book in the past decades.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project excels at presenting its methodology and historical background as well as combining technological methods with social science inquiries. I am very intrigued to see the project&#039;s findings. This is a well-delivered proposal for a computational humanities project.&#10;&#10;If the proposal could mention what are the trends the project examines, it would be much appreciated. For example, the trend of what type of journalists/public voices support Vallières&#039;s choice of title? The trend of audience? Etc.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1228</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wilkens, Matthew</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Strong work on an important topic using a range of methods. I&#039;d love to see more details of the results in the proposals (in place of what currently reads as speculation re: &quot;trends&quot; and &quot;outliers&quot;), and it seems to me that the methods might better use contextual embeddings in place of static ones, since the project is all about temporal shifts in contextual meaning. Overall, tough, a good proposal and one I look forward to seeing at the conference.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Strong accept from a group with a good track record.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1032</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Woo, Jewon</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a fascinating paper, first because it uses computational methods to analyze the historical text to reveal any possible changes that reveal a shift in people&#039;s perception of Vallières&#039;s work as well; second because it responds to Ian Milligan&#039;s call for the transformation of historical research in the digital age; and, at last because it introduces digital methods and their applications (word2vec and PMI) that allow us to detect textual changes in a historical document. While this proposal suggests a promising discovery of the value of computational approaches to a historical document, the authors can offer further considerations, limitations, and challenges they have found. In addition, as the historical and cultural implications of the N-word is very complicated and require our sensitivity, the paper can explain aspect of cultural (mis)appropriation and politics of naming with the example of Vallières&#039;s book.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">94</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
