    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kleinberg, Wintermute, and Des Maladies Mentales: Hallucinating Language Models from Psychology to Cyberpunk to Knowledge Graphs</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">language models, psychology, cyberpunk, hallucination, graph theoy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Software Studies&#10;Global&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;network analysis and graphs theory and application&#10;rhetorical analysis&#10;Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Literary studies&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;network analysis and graphs theory and application&#10;rhetorical analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Software Studies&#10;Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Literary studies&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;While experiments in generative text have led to widespread use of models to produce creative and authoritative&lt;strong&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;texts, with some fields showing up to 17% of papers written with a model (Liang 2024), the outputs are viewed with suspicion. Furthermore, citing the principles of “originality,” and “accountability,” &lt;em&gt;Science&lt;/em&gt; argued that AI is not an author, and so banned generative AI from all submissions (Thorp 2023). Most often, this suspicion is characterized as the model engaging in “hallucinations,” or “confabulations.”&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Our paper performs three interventions. First, we examine the adoption and lineage of these core terms from clinical psychology, narratology, and 1980s cyberpunk genre fiction. From this examination, we find that people have an intuition about a structural defect in language models’ representations of meaning.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Second, we propose this defect may originate from models exhibiting substructural similarity among disparate areas of their data. This similarity may be apparent when the data is modeled as a graph of the word embedding space. To test this proposition, we are producing a graph of the embedding space and measuring the substructural similarity of regions at various granularity using a Kleinberg model.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Third, the notion of confabulating models suggest a divergence between the output and some idealized accurate response. That divergence can be formalized using possible worlds theory. Marie Laure-Ryan’s articulation proposed a textual reference world, which is the proposed reality underlying a text. The divergence between the reference world of the model output, the source documents, and the reader speak to the degree of fictionality.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Techniques such as retrieval augmented generation and drama managers might inhibit fictionality. However, confabulation’s possibility as an accurate reading of structurally-similar language suggest its intractability for embedding-based architectures. Clinical guidance for mnemonic behaviors associated with confabulation and hallucination could inform further bracketing (and creative amplification) of models’ confabulatory behaviors.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While experiments in generative text have led to widespread use of models to produce creative and authoritative texts, with some fields showing up to 17% of papers written with a model (Liang 2024), the outputs are viewed with suspicion. Furthermore, citing the principles of “originality,” and “accountability,” Science argued that AI is not an author, and so banned generative AI from all submissions (Thorp 2023). Most often, this suspicion is characterized as the model engaging in “hallucinations,” or “confabulations.”&#10;Our paper performs three interventions. First, we examine the adoption and lineage of these core terms from clinical psychology, narratology, and 1980s cyberpunk genre fiction. From this examination, we find that people have an intuition about a structural defect in language models’ representations of meaning.&#10;Second, we propose this defect may originate from models exhibiting substructural similarity among disparate areas of their data. This similarity may be apparent when the data is modeled as a graph of the word embedding space. To test this proposition, we are producing a graph of the embedding space and measuring the substructural similarity of regions at various granularity using a Kleinberg model.&#10;Third, the notion of confabulating models suggest a divergence between the output and some idealized accurate response. That divergence can be formalized using possible worlds theory. Marie Laure-Ryan’s articulation proposed a textual reference world, which is the proposed reality underlying a text. The divergence between the reference world of the model output, the source documents, and the reader speak to the degree of fictionality.&#10;Techniques such as retrieval augmented generation and drama managers might inhibit fictionality. However, confabulation’s possibility as an accurate reading of structurally-similar language suggest its intractability for embedding-based architectures. Clinical guidance for mnemonic behaviors associated with confabulation and hallucination could inform further bracketing (and creative amplification) of models’ confabulatory behaviors.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Miller, Ben</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Emory University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bjmiller@mit.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bjmiller@mit.edu, roy.chang@emory.edu, joshua.winston@emory.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Miller, Ben</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bjmiller@mit.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">EDT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">67.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">74.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">54.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">283</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1126</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ElKattan, Alia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors explain how the development of LLMs can in fact be categorized as a process of creating new fictionalities, and how our mental models inhibit our ability to understand that.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Really interesting work, but not entirely clear how the framing at the beginning sets up for the paper&#039;s results. The authors speak about meeting LLM outputs with suspicion, citing lack of originality and authorship, but then speak about degrees of fictionality, which it isn&#039;t clear speak to the same issue. The relationship between that argument and that of hallucinations isn&#039;t totally clear. Finally, the relationship to the conference themes isn&#039;t explicitly laid out, though the work is really interesting in general!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">54</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1240</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wevers, Melvin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The main contribution of this submission is a multidisciplinary analysis of AI &quot;hallucinations&quot; and &quot;confabulations&quot; in generative text models, combining historical, linguistic, and technical approaches to propose new frameworks for understanding and potentially addressing these phenomena.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract presents a novel and multifaceted examination of the phenomenon of AI &quot;hallucinations&quot; or &quot;confabulations&quot; in generative text models. The submission&#039;s main contribution lies in its interdisciplinary approach, combining insights from clinical psychology, narratology, cyberpunk fiction, and computer science to analyze a pressing issue in AI-generated content. It offers significant value by proposing new methodologies for understanding and potentially addressing the limitations of current language models. The interdisciplinary nature of the approach, combining humanities perspectives with technical analysis, makes this submission particularly fitting. The main area where it could potentially improve is in more explicitly addressing the sociopolitical implications of AI-generated content, which would further align it with the conference&#039;s focus on critical and inclusive approaches.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1120</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kurzynski, Maciej</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project investigates the use of terms like &quot;hallucinations&quot; and &quot;confabulations&quot; in describing generative AI outputs, tracing their origins in clinical psychology, narratology, and cyberpunk fiction. It aims to understand the structural defects in language models&#039; representations of meaning and suggests that retrieval-augmented generation and clinical insights could mitigate such issues.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a fascinating project merging insights from clinical psychology, narratology, generative AI, and cyberpunk fiction in order to explore the questions of &quot;hallucination&quot; and &quot;confabulation&quot; in large language models. As language models become increasingly present in our daily lives, this constitutes a very timely proposal and will be a very valuable contribution to the conference.&#10;&#10;The abstract is well structured, elaborating the authors&#039; three theoretical interventions. It is also well contextualized with the Science example.&#10;&#10;That said, the three interventions could have been described much more clearly. For example, the authors say that &quot;people have an intuition about a structural defect in language models’ representations of meaning.&quot; Who are those &quot;people&quot;? Are they cyberpunk fiction authors? Psychologists? The Editors of Science? People in general?&#10;&#10;This question is important because in the following passage the authors suggest that &quot;this defect may originate from models exhibiting substructural similarity among disparate areas of their data.&quot; So is the said defect still someone&#039;s &quot;intuition&quot; or a real issue arising from a particular model architecture? It is not made clear in the abstract. Even less clear is the sentence &quot;confabulation’s possibility as an accurate reading of structurally-similar language suggest its intractability for embedding-based architectures.&quot; Is there a language that is NOT structurally similar? There is a lot of research on the fractality / recursive nature of languages and grammars.&#10;&#10;The use of Ryan&#039;s principle of minimal departure in explaining &quot;confabulation&quot; is very innovative and well taken. It is important to note, however, that according to more recent theories of fictionality (e.g., Richard Walsh&#039;s), fictionality is in the eye of the beholder, not in the text.&#10;&#10;Overall, this is a very intriguing proposal which could be made much stronger if the authors provided clearer descriptions of the three interventions. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">74</ss:Data></Cell>
