    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Digital Approaches to the Literature of Flamenco: Building a Letra Database</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">flamenco, database, lyrics, Romani studies, Spanish literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Spanish&#10;Europe&#10;Global&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Literary studies&#10;Musicology&#10;Performance studies: Dance &amp; Theatre&#10;Hispanic Studies&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Spanish</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital archiving&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cultural studies&#10;Literary studies&#10;Musicology&#10;Performance studies: Dance &amp; Theatre&#10;Hispanic Studies&#10;Multilingualism and translanguaging</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This lightning talk is a presentation of a digital flamenco &lt;em&gt;letra &lt;/em&gt;(lyric) database, which is currently under construction. Using PocketBase, my collaborators and I are digitizing the &lt;em&gt;letras &lt;/em&gt;popularized by artists as diverse as Pastora Imperio, Manuel Torres, Rosalía de Triana, and Antonio de la Malena. The database is an effort to preserve and make widely accessible the cultural heritage of flamenco. Shaped in large part by Spanish Romani artists, flamenco emerged as a multimodal art form in southern Spain in the nineteenth century. Flamenco &lt;em&gt;letras&lt;/em&gt;, or lyrics, are transmitted orally from singer to singer, and despite constituting a vast literary corpus, have rarely been studied as literary texts and have never been systematically collected, organized, and historicized. Supported by the nonprofit organization and dance company Flamenco Arts International, my collaborators and I aim to intervene in Spanish literary studies, flamenco studies, and critical Romani studies and to assist flamenco practitioners by constructing a database that is searchable by singer, theme, historical references, subgenre, rhyme scheme, versification, strophic structure, and more. It also includes English translations of &lt;em&gt;letras &lt;/em&gt;in Spanish and Caló, a language spoken by the Spanish Roma, and is designed to be useful to flamenco teachers and artists as well as academics. This project contributes to and complements the growing body of scholarship that employs digital methods for flamenco research, including the network analysis of Sara Arribas Colmenar, the digital mapping of Blanca Gómez Cifuentes, and the computational musical analysis of Lénica Reyes and José Miguel Hernández Jaramillo.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk is a presentation of a digital flamenco letra (lyric) database, which is currently under construction. Using PocketBase, my collaborators and I are digitizing the letras popularized by artists as diverse as Pastora Imperio, Manuel Torres, Rosalía de Triana, and Antonio de la Malena. The database is an effort to preserve and make widely accessible the cultural heritage of flamenco. Shaped in large part by Spanish Romani artists, flamenco emerged as a multimodal art form in southern Spain in the nineteenth century. Flamenco letras, or lyrics, are transmitted orally from singer to singer, and despite constituting a vast literary corpus, have rarely been studied as literary texts and have never been systematically collected, organized, and historicized. Supported by the nonprofit organization and dance company Flamenco Arts International, my collaborators and I aim to intervene in Spanish literary studies, flamenco studies, and critical Romani studies and to assist flamenco practitioners by constructing a database that is searchable by singer, theme, historical references, subgenre, rhyme scheme, versification, strophic structure, and more. It also includes English translations of letras in Spanish and Caló, a language spoken by the Spanish Roma, and is designed to be useful to flamenco teachers and artists as well as academics. This project contributes to and complements the growing body of scholarship that employs digital methods for flamenco research, including the network analysis of Sara Arribas Colmenar, the digital mapping of Blanca Gómez Cifuentes, and the computational musical analysis of Lénica Reyes and José Miguel Hernández Jaramillo.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
