    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">taniaf@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">taniaf@stanford.edu, mogaburo@gmail.com, amcornejosilva@gmail.com, isabel@flamencoartsinternational.org</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Flores, Tania Arabelle</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">taniaf@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Pacific Standard Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">95.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">90.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">284</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1003</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fernandez, Sylvia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission addresses the process of creating a digital flamenco letra (lyric) database as a collaborative work of digitizing the letras popularized by artists such as Pastora Imperio, Manuel Torres, Rosalía de Triana, and Antonio de la Malena. This work is an effort to preserve and make widely accessible the cultural heritage of flamenco mainly by Spanish Romani artists from southern Spain in the nineteenth century. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The presentation of this database documenting and making accesible data of the artists that form part of the cultural heritage of flamenco. It will be important to discuss what protocols the team is having to decide who is included in this databases and the process of identifying the artists, what sources are being consulted and disseminated. Very looking forward to hearing the team present this in-progress project. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1130</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Murphy, Emily Christina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Creation of a flamenco letra database in Spanish and Caló. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I’m thrilled to see this worthy project, as there is so little digital research on flamenco or Romani artforms. The database will be an excellent resource for scholars and practitioners. &#10;&#10;It’s worth noting that, even though there is limited research on flamenco letras, that the majority of scholarly work on flamenco is ethnomusicological (rather than, say, on dance or multimodal and improvised performance cultures). So, while the authors are correct that flamenco letras “have rarely been studied as literary texts and have never been systematically collected, organized, and historicized,” it’s worth tempering these claims as letras are the most available for digitization. &#10;&#10;I would like to see this project consider the role of digital preservation in oral traditions like flamenco. Since learning letras (and falsetas and choreography…) still operates as an interpersonal, relational oral tradition. What would be the effect of a digital database on this aspect of flamenco culture? I would incorporate theories like Diana Taylor’s The Archive and The Repertoire and Rebecca Schneider’s Performing Remains. The SpokenWeb project (https://spokenweb.ca/), which considers literary audio, also thinks through similar questions of orality and digitization. &#10;&#10;Since this contribution is a lightening talk, the authors may not have time to incorporate all of these comments. However, they should inform some of the framing and I hope that they’ll be integrated in future work. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors have submitted this work as a lightning talk, which is why I have recommended it in that format. I can imagine a version that would suit a longer individual presentation. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1125</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Isasi, Jennifer</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk will present the goals, reasoning and construction state of a highly innovative and needed database of flamenco lyrics. The presenter will speak about the content and data curation process, its significance in the context of Flamenco and Romani studies and, significantly, put their work in conversation with other projects that employ different DH methods (network analysis, mapping, and computational musical analysis) to also study and preserve the cultural heritage of flamenco. &#10;&#10;The abstract is clearly written and shows the purpose, relevance and connection to the conference strongly.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I look forward to seeing this presentation on your database of flamenco letra. The submission makes a strong case for the need of this database, the contributions of it to the fields of Flamenco, Roma and Spanish literary studies, and multilingual DH with the database containing translations of all lyrics. Congratulations!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author, a student, submitted this as a Lightning Talk but I truly believe this would make for a good paper presentation. Is there any way to suggest that to her?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
