    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Un-touring SF Chinatown: A VR Demo course</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chinatown, VR, Digital Pedagogy, Asian American history</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Asia&#10;North America&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;virtual and augmented reality creation, systems, and analysis&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;History&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia&#10;North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digitization (2D and 3D)&#10;virtual and augmented reality creation, systems, and analysis&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;History&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Teaching a historical space in a college class is challenging. Physical tours or visual aids might help students orient themselves in the space; however, there are limitations to these methods. VR technology, on the other hand, can be a game changer in the classroom. The VR demo course, “Un-touring SF Chinatown” (work in progress), aims to create a virtual reality learning experience of the historical San Francisco Chinatown spanning from the late 19th century to the mid 20th century. Using historical photographs and maps, it reconstructs the urban ethnic enclave in 3D design software and creates an immersive learning environment for Asian American history. Given the historical racial othering and marginalization of Asian American communities, Chinatown had been perceived as a space of Orientalist interests; mainstream society learns about this space mainly through tourism and sensationalized and stereotypical media representations without understanding it in the historical contexts. “Un-touring SF Chinatown”, however, invites students to learn and reflect on the history of SF Chinatown without the tourist lenses. In the virtual space, students will walk down Grant Avenue and stop by grocery stores, pharmacies, restaurants, and parading crowds, following the steps of the community members. Each venue hosts a learning activity that connects the venue with an important point in Chinese American history, such as the Chinese Exclusion Act, the paper son history, and the US-China alliance during the second world war. &quot;Un-touring SF Chinatown&quot; challenges the limitations in the traditional classroom and offers an innovative approach to teaching Asian American history through digital pedagogy and VR technology.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Teaching a historical space in a college class is challenging. Physical tours or visual aids might help students orient themselves in the space; however, there are limitations to these methods. VR technology, on the other hand, can be a game changer in the classroom. The VR demo course, “Un-touring SF Chinatown” (work in progress), aims to create a virtual reality learning experience of the historical San Francisco Chinatown spanning from the late 19th century to the mid 20th century. Using historical photographs and maps, it reconstructs the urban ethnic enclave in 3D design software and creates an immersive learning environment for Asian American history. Given the historical racial othering and marginalization of Asian American communities, Chinatown had been perceived as a space of Orientalist interests; mainstream society learns about this space mainly through tourism and sensationalized and stereotypical media representations without understanding it in the historical contexts. “Un-touring SF Chinatown”, however, invites students to learn and reflect on the history of SF Chinatown without the tourist lenses. In the virtual space, students will walk down Grant Avenue and stop by grocery stores, pharmacies, restaurants, and parading crowds, following the steps of the community members. Each venue hosts a learning activity that connects the venue with an important point in Chinese American history, such as the Chinese Exclusion Act, the paper son history, and the US-China alliance during the second world war. &quot;Un-touring SF Chinatown&quot; challenges the limitations in the traditional classroom and offers an innovative approach to teaching Asian American history through digital pedagogy and VR technology.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
