    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">285</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1229</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Adal, Raja</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project proposes to use VR technology to create a historical 3D tour of San Francisco Chinatown, but one that seeks to differentiate between touring as a tourist and as a resident.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I really like the idea of creating a historical 3-D tour.  The historical aspect is key.  So is the idea of positioning the viewer as an inhabitant not as a tourist.  A really great project.  You may want to draw on the relevant literature about the positionality of the subject as a resident or a tourist, or you may already have drawn on it but decided not to cite it in the abstract.  I see this project as having a lot of theoretical potential.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">96</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1259</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Li, Yunxin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project offers an innovative approach to Asian American history through digital pedagogy and VR technology. It makes a great contribution to history pedagogy and decolonization. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project offers an innovative approach to Asian American history through digital pedagogy and VR technology. It makes a great contribution to history pedagogy and decolonization. I very much look forward to it. I hope that it will be published online so that it is accessible to a wider audience beyond the author&#039;s classroom.&#10;&#10;While I am excited about the decolonizing potential of this VR project, I still think it is a challenge to get students out of the tourist mentality. I believe it is essential for students to read scholarship on Asian American History and the SF Chinatown in advance, and to help students to imagine themselves not as pure observers but as residents living in Chinatown at the time.&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1248</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Knox, John Thomas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper discusses an immersive VR project that offers students an opportunity to learn about the history of SF Chinatown and American/China history more broadly.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this is a very strong proposal and a very exciting project. I think this project will be of interest to many ACH participants. If possible, I think it would be great to learn more about how such VR projects have impacted student outcomes in other cases where a VR project has been completed. I&#039;d also be interested to learn more generally about other such VR projects, and how these projects have impacted students and other audiences.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
