    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Semantic-Rich Clustering of Scientific Publications Using Deep Learning and Network Analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bibliometrics, network analysis, machine learning, science of science, science map</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;bibliographic analysis&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;bibliographic analysis&#10;digital humanities and/in libraries</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The clustering of scientific publications is a pivotal technique in bibliometric analysis. These methods allow the identification of research trends, thematic structures, and scholarly communication patterns within a specific domain. The present work introduces a novel clustering methodology by constructing a network that connects publications (nodes) based on how likely they share linguistic and semantic information in content-description attributes such as title, abstract, keywords, and research areas. As a second step, the study compares the performance of multiple community detection algorithms to measure and characterize the formation of clusters in a network with such a structure. This analysis provides researchers with a four-step methodology (data collection, data filtering by inclusion and exclusion criteria, network modelling, and cluster content analysis) to group and detect clusters from bibliometric data.  Unlike traditional science mapping methods that focus on single bibliometric attributes—such as co-authorship, co-citations, citations, and keyword co-occurrence—this method integrates multiple content-based descriptors (research areas, keywords, titles, and abstracts). The similarity score introduced hereby provides more semantic richness to the analysis expanding the chances, with the assistance of state-of-art deep learning technology, to more accurately recognize the relationships between articles. This methodology facilitates a deeper exploration of emerging topics within bibliometric data and their interactions, contributing to a better understanding of the urgent issues that need to be addressed in specific fields of study. &lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The clustering of scientific publications is a pivotal technique in bibliometric analysis. These methods allow the identification of research trends, thematic structures, and scholarly communication patterns within a specific domain. The present work introduces a novel clustering methodology by constructing a network that connects publications (nodes) based on how likely they share linguistic and semantic information in content-description attributes such as title, abstract, keywords, and research areas. As a second step, the study compares the performance of multiple community detection algorithms to measure and characterize the formation of clusters in a network with such a structure. This analysis provides researchers with a four-step methodology (data collection, data filtering by inclusion and exclusion criteria, network modelling, and cluster content analysis) to group and detect clusters from bibliometric data. Unlike traditional science mapping methods that focus on single bibliometric attributes—such as co-authorship, co-citations, citations, and keyword co-occurrence—this method integrates multiple content-based descriptors (research areas, keywords, titles, and abstracts). The similarity score introduced hereby provides more semantic richness to the analysis expanding the chances, with the assistance of state-of-art deep learning technology, to more accurately recognize the relationships between articles. This methodology facilitates a deeper exploration of emerging topics within bibliometric data and their interactions, contributing to a better understanding of the urgent issues that need to be addressed in specific fields of study.</ss:Data></Cell>
