    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">286</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1271</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Coble, Zach</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A scientometrics methodology using clustering to find semantic similarities among publications based on title, abstract, keywords, and subject.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal provides an important and timely contribution to our understanding of the scientific literature. The use of clustering and deep learning is an interesting and innovative approach.&#10;&#10;While the word count for proposals is admittedly too short to give a complete description of the project, there are some important gaps that make it difficult to fully grasp the proposed project. It seems that the primary contribution is the novel clustering methodology - that is, it is not to report out on the research results of a bibliometric analysis using this method. If so, then some specifics are needed about the novel clustering methodology. What clustering algorithm was used and how? Was there dimension reduction? How was the textual data vectorized? Which previous studies are most similar to your approach, and how is yours different?&#10;&#10;Also, if the main goal is to find similarity between publications, does an unsupervised learning approach in fact provide more nuance than the other bibliometric approaches mentioned (i.e. co-authorship, co-citations, citations, and keyword co-occurrence)? There is discussion in the literature of the pros/cons of using clustering to extract topics and measure similarity. For instance, the semantic approach described does analyze much more data than the other approaches mentioned, but this also increases noise. How do you ensure that the clusters form around topics rather than other latent patterns, such language usage (British vs American spelling), &quot;genres&quot; of abstracts (scientific studies, editorials), and so forth?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">52</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1258</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Maselli, Matteo</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&#10;The proposed study falls within a highly relevant field and has the significant merit of offering procedures capable of redefining long-established methodological approaches. What has been presented is therefore noteworthy, and it is hoped that the research will be further pursued.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">80</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1041</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Abbasov, Namig</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The primary contribution in this research is the introduction of a new clustering methodology for the analysis of bibliometric data. This methodology is based on linguistic and semantic information from the research papers. The author states that they explore multiple content-based descriptors such as research areas, keywords, titles and abstracts of research papers to get similarity score.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This suggested research provides a new clustering methodology for the analysis of bibliometric data. It relies on information about research areas, keywords, titles and abstracts to obtain similarity score. I would enjoy reading the full details of this methodology. One suggestion I would make is the possible use of word embeddings to explore similarities, basically, exploring them in a multidimensional space. Word embeddings, specifically, Glove and Word2Vec are excellent methods to obtain similarities based on distance in multidimensional space. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Based on the short abstract, I think the author develops an interesting clustering methodology for the analysis of the bibliometric data. I would like to see it on the conference program. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">18</ss:Data></Cell>
