    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Building Community and a Sustainable Connection Between the Digital Humanities Initiative and the Department of English and Comparative Literature at San Diego State University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Fellowship, Community, Literature, Writing, Tutoring</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces&#10;digital pedagogies&#10;Comparative and World Literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital humanities centers and physical/digital/hybrid spaces&#10;digital pedagogies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cultural studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Literacy, composition, and creative writing&#10;Comparative and World Literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This paper documents an ongoing project by a graduate student, with support and guidance from faculty, which aims to bolster the role of Digital Humanities within the Department of English and Comparative Literature at San Diego State University. This project was conceived when said graduate student participated in a seminar introducing them to Digital Humanities, while also serving as a writing tutor in the English department&#039;s long-established Writing Center. The project has reimagined and expanded the role of the MA Writing Tutor, to also serve as a hub for departmental resources, writing and digital scholarship tutoring. With more faculty teaching DH-related content and courses, but without a specific point of contact for Digital Humanities in the English department, MA Fellows in the former Writing Center, rebranded as The Center For Digital Scholarship, now support the development of a conversation across the department and the sharing of resources. Revamping the Writing Tutor into a 21&lt;sup&gt;st&lt;/sup&gt; Century Digital Scholarship Fellowship now offers graduate students experience tutoring while also learning through service about writing in the digital age and about digital writing. This fellowship is designed to become a desired research position and academic work-experience opportunity for English MA students at SDSU. Fellows are appointed for a year-long term during which they carry out the pre-established primary objectives, ultimately integrating the position within the department, serving as a bridge between the various initiatives in the department and also beyond it, with a particular focus in using Digital Humanities to bring people together.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper documents an ongoing project by a graduate student, with support and guidance from faculty, which aims to bolster the role of Digital Humanities within the Department of English and Comparative Literature at San Diego State University. This project was conceived when said graduate student participated in a seminar introducing them to Digital Humanities, while also serving as a writing tutor in the English department&#039;s long-established Writing Center. The project has reimagined and expanded the role of the MA Writing Tutor, to also serve as a hub for departmental resources, writing and digital scholarship tutoring. With more faculty teaching DH-related content and courses, but without a specific point of contact for Digital Humanities in the English department, MA Fellows in the former Writing Center, rebranded as The Center For Digital Scholarship, now support the development of a conversation across the department and the sharing of resources. Revamping the Writing Tutor into a 21st Century Digital Scholarship Fellowship now offers graduate students experience tutoring while also learning through service about writing in the digital age and about digital writing. This fellowship is designed to become a desired research position and academic work-experience opportunity for English MA students at SDSU. Fellows are appointed for a year-long term during which they carry out the pre-established primary objectives, ultimately integrating the position within the department, serving as a bridge between the various initiatives in the department and also beyond it, with a particular focus in using Digital Humanities to bring people together.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">King, Joey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">San Diego State University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jking3@sdsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jking7538@sdsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jking3@sdsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">King, Joey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">jking3@sdsu.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">PST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">65.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">50.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">287</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1190</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Michael, Krystyna</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project stands to contribute to the field of DH pedagogy by presenting a model for integrating existing traditional administrative structures to accommodate new modes of teaching and learning, and to provide novel avenues for professionalization for graduate students. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract describes a project that contributes to conversations about DH pedagogy, interdisciplinarity, administrative structures, and the place of digital scholarship in the humanities. This contribution will generate interesting and important conversations about how to support the development of digital skills and scholarship at the undergraduate and graduate level. King should address the question of labor distribution within this structure, and should be sure to explain how this project could be used as a model at other institution or scaled. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">88</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1303</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Roy, Samya Brata</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper outlines and critically comments on the author&#039;s experience of being a writing tutor within the English and Comparative Literature Department with close ties to Digital Scholarship and Digital Humanities. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author writes the abstract from experience and highlights an important aspect of being a writing tutor with close contact with the Digital Humanities scholarship and its role within the English Department. The connection with the theme of the conference should have been articulated with a little more clarity. Some relevant research like that of Matthew Kirschenbaum or Roopika Risam could have been referred to as well. As it is more of a work in progress rather than a finished project, I think the lightning talk format would suit it better. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">50</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1277</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karlin, Jojo</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission reflects a graduate student project, and development of a new position, to incorporate techniques from a Digital Humanities seminar in work as a writing tutor in the English department&#039;s writing center. &quot;Revamping the Writing Tutor into a 21st Century Digital Scholarship Fellowship&quot; seeks a space for skills training in digital scholarship within disciplinary writing instruction.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Incorporating teaching DH and digital skills in disciplinary settings is an admirable mission. Finding ways to compensate graduate students for this work is also important. This program sounds like it is taking strides in this direction. &#10;While the topic is not related to conference topics (anti-racist work, Indigenous studies, culture and critical ethnic studies, intersectional feminism, postcolonial and decolonial studies, queer studies, and/or multilingualism), it is broadly applicable to a DH audience. Given the limited space within the proposal, the author hasn&#039;t included descriptions of the pedagogy implemented in the program. It would strengthen the presentation if the author has a chance to describe how the program supports (and makes consistent) both writing instruction and DH instruction.&#10;I would be interested to hear more about the development of this position, and the faculty involvement. I appreciate the objective of articulating digital humanities methods as companions to composition and rhetoric. I would want to know more about how the author and department ensure that graduate students are not being overextended in their role as tutors. I would love to see the author address how specialized labor is compensated and assigned when expanding the role of writing tutors. In my anecdotal experience, composition instructors are already carrying a lot of the weight of teaching students how to organize and articulate their research without adding the extra expectation that they teach digital skills. I know many who could teach both skills, but I would want to know how the fellowship ensures fair compensation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">58</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
