    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Analysing Smart Cities through the Cultural Bottom Line</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Smart Cities, Triple Bottom Line, Quadruple Bottom Line, Culture, Community Health</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Critical Race Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Design studies&#10;Sociology&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital ecologies and digital communities, creation, management, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Critical Race Studies&#10;Communication studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Design studies&#10;Sociology&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Governments across Canada are implementing new technology-based solutions to address current economic, social, and environmental challenges. This paper utilizes a quadruple bottom line approach, extending the triple bottom line (economic, social, environmental) by adding the fourth cultural bottom line. Many of these technology-based projects implemented by governments in partnership with the private sector are described as Smart City projects. Smart city projects in this context refer to city government-supported projects involving substantial investments in Information and Communications Technology (ICT) infrastructure and ubiquitous computing projects for real-time monitoring, management and regulation (Kitchin, 2015). Smart city projects range from megaprojects involving the rebuilding of entire technology-enabled city blocks, such as the Sidewalk Labs project (Morgan and Webb, 2020), to smaller implementations of technology by city governments. Learning from both the successes and failures of Smart City projects is essential to improve ongoing and future projects (Sengupta and Sengupta, 2022). The literature on Smart City projects primarily focuses on the technological and economic benefits, and is less developed in terms of the social and environmental benefits and risks. This presentation describes a quadruple bottom line approach, which includes the cultural bottom line as an integral part of the analysis of smart cities. The cultural bottom line is examined as an indicator of community health. Community health impacts of Smart City projects include changes in social, environmental, and cultural determinants of health (Smale and Hilbrecht, 2016). The implications of this paper are a more comprehensive and holistic analysis of Smart City projects that identify a broader set of risks and benefits by including the cultural bottom line. All Smart City projects have explicit or implicit cultural bottom lines, and therefore understanding the impacts on culture can provide possibilities for increasing community health benefits and reducing risks.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Governments across Canada are implementing new technology-based solutions to address current economic, social, and environmental challenges. This paper utilizes a quadruple bottom line approach, extending the triple bottom line (economic, social, environmental) by adding the fourth cultural bottom line. Many of these technology-based projects implemented by governments in partnership with the private sector are described as Smart City projects. Smart city projects in this context refer to city government-supported projects involving substantial investments in Information and Communications Technology (ICT) infrastructure and ubiquitous computing projects for real-time monitoring, management and regulation (Kitchin, 2015). Smart city projects range from megaprojects involving the rebuilding of entire technology-enabled city blocks, such as the Sidewalk Labs project (Morgan and Webb, 2020), to smaller implementations of technology by city governments. Learning from both the successes and failures of Smart City projects is essential to improve ongoing and future projects (Sengupta and Sengupta, 2022). The literature on Smart City projects primarily focuses on the technological and economic benefits, and is less developed in terms of the social and environmental benefits and risks. This presentation describes a quadruple bottom line approach, which includes the cultural bottom line as an integral part of the analysis of smart cities. The cultural bottom line is examined as an indicator of community health. Community health impacts of Smart City projects include changes in social, environmental, and cultural determinants of health (Smale and Hilbrecht, 2016). The implications of this paper are a more comprehensive and holistic analysis of Smart City projects that identify a broader set of risks and benefits by including the cultural bottom line. All Smart City projects have explicit or implicit cultural bottom lines, and therefore understanding the impacts on culture can provide possibilities for increasing community health benefits and reducing risks.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sengupta, Ushnish</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Algoma University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ushnish.sengupta@algomau.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ushnish.sengupta@algomau.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Sengupta, Ushnish</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ushnish.sengupta@algomau.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern Standard Time</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">54.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">70.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">36.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">288</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1114</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">O&#039;Neil, Erica</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This presentation will present an assessment of Smart City projects in order to more holistically account for the cultural implications of these projects an their impact on community health.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The framing for this paper is well-articulated, but from the abstract I am having trouble envisioning the scope of the cultural bottom line discussion and whether it will be explicated in case studies or some other methodology. It would also be helpful to point to potential biases and downstream effects of monitoring communities in real time, particularly those who are already marginalized and subjected to so much automated inequality as digital privacy increasingly becomes a privilege to those who can afford it. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1285</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Palermo, Gregory</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission proposes an approach to evaluating smart city projects that, the authors argue, can better account for the &quot;risk and benefits&quot; of these projects by looking at &quot;cultural&quot; impacts beyond economic, social, and environmental factors.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While this proposal does a reasonably good job of synthesizing the research on smart city projects and their evaluation, I am unsure from this abstract how the paper would be relevant to the conference and digital humanities more broadly. This proposal seems most geared to contribute to conversations about how smart cities impact community health. A more successful proposal might attempt to connect these discipline-specific conversations to issues relevant to digital humanists’ conversations on topics about digital infrastructure, surveillance, and their cultural implications. In other words, is there something that DHers could take from this approach, using the case study of smart cities to say something broader about how we analyze and understand cultural impact? Or, conversely, is there some way that DH theories and methods frame or complicate this holistic approach that the author brings back to their own field? The proposal could also complement the strong definition it provides of smart cities by defining the disciplinary jargon it includes like “triple bottom line,” better conveying what adding an additional bottom line would mean and the value it would add to our understanding. As it stands, I am unsure what exactly this author means by “cultural” impacts and how they are distinct from things like social and environmental impacts. What does this broader set of risks and benefits look like? Overall, I’d like to see less emphasis on key words and more emphasis on the paper’s specifics. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">36</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1058</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Smith, Nancy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper looks at smart city projects in relation to the cultural aspects of a city, specifically in relation to community health. Smart city literature focuses primarily on the technological and economic benefits of these kinds of digital projects, but this author aims to highlight the cultural elements as an important factor in understanding the success or failure of technology-focused projects. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an interesting proposal as smart city literature tends to exclude cultural elements of projects, and is focused primarily on the technological and economic benefits. There is a lot of potential in this abstract in terms of highlighting lesser-understood elements of smart city projects in Canada. It is unclear how this paper is drawing from the humanities, and which kinds of theory underlie the work. In the abstract, there is no mention of what a cultural indicator would show beyond community health. This connection to community health could be stronger, and it would be interesting to know why that is the element the author is focusing on in relation to culture, as well as what specific aspects of community health are under consideration. &#10;&#10;The triple/quadruple bottom line is not a common approach in the humanities and tends to be used in business and economic perspectives, but it may not be readily understood by everyone at ACH, so this  framework should be explained in more detail. In the disciplines, the author has selected critical race studies and ethnic studies, but there is nothing in the abstract to indicate how these areas will be explored. This would be a great addition to the abstract to give more detail around what will be explored around race and ethnicity in relation to the smart city projects. Additonally, it sounds as if access and activism may be part of the paper, but it&#039;s not clear in the abstract how this will be approached and what the takeaways are for that element of the research. &#10;&#10;Overall, the project needs more detail around the methodologies and contribution, as well as a deeper engagement with humanities and related scholarship. &#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think there is potential in this submission, but the abstract was a bit vague, so it was difficult to know exactly what the content of the paper would be. It doesn&#039;t feel like it&#039;s coming from a humanities perspective, but it&#039;s possible the author just hasn&#039;t highlighted enough to show that connection. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">58</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">-1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rejected</ss:Data></Cell>
