    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Working with undergraduates to identifying social hierarchies in Medieval London</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Linked Open Data, Archives, Medieval History, Digital Humanities Pedagogy</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;5th-14th Century&#10;data modeling&#10;linked (open) data&#10;History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">5th-14th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">data modeling&#10;linked (open) data</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">History</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Cities are entities made of people and of buildings. Those buildings leave traces in the ground that archaeologists can uncover, but the networks of people are less tangible, and thus difficult to recover from historical sources. Nonetheless, to understand how a medieval city functioned, we need to understand both its built environment and its social networks. The aim of this new project is to engage undergraduate students in digital humanities research and medieval history by involving them in the construction of a linked open data project for Medieval London. The project, which was piloted in the spring semester of 2024 with a team of four undergraduate students, aims to reconstruct social networks among the people who lived in the immediate vicinity of London’s Saint Bartholomew’s Hospital in the later middle ages. The core of the project involves extracting data from property records and then joining it with information from other sources, including tax records, judicial materials, civic administrative records, and sigillographic sources. Methodologically, the project builds on the data modeling and information system design work of John Bradley (King’s College -- 2005, 2013, 2014) and the more recent pedagogical innovations of Maryanne Kowaleski (Fordham University -- https://medievallondoners.ace.fordham.edu/). Prospographical research provides undergraduate students with exceptional opportunities to learn digital skills, as it involves them in the active construction of research datasets. However, coordinating multiple inexperienced researchers in prosopographical research is challenging, in large measure because of the problem of nominal record linkage. In this presentation, the project’s distinctive approach to nominal record linkage, through controlled and scaffolded data entry, will be presented and evaluated. Undergraduate students can make a meaningful contribution to linked data project that explore medieval social networks.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Bradley, John. 2014. &quot;Silk Purses and Sow&#039;s Ears: Can Structured Data Deal with Historical Sources?&quot;  Journal of Humanities &amp; Arts Computing&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cities are entities made of people and of buildings. Those buildings leave traces in the ground that archaeologists can uncover, but the networks of people are less tangible, and thus difficult to recover from historical sources. Nonetheless, to understand how a medieval city functioned, we need to understand both its built environment and its social networks. The aim of this new project is to engage undergraduate students in digital humanities research and medieval history by involving them in the construction of a linked open data project for Medieval London. The project, which was piloted in the spring semester of 2024 with a team of four undergraduate students, aims to reconstruct social networks among the people who lived in the immediate vicinity of London’s Saint Bartholomew’s Hospital in the later middle ages. The core of the project involves extracting data from property records and then joining it with information from other sources, including tax records, judicial materials, civic administrative records, and sigillographic sources. Methodologically, the project builds on the data modeling and information system design work of John Bradley (King’s College -- 2005, 2013, 2014) and the more recent pedagogical innovations of Maryanne Kowaleski (Fordham University -- https://medievallondoners.ace.fordham.edu/). Prospographical research provides undergraduate students with exceptional opportunities to learn digital skills, as it involves them in the active construction of research datasets. However, coordinating multiple inexperienced researchers in prosopographical research is challenging, in large measure because of the problem of nominal record linkage. In this presentation, the project’s distinctive approach to nominal record linkage, through controlled and scaffolded data entry, will be presented and evaluated. Undergraduate students can make a meaningful contribution to linked data project that explore medieval social networks.&#10;Bradley, John. 2014. &quot;Silk Purses and Sow&#039;s Ears: Can Structured Data Deal with Historical Sources?&quot; Journal of Humanities &amp; Arts Computing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">McEwan, John</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Kansas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">john.a.mcewan@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">john.a.mcewan@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">McEwan, John</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">john.a.mcewan@gmail.com</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">CDT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">76.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">290</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1282</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Middle, Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This abstract proposes to demonstrate how digital prosopographical methodologies have been applied to data from a combination of historical sources, and how undergraduate students have been engaged with this work.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While this project sounds extremely interesting and would make a strong addition to a Digital Humanities conference, I felt that the proposal could have articulated its relevance to the themes of this particular conference more explicitly.&#10;&#10;The proposal is contextualised well within existing scholarship on the topic of prosopographical data and engagement with the literature is clear. I did wonder if there has also been any pre-existing work that relates to the pedagogical aspects of the study.&#10;&#10;The aims and implications of the project are clearly articulated, as well as the prosopographical research methodology, although I’d be interested to hear if any particular tools or techniques were used to facilitate student engagement with the work.&#10;&#10;The value of the work to the discipline, the students involved, and the broader Digital Humanities community is clearly communicated.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1296</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Château-Dutier, Emmanuel</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The contribution reports on a teaching initiative carried out with undergraduate students on primary sources for conducting network analyses.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal seems to us to be particularly well argued. The project is ambitious, and fits perfectly into the field of digital history and digital humanities. Particularly noteworthy is the willingness to have students work directly on primary sources within an innovative methodological framework. We are curious about the strategies and tools used to produce linked data in the context of such a project.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1287</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kreutel, Jörn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The contribution aims at describing the results of a project in which undergraduate students collected prosopographical data from various sources with the purpose of reconstructing social networks within a given neighbourhood of medieval London. In particular, the proposal intends to focus on the, highly relevant, challenge of record linkage, given a group of relatively unexperienced junior researchers. With regard to the latter aspect and given its focus on everyday history, the proposal can be seen as addressing the issue of diversity of both research objectives and research groups.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Both with regard to the employment of undergraduate students (e.g. supposedly &quot;digital natives&quot;) for data collection and considering the envisaged focus on data linkage, the proposal is of by general interest for those researchers in DH that deal with data collection based on historical sources of any kind. However, it would have been desirable for the authors to be slightly more concrete with respect to the project&#039;s &quot;distinctive&quot; approach to the task of data linkage (unless this does not refer to the mere employment of a wide range of sources, which, for the given research objective could be taken for granted, though). </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">In case the presentation is not accepted as a full paper, it would deserve being presented as a poster.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">76</ss:Data></Cell>
