    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Interactive Digital Storytelling and Queer Archival Resistance in Bangladesh: A Decolonial Framework for Queer Digital Media Activism</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Decolonial Technologies, Critical Making, Online Cissexism and Queer-bashing, Queer Resistance, Digital Publics and Counter-publics.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Queer Studies&#10;Asia&#10;Global&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital archiving&#10;ethnographic analysis&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital archiving&#10;ethnographic analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Queer Studies&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Cultural studies&#10;Gender and sexuality studies&#10;Media studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Through closely looking into aspects of digital production and distribution of several queer affirming networked magazines, comics, and story-telling projects, this paper explores how South Asian Gay, Lesbian, and Bisexual (henceforth GLB) counter-publics engage in resisting dominant practices of online heteropatriarchy, cissexism, and queer bashing in the context of Bangladesh while negotiating visibility. The paper investigates &lt;em&gt;Roopban&lt;/em&gt;, the first gay magazine of Bangladesh, two queer affirming comics – &lt;em&gt;Lathiyal&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;Dhee&lt;/em&gt;, and an interactive digital storytelling project &lt;em&gt;Queer City, &lt;/em&gt;to evaluate their affordances, risks, and future-making aspirations within a societal context that is extremely oppressive towards GLB identities and cultures.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;By example of &lt;em&gt;Queer City, &lt;/em&gt;the paper then explores Twine storytelling through the lens of Critical Making both as a field of critical inquiry and a site that mobilizes trajectories of creative social engagements and digital makerspace activism and resistance against institutions of queer oppression in the context of South Asia. Navigating through Matt Ratto’s conceptual framework around Critical Making, and Debbie Chachra’s critique of the technocentric and technophilic disposition of making that has historically discounted the work of women, queer people, and people of color, the paper also examines the conditions under which the platform of Twine could function as a tactical tool for resistance and community building for GLB subjects.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Through foregrounding interviews with makers of such critical making projects, the talk also aims to assess the motivations, processes, objectives, and challenges of such projects within the larger politics of right-wing and religious extremism and neocolonial aggressions in Bangladesh. Insights from the interview along with analysis of the maker projects, will also trace future trajectories and potentials of a decolonial framework for enclave queer media activism in Bangladesh and South Asia more broadly.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Through closely looking into aspects of digital production and distribution of several queer affirming networked magazines, comics, and story-telling projects, this paper explores how South Asian Gay, Lesbian, and Bisexual (henceforth GLB) counter-publics engage in resisting dominant practices of online heteropatriarchy, cissexism, and queer bashing in the context of Bangladesh while negotiating visibility. The paper investigates Roopban, the first gay magazine of Bangladesh, two queer affirming comics – Lathiyal and Dhee, and an interactive digital storytelling project Queer City, to evaluate their affordances, risks, and future-making aspirations within a societal context that is extremely oppressive towards GLB identities and cultures.&#10;By example of Queer City, the paper then explores Twine storytelling through the lens of Critical Making both as a field of critical inquiry and a site that mobilizes trajectories of creative social engagements and digital makerspace activism and resistance against institutions of queer oppression in the context of South Asia. Navigating through Matt Ratto’s conceptual framework around Critical Making, and Debbie Chachra’s critique of the technocentric and technophilic disposition of making that has historically discounted the work of women, queer people, and people of color, the paper also examines the conditions under which the platform of Twine could function as a tactical tool for resistance and community building for GLB subjects.&#10;Through foregrounding interviews with makers of such critical making projects, the talk also aims to assess the motivations, processes, objectives, and challenges of such projects within the larger politics of right-wing and religious extremism and neocolonial aggressions in Bangladesh. Insights from the interview along with analysis of the maker projects, will also trace future trajectories and potentials of a decolonial framework for enclave queer media activism in Bangladesh and South Asia more broadly.</ss:Data></Cell>
