    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">291</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1267</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shaikh, Hina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am excited to hear this paper presentation as it is very important, thorough and novel focus upon queer storytelling through the first gay magazine of Bangladesh alongside two queer comics and an interactive digital storytelling project. Utilizing Critical Making as an analytic, the author incorporates interviews of makers to interrogate decolonial and queer activisms in Bangladesh and South Asia. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author writes an important and exciting abstract that clearly engages with the urgent political investments of queer and decolonial activisms within Bangladesh and South Asia. My suggestion here is to narrowly define the focus of this paper to one that clearly defines what the author means by “decolonial” and also clarifies their use of “queer” as one that strictly names queer embodiment and/or also names queerness as a politic. &#10;&#10;Additionally, it may be important to engage with queer theory to define more organically how queer theoretical paradigms are perhaps insufficient in naming the multiple axes of power you are engaging with. On the other hand, texts like José Muñoz’s Cruising Utopia might also provide you with rich frameworks to consider at the intersection of futurity and queerness. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1023</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Esmaeili, Niloufar</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This research delves into how South Asian GLB communities utilize digital production to create and share queer content as a form of resistance against online biases in Bangladesh. It analyses magazines, comics and interactive storytelling from the perspectives of Critical Making and decolonial frameworks.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal demonstrates relevance to the conference&#039;s themes effectively addressing queer studies and postcolonial/decolonial studies in the realm of digital humanities. It engages thoughtfully with existing research drawing on Critical Making concepts and critiques of technocentered approaches. The structure and purpose are well defined, merging theory and practice. The proposal presents practicality by exploring how digital tools can be used for resistance. &#10;I recommend enhancing the project by outlining its structure, briefly detailing the interview methods and analysis approach and exploring its connections to similar studies previously conducted. It could also benefit from an outline of how different projects will be discussed.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal presents a unique perspective on digital humanities, highlighting queer activism in South Asia, a region that is not commonly explored in DH conversations. Its inclusive approach and emphasis on using tools to empower marginalized groups make it a compelling choice for consideration. It is recommended to pair this project with others discussing digital activism or queer studies in Global South settings to form a panel.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1180</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karajgikar, Jajwalya</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission combines the study of activism in archives and interactive storytelling. It is a compelling qualitative view of queer narratives in a South Asian context. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Thank you for sharing your fascinating and important work with us. I enjoyed learning about the mixed media research method of queer studies. I am excited to hear more about the tools and processes used in this study. I am also interested in learning more of the data physicalization / technophilic component of critical making in this study. &#10;Good luck!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">86</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
