    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Addressing the Human Challenges of Underressourced Language DH</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Egypt, underresourced languages, open source, open access, labor</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;Africa&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;BCE-4th Century&#10;5th-14th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;open access methods&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods&#10;Linguistics&#10;Philology&#10;Theology and religious studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Africa&#10;Europe&#10;North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">BCE-4th Century&#10;5th-14th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">postcolonial, decolonial, and anticolonial approaches&#10;open access methods&#10;public humanities collaborations and methods</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Linguistics&#10;Philology&#10;Theology and religious studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The technical challenges of working on DH research involving underresourced languages are significant—from challenges with optical character recognition or handwritten text recognition to XML encoding standards to the absence of basic tools such as tokenizers and lemmatizers. This paper, however, will discuss the human challenges that exist in parallel to, and indeed compound, these technical challenges. I will use examples from my project Coptic Scriptorium (https://copticscriptorium.org). While focused on this particular language, the goals are for people working in other under-resourced languages to find resonances with this work and to generate conversations among a larger DH community.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The paper will particularly address human challenges faced while pursuing DH methods to improve access to colonized cultural heritage resources for researchers and the heritage community of origin. As a result of the antiquities trade and Global North scholarly engagements with or reactions to that trade, Coptic manuscripts are dispersed primarily throughout Global North repositories. The Coptic language is the last phase of the ancient Egyptian language family. While not as prized as pharaonic artifacts, Coptic art and literature were traded as commodities and antiquities. I do not claim that these DH methods are specifically anti-colonial, because while they address the legacy of colonialism, they do not and cannot fundamentally change core infrastructures of colonialism—the antiquities trade, the disparate resources between Global North and Global South institutions, and the specific complexities of religion, politics, and heritage studies on the ground inside Egypt. Nonetheless open access and open source work are one step toward a more ethical paradigm.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The paper will examine issues including digitizing dispersed manuscript fragments (and making them accessible in their original order); collaborations with the heritage community in the English-speaking diaspora and in Egypt; translation; collaboration with other DH projects; sustainability.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The technical challenges of working on DH research involving underresourced languages are significant—from challenges with optical character recognition or handwritten text recognition to XML encoding standards to the absence of basic tools such as tokenizers and lemmatizers. This paper, however, will discuss the human challenges that exist in parallel to, and indeed compound, these technical challenges. I will use examples from my project Coptic Scriptorium (https://copticscriptorium.org). While focused on this particular language, the goals are for people working in other under-resourced languages to find resonances with this work and to generate conversations among a larger DH community.&#10;The paper will particularly address human challenges faced while pursuing DH methods to improve access to colonized cultural heritage resources for researchers and the heritage community of origin. As a result of the antiquities trade and Global North scholarly engagements with or reactions to that trade, Coptic manuscripts are dispersed primarily throughout Global North repositories. The Coptic language is the last phase of the ancient Egyptian language family. While not as prized as pharaonic artifacts, Coptic art and literature were traded as commodities and antiquities. I do not claim that these DH methods are specifically anti-colonial, because while they address the legacy of colonialism, they do not and cannot fundamentally change core infrastructures of colonialism—the antiquities trade, the disparate resources between Global North and Global South institutions, and the specific complexities of religion, politics, and heritage studies on the ground inside Egypt. Nonetheless open access and open source work are one step toward a more ethical paradigm.&#10;The paper will examine issues including digitizing dispersed manuscript fragments (and making them accessible in their original order); collaborations with the heritage community in the English-speaking diaspora and in Egypt; translation; collaboration with other DH projects; sustainability.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Schroeder, Caroline T.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">University of Oklahoma</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ctschroeder@ou.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ctschroeder@ou.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Schroeder, Caroline T.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ctschroeder@ou.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Central Time USA</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">79.3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">56.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">292</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1293</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tew, Sarah</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper will present work on the digitization of Coptic manuscript fragments through collaborations with heritage organizations and DH projects.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The work and themes present in this proposal are highly relevant and I think would be appealing to the ACH audience. The proposal, however, is too vague for me. I would have liked to know which specific of even types of cultural heritage institutions collaborated on the project, the scale of the project, specific DH projects and methods used in the project. The main human challenges that will be covered in this talk are unclear to me. The topic and project sounds like it could be a valuable contribution, but the abstract as available to me now makes it difficult to get a clear handle on what exactly the audience will take away from this paper.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">56</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1290</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Gearhart, Julia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The presenter is sharing their own experiences in DH research with an underresourced language to share challenges to spark discussion and problem-solving with other practitioners </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This looks like a fantastic presentation. I&#039;m particularly interested in how the very different challenges suggested, between &quot;digitizing dispersed manuscript fragments&quot; in mostly the global North, to &quot;collaborations with the heritage community in the English-speaking diaspora and in Egypt&quot; can be covered in the time allotted. Seems like a lot, and very different topics, but maybe they are more similar than I suspect. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">90</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1315</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tratarou, Adelina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is a well-organized and detailed proposal that engages with the compounded technical and human challenges in Digital Humanities (DH) research involving under-resourced languages. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">It is evident that the presenter has put considerable thought into the Coptic Scriptorium project. The discussion of human challenges, particularly in relation to colonized cultural heritage resources and the efforts to improve access for researchers and the heritage community of origin, offers a unique perspective on the topic, and the proposal’s presentation makes it clear that the presenter is in dialogue with the current debates in the literature, while also engaging with the significant sociopolitical debates of this work. The consideration of the impact of colonialism on the dissemination and study of Coptic manuscripts is important and thought-provoking. Overall, this proposal covers a wide range of critical issues, including digitization, collaboration, and sustainability, and it makes a compelling case for the relevance of DH methods in addressing these challenges. It will make a great addition to the conference.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">23</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Accept as Lightning</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell ss:StyleID="s22"><Data ss:Type="DateTime">2024-09-07T17:44:11.000</Data></Cell>
