    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Conversations with ChatGPT: Misconceptions about the Global South</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">critical data studies, ChatGPT</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Surveillance Studies&#10;Asia&#10;North America&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;South Asian Studies&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia&#10;North America&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;database creation, management, and analysis&#10;digital access, privacy, and ethics analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Surveillance Studies&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;South Asian Studies&#10;Data science/data studies&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Chat GPT by OpenAI is a conversational generational AI (GenAI) that produces texts and answers the questions of its users. It is a large language model (LLM) trained on publicly available data and other sources using Reinforcement Learning with Human Feedback (RLHF). ChatGPT collects all the conversations that the users have with it. These conversations and the responses of the users are then used as feedback to further improvise the model. But, while having a conversation, the user cannot correct ChatGPT i.e. the user cannot change ChatGPT’s knowledge about a particular topic. The user can state that the ChatGPT is wrong, and the conversational AI will apologize for it, probably change the response also in some cases, but that will not change the technical “wiring” of the system. While human feedback is being heavily incorporated in improvising ChatGPT and its newer models, the user does not have any direct control over what feedback is being utilized and in which ways.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;In this paper, I argue that “human learning” in the feedback loop of ChatGPT and such generative AI systems is a position of privilege which is not held by its users. I investigate the need and lack of user feedback by having conversations with ChatGPT regarding gender translations from English to Gujarati (my native language) and Indian caste system. These conversations highlight that the misconceptions about groups and languages of the Global South prevalent in technical systems and the users of ChatGPT do not hold any power to change that information. While ChatGPT covers its answers in politeness and apologizes when a user says it is wrong, that does nothing to change the biased, prejudiced and patronizing digital reality created by ChatGPT.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chat GPT by OpenAI is a conversational generational AI (GenAI) that produces texts and answers the questions of its users. It is a large language model (LLM) trained on publicly available data and other sources using Reinforcement Learning with Human Feedback (RLHF). ChatGPT collects all the conversations that the users have with it. These conversations and the responses of the users are then used as feedback to further improvise the model. But, while having a conversation, the user cannot correct ChatGPT i.e. the user cannot change ChatGPT’s knowledge about a particular topic. The user can state that the ChatGPT is wrong, and the conversational AI will apologize for it, probably change the response also in some cases, but that will not change the technical “wiring” of the system. While human feedback is being heavily incorporated in improvising ChatGPT and its newer models, the user does not have any direct control over what feedback is being utilized and in which ways.&#10;In this paper, I argue that “human learning” in the feedback loop of ChatGPT and such generative AI systems is a position of privilege which is not held by its users. I investigate the need and lack of user feedback by having conversations with ChatGPT regarding gender translations from English to Gujarati (my native language) and Indian caste system. These conversations highlight that the misconceptions about groups and languages of the Global South prevalent in technical systems and the users of ChatGPT do not hold any power to change that information. While ChatGPT covers its answers in politeness and apologizes when a user says it is wrong, that does nothing to change the biased, prejudiced and patronizing digital reality created by ChatGPT.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shukla, Nishanshi Atulkumar</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The University of Texas at Dallas</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nishanshi.shukla@utdallas.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nishanshi.shukla@utdallas.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shukla, Nishanshi Atulkumar</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">nishanshi.shukla@utdallas.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Central Daylight Time United States (GMT -5)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">44.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">293</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1267</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Shaikh, Hina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author critically analyzes the way ChatGPT incorporates feedback and still creates misconceptions about groups and languages from the global south. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author is engaging with ChatGPT in an important and incisive way to interrogate the failings of RLHF. The author has important critiques about the failings of RLHF and I would recommend the author incorporates the crucial role of labor from the Global South in helping to moderate and train ChatGPT. This may allow for a more robust and situated critique of ChatGPT as well as an important way to connect across global axes of oppressions. If the author is further interested in developing this paper, I would additionally suggest understanding the logic or rationality behind why ChatGPT is programmed to create the world in a way that prioritizes the West. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1180</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Karajgikar, Jajwalya</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper submission focuses on critiquing ChatGPT as a conversational tool with a potential for both multilingual and anti-caste considerations falling short. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Thanks for sharing your work. This is important work that should receive more attention. For improving the abstract, please share the methodological steps and process of the study and the purported outcome. I am glad to see anti-caste framework but would be interested to have the framework perspectives detailed in the abstract.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper seems to be at a rudimentary stage even though the subject matter is important and interesting.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">54</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1202</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tekgürler, Merve</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This contribution studies ChatGPT and the content of the model&#039;s outputs with regards to race, caste, and gender in South Asia. The author converses with the model through the chat interface to capture what the model produces on the topic of gender translations and Indian caste system. The author analyzes the biased reality that ChatGPT creates and comments about how users who despite correcting the model in their own chat instances, do not actually have an impact on how the model is further fine-tuned. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While I find the research question very interesting and convincing, there are many aspects of this proposal that are unclear to me. First, I am very cautious about the use of language like &quot;ChatGPT’s knowledge about a particular topic&quot; or that the model apologizes. Knowledge is a very tricky concept in the context of LLMs and so is anthropomorphizing these models. The author needs to more clearly explain what they mean by that and justify how it serves the research goals that they set out. &#10;Second, I assumed from the submission that the author is using the chat interface to study the model, however this needs to be clarified in a more robust methods-focused paragraph. Which model is the author studying, GPT-3.5, 4, 4o? What are the prompts? Why were these prompts chosen and how does the prompt choice relate to the research questions? Similarly what does gender translation mean and how does that show us biases? Some concrete examples of the conversations would be amazing but it is certainly necessary to provide some more context and details about what these conversations are and how the conversations relate to the research questions.&#10;Thirdly, this paper does not show any engagement with existing literature on AI models and bias. There is a lot of research on bias more broadly but also on RHLF and bias specifically. One of the curious results was that the model responses got longer over time because people prefer longer answers and crowd-workers who need to work really fast just pick the longer answer as the better one, so these models are fine-tuned to produce longer responses. This would be an interesting tangent to follow. On the same topic, most RHLF work is outsourced into the Global South, which means that essentially people who have the privilege to be on the &#039;feedback loop of ChatGPT&#039; are workers in the Global South. How does this further complicate the author&#039;s question about privilege?&#10;Lastly, the subscription version of ChatGPT has a &#039;memory&#039; of conversations. This is still an ongoing research tangent but it could be interesting for the author to look into this memory function and see if the model is able to retain some of the corrections through this new feature. &#10;Overall, I think this is a very cool idea and an emerging research topic that shows great potential.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">It would be great as a lightning talk if the author did not have the chance to further develop this project since submission. They can benefit from the shorter time and more immediate feedback opportunities. If they have done more work, I think a poster could work as well, especially since it would allow individual engagement.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">44</ss:Data></Cell>
