    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">HTR-United&#039;s diversity: a critical analysis on data provenance</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">HTR, machine learning, datasets, open science, diversity</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Europe&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;open access methods&#10;optical character recognition and handwriting recognition&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Computer science&#10;Humanities Computing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Europe&#10;North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">artificial intelligence and machine learning&#10;open access methods&#10;optical character recognition and handwriting recognition</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Book and Print history&#10;Computer science&#10;Humanities Computing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Being able to automatically retrieve the text contained in centuries-old handwritten documents is a promise that has revolutionized access to archival collections. Expert software, like Transkribus or eScriptorium, and the development of more powerful machine learning algorithms, have played a key role in bringing this technology to cultural institutions, academia and amateur users. However, access to the high-quality training data needed to train effective transcription models remains a major challenge. The HTR-United catalog (https://htr-united.github.io/) was born in this context: thanks to a tailored description schema and a search interface, it facilitates the discovery of free, high-quality training data for automatic transcription, whatever the language, writing system, period or software used to produce them.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Due to the geographical roots of its authors, the catalog currently covers mostly Latin alphabet scripts: while 8 different writing systems are found in the datasets listed, over 85% of them include the Latin alphabet. Similarly, French represents about 40% of the datasets, against 21 languages covered in total.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;As part of the ACH 2024 conference, we propose to conduct an analysis of the diversity of languages and geographical areas represented in this catalog, as well as the geographical distribution of the producers of these datasets. The aim of this analysis, which will combine statistical overviews with closer studies of some of the datasets, will be to take a critical look at the catalog&#039;s capacity to include a greater diversity of data and contributions and its potential weaknesses as well as its strengths. With this contribution, we hope to make more users of HTR, especially those who may have more difficulties accessing computation resources, aware of the existence of this catalog. Additionally, we wish to call their attention to the importance of creating common resources and accessible datasets for the rest of the community.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Being able to automatically retrieve the text contained in centuries-old handwritten documents is a promise that has revolutionized access to archival collections. Expert software, like Transkribus or eScriptorium, and the development of more powerful machine learning algorithms, have played a key role in bringing this technology to cultural institutions, academia and amateur users. However, access to the high-quality training data needed to train effective transcription models remains a major challenge. The HTR-United catalog (https://htr-united.github.io/) was born in this context: thanks to a tailored description schema and a search interface, it facilitates the discovery of free, high-quality training data for automatic transcription, whatever the language, writing system, period or software used to produce them.&#10;Due to the geographical roots of its authors, the catalog currently covers mostly Latin alphabet scripts: while 8 different writing systems are found in the datasets listed, over 85% of them include the Latin alphabet. Similarly, French represents about 40% of the datasets, against 21 languages covered in total.&#10;As part of the ACH 2024 conference, we propose to conduct an analysis of the diversity of languages and geographical areas represented in this catalog, as well as the geographical distribution of the producers of these datasets. The aim of this analysis, which will combine statistical overviews with closer studies of some of the datasets, will be to take a critical look at the catalog&#039;s capacity to include a greater diversity of data and contributions and its potential weaknesses as well as its strengths. With this contribution, we hope to make more users of HTR, especially those who may have more difficulties accessing computation resources, aware of the existence of this catalog. Additionally, we wish to call their attention to the importance of creating common resources and accessible datasets for the rest of the community.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chagué, Alix</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Inria / Université de Montréal</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Canada</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">alix.chague@inria.fr</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">alix.chague@umontreal.ca</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">alix.chague@inria.fr, thibault.clerice@inria.fr</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Chagué, Alix</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">alix.chague@inria.fr</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">GMT -4 hours</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">68.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">70.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">295</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1269</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Bell, Eamonn</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper will present an online catalogue of data used to train handwritten text recognition (HTR) applications, notably assessing the geographic and palaeographical diversity of the catalogue with a view to improving its representativeness and usefulness to scholars of varied time periods and text-cultural contexts.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">As the proposal is motivated by growing access to diverse training datasets for HTR, it has a self-evident link to the conference themes though perhaps this could be made even more explicit during the presentation. There was limited engagement with prior work, stretching only to name-checking some existing HTR frameworks; it would be beneficial to clearly situate the work in the context of prior attempts to consolidate and grow &quot;open science&quot; communities around training datasets (even if no direct precursors within the HTR subfield can be found). The analytical method behind this presentation is relatively straightforward: A kind of statistical diversity audit of the existing holdings leading to a rallying call for contributions, which is well suited to the international context of ACH 2024 and stands to have quite some potential for impact. To this extent, it promises a long-term practical contribution to DH, through well-established means. The straightforwardness of the analysis might suggest greater suitability for other formats (i.e. poster or lightning talk) but I do not recommend this, as presentation for this work in the main track should serve to facilitate the greatest engagement with the community, which appears to be a clear aspiration of this presentation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">68</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1118</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Forster, Chris</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper proposes to offer a survey of the languages and regions used in the HTR-United catalog. Such a survey promises the evaluate the strengths and weaknesses of this resource&#039;s scope of representation.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This survey seems absolutely useful and valuable. I&#039;m not entirely sure how such a survey will, itself, &quot;make more users of HTR, especially those who may have more difficulties accessing computation resources, aware of the existence of this catalog.&quot;&#10;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">While useful and fascinating, I wonder a little if the sort of survey proposed is best expressed as a panel paper (rather than another, perhaps shorter, format).</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">66</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1202</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tekgürler, Merve</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission highlights the HTR-United Catalog, a static website that hosts metadata and links to various datasets that can be used for handwritten text recognition model training and allows others to share their data. The authors&#039; goal is to provide an overview of the datasets and raise awareness about the catalog and the importance of collective resources. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am already familiar with HTR United and I think it is a really great project. Thank you for all your work! I certainly think that this project deserves to be highlighted in this conference, however I am not sure about what to expect from this paper. The provenance of the datasets much like any large scale digital project skews towards Europe and North America. While it is important to be critical about this, I would like to see what criticisms the authors bring to this topic and to themselves and what approaches they devised for changing amending the biases in their catalog. I am specifically referring to the authors proposition to take a critical look at the catalog (see paragraph 3). What does this this look entail and what does it mean in practice to take this position? This seems like a rather small project team and potentially a lot of unpaid labor, so I am not suggesting that the authors are responsible for diversifying the entire HTR field. But from the submission it seems like they are going to be critical of these dynamics and I would like to read more clearly what does criticisms will be, how they understand their own positionalities, and how they interface with multilingualism focused critiques to DH/technology.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this could be great as a demo/workshop kind of poster. It would be nice to have the authors show how the upload system works and what their categories are and we can all observe the process together. I really think this project should be highlighted in some fashion because discoverability of HTR datasets is an ongoing issue.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
