    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">66.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">84.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">52.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">296</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1207</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">King, Joey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contributions of social media in political activism in Nigeria. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal aligns nicely with the conference themes, and by drawing on relevant scholarship has the potential to provide a engaging presentation on the impact social media has/can have on the effort of political mobilization in Nigeria. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1283</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Negueruela del Castillo, Darío</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This paper explores the context of social media in the quest for good governance in Nigeria through the political mobilization of the masses</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Interesting to read about the context in Nigeria, but I miss some broader contextualization as to theorize clearly what the author claims to have found in a more convincing but nuanced manner</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">62</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1239</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kunnuji, Joseph</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper examines the role of social media in political mobilization. Social media has been pivotal as a soft power resource in the 21st century, and this contribution focusing on Nigerian politics is essential in creating a robust understanding of netizens’ sociopolitical impact.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper examines the role of social media in political mobilization. Social media has been pivotal as a soft power resource in the 21st century, and this contribution focusing on Nigerian politics is essential in creating a robust understanding of netizens’ sociopolitical impact. The abstract can be improved by highlighting the digital tools used to collect and process the study’s data. Additionally, the conclusion and findings of the study seem obvious. Could deeper insights be drawn to make the study more cutting-edge?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I am unsure about the role of DH in this study.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">52</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
