    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Expansion of Digital Bibliographic Database on Chinese Republican Era Buddhist Publications</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th century Buddhism, database creation, digital indexing</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Asia&#10;20th Century&#10;bibliographic analysis&#10;concordance and indexing&#10;digital archiving&#10;Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Philology&#10;Theology and religious studies&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">bibliographic analysis&#10;concordance and indexing&#10;digital archiving</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Asian and Asian American Studies&#10;Book and Print history&#10;Philology&#10;Theology and religious studies&#10;Bibliographical Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This poster presents an ongoing project that extends the current bibliographic database of Chinese Buddhist publications from the Republican era (1912-1949). This period signifies a transformation in Buddhism, characterized by a reform of Buddhist thoughts and practices, often displayed through periodicals and newspapers. The foundational work for this project relies on the bibliographic database developed by Marcus Bingenheimer et al., which catalogues articles from various Buddhist journals during this era.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;The current project aims to enhance this database by integrating additional sources, specifically the works edited by Xianian Huang et al., including “Collected Works of Buddhist Journal Articles from the Republican Era, part 3” and “Compilation of Rare Buddhist Newspaper Materials from the Republican Era”. These sources contribute to the database by adding article titles, authors, publication dates, and other bibliographic information that were previously unavailable in the digital format.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;By expanding the database, this project preserves valuable historical and cultural artifacts but also facilitates future scholarly research on Buddhism during a crucial stage of modern Chinese history. Researchers can explore trends, shifts, and the dynamics of Buddhist thought and its dissemination through periodicals, thereby gaining insights into the broader socio-religious landscape of the time.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This poster presents an ongoing project that extends the current bibliographic database of Chinese Buddhist publications from the Republican era (1912-1949). This period signifies a transformation in Buddhism, characterized by a reform of Buddhist thoughts and practices, often displayed through periodicals and newspapers. The foundational work for this project relies on the bibliographic database developed by Marcus Bingenheimer et al., which catalogues articles from various Buddhist journals during this era.&#10;The current project aims to enhance this database by integrating additional sources, specifically the works edited by Xianian Huang et al., including “Collected Works of Buddhist Journal Articles from the Republican Era, part 3” and “Compilation of Rare Buddhist Newspaper Materials from the Republican Era”. These sources contribute to the database by adding article titles, authors, publication dates, and other bibliographic information that were previously unavailable in the digital format.&#10;By expanding the database, this project preserves valuable historical and cultural artifacts but also facilitates future scholarly research on Buddhism during a crucial stage of modern Chinese history. Researchers can explore trends, shifts, and the dynamics of Buddhist thought and its dissemination through periodicals, thereby gaining insights into the broader socio-religious landscape of the time.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Li, Tong</ss:Data></Cell>
