    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">No Tech For Apartheid Memory</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital, memory, counter-archive, labor, tech</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Global Digital Humanities&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;North America&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital archiving&#10;user experience design and analysis&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital activism and advocacy&#10;digital archiving&#10;user experience design and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Global Digital Humanities&#10;Labor, Infrastructure, and Critical University Studies&#10;Education/Pedagogy&#10;Humanities Computing&#10;Science, Technology, and Society</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The Big Tech industry finds itself incompatible with public interest and is deeply entrenched in reinforcing oppressive structures. As workers, it is our collective responsibility to ensure our labor respects human life over profit at all times. In the face of heavy repression, we must continue to engage in labor organizing for the sake of transforming technology into a benefit to our society. Building digital memory archives can serve as an act of labor resistance to oppose mainstream capitalist articulations of tech’s history in grappling with the violent reality of our work.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The 2023 - 2024 Google NYC Digital Memory Archive (notechforapartheidmemory.com), is a project centering the worker narrative in tech labor struggles in the wake of the ongoing genocide of the Palestinian people, rooted in my personal experiences as an organizer with No Tech For Apartheid while working as a Software Engineer at Google. This project draws inspiration from the labor-focused digital memory project Memory Work Los Angeles, and many digital counter-archives such as Moleculas Malucas, the Nakba Archive, and the Cyberfeminism Index. In presenting the project, I hope to reflect on the following questions: How have Google workers engaged in labor organizing through No Tech For Apartheid (NOTA) in 2024? How can we archive, build upon, and share our learnings using technology to engage in labor organizing within the wider tech industry through memory counter-archives? How does collective worker action introduce new liberatory potential of technology built by, for, and alongside the public?&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The Big Tech industry finds itself incompatible with public interest and is deeply entrenched in reinforcing oppressive structures. As workers, it is our collective responsibility to ensure our labor respects human life over profit at all times. In the face of heavy repression, we must continue to engage in labor organizing for the sake of transforming technology into a benefit to our society. Building digital memory archives can serve as an act of labor resistance to oppose mainstream capitalist articulations of tech’s history in grappling with the violent reality of our work.&#10;The 2023 - 2024 Google NYC Digital Memory Archive (notechforapartheidmemory.com), is a project centering the worker narrative in tech labor struggles in the wake of the ongoing genocide of the Palestinian people, rooted in my personal experiences as an organizer with No Tech For Apartheid while working as a Software Engineer at Google. This project draws inspiration from the labor-focused digital memory project Memory Work Los Angeles, and many digital counter-archives such as Moleculas Malucas, the Nakba Archive, and the Cyberfeminism Index. In presenting the project, I hope to reflect on the following questions: How have Google workers engaged in labor organizing through No Tech For Apartheid (NOTA) in 2024? How can we archive, build upon, and share our learnings using technology to engage in labor organizing within the wider tech industry through memory counter-archives? How does collective worker action introduce new liberatory potential of technology built by, for, and alongside the public?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
