    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">298</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1284</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rousseau, Paulina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This session emphasizes the importance of our collective responsibility to ensure our labor respects human life over profit at all times in the context of Big Tech, describing a specific digital project that centres on the worker narrative in tech labor struggles in the wake of the ongoing genocide of the Palestinian people, and is rooted in the work of No Tech For Apartheid. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Very pertinent and relevant topic to the conference focus. Good contextualization and framing, as well as reference to other similar work that has been done previously. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This could have also been an individual presentation or part of a larger panel. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1126</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ElKattan, Alia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The submission provides crucial insight on anti-racist and anti-genocide labor organizing within Big Tech companies such as Google. The method highlights the significance of archiving efforts outside the academic sphere, and how organizing archives can provide an avenue for alternative and community/worker-led storytelling and reclamation of narrative. The submission is well-situated within a broader effort of community led and empowering archiving efforts, but offers unique insight into No Tech For Apartheid&#039;s movement building, which is necessary for understanding how to counter the harms and hegemonies of large tech corporations. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The archive is an impressive effort documenting what has become a crucial form of organizing, and your personal experiences as a NOTA organizer are very needed in these largely academic spaces. My recommendations to take this work forward would be:&#10;&#10;1. Reflecting on both how the act of archiving in itself has, if at all, provided a sense of ownership and empowerment over your time, experiences, and story as a Google worker, and what the limitations of archiving has been. What are you best able to narrate through archiving, and what remains difficult to capture or communicate?&#10;&#10;2. How can you expand these efforts to broaden the archive to include the experiences of other tech workers both within and outside of NOTA? What would the scope of such an archive be, and how would the community involvement aspect change it?</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Grumbach, Liz</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This lightning talk will reflect on how archives and labor resistance/organizing can introduce new liberatory potentials for technology. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This is an exciting abstract that will seek to combine lived experience and an analysis of emergent advocacy/archive work to reflect on important questions regarding agency, memory, and momentum in our current moment of labor organizing efforts across Big Tech. This is incredibly relevant to the conference theme, and it is rooted in both archival practices and the (recent) history of labor in the U.S. in relation to technology.  &#10;&#10;While this will no doubt be explicit in the presentation, the abstract here could be slightly enhanced by incorporating some scholarship about counter archives (Azouley, etc.), memory and archives (Caswell, Urgent Archives), personal archives (Singh, No Archive Will Restore You), and/or labor organizing, though the references to existing digital counter archives grounds the abstract in current digital projects.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
