    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Framing the Rhetoric of Atrocity in Nollywood</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Rhetoric, Atrocity, Nollywood, Tiv, Nigeria, Fulani, Tiv cinema, Film</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Africa&#10;Contemporary&#10;cultural analytics&#10;image processing and analysis&#10;rhetorical analysis&#10;African American/Black Studies&#10;Film and cinema arts studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Africa</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">cultural analytics&#10;image processing and analysis&#10;rhetorical analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">African American/Black Studies&#10;Film and cinema arts studies&#10;Media studies&#10;Ethnic studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;Though Nigeria is replete with atrocities that have been reenacted and documented in a variety of creative forms, their cinematic representation has not received profound scholarly attention. There are films that depict colonial and postcolonial atrocities in Nigeria, particularly in Tiv cinema (an emergent form of tribal visual culture associated with mainstream Nollywood). However, conventional discourses of atrocity are largely centered on the Holocaust, the 9/11 massacre, the Rwandan Genocide, Hurricane Katrina, and other Western tragedies, with no significant effort at conceptualizing the depiction of atrocity through localized lenses and culturally specific spaces within Nigeria. Against this backdrop, this article explores how atrocity manifests as a recurring trope in modern Nollywood narratives and calls for rethinking ways of overcoming Nigeria’s existential crises. The study examines how Tiv film re-imagines the ongoing farmer-herder crisis and deconstructs complex issues surrounding Tiv-Fulani massacres. Using a qualitative research method, the article analyzes &lt;em&gt;Bemdoo&lt;/em&gt;, a 2016 Tiv film, to gain insight into nuanced narrative techniques used in depicting an ongoing atrocity.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Though Nigeria is replete with atrocities that have been reenacted and documented in a variety of creative forms, their cinematic representation has not received profound scholarly attention. There are films that depict colonial and postcolonial atrocities in Nigeria, particularly in Tiv cinema (an emergent form of tribal visual culture associated with mainstream Nollywood). However, conventional discourses of atrocity are largely centered on the Holocaust, the 9/11 massacre, the Rwandan Genocide, Hurricane Katrina, and other Western tragedies, with no significant effort at conceptualizing the depiction of atrocity through localized lenses and culturally specific spaces within Nigeria. Against this backdrop, this article explores how atrocity manifests as a recurring trope in modern Nollywood narratives and calls for rethinking ways of overcoming Nigeria’s existential crises. The study examines how Tiv film re-imagines the ongoing farmer-herder crisis and deconstructs complex issues surrounding Tiv-Fulani massacres. Using a qualitative research method, the article analyzes Bemdoo, a 2016 Tiv film, to gain insight into nuanced narrative techniques used in depicting an ongoing atrocity.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Nyikwagh, Felix</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Clemson University</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">fnyikwa@clemson.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">fnyikwa@clemson.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Nyikwagh, Felix</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">fnyikwa@clemson.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">ET</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">88.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">64.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">2</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">299</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1097</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Wigard, Justin</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The critical context and subject matter is explained well, as is the imperative to study Tiv cinema within the broader culture of Nollywood when previous scholarship has focused on other ”conventional discourses of atrocity.”&#10;&#10;However, it’s a little unclear, based on the abstract, what qualitative method is being used, and how this contributed to digital humanities generally. &#10;&#10;Suggestions for improvement would be to: a) explain the specific film being analyzed; b) explain and demonstrate the methods being applied to the film, c) gesture towards the findings, and d) offer brief citations on some of that previous scholarship mentioned. &#10;&#10;Why was Bemdoo chosen, or what is it about? I think the audience would love to know more about how the author sees this film challenging or expanding the aforementioned discourses. &#10;&#10;What particular qualitative methods are being used, as well as what theoretical frameworks? It looks like image processing and analysis, and maybe rhetorical analysis or cultural analytics, but a stronger abstract would work to be specific about the DH methods and guiding frameworks or theories. &#10;&#10;Lastly: what insight was gained into the “nuanced narrative techniques” found in Bemdoo?  How do DH methods (whether image processing or something else) help us better understand Tiv cinema/Nollywood? Or, how does Tiv cinema complicate/enrich our understanding of DH? A brief gesture towards this would help the audience greatly. &#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project seems like it is in early stages, so I think it would be appropriate for a poster. &#10;&#10;The author seems knowledgeable about Nollywood and Tiv cinema, but it is unclear what kinds of DH methods have been applied or will be applied, and to what ends. Subject-wise, I would lean towards accepting, but methods and findings are unclear, hence the recommendation for a poster. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">64</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1136</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cary, Justin Robert</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This submission contributes an important expansion of current mainstream Western Hollywood/Nollywood &#039;global&#039; crises in TV/Film; offering a deconstruction of the farmer-herder crisis and deconstructions of other key global tragedies that often do not appear in mainstream television and film in order to apply more scholarly attention to these no-less important global atrocities. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">An extremely compelling submission; I think your submission is extremely well done and would very well placed at this conference.  The idea of arguing with visual images and how those images are used to create rhetorical situations among audiences resonates very clearly in your work and I imagine some great discussions would be generated by your contribution here; especially in the emerging sphere of AI video.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I think this proposal would be a great contribution to the conference as this work would bring attention to a topic that needs to be given a platform and more scholarly attention. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1315</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Tratarou, Adelina</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The paper contributes significantly to the underrepresented discourse on cinematic representations of atrocities in Nigeria. The author adeptly highlights the lack of scholarly attention to this important topic while shedding light on the localized lenses and culturally specific spaces within Nigeria through which atrocity is depicted. The article&#039;s focus on Tiv cinema as an emergent form of tribal visual culture associated with mainstream Nollywood offers a fresh and compelling perspective.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">One of the strengths of this contribution will be the author&#039;s analysis of the 2016 Tiv film “Bemdoo,” which will provide valuable insights into the narrative techniques used to depict the ongoing farmer-herder crisis and the issues surrounding Tiv-Fulani massacres. The qualitative research method employed demonstrates a thorough and thoughtful approach to understanding the re-imagining of atrocity in modern Nollywood narratives.&#10;&#10;While the paper effectively identifies the dearth of scholarly engagement with cinematic representations of atrocities in Nigeria, the author could consider expanding the discussion to include a comparative analysis with other regional or global cinematic representations of similar atrocities and the literature debates on media culture that may benefit from this Africa-centered perspective. Additionally, further exploration of the potential impact of these cinematic representations on societal perceptions and attitudes toward atrocity could enhance the paper’s significance. The paper serves as a valuable contribution to the academic conversation and opens up pathways for future research and inquiry.&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
