    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Eastern</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">86.7</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">100.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">78.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">300</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1088</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Polyck-O&#039;Neill, Julia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The author has created an index of Arab American Women Academics to build intellectual community and help advance the understanding of the contributions and scope of this group (among other goals). </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The description and contextualization of the project are quite compelling; the author is developing an index and is seeking feedback and opportunities to collaborate while opening up an important conversation about the presence and work of Arab American women in academia. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1022</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Noguera-Henao, Andrea</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">I find the proposal very significant and original. I have some knowledge of feminism and gender studies, and the proposal caught my attention; I think it is very valuable. However, the first question that comes to mind is: why the Arab component? I understand that the author wants to highlight the work of Arab-American writers, and I don&#039;t doubt its value, but I think it would be beneficial to explain in detail why this focus is particularly relevant. Beyond not being part of Eurocentrism, it would be beneficial to emphasize what makes it per se valuable.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The text presents a well-founded and relevant proposal with a clear focus on the inclusion and visibility of Arab-American women in academia and the capacity of Digital Humanities to disseminate knowledge. The proposal could be strengthened with a clear justification for the Arab focus, providing more specific details on why it is significant to draw attention to this niche. The project contributes significantly to the fields of gender studies and rhetoric.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">A lightning talk allows for a more dynamic and powerful presentation by quickly capturing the audience&#039;s attention and maintaining it through a smooth and convincing narrative. The justification behind focusing on Arab-American women can be articulated with greater clarity and detail, providing specific examples and persuasive arguments. Furthermore, the format facilitates direct interaction and immediate feedback, allowing the presenter to delve deeper into the technological tools they will utilize. A lightning talk also offers greater opportunities for collaboration and support to enhance a project that is inherently valuable.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">100</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1310</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Alvarez, Maira Elizabeth</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The project makes a significant contribution to the fields of gender studies and rhetoric by focusing on the visibility of Arab-American women scholars. The proposal holds importance across various fields beyond the humanities and initiates discussions on documentation and dissemination within the DH field.&#10;&#10;I would suggest that the author explore other similar projects to identify various ways to broaden the project. One project that comes to mind is &quot;Black DH in Public: Mapping the Black Digital and Public Humanities&quot; https://humanitiesforall.org/blog/black-dh-in-public-mapping-the-black-digital-and-public-humanities.&#10;&#10;This research shows a lot of potential, and I am eager to see its progress.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The project makes a significant contribution to the fields of gender studies and rhetoric by focusing on the visibility of Arab-American women scholars. The proposal holds importance across various fields beyond the humanities and initiates discussions on documentation and dissemination within the DH field.&#10;&#10;I would suggest that the author explore other similar projects to identify various ways to broaden the project. One project that comes to mind is &quot;Black DH in Public: Mapping the Black Digital and Public Humanities&quot; https://humanitiesforall.org/blog/black-dh-in-public-mapping-the-black-digital-and-public-humanities.&#10;&#10;The proposal could be strengthened by answering the &quot;why&quot; in more depth, that is, the significance and relevance of this research nowadays. This research shows a lot of potential, and I am eager to see its progress.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This proposal is great for a lightning talk. The author will benefit from the experience and feedback the audience can provide to further the research.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">78</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
