    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Aural imaginaries: An auditory machination of a musical performance without listeners.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">aurality, listening, auditory, diversity, temporality</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Global&#10;19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary&#10;digital art production and analysis&#10;media archaeology&#10;music and sound digitization, encoding, and analysis&#10;Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Disability and differently-abled studies&#10;Musicology&#10;Sound Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;Global</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">19th Century&#10;20th Century&#10;Contemporary</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital art production and analysis&#10;media archaeology&#10;music and sound digitization, encoding, and analysis</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Cognitive Sciences and psychology&#10;Disability and differently-abled studies&#10;Musicology&#10;Sound Studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;This performance installation explores complexities surrounding the notion of accessibility, while engaging in a critical conversation around the assumptions and prioritization of perceptual capacities, through the audience&#039;s collective &#039;reading&#039; of a unique soundscape. The piece centers on the Los Angeles Philharmonic&#039;s 2020 performance of Beethoven&#039;s 7th Symphony, that amidst the global pandemic lockdown, became the first philharmonic performance to be ever played to an auditorium without any listeners. At the same time, this piece was originally composed by Beethoven at the peak of his progressive hearing disability, that made him adapt to new techniques in composing and performing, using the sensory reach and temporality of beat and rythm. A recording of this concert was made by the author, from its archived re-broadcasts in the summer of 2021 on a local FM radio station. This recording was re-synthezied, with one channel featuring a cochlear implant (CI) vocoded transmission of the symphony. This manipulation directly confronts the trajectory of historical ableism that encoded itself into the design of the assitive hearing technology, which involved the prioritization of spoken communication with unaided listeners, over all the multiple modalities of human expression. The audience is therefore re-positioned as listeners to an &#039;unintelligible&#039; version of the performance that was originally intended for an audience of no one, prompting reflection on the notion of accessibility and the construction of meaning within the social acoustic realm. By stripping away melody and pitch, the cochlear implant version, lays bare to the audience, the limitations of implant technology in representing the full spectrum of a musical experience. At the same time it is an invitation to unaided listeners, to consider alternate aesthetics and listening that engage a purely temporal aspect of auditory perception. A synchronous conversation component will be facilitated through the performance platform&#039;s chat functionality, allowing for audience members to elicit and share auditory imagery and associations as they engage in a post-performance discussion on the concept of aural diversity.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This performance installation explores complexities surrounding the notion of accessibility, while engaging in a critical conversation around the assumptions and prioritization of perceptual capacities, through the audience&#039;s collective &#039;reading&#039; of a unique soundscape. The piece centers on the Los Angeles Philharmonic&#039;s 2020 performance of Beethoven&#039;s 7th Symphony, that amidst the global pandemic lockdown, became the first philharmonic performance to be ever played to an auditorium without any listeners. At the same time, this piece was originally composed by Beethoven at the peak of his progressive hearing disability, that made him adapt to new techniques in composing and performing, using the sensory reach and temporality of beat and rythm. A recording of this concert was made by the author, from its archived re-broadcasts in the summer of 2021 on a local FM radio station. This recording was re-synthezied, with one channel featuring a cochlear implant (CI) vocoded transmission of the symphony. This manipulation directly confronts the trajectory of historical ableism that encoded itself into the design of the assitive hearing technology, which involved the prioritization of spoken communication with unaided listeners, over all the multiple modalities of human expression. The audience is therefore re-positioned as listeners to an &#039;unintelligible&#039; version of the performance that was originally intended for an audience of no one, prompting reflection on the notion of accessibility and the construction of meaning within the social acoustic realm. By stripping away melody and pitch, the cochlear implant version, lays bare to the audience, the limitations of implant technology in representing the full spectrum of a musical experience. At the same time it is an invitation to unaided listeners, to consider alternate aesthetics and listening that engage a purely temporal aspect of auditory perception. A synchronous conversation component will be facilitated through the performance platform&#039;s chat functionality, allowing for audience members to elicit and share auditory imagery and associations as they engage in a post-performance discussion on the concept of aural diversity.</ss:Data></Cell>
