    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Network Analysis of Vsesvit: Unveiling Global Literary Interconnections</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Network analysis, Slavic studies, Ukrainian studies</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English&#10;Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)&#10;20th Century&#10;digital bibliography, personography, and prosopography&#10;network analysis and graphs theory and application&#10;Library and Information Science&#10;Literary studies&#10;Comparative and World Literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">English</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Comparative (2 or more geographical areas)</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">20th Century</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">digital bibliography, personography, and prosopography&#10;network analysis and graphs theory and application</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Library and Information Science&#10;Literary studies&#10;Comparative and World Literature</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">&lt;p&gt;The proposed poster aims to explore the intricate network of Vsesvit, a Ukrainian translation periodical showcasing global literary connections. Featuring over 1000 poems, 500 novels, and numerous critical essays from more than 100 countries and 80 languages, Vsesvit highlights its vast literary scope.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;Central to this analysis is the Bibliographic Index of Publications, curated by Oleg Mykytenko and Halina Hamaliy in 2004, transformed into a dataset for distant reading analysis. Using network analysis techniques, the poster will visually represent Vsesvit&#039;s literary connections through network graphs, detailed commentaries, and analyses. These visualizations will examine publication patterns, geographical contributions, and the interconnectedness of contributors, portraying Vsesvit as a significant global literary agent within international discourse.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;This study aims to provide insights into the Ukrainian literary market during Soviet Ukraine by tracing Vsesvit&#039;s evolution over decades, revealing its adaptive strategies, global literary influences, and role in cultural shifts. The methodologies employed draw from three articles. Sydney J. Shep&#039;s &quot;At the crossroads: Book history meets digital humanities&quot; highlights the convergence of book history and digital humanities, offering new textual scholarship directions. Melanie Conroy&#039;s &quot;Networks, Maps, and Time: Visualizing Historical Networks Using Palladio&quot; emphasizes data visualization tools like Palladio and its strengths in exploring geospatial and chronological dimensions. Philip Gleissner&#039;s research, &quot;Somehow, I Wasn’t Drawn into The Editorial Office of Novyi Mir,&quot; uses digital humanities to study late socialist literature, aligning with Eikhenbaum&#039;s social mode of being in literature.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;&lt;p&gt;By integrating these methodologies, the poster seeks to unravel the multifaceted nature of Vsesvit, spotlighting its role as a global literary agent and its impact on Ukrainian literary discourse. Network analysis aims to uncover hidden connections and patterns, offering a nuanced understanding of Vsesvit&#039;s significance within the international literary landscape.&lt;/p&gt;&#10;</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed poster aims to explore the intricate network of Vsesvit, a Ukrainian translation periodical showcasing global literary connections. Featuring over 1000 poems, 500 novels, and numerous critical essays from more than 100 countries and 80 languages, Vsesvit highlights its vast literary scope.&#10;Central to this analysis is the Bibliographic Index of Publications, curated by Oleg Mykytenko and Halina Hamaliy in 2004, transformed into a dataset for distant reading analysis. Using network analysis techniques, the poster will visually represent Vsesvit&#039;s literary connections through network graphs, detailed commentaries, and analyses. These visualizations will examine publication patterns, geographical contributions, and the interconnectedness of contributors, portraying Vsesvit as a significant global literary agent within international discourse.&#10;This study aims to provide insights into the Ukrainian literary market during Soviet Ukraine by tracing Vsesvit&#039;s evolution over decades, revealing its adaptive strategies, global literary influences, and role in cultural shifts. The methodologies employed draw from three articles. Sydney J. Shep&#039;s &quot;At the crossroads: Book history meets digital humanities&quot; highlights the convergence of book history and digital humanities, offering new textual scholarship directions. Melanie Conroy&#039;s &quot;Networks, Maps, and Time: Visualizing Historical Networks Using Palladio&quot; emphasizes data visualization tools like Palladio and its strengths in exploring geospatial and chronological dimensions. Philip Gleissner&#039;s research, &quot;Somehow, I Wasn’t Drawn into The Editorial Office of Novyi Mir,&quot; uses digital humanities to study late socialist literature, aligning with Eikhenbaum&#039;s social mode of being in literature.&#10;By integrating these methodologies, the poster seeks to unravel the multifaceted nature of Vsesvit, spotlighting its role as a global literary agent and its impact on Ukrainian literary discourse. Network analysis aims to uncover hidden connections and patterns, offering a nuanced understanding of Vsesvit&#039;s significance within the international literary landscape.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Korotkov, Georgii</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">United States of America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">North_America</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"> </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">georgii@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">georgii@stanford.edu, kvaleria@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Korotkov, Georgii;&#10;Korotkova, Valeriia</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">georgii@stanford.edu;&#10;kvaleria@stanford.edu</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">PST</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">4</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">82.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">92.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">70.0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">3</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">1</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">0.0000</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">302</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1120</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Kurzynski, Maciej</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed poster explores the global literary connections of the Ukrainian translation periodical Vsesvit. The authors use network analysis to visualize Vsesvit&#039;s extensive publication history, employing the Bibliographic Index of Publications as the primary dataset. The poster aims to showcase the journal&#039;s role as a significant global literary agent as well as its impact on Ukrainian literary discourse during Soviet times.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposed poster&#039;s strength lies in its comprehensive exploration of Vsesvit&#039;s global literary connections, supported by a rich dataset. This is a valuable and ambitious contribution to DH, especially given that Ukrainian is underrepresented in digital scholarship and the journal is relatively unknown. However, these very facts might become significant obstacles for the project&#039;s development.&#10;&#10;As far as I understand it, the journal requires NLP tools for Ukrainian. The abstract should discuss the availability and efficacy of such tools and how they will be employed in the project. Additionally, the submission could benefit from more specific details about the data visualization tools and techniques to be used. For example, is Gephi or Cytoscape suitable for Ukrainian text, or will the authors Latinize everything? Will the authors build networks between authors and translators, and what will be the basis for establishing these connections? Is the presence in the same issue of two names enough to draw an edge between these names, for example? These questions should be given more consideration in the abstract. Currently, the abstract appears very ambitious in its scope and slightly too general, with the authors aiming to &quot;examine publication patterns, geographical contributions, and the interconnectedness of contributors.&quot;&#10;&#10;Overall, this project promises valuable insights into an underrepresented topic but would be improved by addressing the above areas for greater specificity.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">82</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1177</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Clawson, Corey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The authors examine a Ukrainian translation periodical considering its patterns, author connections, trends, and geographic distributions. The application of network analysis to examine translation is fascinating and arguably underutilized. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Your abstract very clearly illustrates the work&#039;s methodological foundations and significance to the multilingual focus of the conference.  The intersections of this project considering literary history and translation are full of promise. I&#039;m invigorated by this project&#039;s approach as well as its ambition. My only point of concern is this ambition as I&#039;m left wondering if this abstract—with all of its facets—might be better suited to a paper format given all the ground you intend to cover.  Alternatively, if accepted as a poster, you may consider paring down the scope of visualizations and argument given the potentially limited &quot;real estate&quot; of the poster format.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">If the authors are amenable to the suggestion, I think this may be better suited to a paper presentation.  The authors have a lot they would like to cover and I think it may require some additional focus to work as an effective poster presentation (as indicated in my comments to them). Still, this is fascinating work that really brings value to ACH in terms of its multilingual considerations regardless of the format. </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">92</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1253</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Ford, Linsey</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This poster will illustrate a study examining the Ukrainian literary market during Soviet Ukraine. The focus will be on three related articles that show the evolution of Vsesvit, a Ukrainian translation periodical. It will contribute to the conference by presenting a digital biography and network analysis of relevant literature.  </ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">The proposal is well written and organized. It clearly outlines the methodological framework of the project and engages with relevant scholarship. It would have been beneficial if the proposal was more focused on the project&#039;s practical contribution to digital humanities.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">70</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">1312</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">Torabi, Katayoun</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This poster will demonstrate Vsesvit’s literary connections, using Palladio, a network analysis tool that visualizes relational as well as geospatial and temporal data. I believe this poster will make an important contribution to this conference by effectively using a relatively new digital visualization tool to highlight the impact that an influential Ukrainian publication had on the world during the Soviet era.</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String">This project is engaging, highlights interesting cultural issues, and aligns well with the focus of this conference. A poster is the perfect medium for presenting this work. I highly recommend that this proposal be accepted for the conference. The only reason this proposal received 8/9 ratings instead of 10s is because it would have been helpful if the author had included a sentence or two explaining why Vsesvit was chosen as the focus of this study, and (since the project includes temporal data) a brief statement about the exact timeframe for this study. In the abstract, the author states that Vsesvit is a Ukrainian translation periodical that had a significant impact on Ukrainian literary discourse and influenced cultural shifts in Soviet Ukraine. A sentence or two explaining the type of content Vsesvit published and why it was so important to Soviet readers would help frame the visual argument for those who are unfamiliar with the publication. I think that Palladio is a fine choice for this project. Few network analysis tools offer ways of visualizing relational, geospatial, and temporal data, so it will be interesting to see how this author achieves “GIST” in these visualizations!</ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="String"></ss:Data></Cell>
    <Cell><ss:Data ss:Type="Number">84</ss:Data></Cell>
